DESKTOPS OFFER STUDENTS VERSATILITY  By BECKY WARING 
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A home computer has become an absolute necessity
for school-age children. Fortunately, prices have fallen so far
that most families should be able to afford one. Whether for
homework, Web cruising, e-mail or game-playing, the computer will
likely become the focal point of many home activities. Here's how
to choose one with the right features and the right price.
</P>
<P>
   We have chosen three PCs for varying budgets, plus an Apple iMac
model. All have everything your child needs for school activities.
Some go a lot further, such as adding multimedia playback
capabilities and even the ability to make your own music CDs.
Buying the best you can afford provides some measure of protection
against premature obsolescence, always a consideration with
computer purchases. You will also likely get a much more versatile
and expandable machine.
</P>
<P>
   As for buying the computer, we recommend scouting out the
build-to-order options on most every vendor's Web site (Apple,
Compaq, Dell, Gateway, Hewlett-Packard and Sony all have extensive
online stores, among others). This lets you save money by tailoring
a system to your exact needs.
</P>
<P>
   Features to Look For:
</P>
<P>
   -- Processor/RAM. Budget-conscious desktop buyers looking for
deals for less than $1,000 should consider models with Intel
Celeron and AMD K6-2 processors. Clock speeds around 500 MHz are
just fine for most schoolwork and game playing. You will compromise
on things like 3-D and video horsepower. For serious multimedia
capabilities, look to the Intel Pentium III line and clock speeds
in the 600 to 700 MHz range. Don't overspend on the clock speed
however. A couple hundred extra bucks is probably better allocated
to more memory (get at least 64 MB, or 128 MB for multimedia) and
add-ons such as a CD recorder.
</P>
<P>
   -- Software/Operating System. We recommend Windows 98 over
Windows 2000 for both portables and desktops due to ease-of-use and
compatibility issues. Windows Millennium Edition is coming soon,
however, and may even be shipping by the time you get around to
buying. At the least, ask your salesperson if you can get a coupon
for an upgrade to Window ME when you buy your new computer.
</P>
<P>
   All our recommended systems (except the iMac) include Microsoft
Word and virus-scanning utilities. Most also include an array of
home and educational software. If you are buying a first computer,
online build-to-order vendors like Dell and Gateway also offer
special add-on software value packs that are inexpensive ways to
start building your library.
</P>
<P>
   -- Storage. It's a general rule that however much hard-disk
space you buy, you will quickly fill it up, especially in these
days of huge digital-camera picture files and MP3 music downloads.
We have therefore ``specced out'' our recommended systems with
hefty hard disks, typically 20 to 30 GB. On the higher-end systems,
we also recommend a DVD-ROM drive. You will likely want to add it
on in the near future, and it's cheaper and easier to get it built
in. Another popular extra is a CD-recorder, which is included in
the Sony multimedia-oriented system in our chart. You can add it on
to most build-to-order models.
</P>
<P>
   -- Expansion. All the PC desktops in our chart have plenty of
expansion capability, being tower models. The compact iMac is an
exception. The PCs have varying numbers of USB ports (the new
standard for attaching peripherals like printers and scanners),
serial and parallel ports, and miscellaneous audio and video
connections. They also have extra PCI slots and drive bays for
internal expansion. Because there are so many different home
networking schemes, we didn't price the systems with Ethernet, but
add about $50 for a network card if you need one.
</P>
<P>
   -- Monitor. All our choices include a monitor in the price;
there are two 15-inch models, and two 17-inchers. The extra $100 or
so for a 17-inch monitor is well worth the price. There's more
screen real estate for viewing Web sites and working with multiple
applications, or you can use the extra space to increase pixel size
and ease eyestrain. The 15-inch screens are usually viewed at
800x600 or 1024x768, 17-inchers at 1024x768 or 1280x1024. A given
resolution, for example 1024x768, that looks cramped at 15 inches
will be easy to read at 17 inches.
</P>
<P>
   If you really want to splurge, you might also consider a
flat-screen LCD monitor. These are a lot more expensive than
traditional CRT monitors, but look great and save space.
</P>
<P>
   -- Warranty and Technical Support. Of the four vendors shown
here, Dell has the most generous warranty and tech support
features. Other vendors tend to limit the amount of time you can
make calls related to software issues, although all have one-year
hardware warranty and tech support. All four vendors have excellent
online tech support areas, which are the first place to turn when
you have a problem or need a software driver.
</P>
<P>
   The Budget Saver:
</P>
<P>
   -- Dell Dimension L566cx. Dell is sort of the Wal-Mart of
computing: It has all the most popular products at the lowest
prices possible, backed by good quality and service. The Dimension
line goes all the way to the high end, but we chose the entry-level
model as a paragon of price and performance. The L566cx has all the
basics for home and education, just lacking bells and whistles such
as DVD drives and superfast processors. Keep in mind that you can
customize any Dell with various add-ons, so be careful not to run
up the bill when you start shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The Mid-Priced Speedster:
</P>
<P>
   -- HP Pavilion. HP's Pavilion line is squarely aimed at the home
user and offers excellent value for the money. Rather than going
for one of the off-the-shelf models, we specced out a machine with
a 17-inch screen, 733 MHz Pentium III, top-notch video card,
DVD-ROM drive, 128 MB of RAM and 15 GB hard disk for just $1,271.
It also comes with all the right consumer software in a
well-designed case. What more can you ask? Well, maybe a
CD-rewritable drive or inkjet printer, two bases that HP has
covered in spades, being a market leader in each. Just add them to
your build-to-order list.
</P>
<P>
   The Multimedia Maven:
</P>
<P>
   -- Sony PCV-R553DS VAIO Digital Studio. If you want to go beyond
the basics to get a real multimedia powerhouse, Sony's Digital
Studio lives up to its name. It has an almost dizzying array of
software for editing digital images and movies, even creating Web
video, and has built-in i.LINK (IEEE 1394) ports for DV camcorders.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, it has dual DVD-ROM and CD-RW drives. This lets you
copy files easily from one to the other, for backup purposes or for
making custom CD-audio mix discs. The 17-inch flat Trinitron screen
is also much higher quality than the run-of-the-mill models you
will find in most consumer systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Mac Alternative:
</P>
<P>
   -- Apple iMac DV+. Apple rolled out its new iMac line a couple
weeks ago. As usual, the focus is on multimedia. If you have seen
Apple's TV commercials, you have already guessed that the iMac DV
is the cheapest and easiest way to get into editing video with your
DV camcorder. We recommend the iMac DV+ for its 30 GB hard disk,
DVD-ROM drive and 450 MHz PowerPC G3 processor, which outperforms
Pentium IIIs with much higher clock speeds.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac DV+ is also a great multimedia playback machine, with
its Harman-Kardon speakers, fast video card with 3-D acceleration
and special theater-screen mode, which increases brightness while
playing movies. In a dorm room, it can double as an entertainment
center for CDs and DVD movies.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Beckey Waring at becky(AT)waring.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-13-00 2310EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
