<HEADLINE>
FOX URGES OPENING OF U.S.-MEXICAN BORDER TO BUILD NEW PARTNERSHIP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 25th graf starting: In a rare, etc., delete reference to
Guanajuato bordering Texas. It does not.) By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL, Mexico _ Looking ahead to his first visit to the
United States since winning Mexico's most democratic presidential
election in 71 years, Vicente Fox said Sunday that he will press
U.S. officials to open the border to Mexican workers and denounced
the violence against them.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings this month with President Clinton, Vice President Al
Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Mexican president-elect
said he will also begin dialogue about the formation of a North
American common market. Referring to the successes of the European
Union, Fox said that it would promote economic cooperation rather
than competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never be that good friend, that good neighbor, that
good partner as long as Mexico is lagging way behind in
development,'' Fox said. ``I think it is a solidarity issue. It is
a wisdom issue. It is a talent issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the market, by itself, will do the job,'' he
went on. ``This job has to be done by the intelligence of people,
by the intelligence of governments, by the talent of our nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his election on July 2, Fox has become a towering figure
in Mexico, both because he stands 6 foot 5 inches in his signature
cowboy boots and because he is the first man to seize the
presidency from the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party since
1929.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed and talkative, speaking in fluent English, the
President-elect met with U.S. reporters at his mother's sprawling,
colonial hacienda to discuss his ideas for addressing some of the
most contentious grievances in Mexico's relationship with the
United States, including immigration, the fight against drug
trafficking and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   At many points throughout the 90-minute meeting, he spoke with
candor unique among Mexican politicians about his country's
failings and its continuing need for foreign assistance, and he
encouraged U.S. officials to do the same when he meets Clinton and
Gore on Aug. 24, and Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, the
following day in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In talking about immigration, Fox, a former executive for
Coca-Cola in Mexico, called the labor force one of his nation's
greatest assets. He said he will push for the creation of new
programs that would allow Mexicans to hold temporary jobs legally
in the United States _ including everything from unskilled
gardeners to qualified computer programmers. This would mean, he
noted, that Mexicans would not be forced to risk their lives
crossing the border as illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``American labor has its own point of view, which I respect,''
Fox said, when asked about anticipated opposition to such ideas
from U.S. labor unions. ``But the United States also knows very
well that it needs people to grow, that the United States economy
cannot grow at rates of 5 percent or more if you don't have
Mexicans there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a country that was built up by immigrants,'' he said of
his northern neighbor. ``I don't know why today immigrants should
be rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he would tell Clinton that the violence against Mexican
immigrants on U.S. ranches along the border _ violence in which at
least three immigrants have been killed this year _ is ``not
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, ``we are more intelligent than to accept that as
a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he understands clearly that illegal immigration into the
United States is largely caused by poverty, unemployment and hunger
in Mexico, and in order to keep Mexican workers home, he intends to
turn his campaign promises of 7 percent annual economic growth and
350,000 new jobs a year into reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not possible to have a harmonious, stable border. It is
not possible to solve the migration problem if we don't solve the
gap where a worker in Mexico earns $5 a day, and a worker in the
United States makes $60 a day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Fox went on. ``Migration can be handled with different
alternatives,'' he said. ``By building up walls, by putting up
armies, by dedicating billions of dollars like every border state
is doing to avoid migration, is not the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reinforcing the border, Fox proposes slowly tearing
it down by expanding the North American Free Trade Agreement into a
treaty that creates an open market and a freer flow of services,
goods and workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, they don't compete within each other,'' he said,
referring to the 15-nation European Union, in which citizens of any
one country can work in any other member nation, and passport
controls have also largely been abolished. ``The countries that are
involved, they are partners, so they take all the advantages that
each one has and they put them together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't imagine the huge potential of Mexico, the United
States and Canada 20, 30, 40 years from now,'' he added. ``The
capacity of this bloc of nations would be the best in the world. We
three countries would be absolute winners.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He said he plans to seek similar open market agreements among
some of the members of Mercosur _ Brazil, Argentina and Chile.
Mexico and these three nations, he said, could be ``the four
machines'' that could move Latin America forward and make it a real
power in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said that most of his meetings in Washington, and in
Dallas with Bush, would be informal opportunities to meet and
greet, he would strongly propose an end to the U.S.
drug-certification program. Under the program, the U.S. Congress
annually certifies that Mexico and other individual Latin American
countries where there is a substantial drug trade are meeting
certain standards for combating the illegal traffic. Those
countries that do not meet the standards face an array of possible
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The program has long been criticized by Latin American
presidents as interventionist. Fox said he shared that view, but in
addition, he said the program is ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not serving any purpose,'' he said. ``Drug trafficking
is growing, drug consumption in the United States is growing, the
introduction of drugs to the United States is growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox also said that he would consider ``very positively'' U.S.
law enforcement efforts to win the extradition of suspected drug
traffickers, an issue long the focus of acrimony between Mexico and
Washington. And he promised that, under his government, it would be
harder for criminals to bribe their way out of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Summing up his hopes for his visit to the United States, he
said, ``I want to approach the United States with intelligence. I
don't want to approach it with pressures and complaints. I want to
sit down with the United States and talk long-term and short-term,
and to build, not to destroy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a rare moment of evasiveness, Fox backed away from questions
about which of the U.S. presidential candidates seemed more of a
friend to Mexico. He said he had met previously with Bush when Fox
served as governor of Guanajuato, and he would meet Gore for the
first time in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates, he said, have appeared interested in improving
relations with Mexico, even if only for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Latin vote will be very important,'' he said. ``This will
oblige them to really be serious, to really be committed to Latin
America and to Latin Americans living in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to characterize relations between Mexico and the United
States, he smiled and said, ``The thing I have always said is that
it is a difficult relationship. Sometimes we declare love for each
other, but sometimes we give bear hugs _ too tight an embrace, and
so someone gets hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
