<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES COAST TO VICORY OVER ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Roger Clemens came to baseball as a power
pitcher, and after agreeing to a contract with the New York Yankees
that will endure beyond his 40th birthday, Clemens said he intended
to finish his career as a power pitcher. When he can't throw hard,
he won't throw at all.
</P>
<P>
   And Clemens still throws very hard. The best working definition
of a power pitcher _ radar guns not required _ may be how opposing
hitters respond in late-afternoon shadows. Facing Clemens on Sunday
evening, the Anaheim Angels reacted as if they heard his fastball
better than they saw it.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens (10-6) scattered four hits over six and two-thirds
innings and helped shut down the Angels, 4-1, salvaging the last
game of the three-game series for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is expected to sign his contract extension this week. He
is obligated to play two years for the Yankees and the Yankees are
obligated to pay him $30.9 million for the 2001 and 2002 seasons,
an average of $15.45 million a year, the highest salary in baseball
history. It will be the fourth time in Clemens's career that he
will hold the distinction of earning the highest annual average
salary of any pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   He has 257 career victories and 3,446 career strikeouts. He only
struck out two on Sunday night, but he was overpowering; there was
no hiding his aggressive approach in the early innings of this
game, which started at 5 p.m. Pacific time.
</P>
<P>
   The sun sets behind the stands on the third-base side here, and
when the game started, the shadows cloaked the 60 feet 6 inches
between home plate and the rubber on the mound. The lights of
Edison Field were turned on, but they had no effect until the third
inning. These are almost the worst possible conditions for hitting,
and Clemens seized the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   He threw 14 pitches in the first inning, 14 fastballs, ranging
from 92 to 95 mph, and there was nothing but unsure swings from the
Angels, who were flailing in the dark. Clemens started the second
inning with a 92-mile-an-hour fastball and needed only 10 pitches
in the inning, mixing in a couple of split-fingered fastballs and a
slider.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens threw 13 pitches in the third inning, all fastballs, and
it was not until the fourth that his velocity, perhaps drained by
his early-inning offensive, was diminished and he began to mix in
more splitters and sliders.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's Ramon Ortiz outpitched Boston's Pedro Martinez last
week, armed with a repertory of fastballs and sliders. He is a
power pitcher, like Clemens, and the Yankees took many weak swings
against him on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yankees offered passive resistance: they patiently waited
for Ortiz to throw strikes, and he could not do so consistently.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams walked to open the second, and David Justice was
hit by a pitch. Tino Martinez flied out and Jose Canseco whiffed,
but Jose Posada walked, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius fell behind in the count, one ball and two
strikes, and fouled off three straight pitches before drawing three
straight pitches out of the strike zone for a run-scoring walk.
After two innings, the Yankees had more runs (1) than hits (0).
</P>
<P>
   They added a run in the fourth in similar fashion. Justice poked
a single through the right side with a no-ball, two-strike count,
and Ortiz walked Martinez and Posada. Bases loaded once more.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz began working from the windup, and the Yankees' bench was
working over Eric Cooper, the first-base umpire. It appeared that
Coach Don Zimmer, Manager Joe Torre and others were claiming that
Ortiz was balking as he prepared to throw pitches to Jose Vizcaino.
Stationed on the first-base line, Cooper kept glancing into the
Yankees' dugout and responding viscerally to the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Taking his lead off first base, Posada suddenly took a
three-step rush toward second and stopped, and Ortiz drew up his
hands in front of his face as if he were going to start his
delivery. But he paused to wipe his forehead with his glove, and
Cooper and two other umpires pointed at him and screamed, ``Balk.''
Posada raised both hands in celebration as all the runners advanced
one base; Justice's run gave the Yankees a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored a run in the fifth, but Clemens held that
lead, aided by Justice's sliding catch in the sixth inning with a
runner at second.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens retired the first two batters in the seventh, and when
the pinch-hitter Tim Salmon singled, Torre chose to replace him
with the left-hander Mike Stanton, who promptly picked off the
pinch-runner Benji Gil at first base.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was waiting for Stanton at the top step of the dugout,
hand extended. Clemens's final line: four hits and three walks
allowed in six and two-thirds innings, and just one run. He has not
been charged with a loss since June 9 and has won six straight
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Justice keyed a Yankee rally in the eighth, somehow recovering
after he had been fooled by the breaking ball of the left-hander
Mike Holtz to pull a single to right field. Williams moved to third
on that hit and scored when Tino Martinez singled.
</P>
</TEXT>
