<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RAIDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS RESERVES BLOW ANOTHER LEAD IN LOSS TO OAKLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Evaluate this: Oakland 21, Cowboys 20, Sunday
night at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' preseason philosophy is to use exhibition games to
evaluate backup players, although first-year coach Dave Campo
readily admitted, ``I'm disappointed that we lost the game ...
(but) positively, it's the third straight game that our No. 1s left
with the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second week in a row, the Cowboys' backups blew a
halftime lead. This time, it was a 14-point spread that evaporated
on them against a Raiders team, now 1-1, that pulled it out with
Bobby Hoying and Scott Dreisbach at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys fell to 0-3. They're 1-12 in preseason games during
the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman and the No. 1 offense scored on three of five
possessions, while the Cowboys' first-team defense held the Raiders
to a 47-yard field goal by rookie Sebastian Janikowski in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final two minutes of the game, the Cowboys' second-
and third-team defense allowed Dreisbach and the Raiders to drive
39 yards in three plays, with tight end Willy Tate catching a
15-yard touchdown pass to pull the visitors within one point of the
lead, 20-19, 1:08 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The real hero in this game was Jon Gruden, the Raiders'
third-year head coach who _ fully understanding the importance of
preseason games _ went for the 2-point conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Gruden was rewarded when Dreisbach threaded a bullet pass into
David Dunn, standing tall in the middle of the end zone and giving
the Raiders what held up to be a 21-20 victory.
</P>
<P>
   This was a 3 hour, 20-minute game that started slowly ... then
dragged to a near-halt. The first half lasted 1:41.
</P>
<P>
   The evening marked an early exit for Rocket Ismail (sprained
left thumb/no receptions) and followed an eerie, 10-minute delay
while an ambulance drove directly onto the Texas Stadium carpet and
took Oakland receiver Terry Mickens to a local hospital for spinal
observation (consciousness/feelings in extremities).
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders finished with 11 penalties for 98 yards. The Cowboys
had nine penalties for 59 yards, including two presnap penalties by
the offense and one by the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some things we have to clean up, obviously,'' said
Campo, referring to the presnap flags.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, this game was excessive.
</P>
<P>
   It came down to rookie kicker Tim Seder lining up and trying a
58-yard field goal that would have won the game. It fell short.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, there was a made-for-ESPN
``SportsCenter'', double-fumble play that began with a 58-yard bomb
from Cowboys' third-team quarterback Clint Stoerner to James
McKnight, who was seeing his first game action since 1998 with the
Seattle Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   This nuttiest play of the night went from Stoerner to McKnight,
who fumbled when stripped by Raiders safety Johnnie Harris at the
Oakland 7. Raiders safety Brandon Jennings scooped up the ball at
the Oakland 2 and returned it 48 yards to midfield where Cowboys
receiver-on-the-bubble Chris Brazzell chased him down and swatted
the ball into the turf. The ball then took a Sunday hop directly
into the hands of Cowboys rookie free agent Troy Hambrick, who
returned it the other way 25 yards to the Oakland 25.
</P>
<P>
   The play went for a Cowboys net gain of 35 yards.
</P>
<P>
   This was also a game filled with deception. Aikman and the
first-team offense played all but the Cowboys' final series of the
first half and scored its second and third touchdowns (along with
its third field goal) of the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman and the first offense was in on five possessions but on
the field for only 7:54.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman completed 6 of 14 passes for 61 yards, with no
interceptions and no sacks. Yet 10 of the 17 points scored by the
Cowboys' first-team offense resulted in two drives totaling minus-1
yard.
</P>
<P>
   On their opening drive, the Cowboys lost three yards in three
plays before Seder nailed a 47-yard field goal for a 3-0 lead.
Seder is 3-for-4 (48, 28 and 47 yards) against three different
teams over two continents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's any more clear now than before,'' Campo
said of the kicking competition between rookies Seder and Rian
Lindell, who remains perfect this preseason by adding a 19-yard
field goal Sunday night. ``There is just going to have to be a
decision made at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys opened a 17-3 lead with 3:25 to play in the first
half when the first-team offense went 4 yards in five plays. Rookie
Michael Wiley scored from the 1.
</P>
<P>
   This was set up by another wild play in which Cowboys free-agent
cornerback Stephen Fisher returned his first of two interceptions
of the game for 62 yards to the Oakland 4, where he was caught from
behind as he began to raise his hand in premature celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders came back with a 9-yard touchdown scramble by Hoying
and a 44-yard field goal by Janikowski. Lindell allowed the Cowboys
to extend their lead to 20-13 before Dreisbach led the Raiders'
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Cowboys were glad to get some plays on video tape
to study.
</P>
<P>
   They could go home feeling positive about something. After all,
it's only preseason. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
