<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-USGYMNASTICS-ATLE     08-14 1602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLER'S PATH TO TRIALS DECIDEDLY DIFFERENT 
</HEADLINE>
 GYMNASTICS-ATLER-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All this free time, like it or not . . . six weeks with too
little to do and too much to think about.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dangerous combination for Vanessa Atler. The year 2000,
an Olympic year, was about to take over the calendar, and here she
was, stuck in a strange new home in Plano, Texas, two time zones
removed from her roots in Canyon Country, Calif., with nothing on
her agenda but pondering the mess she was in.
</P>
<P>
   Her nature was to internalize things. Sure, she had set up a
personal Internet Web site (www.atler.com) almost four years ago
when, at 14, she had burst upon the national gymnastics scene as
the US junior champion, and she had taken pains not to make it a
routine, gee-whiz diary. So she had shared some of her most private
thoughts, good and bad, with the nearly 1 million correspondents
who had visited the site. But there were some things that were off
limits, some things not even she was sure about, like whether it
was worth the aggravation to pursue her career through the US
Olympic team trials at Boston's FleetCenter Thursday-Sunday, and,
ideally, on to her ultimate destination, the Sydney Games next
month.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't quite how she had envisioned the final all-out
preparations to secure her passport to Australia. It seemed there
were nothing but negatives to dwell upon; the only problem was
where to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. She need look no further than her useless left ankle,
encased in a cast, veteran of two operations _ the first one two
months ago in October 1999, the second a month later _ to remove
crippling bone chips that had helped ruin her year. This was a
frightening predicament, her first serious injury, and she didn't
know quite how to handle it. She'd been hurt before _ broken
fingers and wrists, the inevitable souvenirs of relentless
gymnastics punishment _ but she'd always been able to work through
them. Not this. She was under strict orders to engage in nothing
more than light duty through the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   She hadn't been away from the beam and the bars and the vault
for so long since she was 5 1/2 years old and revealed her dream
ambition to her mother: to become a cheerleader and date a football
player. Her mother, Nanette, taught tennis, and Vanessa had tried
it briefly. But she was too short both in height _ she was only 4
feet 10 inches _ and desire, and soon she had abandoned the sport
in frustration. So Mom had put her in tumbling class, and Vanessa
quickly discovered two things: She loved it and she was good at it.
Goodbye, pompoms and quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   She began competing at 8, rode the express elevator to the elite
level at 12 . . . And now wondered whether it was time to get off.
There was a particular urgency attached to her training, with the
Olympics so close, and she was woefully rusty and out of shape. All
she could do in the gym was a little casual work on the uneven
bars.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, another obstacle. Those blasted bars. They were one of the
four elements in women's gymnastics _ along with floor exercise,
vault, and balance beam _ known in the parlance as ``skills.'' Such
a cruel misnomer for Atler. She was anything but skilled on the
bars _ at least while performing the routine devised by Steve
Rybacki and Beth Kline-Rybacki, her coaches since she'd signed up
at their Gliders Gymnasium in Covina, Calif., at age 11. They'd
developed her into prominence but also installed an intricate
release on the bars, a move called the Comaneci, that was
sabotaging her career. She could do it in practice and probably
could have done it in competition, but there seemed to be a
psychological barrier she could not cross in front of judges and an
audience.
</P>
<P>
   She had fallen while attempting it in three straight nationals,
and the gaffe had cost her sole possession of the all-around title
in 1997 and even a piece of it in '98 and '99. Everything else
about her performance was virtually flawless _ she'd been a
national champion in the floor, vault, and beam at one time or
another _ but in terms of overall eminence, the Comaneci was her
downfall, and she seemed permanently in the shadow of her good
friend and major rival, Kristen Maloney. That was another stumbling
block, but the Comaneci was the real villain. Atler once had told
reporters that she insisted on keeping the move, but the truth was,
she now acknowledged, that the Rybackis wanted it to stay.
</P>
<P>
   The cumulative effect of the chips and the Comaneci had just
about kidnapped her confidence, made her afraid in competition,
left her at such an emotional ebb that she constantly worried about
Maloney and the other girls instead of concentrating on her
routine.
</P>
<P>
   She divulged none of this until it became unbearable. And then
she dropped a bombshell on her parents and coaches. Instead of
taking an intermediate detour _ say, insisting that the Comaneci be
scrapped _ she decided on a complete break. She wanted to leave the
Rybackis, leave California, and move to Plano, home of World
Olympic Gymnastics and its proprietor, Valeri Liukin, who had won
gold in the high bars and silver in the men's all-around at the
1988 Olympics in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Liukin was pretty much a neophyte coach, never having handled a
star of Atler's magnitude, but Atler long had admired the Russian
gymnastics approach, and this son of the former Soviet Union
embodied it. Still, her decision shocked the Rybackis and her
parents, Nanette and Ted, an electronics technician for the US
Postal Service. But she'd talked things out with them all. She
parted on good terms with the Rybackis and received wholehearted
support from her family; Nanette moved with her to Plano while Ted
and her older brother, Teddy, remained in Canyon Country.
</P>
<P>
   There was no question she needed to do something; the crap shoot
was whether this was it. No less a figure than Olympic team
coordinator Bela Karolyi had recognized her talent and angst and
lethargy. The outsized Romanian mentor/maestro's opinion was
considered gospel. Not only was he the de facto US coach, but he
also had spun Olympic gold out of Nadia Comaneci _ inspiration for
that cursed release move that now haunted Atler _and later Mary Lou
Retton. Karolyi believed she was on the verge of quitting, and ``to
lose a quality athlete like Vanessa,'' he said, ``would be the
biggest shame in the whole world.'' So he told her parents, ``Don't
give up. Don't give up! Make the necessary move if you have to, but
stay in the sport because it's a beautiful thing and there's
(little time) to go and you can fulfill all the dreams that you've
been nurturing around (Vanessa's) athletic performance and athletic
career. So do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So they did it. And Liukin welcomed her. More than that, he
realized that, on the cusp of 18, she was no longer a little girl
but a young woman, someone to be listened to instead of lectured.
He intuitively knew that the Comaneci was history, but for good
measure, Atler told him she wasn't going to do it anymore. Problem
was, she wasn't in condition to do much of anything now. Physically
or mentally. Virtually on the eve of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Happy new year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Darn if it hasn't been a happy year. It may end up being
euphoric. The Olympic trials are here, and the old Atler is back,
assured and proficient, almost a guarantee to go to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that hiatus was the elixir she needed. Rather than
reinforcing her doubts, it rejuvenated her. By the time she went to
Houston for the US Olympic Committee Media Summit in May, the
bounce was back in her step and her voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it was almost a blessing in disguise,'' she said. ``I
started missing (gymnastics) a lot more and loved it again.
Sometimes you're doing it so much, you forget why you're doing it.
When I had to stop for a while, it gave me a lot more motivation _
wanting to do it again and learning new tricks and getting
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The ankle obliged, too. It's always going to hurt, Atler
understands, but she can live with that nuisance and it's no longer
an issue in competition.
</P>
<P>
   And she's buried the Comaneci and streamlined her bars routine
under Liukin's tutelage. ``It was a big chance,'' he said of the
Comaneci. ``You don't want to take a chance at this level. (So) it
was just a matter of getting comfortable technique-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   She's more than that. She's positively refreshed on the bars.
``I just knew that that's what I needed,'' Atler said. ``We changed
a whole bunch, so it wasn't like there's a little bit of that (old)
bar routine in my mind. It was just all like a clean slate, and
it's almost like a new event for me.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is more delighted than Karolyi, who launched into one of
his stream-of-consciousness metaphors, replete with elaborate
pantomime, to illustrate his emotional ride since Atler reached the
crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart was breaking,'' he said, ``because I knew it was like
the gold miner. You dig and dig and dig and dig and dig (each
``dig'' accompanied by a vigorous shoveling motion). Fine. (Now
holding an imaginary nugget) `Oh my God, it's a big one.'
(Mimicking the trauma of watching the prize vanish) Then the gold
starts melting in your hand; your heart is breaking. Or you've
dropped it and the water is taking it away. Golly, it is breaking
your heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``That situation is what I was feeling. But I was very, very
glad she find her place and find her reason'' to continue.
</P>
<P>
   All she had to do first was agonize over her reasons not to.
</P>
</TEXT>
