<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-RUIZ-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUIZ EFFORT DEFUSED BY REFEREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ John Ruiz's downfall was that he came to fight
Saturday night and Richard Steele came to watch.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the wise choice for Ruiz, but not for Steele, who
is supposed to be a law enforcement officer in the ring. Ruiz is
paid to fight, and when you're in with Evander Holyfield, it is the
required thing to do. Steele is paid to enforce the rules that
exist between two people engaged in the most primitive of sports,
and when you're a referee in with Holyfield, it's the required
thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz did his job. Steele did not. And so, at some point during
Saturday night's fight for the World Boxing Association heavyweight
title at the Paris Hilton, the bout slipped from boxing into
brawling and with it went Ruiz's chance to become the first
Hispanic heavyweight champion in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny has the heart of a lion and it overcame him,'' said
trainer Gabe Mari after his fighter lost a razor-thin, 12-round
unanimous decision to Holyfield on a night when many people,
including the Showtime broadcast crew and its online viewers poll,
felt Ruiz won handily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan was to punch and move. He didn't do it. He did it
some, but in a lot of rounds he wanted to fight the guy. Holyfield
made it a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   That had been Mari's fear entering the match, that his young
boxer would be lured into fighting Holyfield's fight, which is more
warfare than art. He feared Ruiz would find the aging and slowed
Holyfield so easy to hit that he would get swept up in the moment
and forget to punch and move. In the end he did, although Mari and
many others still believe Ruiz was a big winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched it twice,'' said former HBO vice president of boxing
programming Lou DiBella, who never has been a Ruiz fan. ``I taped
it and watched it again after I heard the decision. That decision
was an abomination. I thought it was an atrocity. There is no way
Holyfield won. None. Zero. That was a bad, bad, corrupt decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Showtime commentator and former light heavyweight champion Bobby
Czyz had Ruiz leading, 5-1, after six rounds and ended up scoring
the bout 9-3 for Ruiz. After the match, he ripped the decision, as
did fellow broadcaster Steve Albert. Longtime promoters Cedric
Kushner and Mike Acri also had Ruiz winning easily after they
watched at home.
</P>
<P>
   But in Las Vegas, judges Duane Ford and Dave Moretti scored the
bout 114-113 for Holyfield, even giving him a 10-8 round in the
third without benefit of a knockdown because he got Ruiz in big
trouble with 25 seconds left after doing nothing special but
picking up the pace before that. The third judge, Fernando Viso,
obviously filled in his card before the fight, scoring it 116-112
for Holyfield. The Globe card had it even after 11 rounds and gave
the last to Holyfield to make it 114-113 for the now four-time
heavyweight champion. What a scorecard that close means is that it
could have gone either way and many obviously felt it went in the
wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy was swirling at the postfight press conference with
promoter Don King stirring the pot by calling for an immediate
rematch, something that could only happen if Ruiz is left as the
No. 1 contender by the WBA despite the defeat. Otherwise, Holyfield
would be mandated to fight Wladimir Klitschko (ranked third) next
unless King can force a bout between Klitschko and Ruiz as a
box-off for a shot at the new WBA champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain people think Johnny won, so let's do it again,'' King
said, and Ruiz didn't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was close,'' Ruiz said. ``I hope a rematch
comes to put all these doubts aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Those doubts certainly would have been dispelled had Ruiz fought
the entire night the way he fought the first two rounds when he
followed his battle plan brilliantly and won both with stinging
body shots and a jab that slammed often into Holyfield's face.
Seldom did Ruiz get hit. He would punch his way inside, then tie up
Holyfield before any damage could be done by Holyfield's fists,
elbows, head, shoulders, or the laces of his gloves.
</P>
<P>
   There was little Steele had to do up to that point and he did it
well. But after Holyfield landed a big right hand down the pipe
that buckled Ruiz's knees and had him in deep trouble with 25
seconds left in the third round, everything seemed to change.
Wobbling badly, Ruiz held on, wrestling with Holyfield along the
ropes, clutching him like a man holding a lamppost in a stiff
January snowstorm until the wind dies down. As he did, Steele
watched, not moving in to break the two, which would have put Ruiz
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the storm let up, and the round ended with a sagging
Ruiz still holding Holyfield tightly before he returned to his
corner. When he came back out, he was ready to fight, not box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny had taken Holyfield's best,'' Mari said. ``Then the
fighter's heart took over his game plan. Without Johnny, there
would have been no fight. Johnny Ruiz made the fight after that. He
was the one pressing Holyfield, but the referee didn't do his job.
I'm not going to cry about the referee because we knew it before
the fight. He didn't do his job.''
</P>
<P>
   What Ruiz and his cornermen felt Steele didn't do was stop
Holyfield from slamming an elbow into Ruiz's face repeatedly. One
of the blows broke Ruiz's nose in the 10th and another bloodied it
in the 12th, they said. Ruiz even stepped back in that last round
to complain, a complaint that fell on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   Not once did Steele do anything but warn Holyfield against using
his head on Ruiz's face, the same charge Mike Tyson and Lennox
Lewis made against him. It was ignored on those nights and ignored
again Saturday night, according to Ruiz and his manager, Norman
Stone. Ignored even after Stone asked Steele to be aware of
Holyfield's borderline reading of the Marquis of Queensbury's
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he's a rules guy,'' Stone said of Holyfield. ``He's
not a rules guy. I told Steele in the dressing room that I wanted
him to watch two things _ heads and elbows. He said he'd take full
control. He didn't do flip. If he did his job, John is heavyweight
champion of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Ruiz left the ring with a loss, a broken nose, dark
bruises around both eyes, and scrapes and scratches all over,
including the back of his neck and shoulders. Some came from
Holyfield punches. But not all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked Steele to control the fight, but he let Holyfield do
what he does,'' a bitter Ruiz (36-4) said. ``I was happy Holyfield
came to fight, but the referee didn't control the fight. Never once
did I (think) I'd lose. I still feel I won.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield (37-4-1) was quiet as this talk went on, sitting near
Ruiz at a podium and saying only: ``On nights when things didn't go
my way, I didn't cry. I didn't grumble. I did what I had to do. I
went back out and won more fights. He was a very aggressive
fighter. I never knew if he'd run over me or not. He didn't fight
the way I thought he would. I couldn't catch him with the right
hand but once.
</P>
<P>
   ``He earned a lot of respect. I knew I couldn't just run over
him. He didn't give me room to do anything. You don't have to be
hurt to learn to respect a guy. I was just a little bit better. Not
a lot. Just a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a matter of opinion that was in much dispute by the end
of the night. Ringside observers did not seem to have much of a
quarrel with the outcome, but TV viewers clearly did and so did
Showtime's broadcasting team and a wide assortment of veteran
boxing observers not at ringside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander was a lucky guy tonight,'' said Jay Larkin, the cable
network's programming executive and a longtime friend of Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Luck? Corruption? Bad refereeing? In the end, none of that
mattered to Ruiz, the kid from Chelsea, Mass., who made clear that
he belonged in the ring with the top heavyweights in the world
regardless of what anyone had said about him before the fight.
</P>
<P>
   He won his point and he convinced many he won the fight.
Unfortunately, he didn't convince three guys with pencils or a
referee with a hands-off policy, but he convinced the most
important guy. He convinced himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great show,'' Ruiz said through his disappointment.
``I came to fight. Holyfield came to fight. I felt like I won, but
you've got to leave it to the judges sometimes. That's life. But I
still say that belt would look better around my waist than his.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Richard Steele done his job as well as John Ruiz did, it
might have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
