<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS TOO MUCH FOR ANGELS, ORTIZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Anaheim Angels handled Pedro Martinez, and ``El
Duque,'' and even Denny Neagle during their recent run, but Roger
Clemens . . . well, that was a little too much, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens and relievers Mike Stanton and Mariano Rivera limited
the heavy-hitting Angels to just four hits Sunday night, and the
New York Yankees emerged with a 4-1 win before 43,411 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   It snapped the Angels' winning streak at three games, took a
little of the luster off what was otherwise a splendid homestand,
and brought young Ramon Ortiz back to earth after his two-hitter
last week against Boston and the redoubtable Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Scioscia, the Angels manager, looked at Ortiz's performance
two ways: good and not so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave us seven innings and he allowed only two runs,''
Scioscia said. ``We win that game a lot of nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was also too hyper, too anxious. He didn't have the
same mound presence he did against Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz walked home one run in the second inning and balked in
another in the fourth when he absentmindedly rubbed his nose as he
started his delivery with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even realize I did it,'' Ortiz (4-3) said through
interpreter Juan Alvarez. ``It was just sweat coming down and I was
wiping it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens (10-6) won his sixth consecutive decision, coming just
two days after signing a three-year, $3.9 million contract
extension. He gave up four hits, walked three and struck out two.
He retired 10 Angels in a row during one stretch, finally yielding
a run in the fifth on a two-out RBI single by Darin Erstad, making
it a 2-1 game.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens came out after Tim Salmon's pinch single with two outs
in the seventh. Stanton took over and got out of the inning without
even throwing a pitch; he picked pinch-runner Benji Gil off first.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton got the first out in the eighth, then Rivera took over
and retired the last five batters for his 26th save.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz gave up just two runs on three hits in seven innings,
striking out five. But he also walked six.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main difference (from his win over Boston) was I wasn't
consistent with my fastball in the strike zone,'' he said. ``I was
all over the place. I wasn't anxious (as Scioscia suggested), I was
trying to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, one more thing: Clemens' next start will be Friday night at
Yankee Stadium . . . against the Angels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
