<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ESCAPE WITH MINOR INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ If the NFL cast a ballot of those who want fewer
preseason games, receiver Rocket Ismail and fullback Robert Thomas
might vote yes. So might the Dallas Cowboys after bothincurred
minor injuries in Sunday night's 21-20 loss to the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail suffered a sprained left thumb attempting to catch a Troy
Aikman pass in the end zone on the Cowboys' first offensive play
midway through the first quarter. He was taken to the locker room
for X-rays, which were negative. He did not play the rest of the
game but did return to the sidelines in the second quarter with his
left hand heavily wrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas sprained his left knee when he collided with two Raiders
defenders on running back Michael Wiley's 1-yard touchdown run with
3:25 left in the first half. Thomas hobbled off the field and did
not return.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie cornerback Mario Edwards suffered a strained left
hamstring in the first half and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not had a chance to talk to the trainers, but the only
thing I heard just on the field was they didn't feel too bad about
it,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said. ``So, in all three cases, I
don't know for sure, but I feel comfortable with it right now.''
OUT OF THE FRAY
</P>
<P>
   Several key starters and reserves did not play because of minor
injuries. The notables were running back Emmitt Smith (strained
calf), guard Larry Allen (precautionary-fractured hand), center
Mark Stepnoski (flu), receiver Jason Tucker (groin), tight end
David LaFleur (strained groin) and quarterback Randall Cunningham
(coach's decision). STOERNER FAIRS WELL
</P>
<P>
   Rookie free agent Clint Stoerner was the backup quarterback
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   He replaced Aikman with less than two minutes remaining in the
first half and played until Paul Justin relieved him in the fourth
quarter. Stoerner completed 8 of 12 passes for 108 yards and led
the Cowboys to a fourth-quarter field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's easier, but everything slows down a little
bit,'' Stoerner said. ``I am further along than I thought I'd be
simply because I've got more playing time than I thought I'd get.''
</P>
<P>
   He had back luck on a third-quarter interception when a pass
into the end zone popped out of the hands of receiver Damon Hodge
to Johnnie Harris of the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not his fault,'' Dave Campo said. ``He did a good job
of finding the receiver, he was open in the end zone; we just
didn't make the play.'' RAIDER GETS A SCARE
</P>
<P>
   Raiders receiver Terry Mickens was conscious and had feeling in
his lower extremities after being taken off the field in an
ambulance in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After catching a short pass at the 36-yard line, Mickens was
spun down by Dexter Coakley and appeared to be hit on the top of
the helmet by George Teague's lower right side.
</P>
<P>
   Mickens lay motionless for 10 minutes with a sprained neck. He
was put on a stretcher and driven to a local hospital for
observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it scared me,'' Coakley said. ``I wrapped my hands
around him and I didn't know it happened.'' NOBLE EFFORT
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Brandon Noble is listed at 6-foot-2, but
Raiders rookie place-kicker Sebastian Janikowski found Noble's
reach is considerably higher.
</P>
<P>
   On a 57-yard field goal attempt late in the first quarter, Noble
tipped Janikowski's attempt and the ball landed well short.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a longer kick so he kicked it low. (Defensive end)
Michael Myers and I got a real good push and it just hit me,'' said
Noble, who deflected a pass later in the game. ``I should have
caught it. It hit me right in the hands.'' LETT REVISTED
</P>
<P>
   Shades of the Leon Lett's 1992 Super Bowl performance were on
display when cornerback Stephen Fisher intercepted Bobby Hoying's
pass at the Cowboys' 34-yard line and was returning it for an
apparent first-half touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   When Fisher reached the Oakland 10, he raised his right hand to
celebrate only to have Oakland receiver Kenny Shedd tackle him from
behind at the 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to do that in the preseason than the regular
season,'' said Fisher, who added another interception in the
fourth-quarter. ``I was hot-doggin' it a little bit.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
