<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RECEIVERS-TEX </SLUG>
 
McKNIGHT, BRAZZELL IMPROVE CHANCES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Never mind that the Dallas Cowboys' first-team
offense managed 66 yards on five first-half possessions in Sunday
night's 21-20 loss to the Raiders, including six yards in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The game was mainly for players on the roster bubble and those
looking to define their roles with the team.
</P>
<P>
   The first cuts are set for Aug. 22, when the Cowboys roster will
be trimmed from 86 to 65. Considering that head coach Dave Campo
wants to focus on the front-line players and their key backups
Saturday against the Broncos, Sunday night's matchup offered the
last real chance for several players to make a good impression.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those players who got Campo's attention were receivers
James McKnight and Chris Brazzell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazzell did some positive things on special teams,'' Campo
said. ``And I'm real excited about James McKnight. He's everything
we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   McKnight caught four passes for 89 yards in his first action as
a Cowboy since being acquired from Seattle in a trade roughly 14
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee in
training camp last year and missed the entire season. The Cowboys
have brought him back slowly, holding him out of the first two
preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   He said Sunday night's performance was a long time coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to be back out there,'' McKnight said.
``I got knocked around a couple of times and made some plays. I'm
just going to stay humble and keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   McKnight, who displayed his big-play ability with a 58-yard
reception, also showed that he might be the leading candidate for
the third-receiver spot. His chief competitors _ Wane McGarity
(inconsistent play) and Jason Tucker (strained right groin) _ have
been unable to take advantage of his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Brazzell is just trying to make the roster. His three catches
for 44 yards certainly helped his chances, and helped erase the
memories he left with coaches of dropped passes in the first two
preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brazzell's chances are based largely on how he
contributes on special teams. He had a key tackle on a punt return
against the Raiders, and he also showed some difference-making
hustle when he chased down defensive back Brandon Jennings on a
fumble return and created a turnover for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Another player who helped himself was rookie free-agent
quarterback Clint Stoerner. Because the Cowboys know what they have
in backup Randall Cunningham, and are unhappy with the play of Paul
Justin, Stoerner got an extended look.
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner impressed Campo with his ability to scramble and make
things happen in a little more than a quarter of play. He completed
8 of 12 passes for 108 yards with an interception.
</P>
<P>
   On the interception, in the end zone, the ball bounced through
the hands of Cowboys receiver Damon Hodge and into the arms of
Raiders defensive back Johnnie Harris. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
