<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LARRIMORE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' ROOKIE LARRIMORE GETS PRAISE IN FIRST START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ George Teague jolted the butterflies out of
rookie cornerback Kareem Larrimore's stomach in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this man right here,'' Larrimore said, motioning to
Teague dressing in the locker next to his, ``made that big hit, I
was comfortable the rest of the game. I was good to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Teague compiled a bone-crushing highlight reel Sunday night in
support of Larrimore, who made his first NFL start in Sunday
night's 21-20 exhibition loss to the Oakland Raiders at Texas
Stadium. Larrimore chuckled when he admitted his pregame
butterflies were a first in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie out of West Texas A&AMP;M took another step toward
becoming the Dallas Cowboys' starting left cornerback _ in the wake
of Kevin Smith's departure to mull retirement _ when the season
opens on Sept. 3. Sunday night he continued to show promise,
turning in a solid outing while playing nearly three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   His rookie jitters are being taken care of by veterans Teague
and Darren Woodson on and off the field, which Larrimore said is
allowing him to play worry-free football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel pressure, they ease it all out of me,'' Larrimore
said. ``They tell me to just have fun, that's what these games are
for. I thought I did fairly well. I probably made _ I don't want to
say mistakes _ I probably didn't go as far as I was supposed to on
some plays, but I feel I did fairly well.''
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore played opposite Ryan McNeil in the first quarter, the
duo that appears to headed for starting roles. With Deion Sanders
in Washington and Smith possibly not returning, Larrimore, a
fourth-round draft selection, has seized control of the position.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night things were relatively quiet on the left side. The
Raiders took few shots to his side, which Larrimore said _ half
winking _ made him feel a bit like Sanders. Through three quarters,
Larrimore and the rest of the Cowboys defense allowed 137 passing
yards on 14 of 27 passing from quarterbacks Rich Gannon and Bobby
Hoying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done very well,'' Teague said. ``He has a few things to
touch up on, but we are very confident with where he is right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore, second on the team with five tackles, played one down
in the fatal fourth quarter _ the Raiders' successful two-point
conversion to win the game _ when the Cowboys' reserves gave up 71
yards passing and the Raiders' game-winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I liked about him,'' Cowboys head coach Dave Campo
said, ``is he's being relatively aggressive, he's trying to make
things happen out there and that's an area we need him to be doing
out there and he's starting to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Larrimore's few gaffes came when Marcus Knight beat him
for a 30-yard completion from Gannon. However, a double penalty on
the Raiders negated the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel confident,'' Larrimore said. ``I didn't get many passes
my way, but come that first game, I know it will come.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
