<HEADLINE>
SETBACKS DON'T HOLD BACK HALL 
</HEADLINE>
 SWIM TRIALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The Deadhead phase is history. Gary Hall listens
to Bach these days. ``The Greatest Hits,'' he says. But he comes to
the starting line in a hooded black robe that he could have
borrowed from a medieval executioner, then strips down to Apollo
Creed-style star-spangled shorts and shadowboxes on the blocks. ``I
don't really think I'm a showman,'' Hall said. ``I just like to be
me.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing does not change, though. When he hears the starting
beep, Hall still makes sure he beats as many people as he needs to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thrilled to have made it,'' Hall said Sunday &UR;  &LR; night
after he came out of the competitive shadows at age 25 to finish
second behind Neil Walker in the 100-meter freestyle in the US
Olympic Swim Trials at the Indiana University Natatorium and earn a
return ticket to the Games in at least two events. ``I'm really
stoked.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was America's speed king four years ago, anchoring the 4 x
100 freestyle and medley relays to gold medals ahead of the
Russians and grabbing silver medals behind legendary Alexander
Popov in the 50 and 100.
</P>
<P>
   Then life intervened for the man from Paradise Valley, Ariz.
Hall was suspended for three months in 1998 for using marijuana and
lost his Speedo contract. Last year, he was diagnosed with
diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was invincible before,'' said Hall. ``It was a
real shock. It gave me a taste of mortality. That can be a very
sobering experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time he turned up here for trials, he breezed onto the
team. This time, neither Hall nor anybody else knew what to expect.
He's seeded second in the 50, but the race is a crapshoot. In 1996,
world record-holder Tom Jager didn't make the team.
</P>
<P>
   So Hall's best shot was in the 100, even though he had only
raced the distance twice in the last two years before coming here
and was seeded fifth. ``When it comes down to a couple hundredths
of seconds to determine who gets to go to the Olympics and who
doesn't, there's always a possibility you might not make the
team,'' said Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But times never have mattered much to him. In the Olympics,
placement is all. And in the trials, second is as good as first.
When they got to the turn Sunday &UR;  &LR; night in a sizzling 22.71,
six-10ths of a second under Popov's world-record pace, Hall was
sitting second behind Walker.
</P>
<P>
   With 20 meters to go, though, Scott Tucker caught him and went
by. But Hall always has had a reserve tank in his purple microbus,
and he dipped into it deeply enough to touch out Tucker by
11-100ths of a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I touched, I thought about a song by the Clash: `I've
been beat up, I've been thrown out, but I'm not down,' '' said
Hall. ``That's me. You can't keep a good man down.''
</P>
<P>
   Even third place would have gotten Hall a relay spot. Misty
Hyman, who swims butterfly, didn't have that luxury. Four years
ago, she missed a spot on the team by one place. Last week, she
finished seventh in the 100 fly. Sundya &UR;  &LR; night was her last shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it so bad and there was no holding back,'' said the
21-year-old Hyman, who held on to win the 200 fly by 27-100ths of a
second (2:09.27) over 17-year-old Kaitlin Sandeno after leading the
field by two body-lengths halfway through. ``The elation hasn't set
in. It's mostly relief right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the last shot, too, for 19-year-old Kyle Salyards, who
finished last in the 100 breaststroke final. Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, he had
to come out of third place off the final turn to win the 200 breast
to touch out Tom Wilkens by 13-hundredths of a second in 2:13.21.
In a blanket finish, the top four were separated by only
32-hundredths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put everything I had into the last 50 _ and wow!'' said
Salyards, who was only eighth in the event at last year's summer
nationals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
