<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0738 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-RUIZ-BO     08-14 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-RUIZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD JUDGED LACKING BY MANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ His boxer was up above him, up there on the dais of
a postfight press conference that is as much a fixture of the
fight-night ritual as the glitz and glamour of the crowd and the
closing bell. Up there, Evander Holyfield was smiling and saying,
time and again, ``I won't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Don Turner was sitting on a step of the podium. His head was
in his hands. ``Gloomy'' was the only word to describe the face of
Turner, Holyfield's trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Three times Holyfield had ducked questions about his strange
actions in the fourth round of Saturday night's World Boxing
Association title bout against John Ruiz of Chelsea, Mass. All
Holyfield would say was that Ruiz was a puzzle to him, that he
never was sure what Ruiz was going to do, that he never had a feel
for the ``rhythm'' of his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the confusion, Holyfield had rocked Ruiz with several
hard rights in the final seconds of the third round. Even though
Ruiz's legs were wobbly, he had gained huge respect by surviving
the round.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, though, Holyfield would come out in the fourth and
attack Ruiz. Surely, Holyfield would try to put away Ruiz in the
opening seconds. Surely, Holyfield now had his opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Holyfield did nothing. Instead, Holyfield was passive,
never showing any aggression. Instead, Holyfield not only failed to
put Ruiz away, but he also lost the round on the cards of all three
judges and virtually all observers at ringside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' Turner was asked. ``Why hadn't Holyfield gone for the
kill in the fourth round?''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's eyes briefly flashed. ``Maybe he didn't want to,'' he
replied. Then, Turner returned his face to his hands and the gloom
returned. That sight said so much more than hopeful words from
Holyfield up above Turner on the dais _ that he still wants to
continue on at the age of 37, that he still has the skills to take
on the world's best.
</P>
<P>
   There were more histrionics on Showtime about the outcome of the
bout, won by Holyfield by a unanimous _ but close _ decision. The
TV announcers felt Ruiz clearly won the bout, other observers at
ringside felt the bout was close, but most gave the nod to
Holyfield. A poll of media members at ringside had Holyfield
winning on 16 scorecards, Ruiz winning on five, and one observer
scoring the fight a draw.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, virtually all felt this was not a good night for
Holyfield, the former undisputed heavyweight champion of the world.
All also came away with huge respect for Ruiz, whose sharp left
jab, whose constant stepping inside of Holyfield's punches, whose
coming at Holyfield with lowered head left Holyfield unsure of what
to do, how to attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Styles make fights,'' Holyfield said time and again in
explaining his performance. And Ruiz's style had been confusing to
him. Holyfield called that style ``awkward.'' Others saw it as
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing was that I couldn't get impatient,'' Holyfield
tried to explain, as if he had been fighting Lennox Lewis or Mike
Tyson, with their true heavyweight punches, instead of Ruiz, whose
main weapon was his jab. ``If I get impatient, then I put myself at
risk. This guy, he butted me in my nose, and he jumped at me with
his head, coming at me headfirst, and when his head hit me in my
body, it hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the 10th round had arrived, and Ruiz still was
standing, a surprise to many (``I came close to believing all you
people who said I could take this guy lightly''), Holyfield knew he
no longer could worry about Ruiz's style.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that 10th round, I knew I had to hurt him,'' said
Holyfield. ``I knew I had to give him some shots.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Holyfield took the final rounds on the cards of all
judges, giving him the fight.
</P>
<P>
   He had survived a night with John Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite question had been posed entering the fight: Could
Ruiz survive a night with Holyfield?
</P>
<P>
   And the gloomy face of Don Turner said all that had to be said
about the future of Evander Holyfield.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
