<HEADER>
A0740 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PHILLIES-H     08-14 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PHILLIES </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bagwell, Alou bash Phils
</P>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Astros showed off their version of the Bash
Brothers on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell hit two home runs and tied a club record with seven
RBIs, and Moises Alou also homered twice as the Astros flexed their
muscles in a 14-7 rout of the Philadelphia Phillies at Veterans
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell and Alou combined to go 7-for-11 with two home runs,
five runs and 10 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were locked in,'' Astros shortstop Tim Bogar said.
``Everybody was pretty confident at the plate. Not too many pitches
were missed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros matched a club record with six homers _ Richard
Hidalgo and Chris Truby also connected _ and collected a
season-high 19 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell went 4-for-5 and was hit by a pitch as he tied the club
record for RBIs shared by Rafael Ramirez (1989) and Pete Incaviglia
(1992).
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell hit a three-run homer in the fourth inning off Phillies
lefthander Omar Daal (3-13) as the Astros built a 9-5 lead and
added his 33rd homer in the eighth off Chris Brock. He also had a
pair of RBI singles and a run-scoring grounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a machine,'' Alou said. ``He's unbelievable. That's why
he needs to stay in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou wasn't too shabby, either. A day after being ejected in the
fourth inning for arguing balls and strikes in a 3-2 Astros loss,
the right fielder hit home runs No. 19 and 20. He had a two-run
homer in the first and a solo shot in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy can just flat-out hit,'' said Bagwell, who extended
his hitting streak to a season-high 12 games. ``He's the best
hitter we've got. He's clutch. He comes up with big hit after big
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case up and down the Astros' lineup Sunday as every
starter except pitcher Brian Powell had at least one hit.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Lugo had one of his best offensive games of the season,
going 3-for-3 with two doubles and three runs. He also drew a pair
of walks.
</P>
<P>
   Bogar had a season-high three hits, including a triple, and
Truby chipped in two hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had that triple easy, but I had to get dirty, so I slowed
down so I could slide,'' said Bogar, who started all three games in
the series. ``It's hard to get dirty on turf.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the offensive explosion, it nearly wasn't enough as
the Astros watched a 5-0 first-inning lead almost evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Houston jumped on Daal for five runs and four hits in the first
inning, highlighted by home runs by Alou and Truby.
</P>
<P>
   Daal, who relied mostly on changeups and off-speed pitches,
surrendered 10 hits and nine runs in four innings. He is 0-6 with a
7.43 ERA in 22 career games against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Daal and Brock each gave up three homers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what we did is what we should do when you face
pitchers that aren't throwing well,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies scored two runs in the bottom of the first off
Powell on Bobby Abreu's RBI triple and Mike Lieberthal's RBI
groundout.
</P>
<P>
   After Bagwell drove in a run in the second inning with a
grounder to short, the Phillies closed the gap to 6-5 on a
three-run homer by Marlon Anderson. Powell was ahead 1-and-2 in the
count before serving up a fastball across the middle of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the pitches I wanted back,'' said Powell, who
lasted only 2 innings. ``I had him where I wanted, but I didn't
make the pitch at the crucial time. I felt like I did that my last
couple of times out. I made a pitch when I needed to make it, and
today I just didn't do it. I hate that I didn't contribute more.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who held the New York Mets to one run over seven innings
in his last start, allowed five runs on six hits during his
58-pitch outing. The righthander pleaded unsuccessfully with
Dierker before being replaced by Joe Slusarski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was one pitch away from righting the ship,'' Powell
said. ``I didn't want to come out of the game, but obviously he
made the right choice for the team, and the bullpen did an
excellent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's three-run homer in the fourth put the Astros ahead
9-5, but the Phillies rallied again in the bottom of the inning
when Rob Ducey hit an RBI double and eventually scored on a wild
pitch by Slusarski.
</P>
<P>
   From that point, Astros relievers Jose Cabrera, Wayne Franklin
and Marc Valdes combined to hold the Phillies hitless over the
final five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera (1-2), who was making his first appearance since being
recalled from Class AAA New Orleans on Thursday, pitched two
innings for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Alou, who said he entered the game with a plan to sit back on
pitches and drive them to right-center field, hit a solo homer off
Brock to lead off the seventh, and Bagwell and Hidalgo connected
for back-to-back shots in the eighth. The home run barrage marked
the seventh time this season the Astros have hit four or more
homers in a game, including six on three different occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Of further significance, Hidalgo became only the fifth Astros
player to reach 30 home runs in a single season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been struggling lately,'' said Hidalgo, who was in a
1-for-13 slump before his homer. ``I just need to relax and be more
confident. When you've got confidence, nobody can stop you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell credited his club-record-tying RBI performance to the
top of the order's consistently reaching base. Lugo and Bogar, who
batted 1-2 in the lineup, reached eight times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys in front of me did a tremendous job of getting on
base the whole game,'' said Bagwell, whose previous single-game
high was six RBIs. ``Every time I came up to the plate, there was
somebody on base. That makes it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
