<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-WONDERLAND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREYS FREE BIRD FLIES AWAY WITH DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
 DERBY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVERE, Mass. _ For whatever reason, Billie Van, the 8-5 choice
in Saturday night's 66th running of the $100,000 Wonderland Derby,
hesitated at the break. Greys Free Bird, a noted closer, took full
advantage of the favorite's moment of indecision, and flew out of
the box in great position, a move that led to victory at 7-1
($16.60).
</P>
<P>
   A converted sprinter from Raynham, Billie Van had drawn the
coveted No. 1 box Thursday. The 67-pound black female had broken on
top in three of her four Derby preliminaries, breaking third in the
other, but she came out seventh in the final, despite the advantage
of the rail. Greys Free Bird, a 64-pound red brindle female who
usually does her best running late, popped out in second position
from box No. 2, behind speedy front-runner NR's Fast Eddie, who
zipped to the lead from box No. 4 at 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   NR's Fast Eddie, who finished second as the favorite in last
year's Derby, opened a 2-length advantage, but Greys Free Bird was
too close too early for him to hold on. NR's Fast Eddie ran hard
all the way, but Greys Free Bird ran around him in midstretch, and
drew off to win by 2 lengths. The time for the Revere Course (2,045
feet) was 38.53 over a fast track.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Billie Van was too far back too soon. She stayed on
the fence and worked her way forward, coming on strongly at the end
to gain third, another length back. But the damage had been done at
the start, and the victory belonged to Greys Free Bird, an invader
from Derby Lane in Florida, with $60,000 going to her owner, Joe
Frenette.
</P>
<P>
   ``She ran in a lot of stakes in Florida, and won the consolation
race of the St. Pete Derby,'' said Frenette. ``For a while she was
the best dog at Derby Lane, running the four fastest times of the
meet. But then she had a lot of problems. She hit a streak when she
wasn't breaking real well, and that hurt her record.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Green Bay, Wis., Frenette has been in the greyhound
business for nine years. He owns 80 greyhounds, and leases them to
run at various tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife took me to a dog track, Wisconsin Dells, and I got
hooked right there,'' he said. ``After a while, I got into
breeding. It's a lot different from my regular business in
Wisconsin, where I work in radiation protection. It's an
environmental business.''
</P>
<P>
   Frenette obtained Greys Free Bird in a deal that would make Red
Sox general manager Dan Duquette envious, trading with the
Greymeadow Kennel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I own Greys Betsy Ross, who ran second in the 1998 Wonderland
Derby to Granny. Greymeadow wanted one of her pups, and I wanted a
pup with Greys Free Bird's breeding (by Fortress-Greys Juliana). I
got lucky, and the pup I traded hasn't run yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Greys Free Bird will continue to race at Wonderland for a month,
and then go to the $60,000 American Derby at Lincoln Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest disappointment in the Derby was the effort of 9-5
second choice Flying Penske, who represented Bluffs Run in Iowa.
Flying Penske had won all four qualifiers in handy fashion, but he
broke wide from box No. 7 in the final, and lost too much ground
throughout the race to be a factor, finishing fifth, a half-length
behind 12-1 shot Eloozhun . . . The 2-4-1-5 superfecta returned
$2,431; the trifecta was worth $377, and the quiniela paid $56.80 .
. . The Derby drew 2,115, and the total handle on the 21-race
doubleheader program was $490,439.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
