<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL HAS ALREADY WON GOLD _ FOR BEST COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Swimmer Gary Hall Sr. went to three Olympics, won
four medals, and carried the American flag in the opening
ceremonies at Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the gene pool, meanwhile, swimmer Gary Hall
Jr. went to the Atlanta Olympics, won four medals, and tested
positive for pot.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, a little more than an hour after his father
delivered a rah-rah ``U-S-A!'' speech to a capacity crowd at the
U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials, Gary Hall Jr. swam his way back into
the good graces of the gods of Olympus. Well, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's second-place finish in the 100-meter freestyle _
finishing behind Texas-ex Neil Walker _ made his stormy comeback
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, back when sponsors weren't backstroking away
from him, Gary Hall Jr. endorsed a brand of sunglasses _ the
Grateful Dead signature line. Once he also dyed his blond hair
purple.
</P>
<P>
   Recruited to swim at Texas, it was determined that Hall and the
Longhorns were not the best of fits. So he went home to Arizona
and, questionable training habits aside, became one of the best
freestyle swimmers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   When Hall won Olympic silver medals in Atlanta in both the 50-
and 100-meter freestyle, it surprised no one. And when he tested
positive for marijuana in early 1998, prompting FINA (swimming's
world governing body) officials to reveal he had committed the same
indiscretion at the Atlanta Games, it didn't surprise many swim
observers, either.
</P>
<P>
   He was slapped with what could have been a three-year
suspension. And while Hall didn't dispute the results of the tests,
he and his lawyers did contest the fact that there was confusion
over whether marijuana was on the International Olympic Committee's
list of banned substances _ it wasn't during the 1996 Olympics, but
it is now _ and whether his second failed test was administered
properly.
</P>
<P>
   His suspension was eventually reduced to three months, not three
years.
</P>
<P>
   His contract with Speedo vanished. His lawyer fees ate up what
was left of his post-Atlanta earnings. And in March 1999, things
really turned worse.
</P>
<P>
   While at a party with his fiancee, the heretofore unflappable,
bulletproof Gary Hall Jr. collapsed and had to be rushed to the
hospital. Doctors diagnosed Hall, who is 26, as a Type I diabetic.
Doctors told him that he would need to watch his diet and
administer insulin shots for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a comeback story, not a surrender.
</P>
<P>
   When the finalists for the men's 100-free marched out Sunday
night at the Indiana University Natatorium, Hall was dressed in a
black robe with a ``Grim Reaper'' hood nearly covering his face _
Sugar Ray Hall. When he shed the robe, Hall revealed a
star-spangled pair of floppy boxing shorts, not unlike the ones
that Apollo Creed wore in ``Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked these up at a Muhammad Ali Fight Night benefit for
Parkinson's disease,'' Hall later explained. ``It was a black-tie
event, and I ended up wearing them home.''
</P>
<P>
   His opponents in the finals said they tried not to stare at him.
After a few air punches, ``Insulin Ray'' stripped down to his
racing suit.
</P>
<P>
   The race that followed was one of the best of the meet. Walker
hit the turn 0.62 seconds ahead of world-record pace. Behind him
was a thick wave of churning water. Hall, always the sprinter,
seemed to find another gear in the final 25 meters and touched the
wall second in 48.84. Walker was first in 48.71.
</P>
<P>
   When he realized what he had done _ the pot suspension, the
diabetes, the eight insulin injections he has to take to get
through some days _ Hall said a song flashed through his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Clash song,'' he explained. ``It says, `I been beat up,
I been thrown out, but not down.' And that's me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was asked about the ``sweep the medals'' (complete with
broom) speech that his father had given to start this fifth night
of the Olympic trials. All Gary Jr. remembered, however, was that
he was in the warmup pool, eager to get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was that him rambling on and on?'' Hall Jr. asked, shaking his
head. ``I was thinking, `Start the meet, already.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This will be a different trip to the Olympic Games, the son
promised. His struggle with diabetes has given him a new and
humbling outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot better understanding of what the Olympics is,''
Hall said. ``I don't think I had much of a clue in '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot more appreciation of the experience. Maybe that's
why I've grown up a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Some genes, it seems, just take a little longer to fit. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
