<SLUG> BC-SOC-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOORE BACK ON FAMILIAR FOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
 TEAM-MOORE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEEDHAM, Mass. _ Joe-Max Moore is the leading scorer in
Revolution history and No. 2 all-time scorer for the US national
team. But though Moore has scored many goals at Foxboro Stadium,
none was as a member of the US national team.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when the US meets Barbados in a World Cup qualifying
match Wednesday night, it will be Moore's debut at Foxboro Stadium
in a national team uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something special to me to come back here for this
game,'' Moore said. ``I really enjoyed my time in Boston. I think
this is the best sports city in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the Revolution did not do very well when I was
here, the fans were great. I felt I had a good relationship with
them because they respect players who give everything they've
got.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore has moved into an even more fanatic situation in
Liverpool. His club, Everton FC, is considered among the powers of
the England Football Association. The crosstown rivalry with
Liverpool FC alone inspires all sorts of competitive craziness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing over there is a battle, a fight, every day,'' said
Moore, noting a cut over his right eye. ``There are so many good
players, and every week is another awesome game. You are training
at a high level every day and almost everybody you are training
with is an international player.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the players are hard workers. You have to be, there is so
much competition. Our manager spent a lot of money to bring in
players _ they just signed Duncan Ferguson (Scottish international)
and now we have eight forwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Everton also added midfielder Paul Gascoigne and Ghanaian Alex
Nyarko.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as you stop improving, you are in trouble,'' Moore said.
``I'm glad I went there. I always wanted an opportunity to play at
the highest level.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore arrived the day after Everton took a 3-1 win over
Manchester City in an exhibition game Saturday. Everton opens the
Premier League season against Leeds next Saturday, and manager
Walter Smith likely will use Moore as a substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to get 20-30 minutes in that game,'' Moore said.
``(Smith) knew when he signed me that I would be away playing in
internationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds corny to say, but any time I get the opportunity to
play for the US I'll take it. Especially in a big game. And this is
a big game. I wouldn't say it's a crisis, but we've still got to
win these games or we will have some trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say this is definitely a home game for us and that
isn't always the case in the US. When we played Jamaica in
Washington, it was like playing in Kingston.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United defenders Jeff Agoos (right hamstring) and Eddie
Pope (right ankle, left hip) are probable . . . Gregg Berhalter is
the only US player without a club, after failing to agree to a
contract with Huddersfield Town in England.
</P>
</TEXT>
