<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION LET DOWN THEIR DEFENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution were stunned by the
combination of concentration lapses and controversy in the last
minutes of a 2-1 overtime loss to the MetroStars Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Now they will attempt to regroup for the final six games of the
MLS season, starting against Tampa Bay at Foxboro Stadium Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution failed to defend effectively against the
MetroStars, despite playing with a man advantage for the final 23
minutes of regulation time. They surrendered the tying goal less
than two minutes after Wolde Harris supplied an 87th-minute lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible in the MLS,'' defender Mauricio Wright
said. ``We didn't control the game in the last two minutes. You
have to protect your goal, clear everything out, and keep doing it
until the referee whistles the end of the game. We have to
concentrate for 90 minutes, then 10 minutes of extra time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to say why, it's not anyone's fault. We lost
the game on the field with a one-man advantage. It's a few little
things that cost us and if we don't do better, those things are
going to hurt our chances for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution struggled to create with a passing game, but
revealed individual offensive weapons in Jamar Beasley and Eric
Wynalda, whose potential winning goal was disallowed for an offside
violation in the second minute of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley had the most effective 90-minute performance of his
career, filling in for Ted Chronopoulos on the left side of
midfield. Beasley established himself against Petter Villegas early
in the match, then began expanding his play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had that freedom; it was a matter of taking
advantage of it,'' Beasley said. ``All the guys are always saying
in practice for me to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Beasley's remarkable speed produced dangerous attacking
situations. On one play late in the game, Beasley failed to connect
with Joe Franchino near the halfway line, but Beasley chased down
his own pass, arriving before the MetroStars could recover.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this was his most rewarding performance with the
Revolution, Beasley replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because we lost. I just have to be ready to come back to
practice and get ready for Tampa Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   But coach Fernando Clavijo decided to give the Revolution Sunday
and Monday off. The team has earned only eight of the last 33
possible points and is in danger of falling out of playoff
contention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 0149EDT &QL; 
