<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAPLER MOVES STREAK TO 26, BUT RANGERS TUMBLE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Gabe Kapler eventually got the single he
needed to extend his hitting streak to 26 games. But he also got a
sacrifice fly from an earlier at-bat when he needed a hit to keep a
big inning going for the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler did hit the ball hard, but the Rangers needed more than
one run batted in from him in that situation and more than two runs
in that inning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they let Boston Red Sox rookie starter Tomo Ohka
slither out of the jam, and he went on to get his first
major-league victory by beating the Rangers, 4-2, at The Ballpark
in Arlington on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were able to do more damage in their big inning,
scoring four off Rangers starter Kenny Rogers in the third. Rogers
allowed no runs and only three hits in the other seven innings he
pitched, but the Rangers could never overcome the Red Sox's
four-run third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our at-bats, we looked a little sluggish, but their
kid had something to do with that,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Rangers' seventh in 10 games and 10th in 14.
They are 11-18 since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting tough, but we just have to keep battling and get
out of this,'' Rangers second baseman Luis Alicea said. ``It seems
like the whole team is in a funk except for one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Kapler, but even he couldn't save the Rangers when
they had a chance to hammer on Ohka in the fourth. Frank
Catalanotto led off the inning with a single to left, and Rusty
Greer followed with a long fly to deep right-center. Center fielder
Carl Everett got under the ball but stumbled at the last moment,
and the ball fell in for a double. Rafael Palmeiro then walked to
load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler then smacked a scorching liner to center, but right at
Everett. Catalanotto scored, Greer moved to third and Ricky Ledee
followed with a bad-hop single over second baseman Mike Lansing,
making it 4-2. But Ohka got out of the inning by striking out Bill
Haselman and getting Mike Lamb on a fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is hit the ball hard; I can't control where it
goes,'' Kapler said. ``I'm not too concerned about that. It would
have been nice to bloop one in there and score two runs, but I
can't do anything about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had one more shot at Ohka in the sixth when Kapler
delivered a two-out single to left and Ledee and Haselman walked to
load the bases. But, after Rich Garces replaced Ohka, Lamb hit a
little foul pop toward the Red Sox dugout and third baseman Ed
Sprague made a terrific backhanded catch as he went down the
stairs. That left Lamb hitless in 18 at-bats. He snapped the
hitless streak too late, with a two-out single in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a rough few games,'' Lamb said. ``Part of the ups and
downs I guess. It was bound to happen. I don't think it's been this
bad since I've come up. That was a couple a months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox didn't waste their one chance after loading the
bases with two out in the third against Rogers. Nomar Garciaparra
lined a two-run single to left to give the Red Sox a 2-0 lead, and,
after Rogers hit Troy O'Leary, Jason Varitek smacked a single up
the middle to score two more.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got the one big base hit, and we didn't get it,'' Oates
said. ``You could flip a coin on the outcome of the ballgame
tonight. It really came down to who had the two-out single with the
bases loaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers lasted eight innings for the seventh time this season but
dropped to 11-10 with a 4.32 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my focus for about four pitches,'' Rogers said. ``I hit
O'Leary with a changeup, and hung a slider to Varitek. You have to
minimize the damage, and I didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maximize the damage when it's the other pitcher in trouble,
and the Rangers didn't do that either. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
