<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTCO-SHOOTING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE KILLED, SEVERAL WOUNDED IN WAREHOUSE STORE SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Daily News Staff Writer David Greenberg contributed to
this story.) 
By ORITH GOLDBERG and SYLVIA OLIANDE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hysterical parents grabbed their children, and
customers dove for cover when an attempted armored car holdup at a
Costco store turned into a shootout, leaving one man dead and three
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   One suspect who was wounded in the shooting was arrested nearby
after fleeing in a white van. An intensive five-hour search of the
San Fernando Valley neighborhood using police dogs failed to find a
second suspect in the foiled holdup.
</P>
<P>
   About 2:30 p.m. on a busy Sunday, a gunman attempted to hold up
a Sectran Security Inc. guard as he left the Sepulveda Boulevard
store after making a pickup.
</P>
<P>
   As the gunbattle erupted, customers scurried for safety in a
chaotic scene. The exchange took place in the entranceway outside
the food court, and witnesses said about a dozen shots were fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard shot-shot-shot-shot-shot and saw people were running
from the front of the store to the back and left their carts,''
said Laura Berggren, a 39-year-old Van Nuys resident shopping at
the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, it was just horrible! I'm still shaking, I'm so
scared.'' The suspect was arrested by police and taken to Valley
Presbyterian Hospital in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   A 29-year-old man shot in the head was taken to the hospital
where he died at 4 p.m., spokeswoman Kelly Tarelkashe said.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously injured victims were being treated at Providence Holy
Cross at Northridge Hospital Medical Center. Four other people
suffered non-gunshot injuries and were treated at area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Police said a man armed with an AK-47 came up to the armored
guard, who was walking out of the store with his gun drawn, and
demanded the sack of cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a robbery. Give me the money,'' Lt. Jim Grayson of
LAPD's Robbery-Homicide Division quoted the robber as saying.
</P>
<P>
   As gunfire erupted, a second suspect lurking in the food court
came out of the store.
</P>
<P>
   The guard, who was not injured, ran back to the armored truck
and got in as the suspects fled.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Fire Battalion Chief Richard P. Kay said the scene
was ``manageable but chaotic'' when firefighters arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were trying to stabilize patients,'' he said.
``One man fell down and broke his collar bone, and his wife
received shotgun pellets in her legs.''
</P>
<P>
   As ambulances and fire engines rolled to the location at 6100
Sepulveda Boulevard, entrances to the Costco parking lots were
cordoned off. Windows of at least three cars about 75 to 100 feet
from where the gunfire erupted were shattered.
</P>
<P>
   Grayson said the Van Nuys division had more than enough officers
to respond to the shooting despite the massive police presence
downtown in preparation for the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   One witness, Edgar Marroqun, 22, said his roommate was nearly
carjacked by the gunman, who approached him as he drove out of his
apartment complex at the corner of Kester Avenue and Sylvan Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy with the gun told him to stop, but he put his car in
reverse, got out and took off running to the house,'' Marroqun
said. ``He came in and told us what happened, and when we got out
we saw the guy on the floor, bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrested suspect was spotted by an off-duty LAPD police
officer who called in a report of a suspicious person walking down
Sylvan Street, said spokesman Sgt. John Pasquariello.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was walking down the street, apparently carrying a gun, and
the officers told him to give up and he did,'' Pasquariello said.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
