<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHKA, SOX BEAT RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-RANGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ When their long march ended, under a pearly
moon on a faraway patch of grass, the sweat-stained Red Sox
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night could be forgiven for flashing a smile as wide as the
Texas sky.
</P>
<P>
   They were homeward bound with much more in their lunch buckets
than a savory 4-2 victory over the Rangers in the oven that is The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Their victory allowed the Sox to return home from their 18-day,
16-game dash across America with an 8-8 split, as they prepare to
open a 10-game homestand Monday night against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   They also squeezed the most out of their only scoring
opportunity a night after they had made so little of so many
moments of promise in a dismal 6-3 loss to the Rangers. Squeezing
the hardest were Nomar Garciaparra and Jason Varitek, whose two-run
singles in the fourth provided more runs than the Sox needed to
head home on a high.
</P>
<P>
   The win lifted Boston within 1 1/2 games of the lead in the
wild-card race, though the Sox remained four games behind the
Yankees in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling to be in this position,'' Varitek said,
``knowing that if we get on a roll and start hitting on all
cylinders, we can make a lot of people turn their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Sox, it also was sweet to beat a lefthander, since they
entered the game with a record of 11-16 against lefties. Texas's
Kenny Rogers had been one of the prickliest thorns in their sides,
going 10-3 against Boston before he took Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's loss.
</P>
<P>
   The many splendors of their victory also included the solid
effort of Boston's temporary starter Tomo Ohka, who put the team in
position to win even if his outing was as uneven as his previous
two starts.
</P>
<P>
   A mystery to the Rangers, who never had faced him, Ohka yielded
five hits and four walks before he was lifted with a 4-2 lead and
two outs in the sixth. But he left the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. With Rich Garces on in relief, third baseman Ed
Sprague killed the Rangers' rally by making an acrobatic lunge into
the Boston dugout to snare Mike Lamb's foul pop and end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I was happy to get the win,'' Ohka said through
a Japanese journalist. ``But my pitching was not very good.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garces's was superb, as usual, as El Guapo pitched 2 1/3
hitless innings before yielding to closer Derek Lowe, who yielded a
harmless hit in the ninth for his 26th save.
</P>
<P>
   To Lowe, the night also presented a sign of better days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time it seems like we're getting ready to do something,
we kind of falter a little bit,'' he said. ``But we're going home
for 10 days and hopefully we can get off on the right foot
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The chances are good, since the savior, Pedro Martinez (13-4),
is going against Tampa Bay's Dave Eiland (1-1).
</P>
<P>
   Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, Ohka was good enough, mainly because Sox hitters
didn't let a fleeting opportunity vanish.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the third, Mike Lansing beat out an infield hit.
Darren Lewis walked, which brought up Sprague, who was hitting .121
(4 for 33) with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprague surprised the doubters, lashing a single to left
that loaded the bases. Up came Carl Everett, who powered the Sox to
victory Friday night with two home runs but made the final out in
four innings Saturday night, stranding seven.
</P>
<P>
   Everett missed another chance, lining to short for the second
out. But Garciaparra picked him up, lining an 0-2 pitch to left for
a single that scored Lansing and Lewis for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers then hit Troy O'Leary with a pitch to load the bases
again, this time for Varitek. The catcher promptly muscled a single
to center to score Sprague and Garciaparra, making it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a pitch to hit,'' said Varitek, who came to the plate in
a 2-for-18 slump. ``But the big thing is, I'm just trying to be
more consistent with the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohka escaped a serious scare an inning later, after Frank
Catalanotto singled and Rusty Greer doubled. Following the Sox'
doctrine on Rafael Palmeiro, Ohka walked the Texas slugger to load
the bases with none out. It was the seventh walk Palmeiro received
in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was particularly risky because next up was Gabe
Kapler, who was on a .372 tear.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler lined a sacrifice fly to center to score Catalanotto.
Ricky Ledee then punched a bad-hop single past the lunging Lansing
at second, bringing home Greer and making it 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Ohka spared himself further damage by fanning former Sox catcher
Bill Haselman and getting Lamb to fly out.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, Ohka allowed only two runners in the first five
innings, a one-out double by Catalanotto in the first and a walk to
Ledee in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five hits Ohka yielded, one was Kapler's sixth-inning
single to left, which extended his hitting streak to 26 games, the
longest in the majors since Shawn Green, then of Toronto, hit
safely in 28 straight last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
