<HEADER>
A0749 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-HNS &LR;      08-14 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walker pictures Olympics with 100 freestyle victory
</P>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It was one of those pictures truly worth a
thousand words: A disconsolate Neil Walker sitting on the edge of
the warmup pool at the Indiana University-Purdue University
Natatorium as his coach at the University of Texas, Eddie Reese,
tried to console him.
</P>
<P>
   The photo was taken by Walker's mother, Barbara, moments after
the men's 100-meter freestyle at the 1996 U.S. Olympic Swimming
Trials and pretty much said it all about what had transpired for
Walker, who had finished seventh in the event and missed the last
relay spot by one-hundredth of a second.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, the setting and the stakes were the same, but the
picture was completely different, Walker this time leaving no doubt
about his place on the U.S. Olympic team in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who competed for Texas from 1995-98, won the 100
freestyle in 48.71 seconds, beating out Gary Hall Jr., who recorded
a 48.84. Although Walker had already qualified for a spot on the
team by finishing second in the 100-meter backstroke, his showing
in the 100 freestyle established him as a top challenger to Russian
world-record holder Alexander Popov in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Walker posted his lifetime best (48.55) in the semifinals,
making him the fourth-fastest man in the event and putting him
within range of Popov's world record (48.21).
</P>
<P>
   ``The 100 free is going to be an amazing event at the Olympics,
like it was here,'' Walker said after his victory. ``I think it's
going to take a world-record performance to win. But it's such a
hard thing to predict. One of us Americans has a shot at it (the
record), and we have to go to Sydney believing we can (break it).''
</P>
<P>
   Walker found himself making plans for Australia on a night when
one of the United States' brightest stars, breaststroke specialist
Ed Moses, saw at least part of his Olympic dream die.
</P>
<P>
   Moses tried to set a blistering pace in the 200 breaststroke but
faded at the end and finished fourth, out of the running for
Sydney. First place went to 19-year-old Kyle Salyards. Second went
to former Stanford swimmer Tom Wilkens, whose chances at making the
team had dwindled after he finished third in the 400 individual
medley.
</P>
<P>
   Although Moses will swim the 100 breaststroke in Sydney, he will
be doing less than had been expected of him on the basis of wins in
both breaststroke events at the spring nationals.
</P>
<P>
   Moses, entering his junior year at Virginia, declined to speak
to reporters after the race but expressed his feelings to an
official with USA Swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' the official quoted Moses as
saying. ``I'm really disappointed. I don't know what happened. I'll
get over it and be ready for the 100 in Sydney, but tonight
definitely didn't go the way I planned or wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Tucker, a former Auburn swimmer, and Jason Lezak, who
competed for Cal-Santa Barbara, were the fourth-and fifth-place
finishers in the 100 freestyle, meaning they are assured of 400
freestyle relay spots. University of California sophomore Anthony
Ervin and UT ex Josh Davis were fifth and sixth, making them relay
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who grew up in Verona, Wis., and believes fishing is
about the best thing life has to offer, is far different from Hall,
who has a Top Gun mentality and appeared on the deck for Sunday's
race wearing red, white and blue boxing trunks over his swimsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the swagger is one of the year's most compelling
stories. Since the 1996 Olympics, when he finished second to Popov
in both the 50 and 100 freestyles, Hall has faced a variety of
hurdles, including a three-month suspension in 1998 for testing
positive for marijuana and the diagnosis in March 1999 that he is a
diabetic. He treats the disease with insulin injections _ five
Sunday, he said, and sometimes as many as eight a day _ and glucose
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a Clash song that says, `I've been beat up, but I'm
not knocked down,''' he said, ``and that's me. You can't keep a
good man down.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
