<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0750 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ORTHODOX-AZR &LR;      08-14 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORTHODOX-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-ORTHODOX-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    A MATTER OF FAITH: ORTHODOX JUDAISM AND SEN. JOSEPH
LIEBERMAN(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MAUREEN JENKINS(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to Sen. Joseph Lieberman's selection as Al Gore's
Democratic vice presidential running mate last week, Americans
probably have heard, read and seen more about Orthodox Judaism than
at any time in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a 58-year-old Orthodox Jew from Connecticut, was a
historic choice, marking the first time a Jew - not to mention a
highly observant one - was tapped by the Democrats or Republicans
for vice president. And to an America that's largely unfamiliar
with this most traditional branch of Judaism, the selection
prompted questions wondering whether Lieberman would be able to
easily function in so high an office.
</P>
<P>
   But having been a Connecticut state senator and attorney general
as well as a two-term U.S. senator, Lieberman's no stranger to
weaving his public service work around his faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lieberman phenomenon is growing out of a changed world
where it's become increasingly easier for American Jews to live
productive lives in an increasingly tolerant American world,'' said
Jeffrey S. Gurock, who teaches American Jewish history and studies
American Orthodoxy at Yeshiva University in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Some pundits - and regular folks - have wondered how Lieberman,
who strictly observes the Jewish Sabbath from sundown Friday to
sundown Saturday, would be able to cast important votes, attend
crucial meetings or consult on matters of national importance. And
even (beginitalic)before(enditalic) the election, how he'll
campaign without violating the Sabbath and Jewish holy days down
the stretch. The two holiest days on the Jewish calendar, Rosh
Hashanah and Yom Kippur - as well as Sukkot and Simhat Torah - fall
during the critical campaign crunch of late September and October.
</P>
<P>
   They wonder whether Lieberman, if elected would be able to
attend his own inauguration as it's scheduled for Jan. 20, 2001,
which falls on the Sabbath. And for that matter, swear to uphold
the office, as Orthodox Jews never swear in God's name but rather
affirm to carry out a task.
</P>
<P>
   These and other questions are ``legitimate,'' says Gurock. But
he says that Lieberman showed he ``has cogent answers for these.''
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews believe that the Torah, the first five books of
the Bible, and Halachah, or practical Jewish law, govern all
aspects of daily life, from work to play to religious rituals. But
despite adherence to laws Jews believe were given to the prophet
Moses more than 3,000 years ago, Halachah makes allowances for
public servants like Lieberman to handle critical or life-or-death
situations, even on the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   And in those cases where Lieberman questions if his work
conflicts with Jewish law, says Rabbi Steven Dworken, executive
vice president of the Rabbinical Council of America, which
represents Orthodox rabbis, ``he's going to have to feel
comfortable with the [rabbis] he consults with on religious
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 6million Jews live in the United States, with about
8percent identifying themselves as Orthodox. The 1999 Annual Survey
of Jewish Opinion found 34percent are Reform and 31percent
Conservative, with most of the rest calling themselves secular or
cultural Jews.
</P>
<P>
   While most Americans draw upon images of the bearded,
black-wearing Hasidim when they think of the Orthodox, many - like
Lieberman - wear regular contemporary clothing and live within the
mainstream of American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you wear a black coat doesn't mean you don't have
a cell phone or use a computer or live in the real world,'' said
Betty Ehrenberg, director of international affairs for the Orthodox
Union, which represents about 1,000 Orthodox synagogues across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   While their numbers aren't large, Orthodox Jews are represented
in high levels of American government. There's U.S. Rep. Robert
Wexler, a Democrat from south Florida, and Sheldon Silver, speaker
of the New York State Assembly. Even the U.S. ambassador to Egypt,
Daniel Kurtzer, is Orthodox and keeps a kosher kitchen in his
overseas residence.
</P>
<P>
   And while many might see an Orthodox Jew's life as tough, says
33-year-old Rabbi Chaim Silver of the Young Israel of Phoenix
congregation, ``for me, it's definitely not a sacrifice. It's a
state of awareness where instead of being led by outside cultures
and the secular society, we're {hellip} living our lives the way
God would have us to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about a world-class runner or sprinter and tell
him he can't eat Baby Ruth candy bars for breakfast, it's not a
sacrifice for him. It's a discipline and a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Jewish Sabbath, Orthodox Jews refrain from turning lights
on or off, talking on telephones, operating electric-powered
devices or writing. But ironically today's high-tech advances make
it easier for observant Jews to keep the laws. Automatic timers on
electric lights allow the Orthodox to still see on the Sabbath, and
voice-mail takes messages that Jews can return later on.
</P>
<P>
   With a better understanding of Jewish Orthodoxy, says Gurock,
many Americans may come to consider Lieberman not only ``a role
model for Jewish people, but for religious people of all faiths.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at maureen.jenkins(a)arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   republic.com or at (602) 444-7945.
</P>
<P>
   Associated PressSen. Joseph Lieberman and his wife, Hadassah,
arrive in Nashville on Monday, when he became the first Jewish vice
presidential candidate in history.Associated PressSen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., walks to temple in New Haven with his wife,
Hadassah, and their daughter Hana.Arizona RepublicRabbi Chaim
Silver of the Young Israel of Phoenix congregation says life as an
Orthodox Jew is not a sacrifice.
</P>
</TEXT>
