NYT-08-14-00 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0752 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     08-14 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX MUST HIT ON A SOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This is the type of hitter the Red Sox need
as they return home from the make-or-break, 16-games-in-18-days
trip that did neither.
</P>
<P>
   --One who comes off the disabled list after missing 20 games and
hits a home run on the first pitch he sees, then hits nine more in
his next 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   --One who hurts himself again, refuses to go on the DL, and
twice pinch hits with the bases loaded and delivers hits, then in
his first game back in the lineup hits two home runs, including a
game-winner in the bottom of the 13th, and goes 4 for 4 the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   --One who hits a grand slam and knocks in six runs one game, and
10 days later hits an inside-the-park home run and a game-winning,
two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   --One who hits a home run in his first at-bat after learning
he's been suspended 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   --One who hits a home run in his first game back after serving
his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the Red Sox already have that player in Carl
Everett, who was Houston's hottest hitter down the stretch last
season when the Astros won a division title and who will have to
come close to doing the same now if the Sox hope to be playing
again in October.
</P>
<P>
   You remember the old Boston Braves mantra, Spahn and Sain and
pray for rain?
</P>
<P>
   These days with the Sox, it's Nomar and Carl and . . . well,
there isn't anything else.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's series finale victory over the Texas
Rangers, the Sox were 8-8 despite batting just .223 on the trip. In
nine of the 16 games (that three-game stayover in Boston last
weekend was just another road stop), the Sox scored four runs or
fewer 10 times, and scored one run four times. They hit just 15
home runs in 16 games, no more than two in any game, and none in
five games.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Daubach hit .111 with a home run and one RBI. There were
no home runs and three RBIs from .180-hitting Troy O'Leary. Jose
Offerman was hitless in all 10 of his at-bats before he went on the
disabled list. Of the newcomers, Mike Lansing was the most
successful, but all 14 of his hits were singles. Manny Alexander
had more home runs (1) than O'Leary, Trot Nixon, Rico Brogna, and
Bernard Gilkey.
</P>
<P>
   Everett hasn't torn it up since being reinstated to the lineup
nine days ago, batting just .206 (7 for 34, 0 for his last 10), but
his two-homer, five-RBI game against the Rangers Friday night was
the biggest by any Sox player in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, as always, has held up his end, playing every day
of this marathon (and all 19 innings of that marathon in Seattle)
and batting .354, with five home runs and 14 RBIs, all team-leading
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But it's all falling on two players, Garciaparra and Everett.
O'Leary, who is chasing a lot of high pitches, insists his
off-field woes are not responsible for his current slump, but if
there is anything else at play, he isn't saying, though there are
definitely grounds for suspicion. Offerman is ready to come off the
DL, but with his sore knee and subpar play, he looks eligible for
the AARP. Daubach, who was used as a No. 3 hitter while Everett was
suspended, was in the No. 8 hole Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   He's lost at the plate. The new guys, meanwhile, are struggling
to find their place. Sprague hasn't been the answer at third. Jimy
Williams hasn't played Brogna enough to find out what he can do at
first.
</P>
<P>
   And the myth perpetuated by the Red Sox that Jim Rice is a
terrific hitting coach has been exposed this season. Teams like the
Mariners, White Sox, and A's all have an idea of what they're doing
when they go to the plate. Gabe Kapler, the Rangers outfielder who
was batting .241 when he began his current 26-game hitting streak,
was helped immeasurably by batting coach Rudy Jaramillo, who
suggested a change in his leg lift.
</P>
<P>
   If Rice has a plan, he isn't sharing it with the people he's
being paid to help. Rice may have Hall of Fame credentials as a
player, but as a teacher, he would flunk John Silber's MCAS test.
Where are the adjustments being made by O'Leary or Daubach? Who's
there to help them see what they're doing wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's game, Jason Varitek was studying videotape with
first-base coach Tommy Harper. Call it a coincidence, but Varitek
delivered a two-run single, giving him 10 RBIs on the trip, second
only to Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the Sox' hitting woes, they lost little ground on
this trip. They were in third place in the AL East when it started,
3 1/2 games behind the Yankees and a half-game behind the Blue
Jays. They were in second place Sunday, four games behind the
Yankees but a game and a half ahead of the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   In the wild-card race, they were 2 1/2 games behind with three
teams ahead of them when the trip began. They are now 1 1/2 behind,
with just two teams ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings it all back to Everett. His relationship with
Williams remains strained since their shouting match in the
manager's office last weekend. Neither man has approached the other
about making peace, but at least it hasn't gotten worse.
</P>
<P>
   Everett still isn't talking to the Boston print media, but on
Saturday, he did a radio interview with Dennis Quinn, a
transplanted good ol' boy from Pawtucket now working for KEYS in
Corpus Christi who reminisced with him about his Houston days. And
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, he did a taped interview with Sox broadcaster Joe
Castiglione that was aired on WEEI's radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Castiglione asked Everett if has he had any trouble staying
focused given all that has happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not for me,'' Everett said. ``I think a lot of other folks
have missed a bit. For me, I already threw it on a back burner.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not just blowing smoke. Ask anyone in the Sox clubhouse.
When the game begins, it doesn't matter with whom he may have been
warring, his sole enemy occupies the other dugout.
</P>
<P>
   That's a great quality to have, especially in a place like
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I let bygones be bygones,'' Everett said in his radio
bit. ``A lot of times, those bygones won't go away. Sometimes,
you've got to do things to let them know.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, he was referring to his critics. But if he plays the
way he did down the stretch in Houston, and doesn't get sent to the
penalty box again, he'll find that even in Boston, memories can be
short, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 0158EDT &QL; 
