<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0754 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      08-14 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ANNE STEPHENSON'S ``NEW &AMP; NOTABLE'' BOOK REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``E'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``I Loved You All''
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Sharp
</P>
<P>
   (Hyperion, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like I've grown to be too much for myself to
handle,'' widow Marguerite Daigle tells her daughters, Mahalia and
Penny, one day in 1977, and with that she allows herself to be
taken to a convalescent home for alcoholic women, leaving the
girls, who are 15 and 8, in the care of a baby-sitter, Isabel
Flood. That Flood is a religious zealot and militant right-to-lifer
is something Penny already knows. She suspects, in fact, that her
older sister wants to replace their mother with Isabel. The truth
is that Mahalia craves structure and finds it in Isabel while the
rebellious Penny has other things in mind - their divergent needs
are reminiscent of the young sisters in Marilynne Robinson's
wonderful novel (beginitalic)Housekeeping(enditalic). Penny's
narration has all the clear-eyed honesty we expect from a child,
which makes it the perfect voice to tell a surprisingly funny story
about that most difficult of issues, abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Lieu of Flowers''
</P>
<P>
   By Nancy Cobb
</P>
<P>
   (Pantheon, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Get out your hankies, folks, the tears start early. Fortunately,
the cry is worth the trouble. Cobb has written a brief but potent
reflection on death and grief, subtitled (beginitalic)A
Conversation for the Living(enditalic). In essays about her
experiences with her parents and friends, she discusses the
transcendent opportunities hidden within the act of facing death
with loved ones and the healing process that follows great
suffering. She laments that too many people struggle with both.
Why, she asks, ``is it easier to express our grief for an English
princess in a French tunnel than it is to visit a dying neighbor
down the block? Would that we could bring a fearlessness to a
friend's deathbed or to a grieving family as easily as we now bring
a casserole to an already full table on the day of the funeral.''
Her book is a thought-provoking look at something we all face
eventually, a rite of passage that ``dares us to define what really
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice Neel''
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Ann Temkin
</P>
<P>
   (Abrams, $45)
</P>
<P>
   Alice Neel first painted herself, wearing only her eyeglasses
and holding an artist's brush, just four years before she died in
1984. She was 80 and looked it. ``Unsmiling, ungiving, the portrait
is not calculated to please anyone, least of all the misshapen
sitter,'' writes Ann Temkin, a curator at the Philadelphia Museum
of Art. ``Like much of Neel's work over the course of five decades,
the painting is happy to look wrong.'' One can't help but think
that the outspoken Neel would have delighted in that description of
her work, the bold, honest portraits that so often ``looked wrong''
(one is her depiction of Joe Gould, the Greenwich Village ``bum''
immortalized by Joseph Mitchell in ``Joe Gould's Secret,'' the
profile that appeared in the(beginitalic) New Yorker(enditalic)).
This retrospective of Neel's work contains 75 paintings and
watercolors and a discussion by many of Neel's subjects on the
sometimes unsettling experience of sitting for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Burning of Bridget Clearly''
</P>
<P>
   By Angela Bourke
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   In March of 1895, a 26-year-old Irish dressmaker named Bridget
Cleary was tortured and burned to death by her husband, who had
come to believe that she was a changeling left behind by fairies.
Bridget had been clever, ambitious and sexual - it was even rumored
that she'd had a lover. Her murder, the ensuing trial of Michael
Cleary and a group of his relatives and neighbors charged with
aiding in the murder caused a sensation in the British newspapers,
coloring the debate over home rule in Ireland and heightening the
perception of the Irish peasantry as savages. Bourke's retelling of
the murder and its reflection of the religion and politics of the
time is exhaustively researched and thick with details. She calls
the crime, which was rooted in superstition and confusion, ``the
sort of human tragedy in which nobody is entirely to blame or
entirely innocent, and there are no winners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
