<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0755 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PROFILING-AZR &LR;      08-14 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILING-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-PROFILING-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    RACIAL ISSUES STIR CASA GRANDE, ARIZ., FUROR(a) 
 &HT;    (Resending, changing slug from Bad Cops)
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By EDYTHE JENSEN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a Black teenager driving in the streets of Casa Grande, Byron
Jackson said he expected police to pull him over.
</P>
<P>
   Now a 35-year-old city councilman in neighboring Eloy, Jackson
said he was stopped many times by Casa Grande police ``because they
pulled you over if you were young and Black and were driving a
half-decent vehicle. They still do.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's exposure of two police officers' racially charged
phone pranks are calling attention to what Jackson and others say
is a history of racial profiling by Casa Grande police.
</P>
<P>
   Although the chief has minimized the frequency of prank calls
and described other bizarre practical jokes at minority residents'
expense as ``isolated incidents,'' others see them as representing
a pattern of harassment of racial minorities that has gone on for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-grade teacher Laura Mims started Casa Grande's Black
History and Juneteenth celebrations 10 years ago and said she has
been complaining to civic leaders for longer than that about ``the
police targeting young people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good here,'' she said. ``I tell my grandson: if the
police stop you, say, 'Yes, sir,' get his name, badge number and
ask him why he stopped you. Give him your phone number, your
address and call a parent.''
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Ken Buchanan said he has heard of no racial
problems between residents and police.
</P>
<P>
   Mims said her 14-year-old grandson was handcuffed and thrown to
the ground outside a convenience store where he was buying a snack
this year. It was late on a Saturday night, and the youngster and
his friends were out past curfew, but police were overly aggressive
and abusive, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Casa Grande native Dora Vasquez, who now chairs the Arizona
Civil Rights Board appointed by the governor, said state programs
aimed at eliminating racial profiling and increasing police
awareness of diversity aren't reaching her hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've witnessed firsthand police harassing children in Casa
Grande,'' she said. ``In their zeal to catch gang members, they
stop people for the color of their skin, the kind of jewelry they
wear or a tattoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Profiling conference
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez, Jackson and Mims recently attended a racial profiling
conference sponsored by the Arizona Attorney General's Office's
Civil Rights Division. All said the conference was enlightening and
that they were dismayed that no representatives of the city or Casa
Grande Police Department attended.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Robert Huddleston said earlier that he intends to
send a representative to the next scheduled racial profiling
conference. He did not return phone calls to his office Friday, but
said earlier that he intends to require additional cultural
sensitivity training for his officers within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted during personnel hearings last week that two years
ago he listened to and laughed at a racially derogatory crank phone
call made by one of his officers. In it, the officer mimicked a
Black man calling for a female police officer to help him change a
child's diaper.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is vocal in her criticism of some individual police
officers, Mims said Huddleston may be Casa Grande's best hope for
change.
</P>
<P>
   More responsive
</P>
<P>
   Since Huddleston took the office two years ago, he has been more
responsive to residents than his predecessors, she said. Mims
praised the chief for punishing Officers Galen Flynn and Chris
Western for making racially derogatory prank phone calls to their
own department.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the former chief, we complained, we met with him, but he
never did anything,'' she said. ``It's a good sign that this chief
let these officers know they weren't above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   He said he grew up with Flynn and Western and is convinced
they're not racists. Their prank call was tasteless, he said, ``but
it was the sort of thing supervisors let slide for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eloy councilman said minorities in Casa Grande don't trust
city officials . Their complaints have gone unanswered for years,
and incidents of racial improprieties have been covered up, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Home to about 33,000, Casa Grande's population is 37percent
Hispanic and about 5percent Black. The mayor, city manager,
seven-member City Council and police chief are all White
non-Hispanic males.
</P>
<P>
   ``In small towns, things like this can be hidden. It's your word
against somebody else's,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Support for chief urged
</P>
<P>
   Casa Grande police Sgt. Lupe Reyes, a Hispanic native of Pinal
County, said that if residents are outraged by the racist pranks,
they need to support the chief, who's doing something about them.
He said the department doesn't deserve the criticism that the two
officers' behavior is generating.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence came out at Flynn and Western's personnel hearing last
week that Reyes' brother Rudy - also a Casa Grande police officer -
made a tape that mocked Blacks, which was played for the chief in
1998 and has been used as entertainment at police parties and
briefings.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence also shows that Lupe Reyes was a victim of a police
prank. Another officer set off a firecracker while Reyes was
inspecting an apartment building at night. The firecracker made
Reyes believe gunshots had been fired. He called for backup, and
two innocent residents were detained for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   He said he never reported the incident because he believed it
was an isolated prank.
</P>
<P>
   Both Reyes are sons of Pinal County Sheriff Frank Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   Pranks, racial profiling and harassment of minorities have never
been condoned by the department, Lupe Reyes said.
</P>
<P>
   The phone calls are embarrassments, but the chief's disciplinary
reaction deserves praise, not criticism, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the community doesn't like what they're hearing, if the
community is outraged, they need to support our chief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Bridges, 82, sat in the audience of the two officers'
hearing last week and listened to the prank tapes. A 50-year Casa
Grande resident, Bridges didn't want to talk about the tapes, she
said she just came to watch and listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with the police,'' she said. ``When I came
here, the schools were segregated; everything was segregated.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at edythe.jensen(a)arizona republic.com or
(602) 444-7939.
</P>
<P>
   Photos by Jennifer Grimes/The Arizona RepublicAt a hearing
Wednesday night, Casa Grande police Officers Chris Western (left)
and Galen Flynn learned that the City Council upheld their
punishment for racial pranks.Police Chief Robert Huddleston is
questioned during a hearing at the Casa Grande City Council
Chambers.
</P>
</TEXT>
