<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL PRESEASON GAMES ARE HIGHWAY ROBBERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ In the never-ending search for truth, justice
and a single legitimate reason for preseason NFL games, we bring
you these late-breaking developments Sunday night from Texas
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman still wears No. 8 and can, indeed, overthrow Joey
Galloway and Rocket Ismail (and you said he couldn't do it).
</P>
<P>
   George Teague continues to happily deliver bone-crushing shots
to any exposed rib cage in his general vicinity. Check with Oakland
rookie wideout Marcus Knight _ assuming he's breathing again _ for
further details.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-year-old girl broke the sound barrier singing the national
anthem (but she still didn't scream as loudly as Knight when Teague
hit him).
</P>
<P>
   It's safest to celebrate long interception returns ``after''
you're in the end zone, not before (look out behind you, Stephen
Fisher!).
</P>
<P>
   As usual, no lead is safe when the Cowboys' third-teamers are in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   An announced crowd of 56,878 paid upward of $61 a ticket to see
the Dallas Cowboys blow a 17-3 halftime lead and lose 21-20 when
the Raiders scored a touchdown and a 2-point conversion in the
game's final 68 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the meaningless details.
</P>
<P>
   If you were one of those fanning yourself with a program in the
Texas Stadium sauna Sunday night, crisis counselors are standing by
at our phone banks as we speak, ready to offer free psychological
counseling. Just dial 1-800-GET-A-LIFE.
</P>
<P>
   And even if you spent the better part of four hours watching
from the relative coolness of your air-conditioned living room,
don't act so smug. You missed a feisty John Wayne festival ('']Sons
of Katie Elder, Rio Lobo, Big Jake'') on TBS.
</P>
<P>
   I had to be there; it's my job. What's your excuse?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, I almost forgot. In one of the biggest boondoggles in
sports history, Tex Schramm _ no, somewhat surprisingly it wasn't
Jerry Jones _ some years ago came up with the idea of tacking the
Cowboys' annual slate of preseason games onto the team's
season-ticket package. This forces fans who want to see legitimate
regular-season games to buy the preseason games, too.
</P>
<P>
   Master swindlers like Al Capone have landed in The Big House for
far less devious scams. Tex, instead, was ushered into the Hall of
Fame on the shoulders of joyous NFL owners, who still can't thank
him enough.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's your out. You just couldn't find anyone else stupid
enough to take the tickets off your hands.
</P>
<P>
   You get my drift. Preseason games _ even those with a
cliff-hanger ending like Sunday night's _ are about as useless as
cream gravy when the biscuits run out.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because there might not have been a single player on the
field in the fourth quarter who would actually be there under
similar circumstances during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a fortuitous pass interference penalty against the
Raiders and Fisher's should-have-been-a-touchdown interception and
62-yard return to the Oakland 4, Dallas' first-team offense scored
three times from the red zone and built a 17-3 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted (the first offensive unit) to get a more extended
period of time on the field because their opportunities have been
so limited so far,'' head coach Dave Campo said. ``Our plan was to
see those guys get 25 to 27 snaps and I think we got close to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Thank God we got their butts off the field before
anybody got seriously hurt (Rocket Ismail did leave with a sprained
thumb).
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively they moved the ball a little on us, even our first
unit, but we were able to come up with a few big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Wait'll I get those defensive linemen back in
Wichita Falls this week, I'll show 'em some heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying a lot of things, trying to get a look at
them on film, so everything we did probably didn't look as clean as
you would like,'' Aikman acknowledged. ``I did like us putting
points on the board with three possessions, especially with
touchdowns in the red zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: We were actually pretty damn sloppy but that pass
interference penalty saved our butts.
</P>
<P>
   The questionable flag on Charles Woodson defending against Wane
McGarrity on a pass that was likely uncatchable gave the Cowboys a
28-yard gift early in the second quarter and set up Chris Warren's
1-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes later Fisher picked off an ill-advised Bobby Hoying
lob in the right flat and had such clear sailing to the end zone,
he started jabbing his right finger in the air as he crossed the
10, just before Oakland's Kenny Shedd ran him down from behind.
Michael Wiley, battling for the third running back spot behind
Emmitt Smith and Warren, found the end zone on a fourth-and-one
play.
</P>
<P>
   The pass interference penalty and interception were the two
biggest plays of the game right up until the Raiders' Scott
Dreisbach, listed fourth at quarterback on their depth chart, hit
Willie Tate in the end zone from the 15 with 1:08 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Dreisbach then found David Dunn open for the 2-point conversion,
sentencing the Cowboys to an 0-3 preseason start.
</P>
<P>
   Counting preseason wins or losses, though, is sort of like
counting sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Keep it up and you're guaranteed to doze off. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
