A0787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN14-COX     08-14 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Gore has always been a decent man
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The widely held notion that Al Gore hired on the overtly
religious Sen. Joseph Lieberman as his running mate in order to
wash himself of scandal raises an awkward question. Dare we ask,
``What scandal?''
</P>
<P>
   Two matters are charged against the vice president's account,
neither amounting to a hill of beans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore phoned for political contributions from the White House
using a Democratic National Committee credit card. If that violated
the law against fund-rasing on government property _ and it
probably didn't _ the violation was purely technical. The law was
meant to prevent elected officials from shaking down government
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress use cell phones to hustle dollars from their
offices. The only distinction between that practice and Gore's was
that the vice president's phone was tethered. Scandal? Please.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger stink was been over the vice president's presence at
a Buddhist temple where money was harvested for the Clinton
re-election campaign. Gore knew the event was fund-related, but
there is no evidence he knew the contributions had been gimmicked
in a way that was illegal and would have to be returned, as they
were.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president should have known better, but in a campaign
in which both parties grubbed shamelessly for money _ the Democrats
more grotesquely than the Republicans, though to lesser success _
Gore's sin was more of omission than commission.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. That's the whole Gore scandal record. For the rest,
he is being held guilty by association for the Clinton scandals,
and those _ wait a minute. When you think about it, even those are
blowing away like dark clouds in a high wind.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the president nor Hillary Clinton actually murdered
their friend Vincent Foster, put out a contract on him or even
muttered, ``Will not someone rid me of this troublesome fellow?''
</P>
<P>
   The firing of the White House travel staff in the blundering
first days of the administration was politically bollixed but it
wasn't illegal, and the special prosecutor could find nothing worse
than ordinary political spin in the First Lady's testimony about
her role in it.
</P>
<P>
   To little notice _ page 28 in the New York Times and many papers
skipped it altogether _ the independent counsel recently concluded
that, for all the hollering otherwise, the appearance in White
House computers of FBI files on, among others, some prominent
Republicans was only a bureaucratic snafu, innocent of partisan
purpose or consequence _ just as the administration has been saying
all along.
</P>
<P>
   We're still to hear the last word on Whitewater _ remember
Whitewater? _ but as time has gone on, that supposed scandal has
looked more like a miasma of confusing piffle than like anything
worse. We'll see, but in any event Gore wasn't anywhere around it.
Nor he was never within even air-kiss range of Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman aside, Al Gore, a life-long straight arrow and solid
family man, cleans up nicely all on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
