<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0855 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-NY-GUIDEBOOKS-TEXT-     08-14 2204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-GUIDEBOOKS-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY CAME, THEY SAW . . . THEY BROUGHT GUIDEBOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are now official surveys to confirm that tourists are
taking over New York City.
</P>
<P>
   With a population approaching 9 million, the city played host to
about four tourists per resident last year, according to federal
surveys and tourist research announced by city officials last week.
The figures pushed New York up into second place for tourist
destinations in the United States, bested only by Orlando, Fla.,
home of Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Most of New York City's 36.7 million visitors came from within
the United States, but foreigners made up about 20 percent of the
total. Britain, Canada, Germany, Japan and France had the honor of
providing the largest numbers of New York City's 6.6 million
international visitors.
</P>
<P>
   So how do they know where to go? What do they expect of the
strange and fearsome New Yorker? What is considered surprising and
noteworthy?
</P>
<P>
   The questions are all the more interesting because the answers,
as found in excerpts from foreign guidebooks, reveal as much about
the culture the travelers are coming from as the one they intend to
gawk at.
</P>
<P>
   And they also demonstrate, as many New Yorkers can testify, that
no one has warned tourists not to come to a dead stop on Times
Square's sidewalks at rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANDREA KANNAPELL
</P>
<P>
   Japan
</P>
<P>
   From ``Chikyu no Aruki-kata (How to Walk on Earth),'' Vol. 38:
New York 2000-2001 edition, published by Diamond Big Co.
</P>
<P>
   AT THE MOVIES: As the film starts, the audience gets absorbed
immediately. Although you are not allowed to make noise in the
cinema, some people shout and cry. Literally, it is breathless
movie-watching. If you are watching action film, there will be a
storm of applause and cheers at victorious scenes. This noise isn't
unpleasant but heightens excitement.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ON SUNDAY: You see a lot of people sitting inside cafes and on
benches on the street, reading weighty The New York Times Sunday
edition, holding a cup of coffee in their hand.... People don't
read everything carried in there but only those sections that are
necessary to them, which is the New York style. Apart from reading
materials, in terms of information gathering, it is useful for even
those travellers who are not good at English. Even if you can't
read it, you will be in a jolly good mood just to open its pages
and look at it. It's a bit heavy to take back to Japan but it may
make a good souvenir. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S OK IN HARLEM: There are frequent muggings and violence in
back streets. It is said drug transactions take place in abandoned
buildings, and drug addicts reportedly won't hesitate to kill
others in order to get $50. . . . New Yorkers dislike to venture
into such areas, and tourists should stay away from them. In fact,
the atmosphere changes drastically when you go off the main street.
Taxis, too, don't want to go into narrow streets. For some reason,
there are a lot of people in restricted buildings. Is it meaningful
to visit such areas for sightseeing? It is OK to go to church to
listen to gospel or visit a jazz club, but you shouldn't go to
observe poor people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ON DENTAL VALUES: It depends on the kind of treatment and skills
of the doctor, but perhaps it may be cheaper to buy a return air
ticket and come back to Japan for treatment. However, it is true
that dental treatment in the U.S. is far advanced compared to that
in Japan. It could be said that once you have dental treatment
there, that tooth wouldn't require any more treatment for the rest
of your life. Also, treatment is completed within 4 to 5 days [in
Japan, it takes a few weeks to fill a cavity), so maybe it is a
good idea to make it an opportunity to expose yourself to American
dental treatment. It is up to you to decide which is inexpensive.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   China &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``CityPack _ New York,'' Chinese-language edition,
published by Joint Publishing Ltd., Hong Kong, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   STREET MANNERS: Don't talk to the crazy people on the street,
even though they may seem fun to be with. . . . New York women are
very straightforward and can adapt well on the streets. So if
someone harasses you, be like New York ladies: speak your mind and
tell the person to blow off.
</P>
<P>
   Germany
</P>
<P>
   From ``Marco Polo _ New York,'' published by Mairs
Geographischer Verlag, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   RULES: Do not go to the park alone at night. And never carry
more than $50 in cash. Do not shop spontaneously. Shops on Fifth
Avenue which advertise ``going out of business'' sales are rarely
on the verge of actually closing. Do not eat from salad bars. They
are popular in delicatessens and self-service restaurants, but the
health commission warns that these unpackaged foods can make one
ill. . . . Do not count on seeing celebrities in restaurants which
have photos of famous people on the wall. The chances of seeing
Woody Allen or Madonna during a walk in Central Park or running
into Kevin Bacon or Demi Moore while shopping on Columbus Avenue
are greater. . . . Do not underestimate bicyclists. Always look
right and left even before crossing a one-way street, as bike
riders often speed in the opposite direction. Do not travel in
``gypsy cabs.'' New Yorkers do, but they also know how to negotiate
the right prices.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Goldstadt Fuehrer _ New York,'' published by
Goldstadtverlag, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   VALUABLES: When in a hotel room, always put the chain on the
door. Don't leave your key at reception. If a thief enters your
room, act as if you are sleeping. Call for help only after he has
left. . . . Don't visit deserted places like Central Park or the
Bowery at night. Don't ride elevators or enter subway stations
alone. Don't let your bags be carried by the mostly young men at
Penn or Grand Central Station as they will often disappear.
</P>
<P>
   THE COLOR OF MONEY: Be careful! Paper money is easy to confuse.
All bank notes are green and the same size. What makes them
different is the former president who appears on the front.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-NY-GUIDEBOOKS-TEXT-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: the front. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Czech Republic
</P>
<P>
   From ``Globetrotter Travel Guide _ New York,'' by Michael Leech,
published by New Holland Publishers, Czech edition: 1999, Geodezie
Brno.
</P>
<P>
   LOGIC DEFIED: In theory, it should be easy to get in and out of
the city. But the traffic becomes unbearable at times, resulting in
traffic jams. Moreover, winter frosts sometimes eat through the
asphalt, creating large and dangerous holes. In the spring, the
yellow taxicabs race through those holes tilted to a side.
</P>
<P>
   CHINATOWN REALITY: The streets are always full of people,
everything is incredibly dirty, the facades scream with tasteless
bright neons. Yes, on one hand this place does stink, but on the
other hand it emanates spirituality. One thing is sure: it does not
try to pretend anything.
</P>
<P>
   England
</P>
<P>
   From ``Manhattan,'' by Vanessa Letts, published by Cadogan.
</P>
<P>
   EAVESDROPPING: Keep your ears pricked at all times and you will
be as entertained as much by what you hear as by what you see.
Behind the gruff exteriors, Manhattanites are a wistful,
open-hearted lot, and, perhaps because over 40 per cent are
immigrants, they have a knack of muscling newcomers into instant
conversations which can culminate in lifelong friendships.
</P>
<P>
   DIALECT Bus drivers are a higher breed and will appreciate it if
you thank them as you disembark (one is said to salute his
passengers with ``Get'cher smile on, folks; nobody rides dis bus
today widdout a smile'').
</P>
<P>
   From ``New York City: The Rough Guide,'' by Martin Dunford and
Jack Holland.
</P>
<P>
   BOBBIES' COUSINS: The New York City Police _ the N.Y.P.D., a k a
``New York's Finest'' _ are for the most part approachable, helpful
and overworked. This means that asking directions gets a friendly
response, reporting a theft a weary ``Whaddya want me to do about
it'' _ and any smile is greatly appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   MOOD: A sense of nervy self-preservation is rife here. People
make studied efforts to avoid eye contact, and any unusual
behaviour clears a space immediately: the atmosphere of impending
violence is sometimes sniffable. . .
</P>
<P>
   New York's tension doesn't automatically mean violence; it's
largely due to the frenetic pace at which most of the city
operates. Take several million people, pump them full of caffeine,
make them believe that they have to get where they're going five
minutes faster than is actually possible, and pack them onto a tiny
island _ there's bound to be an edge in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ... Few people seem to have time for anything not on their
mental schedule. Even asking for directions on the street is best
done with an awareness of this, ideally while moving at the same
pace and in the same direction of the informant.
</P>
<P>
   From ``New York City (Condensed),'' published by Lonely Planet.
</P>
<P>
   EXTREMES: Dense, immense, intense _ there is no other place with
as much upfront allure. The bagels have the most cream cheese, the
panhandlers have the best stories, you can take your dog to church,
you can pray to Mecca (or Wiccan) in the street, sell lobster
bisque from a hot-dog stand and no one will bat an eyelid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   France
</P>
<P>
   From ``Le Guide du Routard,'' published by Hachette, 2000/01.
</P>
<P>
   PACE: Watch out, New Yorkers despise those who are on the slow
track. To take a break for them is a waste of time. One has to go
faster and faster.
</P>
<P>
   ONE CROWDED PARK: New Yorkers are crazy about sports: gym, body
building, jogging. They work out early in the morning or after
work. On Sundays, they all meet at Central Park where they jog,
bike or roller-blade.
</P>
<P>
   TAXI DRIVERS: Curiously, New York taxi drivers hardly speak
American, or even English. At least, not the same English as you
do. They are foreigners from Asia or Haiti. They are very nice and
don't mind driving you only a few blocks! A dream for the
Parisians, used to the arrogance of local drivers. Yet, their way
of driving is harsh; they might slam on the brakes and suddenly
speed up, insult other drivers. This is a part of the city's
climate.
</P>
<P>
   HEDONISM: Alcohol is still taboo in the U.S. American society,
very puritan and conservative, allows the free sale of arms but has
outrageous regulations for anything related to taboo pleasures
(sex, marijuana, alcohol and even some rock CDs, considered too
subversive). . . . You can buy a Kalaschnikov without any special
license, yet you will have to show your passport while buying a
simple beer. You should never go out without your passport, as some
bars may request it. They are crazy, these Americans.
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE: Americans drink all the time _ Coca-cola, Seven-up, Dr
Pepper, Fresca, Tab and other soft drinks. Thus, in many places you
can get as many refills of soda as you want. If you want to avoid
drinking what is called regular or American coffee, which tastes
like dishwater, buy some Nescafe and add it in.
</P>
<P>
   CULINARY MATTERS: To say that an average American has bad eating
habits and eats too much is at the same time true and too easy.
Every region has its particularity: organic and vegetarian cusine
in California; cosmopolitan and diverse in New York. . . .
Americans are rather partial to food. You will be struck by the
number of overweight people.
</P>
<P>
   . . . If you eat at chic places keep your fork in your right
hand and put your left hand on your knee. Otherwise they will take
you for a country bumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   From ``U.S.A.: Est et Sud,'' Guides Bleus, published by Hachette
Tourisme, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   MORE CULINARY MATTERS: Please note the strange custom of the
doggy-bag. It is common at restaurants to take away your leftovers;
you get a bag for a dog filled with food even if you do not have a
dog.
</P>
<P>
   From ``New-York,'' by Egle de Bure, published by Guide Marcus,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   AND MORE: &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . We have often criticized New York cuisine for
being mediocre. This is not true anymore as New York has become one
of the world capitals of bonne cuisine. First, the service is
great, you are treated well (except in the fashionable restaurants,
but this is a part of the contract). . . .
</P>
<P>
   VOCABULARY Cockroach: famous New York bug that is found
everywhere, even at very fancy places.
</P>
<P>
   Italy
</P>
<P>
   From ``Guidebook for New York and Washington,'' published by
Touring Club Italiano, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE IN MOTION: Walking is important to New Yorkers. Numerous
office workers, at exactly 5 o'clock, will walk out of their
buildings, quickly taking off their dress shoes and putting on
sneakers for their long treks to the subway or buses. Like in the
Woody Allen movies (a New Yorker to the extreme), people are
constantly walking, not just for exercise, but to relieve stress
and to socialize. ``Will you come with me?'' is a common question
that usually ends up in a 20-, 30- or 50-block walk.
</P>
<P>
   LYRICISM: The truth is that it is New York, not Washington,
D.C., that is the capital of America. It is Gotham, not Hollywood,
that is the factory of dreams. It is part of our collective
imagination. . . .  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 0922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
