<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-JEWS-U.S.-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN NOMINATION REFLECTS ACCEPTANCE OF JEWS IN AMERICAN
MAINSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
(editors: optional sidebar at end of article) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
 &HT;    While Ron Wyden was campaigning for a U.S. Senate seat in Oregon
in 1996, a local newspaper ran a letter denouncing him as an
``Ashkenazi'' _ clearly a code word for Jew. It set off an uproar
and some soul-searching in Oregon. How dare a responsible paper
publish such anti-Semitism? But what happened next was instructive:
the editors apologized, explaining that they had never heard the
term and were unaware it could give offense.
 &HT;    Wyden, whose parents fled Nazi Germany, is now the Democratic
senator representing a state in which Jews account for less than 1
percent of the population. Oregon, by the way, is home to not a few
militia members and black-helicopter conspiracy buffs. And yet,
Wyden says he encountered only a ``small hard core'' of haters.
 &HT;    The tale of Wyden bears retelling for those who reacted to the
news of Al Gore's selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut
as a running mate with the queasy suspicion that this just cannot
be good for the Jews. Will it awaken the sleeping giant of
anti-Semitism, they asked themselves? Will Jews be the scapegoats
if the Gore-Lieberman ticket is defeated?
 &HT;    Although bigotry thrives, Jews in this country have never before
had so little reason to worry. The reason is that Jews are no
longer considered ``the other'' in America.
 &HT;    As Wyden found in Oregon, even where Jews are few, acceptance is
at an all-time high. Americans typically either see Jews as
neighbors or kin, or as objects of fascination, or have no
experience with them at all. Paradoxically, the reasons have little
to do with television hits like ``Seinfeld'' and everything to do
with the nation's intense Christian faith. Visit the most
conservative evangelical church in America today and you will hear
from the pulpit mention of ``our Judeo-Christian heritage.''
President Ronald Reagan used the phrase in speeches, and the
concept has been thoroughly assimilated by the religious right.
Gary Bauer invoked it on the campaign trail.
 &HT;    Mainline Protestants talk of Jews and Christians as ``people of
the Book,'' the Old Testament that both faiths share. Pope John
Paul II stood in a Roman synagogue and referred to Jews as ``our
elder brothers,'' setting a tone for reconciliation that has
reverberated through the Roman Catholic Church.
 &HT;    More than mere tokenism, this language represents a major shift.
A broad swath of Christians in this country have begun to
recognize, to study and even embrace the Jewish roots of their
faith. Most Christians still believe that Jews would be better off
accepting Christ, but respect for Jews who do not has grown
substantially, scholars say.
 &HT;    ``I think there is a growing rapprochement and a sense of
commonality,'' said Max L. Stackhouse, professor of Christian
social ethics at Princeton Theological Seminary. ``Part of it has
to do with the increased encounters with others of the world
religions and the new sense of pluralism in this country.''
 &HT;    In other words, to the average American Christian who sees
Buddhist books on the best-seller list and Hindu temples rising in
the suburbs, Jews seem downright familiar.
 &HT;    ``Jews are more like us,'' said Stackhouse, summing up a common
attitude among Christians. ``We feel greater affinity to those who
are Jewish.''
 &HT;    Another factor is intermarriage, each wedding vow a chink
closing up the old religious divide. The 50 percent intermarriage
rate that for 10 years has caused angst among Jews has a flip side:
more and more Americans count a Jew in the family tree. When Uncle
Michael goes upstairs to read the children a bedtime story, it
becomes harder to regard Jews as ``the other.''
 &HT;    But what really keeps many Jews awake at night is the fear that
every new Jewish-sounding surname in the headlines only stokes the
widely held conspiracy theories that the world is run by Jews.
 &HT;    Someone who knows the conspiracy thinking well is Paul T.
Coughlin, an evangelical Christian who wrote ``Secrets, Plots and
Hidden Agendas'' (InterVarsity Press, 2000), because he was stunned
by the amount of conspiratorial talk from callers to his Christian
radio show in Oregon.
 &HT;    ``There are millions of people who feel that Jews control the
economy through what's called the New World Order, and people on
the far right argue that this is all dictated in the Book of
Revelation where the Apostle John wrote about a world government,''
he said.
 &HT;    But surprisingly, Coughlin said, even for a large majority of
those believers _ all but the anti-Semitic and racist fringe _
Judaism is ``not an issue.''
 &HT;    Why? They believe that membership in the New World Order is
determined ``more by ideology than heritage,'' he said. ``It's
actually liberal elitists, the media, people in universities, who
are going to control the New World Order.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (MORE)
 &HT;     
 
 BC-JEWS-U.S.-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT  
 UNDATED: World Order.''  
 &HT;     
 &HT;    Although liberal Jews are suspects, Lieberman, as an Orthodox
Jew who represents conservative family values, is not, Coughlin
said. The senator may convince the conspiracy thinkers that
``Jewish'' and ``liberal'' are not synonymous, he said. He adds
that many of these same Christian conspiracy thinkers actually
venerate Jews because the Bible talks of God's covenant with
Abraham, Isaac and Jacob. ``It is actually beneficial for Lieberman
to be Jewish,'' he said.
 &HT;    This is not to claim that anti-Semitism has been eradicated,
like smallpox. It lives on, mutates, makes people sick. Wyden says
he received a heap of hate mail when, in a memorable moment
broadcast on television, he asked a lineup of tobacco executives at
a congressional hearing whether nicotine is addictive. The
anti-Semitic letters came mostly from those in tobacco-growing
country, accusing him of destroying their livelihoods, but were
filled with ``religious animus,'' he said.
 &HT;    In the Midwest, the Rev. David Ostendorf, executive director of
the Center for New Community in Chicago, said: ``We did a seminar a
few months ago with five or six Chicago high schools, and when we
asked how many of you have seen racist symbols like swastikas in
your neighborhoods, 90 percent of the kids raised their hands. It
kind of jarred us.''
 &HT;    The selection of Lieberman is likely to uncap a geyser of ugly
extremism. Already, Internet message boards have been swamped with
anti-Semitic postings. The head of the local chapter of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in
Dallas rambled on about greedy Jews on a talk show.
 &HT;    The response was telling. Scores of people posted Internet
messages expressing their disgust at anti-Semitism. The NAACP
official was immediately dismissed.
 &HT;    ``You have your crazies,'' said Jerome A. Chanes, the editor of
``Anti-Semitism in America Today: Exploding the Myths'' (Carol
Publishing, 1995). ``But in the year 2000, whatever anti-Semitism
does exist does not compromise the ability of any Jew to
participate in the workings of society at any level.''
 &HT;    Gallup polls show that 92 percent of Americans say they would
vote for a qualified Jew for president, up from 62 percent in 1958.
Other polls that ask the question differently show similar results.
Even if twice as many people are lying _ and respondents to polls
gauging tolerance often do _ that is still a huge approval rating,
Chanes said. The polls indicate that it is far worse to be a Mormon
or an atheist running for office than a Jew.
 &HT;    So why do polls also show that Jews see anti-Semitism as a
serious problem in this country, and one likely to worsen? There is
a generational divide, said Spencer Blakeslee, author of ``The
Death of American Anti-Semitism'' (Praeger), between older,
immigrant Jews who experienced the most vicious anti-Semitism and
``the post-World War II generation,'' for whom the Holocaust is
history.
 &HT;    A headline in last week's New York Observer rendered the divided
response to the Lieberman candidacy partly in Yiddish: ``Alter
Kockers Shaking, Pishers Are Thrilled.''
 &HT;    ``We have a lot of Jews walking around who are frightened at
things they need not be frightened about,'' said Blakeslee, a
sociologist at Framingham State College in Massachusetts. ``When in
the world are Jews going to learn to take yes for an answer?''
 &HT;    Wyden said that for him the challenge is ``not overt
anti-Semitism or prejudice, but that there may be a significant
number of people who have had little or no contact with Jews,
aren't familiar with the Holocaust and so much of the history that
Jews are sensitive to.''
 &HT;    Wyden says he considers any campaign for a Jewish candidate to
be ``a terrific opportunity, because the slate is clean.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;     THE ORIGINAL LIEBERMAN   
 &HT;     By RICK MARIN    
 &HT;     c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the exhaustive analysis of Al Gore's selection of Sen. Joseph
Lieberman as his running mate, one factor has been strangely
overlooked: Lieberman's uncanny resemblance to Sam Jaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Voters of a certain generation may not be able to look at the
man who would be vice president without thinking of the late
character actor best remembered as the High Lama in ``Lost
Horizon,'' Dr. Zorba in the TV series ``Ben Casey,'' and Gunga Din.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is known as a religious man; Jaffe often played
priests, though he too was Jewish, born Shalom Jaffe in 1891 on
Manhattan's Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   In a career that spanned half a century (Jaffe died in 1984), he
played only a few Jewish roles. In ``Ben-Hur,'' he was Saimonides,
Charlton Heston's family retainer and book-keeper, who utters the
line: ``Judah Ben-Hur! You've come back to us like a returning
faith!''
</P>
<P>
   But it is in ``Gentlemen's Agreement'' that the connection with
the senator takes on cosmic meaning. Here, in Elia Kazan's
indictment of anti-Semitism, Jaffe played a Jewish professor. His
name? Lieberman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
