 &HT;    
 &HT;     THE ORIGINAL LIEBERMAN   
 &HT;     By RICK MARIN    
 &HT;     c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the exhaustive analysis of Al Gore's selection of Sen. Joseph
Lieberman as his running mate, one factor has been strangely
overlooked: Lieberman's uncanny resemblance to Sam Jaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Voters of a certain generation may not be able to look at the
man who would be vice president without thinking of the late
character actor best remembered as the High Lama in ``Lost
Horizon,'' Dr. Zorba in the TV series ``Ben Casey,'' and Gunga Din.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is known as a religious man; Jaffe often played
priests, though he too was Jewish, born Shalom Jaffe in 1891 on
Manhattan's Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   In a career that spanned half a century (Jaffe died in 1984), he
played only a few Jewish roles. In ``Ben-Hur,'' he was Saimonides,
Charlton Heston's family retainer and book-keeper, who utters the
line: ``Judah Ben-Hur! You've come back to us like a returning
faith!''
</P>
<P>
   But it is in ``Gentlemen's Agreement'' that the connection with
the senator takes on cosmic meaning. Here, in Elia Kazan's
indictment of anti-Semitism, Jaffe played a Jewish professor. His
name? Lieberman.
</P>
