<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0859 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-XGAMES-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-14 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-XGAMES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS EXTREMELY SPORTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ See. See Lee. See Lee Dansie, a champion street
luger with a Mick Jagger haircut, come streaking through the fog
toward the Pacific Ocean on a flying bit of metal, shoes smoking.
</P>
<P>
   It's the 2000 X Games, in which some 450 athletes from 23
countries participate in such once-renegade ``extreme'' sports as
dirt-bike jumping, aggressive in-line skating, street luge and
sky-surfing. That last is the ultimate exercise in narcissism, in
which a surf-rider and a camera flyer, sky-surfboards strapped to
their feet and parachutes to their backs, jump simultaneously out
of a plane at 13,000 feet, and fall for 9,000 feet or so,
spiraling, flipping and diving as they hurl merrily toward earth at
about 180 mph, filming all the while.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, this city of extremes, both topographical and
economic, has embraced the X games with messianic fervor. Last
summer, the event drew over 270,000 spectators, not to mention over
5 million ESPN viewers, including 37 percent of all male teen-agers
in the United States, according to Nielsen analysis for the
company. (The games will start on Thursday; delayed television
coverage starts on ABC and ESPN this Saturday.)
</P>
<P>
   Josh Blackman, 5, standing bug-eyed on Friday as the lugers,
bigger boys with iron abdominals, whizzed past him in a practice
event, succinctly summed up the appeal of the lugers: ``They turn
and they wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   The games, now six years old _ an eternity in youth culture _ as
well as the newer Gravity Games on NBC, are spawning extremes of
their own. This fall, for instance, will see the debut of not one
but two brands of extreme sports trading cards. The stunt biker
Dave Mirra, the Michael Jordan of the dirt set, has his own chewing
gum (Dave Mirra's BMX Bubble Gum), as well as his own pro model
signature Adidas sneaker as well as a cereal en route.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous athletes, including the skateboarder Tony Hawk, ace
executor of ``the 900'' (two and a half turns in the air on a
skateboard off a vertical ramp), have their own videogames, and
extreme action figures and finger-size street luges and dirt bikes
are popping up at toy stores near you. ( Dansie, soon to be an
action figure, said he was looking forward to his check.)
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the unkindest blow to the dwindling band of athletes
who are corporation-shunning street-purists, a Barney-colored
miniature ``vert ramp'' with skateboard now comes with every
McDonald's Happy Meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the way things work,'' said Chad Kagy, a 21-year-old
stunt biker and bronze medalist from Gilroy, Calif., who may
resemble Harry Potter on his Nimbus 2000 broomstick as he performs
his favorite trick this week. Dubbed the Superman Seat Grab, the
move has his feet soaring behind the bike while his left hand grabs
the seat and his right hand spins the handlebars (got that?). ``One
day you're riding with your friends,'' he said. ``The next day
people want you to represent their bubble gum.''
</P>
<P>
   The extremely big business of extreme sports has been fueled not
only by television but by extreme agents, who now represent
approximately 20 percent of all athletes competing in the games.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme marketing is extending far beyond sports figures and
products. In sportswear, ankle-high skateboarding shoes are
replacing hightops, and cargo pants with extra pockets have become
teen-age uniforms. Adolescent males and those beyond can avail
themselves of Right Guard Xtreme Deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Astephen, founder of The Familie, an alternative youth
marketing agency that represents extreme athletes, says that the
days of ``hey bro'' sponsorship were over, which he defined as an
ex-rider coming up to a rider and saying: ``Hey bro, what's going
on? Wear our sticker and we'll give you a couple of bucks.''
Corporations, Astephen said, have woken up to the fact that extreme
athletes speak to the lucrative market of Y Generation (12- to
24-year-old) males and their $650 billion in annual spending power.
The lure: individualistic sports that look cool and don't require a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are tangible heroes,'' Astephen said of his stable.
``Tony Hawk tours local skate parks and skates with your son or
daughter. When's the last time you saw Tiger Woods or Michael
Jordan doing that?''
</P>
<P>
   Looking svelte for a 47-year-old in racing leathers, Steve
Fernando, a Los Angeles firefighter who took up street luging after
watching it on television, offered a contrasting theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people are having virtual thrills through computers
and Playstations,'' he said. ``We're an adjunct on TV, seen through
a point-of-view camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bryant, editor of Men's Journal, a bible of testosterone,
notes that every generation has its instruments of rebellion,
whether electric guitars or scooters whizzing up Eighth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme sports, he said, ``reject the apparent dullness of
modern life, at least as perceived by a 20-year-old.'' He sees them
as an attempt to ``juice up life,'' to inject a note of edginess
into a flush economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point where certain socioeconomic groups are
thinking, if life is full of so many possibilities, why am I not
having more fun?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, of course, is that efforts to market the extreme
naturally take the edge right out of it. Or, as Bryant put it,
``What could be more mundane than deodorant?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 0925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
