<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      08-14 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER NOT TO RISK THE RISKS AND WAIT FOR PENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. My husband is wrestling with a dilemma involving a small
pension. Is he better off leaving the money where it is, or would
he be better off to cash in now and invest the proceeds in mutual
funds?
</P>
<P>
   P.G., Dorchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the odds are he would be better off waiting for the
pension payments.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the math I did: If he were to take the $6,500 and invest
it in a mutual fund portfolio that averaged 10 percent annual
returns, he would accumulate $10,693 after five years. If he then
began withdrawing $170 a month and returns remained at 10 percent,
the account would be depleted after 89 1/2 months, just less than 7
1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if he takes the cash, he will shoulder the risk that
comes with investing in stocks and stock funds. With a long bull
market behind us, I am not sanguine about getting short-term
returns from stocks in the neighborhood of 10 percent. So my guess
is that the odds are higher that the account would be depleted
before 7 1/2 years, rather than after. If he takes the pension,
there is minimal risk.
</P>
<P>
   That risk involves the terms of the pension. Would the $170 a
month be paid only as long as he is living, or in the event of his
death would it be paid to you? If both of you were to pass away,
would the remaining payments end, or would they go to your estate?
Do either of you face any predictable health risk that makes you
particularly unlikely to reach age 75? If I were you, I would
consider the answers to these questions _ and then probably wait
for the pension.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I expect to retire at age 65 if good health and the job
market permits, and at age 62 if I'm in poor health. I am acutely
aware of the inflation factor, which means my current funds will be
worth about one-half of what they are now in 10 years or so. I am
running out of time and must overcome my fear of investing so that
I can add to the existing balance and buying power. My last
full-time job ended in 1998 and I have been having trouble finding
another permanent full-time job. I expect to be divorced soon, but
that should not affect my finances either way.
</P>
<P>
   H.B., Garden Grove, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. The inflation factor isn't quite as bad as you imagine. If
inflation runs at 3.5 percent, you will need $141.06 in 10 years to
buy what $100 buys today. On the other hand, a huge amount of your
money _ $98,980 _ is doing little or nothing for you. If your
checking account is a NOW account, you are probably getting a
nominal interest return, but that $31,400 in the safe deposit box
is simply rotting. I calculated your total portfolio return at 4.4
percent, after making a estimate of a 2 percent yield on your
checking account balance. You can do a great deal better than that
without assuming any more risk.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, I suggest you begin by calculating just how much
you really need in emergency savings, perhaps tallying 50 percent
of your annual living expenses. Whatever that figure comes to, that
should be the maximum left either in your checking account or in a
money market fund. I would suggest a maximum $5,000 target balance
for your checking account, and obviously you want the rest of it in
the money fund with the higher yield.
</P>
<P>
   Then scour out that safe deposit box. Put this in carefully
chosen CDs. Then, as your various current CDs mature, replace them
with the new CDs. By carefully selected CDs, I mean CDs that are at
or near the nation's highest interest rate at the time you purchase
them. Currently the best CD rates in the nation are 7.91 percent
for a five-year Jumbo CD. A jumbo is a CD of at least $100,000.
Limit each CD account to that $100,000, so you will enjoy the
maximum FDIC insurance on the accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, all I have done is suggest you move from poor and
mediocre cash-type investments. That is partly because I don't like
to suggest that people who have developed very conservative saving
patterns make dramatic changes, and partly because I think moving a
large amount of money into the stock markets at this time
represents a significant risk.
</P>
<P>
   But what I do suggest is that you open a mutual fund account for
your ongoing savings. Try to figure out how much you can save from
your earnings and establish a regular monthly amount to contribute
to a conservative mutual fund account. What I suggest for you is a
balanced fund _ these funds balance a stock portfolio that is
typically 60 to 65 percent of their assets with a portfolio of
bonds representing the balance. Excellent examples of funds in this
category are Vanguard Balanced Index, and Fidelity Puritan.
</P>
<P>
   Why would I be comfortable advising that your ongoing savings go
into a vehicle dominated by stocks while I am leery of moving your
current investments to stocks? Because what I am suggesting is a
discipline called dollar-cost averaging. By this plan, you
establish a set amount and shovel it into your investment at
specific predetermined periods, regardless of the state of the
market. When the market is low, it means you are buying cheaper
shares, thus bringing your average cost per share down. When the
market is up _ well, that's why you established the account in the
first place. You should expect long-term returns in the
neighborhood of 8 to 9 percent from a balanced fund account.
</P>
<P>
   If you can afford to pay the taxes and forego the deduction you
would be entitled to on a contribution to a traditional IRA, I
suggest the first $2,000 you save each year go into a Roth IRA in
your balanced fund. If you think the tax deduction would be
important, then put your first $2,000 of savings into a traditional
IRA in the fund. You could then open a taxable account in the fund
for additional savings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 35 and single and have a 401(k) account and some small
investments for my retirement. I don't make a lot of money but
would like to start tucking away a few dollars every month to help
my best friend's daughter go to college. What are the options for
setting up this fund? I'd like to limit the taxes I'll pay on the
money, even if it is just on the earned interest. I'd also like to
make sure the child won't have to pay a lot of taxes when the money
is transferred to her.
</P>
<P>
   J.H., Vista, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, I think the logical starting point would be to
establish an Education IRA for the child, in which you could
deposit up to $500 a year. Provided the money is used for
educational expenses, it can be withdrawn with no tax liability at
all. Anybody can contribute to an Education IRA, provided the
contributor's modified adjusted gross income doesn't exceed
$110,000 for an individual or $160,000 for a joint return. There is
no tax deduction for contributions to an Education IRA.
</P>
<P>
   You should also note that the $500 maximum annual contribution
to an IRA applies to the child and not to the donor, so you should
make sure the parents are not using this vehicle before you go
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback to the Education IRA is that the amount in it
would be factored in if the student applies for financial aid.
Still, from the student's standpoint, it's a gift, and a handsome
one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose you decide to hit the midpoint of your anticipated
gifts, at $75 a month. This would mean you would have to save the
other $400 a year in some other vehicle. This could be deposited in
an account in the child's name, with yourself or the child's
parents as custodian. But such savings would enjoy no tax break,
and, again, they would work against the child in applications for
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   The general rule of thumb, unless the family of the child is
staggeringly rich, is not to put college savings in the student's
name. In this case, since the assets of the parents are considered
as a factor in determining the eligibility for financial
assistance, it would probably be better if you saved that
additional $400 a year in your own name.
</P>
<P>
   As for an investment vehicle, you have a broad choice, ranging
from CDs to mutual funds to stock brokerage accounts. If I were
doing it I would go with a plain vanilla stock fund, such as
Vanguard's Index 500. Vanguard will allow an Education IRA to be
opened with a $500 minimum deposit, so you would have to save
elsewhere for a while until you could make the first contribution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
