<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-REVERSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE YOUR DOLLAR IS ON THE BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I still get wistful at the thought of the TV ads Mercata.com ran
this spring: A fast-talking auctioneer accepts lower and lower bids
as giddy buyers race to lock in the rock-bottom prices.
</P>
<P>
   If only auctions _ or e-commerce _ really worked that way.
</P>
<P>
   They don't, of course, even for collective-buying companies such
as Mercata. Such sites offer volume discounts to Web-heads who come
together and place orders en masse, but that's hardly the same
thing as having companies bid down prices just for little old you.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, life imitates art. Or at least artful
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Web sites recently began promoting themselves as
``reverse-auction,'' ``upside-down auction,'' or
``reverse-marketplace'' services. Regardless of the name, the idea
is pretty much the same in every case. (And it looks a lot like the
Mercata advertisement, if not the Mercata.com service.)
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the sites turn the normal auction process on its
head. Rather than having buyers bid on items listed by sellers,
these services have sellers compete to fill orders submitted by
individual buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new sites focus on small businesses
(www.bizbuyer.com and www.onvia.com, for example); others target
niche audiences (such as www.improvenet.com and www.teetime.com).
But the best are geared to replacing the yellow pages as the place
everyday folks can go to find local service providers _ a plumber,
say, or a mechanic to work on your '67 Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is fairly simple: You go to one of these sites, type in
your ZIP code along with what you want and how much you're willing
to pay, and then you sit back and wait for local companies to beat
a path to your e-mailbox. Some sites even provide information on
providers' track records on customer service to help you sift
through the offers.
</P>
<P>
   How many of the reverse-auction sites will survive remains to be
seen, but the market is huge. Services represent more than 70
percent of the US economy, and local services represent one of the
gaping holes in the Web. Sites that can tap into that are likely to
make money for themselves, while saving time and cash for the rest
of us. (Businesses typically pay a percentage of sales they
generate from site referrals.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the early contenders:
</P>
<P>
   _ www.eFrenzy.com, unlike some of the other sites, is focused
almost exclusively on the consumer market for local services. It
features 10 categories of service providers, with dozens of
subcategories, ranging from career counseling to dog-walking.
</P>
<P>
   To use the site, you first have to take five or 10 minutes to
register. As these things go, it isn't overly intrusive or
time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   One of the advantages of eFrenzy is that you can read or post
reviews of service providers. And a la Web-auction pioneer eBay,
the directory of past reviews helps future clients decide whom to
do business with.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.eWanted.com works on a different principle. Rather than
send your request to professionals who can bid on it, eWanted posts
it (anonymously, of course) for the whole world to see. Anyone who
wants to fill the request is invited to send an e-mail reply.
</P>
<P>
   The variation creates a very different type of site. People on
the site are looking to buy all kinds of things, from rare books to
commercial real estate. Personal services have a place, also, but
it's a smaller piece of the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drawback at this stage appears to be traffic _ or
lack of it. The day I stopped by, the vast majority of the requests
had received few e-mail responses, and even fewer real bids.
</P>
<P>
   --www.imandi.com, like eWanted, focuses on a host of areas other
than local services. Unlike eWanted, though, Imandi has more than
200,000 service providers in its nationwide network.
</P>
<P>
   When I typed in my Boston-area ZIP code, for example, the site
informed me that it could put my work out to bid to 15 contractors
who could repair my fence, or 14 services that could clean my
house.
</P>
<P>
   Imandi will e-mail your request to the companies you want to
bid, post the request on the site for all comers, or both. It also
features a helpful ``buyers guide'' that tells you what questions
to ask different types of providers and how to choose someone.
</P>
<P>
   --www.respond.com is an interesting reverse-auction site, but
it's thin on local services. You can submit requests for
photographers, mechanics, and a few types of repairmen, but the
site is mostly dedicated to hooking up buyers and sellers of
hard-to-find things such as out-of-print albums or Gothic-style
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   If the site does have a category for what you want, though, it's
not a bad option. Respond.com is simple to use, and it provides the
opportunity to swap information with people and professionals,
whether or not you find a seller of the service in question.
</P>
<P>
   --www.SimplyDone.com isn't really a reverse-auction site, though
it accomplishes much the same thing. Instead, it's the best of the
matchmaker sites, which will pair you with local service providers
_ but it won't put your job out to bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give you the phone numbers and rates for each service,''
said spokeswoman Lynn Hackman. ``You could always call them to
negotiate something lower, based on what you found on the site.''
</P>
<P>
   I like SimplyDone.com because it's easy to use, it's focused on
local services exclusively, and it partners with the Better
Business Bureaus and the San Francisco-based Value Star system to
evaluate service providers in its network.
</P>
<P>
   Relaunched last month with a new name (it used to be
Handshake.com), the site features eight categories: house cleaning,
carpet cleaning, upholstery cleaning, pest control, massage
therapy, pet grooming, oil change, and limousine or car service.
</P>
</TEXT>
