<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-ART-B     08-14 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 2D-QUARTER DEALS RAISE $19.58   BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bucking all predictions, US venture capital deals notched a new
record in the second quarter, as companies landed $19.58 billion in
financing, 14 percent more than in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The number of companies reaping funds inched up 1 percent, to
1,432, according to the Boston Globe-PricewaterhouseCoopers Money
Tree Survey. If venture capitalists showed a reluctance to quicken
their deal pace on the heels of the April technology stock dive,
they weren't stingy with their money: The average funding round
rose 13 percent to $13.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   New England remained the most active region after Silicon
Valley, as local startups grabbed 13.3 percent of the funds
invested nationally, or a record $2.61 billion, up from $2.42
billion in the first quarter. Silicon Valley claimed 35.1 percent
of total venture funding, or $6.87 billion, while the Southeast
ranked third, at 7.8 percent, or $1.54 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest sector in New England was telecommunications,
outpacing software, networking, and other technology sectors for
the first time in the survey's history, while consumer and
business-to-business financings sagged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The b-to-b bloom has fallen off,'' said Bill Collatos,
managing general partner at Spectrum Equity Investors in Boston.
``People are now focused on the reality that b-to-b is only as
effective as the infrastructure that supports it.''
</P>
<P>
   The booming demand for telecommunications services _ from voice
and data lines to wireless technology _ is seen as a vast
investment opportunity for at least another five years. Consumers
around Boston were reminded last week of how integral these
services have become, as the workers' strike at Verizon
Communications made it harder to get directory assistance, new
lines, or repairs on modem hook-ups.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, data traffic has taken over voice traffic on
the nation's telecommunications systems with the soaring use of the
Internet. Three years from now, data is expected to account for as
much as 70 percent of all the traffic, said Sanjay Mewada, director
of telecom/e-business analysis at the Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a tree,'' Mewada explained. ``As the trunk gets
bigger, the branches get bigger, and the connection points have to
become faster and more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   There are scores of young companies scrambling to tackle this
problem, many of them led by former executives of Lucent
Technologies, AT&AMP;T, MCI, and the former Baby Bells. Fiberoptics _
light signals pulsing through glass fibers _ are attracting big
money, as are wireless technologies. And all the companies have
different approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Quantum Bridge Communications of North Andover received $102.5
million of third-round financing in the second quarter, the
second-biggest funding the Bay State has seen. A Wallingford,
Conn., fiberoptics company, Cidra Corp., reaped $100 million, while
four other Massachusetts companies involved in communications
received more than $50 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Gray, a Boston partner in PricewaterhouseCoopers'
Technology Industry Group, marveled at the super-size deals being
inked in the region _ more than double the biggest financings 12
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that some companies may be recasting the way they
describe themselves to shed the unfashionable Internet category and
fit into telecom. At the same time, he said, ``The true telecom
companies need a lot more money than Internet companies do to
succeed.'' Such spending goes largely to hardware, research and
development, and building out networks.
</P>
<P>
   Quantum Bridge has just leased 100,000 square feet of new space
in Andover, more than tripling its current 30,000 square feet in
North Andover. The company has grown from 90 employees at the end
of 1999 to 220 now, and it expects that count to hit 300 by
year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Zona, Quantum's chief executive, said raising money has
been relatively easy. The company is backed by big name VCs,
including Atlas Venture, BancBoston Capital, New Enterprise
Associates, and Texas Pacific Group, among many others. He thinks
venture capitalists are betting heavily in the sector because
revenues and profits are clearly in the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only two technologies will be left standing _ optical
technology and wireless,'' Zona said. ``If you want capacity and
you want a high-speed experience, you're only going to get that
through optical technology.''
</P>
<P>
   David Barry, senior editor of Venture Capital &AMP; Information
Technology, a Wellesley-based trade journal, said part of the
allure of the communications companies for investors is that they
are attractive buyout candidates for the telecom giants, from Cisco
Systems Inc. and Lucent to Nortel Networks Corp. and Sycamore
Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisitions are coming earlier in the startups' lives and
at big premiums, Barry observed. ``You can start a company and
throw a few million dollars into it, and a Nortel will come along
and pay a billion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Nortel has done a string of acquisitions. In July,
it agreed to buy Alteon WebSystems, Inc. of San Jose, Calif., for
$7.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If telecom enjoyed an embarrassment of riches in the second
quarter, the Web darlings of late 1999 went begging.
</P>
<P>
   While Internet-related companies nationwide saw their funding
rise 7.5 percent to $11.67 billion in the quarter, service
companies and applications players garnered the biggest share of
that money. Content sites, business-to-business companies and
e-commerce sites lost their luster after the April stock-market
dive and saw their financings drop off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sector rotation has been really, really fast,'' said Geoff
Yang, founding partner of Redpoint Ventures in Silicon Valley,
during a conference call hosted by the National Venture Capital
Association. ``There's no question that the shift in the public
markets has caused a shift in where VCs invest.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial public offering window had closed abruptly in April
and May, sparking fears that venture capitalists would fund fewer
companies if they couldn't take other companies in their portfolios
public. But the IPO market has since rebounded to record levels _
and the venture money keeps flowing, but into different sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Top IPOs in the second quarter included Sonus Networks, a
Westford voice-infrastructure products company, which has soared a
stunning 763 percent. StorageNetworks Inc., a Waltham data storage
player, has seen its stock jump 330 percent, while shares of
Charles River Laboratories Holdings Inc., a Wilmington drug
development company, have risen 84 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, $36.7 billion of venture investments
nationwide have outpaced all of 1999, when $35.6 billion was
invested. Analysts and people who work with venture capitalists
said while the pace remained vigorous, deals were being done in
less haste than in the prior two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace of investing feels less frantic than it did last
quarter,'' said Jesse Reyes, a vice president with venture
economics in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Is it time to worry that communications is overheating, just as
b-to-c and b-to-b did? That time could be just around the corner,
pros warn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems all the momentum money is moving into
communications,'' Yang said. If the financing trend follows what
happened in the Internet arena, copycat companies will soon start
to surface, trying to muscle in on hot sectors. ``We haven't seen
that yet,'' Yang said. ``But it wouldn't surprise me.''
</P>
<P>
   Collatos of Spectrum said surely all the telecom startups won't
make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these companies are being acquired on promise, not
proven revenues,'' he said. ``That sounds remarkably like the
Internet environment of the last three years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
