<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0880 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-CO     08-14 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds. For release Aug. 16, 2000.
 &HT;    FIXES THROUGHOUT
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: There's English, and there's English
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of times my wife and I turn to each other to ask,
``What did he say?'' during the viewing of a TV program or movie is
increasing with alarming speed. Likely, it is the onset of age and
all the declines that brings with it but I reserve much of the
blame for mumbling actors and actresses and, particularly, the
British.
</P>
<P>
   This now is compounded with the discovery, delighted though I
might be, that the British Broadcasting Company has invaded the
American market, establishing the BBC America channel which I
receive through my tiny satellite dish.
</P>
<P>
   I spent much of last weekend watching BBC America and, having
been often to the United Kingdom, was familiar with much of its
programming, notably its newscasts which, unlike so many U.S.
newscasts, devotes its time more to world affairs than to
Madonna's.
</P>
<P>
   There is a request I would like to make, however: Subtitles. The
playwright George Bernard Shaw often was quoted as saying that the
British and Americans ``are two countries separated by a common
language.'' Likely, Shaw intended that in the use of words and
idioms (we do have a voluminous number of dissimilar terms) but
it's the pronunciation that wipes me out.
</P>
<P>
   I imagine that someone from Liverpool would have a terrible time
trying to understand the Southern inflections of Tennessee
Williams' ``Cat On a Hot Tin Roof'' and that's the way I am with
``Fawlty Towers'' and the old ``Benny Hill'' reruns. I miss about
one-third of what is being said but make up for it with the
tremendous sight gags.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having an entire channel of Briticisms, pronounced any
number of ways (no country so small should have that many varied
accents) I am appealing for some relief. I am a big fan of foreign
films inasmuch as we supposedly get only the best of what the world
produces. If you're watching a French, Chinese or Iranian film, you
get subtitles and you can understand what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with a British or Aussie film. There are no subtitles and
you sit in the theater turning to your partner to find out if he or
she understood a word of what just was said. I couldn't make it
through ``Howard's End,'' not because the film was deadly dull in
of itself, but because I couldn't understand a single syllable of
what was being said.
</P>
<P>
   I find it interesting that I can understand every word of what
is being said by the anchors and reporters of BBC World News but
hardly a word of those ``down-home'' Britcoms where the characters
sit around sipping their pints and uttering indecipherable babble.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, I watched hours of something called ``The Royle
Family'' and hardly knew what they were saying. Then came World
News and I was back on track. Obviously, the news department has
higher pronunciation standards than does the entertainment
division.
</P>
<P>
   I have a great deal of experience with this as I have British
family which I visit almost yearly. We often have a hard time
understanding one another. If it is not the pronunciation, it's the
terminology.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Several months ago, in London, I mentioned to the
family that my grandson was going to enter college this Fall.
``Brilliant!,'' exclaimed cousin Joanne. ``Well, I wouldn't say he
was brilliant, but he's a smart kid,'' I told her. ``No,'' she came
back, ``Brilliant! Wonderful! You know?''
</P>
<P>
   That's terminology. Pronunciation is another barrier to our
cross-Atlantic relationship. Particularly when cousin Simon's
friend Adam is around. He speaks much like Eliza Doolittle did when
Prof. Higgins first found her in Covent Garden. I'd do better with
Adam if he wrote down on paper what he was trying to say.
</P>
<P>
   But, I digress. BBC America needs to do America, and itself, a
favor if it hopes to be successful here. It needs to throw
subtitles onto those sitcoms and dramas. While ``Masterpiece
Theater'' is outstanding drama, it needs a little help in the
accent department for the American ear.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, I caught Oscar Wilde's ``An Ideal Husband'' on
one of the U.S. movie channels. If it had not been for the fact
that I could use the closed caption feature on my TV set, I would
have been out of luck; massive mumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, BBC America does not yet come with closed
captions (except for a couple of American commercials) and I would
urge it to do so quickly, for my sake and for its.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
