<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0882 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN0815-COX     08-14 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The sign-guy and old Perotnistas
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Everyone but the most hardened partisans
have decried the staged, empty, smiley-faced conventions of the
major parties. Commentators of all stripes have wished out loud for
the old days of platform fights, credential challenges, delegate
walkouts and red-meat oratory that lambastes the bad guys, exalts
the good and whips the faithful into spear-shaking battle
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Well, be careful what you wish for.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, we got to see an old-fashioned
thrash-it-out-in-public convention. It wasn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party was in full hoot and holler. If some of the
delegates weren't so cranky and scary, it would have been
refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   We also have something I've never heard anyone wish for _ twice
as many Reform Parties. The delegates opposing Pat Buchanan walked
out and held their own convention 100 yards down the street.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why. Buchanan did not win over the Reform
Party; he used it as a host organism. He infected it until he
emerged screaming from its abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   On the first night of the Buchanan-Reformed Reform Party
convention, delegates were shown a campaign video of the candidate.
(Bizarrely, it used a reworked version of ``When You Say Nothing at
All'' as a campaign song. A title that seems more fitting for
George W. Bush than Buchanan.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the video's big applause moments was a clip of Buchanan's
defiant, post-Watergate defense of Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Think about this. Here is a party founded first and foremost on
cleaning up government and containing the power of special
interests. And now its new members are cheering the memory of
Nixon. Kind of weird.
</P>
<P>
   And kind of sad.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot that was goofy, grating and grandiose about the
original Reform Party. But I have a soft place in my heart for it.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't feel this until the close of the 1996 election when
Ross Perot signs began popping up around town. Not the usual slick,
mass-produced signs. But crude, hand-lettered, red-white-and-blue,
signs painted on scraps of plywood. They just said ``Perot'' with
big black-outlined white stars and sometimes red circles.
</P>
<P>
   And not in the usual political-sign places. In odd places.
Fences on the edge of pine woods. Lonely country roads. In vacant
lots on U.S. 1. Nailed high up on telephone poles suggesting
someone had climbed up hammer in hand.
</P>
<P>
   The election ended and Bill Clinton began his second term. But
the signs kept appearing. All winter long. It was as though the
sign guy couldn't bear to admit it was over. He had to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   There was something very poignant about these folk-art,
wavy-lettered Perot signs standing alone, often in the middle of
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   For me, they suggested the intense, personal and doomed
sentiments behind the old Reform Party and made me stop snickering
at it.
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious sign guy and his allies were people who felt that
politics, politicians and their very nation were passing them by as
though they didn't matter. And this strange party offered them just
a little hope for keeping these dark forces at bay. They threw
their hearts and leftover plywood scraps into it.
</P>
<P>
   With the Buchanan takeover, these are the people who will likely
drift away from politics and even voting. The party that was the
handiwork of their hopes will die the slow death of court appeals,
ballot-eligibility rulings and splinter parties. The Reform Party
is all but dead.
</P>
<P>
   I never thought I'd say this, but I will miss it.
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine anyone painstakingly applying acrylic paint to
plywood and driving back roads at night to climb telephone poles on
behalf of Bush or Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And the political process will be poorer for it.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
