<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0815-CO     08-14 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The sounds of silence lost
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDWICH, Mass. _ Listen carefully and tell me what you hear.
Car horns? Power lawn mowers? An '81 Oldsmobile excreting trash-rap
through its open windows?
</P>
<P>
   If you answered yes to any one of the above, or heaven forbid,
all of them, then you're probably an average Joe, living on Main
Street, Anywhere, USA. And you're pretty used to the cacophony
we've come to accept as a part of our daily
</P>
<P>
   lives, not even noticing until it turns up missing.
</P>
<P>
   A while back, I read of a tribe of natives living in a jungle _
can't remember exactly where...maybe South America, maybe Africa,
definitely not New York _ whose hearing was so acute they could
carry on conversations with each
</P>
<P>
   other even though they were the equivalent of a football field
apart _ and without raising their voices. No market for Miracle Ear
here.
</P>
<P>
   But not so in the civilized (that's supposed to be us) world.
Most of the folks I know are lucky to hear well enough to find the
cordless phone ringing under a pile of laundry where they left it
the last time they used it, much less chat with a friend who is not
electronically connected.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of impairment, don't you just love having to say
everything twice? Not so much because you weren't heard the first
time, but because you have been tuned out along with ``shriek TV''
and the Cuisinart?
</P>
<P>
   I have a dear friend who spent too many years around heavy
construction equipment, rendering conversation with him an exercise
in futility. That's frustrating, particularly when it was only
trivia to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Example: We're driving down a country road in his pickup and I
point out my window and comment on the passing cornfield.
</P>
<P>
   Me: ``Knee high by the fourth of July. Looking pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Him: ``Hmmh?''
</P>
<P>
   Me: ``The corn. It's just right.''
</P>
<P>
   Him: ``Say again.''
</P>
<P>
   Me: ``THE CORN. IT'S LOOKING GOOD.''
</P>
<P>
   Him: ``What corn?'' Naturally, he doesn't see any corn because
by the time he's heard what I'm saying we're in the next county _
where they only grow soybeans. He can't help it. It's what happens
when we live in a strident world, but when I mention hearing aid he
goes ballistic. ``I CAN HEAR JUST FINE,'' he insists.
</P>
<P>
   Noise, according to Webster, is defined as a nonharmonious or
discordant group of sounds. Silence is the glorious absence of all
that.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what's happening around me this early morning at a
friend's house on Cape Cod. The stillness outside Gail's open study
door, where I happen to be working, is interrupted only by the
chatter of birds and the tinkle of the little bell Puss Puss's
mistress has strung onto her collar to warn the wildlife of a
well-fed, but nonetheless predatory creature lurking in the hostas.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, Grandfather, the 9-foot tall people-friendly
7-day clock Gail inherited from her Aunt Alice, ticks and chimes
its reminder of a gentler era. I think I can still remember going
to sleep by just such a sound when I
</P>
<P>
   was a little girl _ back when lawnmowers whooshed and purred on
summer lawns, and laughter, rather than canned heavy metal, drifted
from neighborhood porches.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, and this is now. And silence, though still
golden, is also, unfortunately, rare.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
