<HEADER>
A0885 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-GAMER0815-COX     08-14 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GBy Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Street Fighter EX2 Plus ($35; www.capcom.com; for the
PlayStation) is maddening! Following in the steps of Capcom's
flagship Street Fighter series, Street Fighter EX2 Plus pulls you
into the fiercest brawls against some of the baddest characters on
the videogame block. Menacing fighters with moves like the Psycho
Crusher, the Atomic Suplex and the Death Press wreak mental anguish
and virtual pain on your character, forcing you to open up your own
little can of whip-butt. But no matter how many blows you land,
nine times out of 10 you're gonna lose when you play against the
PlayStation fighters. With its vivid 3-D graphics, rapid, smooth
animation and those nauseating grunts, groans and yelps so germane
to these types of fighting games, Street Fighter EX2 Plus will keep
you and your thumbs busy _ at least until you're too frustrated to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Who Wants to be a Millionaire 2nd Edition ($40; www.playstation
.com; for the PlayStation) tries to emulate the essence of
Philbin's game show phenomenon by adding a dramatic pregnant pause
every time you select your multiple choice answer. This is
aggravating in a PlayStation game where we suffer enough loading
delays as it is. Ironically, that's the best this game has to
offer. It's trivia with Regis Philbin doing some voice work _ and
most of that is just sampled from the actual show. Other than that,
there's almost nothing here remotely resembling a video game: The
graphic interface is sparse and cheap (you stare, alternately, at
two empty chairs, or text, or an empty set mock up). And the
capper: Questions must be answered within an allotted time frame;
unlike the show, contestants are not allowed to reminisce about the
7th grade school teacher who taught extensively on the subject; no
hemming and hawing, no repartee with the host. The nerve! Give me a
time limit and then preprogram a pregnant pause before telling me
if my rushed answer is right or wrong? Lame. Who thinks it's
possible to be a millionaire by starting out $40 in the hole and
that much further away from being a millionaire with nothing to
show for it except for ``branded consumer who doesn't deserve to be
a millionaire'' emblazoned on their forehead?
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to say that the problem with Doom designer John
Romero's highly anticipated Daikatana ($40; www.daikatana.com; for
Windows) is that because it came along far later than promised,
truly great shooters like Unreal: Tournament and Half-Life arrived
in the meantime to leave it in the dust. And that's true. But the
real cruncher is that, though it bulges with visual flourishes and
mildly interesting weapons and monsters, the gameplay itself lies
along a spectrum from annoying to tiresome. It simply isn't much
fun. With ``save gems'' that must be tediously collected prior to
ending a session, maddeningly frustrating (but much-touted and
politically incorrect) sidekicks, laughable cinematics and
half-hearted (but seemingly endless) level designs, this story of
time-travel and swordplay offers little sparkle and no spark,
arriving stillborn after the long, long wait. Vampire: The
Masquerade _ Redemption ($45, www.activision.com; for Windows)
drops you into an immersive 3-D world where role-playing, action
and puzzle-solving are well balanced. That's the good news.
Creeping about in the shadows as the undead anti-hero Christof and
hacking away at one's enemies or drinking the blood of one's
victims is sinister fun. The smooth-running landscapes and special
effects are detailed and atmospheric. The controls are intuitive
(toggle between third- and first-person), the cinematic cut scenes
are lovely and the characters who join your party are interesting
and even helpful. But the most highly anticipated aspect of the
game, storyteller mode, in which one player builds and controls a
world as the game is running, disappoints in that it requires a
sure hand at the helm _ something difficult to find in the
twitchfest of the Internet _ and generally degenerates into a
free-for-all. But given the right circumstances _ a well-built LAN
game with all the players physically in a room together _ Vampire
has the potential for transcending even its worst glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
