<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sound with style
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Listening to music at work often involves wearing headphones so
as not to disturb your office- or cubicle-mates, but if you have
agreeable tastes or your own space, you might want to check out the
Monsoon iM-700 multimedia speakers ($170; www.monsoonpower.com).
The set, which comes with two flat desktop speakers, a powered
amplifier/subwoofer and a tiny ``puck'' for volume and mute
control, is perfect for a workstation _ the speakers are sleek and
take up little room on a desk. They also sound great, offering good
sound on a Mac or in Windows, whether its for music or games. In
Windows, however, there is a noticeable hiss when nothing is
playing. The speakers also require finicky positioning to sound
good and are sometimes a little too sibilant, especially when
playing CDs. But if style's your thing, you probably won't find a
better-looking set of speakers to impress your co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   BACK UP BEFORE YOU CRASH DOWN
</P>
<P>
   There are three rules to digital information fabrication: Back
up, back up, back up. It took a couple of hard crashes for this
axiom to sink in, but now, ever present at my cluttered workstation
is the stalwart and reliable Iomega Zip Drive. The USB Zip 100
($100; www.iomega.com) is particularly functional for me as it is
external and works for Windows and on Macs. Plus it's sleek and
portable. Though 100 MB of storage is smallish by today's
standards, it's more than adequate for typical duplicate document
desires. And because I'm lazy, the USB hot-swap deal allows me to
plug in and back up without rebooting. And because I'm
</P>
<P>
   into fruit, I particularly appreciate the translucent
blueberryish Mac look, even though my Mac isn't even remotely blue,
and my PC is decidedly colorless.
</P>
