</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old photographer ready to go digital
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The big thing for home computer users now is digital
imaging, which is a fancy way of saying home photographs and
movies.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, high on my wish list these days is a decent digital
camera. A still camera would be nice; a video camera would be
doubly nice so long as stills could be made from its output, and
generally, I believe, they can.
</P>
<P>
   With a computer of fairly recent vintage and an inkjet printer
capable of 1200 dpi printing _ which can be had for under $200 _
you have all the darkroom that will ever be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Digital cameras within the financial reach of most of us are
pretty simple things compared to your average single-lens reflex.
The latter will have interchangeable lenses, allowing you to
completely manipulate the exposure and the focus. There are digital
cameras that provide all that, too, but they are in the very
serious professional range.
</P>
<P>
   Most digital cameras have, at best, a lens with a zoom range of
3X, or three times normal. They are autofocus and offer only a
general kind of exposure control.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest advantages of digital cameras is that most
have a little screen on which you can get a look at the picture you
just made. If it doesn't suit you, it can be dumped from memory;
you don't have to take up the camera's limited memory with unwanted
photos.
</P>
<P>
   I used to make pictures for money as a sideline. I had my own
darkroom and all that. I gave it up when color became the standard.
Printing color, at that time, was more trouble and expense than I
cared to get into. My cameras were state of the art for the time.
</P>
<P>
   Now I would be deligh Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
