<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Common sense handy when judging technology reports
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The next time you feel silly or dumb because you don't
understand technology, just head for the library, pick up some back
issues of newspapers and magazines, and read some of the technology
stories.
</P>
<P>
   You're almost guaranteed to feel better fast. When it comes to
predicting the future of technology, experts don't get it right
either. And the reporters who write about it are as confused as the
experts.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that technology experts and reporters are stupid. It's
just that predicting technology has never worked. Maybe you
remember the famous quote from Thomas Watson, chairman of IBM, in
1943: ``I think there is a world market for maybe five computers.''
And my favorite comes from Popular Mechanics in 1949: ``Computers
in the future may weigh no more than 1.5 tons.''
</P>
<P>
   Since all of us have such foggy crystal balls when it comes to
technology forecasting, you need to be vigilant when checking out
technology news on TV or in the newspaper. A healthy amount of
skepticism isn't such a bad thing when reading any news story, so
it's a good habit to acquire.
</P>
<P>
   One way to double-check what you read is to use a little known
human power. It's not very popular but it does exist and _ without
learning yoga, taking ginko tablets or attending night classes _ it
can be developed. This mysterious power is called common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put it to work. Just like in the third grade, we will
start with a practice problem.
</P>
<P>
   Last week my morning newspaper told me that conventional car
radios will go away completely, replaced by fancy radios that
include Internet access. You'll also be able to talk to the car
radio to give it instructions.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   Well, start with the rough estimate that only a little more than
half the U.S. population has Internet access. And only 64 percent
of the U.S. population has used the Internet at all _ even one time
counts _ over the past 12 months. So you'd have to figure that
these folks who don't use the Internet (and remember there are ways
to get access free nowadays) probably aren't going to pop for some
fancy wireless Internet radio in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Next, remember that _ even today _ not all cars have radios
installed. My car radio has been broken for about three months and
I haven't gotten around to getting it fixed. So it's a real stretch
to think that all these folks without any radio at all, or who are
driving some beat up pickup truck with a hole where the radio used
to be, are going to switch over to Internet radios.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, as is usually the case, falls in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   These radios are coming _ have been coming for a long time _ and
almost certainly will be fairly common some day. But common sense
tells you that _ unlike what the story said _ the old regular radio
is not going to disappear any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not picking on that one story. Like I said, it's almost
certain that these newfangled radios will be common in luxury cars
and later_ as the years go by _ it'll be found in the sort of cars
that I can afford. But it's also very likely that the regular car
radio will be around for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we're using that story as a teaching point.
</P>
<P>
   Since it is unlikely that the experts and the technology writers
are going to become infallible anytime between now and Christmas,
you're going to have to shoulder some of the burden of
understanding technology. And since technology has become so
important in our daily lives, fair or not, it's a task you need to
undertake.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time you read a technology story that says a new
gadget is going to change the world by Tuesday, or that a horrible
new computer virus is going to wipe out everything from Santa Claus
to Santa Cruz, N.M., you need to run the facts through that high
tech filter called common sense.
</P>
<P>
   And, I have some important news for you. Common sense, if used
correctly, can truly change the world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
