<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-AUSTRALIA0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's look down under as Australia gets ready to welcome the
Olympics
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   OFFICIAL NAME
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth of Australia
</P>
<P>
   CAPITAL
</P>
<P>
   Canberra, which is located southwest of Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE IN THE WORLD IS IT?
</P>
<P>
   Australia lies in the Southern Hemisphere between the Indian and
South Pacific oceans. It is just below Indonesia and Papua New
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   Australia is not only a country, it's a whole continent. As a
continent, it's the world's smallest. But as a country, it is the
sixth largest.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERCONTINENT
</P>
<P>
   Australia used to be part of a large land mass, called the
Pangaea. The Pangaea was a supercontinent until it split into two
continents about 200 million years ago _ Laurasia and Gondwanaland.
About 60 million years ago, Gondwanaland began to break up into
what we know now as South America, Africa, Antarctica, India and
Australia. Australia has been on its own as an island continent for
about 35 million years.
</P>
<P>
   WHO LIVES THERE?
</P>
<P>
   More than 18.7 million people inhabit the country. Most of those
people come from European backgrounds. Captain James Cook (not
Hook!) claimed Australia for Great Britain in 1770. Many of the
first colonists were prisoners who were sentenced to live there far
from England. For a long time, mainly British and Irish people
moved to Australia. After World War II, people from Asia, Latin
America, the Middle East and other European nations began moving
there.
</P>
<P>
   THE FIRST AUSTRALIANS
</P>
<P>
   Aborigines are descendents of the Australians who lived there
thousands of years before any Europeans arrived on the continent.
Today, Aborigines make up less than 2 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   HOW BIG IS IT?
</P>
<P>
   Australia is about 3 million square miles _ much of which is
flat, dry land. Aussies call the interior land, away from the
coastal areas, the Outback. If you look at a map, you'll see that
area is huge.
</P>
<P>
   Not many people live in the desert or semi-desert area of the
Outback. Those who do live in ``never, never land'' often work on
huge cattle and sheep ranches, which Australians call ``stations.''
Stations are so big that workers who herd the cattle and sheep use
helicopters and small planes to round up their stock or check
fences.
</P>
<P>
   Kids who grow up in the Outback often don't have neighbors, let
alone schools, within a day's drive. Some learn from the School of
the Air, which allows students and teachers to interact via two-way
radio. You can get medical help from the Royal Flying Doctor
Service, which has airplane ambulances and clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Most Australians live in the coastal cities of the east,
southeast and southwest, like Sydney, Perth, Melbourne and
Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT
</P>
<P>
   Australia gained its independence from Great Britain in 1901,
but it still recognizes England's Queen Elizabeth as its chief of
state. Like England, Australia has a prime minister and a
parliament. Their parliament has a Senate and a House of
Representatives similar to the United States' Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Australia is divided into six states and two territories:
New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria,
Western Australia, Australian Capital Territory and the Northern
Territory.
</P>
<P>
   AYERS ROCK
</P>
<P>
   Ayers Rock is a monolith of mystery. Located deep in the
Outback, this huge rock is about 600 million years old. It was once
a part of a huge mountain range. As the sun moves throughout the
day, the rock changes color from mauve to blue to pink to brown to
red. It also entral Moscow's Pushkin Square. It also rattled the
nerves of many who remember the series of explosions that killed
more than 300 people in Russia last year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's bombers reportedly left a bag of explosives in the
middle of a walkway, then ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians are cautious of abandoned bags and boxes.
Officials are trying to track those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe the bomb was planted by rebels from the Chechen
region, where there has been a long, bloody fight for independence
from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen president has denied involvement.
</P>
<P>
   WILDFIRES: Blazes scourge the West
</P>
<P>
   Fire crews from New Zealand, Australia, Mexico and Canada are
arriving in Western states to help 20,000 U.S. firefighters and
National Guard troops battle fires.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 large blazes are burning in the West, with 4.3 million
acres already charred.
</P>
<P>
   Montana's governor closed 6 million acres of land in the state
to keep people from getting trapped by the blazes and to prevent
more fires.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are calling this year's fire season the worst in 50
years. Very hot, dry weather and lightning from thunderstorms are
fueling the blazes. Thousands of people have been forced out of
their homes. No one expects to make significant progress in
fighting the flames until the weather changes.
</P>
<P>
   DANGER: Kids' meal toy recalled
</P>
<P>
   If you got a Tangled Treeples toy in a KFC kids meal recently,
you may want to take it back. Small blue animals are packaged in a
green plastic container.
</P>
<P>
   That container could suffocate kids younger than 3. The bottom
of it can fit over a small child's nose and mouth.
</P>
<P>
   KFC voluntarily recalled the toys after a 19-month-old girl
reportedly got the container stuck over her face. She was not
seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The toys were in kids' meals in June and July.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
