<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-KIDGEAR0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A pacifier with peace of mind
 &HT;    By Shaun Conlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Since my son prefers his thumb and did not take to those tried
and true ``face-plugs,'' as my wife and I like to call baby
pacifiers, I never got a chance to truly evaluate Mabis'
TenderTykes Digital Pacifier Thermometer ($10; www.mabis .net).
Instead, I stuck it in my own mouth, much to my son's delight, and
found that yup, it works, and yup, I feel silly. A nifty device as
relevant now as it was in the caveman days, the unit contains a
digital thermometer within an orthodontic nipple with a little,
easy-to-read liquid crystal display that does not require you to
remove the pacifier in order to see it. The device also has an
oxymoronic ``Lullaby Alarm'' should it detect a fever. It has
memory and will recall the last reading, too, so you can gauge
where exactly this fever may or may not be going. To be truly
effective, of course, the fevered wee one has to like face plugs in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   THE TOYS ARE BACK IN TOWN
</P>
<P>
   Console games that appeal to both kids and adults and
notoriously difficult to produce. That's why it's such a breath of
fresh air to play Toy Story 2: Buzz Lightyear to the Rescue ($40;
www.sega.com; for the Sega Dreamcast), which appeals not just to
the gaming tyke but to the more mature gamer as well. The game,
featuring the original voice actors from ``Toy Story 2,'' uses
environments from the movie to create an immersive 3-D environment
that is only enhanced by the Dreamcast's graphic abilities.
Everything is sharp and gorgeous, as in the Pixar film. Controlling
Buzz as he navigates a playroom or the kitchen is a treat. If
there's one drawback it's that the wide range of controls and huge
environments can be a little intimidating _ you get to feel like a
tiny toy lost in an oversized world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
