<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cool running
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When you're hot, you're hot _ but you should
have some say in the matter. Consider then the Convair 900
``Prestige'' Evaporative Air Cooler ($300; www.convair.net.au). Not
to be confused with conventional air conditioners, evaporative
coolers employ a contrary, environmentally friendly means to
comfort-zone ends. Air is drawn through a large, wet filter pad by
a powerful (and distinctly audible) fan, a process similarly seen
in nature when air is cooled when it passes over an ocean or large
body of water. The Prestige holds up to four gallons of water and
has a tank gauge to monitor consumption. As a self-contained,
free-standing unit requiring only an AC power source, the Convair
900 Prestige does not require permanent installation of gaudy bulk.
It can be wheeled to any room as needed, including the storage shed
during the off-seasons. Essentially a humidifier, the Convair
Prestige is innately less effective in extremely humid climates,
but when it's simpatico with the environment, the Prestige is very
cool.
</P>
<P>
   A MOVIE AND THEN SOME
</P>
<P>
   ``Independence Day'' was certainly a resplendently overblown,
over-acted blockbuster extravaganza when it hit the theaters back
in 1996. Now you can see it all over again _ along with nine
additional minutes of fantastical footage _ in all its widescreen,
invading-alien glory. With optional running commentaries from
members of the production crew accompanying the first disc,
Independence Day Five Star Collection ($35; www.foxhome.com) also
includes a second DVD stuffed with features such as a ``making of''
ID4 documentary, a cheeky alien invasion ``mockumentry'' and an HBO
First Look featurette hosted by Jeff Goldblum, as well as deleted
scenes, outtakes, storyboards, concept art, production stills and
even a DVD-ROM game called ``Get Off My Planet'' playable directly
from one's DVD player.BARBECUER'S DECK HAND
</P>
<P>
   Does your grill drool grease or sputter sparks? At one time or
another most grills become the source of a deck-top mess. Instead
of pressure washing wood or stone after every cookout, why not buy
a bib for the barbie? The ``Original'' Grill Pad ($25 to $40
depending on size; www.diversitech.com) is little more than a pad
of thick, felt-like material coated in colored concrete. But it's
big enough (30-by-42-inch rectangles or 30-inch rounds) to protect
the deck and can be cleaned off with a shot from the garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
