r f BC-FAMILY-COLUMN0815-COX     08-14 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resources on Web can ease usual back-to-school frenzy
 &HT;    By Jennifer Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I can tell summer is drawing to an end. Almost daily,
more and more people ask me, ``Are you ready for school to start?''
</P>
<P>
   I've starting making the before-school-opens runs: to the
pediatrician to pick up the immunization form; by the school to
drop off forms and pick up fund-raising packets; to the
orthodontist for an end-of-summer check. My family has checked out
the new band color scheme. (We switched from a startling orange and
green to a more sedate black and gray. ``Makes me look older, don't
you think?'' he asked. ``Yes,'' I agreed, ``not to mention less
pulsating.'')
</P>
<P>
   All summer I've been randomly gathering thoughts, tips, Web
sites and information on reading, studying and homework with the
idea of developing a plan that would help get us through the school
year. Of course, with school a week away, it's not ready, but I'm
working on it.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I've been scouting the Internet searching for sites
that help with homework and research. I found www
</P>
<P>
   .bookadventure.org, an online reading program sponsored by
Sylvan Learning Center, Barnes &AMP; Noble and Lycos to be a helpful
source for a number of educational resources.
</P>
<P>
   The site promotes its own online reading program, created by
Sylvan Learning Foundation, on which parents and children register.
The kids are quizzed on books selected from the site's list and are
rewarded with prizes selected by their parents. I didn't use the
reading program, but I found the educational resources listed
useful.
</P>
<P>
   Book Adventure led me to www.familyeducation.com. There I found
several features and programs that can be downloaded, including a
definition-testing program that can be customized with your child's
vocabulary words. On many a night last year, such a program would
have come in handy at my house.
</P>
<P>
   This site offers suggestions on a wide range of topics based on
age and grade levels ranging from babies and toddlers to high
school. Advice from teachers regarding specific issues that parents
have raised are also available. Reading such Q&AMP;As often helps me
identify issues and helps frame questions I want to ask my own
sons' teachers.
</P>
<P>
   I also encountered some pertinent advice concerning my master
plan. One was a feature titled ``Go Back to School in Six Easy
Steps.'' Step 3, ``Don't Clean the Slate,'' advises:
</P>
<P>
   ``This may seem like a great time to clean up, sort out and set
new ground rules for family life. Chores are reassigned, allowances
renegotiated, and after-school sports and activities scheduled.
While change is good, the timing requires some reflection. Too much
too soon can make even the most cooperative child balk. Focus on
the start of school, and revisit the other issues after your kids
feel more settled.''
</P>
<P>
   It was like hearing Pavlov's bell. Clearly with the summer's
reprieve, I tried to bury memories of the rigors of getting back
into a routine. But luckily my subconscious was on the case, and we
are safe for now from a ``Mom's going crazy and changing
everything'' episode.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the boys will be relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
