<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flash Player brightens Web sites
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   What is Macromedia Flash 4? Will it affect other programs? Is it
a program that you can install but never remove? I am requested to
download it before using some educational materials.
</P>
<P>
   _ R.H. Downing
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Sounds like you're talking about the free viewer called
Macromedia Flash Player. Through your browser, it lets you
experience animation and entertainment that designers weave into
Web sites. Fun buttons. Movies. Flying logos. Graphics. You name
it.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: We're talking Web sites with sizzling content, such as
cartoons, interactive interfaces, online tutorials and information
graphics that were created using the ``Big Daddy'' program,
Macromedia Flash. Unlike the player, it isn't a freebie (Cost: $250
to $280). The software is part of Macromedia's graphics, Web
authoring and integration tools. A new release, Flash 5, is due out
in September.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Like its name, it has ``flash.'' The operative word is
``animation.'' Web designers use the animation tool to dazzle,
adding sounds, interactivity, the whole shebang, to create a
high-impact, low-bandwidth Web experience.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Low bandwidth is a good thing. Flash-based files are
smaller in size and can be viewed fast and efficiently. A mega-huge
data pipeline isn't required, and you don't wait all day for
animation or graphics to do their thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Let's get back to Flash Player. It's a browser plug-in
available for Mac and PC, and we haven't seen any ill effects on
other programs. The player is tiny and takes a short time to
download, which you can do when a Web site tells you that you need
it or go to cnet.com/downloads/ or macromedia.com/software/.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Flash Player works hand-in-hand with another free
plug-in, Shockwave Player, the king of multimedia playback. Add
that to your download list, too. What's cool, if you download
Shockwave first, Flash Player will tag along. Other fun Internet
players also can be found at CNET. Get RealPlayer Basic to enjoy
streaming audio and video. Mac users can find the Quicktime
plug-in, too. It's Apple's video technology that allows you to play
high-quality video directly on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: The plug-ins don't have to become permanent residents on
your computer. You can evict them. Once you see how they enrich
your Web visits, I bet you let 'em stay.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Explore how companies such as K-Swiss, North Face,
Sprint, Nike, Disney, Macy's, etc., used the ``Big Daddy'' Flash to
add pizzazz to their Web sites. The Air Force is a Flash fan, too.
Surf to macromedia.com/showcase/ and click the Flash link.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Without Flash Player, you'd miss seeing the shimmer of
those sites.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
