r a BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0815-COX     08-14 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: I have a question that has been bugging me
for a while. There are insects that live in the trees in the Hill
Country that make short, very loud noises after sunset, typically
in the spring and early summer (brzzzt, brzzzt, brzzzt). There are
also insects that make a loud, continuous droning noise in the
trees during the heat of the day, like zzzzzzzzz. I have heard the
latter called ``heat bugs,'' maybe a type of cicada. What are the
former bugs? Are they the same cicada, giving off their night
sound? Or katydids?
</P>
<P>
   _ James Machin
</P>
<P>
   A: Cicadas make the loud buzzing noise from trees during the
day; katydids and tree crickets chirp after dark. There is almost
no overlap in the time that they ``sing,'' reports Texas A&AMP;M
entomologist John Jackman. A male cicada rests in trees, singing to
attract females using vibrating membranes in the side of the
abdomen. Male katydids generate sound by rubbing their wings
together. Want to know more? Check the Texas Agricultural Extension
Service Field Guide at
http://insects.tamu.edu/images/insects/fieldguide/index.html. Q:
I'm looking for a gift for a friend who often gets far too wired on
coffee and caffeine. The character Too Much Coffee Man (TMCM)
really fits. Where can I get a T-shirt with this character?
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Shirts sporting the popular cartoonist Shannon Wheeler's
character can be ordered at the keyboard by visiting www.tmcm.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was wondering about Jell-O. Doesn't it contain ground-up
hooves and horns?
</P>
<P>
   _ Lee Brown
</P>
<P>
   A: No, Jell-O is made from collagen found in animals used for
food. Hooves and horns do not contain collagen, according to Kraft
Foods spokeswoman Mary Jane Kinkade. But the hide trimmings do. So
collagen from the trimmings is processed, purified and filtered
before being ground into powdered gelatin. Popular food, Jell-O.
Did you realize more than 1.1 million packages are purchased or
eaten every day? Guess the nadir of the congealed fruit salad has
yet to come. Q: My friend is trying to load a wild cow (600
pounds). Is there any food additive to calm down the animal?
</P>
<P>
   _ Mayte S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Nothing that is approved by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture or the Food and Drug Administration to be given orally
to food-producing animals, reports veterinarian Gary Warner, who
has extensive experience with large animals. Loading a cow, says
Warner, is usually not a problem. In order to sedate all 600
pounds, you will need something such as Ace Promazine administered
intramuscularly to the animal. Happy trails.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
