<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0914 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TV-COLUMN081     08-14 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TV-COLUMN0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wall Street's bears and bulls come to prime time
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Once is a fresh idea; twice is a trend. That's
the way television operates.
</P>
<P>
   For years we've had legal dramas, medical dramas and cop dramas.
This season at least two networks hope the next big thing is the
financial drama.
</P>
<P>
   Churning, blow-out, garbatrage, hammering, IPO, OTC. The
rapid-fire lingo could become as impenetrable as the frantic
doc-talk on ``ER,'' but it didn't take us long to get used to crash
carts, chest cracking and stat!, now did it? The fact that there
are two business dramas on the horizon means that the subject is
out there, and TV is trying to cash in on it.
</P>
<P>
   TNT has ``Bull,'' the cable network's first original series. Set
in the pressure-packed world of Wall Street, it debuts Tuesday at 7
p.m. and spotlights a group of investment bankers and traders who
break away from an established firm to start their own company.
They're s than ``$treet.'' Michael S. Chernuchin, the former ``Law
&AMP; Order'' executive producer who created ``Bull,'' was inspired by
his own experience as a lawyer with a high-priced firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I was sitting with three friends who were Wall Street
investment bankers, and they asked if I wanted to play golf the
following Saturday,'' Chernuchin said. ``They had leased a plane
and were flying across the country to Pebble Beach. I couldn't
believe that 25-year-old kids had that kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernuchin also believes viewers will be attracted to the
financial milieu because so many people are playing the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street is the new American pastime,'' he said. ``People
watch CNBC the way they watch ESPN. They follow the Dow and Nasdaq
like they were sports scores. Everyone seems to have a 401K or an
IRA. This phenomenon, with high finance being a great place to
explore a character, is what will attract audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   And what if the market suddenly collapses?
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is market-proof,'' Star insists. ``If the market goes
down, the show stays the same. It's about the high-pressure
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Television series generally live and die by the appeal of the
characters, which makes you wonder if ambitious investment types,
who work 14- to 16-hour days, are even remotely interesting. Aren't
these workaholics about as exciting as calculating the Dow Jones
average?
</P>
<P>
   ``The short answer is yes; the long answer is no,'' says
investment adviser Carl Stuart. ``That's because the vast majority
of people who go into the brokerage business either quit or fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your point of view, failure might be just as
exciting as success. Both new series presumably could burn through
characters like so many chunks of charcoal. Stuart compares the hot
young brokers of today to ``the gaggle of young commercial real
estate brokers who were making hundreds of thousands of dollars
'flipping' real estate'' (buying and selling for a profit in one
day) in the '70s and '80s. When the market was flush, they were
rich, but when the market cooled, they went bust.
</P>
<P>
   There's a line in ``Bull'' that says the average age of
millionaires in New York City is 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Stuart says. ``And the average age of bankruptcy is
probably that young, too. It's a bubble, and it will burst.''
</P>
<P>
   The downside could be compelling _ as long as the up side of the
market holds on long enough for the young characters to strike it
rich. A chronicle of Wall Street's hair-raising roller coaster
ride, along with the requisite dose of TV bed-hopping, could keep
``Bull'' and ``The $treet'' going. But only if viewers warm to the
cold-hearted milieu in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
