<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0976 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FARM-WOES-HNS &LR;      08-14 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-WOES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA FARMERS STUGGLE WITH COLLAPSE OF CO-OP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATTHEW YI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLARKSBURG, Calif. _ Gazing at acres of tomatoes ready for
harvest, third-generation California farmer Jeffrey Merwin said he
is living his childhood dream of working the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wanting to farm since I was 5 years old, and I've
enjoyed doing it, until about the last year or so,'' Merwin, 38,
said, shaking his head in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   His dream has turned into a nightmare as he and scores of other
farmers in Northern California struggle with the financial collapse
of their fruit and vegetable processing cooperative, the
once-profitable Tri Valley Growers in San Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   The financial woes at one of the largest canneries in California
have been brewing for at least a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Tri Valley posted sales of $960 million in 1995 but by the
fiscal year 1997-98 it announced a record loss of $53 million. That
figure was later revised to $79 million.
</P>
<P>
   The board of directors promptly fired the chief executive,
Joseph Famalette, who now faces a class-action lawsuit involving
more than 500 farmers. They allege that Famalette fraudulently
induced the growers to approve the change from receiving cash from
the co-op's pooling system to receiving stock instead.
</P>
<P>
   The losses continued as the cooperative's debts mounted to more
than $400 million owed to at least 1,000 creditors. Last month, the
co-op filed for bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to members of Congress, Bill Pauli, president
of the California Farm Bureau Federation, wrote Tri Valley's
decision to take only a portion of the contracted fruit from its
growers will translate into an estimated $200 million in losses
this year with 4,500 jobs lost for farm and cannery workers.
</P>
<P>
   Tri Valley's 500 members lost $35 million in payments not made
for 1999 crops and $145 million in lost equity (cooperative
dividends for which members have already paid taxes).
</P>
<P>
   On July 28, a U.S. Bankruptcy Court judge in Oakland approved a
$270 million financing package that will help the grower-owned
company process some fruits and vegetables this season.
</P>
<P>
   A large chunk, $169 million, will be spent to help pay off the
debt while $101 million will be used for processing crops. In
return, Tri Valley must try to sell its assets or go into
liquidation by Feb. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bailout, farmers are still expected to feel the
crunch because the money is not enough to process all of the
contracted crops.
</P>
<P>
   Tri Valley will take only 40 percent of the contracted tomato
acreage, 70 percent of the pears and apricots, and 85 percent of
the peaches, and all at a reduced price. The co-op will pay 70
cents on a dollar for peaches and 60 cents on a dollar of all other
crops.
</P>
<P>
   The move has left growers scrambling for new outlets in the
middle of harvest while most processing plants committed their
facilities to other farmers at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that we're doing right now . . . is actively
working with a food broker who is trying to find the processing
capacity,'' said Merwin, who has 400 acres of tomatoes in south
Sacramento County.
</P>
<P>
   He still feels fortunate. Unlike some of his neighbors who are
contemplating bankruptcies themselves or potential foreclosures on
their farms, Merwin thinks he can squeak by this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in very close contact with my banker and the fact of
the matter is that we've been healthy enough over the years'' that
we can survive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the problem is that in order to get out of the hole, you
need something that makes you money. . . . I'm fearful that we're
not at the bottom of the cycle yet. I think we've got another year
before we hit bottom and that's bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Peach, pear, apricot and tomato growers are expected to lose $60
million this year for crops that aren't processed and reduced
payments on deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the U.S. Department of Agriculture has
announced it will buy 36 million pounds each of canned peaches and
processed tomato products and 64 million pounds of canned pears,
using funds set aside for fruit purchases when there is a glut in
the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The USDA, at this point, I don't think is going to extend any
other assistance programs directly to the people affected by this
problem,'' said Enrique Figueroa, deputy undersecretary for
marketing and regulatory programs at the USDA. ``What may occur,
however, is for Congress to draft some legislation to specifically
target some of these affected growers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
