<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOOTER-CRAZE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TWO-WHEELED TRANSPORT GETS NEW LEASE ON LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELAINE ARADILLAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ First it was the Radio Flyer wagon. Then it was
the Hula-Hoop. Now it is time for the push scooter to relive its
glory days.
</P>
<P>
   If the rapid sales are any indication of their popularity,
scooters are rolling their way back into the hearts of children _
and adults _ and the momentum isn't slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell about 15 to 25 a day on average,'' said Erik Camacho,
sales associate at Sharper Image at San Antonio's North Star Mall.
</P>
<P>
   For a year, the Razor scooter, which sells for $99.95, has been
displayed at the trendy gadget store. But sales jumped recently,
and Camacho does not anticipate the popularity of the scooter will
lose momentum anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think it's going into Christmas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two-wheel Razor scooter, made by Taiwan-based J.D. Corp., is
among the best selling products for San Francisco-based Sharper
Image.
</P>
<P>
   The wooden footboards and metal skates of yesteryear have been
replaced with light-weight alloy and polyurethane wheels. The
device folds in half and is easy to tote. Its sleek appearance is
appealing and features an upright steering mechanism attached to a
narrow, chrome footboard.
</P>
<P>
   The wheels and handlebars come in a variety of colors _ red,
green, orange and the most popular color, blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always running out of blue,'' Camacho said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mad dash for the Razor, Sharper Image has been selling
fancier models like the Razor Wheel e, which allows the more
advanced rider to pop wheelies and pivot without losing balance.
Thirteen-year-old Jose Lopez jumped on the more expensive Xootr
($369) and took laps around the store while his mother checked out
the remote-controlled swivel air-conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more comfortable than walking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most transportation trends, the scooter experienced a
resurgence in coastal cities such as San Diego and San Francisco
before making its way across the country to New York. The scooters
are being used by children, but also by urban commuters and office
workers as a convenient form of transportation to and from meetings
and subway stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for the Rollerblade's replacement,'' said Mary Ann
Crenshaw, the president of Mary Ann Crenshaw &AMP; Associates in New
York City. The agency manages public relations for the Children's
Place, a nationwide clothing chain.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Place sells a similar model called the Yaak for
$59.50. ``We saw how hot it is, and we're bringing it in at
half-price. Every kid wants one and we're out to please kids,''
Crenshaw said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 1226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
