<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1021 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-LORETTA-SANCHEZ-HNS &LR;      08-14 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LORETTA-SANCHEZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HISPANIC LAWMAKER SKIPS HIGH-PROFILE EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Latino Committee 2000 Sunday brunch at
Paramount Studios included almost every top California Hispanic
politician, but was notable for one no-show: Rep. Loretta Sanchez,
D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The second-term congresswoman from Orange County was on the list
of invited VIPs to the lavish event, which featured chicken
tamales, music by the band Culture Clash, and speeches on the
influence of Hispanics in politics.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanchez, criticized by the Democratic National Committee
over her plans for a fund-raiser at the Playboy Mansion, has kept a
low profile since the issue went public last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, 40, caved in Friday and announced she was moving the
fund-raiser to B.B. King's Blues Club at Universal Studios'
CityWalk, a touristy street of restaurants and shops. In return,
Democratic leaders restored her speaking slot for this Thursday and
canceled their threats to consider ousting her as the highest
ranking woman in the Democratic Party. Sanchez is co-chair of the
Democratic National Committee, along with Detroit Mayor Dennis
Archer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been about the Playboy Mansion,'' she said Friday.
``It's about putting on a good event and raising money.''
</P>
<P>
   But the flap has brought successive waves of criticism for
Sanchez, who gained national attention in 1996 when she narrowly
beat incumbent Rep. Bob Dornan, a conservative Republican. First,
party leaders said the Playboy event could embarrass Vice President
Al Gore, then others criticized her for caving in to the moralists
and moving the event.
</P>
<P>
   Several people attending Sunday's brunch at the Paramount
Studios lot in Hollywood said they strongly support Sanchez,
despite the criticism. And few thought the flap would have any
lasting effect on the Democrats' popularity with Hispanic voters at
the polls in November.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalinda Guillen, political director of the United Farm Workers
in Sacramento, said she saw nothing wrong with Sanchez's Playboy
Mansion fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope she doesn't apologize,'' she said. ``What does she have
to apologize for?''
</P>
<P>
   When Sanchez initially refused to move the fund-raiser, DNC
Chairman Joe Andrew stripped her of her scheduled speaking role at
the convention and threatened her position as a party co-chair. By
moving the event, she regained her speaking slot.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC ``had to do whatever is in keeping with the tone (of the
convention), but I think it's unfortunate that it happened to
Loretta, who is a star,'' said Carmen Delgado Votaw, a Maryland
delegate to the convention. Votaw said Sanchez made the right
decision to move the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was flexible in order to stay in the game,'' she said.
``She wanted some of the limelight at this convention _ and she
deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Hispanics believed that the national party officials
unfairly singled out Sanchez, noting that Playboy magazine founder
Hugh Hefner and his daughter, Christie, have donated money to the
Democrats and to the campaigns of President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all posturing for the conservative vote,'' said
Esai Morales, an actor who starred in the movie ``La Bamba.'' ``If
you can take money from Hugh Hefner, you shouldn't be hypocritical
about having an event at his house.''
</P>
<P>
   Raul Hinojosa, an economics professor at the University of
California at Los Angeles, said Hispanics view the Sanchez-DNC feud
as a serious matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very sensitive to how national Latino politicians
are treated,'' he said. ``We haven't been in the spotlight that
long, so we wonder when we see this ton of bricks come down on
Loretta.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Hinojosa said the event at Hefner's estate,
coming during the Democratic convention, would only have fed
Republican attacks. ``Everyone would probably agree that
politically it was not a very smart thing to do,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
