<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-RDP-ART-650(2TAKE     08-14 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-RDP-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S CHALLENGE: EMBRACING A LEGACY WHILE CREATING SOME DISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Democratic party's convention, which opens
Monday, presents Vice President Al Gore with perhaps his best and
perhaps last major chance to win some credit for the country's
economic good times while distancing himself from the unsavory
elements of the Clinton administration that he has served for the
last seven and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   The convention marks the final political ceremony before
full-fledged campaigning resumes. It comes two weeks after the
well-oiled Republican political convention in Philadelphia and less
than a week after Gore, who continues to run behind his Republican
opponent, George W. Bush, in the polls announced his choice for his
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, in a day given over to little substantive business,
the convention will focus its attention on President Bill Clinton
and his wife, Hillary, who is running for the Senate seat being
vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan in New York. Both Clintons will
be delivering prime-time speeches. Gore, who is campaigning in the
Midwest, will not address the convention until its conclusion on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, with their campaign theme of looking to the
future, will open their convention by recalling the prosperity and
progress achieved under the Clinton administration. The trick will
be to celebrate Clinton without detracting from Gore's claim of
independence as the new Democratic contender for the White House.
His campaign has been encumbered by a fatigue that many voters say
they feel about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times/CBS News poll of the Democratic delegates
coming to the convention to nominate Gore found that while they
viewed themselves as political moderates, their views on issues
from affirmative action to an activist federal government were more
liberal than those of the public or even other Democrats in
general.
</P>
<P>
   And a Gallup poll taken this last weekend and released Monday by
USA Monday and CNN reported that 47 percent of 641 likely voters
sampled said there was ``no chance whatsoever'' that they would
cast their ballots for Gore in November. Only 30 percent said the
same about Bush. Yet 68 percent of the likely voters sampled said
they considered Clinton's presidency successful, despite the
scandal over his relationship with the former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky. The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 4
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the convention is seeking to highlight Hillary
Clinton's campaign to represent New York in the Senate by
presenting six women who already are senators: Barbara Mikulski of
Maryland, Barbara Boxer and Diane Feinstein of California, Mary
Landrieu of Louisiana, Blanche Lambert Lincoln of Arkansas and
Patty Murray of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton is then scheduled to deliver remarks before the
president is introduced with a film and makes his farewell address
as the party's leader. The convention is traditionally the time for
a departing president to pass the political torch to the candidate
nominated to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   There has been concern that the Clintons would steal the
limelight from Gore, making it harder for him to present himself as
a strong, independent leader. But Hillary Clinton promised on
Saturday that she and the president would only remain long enough
to endorse Gore's candidacy and then be ``gone, absolutely,'' from
the convention. The Clintons have irritated some Gore aides by
coming to Los Angeles over the weekend to raise millions of dollars
from Hollywood's entertainment industry for the presidential
library he plans to create in Arkansas and for her Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, the convention will also briefly pay tribute
to former President Jimmy Carter, who was defeated after a single
term by Ronald Reagan in 1980. That defeat began 12 years of
Republican leadership in the White House before the Texas
governor's father, George Bush, was ousted by Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Democrats will adopt a platform that competes
with the Republicans for voters in the political center. The
platform will call for schools to be made more accountable for
their students' performance, for tighter control of the country's
borders, for expanded world trade, for a stronger military and for
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats' platform will differ from the Republicans' in
its support for abortion rights, for mandatory trigger locks on
guns and for campaign finance reform. Gore has promised to make the
latter the first piece of legislation that he sends to Congress as
president.
</P>
<P>
   The convention will also emphasize the legacy of the late
President John F. Kennedy, with speeches from his daughter,
Caroline Kennedy, and his brother, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, whom Gore defeated in
the early round of primaries, is also scheduled to speak, as is the
Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   As the delegates arrived at the Staples Center in downtown Los
Angeles, protesters, espousing a variety of causes, from opposition
to the death penalty to vehement complaints about free trade, also
converged at the fences and police barricades erected around the
convention center. Thousands of police officers were on hand,
closing off major thoroughfares and some freeway exits and playing
havoc with the city's already chaotic traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The convention offers an opportunity to make Lieberman better
known to the voters. The senator from Connecticut was kept busy
with talk shows and interviews Sunday. In an interview on CNN's
``Late Edition With Wolf Blitzer,'' Lieberman acknowledged that
``there have been some differences of opinion between Al Gore and
me. And I think it is a mark of his strength as a leader that he
didn't look for somebody who agreed with him on everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator has differed from Gore in looking favorably on
school vouchers and some private retirement investment accounts in
the Social Security program, among other issues. But Lieberman said
he recognized that ``when the president decides, the vice president
supports it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is the first Jewish candidate of a major party for
vice president. As the first Democratic member of the Senate to
formally criticize Clinton for his behavior in the Monica Lewinsky
scandal, Lieberman is seen as inoculating Gore against Republican
attempts to portray the presidential candidate as tainted by the
controversies surrounding the president.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman will address the convention on Wednesday, just before
Gore is formally nominated as the Democratic party's presidential
candidate. The delegations from Tennessee and Connecticut, the
respective states of Gore and Lieberman, have been placed in front
of the stage so their announced votes will be seen as putting Gore
over the top in the required number of votes. The vice president's
elder daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, 27, will speak after the
formal nomination of her father.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has promised that his speech will be long on specifics,
spelling out his plans for trimming taxes for middle-class
families, improving the Social Security system, protecting the
environment and reforming welfare. And while he is likely to make
prominent mention of President Clinton's success in creating a
thriving economy, Gore has stressed that he is running on his own
agenda and with his own voice.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is scheduled to be introduced by his wife, Tipper, who in
turn will be introduced by their younger daughter, Kristin, 23, who
lives in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual touch, after the speakers leave the podium, they
will each spend 10 minutes or so answering questions about their
remarks from designated Americans. These so-called ``chats'' will
be presented in webcasts between 8 and 11 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are using their convention to attempt to draw a
distinction between Gore and Bush that goes beyond political
differences.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on Thursday the convention will offer a tribute to
Vietnam veterans, including Gore, who served there for seven months
as an Army journalist. Bush chose to serve as a pilot in the Texas
National Guard and did not go to Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
