<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1039 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-SPORTS-ARENA-HNS &LR;      08-14 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-ARENA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAYOR TOUTS NEW SPORTS ARENA FOR SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ILENE LELCHUK and JENNY STRASBURG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown has a grand
plan for a sports arena on the waterfront. But he has no anchor
team. He has no guaranteed funding. And no clear path toward
approval from a key agency that oversees development along the San
Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mayor and the head of the Port of San Francisco have
invited a major Texas investment and development group, Olympus
Real Estate Corp. of Dallas, to San Francisco later this month to
lay out its vision for a 19,000-seat arena south of the Pacific
Bell Park, the stadium where the Giants baseball team plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do whatever needs to be done to complete the things
I've started before I'm out,'' said Brown, who has been floating an
arena plan for a few years. His term expires in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and others advise caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it may be a very good idea to build an arena in San
Francisco,'' said Marc Ganis, president of the Chicago-based
SportsCorp industry consulting firm. ``But there should be an
expectation that there will be major sports leagues flocking to the
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and Doug Wong, port executive director, visited Dallas
earlier this month to tour the $340 million arena being built by
Olympus and the Hillwood Development Corp., headed by Ross Perot
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Olympus is willing to sketch a preliminary design for
San Francisco at no cost to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Olympus President David Deniger said it is too early to
speculate about an arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, before you can start a project like that, you've
got to know what users are going to be there. But again, you're way
ahead of us,'' Deniger said.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey does not appear to be an option for the arena. The
National Hockey League Sharks are thrilled with their arena in
nearby San Jose and signed a 15-year lease in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As for basketball, the Warriors have had a troubled recent
history in Oakland but their spokesman declined to comment on
speculation about a move to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors, who started in San Francisco and moved to Oakland
in 1971, signed a new 20-year contract in 1997 to play in the
renovated Oakland Arena. They can kill the contract in 2007 if the
team pays Oakland all the remaining debt on the arena construction.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors already are in debt to Oakland for more than $17
million in back rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice is (a new arena) should be a totally private
investment,'' said Oakland Councilman Ignacio De La Fuente.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been having trouble getting money from the A's,
Warriors, all of them. . . . There are not too many teams willing
to put their money where their mouth is,'' Fuente said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Wong said they do not want to rely on public
financing. But Olympus _ the real estate arm of high-powered Dallas
private investment firm Hicks Muse Tate &AMP; Furst Inc. _ did just
that in Dallas. Taxpayers are financing the new American Airlines
Center for the Stars hockey team and Mavericks basketball team with
up to $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he has received offers from other developers and
investors interested in a San Francisco arena but Olympus swayed
him, in part, by offering to draft some preliminary plans for free.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has solid relationships with professional
sports franchises: Tom Hicks, chief executive of Hicks, Muse, Tate
&AMP; Furst, is a majority owner of the Stars and the Texas Rangers
baseball team. Deringer is a minority partner in the two teams.
</P>
<P>
   At the waterfront, the new arena also could house circuses, pro
tennis tournaments, World Wrestling Federation matches and large
conventions, Wong said. Moreover, if the city ever wants to host a
major political party convention again, as it did with the
Democrats in 1984, a new arena is a must, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   Winning government approval for an arena would not be easy.
Officials at the Bay Conservation and Development Commission
already are leery. The regional agency is charged with limiting bay
landfill and preserving public access to the water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
