<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-PEDOPHILES-BOS </SLUG>
  
 BRITONS RAGE AGAINST SUSPECTED PEDOPHILES
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, England _ Some who live in this old harbor town
where Charles Dickens was born think there are too many people here
who resemble the creepiest of Dickensian characters, Fagin, a
nefarious, unkempt man who exploited and abused Oliver Twist and
other children.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Paulsgrove section of town, the literary parallel for
what is going on here was not penned by its most famous son, but by
Arthur Miller, the American author of ``The Crucible,'' a play
about the Salem witch hunts.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the terraced houses of Paulsgrove there is a whiff of
hysteria in the air. In 17th-century Salem, it was witches. In
21st-century Portsmouth, it's pedophiles.
</P>
<P>
   In Paulsgrove last week, mob rule was the only rule.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, on a warm summer's evening, young mothers and
their children surrounded the house of a suspected pedophile,
chanting: ``Sex case! Sex case! Hang him! Hang him!'' In the middle
of the baying mob, 4-year-old Shay Calvert stood aimlessly, sucking
her thumb and holding a homemade sign that read ``Kill the
paedophiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Shay was her daughter, Jodi Calvert beamed with pride,
saying, ``Yes, isn't she lovely?''
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon, luv, wave it, wave it,'' she urged her sleepy daughter,
who dutifully obliged, waving the sign and smiling meekly.
</P>
<P>
   Young men stood to the side, drinking beer. Earlier, they had
thrown stones, and one of them had punched a police officer,
breaking his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Katrina Kessell, a 33-year-old single mother of four, was the
self-appointed leader of the mob. Nearly every night for the past
week, she had led crowds of up to 200 people who had surrounded the
homes of suspected pedophiles. The mob bayed for blood, stones were
thrown, windows broken, people driven out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to protect our children, because the police can't,''
said Kessell, a chain smoker with spiked hair.
</P>
<P>
   But police say the mob is out of control. While one of the men
driven from his home by the crowd, Victor Burnett, 53, had been
convicted of molesting more than 100 children, four other families
who were intimidated into leaving are innocent, said the Hampshire
police superintendent, Bob Golding.
</P>
<P>
   They were guilty only of having the same name, or of bearing a
resemblance, or of having the misfortune of living next door to
alleged pedophiles who have been ``named and shamed'' in a Sunday
tabloid, the News of the World.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper began its campaign last month after an 8-year-old
girl, Sarah Payne, was found naked and murdered. The girl's
siblings told police that she had been abducted by a stranger. No
one has been charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are innocent victims of gossip and rumor,'' Golding said
of the four families who were driven out of Paulsgrove in the past
week. ``There is nothing to suggest they had anything to do with
pedophiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, that is, except the list that Kessell waved around
furiously as if it were an indictment of the law enforcement and
government officials whom she and her neighbors were defying. In a
society where most people show extraordinary deference to authority
figures, some of those who live in Paulsgrove have taken matters,
and the law, into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
   Told that police say she and the mob she leads have driven out
innocent people, Kessell exhaled a long plume of smoke, shrugged,
and refused to accept responsibility. She considers them collateral
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the fault of the police and social services,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they hadn't put pedophiles on this estate and among our
children, their neighbors wouldn't be receiving any aggro,'' she
said, using a slang word for aggravation.
</P>
<P>
   Kessell said her list of 15 to 20 ``known pedophiles'' in the
housing project, or estate, of 16,000 people was compiled from the
Internet, court documents, and by listening to the police radio.
</P>
<P>
   Golding said the list is bogus, more a product of rumor and
personal vendettas, which have led people in the mob to throw out
the name of a person they don't like. The names get added on, no
debate, no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak of mob rule is not limited to Portsmouth. Since
July 23, when the News of the World began printing the names,
pictures, and hometowns of people it said were pedophiles,
vigilante justice, and mistakes, have cropped up across England.
</P>
<P>
   Several suspected and convicted pedophiles have killed
themselves over the past two weeks. One of them, James White,
committed suicide after a mob attacked his home near Manchester.
White's lawyer, Milton Firman, blamed his death on the hysteria
created by the News of the World. The mob was led to his door by a
mention in a local newspaper that he had pleaded guilty to
molesting three girls.
</P>
<P>
   Many have noted the irony that such a high-profile,
self-righteous campaign against pedophiles was launched by Rupert
Murdoch's News of the World, a tabloid that routinely runs
photographs of naked women, and which critics accuse of sexualizing
everyone, including teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Under intense pressure from police, which it relies on for many
of its sensational crime stories, the tabloid relented Aug. 4,
saying it would cease its name-and-shame campaign. But it has
threatened to resume it if the government does not create a public
register of pedophiles. And the mobs it spawned continue unabated.
</P>
<P>
   Probation officials say that about 97 percent of convicted
pedophiles had regularly reported to them as required before the
newspaper began naming and shaming them, but the number dropped
dramatically in the hysteria created by the campaign. In the United
States, the compliance rate with registration laws for sex
offenders is about 89 percent, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While it refuses to divulge the sources of its information, the
News of the World has made mistakes. One man it named had died five
years earlier and had never been convicted of molesting children.
Acting on the newspaper's photos and names, the mobs have made
mistakes more frequently, attacking the homes of people who have
the misfortune of sharing a name or a resemblance with one of those
named.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Corbett, the chairman of Parliament's Home Affairs Select
Committee, asked the British government to prosecute the News of
the World for inciting violence. The newspaper remains defiant.
</P>
<P>
   While the mother of the girl whose murder inspired the newspaper
has backed the tabloid's campaign, saying parents need to know the
identity of pedophiles so they can protect their children, she
begged the mobs in Paulsgrove and elsewhere to end their violence.
She said the mobs were discrediting efforts to create a community
notification system modeled after ``Megan's Law,'' named for a New
Jersey girl murdered by a sex offender who was living next door
unbeknownst to her parents. Supporters want to call it ``Sarah's
Law'' in honor of the murdered English girl.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the Rev. Gary Waddington, sitting on the couch
in the vicarage across the lane from St. Michael's and All Angels
Church, was trying to prepare a sermon that would urge his
congregation to take a longer view of what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   Waddington, an Anglican, believes that pedophiles have to be
reintegrated into the community _ indeed, he believes there is less
chance they will commit new offenses if they become part of a
community and have an incentive to follow its mores.
</P>
<P>
   But Waddington is sympathetic to the mostly poor community he
serves. Many in Paulsgrove are frustrated by their poverty and
their powerlessness, and he sees the angry epithets directed at
pedophiles and police as a cry of frustration over other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, Paulsgrove is unremarkable. It's not a horrible,
rough community. In lots of poor communities, what often comes
across as aggressiveness and anger is simply frustration at not
being able to find middle-class political language,'' Waddington
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people here believe that pedophiles are being dumped here
by the government because this is a poor community where no one has
the power to fight back.''
</P>
<P>
   But Waddington's sympathy stops with the mob.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hysteria breeds fear, fear breeds prejudice, and it allows
people to engage in vendettas,'' he said. ``This has got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Golding hopes it has. After police and local officials promised
they would offer new housing to any suspected pedophile in the
neighborhood, Kessell and her supporters called off Thursday
night's planned rallies. But they vow to resume them if the
authorities don't deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside St. Michael's, watching her 5-year-old son
Charlie like a hawk, 30-year-old Patricia Smith said she and her
neighbors are only demanding their rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think the government would relocate pedophiles to
middle-class estates, or put them in posh places?'' she asked. ``So
why should we put up with them? Are our kids not worth as much?''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that there are simply too many children here, and
that the pedophiles must go elsewhere. Just where, she didn't know.
Or care.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a hole in the ground, the council (local
government) would be expected to put up a sign warning children and
their parents. This is no different,'' she said, stressing that she
opposes the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists say forcing pedophiles out of stable neighborhoods
only makes them more likely to commit new offenses. Parents like
Smith don't want to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we move all the pedophiles to Downing Street? They
can live next to Tony Blair,'' she said, referring to Britain's
prime minister. ``See how he likes it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
