u i BC-AFRICA-PEACE-BOS &LR;      08-14 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES FOR PEACE IN AFRICA FADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ The winds of war in central Africa are gusting
heavily as efforts to come up with a peace plan in Burundi hit a
brick wall and Congo's president launched major new offensives deep
into rebel-held territory.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of events heightened fears that this region,
torn by ethnic warfare almost continuously for seven years, is
descending into a new round of bloodletting despite the efforts of
Nelson Mandela, the United Nations, and others to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   In a region of genocidal ethnic conflicts, security analysts had
hoped that a peace deal to end Burundi's long-running civil war
might curb Congolese President Laurent Kabila's appetite for war,
since his forces include many rebel fighters from Burundi. But as
he attempted what appeared to be a major escalation of his war
effort this week, international observers began to fear a new
ethnic calamity. Backed by extremist Hutu militias from Burundi and
Rwanda, Kabila has vowed to overthrow the ``Tutsi regimes'' that
rule the two small countries on his eastern border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burundi is critical,'' said Jan van Eck, a consultant to the
faltering peace talks. ``Its peace process has to show that the
Tutsi-Hutu problem can be solved. Unfortunately, the arming of
Burundi's rebellion is undermining the possibility of success.
Kabila's strategy is to allow Rwanda and Burundi to be destabilized
by their own rebel militias operating from Congo.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-year old war in the Democratic Republic of Congo has
been virtually deadlocked for a year, with Rwandan-backed rebels
controlling most of the east of the country and Kabila entrenched
in the west. Until now, neither side has seemed capable of moving
beyond the existing front lines.
</P>
<P>
   But security analysts say Kabila has been rebuilding his army
while teasing peace talks forward. His military strength is
unknown, and UN officials doubt he has the power to push clear
across the country, but he seems prepared to try. Last month, in an
ominous sign of his intentions, he blocked the UN from deploying
peace monitors and declared null and void a cease-fire accord he
had previously signed. This week, he was a no-show at a regional
summit called to discuss the war in his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kabila's intentions have always been consistent,'' said a UN
official monitoring the war in Congo, who spoke on condition he not
be identified. The peace process, for Kabila, ``was a ploy to let
him regroup and rearm.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the gloom, talks meant to culminate later this month
in a deal to end Burundi's seven-year civil war appear to stall
this week, as rebel factions rejected a draft accord and warned
that peace was ``very remote.'' No one would say the process had
collapsed, but rebel attacks around the capital of Bujumbura have
intensified in recent days. A rebel ambush outside the capital last
Sunday night left 27 army cadets and seven civilians dead.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-Tutsi hatred that has fed cycles of war and genocide in
the region has been rising to dangerous levels for months,
observers said. The Tutsis form powerful but threatened minorities
that dominate the military and governments in Burundi and Rwanda.
Tutsi rebels also hold broad swaths of eastern Congo, where
residents say with growing resentment that they live under Rwandan
occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, when radicalized Hutus slaughtered 800,000 Tutsis
and moderate Hutus in Rwanda, the pivotal issue in achieving
stability for the region has become the need to provide security
for the Tutsis, despised and besieged since the 1950s by the Hutu
majorities in Burundi and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   A Tutsi-led army eventually defeated the Hutu government that
launched the genocide, but the problem didn't end there. Roughly 1
million Hutus fled into eastern Congo to avoid revenge and
prosecution. Most refugees have since returned home, but perhaps
tens of thousands of former soldiers and Hutu extremists, known as
interahamwe, remain in exile in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda fears these Hutu militias are bent on completing the
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   In next-door Burundi, the Tutsi-led government harbors similar
fears. The country's civil war started seven years ago when Tutsi
paratroopers raided the presidential palace and killed several
prominent Hutu politicians, including then-President Melchior
Ndadaye. Two Hutu rebel factions have since taken up arms against
the government, and more than 200,000 people have died in the
ethnic fighting. Hundreds of thousands of Hutus have fled into
refugee camps in western Tanzania or into the forests of eastern
Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila, backed by Rwanda, toppled Zaire's longtime dictator,
Mobutu Sese Seko, in May 1997. Since then, he has turned against
his former allies, stoking anti-Tutsi sentiments to build political
support.
</P>
<P>
   The UN Security Council, which authorized a modest peace
monitoring mission early this year, is due to meet later this month
to discuss the ongoing crisis in Congo, and regional leaders have
called for a meeting with Kabila on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Congolese leader turns his back on peace, some in the
region looked for hope in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cease-fire in Burundi would have a positive impact on
eastern Congo, where a lot of the Burundian rebels are hiding,''
said Bizima Karaha, a rebel leader in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight months since Mandela agreed to mediate the Burundi
talks, he has prodded the nation's 19 political parties closer to
an accord that would oversee a transition to majority rule.
Optimistic, he set a deadline of August 28 for signing an
agreement, even though the parties still disagree on key points,
including who would head a transitional government.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela also has yet to bring the two rebel armies formally into
the talks, and observers worry that even if a peace accord is
signed, it will be hollow without a cease-fire. Two separate tracks
of negotiations, in Pretoria, South Africa, and Arusha, Tanzania,
made little progress this week in clearing these obstacles, said
Van Eck, the consultant to the talks. Without the rebels on board,
Mandela's deadline now seems out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   As the crises in central Africa deepen again, the UN official
said the faltering talks in both Congo and Burundi illustrate the
need to find a regional formula for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congo is pulling Burundi back away from peace,'' the official
said. ``The Hutu rebels won't let Burundi be peaceful by itself.
There has to be a regional solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
