<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1056 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DR.LAURA-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      08-14 1537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DR.LAURA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. LAURA BETTER FROM A DISTANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Laura Schlessinger _ or, as her legion of radio patients
simply refer to her, Dr. Laura _ has come aggressively under fire
of late for unkind remarks aimed at gays and a seemingly intolerant
demeanor in general. A doctor _ which Schlessinger may be, but not
of psychology or psychiatry, which is what she pretends to practice
on the air _ would obviously be a country mile more tolerant of
homosexuality. Moreover, few therapists openly berate their
patients, as Dr. Laura delights in doing on her highly rated,
nationally syndicated radio show _ unless of course they moonlight
as a dominatrix.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dr. Laura's bringing her act to TV with a syndicated series
that debuts Sept. 11. Gay groups have protested her show before it
even airs _ as close as the Paramount Studio lot (the studio is
producing the show) and as far aways a small town in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura herself, understanding the levels of controversy she
engenders, courageously avoided meeting with the nation's TV
critics in July, but she did post a message on her Web site
bullying fans into buying her advertisers' products. She wrote, ``I
am encouraging _ no, insisting _ if you value our relationship as
much as I do _ that you support these loyal sponsors by using their
products and services whenever you have the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   How will her patented brand of bile play on TV? Based on a
recent taping of the series _ only the sixth episode in the can _
it seems she's toning down her act for viewers. Protesters needn't
worry _ judging by what we saw, the only thing her show will
inspire viewers to do is nod off.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Dr. Laura is emboldened to insult and batter her
subjects when they're safely distant, on the other end of an
anonymous telephone line; when someone standing right next to her
makes a nitwit statement, on the other hand, she isn't nearly so
combatant. And she brings in guests and cronies to make her points
for her on the show, reserving fairly safe targets for her own
fusillade of snipy comments.
</P>
<P>
   The episode I sat in on was entitled, promisingly enough,
``Putting the Jail in Jailbait.'' But instead of inspiring a
``Jerry Springer''-style melee of confrontations and exhibitionism,
Dr. Laura served as ringmaster for a terribly clinical discussion
that grew increasingly pedantic, in a blase sort of way, as the
show dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   I was one of as few as three _ and maybe up to eight _ people
who wasn't getting paid to sit in her audience and cheer (so one
might reasonably ask, who's the dope in this equation?). Now,
bringing in busloads of ringers and promising them enough beer
money to induce them to feign enthusiasm for a program is a
standard practice in the industry, but in Dr. Laura's case it also
means that no screening process is necessary to weed out those
pesky gay activists who might act out against her.
</P>
<P>
   In accordance with the episode's theme, a group of teens was
among the hired hands. One, sporting a navel ring and T-shirt that
read ``Hottie'' (just Dr. Laura's kind of gal) asked a page, ``Will
we see any celebrities here?'' The page responded, ``No, Dr. Laura
looks at issues.'' The self-proclaimed hottie's eyes promptly
glazed over. Nonetheless, the audience _ most of which didn't
really seem to recognize their host _ was professionally attentive
and applauded a few notches above ``listlessly'' when instructed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura's set, situated in a Canoga Park soundstage, is a
tastefully designed in-the-round number highlighted with wood
accents and earth tones. Surrounded by roughly 180 seats, Dr. Laura
either sits with guests at a triangular desk or stands next to an
ultra-thin TV monitor as she dispenses her wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   The show's officious floor manager sported long graying-blond
hair, a navy sport coat and tie, and moccasins. It was hard to tell
if his jacket and tie were in deference to working with Dr. Laura,
or if the long hair and moccasins were in deference to working in a
``creative'' industry (which isn't out of the question, since he at
one point boasted of his golf handicap).
</P>
<P>
   He ordered the audience not to pick their noses during the
taping (lest they be immortalized on the show with a
nostril-obscured digit). When the director messed up, he servilely
told Dr. Laura, ``We'll spank him for you,'' to which Dr. Laura
replied, ``Too kinky for me.'' He also stopped the taping at one
point to scold a group of teen-age girls who had the bad form to
come down with a case of suppressed giggles while sitting
prominently in the background of a shot.
</P>
<P>
   In the episode I witnessed, Dr. Laura _ clad in black save for a
longish powder-blue jacket (a couple of female floor assistants
copied _ coincidentally? _ the powder-blue and black color scheme)
_ railed and railed against men who would take advantage of what
she referred to, at one point, as ``young female girls.'' Outside
of a handful of Humbert Humberts in this world, is there really
anyone who could conceivably come to the defense of such people?
The fish Dr. Laura was shooting weren't in a barrel; they were in a
thimble.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of her guests were women who had gotten pregnant as
teens at the, um, hands, um, not !ital!hands _ well, you know _ of
significantly older men. One was humiliated by her experience, but
not so humiliated that she wouldn't talk about it on national
television, while the other, now in her 30s, seemed to have gotten
over her travails, maintained a good relationship with her family
and in general was pretty well-adjusted. Which didn't really seem
to jibe with the soberly cautionary tone of the show.
</P>
<P>
   The good doctor also had a couple of guests who worked at local
women's shelters _ curiously, one of these was the sole person she
did sort of harangue _ who didn't seem to subscribe to their host's
notion that older men exploiting younger women was a phenomenon
that could be stopped cold in its tracks. Having flogged the older
guy/younger woman dead horse to even further death, she then
shifted gears to discuss teens having sex with one another.
Surprise, she's against that, too.
</P>
<P>
   She dragged out a couple of pre-approved teen-agers who
announced that they intended to wait until marriage before they had
sex (to desultory audience encouragement). She then turned to an
Orthodox Jewish family friend, who sternly lectured the crowd that
the purpose of dating is a serious one; find a suitable mate;
undertaken with utmost gravity; blah blah blah blah. As comedowns
go, this ranked up there with Bill Buckner's tank job in the '86
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the teens _ and their parents _ were frightfully
inarticulate, but since Dr. Laura missed her cue to go to
commercial nearly every segment and often by more than a minute,
there'll be a lot that can easily be trimmed from the episode to
thin it down to broadcast length. The show concluded with the
results of a poll conducted on Dr. Laura's own Web site, which
found that 38 percent _ of her own fans _ didn't believe teens
should be thrown in jail for having sex before the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   Duly scandalized, Dr. Laura ranted against the idea of
teen-agers having sex _ though, to be honest, it seemed more to be
a rant against the idea of teen-agers in general _ and then we were
sent home. But not before they shot a series of reaction shots _
people laughing on command at nothing in particular, to be inserted
into the show at sundry points to make Dr. Laura look even funnier
than she really is, one supposes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura seems adamantly incapable of understanding why anyone
would want to do anything besides toe the straight and narrow path,
though there exists a batch of photos that suggests she once was
capable of straying herself. But people like Dr. Laura are resolute
in their quest to ``rescue'' others from dabbling in the same sorts
of lifestyles that they themselves may have indulged in, even
though it's apparent that youthful rebellion doesn't automatically
result in a squandered adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Look, for an easy example, at Dr. Laura herself _ she sowed some
wild oats and made a few mistakes, but that hasn't prevented her
from becoming a phenomenal success story. George W. Bush partied
heartily into middle age, and now he's only a few micro-manipulated
Presidential debates from kicking his reptilian-skinned cowboy
boots atop the desk in the Oval Office. Some of those who fare
worst in their adulthood, in fact, are timorous souls who quivered
under the domineering reigns of oppressive parents who
psychologically cudgeled their progeny and prevented them from ever
making a life for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But hey _ guys who complain about people who tell others what to
do shouldn't tell those people what they should be doing, so I'm
not about to suggest Dr. Laura change her imperious ways. It's
pretty clear it's all showbiz anyway _ just another
attention-grabbing shtick in a town that can never have too many of
them. Based on what I saw, however, it seems pretty safe to say
that Dr. Laura's far more in her element on the radio than before
the cameras. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
