<HEADLINE>
`BROCKOVICH' NOT ENOUGH; `SHANE' SHINES ON DVD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``Erin Brockovich'' (DVD) _ Julia Roberts is the
box-office queen. Despite a limited range, or maybe because of it,
she's carved a career out of playing sexy mainstream characters.
And though this hit is based on the true story of one woman's fight
against the system, it lacks conviction. It makes you want to run
out and rent Martin Ritt's ``Norma Rae'' with Sally Field, or catch
``Silkwood'' with Meryl Streep. Those were politicized characters
with range and grace and guts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW ON DVD: ``Shane'' _ Producer-director George Stevens was
Cecil B. DeMille with heart. The filmmaker who counted ``A Place in
the Sun,'' ``Giant,'' and ``The Greatest Story Ever Told'' among
his epic works made this rather intimate Western in which character
dominates the landscape. Alan Ladd, as the reluctant title
character, is called upon to defend Jean Arthur and Van Heflin's
homestead. One of the first of the so-called ``adult'' Westerns,
``Shane'' is a morally ambiguous story about gunfighting and the
internal consequences endured by the victor. Jack Palance is
terrific as the villain. George Stevens Jr., who was a child at the
time of the production but who spent time with his father on the
set, provides a commentary on the alternate track. The spectacular
Western vistas are enhanced by the crystal-clear reproduction on
DVD.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OLD ON DVD: ``Jaws'' has more bite than Universal Studios
imagined. The 25-year-old movie beat all the current DVD releases
in the sales department during its first two weeks out. Sales
reached nearly 500,000 over the first 10 days, making an estimated
$25 million for Universal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DVD ONLINE: Black DVD Online (www.blackdvdonline.com) is a
clearinghouse for news, reviews, and locations of African-American
films on DVD. The site provides details on more than 300 titles
featuring black themes and performers. ``There are sites about DVD
and sites about black movies,'' said Samuel L. McLemore Jr.,
founder of the Web site, in an interview in Video Business. He told
the magazine the site averages 130,000 to 150,000 hits a week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: Aug. 22: ``Simpatico.'' Sept. 5: ``A Summer's
Tale'' (DVD), ``The Unknown Jonathan Winters'' (DVD), ``The Unknown
Peter Sellers'' (DVD).
</P>
</TEXT>
