<SLUG> BC-COLLEGES-MALE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Includes friendly/unfriendly campuses text table.)  
 WOMEN'S RIGHTS, MEN WRONG?  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ Rapist.
</P>
<P>
   Just the whiff of accusation was enough to chill the campus
climate last winter for Ryan Girard and Chris Bombardier and other
University of Massachusetts students whose only sins were their
average height, their baseball caps _ and their gender.
</P>
<P>
   Four rapes had allegedly taken place near the Campus Pond, and
all that students had to go on was a composite sketch that looked
like half the men on campus. Male students began feeling studied
over, as if they were being compared to the description.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough being a guy around here,'' said Girard, a junior
with thick sideburns and a slight goatee. ``You get dirty looks
from girls all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   For students such as Girard, a new survey by a leading magazine
confirmed what he sometimes suspected: UMass Amherst is one of the
10 worst campuses in the nation for male students, according to
Men's Health.
</P>
<P>
   Three other New England schools _ Brown University, Dartmouth
College, and Bates College _ also made the list, based on a survey
of students and professors about campuses that were unwelcoming to
men.
</P>
<P>
   The rankings' thesis _ that the 10 were havens of political
correctness, where men were regarded as drunken, horny predators _
dismayed many college officials. ``We're not an unfriendly school
to anyone,'' said Javier Cevallos, UMass's interim vice chancellor
for student affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Others note that some so-called ``anti-male'' policies that
Men's Health complains about are really just efforts to level the
playing field in institutions that, only a few decades ago, were
still all-male or had special curfews and rules for women.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, some male students and experts on campus life say higher
education _ while not overtly anti-male _ has become less welcoming
to men.
</P>
<P>
   They say the strength of the women's movement at Northeast
colleges, and the fact that women outnumber men enrolling and
graduating today, have led to a new kind of special treatment for
women _ such as harassment codes and orientation programs that,
some men say, cast them as potential predators.
</P>
<P>
   ``If campuses believed in truth in advertising, this is what
their catalogs would start off with: `We believe your sons are the
sexist, privileged beneficiaries of a system of patriarchy, and for
massive taxpayer subsidies or $30,000 a year, we'll assign them
unequal rights,' '' said Alan Charles Kors, a professor of history
at the University of Pennsylvania and coauthor of ``The Shadow
University,'' a polemic against political correctness on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Kors said male students have become targets particularly of
student-life codes in higher education. Most famously, a male
freshman at Penn was charged in 1993 with violating a speech policy
when he called five black women ``water buffalo'' for making noise
outside his dorm. The student said he had not meant to malign the
women, and the complaint against him was eventually dropped. Penn
also settled a lawsuit by the accused, and changed the code.
</P>
<P>
   At Antioch College, an institution in Ohio that also made the
magazine's worst-school list, a policy warns that when students
become intimate, they risk being punished unless they follow a
detailed playbook for rounding the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Verbal consent should be obtained with each new level of
physical and/or sexual behavior in any given interaction,
regardless of who initiates it,'' the code states. ``Asking `Do you
want to have sex with me?' is not enough. The request for consent
must be specific to each act.''
</P>
<P>
   UMass does not have such a policy, but some critics of speech
codes say the university's policy governing verbal harassment does
infringe on students' First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of men are afraid to speak up because they get labeled
sexist,'' said Daphne Patai, a professor of Brazilian literature at
UMass Amherst, who has written about gender issues on campus.
``That a climate of suspicion about words and gestures has been
created by the concept of sexual harassment seems clear.''
</P>
<P>
   But are such policies anti-male? Arlene Avakian, an associate
professor of women's studies at UMass, said clashes on many
Northeast campuses between women's activists on the one side, and
conservative students and professors on the other, may give some
men the ``myopic'' view that they are treated badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think it's a good campus for men because they could
learn more about women's issues so they could work to create a more
humane world,'' Avakian said. ``If this is a bad place for men
because women are getting supported, it's a much worse place for
women who are being assaulted.''
</P>
<P>
   Several male UMass students said last week they were disgusted
by the attacks last winter. At the same time, they felt unfairly
under suspicion, and placed part of the blame for that on the
campus environment for men.
</P>
<P>
   Bombardier, a senior at UMass, recalled his freshmen
orientation, when new female students were warned that rape and
harassment were problems on campus. Bombardier said the message was
that women should be on guard constantly, which he felt was unfair
to the men in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like walking on eggshells at this school,'' he said.
``You're not sure if people are looking at you like a rapist.''
</P>
<P>
   Lionel Tiger, a professor of anthropology at Rutgers University,
said he believes male students do not feel comfortable pressing
their needs now that campuses have becoming increasingly dominated
by female students. About 8 million women attend college, compared
to about 6.3 million men, according to federal statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has stood up for them, in a sense,'' said Tiger, author
of ``The Decline of Males,'' a 1999 book about the role of men in
families. ``For a lot of males, they feel kind of left out of the
larger dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   But many male students at Dartmouth College certainly spoke up
last year when officials proposed opening Greek houses to both men
and women. Dartmouth, which is widely regarded as a comfortable
school for men, watered down that plan, but was still spanked by
Men's Health for broaching the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the job of all of us to make students, faculty, and
everyone feel welcome,'' said Laurel Stavis, a Dartmouth
spokeswoman. ``These are not easy things to accomplish, but they're
crucial things to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities for women, however, add to the perception of some
students that colleges set a double-standard for men.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Wortman, a UMass junior studying computer science, said he
and some friends were bewildered when a computer lab posted a job
ad that specifically sought female workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little unsure if that was legal,'' he said, with a
note of derision in his voice. A male friend of his ended up
getting the job.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Fix, a senior majoring in speech pathology, and her
boyfriend, Jason Eiseman, a 1998 graduate, said they thought the
anti-male label for UMass was unfair. But the university's efforts
to clamp down on its ``ZooMass'' party reputation has curbed
staples of campus life that many men enjoy, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a pink blanket near the pond here, in between bites
of his picnic lunch, Eiseman described how men flocked to his
dormitory freshmen year to play drinking games. One concoction of
choice, he said, was a shot of Sambuca with a live goldfish slipped
in.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, UMass officials have shut down a couple of
fraternities for alcohol violations and enforced a zero-tolerance
policy for underage drinking. Last year, disciplinary action
involving drinking cases fell 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be a huge party and fraternity scene,'' Eiseman
said. ``The tide definitely turned.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE MOST ANTI-MALE CAMPUSES &QL; 
a. Antioch College &QL; 
b. Brown University &QL; 
c. Columbia University &QL; 
d. Dartmouth College &QL; 
e. Georgetown University &QL; 
f. Oberlin College &QL; 
g. University of California-Santa Cruz &QL; 
h. University of Michigan &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE MOST FRIENDLY CAMPUSES FOR MEN &QL; 
 &QL; 
a. California State University-Long Beach &QL; 
b. Davidson College &QL; 
c. Illinois Wesleyan University &QL; 
d. Indiana University &QL; 
e. Lewis &AMP; Clark College &QL; 
f. Princeton University &QL; 
g. Vanderbilt University &QL; 
h. Washington &AMP; Lee University &QL; 
 &QL; 
Source: Men's Health magazine &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
