<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1067 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-IVY-CANDIDATES-BOS &LR;      08-14 1689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVY-CANDIDATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN (IVY) LEAGUE OF THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's ability, not pedigree, that matters. Or so we're told.
</P>
<P>
   Believe that? Consider this.
</P>
<P>
   Come fall of 2001, when ``The Game'' _ the yearly gridiron clash
between Harvard and Yale _ rolls around, both the Democratic and
Republican tickets could be there in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Among the four candidates, three are Yalies, one a Harvard man.
Joseph Lieberman, Al Gore's running mate, has two degrees from
Yale, George W. one from each school. Dick Cheney, Bush's second
banana, did two years, on and off, at Yale before finishing at the
University of Wyoming. Gore went to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two major parties are competing to see who can pay greater
homage to American diversity, and their own version of diversity is
three guys from Yale and a guy from Harvard,'' jokes Ralph
Whitehead, professor of journalism at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, so exclusive is this particular election that even the
third-party candidates have Ivy League diplomas. Green Party
champion Ralph Nader got his undergraduate degree at Princeton
before earning a law degree at Harvard. Pat Buchanan, who passes as
the scrappy mutt in an Ivy League litter, went to Georgetown
undergrad, before getting a master's at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Ivy League's lock on the 2000 presidential
campaign even more remarkable is that it comes when the elite
schools are supposedly less revered in everyday American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The influence of the Ivy League was much stronger 40 years ago
than it is now,'' says Ted Morgan, biographer of Franklin
Roosevelt. ``At that time they had a monopoly on America's elite.
Now there are other schools that are just as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is one reason Boston University chancellor John Silber,
who earned his MA and PhD at Yale, sees no significance to the
Yale-Harvard face-off. ``It is just a fluke,'' says Silber. ``Those
things happen. You go to a casino and every now and then, three
cherries line up or three oranges or three lemons.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so _ and yet, be they cherries or lemons, the Ivy Leaguers
seem to be lining up and squaring off an awful lot in the last few
elections. In New Haven, Director of Public Affairs Larry Haas
boasts that the presence of a Yale graduate on both the Democratic
and GOP tickets means a son of Eli will have been on every
successful national ticket from 1980 to 2000. Of the 28 major-party
national ticket slots since 1976, Yale claims nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it is fate, but I do believe it is more than
coincidence,'' says Richard Brodhead, dean of Yale College, who
says the Yalies on the national tickets are only the most visible
manifestation of a public-service mission that sees Yale graduates
serving in all levels of government.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, if graduate degrees are counted, Harvard still leads,
with six presidents to Yale's four. Interestingly, though, while
Harvard hasn't had an alum in the Oval Office since John Kennedy
(1961-63), Yale has had three since 1974: Ford, Bush, and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Counting this year, three of the most recent four elections,
meanwhile, have had a distinct Yale-Harvard cast. In 1988, George
H.W. Bush was, of course, a Yalie, while Michael Dukakis, who
earned his undergraduate degree from Swarthmore, had a Harvard law
degree. (Who can forget Bush's poisonous Ivy League insult that
Dukakis got his foreign-policy views from a ``Harvard boutique''?)
Ditto 1992, given Bill Clinton's time at Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is the first year in modern memory where Yale and
Harvard have so clearly dominated the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Why? One reason seems to be the presidential recruitment
pipeline. In the modern era, chief executives come from three
places: the vice-presidency, a governorship, or the US Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Ivy League and other elite schools are disproportionately
represented there.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 151 possible candidates _ two senators, one governor, per
state, plus the VP _ 41 have a degree of some sort from one of six
colleges: Harvard, Yale, Stanford, Columbia, Princeton, or
Dartmouth. (If, like Bush, an officeholder has a degree from each,
he's credited to the school that awarded the BA.)
</P>
<P>
   Thus, all other things being equal, there's a 27 percent chance
that a given candidate for president hails for an elite university.
(By that reckoning, Harvard currently counts 16
presidential-eligible officeholders, Yale 10.)
</P>
<P>
   But all other things are hardly equal; there also appears to be
a significant amount of self-selection at play in the field of the
political lords. This year, for example, both Democratic candidates
and three of the five plausible Republicans hopefuls had elite Ivy
League degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to a variant of the age-old chicken-and-egg question
of causation: Is an elite university education something that
shapes a candidate for high office? Or is it family background that
pushes a person both to a Harvard or a Yale and then along a
high-profile political path?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly ability is important, and the best of Harvard and Yale
students can make a legitimate claim to be the nation's best and
the brightest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They happen to be very good schools, which says something
about the caliber of candidates who are running,'' says Dukakis,
who modestly counts himself a Swarthmorean.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, objects social critic Camille Paglia. Paglia, who
earned a doctorate at Yale, contends that the real power of a
Harvard or Yale degree is less in what, than whom, one knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yale or Harvard connection has nothing to do with superior
education or superior people; it has to do with a web of
friendships and affiliations built up in school,'' she says. ``We
have gone back to the era of the aristocratic court.''
</P>
<P>
   Paglia's critique wins basic agreement from Garrison Nelson, a
professor of political science at the University of Vermont who has
studied leadership recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't come to these schools to be educated, they come
to be credentialed and to network,'' Nelson says. ``These are the
most ambitious young men in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeping statements, those. Yet apply them to this year's
election: Watching a pedestrian campaign, or viewing academic
records that run from mediocre to middling, it's hard to spot real
intellectual sparkle in either Bush or Gore.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there's no denying that both were sons of
privilege who attended prestigious prep schools and benefited from
politically connected fathers. Which makes it hard not to conclude
that their Ivy League diplomas may be better barometers of family
background than intellectual distinction.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps there's something more at work here.
</P>
<P>
   If Harvard and Yale attract students who not only hope someday
to be a governor or senator or even president, but who consider it
altogether possible, voters also look at them in a special way. In
an age that stresses education, a degree from a top-flight school
is a mark of validation as ``a certified achiever, part of what you
might call the status reference groups,'' says Tobe Berkovitz,
professor of communication at BU.
</P>
<P>
   ``These schools basically give you cachet,'' concurs Nelson.
``This is a brand name. It is shorthand for competence.''
</P>
<P>
   The media seems just as fascinated by pedigree, so much so that
entire chapters in the newspaper biographies of Bush and Gore have
been devoted to the candidates' college careers in Cambridge or New
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to think that if Gore or Bush had gone to, say, the
University of Tennessee or Texas A&AMP;M, quite so much ink would have
been spilled chronicling their college years. What, after all, do
we know of Reagan at Eureka College? Can anyone remember where Bob
Dole went to college?
</P>
<P>
   If Harvard and Yale weigh heavily in the public mind, they
figure just as importantly in shaping identity and validating
ambition. If caricature of a Harvard grad always eager to sprinkle
that fact into conversation is in some part a stereotype born of
Ivy envy, it's still fair to say that self-confidence is in
sufficient enough supply in Cambridge and New Haven that neither
college has ever had to resort to rationing.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly the Harvard or Yale experience plays a stronger
part in a graduate's everyday sense of himself than do most other
colleges. Here, for example, is how Harvard graduate _ and former
governor _ William F. Weld answered a recent question about why he
prefers the shorter reviews of the New York Times Book Review to
the longer essays in the New York Review of Books: ``I enjoyed
being a member of the Fly Club more than a member of the Signet
Society at Harvard.'' Signet, Weld hastened to explain, is a
literary society, while the Fly Club is basically a social
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what other college's graduates assume that others know,
or are interested in, the difference between their college's clubs,
societies, or, even, residence halls? Or that their college days
are relevant reference point decades later?
</P>
<P>
   In other times and places, a privileged background might play as
a distinct disadvantage. Certainly it did for Bush in his
unsuccessful 1978 race for Congress, when opponent Kent Hance
mocked him as a son of privilege.
</P>
<P>
   But prosperity has muted American suspicion of privilege and
made elites more broadly trusted and acceptable, contends Jeffrey
Bell, author of ``Populism and Elitism,'' and a veteran of Ronald
Reagan's presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compare this year to 1992, when a sitting president gets 37
percent of the vote and Ross Perot gets 19 percent even though he
is talking about Martians invading his daughter's wedding,'' says
Bell. ``But now, (Federal Reserve Chairman) Alan Greenspan is one
of the most admired figures in American life. It is just a very
unusual mindset on the part of the American voter to have that much
of a trust in the people who are on top.''
</P>
<P>
   In those circumstances, you'd trust Ivy too. Wouldn't you?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Scot Lehigh is the Boston Globe Focus writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
