<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RESUME-FRAUD-BOS &LR;      08-14 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESUME-FRAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALSE CREDENTIALS WORRY HEALTH CARE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Roark performed surgery on hundreds of patients in Ohio,
Michigan, and Canada before supervisors learned his medical degree
was bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen applicants for a gastroenterology fellowship at the
University of Pittsburgh falsely claimed they had published
research papers.
</P>
<P>
   The chief financial officer of UMass Memorial Health Care was
demoted to vice president last month when his bachelor's and
master's degrees were exposed as fictional.
</P>
<P>
   Falsified credentials have become a nagging problem for the
health care industry, helping to spur a whole new cadre of
background-checking firms in recent years to stem the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Although executive search firms say resume fibs are at epidemic
levels across professions, the problem is particularly worrisome in
the health care industry, where lapses in integrity can not only
embarrass a company but also endanger a patient. Roark, for
example, has been sued by a man who says his botched surgery left
him with no feeling in one hand.
</P>
<P>
   Now, UMass Memorial's willingness to keep Michael Greene on as
vice president has some critics calling for more serious attention
to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachusetts, two areas in which we are national leaders,
education and medicine, are also two areas where qualifications and
personal integrity are paramount,'' said Nancy Achin Sullivan,
executive director of the state Board of Registration in Medicine.
``I think we should expect better.''
</P>
<P>
   While Greene never pretended to be a doctor _ a more severe
offense in most people's books _ some feel UMass Memorial set a bad
example by deciding to demote him, not fire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am stunned. It is incomprehensible to me,'' said Peter
George, a headhunter for Management Recruiters International who
said he has located 12 new hires for Massachusetts General Hospital
in the past year. ``They should demote him to unemployed.''
</P>
<P>
   But UMass Memorial trustees and executives have essentially
pleaded ``no harm, no foul.'' Although Greene's falsified resume is
regrettable, they say, he has been good for the institution. Greene
declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant outsider who lacks the right pedigree but bluffs a
way into success is almost as much an American icon as the Horatio
Alger hero who rises from humble origins by following the rules.
Resume-bluffing is often viewed as a victimless crime, something
``everybody does,'' job recruiters say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, claiming false credentials or omitting negatives from a
resume can have real, harmful consequences, say physicians,
headhunters, and educators. The harm, they say, ranges from the
physical, such as subjecting patients to treatment by phony
doctors, to the intangible, such as devaluing the sacrifices of
people who honestly earn degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said the Massachusetts medical board disciplined 17
doctors between 1995 and 1999 for embellishing credentials _
nothing nearly as extreme as faking a medical degree _ or failing
to disclose disciplinary actions or malpractice lawsuits against
them. The doctors were fined between $2,500 and $5,000 as part of
the board's mission of ``protecting the public,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with non-physician employees, teaching hospitals, including
UMass Memorial, which is affiliated with the University of
Massachusetts Medical School, have a special responsibility to
uphold academic integrity, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Witt/Kieffer, a national executive search firm that specializes
in health care and has Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston among
its clients, automatically rejects candidates, physicians or not,
who are found to have falsified a resume, spokeswoman Susan Nalepa
said.
</P>
<P>
   Health systems have a ``sacred trust'' to provide care, she
said, and the leader of the system must be ``regarded as having
very high personal integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiter and vice president Emanuel D. Berger said applicants
should be straightforward: ``Most executive search consultants are
willing to look at an unusual candidate, perhaps without a degree,
if they have other qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene built his 20-year career partly on claims he had a
bachelor's degree from the University of Massachusetts and a
master's of business administration from Northeastern University,
schools he attended but from which he did not graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The fiction helped get him a two-year stint as top administrator
at Cambridge City Hospital in the 1980s and a succession of jobs at
University of Massachusetts Medical Center, which he helped
shepherd through a merger with private Memorial Health Care.
Questioned by his bosses last month after the Worcester Telegram &AMP;
Gazette raised questions, Greene offered his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of accepting it, chief executive officer Dr. Arthur
Russo said Greene was a brilliant administrator who had made a
youthful mistake, and demoted him to vice president.
</P>
<P>
   John O'Brien, who worked under Greene at the Cambridge, Mass.
hospital and is now its CEO, declined to pass judgment on the UMass
decision. ``Every (health care) system has to make a decision like
that on their own,'' he said, adding that Greene was a
``hard-driving, results-oriented'' administrator.
</P>
<P>
   That is beside the point, said Barmak Nessirian, an analyst with
the American Association of Collegiate Registrars and Admissions
Officers, which represents 9,300 higher education administrators in
the United States and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all the sympathy in the world with people who feel that
their performance in itself explains their qualificaton,'' he said.
``It may be that there are plenty of positions that currently
require a degree that should not. But the college degree represents
a significant commitment of resources in terms of cost and in terms
of academic effort. People shouldn't simply decide that . . . they
can essentially award it to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Harvard Medical School fired a middle manager
who was found to have exaggerated educational credentials and prior
work experience, said Don Gibbons, director of communications. He
said the school checks references but does not routinely verify the
college degrees of applicants for non-medical positions.
</P>
<P>
   The physician who finally caught Roark _ by carrying out a
routine check with an American Medical Association database when he
applied for a job _ said most physicians would be perturbed if they
had to work under a hospital executive with a faked record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to think you've affiliated yourself with an
organization that's not as assiduous as they might be in checking
one's credentials or qualifications,'' said Dr. Linda Nash, chief
of medicine at Ingham Regional Medical Center in Lansing, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Her experience with Roark has prompted her to lobby for tighter
credential-checking requirements for hospitals. She is not alone:
James B. Stewart's 1999 book ``Blind Eye'' criticized doctors for
failing to police their own in the case of Michael Swango, the
physician accused of killing patients in a series of hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Roark practiced medicine for 10 years, although he never
attended medical school and was dropped from two residency programs
for inadequate performance. In 1998, he was sentenced to six to 14
years in prison by a judge who compared his conduct to sexual
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Even criminal background checks have their limitations. Henry M.
Jiminian, a 33-year-old clerical worker at Massachusetts General
Hospital, was arraigned last week on charges of killing a man in
New York eight years ago. The charges hadn't been filed in 1995,
when he was hired, and the hospital's routine criminal background
check wouldn't have caught an out-of-state offense.
</P>
<P>
   Companies afraid they could be sued for hiring people with false
credentials have fueled the growth of an entire industry of
credential-checking firms, Nessirian said. Thousands of falsifiers
are caught each month through calls to registrars' offices,
according to a five-year-old study.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Connors, of Risk Management Advisors in Stoneham, Mass.,
said his firm does about 4,500 credential checks a year, half in
the health care industry, and finds significant misinformation in
about one-fourth of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   If an applicant lies about credentials, he said, ``how can you
believe them when they come to you with information that's critical
to the health of the company?''
</P>
<P>
   Credential-checking firms have plenty of stories to tell about
bogus health care applicants.
</P>
<P>
   According to Paul Byron, senior vice president of LCF Associates
in Braintree, Mass., which charges $500 to $5,000 per search, one
applicant for a senior position claimed he had been blinded in a
boating accident for 12 years and regained his sight through
surgery. In fact, Byron said, he'd been in jail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service Information was used to prepare this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
