<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-14 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK'S TRANSFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Back in the early 1970s when I was living in New
York City, there was a standing joke that pretty much summed up the
attitude of the typical Manhattanite and the atmosphere that
attitude created:
</P>
<P>
   Late in her first day in the Big Apple, a weary tourist walks up
to a New Yorker on a street corner and says: ``Could you please
tell me how to get to the Empire State Building _ or should I just
go bleep myself?''
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? Things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   And they have changed so much for the better, I believe that the
inhabitants of my fabled little West Coast paradise _ San Francisco
_ could take some lessons in civility from New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   I noticed the beginning of the transformation in the early-'90s
when I was in New York on business. Friends had told me it was a
kinder, gentler town than the one I'd called home and visited
through the '80s. Friends were right.
</P>
<P>
   The streets were cleaner, there was less gratuitous horn
blowing, and the mass transit system, perhaps the most revealing
arena for a city's values and manners, was a relatively benign
experience. Even the subway.
</P>
<P>
   As I discovered last week, the situation has only improved.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan is not just a friendlier and more gracious place than
it used to be, it's friendlier and more gracious than - I never
thought I'd say this - San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Because I saw the change coming before he took office, I don't
credit Generalissimo Rudy Giuliani for New York's metamorphosis.
Yes, the current mayor has rid the streets of squeegee-wielding
mendicants and attempted to outlaw being poor.
</P>
<P>
   But scruffy men still push contraband shopping carts along the
sidewalks; women wearing five layers of clothing still stretch out
on the grass of Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than cosmetics or ``quality of life'' legislation, the
new New York seems to me most about attitude. And I suspect that
the turn-around is the result of New York's citizens reaching a
kind of change-or-die fork in the road.
</P>
<P>
   When I left Manhattan in 1975, the city was on the verge of
economic bankruptcy and all the municipal woes that sorry state
implies. People who had for years relished the Stein cartoon
perspective of New York _ all-important Manhattan in minute detail,
the rest of the United States represented by a few fuzzy landmarks
_ found themselves living in a seething, hostile, loser of a town.
</P>
<P>
   Humbled and threatened from within, they chose _ individually
and municipally _ to stop blaming each other, the latest wave of
immigrants or all elected officials. They took stock of their
community. They began to acknowledge a common thread of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike contemporary San Franciscans, Manhattanites today no
longer seem to have a collective chip on their shoulder. Nobody
owes them; they wear no mantle of entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere on the streets, in restaurants, in parks and on
buses is one of shared community. Whether they are conscious of it
or not, a great many New Yorkers appear to subscribe to a karmic
theory of existence:
</P>
<P>
   Dump some bad energy on a stranger and, be assured, it will come
back to you and the folks around you, probably three-fold.
Conversely, if you deliberately short-circuit a big dump of anger,
selfishness or stupidity - work to neutralize it, not nurture it -
you and the entire community benefit.
</P>
<P>
   I saw this approach manifest itself all over Manhattan in the
long weekend I was there.
</P>
<P>
   On crowded, behind-schedule buses, people still maintained a
kind of benevolent awareness of others. The younger and more
able-bodied noticed the older and more frail, and they gave them
their seats or an easier hand-hold on poles and railings.
</P>
<P>
   At least half of departing passengers, I swear to God, said,
``Thank you'' or ``Bye'' to the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   In three days, walking from the lower East Side to the Upper
West, through Hell's Kitchen, Central Park and my old neighborhood
in Chelsea in the West 20s, I heard more Excuse-me's and
I'm-sorry's than I have heard in San Francisco in the past 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Am I saying Manhattan has turned into some kind of Zen retreat
center?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. It's still noisy, bustling and as dirty as a small
island of 3-plus million people can't help but be. Lots of taxi and
truck drivers still negotiate the streets as if they were a Formula
One race course or use their horns like turn signals.
</P>
<P>
   But an awful lot of folks seem quick to smile back, hold open a
door, stand patiently in line for a cab at Penn Station or a hot
dog and kraut in United Nations Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   And while I didn't actually attempt it, my guess is, if you go
up to a New Yorker these days and ask how to get to the Empire
State Building, nine times out of 10, you'll get directions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
