<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT TIME FOR FELINES ONLINE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Do cats need e-mail?'' asks a press release from MeowMail.com.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they might want e-mail. Cats want so many things. But do
they really need it? My own cats were perfectly happy with their
cell phones until they heard about MeowMail.com. Now they want
their own e-mail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   I blame Stacey Miller and Steve Bennett, who together started
what they like to call ``the first online feline cat colony.''
Although maybe I should blame Maggie, the dog who inspired it. Yes,
a Web site for cats was inspired by a dog. Shocking, no?
</P>
<P>
   Maggie, a dog who lives in Medford with Cynthia Lima, likes to
send e-mail to her many friends of various species, including Chita
McChew and Nala La, the cats who share Miller's Randolph home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Steve about it,'' Miller says, ``and we looked at one
another and we both said `MeowMail.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't exactly ``Eureka!'' But it seemed like a timely idea.
This is a cat-crazed culture, and it's getting crazier by the day,
apparently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think all cats will want to be wired this millennium,''
Miller says. ``After all, your cat only goes around nine times.''
</P>
<P>
   Many cats already are wired, and not just temperamentally. Some
have their own Web sites. The magazine Cats &AMP; Kittens is even
holding a contest for the best cat-related Web design.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Bennett have been having fun with MeowMail.com.
``It's a great way to let our hair down and morph into our cats,''
says Bennett, a communications consultant who lives with a cat
named Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett says they have ``thousands'' of registered box holders,
although he wouldn't say just how many thousands. The e-mail
accounts are free. Bennett and Miller have also started selling a
few MeowMail.com products, such as printable cards, notepads, and
letterheads. They contribute a percentage of the sales to Alley Cat
Allies, a national feral cat network based in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably fair to say that most of those who visit the site
don't do it to buy anything, but to share the fun. Bennett's and
Miller's feline senses of humor appeal to cat owners, or ``human
valets,'' in the MeowMail.com argot.
</P>
<P>
   The site has a weekly newspaper, The Morning Hairball, with
``All the News That's Fit to Spit.'' This week it coughs up a story
on Cambridge's efforts to create a ``catnip-free'' zone. Previous
scoops have included a look at the controversial tightening of
federal litterbox-emission standards, a story about two heroic cats
who rescued a human stuck up a tree, and a piece about a possible
cure for the rodent-obsessed cat (``Are you consuming rodents? Or
are they consuming you?'').
</P>
<P>
   Cats are polled weekly. In one recent survey, 38 percent said
they think humans should be declawed, 67 percent said they think
they shouldn't be allowed on the furniture, and 90 percent think
they shouldn't be allowed to drink out of the toilet bowl.
</P>
<P>
   MeowMail.com also has an advice columnist, Felinadonna, a cat
who answers questions such as ``What's the proper protocol for
throwing up at human social events?'' The real question,
Felinadonna replies, is not when, but where. ``Well-mannered
felines will always move to carpeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, MeowMail.com knows its audience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
