<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HARRIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMYLOU HARRIS ENLISTS IN THE LAND-MINE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They make an odd couple, the Grammy-winning country singer and
the disabled Vietnam veteran. After 30 years in the recording
business, Emmylou Harris has little left to prove musically, yet
she continues to break new ground, as she did on her 1995
``Wrecking Ball'' album and ``Western Wall,'' last year's
collaboration with Linda Ronstadt. Harris has seldom been strongly
identified with political or social causes.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 years in a wheelchair, Robert Muller has a share of a
Nobel Peace Prize to his credit (awarded in 1997) and
near-universal respect for his work to rid the world of land mines.
However, until two years ago, Muller, president of the Vietnam
Veterans of America Foundation and a former Marine infantry
officer, was on a first-name basis with many more legislators than
singer-songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet fate, or something even more powerful, has thrown these two
unlikely allies together. It joined them with such force that as
Muller sat offstage recently at a $1,000-a-seat fund-raising
concert in Weston, where Harris performed a moonstruck 90-minute
set with Nashville sideman Buddy Miller, Muller glanced at the
singer and confessed, ``I'm half in love with Emmy. I really am.
She is truly our savior.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before the concert, Harris said, ``I'm an
attention-getting device, I know that. But after going to Cambodia
and Vietnam with Bobby, I've been fully committed to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Harris, who met Muller three years ago through a mutual
friend, ``There are a lot of good causes out there, but this is an
opportunity for me to do something in an area that people need to
know about. I thought land mines were something out of an Audie
Murphy movie. I didn't think they were killing and maiming
civilians all around the world every day.''
</P>
<P>
   What Harris, 53, has done, both in support of Muller's
foundation and in recharting her own career, says a lot about the
recording artist and her priorities. Long admired as a musician's
musician, a peerless harmony singer who has partnered with everyone
from Bob Dylan and Roy Orbison to George Jones and Dolly Parton,
Harris has called in some heavy chips in support of Muller's
efforts. Virtually no one has turned her down.
</P>
<P>
   A series of songwriter-in-the-round benefit concerts put
together by Harris last fall featured the likes of Willie Nelson,
Sheryl Crow, Steve Earle, Lucinda Williams, Nanci Griffith, John
Prine, Bruce Cockburn, Mary Chapin Carpenter, Bonnie Raitt, and Guy
Clark. And like Harris, Cockburn, Earle, Griffith, and Crow have
all toured Southeast Asia with Muller, whose group has established
rehabilitation clinics in some of the world's areas most affected
by land mines, notably Cambodia, Vietnam, and Angola. The concert
series netted the VVAF $175,000, plus priceless amounts of media
exposure, blue-chip connections, and political capital.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than a presence
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harris dedicated proceeds from last year's Gram Parsons tribute
album she co-produced to Muller's group as well. At Muller's
behest, she performed at the 1997 Nobel ceremonies in Norway,
televised to 200 million people worldwide. Since then, Muller and
Harris say, the spotlight has largely shifted to other concerns
such as chemical and biological weapons. With nearly 100 million
mines still in the ground, however, and with the United States
balking at signing a global land-mine ban (Harris personally
lobbied fellow Tennessean Al Gore for his support), the urgency is
just as great, they maintain, even if public awareness is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fade from political consciousness, forget it,'' Muller
declared during an interview in Cambridge before the first of two
benefit concerts. ``We're not going to get appropriations for
de-mining operations. It's really the entertainment world that
keeps us in play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's not a political issue,'' said Harris. ``The war's
over, we're gone, so people think the issue is resolved. It's not
resolved. The trash we left behind is killing someone every 22
minutes. We take for granted that we can go outside for a walk, or
our children can, without getting our genitals blown off. But
millions of people live with that fear. That's why they call it
terrorism in slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to know intellectually that people are victims
of land mines,'' she said. ``It's another thing to actually see it
and how common it is. We're not talking about handicapped-access
countries, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris is as good at jawboning Washington pols as she is at
crooning a Louvin Brothers ballad, according to Muller. When the
two of them met with Vice President Gore, Muller recalled, Harris
cut off the pleasantries and immediately began talking up the
land-mine treaty. Senator Fred Thompson (R-Tenn.) told Muller, ``If
it wasn't for her, you wouldn't be in here.'' Muller doesn't doubt
that.
</P>
<P>
   For Harris, this crusade coincides with several career changes,
among them a new record label (Nonesuch) and a forthcoming album of
mostly her own tunes, titled ``Red Dirt Girl.'' After ``Wrecking
Ball,'' she decided to jettison her old label (Asylum), management
team, and touring band. Two years on the road had left her in a
professional funk, Harris admitted, who has also been through three
marriages and raised two daughters while fashioning a career that
won her last year's prestigious Billboard Century Award.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the leap
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `` `Wrecking Ball' was a huge creative leap for me,'' she said.
``The downside of a record like that is, what do you follow it
with? Even if you've got the same people backing you, you don't
want to make `Son of Wrecking Ball.' I knew that the one thing I
could bring to the table that would be different this time were my
own words and music.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was also disappointed in how Asylum supported the
record, which won a Grammy _ Harris now has nine overall _ for best
contemporary folk album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I committed myself to working this record, and I expected the
same from them,'' she said. ``And I didn't get it. If they feel
they can't get a hit song on the radio, most major labels don't
know how to work an artist. They couldn't give me what I needed,
and I couldn't give them what they needed. There's no point in
being bitter about it. Ultimately, the record is there, and nobody
can take that away from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have just as easily played shows where people expect
to hear `Blue Kentucky Girl. I'm not going to forget `Blue Kentucky
Girl,' but that was 20 years ago. And I have something else to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Her latest musical statement, due out next month, ends a
self-described sabbatical during which Harris focused on other
kinds of projects. Her ``Trio II'' album (with Ronstadt and Parton)
and ``Teatro'' (with Willie Nelson) came out, joining ``Western
Wall,'' the Parsons tribute album, and a live album (``Spyboy'') on
store shelves. ``The Ballad of Sally Rose'' (1985) was the last
Harris album on which she served as chief songwriter. ``Western
Wall,'' a warm-up of sorts for ``Red Dirt Girl,'' has three Harris
compositions on it, another indication that at this stage of her
musical life Harris is determined to push forward.
</P>
<P>
   Friends such as ``Wrecking Ball'' producer Daniel Lanois,
engineer Malcolm Burn, and ex-husband Paul Kennerly had been
encouraging Harris to write more, she said. The title track, a
bittersweet tale about an Alabama girl and her unrealized dreams,
was written during a car ride from Nashville to New Orleans, where
``Red Dirt Girl'' was recorded. Harris performed it at the Weston
concert, where it stood out alongside such old chestnuts as
``Pancho and Lefty'' and ``Love Hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still sort of in shock,'' said Harris, ``from three years
ago until last November, when I went in with three songs written.''
By March, when she finished the album, Harris had written eight
more originals, some with Jill Cunniff. ``I don't know where it
came from, and it may never happen again,'' Harris said, shaking
her head. ``But I'm grateful for this record.''
</P>
<P>
   Burn produced and played on the album, recorded at his house in
New Orleans in a deliberately casual setting. Harris is joined by
Buddy Miller, his wife Julie Miller, and musicians Daryl Johnson,
Ethan Johns, Luscious Jackson, and Jill Cunniff. Guest vocalists
include Patti Griffin, Dave Matthews, and Kate McGarrigle. Harris
also realized a longstanding fantasy of hers by getting Patti
Scialfa to sing on one album track. When her husband, Bruce
Springsteen, came up with a third harmony part, said Harris, it was
pinch-me-I'm-dreaming time.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is also excited about signing with Nonesuch Records, a
small New York-based label that, as she said, ``has made its living
on the fringes of the mainstream'' with artists such as Laurie
Anderson and Audra McDonald. ``I may be the most mainstream artist
they have,'' she laughed.
</P>
<P>
   And while her tour this fall will focus on the new album, it's a
safe bet that Harris will continue to mix anti-land-mine messages
with the music. Muller is certainly not about to let her get away.
Being ``half in love'' will do that to a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come for the music and get something else,'' he said,
rolling his wheelchair across a soft suburban lawn where guests
nibbled on canapes and strawberries under summertime stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not going to watch a documentary film about land
mines,'' said Muller, ``but they'll fill a seat to hear Emmy. And
that creates a resonance, a buzz in the industry, that keeps us
alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
