<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1085 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-GUINNESS-BOS &LR;      08-14 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-GUINNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEC GUINNESS'S ACTING VISION ALWAYS CAPTURED OURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Sir Ralph Richardson, Sir Laurence Olivier, Sir John Gielgud,
and now Sir Alec Guinness. They were the monarchs of 20th-century
British acting. With the passing of Guinness last weekend at age
86, the kings are dead. They were kings of different realms _
Richardson of an almost mystical eccentricity, Olivier a high-wire
act of febrile intensity, Gielgud a flow of silvery music.
Guinness's art is the most difficuilt to capture in a phrase.
Partly it's because he was the most self-effacing of the four. He
often said he could never behave like a star because he had to
simply be his personality. Then, in the next breath, he would add
that he didn't have much of a personality.
</P>
<P>
   It was Guinness's chameleon ability to disappear into his
characters, however, that made him, over the long run, the most
successful of the four in film. Not that he would disappear
entirely. One will always remember his eyes, flashing with slyness,
mischief, fun, wary alertness. Time and again, those singular eyes
told us that this or that character knew something we didn't know,
or deliberately wasn't telling us everything. Film is faces, and
faces are eyes. It was Guinness's ability to engage us with his
eyes, yet convince us he was withholding something, making us
wonder what it was, that was most remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   That was the thread that linked so many of his memorable
performances. We somehow never noticed that he was a blue-eyed
Prince Faisal in ``Lawrence of Arabia'' (1962). As Obi-Wan Kenobi,
he anchored ``Star Wars'' (1977). Guinness persuaded us we felt
Obi-Wan's wisdom. But what first struck us was the twinkle in his
eyes as he doled out guidance to Luke Skywalker. Guinness's eyes
shone with the vision of the well-heeled expatriate liberty he
envisioned as a lowly bank clerk masterminding a gold heist in
``The Lavender Hill Mob'' (1951). He always made larceny look
deliciously naughty. He made instant accomplices of us with the
childlike gleam of pleasure in his eye as the untamable painter
Gulley Jimson in ``The Horse's Mouth'' (1958).
</P>
<P>
   Who can forget the scene in which Gulley stands alone in the
study of the art dealer who made lots of money off him, stuffing an
expensive jade figurine into his baggy pocket. When his respectable
lady friend in the next room, sensing that Gulley is up to no good,
shouts, ``What are you doing?'' he replies, ``I'm bettering
myself.'' Actors often tweak their scripts. ``The Horse's Mouth''
marked the only time Guinness got full writing credit, in this case
for adapting Joyce Cary's novel. Guinness earned an Oscar
nomination for writing that screenplay. His delight in playing a
rascal at one with the unruly impulses of art, and its refusal to
be hemmed in, remains no less zestful today. &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Bridge' work &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guinness won a best acting Oscar for his interned British
martinet, Colonel Nicholson, in David Lean's ``The Bridge on the
River Kwai'' (1957), playing out a clash of wills with his Japanese
counterpart, Sessue Hayakawa's prison camp commandant. Guinness
researched that role the hard way, observing military types up
close during a wartime navy stint. Guinness said he never was able
to empathize with the blinkered Nicholson. Perhaps it had something
to do with the fact that Guinness was the third choice for the
role, after Charles Laughton and Noel Coward.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was Lean who cast Guinness in the latter's
breakthrough film, ``Great Expectations'' (1946). Lean remembered
Guinness in the latter's own stage adaptation of it in 1939. In the
film, as onstage, he portrayed Herbert Pocket, who befriends
Dickens's young protagonist, Pip, played by John Mills, who was to
become Guinness's lifelong friend. (They acted together in the
lesser-known but first-rate film about a Scottish regiment, ``Tunes
of Glory'' in 1960, and took turns playing Lawrence of Arabia
onstage in the 1960s in ``Ross.'')
</P>
<P>
   A mere two years after playing Pocket, Guinness proved an artful
codger, aging decades to play Fagin in Lean's film of another
Dickens classic, ``Oliver Twist'' (1948). The fruitful
Lean-Guinness collaborations, unhampered by the fact that Guinness
found Lean humorless, ended with ``A Passage to India'' (1984), in
which Guinness, uncharacteristically but persuasively, played a
Hindu mystic. Roles in a series of Ealing Studio comedies first
cemented Guinness's hold on international audiences, starting with
his unprecedented portrayals of eight characters in the disarmingly
dotty comedy of murders, ``Kind Hearts and Coronets'' (1949). In
it, he plays eight members of an aristocratic family standing
between a killer and a title, including a dowager and, of course,
the obligatory vicar. He was a blissful high flyer in ``The Man in
the White Suit'' (1951), carrying over some of that character's
long-bottled-up glee to ``The Lavender Hill Mob.''
</P>
<P>
   To many, this observer included, Guinness hit his criminal peak
in ``The Ladykillers'' (1955). In it, he plays a mad professor
orchestrating grandiose larceny to the hilariously incongruous
strains of Boccherini's Minuet in E Flat, a recording of which he
would play while hatching plans with his gang. The idea was to
throw off the professor's nosy landlady (the immortal Margaret
Rutherford), who had been told that they were a string quintet
meeting behind closed doors to rehearse. The crazed, toothy smile
Guinness slapped on the face of the hyperventilating professor,
making him seem sublimely zany, was his revenge on drama critic
Kenneth Tynan, who had panned a Guinness stage performance. The
public was oblivious to the actor's source of inspiration for his
mad professor, but the tightly knit London film and stage community
recognized it immediately. For them, it was a source of mirth; for
Tynan, a source of discomfort. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A self-effacing tradition &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guinness was a regular participant in Hollywood
mega-productions, ranging from the ponderously respectable ``Doctor
Zhivago'' (1965) to the massively ridiculous ``The Fall of the
Roman Empire'' (1964). Not that he took any of them that seriously.
To be self-effacing, or at least appear so, was a strong part of
the tradition out of which he came, starting when Gielgud, a
frequent collaborator-to-be, cast him as Osric and the Third Player
in ``Hamlet'' in 1934 following Guinness's wordless West End debut
the year before as a jury member in ``Libel!'' By 1938, Guinness
was starring in his own ``Hamlet,'' a modern dress version. Some
obituaries listed ``Great Expectations'' as his first screen
credit. Actually, Guinness first appeared as an uncredited extra, a
World War I soldier in a concert audience in ``Evensong'' (1934).
</P>
<P>
   He later was to revel in virtual invisibility, especially in his
mesmerizing TV portrayal of John Le Carre's spymaster, George
Smiley, in ``Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy'' (1980) and ``Smiley's
People'' (1982). Remarkably, he was able to triumph over his own
lack of physical resemblance to Smiley. As Le Carre described him,
Smiley was fatter, with several chins. Le Carre's Smiley suggested
an Alfred Hitchcock ringer. But Guinness drew our attention to his
eyes, not his lack of chins. Those eyes were filled with acuteness,
pain, worldweariness and a refusal to buckle despite a life
betrayed by everyone on his side _ wife, fellow spies, bureaucrats.
The scene in which Smiley blandly soldiers through a Whitehall
budget meeting, surrounded by back-stabbing bureaucrats, mumbling
into his chins, never completing a sentence, but somehow emerging
with everything he wants, is one of the century's sublime pieces of
high comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Smiley's way with the bureaucrats was not unlike Guinness's way
with acting. He never was obvious, yet always seemed to get what he
wanted _ from a role, a film, a career. More of a literary man than
he ever let on except when he surfaced with that screenplay credit
for ``The Horse's Mouth,'' he appreciated irony. Until ``Star
Wars,'' which he came to describe as his pension, he never earned
astronomical sums. Because George Lucas was broke, he signed
Guinness for 2 1/4 percent of the gross. ``Star Wars'' grossed
hundreds of millions. Guinness, late in life, earned millions from
it. Not that it deepened his respect for the film. He persuaded
Lucas to rewrite it so Obi-Wan could die sooner. Convincing
audiences he was Hitler and Sigmund Freud and, onstage (where he
maintained he did his best work), Dylan Thomas, took some doing.
Donning a hooded robe and sounding wise did not. ``They think I
really am a Jedi knight instead of just a Knight of the British
Empire,'' Guinness once said in a radio interview, in his
inimitably dry, measured tones, pronouncing Jedi as if it rhymed
with ready. ``They think I have wisdom!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
