<P>
   These excellent articles are from the current ECONOMIST magazine
(week beginning 12 August 2000); they have all moved to the ``k''
commentary category code. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from the New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use these articles only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL THE REAL AL GORE PLEASE STAND UP? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOUR-HEADED-GORE-ECONOMIST-575&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the Democrats gathering in Los Angeles for their convention
next week, America's voters will have before them four men bidding
to lead their country. Should they choose the pragmatic politician,
the co-chief executive of their country, who has supervised eight
years of staggering prosperity? Or what about the dreamy idealist,
the policy wonk absorbed by technology and the environment? Or
perhaps the sour, partisan reactionary _ a brutal attack dog who
specializes in ripping apart the ``risky'' dreams of others? Or
then again, there is the panicky panderer, who changes his mind
about a small Cuban boy's future just to win a few votes in Miami.
It shouldn't be too difficult, but for one thing: all four of these
men are Al Gore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 150; total uncut is 1,100) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KASHMIR PEACE PROCESS: BACK TO GROUND ZERO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KASHMIR-GOADS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After barely a fortnight of frail life, the peace process in
Jammu and Kashmir is officially dead. The conflict seems to be back
to the same hopeless state in which it has languished for 53 years
_ except that nowadays, on a whim of either India or Pakistan, it
could turn nuclear. Even if the past hopeful fortnight's events
turn out to be no more than a feint in the direction of peace,
though, they have revealed the contours of how a peace process
might evolve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILIBUSTIN' FIDEL FINALLY RUNS OUT OF AIR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CASTRO-SHUTS-UP-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans will this week have found themselves in
the unusual position of agreeing with Fidel Castro. Both George W.
Bush and Al Gore are ``boring,'' said the Cuban leader. Sheer
hypocrisy, Bush and Gore might reply. After all, for four decades,
Castro has notoriously bored his long-suffering people with
speeches lasting hour after hour. In the view of the old guerrilla,
it has always seemed, fatigues are not just to be worn but also to
be inflicted. No longer, though: the Cuban president has at last
realized that, when it comes to words, less can be more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOE LIEBERMAN'S SHOCK VALUE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GUTSY-GORE-LIEBERMAN-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Before the current stage of the presidential
campaign began, conventional wisdom (excuse the term) held that
George W. Bush's choice of running mate would define his candidacy
but the Republican shindig in Philadelphia would not. Conversely,
it was thought that Al Gore's running mate would hardly matter
(because the options were all so dismal) but his speech to the
Democratic National Convention would be decisive. So far, every
part of this wisdom has turned out to be wrong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 100-word optional trim; total uncut is 1,075) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINALLY, CAMPAIGN 2000 GETS INTERESTING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RACE-GETS-RACY-ECONOMIST-900&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``There's a lot at stake in this election and real
differences between the two parties.'' When Joe Lieberman said that
just after Al Gore had formally picked him as the Democratic
running mate, it sounded like the sort of bland remark that
politicians perpetrate when they have nothing much to say.
Actually, it was both surprising and true. It was surprising
because for most Americans, this is one of the least gripping
elections on record. The discrepancy between what people seem to
think about this race and what is actually at stake is becoming
more striking during the current convention season _ ``the most
critical period of the campaign,'' claims Tom Mann of the Brookings
Institution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand alone in 900 words; 1,000 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IS THERE RAW SEWAGE IN YOUR DRINKING WATER? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `CRAPPY'-WATER-INDY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Watkins Park, with its meandering stream and its
thicket of greenery, is as bucolic as downtown Indianapolis gets.
But look a wee bit more closely _ or inhale a wee bit more deeply _
and reality intrudes. ``My God, look at that crap!'' shouts Tom
Neltner. As as activist environmentalist, he knows whereof he
speaks, and there it is: raw sewage, as well as condoms, clearly
visible in the stream. This rustic scene comes courtesy of
Indianapolis's ``combined sewer overflow'' (CSO) system, which was
designed nearly a century ago to carry both sewage and storm water
through one set of pipes. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Indianapolis, Midwest and Northwest Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOWN AND OUT IN NOT-SO-BUENOS AIRES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEPRESSED-ARGENTINES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES _ Not for nothing does Buenos Aires claim to have
more psychoanalysts per square mile than any other city in the
world. Good thing, too, for at the moment the national mood in
Argentina is one of deep depression, manifested in recent days by
an outpouring of anguished self-analysis over the suicide of a
well-known surgeon. And the sense of despair goes wider still: a
million or more Argentines flocked this week to the shrine of San
Cayetano, patron saint of labor, praying for his help to find work.
At least Argentina's psychoanalysts should face no problems finding
work in the coming months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECONOMICS &AMP; FINANCE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRITAIN'S LAGGING ONLINE INVESTORS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRITS-E-TRADERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Following the explosive growth of Internet
stockbroking in American in 1996-99, it was natural that American
online brokers would start expanding into Europe. Natural, too,
that their eyes should alight first on good old Britain:
English-speaking, Internet-hip and, since the privatizations of the
1980s, home to a broad-based ``shareholder culture.'' Yet Britain
is proving slower to embrace online investing than are continental
countries, supposedly so much more leery of the American way of
capitalism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EILEEN CLAUSSEN: MOTHER EARTH VS. GLOBAL-WARMING SKEPTICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EARTH-MOTHER-WONK-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ ``Dear Tony,'' begins the earnest memo from one
policy wonk to another. ``Knowing ouir shared interest in global
climate change, I have enclosed a report on the benefits of
greenhouse gas emissions trading... With best regards, Bill.'' The
casual snoop might pass over this epistle as merely the
unremarkable ramblings of an academic or bureaucrat. Inspect more
closely, though, and two surprises emerge. First, this letter,
penned recently by U.S. President Bill Clinton to British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, is about an issue both take seriously: global
warming. Second, the letter reveals just how influential Eileen
Claussen, the head of the nonprofit Pew Center on Global Climate
Change, has now become. Why does Claussen _ the scourge of
global-warming skeptics _ have the ear of the world's most powerful
man? The answer is that she knows how to dance circles around the
big boys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (925 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARTY LINE: PHONE.COM AND SOFTWARE.COM MERGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHONE.COM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The search for the next Microsoft is an
understandable obsession. But, although this week's $6.4 billion
merger between two of Silicon Valley's highest-flying software
communications firms, Phone.com and Software.com, inevitably
prompted such talk, the reality is that Phone.com already looks
rather more like the next Netscape _ Microsoft's erstwhile victim. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BAGGY FIT: U.S. RETAILERS OVER-EXPAND &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLUE-RETAILERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ America is in the ninth year of its longest-ever
peacetime expansion, but somebody has forgotten to tell its
retailers. While department stores such as Nordstrom, J.C. Penney
and Federated have been fighting decline for years, and the woes of
``category killers' such as Toys ``R'' Us are well-known, the
country's hugely successful specialty retailers _ such as Gap,
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, American Eagle Outfitters and Office Depot _
are only now hitting trouble. There are many reasons, but above
all, the fat years of the recent past have tempted store groups
into over-ambitious expansion plans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `LIGHTS, CAMERA...BOMBAY!': INDIA'S FILM INDUSTRY GROWS UP &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `BOLLYWOOD'-BOMBAY-BIZ-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUMBAI _ Subhash Ghai is all smiles these days _ and with good
reason. Mukta Arts, his movie production company, has just closed
the first-ever public offering of shares by a big firm from
Bollywood, the name for the Hindi movie industry located around
Mumbai (Bombay). As investors pore over the volatile cash flows of
his firm, Ghai is jazzed by the idea of building a Hollywood-style
studio that hires and trains Indian movie directors, writers and
technicians. Some optimists even see India as a low-cost producer
for the global movie industry. Film City, a newly expanded
2,000-acre complex on the outskirts of Hyderabad, offers 40 studio
floors and sophisticated post-production facilities; it has already
attracted a handful of movie-makers from Hollywood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SET A BUG TO CATCH A BUG: PROTECTING CALIFORNIA'S VINEYARDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASTY-BUGS-VINEYARDS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Grapevines, being clones (they are propagated as
cuttings), are extremely susceptible to disease. That is why
California's viticulturists are so worried about Pierce's disease.
It has ravaged the state's vineyards twice in the past and now, to
the horror of wine lovers everywhere, it is threatening to do so
again. It has already been recorded in 11 of California's
grape-growing counties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: California) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (375 words) &QL;
</P>
