<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-REALITY-BOS &LR;      08-14 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDELINED BY REALITY TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. _ Every time Camryn Manheim sees one of the
``reality'' shows that have engulfed television, she smolders at
the thought of what she's not seeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about my comrades, my actor friends, who should be in
those slots,'' said Manheim, a mainstay of ABC's ``The Practice.''
``Let our artists work!''
</P>
<P>
   This has been an odd, unsettling summer for the actors, writers,
and producers who ply their trade on the entertainment side of the
TV business. Prime time has been colonized by unscripted programs
that don't need the services of those who create dramas and
sitcoms. The shift from ``fiction'' to ``nonfiction'' has left some
TV veterans wondering what role is left for the medium's
storytellers, and whether TV's creative muscles will atrophy from
disuse.
</P>
<P>
   As Manheim suggested, the picture is no brighter for performers.
The ``casts'' of the summer's most talked-about shows are unknowns
who don't carry SAG or AFTRA cards: the contestants on CBS's
``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother,'' the students on Fox's ``American
High,'' the wannabe pop stars on ABC's ``Making the Band,'' and, of
course, the average Joes and Josephines on ABC's ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire'' (hosted by Regis Philbin, but given dramatic oomph
by its contestants).
</P>
<P>
   The backlash was given voice by scriptwriters Lowell Ganz and
Babaloo Mandel in an essay in a recent TV Guide headlined ``Reality
TV Bites.'' The pair asked: ``What ever happened to the concept of
being entertained by professional entertainers _ people who are
more talented than our friends and family? Bombast and
shamelessness have become a substitute for talent. People with
nothing to say are being given the opportunity to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   And they'll be given the opportunity to say a lot more. The
networks are scrambling to develop still more reality series, with
at least half a dozen already planned for mid-season or the
2001-2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Send in the clones,'' growled a skeptical Dick Wolf, executive
producer of NBC's ``Law &AMP; Order'' and ``Deadline,'' a new newspaper
drama. ``Every time something happens, then everybody wants to
imitate it.'' Yet even Wolf seems to have concluded that if you
can't beat 'em, join 'em: He will premiere a syndicated reality
show of his own this fall titled ``Arrest and Trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the reality craze could fade as quickly as it
ignited. That hope was voiced repeatedly by actors and producers in
interviews here and in sessions before TV critics. Drawing hope
from recent history, they pointed to the failure of a spate of
copycat quiz shows launched last year in an attempt to duplicate
the success of ``Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short-term fallout
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in the short term at least, the fallout from the reality
binge is considerable. The implications for the ``creative
community'' were apparent when the networks rolled out their
schedules here last month.
</P>
<P>
   The shrinkage of dramas and sitcoms was most acute at ABC, which
introduced four new programs, the fewest in recent memory. The
reason for the dropoff isn't hard to pinpoint: A hefty chunk of
ABC's fall schedule will consist of programs that could be lumped
together as nonfiction, either ``Millionaire'' (four times a week),
newsmagazines, such as ``20/20,'' or ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   But NBC entertainment chief Scott Sassa also made it clear that
the Peacock Network _ home of many of the leading sitcoms and
dramas of the past decade _ is making the development of nonfiction
programs a top priority. CBS, meanwhile, has led the reality charge
this summer, even though last year, network president Leslie
Moonves argued that for every quiz show or reality series on the
air, 100 people in Hollywood were thrown out of work.
</P>
<P>
   All the network executives speak of having ``balance'' in their
schedules, and none appears ready to jettison dramas and sitcoms
and tie their networks' fortunes to reality TV. Nonetheless, some
in the TV industry are already adapting to the new reality.
</P>
<P>
   For example, with the market for fictional TV contracting (at
least on the broadcast networks), some writers have curtailed
ambitions to launch their own shows and taken jobs as staff writers
on existing programs.
</P>
<P>
   David E. Kelley, executive producer of ``The Practice'' along
with Fox's ``Ally McBeal'' and the upcoming ``Boston Public,'' said
that ``if there's been one blessing in the dawn of reality-TV
programming, it's been there's much less pilot development, and a
lot of writers who would be off doing their own pilots, getting
their own shows, are now falling back into ranks where they're
available to go on staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as a result, I have the strongest writing staffs that I've
ever had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the creative community is on the run, its members have
themselves partly to blame, in the view of Edward Zwick, co-creator
and executive producer of ABC's ``Once and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about it a lot lately,'' he said. Zwick
maintained that the success of reality programs is partly due to
``the failure of certain writers and producers'' to create dramas
and comedies that ``describe real people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to see something that reflects themselves more
accurately,'' said Zwick. ``The appetite for the breadth of life _
that's always existed.'' Instead, he said, television has primarily
dished up rosy scenarios and pat resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   However, other creators of ``fictional'' TV scoff at claims for
the reality genre's verisimilitude. They argue that such programs
rest on contrived situations (how often, they ask, do a dozen
strangers end up on a deserted island or jammed into a house on a
studio lot?) and that reality programs are sometimes as boring as .
. . well, as real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a reality show gets into some real drama, you can get
caught up in it,'' said Chuck Lorre, executive producer of ``Dharma
&AMP; Greg'' on ABC. ``When it's a bunch of people sitting around
watching paint dry, you can feel pretty stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No future
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Thigpen, co-star of CBS's ``The District,'' suggested that
viewers may eventually be turned off. ``There's no way to get away
from the word `voyeuristic,' '' said Thigpen. ``They try to talk
around it, but that's what it is. I don't think anybody thinks that
reality television is the wave of the future. It might be the wave
of the next couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be wishful thinking, or it may be a genuine conviction,
but numerous actors and producers echo Thigpen in arguing that
reality TV is no more than a flash in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has its moment, but I don't think that anything
will ever take the place of storytelling,'' said Calista Flockhart,
star of ``Ally McBeal.'' ``Storytelling has been around since the
beginning of time. People need it. People crave it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Richard Schiff, who plays White House communications
director Toby Ziegler on NBC's ``The West Wing'': ``As soon as you
get 15 people imitating it, you get dilution. It becomes just so
much noise. I'm very unafraid of the reality movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Bochco, executive producer of CBS's ``City of Angels''
and ABC's ``NYPD Blue,'' said ``there's always going to be room for
something bizarre,'' but he has learned after 30 years in the TV
business that ``everything cycles, things come and go, but
ultimately, it's about entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Frankie Muniz, the 14-year-old star of Fox's ``Malcolm in
the Middle,'' takes the long view of reality programs. ``When
`Millionaire' first came out, it was all anybody talked about, but
now it doesn't seem so huge,'' he said. ``They're not going to be
on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Manheim certainly hopes so. Professing both puzzlement and
dismay at the ``love affair with reality TV,'' she voiced the
desire of many in her profession that television will return to its
roots. ``I'd like to see us get back to being a prime-time
entertainment medium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
