<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Aug. 15:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NERVE-CELLS (Undated) _ Researchers report that they have
found a way to transform bone marrow cells into nerve cells. The
finding, if borne out by further research, holds promise for people
with spinal cord injuries. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ARCHEO (Sardis, Turkey) _ In the ruins of Sardis, Turkey
archaeologists are striving to separate fact from legend, seeking
glimpses of what it meant in antiquity to be ``rich as Croesus.''
But they are also finding much more: monumental remains of the
passage of time and fortune for a major city under subsequent
Persian, Greek, Roman and Byzantine rule. By John Noble Wilford.
(2500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-DIG (Sardis, Turkey) _ The daily rythm of a summer's dig
by the Harvard-Cornell Sardis expedition has been repeated with
little variation since 1958. Some archaeologists come and go. But
the continuity is maintained in part because so many keep coming
back (three generations of archaeologists). It has become a
professional home, and the search for Croesus a consuming passion.
By John Noble Wilford (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CITIES-WEATHER (Undated) _ The idea that cities generate
their own heat and alter their own climates as a result is not new.
But now scientists scientists using high-tech sensors have produced
a more detailed picture of just how human activities change the
weather. By Kenneth Chang. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RADIO-TELESCOPE (Undated) _ Astronomers from 10 countries
have announced plans to build a radio telescope, the SKA, which
will have a collecting area 100 times as large as today's largest
radio telescope. The design and location of the telescope will be
decided in 2005 and construction will begin in 2010. (275 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RIBOSOME (Undated) _ Scientists at Yale have figured out the
three-dimensional structure of a ribosome, a structure in cells
that constructs proteins. By Kenneth Chang. (230 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MALAYSIA-VIRUS (Undated) _ Researchers in Malaysia have
confirmed a link between fruit bats and a recently discovered virus
that last year killed more than 100 people and compelled
authorities to slaughter roughly one million pigs. By Wayne Arnold.
(1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PHYSICS-QUESTIONS (Undated) _ A look at some of the most
important questions in physics to be pondered and answered in the
next century (or millennium). Questions that scientists will
address include the mysteries of the strong force, alpha and
gravity. By George Johnson. (2050 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Most high-level
nuclear waste storage containers are designed to last only a
century or so. Now, scientists from Los Alamos National Laboratory
and universities in Britain and Japan say that a class of ceramics
known as complex oxides may hold promise for longer-term waste
storage because they can tolerate radiation-induced defects. Other
items on the comet that fizzled and Europa, a moon of Jupiter. By
Henry Fountain. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ACUPUNCTURE-COCAINE (Undated) _ Acupuncture appears to be
effective in helping cocaine addicts escape their dependence on the
drug, according to a report published today by Yale University
researchers. By Erica Goode. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AUTO-IMMUNE (Undated) _ Autoimmune diseases, which are set
off when an out-of-whack immune system causes the body to attack
its own tissues, strike at least 14 million Americans every year.
Of those afflicted, the vast majority are women. The diseases can
attack the skin, nervous system, the joints and any of the organs.
New research now is showing just how hard it is to diagnose such
disease. And treatment, it seems, can be as difficult or more so.
By Linda Villarosa. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Oral
cancer, usually caused by the use of tobacco products and excessive
alcohol consumption, is an easily preventable disease. Before it
becomes a potentially deadly disease it usually forms precancerous
lesions that can be easily seen by any doctor. Yet, each year more
than 8,000 people die of the disease, in large part because few
professionals look for it. By Jane E. Brody. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BABY-CARE (Undated) _ A brief review of baby care books over
the past century shows that experts change their minds far too
often. The tips pediatricians offer on infant behavior must be
recognized as mere guideposts rather than exact road maps to
specific destinations. A pediatrician discusses just what happens
to an ``expert'' when a real baby joins his family. By Howard
Markel, M.D. (770 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Muscle Groups) Scientists have gained new insight into what
happens when athletes stretch, but the actual advice handed out by
coaches, trainers and even physicians is incorrect, according to an
article in The Physician and Sports Medicine. (225 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Infants being fed only breast milk, especially black infants,
should be given vitamin D supplements to prevent rickets. The
disease is especially high among darker-skinned infants because
dark skin prevents the absorption of sunlight which is needed to
make vitamin D, according to an article published in The Journal of
Pediatrics. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A new article in The Annals of Internal Medicine reports an
association between drugs that have a side effect of allowing
gastric reflux and the rates of a rare but deadly kind of gastric
cancer whose incidence has been on the rise. (370 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Using mesh to repair hernias is more effective than repairing
them with stitches when the hernia occurs during surgery, according
to a recent study published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
The researchers stipulated that stitching the wound could subject
the surrounding tissue to excessive tension while using mesh allows
new flesh and scar tissue to close the gap. (175 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ To figure out what goes on in the head of a sleepwalker, Swiss
researchers hooked a teenager to a device that measures brain
activity as he slept. The researchers reported that a part of the
brain known as the cingulate cortex was active while another part
that normally functions in tandem with it was quiet. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Do aphids milk
ants or vice versa? In any event, how can I rid my houseplants of
the aphids? By C. Claiborne Ray. (290 words)
</P>
