<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-PERLMAN-BOS &LR;      08-14 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PERLMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `SENSATION OF POWER': PERLMAN TAKES UP THE BATON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Itzhak Perlman, principal guest conductor of the Detroit
Symphony, has been an annual visitor to Tanglewood throughout his
career. Along with the Boston Symphony Orchestra and Yo-Yo Ma, he
is among the festival's most enduringly popular attractions. He has
appeared as concerto soloist, chamber-music player, and recitalist;
Saturday night he takes his first bow in his new capacity as
conductor. His program includes symphonies by Brahms and Mozart,
and he will also lead Beethoven's Romances for violin and orchestra
from the violin.
</P>
<P>
   Perlman, 54, called in recently to talk about this recent
development in his career, which began about five years ago in a
six-week institute founded by his wife, Toby, to help train
college- or conservatory-bound young musicians, the Perlman Music
Program. (``A little name recognition helps raise money,'' the
violinist confesses.) This experiment proved so successful that
Perlman began to work with professional orchestras as well; he has
led the Chicago and Houston symphonies as well as the Israel
Philharmonic, so he says he will come to Tanglewood as a
``veteran'' interpreter of the Brahms Fourth Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Several international violin virtuosos have preceded Perlman to
the podium (Georges Enesco and Yehudi Menuhin, among others), and
the ranks of conductors are full of former concertmasters and
violin section veterans (Joseph Silverstein, Charles Dutoit,
Neville Marriner). Asked what the appeal of conducting is, Perlman
responds, characteristically, with a joke: ``It's the power, the
sensation of power.'' Then his voice turns more serious as he
continues. ``The real appeal is new repertory and new musical
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also it's quite fascinating to see how feeling transfers to a
group of musicians through motion _ just how does one subtle
movement of the hand and arm, or a change of facial expression,
create an entirely different sound? This is the great mystery of
conducting. When I am playing the violin, I am totally in control
of what I am doing. When I am conducting, this is not always the
case. I feel I have embarked on an adventure of discovery. I have
been especially lucky to work with such wonderful orchestras _ with
them, words are not often necessary; they know what to do when you
show them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Perlman Music Program started out on Long Island; now it has
its own home on Shelter Island, where the orchestra rehearses in a
tent before coming into Manhattan to perform in Avery Fisher Hall
in Lincoln Center. ``In the tent, we work very hard to get a sound,
but when we get into the hall and the players hear what they are
doing in that acoustic, the look on their faces of bewilderment and
awe is amazing. The oldest players are 18, but most of them are 12
to 15. It was my wife who suggested that I try to conduct them, and
all of us enjoyed it. I had taken some conducting classes when I
was still a student at Juilliard. We just did Tchaikovsky's
`Serenade' for strings, which is not an easy piece, and the kids
did a really great job. When there were nice results with the kids,
I thought I would try to work with professional musicians too, and
see what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The powers of observation
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to attending conducting classes, Perlman has taken
careful note while working with most of the prominent conductors
active during the last 40 years. ``Yes, I've had the benefit of the
experience of great and not-so-great conductors _ both kinds of
experience were equally beneficial. I know what's a bad thing to
try to do, and what's good. An awful lot of the things I do come to
me naturally; if something doesn't work, I start asking myself
questions. I bring the same philosophy to conducting that I do to
teaching. Whenever somebody doesn't do what you want them to do, it
isn't their fault _ it's yours. What you're trying to do is to
suggest things, to try to get people to play the music the way you
hear it, whether it's right or wrong. When you get what you are
looking for, that's tremendously satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   Perlman says he never wants to patronize musicians. ``It is
important to put everything in a positive way. For every minus,
there is a plus. If something doesn't sound good, you should talk
about bringing it up to the level of something else that they have
already done well. There is no room any more for brutal
hit-them-over-the-head criticism. I have never liked that approach
in anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he wants to hear in the Brahms Fourth, Perlman
replies, ``I just want to hear the Brahms in it. This happened to
be the first symphony by Brahms I ever heard. I was about 16 at the
time _ I was a late bloomer when it came to things outside the
violin repertory. After I heard it, I couldn't sleep all night, and
during the day I just wanted to keep repeating the recording. The
first time I every hear anything wonderful that wasn't written for
the violin, I wish I were a cellist or a singer or a pianist or an
orchestra! In Brahms I want to hear romanticism, great washes of
sound, together with clarity, and I will try to do the best I can
to get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Perlman will bring his lifelong experience of the
Brahms Violin Concerto to bear on the symphony. ``The concerto is a
very symphonic work; the phrases arch the same way. The music is
different, but the conception of the music is the same. If you are
playing the concerto, it really helps to understand the textures of
the winds, the strings, and the brasses. To conduct means to play
an instrument but without actually playing it. When I play the
violin, I worry about myself; when I conduct, I worry about other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeing more clearly
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some listeners have noted new qualities in Perlman's playing
since he started conducting. Perlman has noticed them too. ``I feel
I see things more clearly now, and I have a different feeling for
rhythm. I am able to ask more of myself than before, and I am aware
of what is happening around me in a different way. The other day,
during a concert, I was saying to myself, `Here I want a little bit
more _ so go ahead and do it!' And I did it.' Afterwards, I said to
myself, `Hey, this is great. I can listen to myself in a different
way.' Dynamics are incredibly important, and so are silences. The
not playing is just as important as the playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all, what I am learning is pacing. Here and there you
can do a little bit of this and a little bit of that, but it is
important to make sure that a piece really holds together. The
phrases, the line, have to hold. This is what a conductor has to
deal with, but a solo artist should be dealing with it as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Perlman, who recently became a grandparent, says that three of
his five children are playing music. One daughter is a pianist,
with an active career and a first CD on the way; another daughter
is a singer who, her proud father says, ``is sounding good.'' The
youngest child, 16, is a ``serious flute player'' who is studying
at Juilliard. A fourth child is a lawyer, and the other divides his
time between his rock band and ``very serious painting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all in good shape,'' Perlman says proudly, ``and we
have a very interesting household.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
