r k BC-CASTRO-SHUTS-UP-ECONO     08-14 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTRO-SHUTS-UP-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILIBUSTIN' FIDEL FINALLY RUNS OUT OF AIR  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 575-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Millions of Americans will this week have found themselves in
the unusual position of agreeing with Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Both George W. Bush and Al Gore are ``boring,'' said the Cuban
dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Sheer hypocrisy, Bush and Gore might reply. After all, for four
decades, Castro has notoriously bored his long-suffering people
with speeches lasting hour after hour: in the view of the old
guerrilla, it has always seemed, fatigues are not just to be worn
but also to be inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps Castro was merely trying to extract advantage from a
recent and little-noticed change of heart. For Cuba's president has
at last realized that, when it comes to words, less can be more.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Castro broke the news of this revolutionary
change _ but in characteristic fashion. ``I have reached the
conclusion, a bit late perhaps, that speeches should be short,'' he
told Granma, the Cuban Communist Party daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Well, better late than never, even if this startling admission
came at the end of an interview that filled four pages of fine
print. More remarkable, however, is that Castro has been as good as
his new, short, word: none of his recent speeches has lasted longer
than 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And on July 26, a big anniversary in Cuba's revolutionary
calendar and always good for several hours of uninterrupted
oratory, the old windbag's harangue lasted less than half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Cubans will no doubt be delighted. Anyone who has stood
through a Castro speech in Cuba's tropical sun will know that even
mad dogs and Englishmen risk keeling over from heatstroke as the
latest sugar harvest is dissected in mind-numbing statistical
detail.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden urge for brevity will doubtless also be celebrated by
the 73-year-old's enemies, but as a sign of failing vigor. They may
be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's Communist government is using ``new and efficient media
methods'' to get its message across. Does this mean that Castro is
about to embrace that dreaded imperialist tool, the soundbite?
</P>
<P>
   Doubters will explain that Latins hate silence, and that
long-winded speeches are therefore intrinsic to Latin American
culture.
</P>
<P>
   In support, they may cite the example of Hugo Chavez,
Venezuela's paratrooper-turned-president, who, intoxicated by the
exuberance of his own verbosity, is doing his best to imitate the
lengthy speeches that Castro has just vowed to eschew. Last week he
entertained the press to a three-hour news conference.
</P>
<P>
   But is prolixity really Latin American? This year's Cervantes
prize, the highest literary award in the Spanish-speaking world,
went to Augusto Monterroso, a Guatemalan novelist celebrated partly
for a short story about the seemingly never-ending rule of Mexico's
Institutional Revolutionary Party. It consisted of just one
sentence. (``When he woke up, the dinosaur was still there.'')
</P>
<P>
   Now, happily, Mexico's dinosaur is about to depart, after an
election campaign that was notable for its cacophony of soundbites.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being an inevitable part of political life in Latin
America, the long-winded speech is the mark of the caudillo.
Monologue is inherently undemocratic: it demands the kind of
buttock-aching passivity to be found only among the cowed or the
deferential _ appropriate perhaps to a medieval court, but not to a
modern polity.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains now is for Castro to allow other, dissenting,
voices to fill some of the silences he proposes to leave. For
Cubans, that would be an even more welcome revolution. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
