<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1120 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GUTSY-GORE-LIEBERMAN-     08-14 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUTSY-GORE-LIEBERMAN-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOE LIEBERMAN'S SHOCK VALUE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 100-word trim; 1,075 uncut)  (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: 100-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 650; TOTAL UNCUT IS
1,075)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Before the current stage of the presidential
campaign began, conventional wisdom (excuse the term) held that
George W. Bush's choice of running mate would define his candidacy
but the Republican shindig would not.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, it was thought that Al Gore's running mate would
hardly matter (because the options were all so dismal) but his
speech to the Democratic National Convention would be decisive.
</P>
<P>
   So far, every part of this wisdom has turned out to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's choice of running mate said little more than that he
likes to surround himself with well-qualified politicians with
conservative voting records.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Convention, on the other hand, was an eye-opener,
showing what the ``new Republican Party'' is willing to do to
attract independents.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gore's choice of Senator Joe Lieberman of Connecticut may
go as far as any vice-presidential pick can go towards changing
perceptions about a candidate. It gives a spark of excitement to a
candidacy that has so far plodded from one unconvincing moment to
another.
</P>
<P>
   It is an axiom of American politics that a huge problem for any
incumbent vice president is to distinguish himself from the
president without repudiating the record on which he is running.
</P>
<P>
   In principle, Gore's task should be easier than most. He should
be able to distance himself from the personal lapses while
endorsing the policy achievements. In practice it has been harder,
since, during the Lewinsky scandal, he felt obliged to be loyal to
his boss.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was the first Democrat to attack Clinton during the
Lewinsky affair, saying on the Senate floor that the president's
behavior was not just inappropriate but immoral.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking innocence by association will not help Gore overcome
``Clinton fatigue'' at a stroke. Nor will it remove the question of
presidential morality from the debate (arguably, it puts the matter
back near the top of the agenda for a while).
</P>
<P>
   But it will blunt the force of criticism because Republicans can
no longer say _ as Dick Cheney did in Philadelphia _ that ``it is
not possible to look at (Gore) without thinking about (Clinton).''
It now is.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the choice of Lieberman may encourage voters
to reassess Gore himself. This is not just because, as both men
have repeatedly said, Lieberman is the first Jew on the
presidential ticket of a big party. Rather, it is because some of
the qualities that make him unusual are shared by Gore too.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman were two of only ten Democrats in the Senate
to vote for the Gulf war. Lieberman's religious side _ he observes
Orthodox Jewish practices, and quoted the Book of Chronicles when
his nomination was announced _ chimes with Gore's less remarked
upon, but still marked, Baptist faith.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman hands out ``silver sewer'' awards to ``culturally
polluting'' movies, music or videos. One of the first people who
tried to shame the entertainment industry into restraint was Gore's
wife, Tipper, in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a small personal link. Orthodox Jews may not drive
on the Sabbath. When there was a Senate vote on that day, Lieberman
used to stay at an apartment near the Capitol owned by the Gores,
and the Shabbosgoy (the Gentile who would do other banned things
like turning on the lights) was none other than Al.
</P>
<P>
   If Lieberman had been merely a pillar of rectitude with no
connection with Gore, his selection would have been tokenism. As it
is, his reputation may help to improve Gore's own.
</P>
<P>
   And, as an immediate consequence, it should help him both with
socially conservative voters _ notably suburban women and
blue-collar men, among whom Gore is getting hammered _ and with the
large number of people who disapprove of Clinton personally but
like his policies.
</P>
<P>
   In picking Lieberman, Gore did something unusual: he took a
risk. He did so with Lieberman's religion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (100-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 650) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Semitism in America is less potent than it used to be, but
it has not vanished. One Jewish candidate was defeated by a rival
who went around asking, ``How can North Carolina have a
representative in Washington who won't eat North Carolina
barbecue?'' (the state is famous for barbecued pork). That was in a
Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how widespread this attitude is. But people are
more prejudiced than they are willing to tell others, and in one
recent poll 6 percent of the population still said they would not
vote for a Jewish candidate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,075) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman is also a risk on particular issues. He has spoken
in favor of the partial privatization of Social Security _ which
Gore excoriates Bush for proposing. He has favored school vouchers
_ for which Gore excoriated Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has now backed off both ideas, and even though in
general his policies are similar to Gore's, the Democratic ticket
still looks less than united on these two controversial policies.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, Lieberman is a risk to party unity. Vouchers
are anathema to the teachers' unions (a huge proportion of
delegates at next week's Democratic Convention are teachers). His
campaign against pornography is anathema to Hollywood. His support
of free trade is unpopular with unions.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he offends three large Democratic interest
groups at a time when Gore has not yet nailed down the support of
the whole party.
</P>
<P>
   With Ralph Nader ready to snap up all Democrats who put ideology
above party, the risk is not trivial.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats have lauded the nomination. But that is partly
because Lieberman has backtracked on Social Security and education,
two of the issues that endeared him to independent voters in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore took a gamble and, in bringing it off, has lessened
his reputation as a shameless panderer.
</P>
<P>
   This has been the most important decision of his campaign so far
and, on balance, it is a good one. But it is good, mainly, because
of its shock value.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman will cause voters to look at Gore anew. The question
is what Gore does then. He has to appeal to the center, solidify
the base and clarify what his candidacy is about.
</P>
<P>
   It is no easy task, and one that Gore must confront alone. To
that extent, the last part of the conventional wisdom _ that the
Democratic gathering next week is vital for Gore _ still seems
right. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
