r k BC-BLUE-RETAILERS-ECONOM     08-14 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-RETAILERS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAGGY FIT: U.S. RETAILERS OVER-EXPAND  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 675-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ America is in the ninth year of its longest-ever
peacetime expansion, but somebody has forgotten to tell its
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   While department stores such as Nordstrom, J.C. Penney and
Federated have been fighting decline for years, and the woes of
``category killers'' such as Toys ``R'' Us are well-known, the
country's hugely successful specialty retailers are only now
hitting trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, there have been two profit warnings from Gap, a
clothing retailer, and warnings or falling sales numbers from,
among others, Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, American Eagle Outfitters,
Pacific Sunwear and Office Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers' average ``same-store'' sales growth _ for units open
a year or more _ has been falling since late last year; according
to Buckingham Research Group, growth at the end of July averaged
3.6 percent, little more than half the level in December.
</P>
<P>
   The retailers blame a variety of things, from the weather to a
slowing economy. A relatively rainy summer may, admittedly, be
holding back clothing sales. And consumer spending appears to have
dropped off from the exceptional levels of the first quarter of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But June's retail sales figures, which showed a healthy
annualized increase of 8.7 percent, suggest that American shoppers
are still hitting the malls in force.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem, in truth, is not demand but supply. The fat
years of the recent past have tempted store groups into
over-ambitious expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Julian of Credit Suisse First Boston points out that
America now has ten times more square footage of retail space per
head than does Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers are ``ignoring any notion of overcapacity,'' he says.
Clothing chains such as Gap are particularly guilty, because their
small stores are quick to build and tempt with the fattest returns.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Slater of Lazard Freres thinks that the supply of specialty
clothing space is already outstripping consumer demand, and that
the gap will grow. He calculates that growth in square footage at
American clothing chains will accelerate to 9-10 percent for this
year and next.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, Gap and American Eagle all plan to increase
floor space by two to three times that rate this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, many of these expansion plans might seem sensible
_ after all, even the seemingly omnipresent Gap has just 6 percent
of the country's clothing market. Combined, however, they are
threatening to saturate Main Street. And, as Slater points out, too
much supply will force discounting to clear excess stock.
</P>
<P>
   In a business such as retailing, with high fixed costs,
discounting spells death for profit margins. In addition, the
retailers face increasing competition, both foreign and domestic.
</P>
<P>
   While Gap has for years successfully expanded abroad, foreign
chains such as Sweden's Hennes &AMP; Mauritz and Spain's Zara have now
established a foothold in New York and plan a nationwide expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, domestic discounters, such as Costco, Kmart and above
all Wal-Mart, are continuing to take market share. Their same-store
sales growth has remained stable at around 6 percent in the past
six months, while growth at specialty clothes stores fell to just
over 1 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the industry ramped up capacity too quickly, in
the early 1990s, the result was a wave of bankruptcies that led to
a decline in overall store space in 1995 and 1996, before growth
resumed.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious solution, therefore, would seem to be for the
companies to rein in their expansion plans before they get into a
similar mess. But it may take longer to remove supply from the
market this time: most of the current growth is being driven by big
branded retailers, armed with balance sheets that are stronger
today than they were a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will any company want to be the first to blink. Tellingly,
Gap remains committed to its growth plans despite a sharp drop in
its share price since its latest warning.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, retailers are hoping that consumers will shop them
out of trouble. And once again, they are likely to be
disappointed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
