<HEADER>
A1136 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-SHOES-MAGNETS-MED &LR;      08-14 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOES-MAGNETS-MED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORSHEIM IS SUED FOR SHOE-MAGNET CLAIMS  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY ANN QUIGLEY  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Florsheim says its magnet-laden shoes can ease pain and make
your legs and back less tired. But a California consumer group is
not just taking issue with these claims; it is suing the company
for touting them as remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Justice Center, a nonprofit consumer protection
group, filed the suit last week in Orange County and asks that
Florsheim stop advertising the MagneForce shoes as a health aid and
refund the purchase price (about $122 plus tax) to people who
bought the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Karen McKenzie, a spokeswoman for Florsheim Group, Inc., in
Chicago said the company could not comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Any health claims for magnetic shoes is ``a commercial fairy
tale,'' says Dr. Stephen Barrett, a retired psychiatrist in
Allentown, Pa., and operator of Quackwatch, Inc., a nonprofit
watchdog organization that alerts the public to health-related
frauds, myths and fads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The claims that magnets affect the body's magnetic fields is
utter nonsense,'' he says. ``The magnets in shoes _ similar to
refrigerator magnets _ are too weak to produce any measurable
effect within the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett was a consultant to the Consumer Justice Center's legal
action.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate is not clear-cut, and some mainstream doctors are
finding that magnets are not as easily dismissed as pain relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the suit: MagneForce shoes ``generate a
deep-penetrating magnetic field which increases circulation;
reduces foot, leg and back fatigue; provides natural pain relief
and improved energy level,'' the company says on its Web site, a
claim also cited in the suit. Other health claims cited in the
lawsuit _ for example, one regarding benefits to circulation _ have
been removed from Florsheim's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   An ancient folk remedy, magnets have become a $5-billion-a-year
worldwide industry, according to Dr. Edward Collacott, department
head for physical medicine and rehabilitation with the Northern
Arizona Veterans Affairs health-care system.
</P>
<P>
   Popular in Asia, touted by sports figures and sewn into women's
corsets and offered in early Sears Roebuck catalogs, magnetic
devices today come in all shapes and sizes _ from $25 bracelets to
mattress pads costing $400.
</P>
<P>
   Florsheim introduced magnets into the insoles of Florsheim
MagneForce golf shoes in 1999 and golfers who wore them said the
shoes helped. The shoemaker worked with Magnetherapy Inc., the
makers of magnetic therapy to produce its MagneForce line.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett says that Magnetherapy ``has been warned by the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration to stop claiming that its products
would relieve arthritis, tennis elbow, low-back-pain sciatica,
migraine headache, muscle soreness, spurs, bunions arthritic
fingers and toes or could reduce pain and inflammation.'' In 1998,
Magnetherapy paid a $30,000 penalty and agreed to stop making
health claims for its magnetic products, according to the Texas
attorney general, where the penalty was paid.
</P>
<P>
   Florsheim says the success of the golf shoes spurred the company
into introducing magnets into dress and casual shoes in June of
this year. According to the company's Web site earlier last week,
the magnets generate a field that ``penetrates the foot to a depth
of two inches. Studies indicate that magnetic fields increase blood
circulation, bring natural pain relief and increase range of
motion, leading to an increased level of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett dismisses any endorsement by golfers. ``Lots of athletes
swear that doing one thing or another has improved their health or
their performance. I am not aware of any published scientific study
demonstrating that golfers who wore magnetic shoes improved their
game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the jury could still be out on magnets, according to Dr.
Michael Weintraub, chief of neurology at Phelps Memorial Medical
Center in Sleepy Hollow, N.Y. He began a study of magnets in 1995,
using a ``skeptical approach.'' People who were in pain who had
back surgery because of ``failed back syndrome,'' as well as those
with ``peripheral neuropathy and carpal tunnel syndrome,'' were
tested.
</P>
<P>
   Peripheral neuropathy is a common disorder that comes from
damage to certain nerves, according to the National Institutes of
Health. It may be caused by diseases of the nerves or as the result
of illnesses such as diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Weintraub used people whose problems stemmed from diabetes. ``I
was surprised. These people got significant relief _ a 75 percent
response rate in the diabetic group and a 50 percent response rate
in the nondiabetic group.''
</P>
<P>
   The results of the earlier studies have prompted a national
study of the effects of magnets for diabetics, for those with back
pain and for carpal tunnel syndrome, Weintraub says.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
