r k BC-NASTY-BUGS-VINEYARDS-     08-14 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASTY-BUGS-VINEYARDS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SET A BUG TO CATCH A BUG: PROTECTING CALIFORNIA'S VINEYARDS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: California)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 375-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Grapevines, being clones (they are propagated as
cuttings), are extremely susceptible to disease. Once a bacterium
has worked out how to get past a clone's defenses, it can run riot.
</P>
<P>
   The subtle differences of response to infection that are found
in genetically diverse host organisms, and which serve to slow
pathogens down, are absent in cloned crops.
</P>
<P>
   That is why California's viticulturists are so worried about
Pierce's disease. It has ravaged the state's vineyards twice in the
past _ once in the 1880s, and once in the 1930s and 1940s. Now, to
the horror of wine lovers everywhere, it is threatening to do so
again.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's disease is caused by Xylella fastidiosa, a bacterium
that infects the tissue which carries water from a plant's roots to
its leaves, and whose genome was unravelled by researchers in
Brazil earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the insect mainly responsible for spreading
Xylella in California was a leafhopper called the blue-green
sharpshooter. This bug usually feeds at the edges of vineyards, and
then only on tender new shoots. That makes it easy for farmers to
prune away the infected portions of a vine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, however, a new Xylella vector _ the glassy-winged
sharpshooter _ appeared in California. This bug confines itself
neither to the edges of vineyards, nor to the tenderest shoots. It
will feed, vinewise, on anything, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   It thus spreads Xylella very fast. And it has already been
recorded in 11 of California's grape-growing counties. The state's
officials are understandably paranoid about this.
</P>
<P>
   So, like the lady who swallowed a spider to catch the fly, they
have been casting around for something that likes to eat
glassy-winged sharpshooters, preferably in large quantities.
</P>
<P>
   They have come up with a small Mexican wasp called Gonatocerus
triguttatus. The females of this wasp hunt out sharpshooter egg
masses and lay their own eggs there. When the wasp larvae hatch,
they eat the sharpshooter's eggs.
</P>
<P>
   According to Larry Bezark, the entomologist at California's
Department of Food and Agriculture who is in charge of the program,
experimental releases of Gonatocerus will begin this month. If all
goes well, a mass release of the critters will take place next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Those who enjoy a glass of chardonnay, merlot or cabernet
sauvignon should keep their fingers crossed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
