<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
! 1/2 ``Bless the Child'' Yet another ``Exorcist'' and ``Omen''
knockoff, more hollow than scary. Good guys Kim Basinger and Jimmy
Smits battle devil's disciple Rufus Sewell for custody of a
6-year-old with supernatural powers. As the kid, newcomer Holliston
Coleman is the best thing in the film, but she can't lift the curse
of a pedestrian screenplay. (R) 
 
!! 1/2 ``Cecil B. DeMented'' John Waters has fun with both sides of
the movie spectrum, puncturing megabore mainstream and
sanctimonious indie types. But the film runs out of steam. It
admires the energies of guerrilla filmmaking, but can't recapture
them, settling for irony instead. Not that Melanie Griffith ever
lets down. She's a source of nonstop fun as an aging movie queen
held hostage by film renegades in a replay of the Patty Hearst
kidnapping. (R) 
 
!!! ``The Little Thief'' French director Erick Zonca follows up his
extraordinary ``Dreamlife of Angels'' with another portrayal of a
teen falling through the cracks of the new Europe. A young man
fired from a baker's job takes up with low types aspiring to
gangster lives in Marseilles, only to find himself at odds with the
nonstop violence. (Unrated) 
 
!!! ``The Opportunists'' Gritty, involving slice of life from a
crumbling ethnic enclave in Queens. It's centered by the
extraordinary rightness of Christopher Walken's performance as an
ex-con trying to stay clean. He wants to make a life with his
tavern-owning girlfriend (nicely nailed by Cyndi Lauper), but a
pushy Irish visitor attempts to pressure him into another heist.
(R) 
 
!! ``The Replacements'' This film about football temps getting a
belated shot at glory during a pro players' strike never met a
cliche it didn't like. Yet it's more entertaining than it deserves
to be, thanks to engaging performances, including Keanu Reeves's
uncharacteristically relaxed one as the salvage boat operator (get
the symbolism?) quarterbacking them. (PG-13) 
 
!!!! ``The Tao of Steve'' Jenniphr Goodman has made a smart,
sparkling, convention-defying comedy about a fat slacker in Santa
Fe who somehow still attracts women even though his star has faded
since his high school babe-magnet days. Donal Logue delivers one of
the year's most improbably delightful performances as Dex,
reminding us that brains and humor can be sexier than abs. Greer
Goodman is a find, too, as a savvy woman who likes him, but is too
smart to fall for his line. (R)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Wonderland'' Michael Winterbottom's London soap opera, shot
in raw verite style, plays out engagingly and compellingly. Credit
the bright, bristly ensemble that brings vast reserves of gusto and
resilience to its screenful of characters. Though they slosh around
in loneliness and misery, they never quit _ and the women (led by
Gina McKee's gawky placer of ads in the personals columns) never
give up on one another. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
