<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GENTLEMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYNIHAN: PROFESSOR BECOMES POLITICIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GENTLEMAN FROM NEW YORK 
Daniel Patrick Moynihan: A Biography 
By Godfrey Hodgson. 
Houghton Mifflin. 464 pp. Illustrated. $35. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has had a dazzling assortment of careers: naval officer,
bartender, professor, speechwriter, sub-Cabinet official, city
council candidate, White House adviser, ambassador, and, since
1977, an adornment to the US Senate. In January of 1993, the
capital guessed about the new chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee. In the apt words of David Rogers in The Wall Street
Journal, ``Washington has always wondered whether Pat Moynihan was
the professor playing the politician or the politician playing the
professor. This year, Washington finds out.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington did and so did New York, as the chairman adroitly
raided the federal pork barrel on behalf of the Empire State's
schools, hospitals, and transit systems. The politician persevered
without losing his academic edge; the professor's briefcase bulged
with bacon. ``Pat can count,'' Bob Dole said. ``He always knew
where the votes were.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Almanac of American Politics,'' Michael Barone declares
that Moynihan is ``the nation's best thinker among politicians
since Lincoln and its best politician among thinkers since
Jefferson.'' Godfrey Hodgson, a keen British observer of American
politics, tests this thesis in ``The Gentleman From New York'' and
mostly agrees with it.
</P>
<P>
   This is a friendly biography, but amply quotes Moynihan's
critics. Nearly everyone forgets his harshest foes from 1970 and
even an unfriendly biographer would find it hard to prove the most
frequent charge, that Moynihan counseled ``benign neglect'' of
blacks in America in a memo to President Nixon. The memo emphasized
that ``the issue of race could benefit from a period of `benign
neglect.' The subject has been too much taken over to hysterics,
paranoids and boodlers on all sides. We may need a period in which
Negro progress continues and racial rhetoric fades.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Benign neglect,'' an obscure phrase from 19th-century British
politics, was instantly seized by the aforesaid ``hysterics,
paranoids and boodlers'' who battered Moynihan with charges of
racism. He was for affirmative action before most people were, but
was accused of bigotry in 1965, when he was assistant secretary of
labor in Lyndon Johnson's administration. ``The Negro Family: The
Case For National Action'' brought accusations that because it
focused on children born out of wedlock, its author was therefore a
bigot. Many politicians claim they are misunderstood. Pat Moynihan
was deliberately misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   On his own, as a senator, he has faced few such problems. To
begin with, he had as a campaign manager his wife, the former
Elizabeth Brennan. They met in Albany while both worked for
Governor Averell Harriman and she has steered her husband to
comfortable majorities four times. Many Moynihan speeches are too
abstract for his colleagues, his range of interests astonishes
them, and his gift for prophecy bedazzles them. Because he had
predicted the implosion of the Soviet Union, even an inveterate
red-baiter, Jesse Helms, signed off on a plan to reduce government
secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan's patient pursuit of his own interest in architecture
has served the nation and the nation's ``Main Street,''
Pennsylvania Avenue. It took perseverance through seven
presidencies, but that boulevard is finally grand. Above all,
Hodgson argues, he has stood for standards, an often lonely
position. ``In 1992, in an academic lecture at Yale, he coined one
of the phases that will become part of his intellectual legacy,''
the author writes. ``Defining deviancy down'' was a call to
standards which, like many Moynihan observations, also transcended
ideology. Hodgson quotes John Kenneth Galbraith, who told him,
``You will never understand Pat in terms of commitment to Left or
Right. He has a mind wholly free from ideological commitments. His
long-term commitment is to cities, the poor, and especially to poor
children.''
</P>
<P>
   But how could he work for Presidents Kennedy, Johnson, Nixon,
and Ford? How could he shed neoconservatives in the 1970s and
reemerge as a liberal in the 1980s and 1990s? Hodgson, now at
Oxford University, has devoted this sprightly, readable biography
to answering such questions. He often quotes his countrymen, in
this instance, John Maynard Keynes. ``When circumstances change,''
Keynes said. ``I change my opinion. What do you do?''
</P>
<P>
   On another matter, Hodgson cites an American thinker and
politician ``to address a topic on which little has been written
but much said. Pat Moynihan has always liked a drink. His father
was a drinking man, after all, and his mother ran a bar.'' Hodgson
testifies that in many meals with his subject since 1962, ``I have
never seen him lose his temper or lose control under the influence
of alcohol.'' In dealing with gossip, he concludes, ``my own
judgment inclines to that attributed to Abraham Lincoln. When they
told him (Ulysses S.) Grant drank too much whiskey, he is reputed
to have said, `Go out and find out what kind of whiskey he drinks,
and give a barrel of to some of my other generals.!' ''
</P>
<P>
   America could use 99 more barrels of this stuff and 99
senatorial biographies, if only their subjects merited such a
well-written ode to triumph and survival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
