<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-49ERS-OWENS-HNS &LR;      08-14 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-OWENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NINER'S MAIN DISTRACTION IS FAR FROM THE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEVIN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Terrell Owens, a five-year receiver for the
San Francisco 49ers, is exhausted. Not physically, for his body is
in the best of shape. Rather, Owens is dealing with the emotional
trauma of coping with the Alzheimer's disease that has stricken a
close and dear relative.
</P>
<P>
   Owens has broken down with coaches and even reporters while
talking about the insidious march of the degenerative disease into
the mind of his grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Black's wisdom and reasoning are being crowded out by
befuddlement and confusion. To see a woman so strong and
disciplined subjected to Alzheimer's damage tortures Owens.
</P>
<P>
   With no father figure to speak of, Owens was raised by his
grandmother and mother, Marilyn Owens. The relationship between
Terrell and his grandmother was never easy.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Black, 66, is from a different world. She grew up in
Alexander City, Ala. And to her, the trappings of modern culture _
television, airplanes, sporting events _ are almost evil.
</P>
<P>
   Black fiercely shielded her grandson in his adolescence. Owens
wasn't allowed to play sports, or even run around with neighborhood
children. He couldn't ride his bike in the street.
</P>
<P>
   Owens passed his time by himself, peddling up and down the
driveway, or by tossing a football to himself. Owens didn't play
sports until his teens when his mother signed him up for football
behind Alice Black's back.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, of course, resented his grandmother for disallowing
sports, television or radio. But nevertheless, a bond as strong as
rope was woven between the two.
</P>
<P>
   She is his rock. When things are tough, Owens will call her and
she will pray to him over the phone. Now 26 years old, and
tremendously successful, Owens feels no resentment about how he was
brought up. What he does feel is compassion for what his
grandmother must now endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just hurts me because she was walking in and out of the
house about a month ago,'' Owens said while sitting in the shade
after a recent training camp practice. ``I talk to my mom every day
and it seems like she gets worse every 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Owens is now playing the mother to her mom. Black moved
in with her daughter in the house Terrell had built in Alexander
City after signing his first pro contract.
</P>
<P>
   Owens thinks of his grandmother's declining health even during
training camp practices. But there are times when the demands of
his career occupy him.
</P>
<P>
   Owens is attempting to patch a somewhat damaged image. His
receiving numbers fell off after signing a 7-year, $35 million
contract before the 1999 season. A shoulder injury and ankle sprain
dogged him most of last season, and Owens never established a
chemistry with new quarterback Jeff Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' persistent losing made Owens surly and quieter than
usual. Owens' strained relations with the media grew worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been media-friendly, but those are the types of
things I've tried to work on, to have a better attitude,'' Owens
said.
</P>
<P>
   A fierce loner and distrustful, Owens is trying to open up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a moody person,'' he admitted. ``Those (media relations)
are things I thought about during the offseason. I pray on things
like this, because I try not to rub people the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   A larger challenge looming in front of Owens is his place on the
team. The offense is trying to make the slow transition from the
aging Jerry Rice to Owens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the confidence to say I'm as good as he is right now,''
Owens said. ``Sometimes, when I'm out there, sometimes I feel I can
just take over the ball game. But I'm not going to create a
distraction, and tell them (the coaches) to throw me the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's that going to hurt in the long run? It will probably
hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens usually stays after practice to take extra throws from
Garcia. The added work has yet to manifest itself on the field.
Against San Diego, Garcia failed to throw a pass to a wide
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   And Garcia couldn't find Owens during a recent two-minute drill
in practice designed to highlight the 6-foot-3, 220-pound target.
</P>
<P>
   But Owens' mind floods with other concerns when he leaves the
field. One of his only solaces is his 9-month-old son, Terique, who
lives with his mother in Hayward, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dear to me,'' said Owens, who visits often and had
Terique with him for a time in the offseason during a visit to
Alexander City. ``He's a great joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens is standing on the threshold of life's fragile cycle,
caught between his fading grandmother and infant son. Owens is now
the caretaker in his family, not only for Terique but his
grandmother too.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, Owens appears determined to give his son
something he never had.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom and my grandmother were pretty much my mom and dad,''
Owens said. ``I'm going to give him me, as a father.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 1422EDT &QL; 
