<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-NYT &LR;      08-14 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL VOTES TO SET UP WAR CRIMES TRIBUNAL FOR SIERRA
LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. Security Council agreed Monday to set
up a war crimes tribunal for Sierra Leone, where brutal rebel
armies have engaged in torture, amputated limbs and destroyed
villages to intimidate civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, passed by a 15-0 vote, stopped short, however, of
actually establishing the court or deciding its composition and
functions. There are some lingering questions over the how
authority should be shared between Sierra Leone's judicial system
and neutral international legal experts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the council asked Secretary General Kofi Annan to
address these and other questions and to produce a detailed
blueprint for the court within 30 days. The council had been ready
to vote on the court Friday, when Russia asked at the last minute
for more time to study the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador, said in an interview
that the secretary general will be bound by a council consensus
that the court has to have international input, even if council
members were not all in agreement on details.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not have the option of saying, `Put it all under
Sierra Leone,''' Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal will be the third to be created over the last
decade of increased civil conflict, following the establishment of
war crimes courts for the Balkans and Rwanda. Plans for a fourth
court, to try officials of the Khmer Rouge, who were responsible
for the deaths of more than a million Cambodians in the 1970s, are
in the final stages of negotiation with the Cambodian government.
</P>
<P>
   The newest tribunal is to try ``crimes against humanity, war
crimes and other serious violations of international humanitarian
law, as well as crimes under relevant Sierra Leone law committed
within the territory of Sierra Leone.'' It will draw on precedents,
but it will at the same time be tailored to Sierra Leone's
particular situation, diplomats said Monday. The country has a
democratically elected government, which has asked for
international help with the court and is expected to cooperate
fully.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent prisoner to face the Sierra Leone tribunal is
expected to be Foday Sankoh, leader of the rebel Revolutionary
United Front, who jettisoned a 1999 agreement with the government
of President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah and resumed attacks on the Sierra
Leone army. In May, his forces also captured 500 U.N. peacekeepers.
They were all subsequently released, but not without embarrassment
to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh is now in Sierra Leone's custody. Some of the concerns
about the composition and functioning of the court rest on the fear
that Sankoh will try again, as he has in the past, to bargain for
amnesty if the country's weakened judicial system has control of
the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   The council called Monday for a tribunal based on
``impartiality, independence and credibility,'' and suggested the
possibility that appeals hearings, at least, may have to be held
outside Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that several important steps have now been taken
by the council on Sierra Leone. Last month, the council voted to
ban diamond sales from the country until a certification system is
put into place by the government. Diamonds have been fueling
Sankoh's war and enriching the president of neighboring Liberia,
Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the council voted to strengthen the role of the
peacekeeping force, giving it authority to ``take down the RUF,''
Sankoh's rebel army, Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   The next move on Sierra Leone will be the expansion of the
peacekeeping force, now limited to 13,000 troops. Council members
expect Annan and the peacekeeping department to recommend a number
between 19,000 and 25,000. The Clinton administration, usually
skittish about approving large peacekeeping operations because of
opposition in Congress, is backing the highest number this time.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that in recent days both George W. Bush and his
leading foreign policy adviser, Condoleeza Rice, have given public
support to a strong bipartisan policy on Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Some differences over the jurisdiction of the tribunal arose
between the United States and Britain, which had taken the lead in
responding to the crisis in Sierra Leone. Holbrooke said that the
disputes were ``technical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted an international umbrella over the court, but we
didn't want to create a third tribunal because they are very
expensive and very slow and we wanted to move fast,'' he said.
``There was initially some thought among some lawyers in Washington
and New York and London that this ought to all be under Sierra
Leone law.'' In the end, the council fell somewhere between.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
