<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1174 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-CONVENTIONS-MCCA     08-14 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-CONVENTIONS-MCCARTHY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CONVENTIONS MATTERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Monday, Aug. 14, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By EUGENE J. MCCARTHY    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is a long distance from the political
conventions that nominated Al Smith and Franklin D. Roosevelt to
the weeklong infomercials that are called conventions today. Once
conventions were battlefields where real fights were waged over
platforms, personalities and power. Vice presidential choices were
not made beforehand; the selection of the presidential nominee was
seldom sure until the convention had run its course. Conventions
had lives and logic all their own. And they mattered.
</P>
<P>
   This was true for both parties, but the conventions where I
observed it were Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia in 1948, Hubert Humphrey, then mayor of
Minneapolis, gave a speech that made history. ``The time has
arrived,'' he said, ``for the Democratic Party to get out of the
shadow of states' rights and walk forthrightly into the bright
sunshine of human rights.'' President Harry S. Truman accepted the
civil rights platform, causing the Dixiecrats to bolt the
convention, splitting the party _ or so it seemed. In fact, Truman
united the party by giving it a cause.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, in Chicago, delegates drafted Gov. Adlai Stevenson of
Illinois at Truman's urging _ the last presidential draft. Four
years later, when Stevenson was nominated again, he threw the
choice for vice president open to the convention, which eventually
nominated Estes Kefauver of Tennessee. I supported Humphrey, by
then a senator, and managed his campaign on the convention floor.
John F. Kennedy was also a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to 1968. The Democratic Convention was controlled
by President Lyndon Johnson and Mayor Richard Daley of Chicago. The
process was corrupted and the people betrayed. Even the effort to
pass an antiwar platform was stifled.
</P>
<P>
   The last real Democratic convention was in 1960. Although
Kennedy arrived in Los Angeles in very good shape, his nomination
was not a sure thing. The reason was Stevenson, who still commanded
considerable support even though he had done little to promote his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of the convention, I attended a pro-Stevenson
luncheon at which Eleanor Roosevelt spoke, and I spoke at a
late-night rally.
</P>
<P>
   The next day the Minnesota delegation's leaders caucused on the
question of whom to support. Humphrey was undecided. Gov. Orville
Freeman, who would be making Kennedy's nominating speech, argued
for supporting him on the first ballot. I announced my support for
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   The next evening I placed Stevenson's name in nomination on the
floor. Only 79 of the 1,512 delegates voted for him. But the
demonstrations after my speech and the seconding speech were far
more intense and enthusiastic than those for the other nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were strong for Adlai cheered, of course. Others
uttered purging cries of approval to make their change of loyalty
easier. And the rest cheered simply as a testimonial to the career
and example of Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   That 1960 convention marked the end of the active political
career of Adlai Stevenson, the purest politician of our times. He
was indifferent to what history might say about him and, in 1956,
willing to be a sacrificial candidate for the common effort. He
became a national figure not because of the press, or even
primaries, but because of conventions.
</P>
<P>
   (Eugene J. McCarthy was a senator from Minnesota from 1959 to
1971. Keith Burris, the editorial page editor of The Journal
Inquirer of Manchester, Conn., assisted with this article.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
