 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release FRI., AUG. 18, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Rock returns for a fifth season of his self-titled HBO
show tonight at 12:00 a.m., with two Emmy nominations pending _ for
best variety, music or comedy series, and best writing. The show
won its first statuette last year, for writing, and as with HBO's
``Dennis Miller,'' the opening monologues are the best part of the
show. Rock's mind is nimble, and his take on life is anything but
predictable. But unlike a typical episode of Miller's show, the fun
continues after the initial rant, with pre-taped comedy bits, guest
interviews and music.
</P>
<P>
   At deadline, Rock's guests were still unannounced, but we hope
the comedy bits will include his recent ``Free Bobby Brown'' vigil
outside a Florida jail. That was a bit, Chris, wasn't it?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: Pssst! We hear the chickens are going
to make a break for it tonight!
</P>
<P>
   ``Making the Band,'' ABC at 9:30: The replacement O-Towner
arrives for an audition. Preceding this, at 9, there's a repeat of
last week's episode when Ikaika quit the band, opening up the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providence,'' NBC at 8: Dr. Jim (Mike Farrell) seems to be
spending a lot of time with Syd's photographer friend. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Blues,'' WB at 8: Only terrible tyke Rodney can get baby
Zoe to sleep, so the Bittermans are more than happy to have him
visit. (A rerun follows at 8:30).
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit,'' NBC at 10: A piano
instructor is molesting his students, but it's difficult to get the
testimony of one who could put him away. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``PGA Championship Highlights,'' CBS at 12:35 a.m.: Between
Letterman and Kilborn comes the Tiger Woods show. Or at least CBS
hopes Tiger is still in the chase.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sabrina, The Teenage Witch,'' ABC at 8: Torn by trying to
please everyone in making her college decision, Sabrina splits into
four. A cautionary tale that should provide good family-discussion
fodder. Melissa Joan Hart stars.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Live Through This,'' MTV at 8: New series about a '70s rock
band on a reunion tour, but the focus is on the band members' kids,
all teens and twentysomethings, who really run the tour _ and their
parents. Tonight, Lu fears her mom has fallen off the wagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Invisible Man,'' Sci Fi at 8: Vincent Ventresca is Darien
Fawkes, the small-time thief who bought his way out of jail by
participating in a secret government invisibility experiment. In
this episode, surgery helps deal with one of the side effects _
memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Daddy,'' HBO at 8:30: Adam Sandler's 1999 parenting comedy
was a hit. Go figure. Rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farscape,'' Sci Fi at 9: Crichton (Ben Browder) finds himself
in a strange, alternative reality _ and back on earth. Can Scorpius
(Wayne Pygram) really be the key to freedom?
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Velvet,'' Bravo at 9: David Lynch's R-rated 1986
melodrama opened the way for a whole world of weirdness, including
Lynch's own ``Twin Peaks'' series. But few people have seen it
lately, and it's worth another look. Kyle MacLachlan stars as the
nice young lad who tries to solve the mystery of a severed ear;
Isabella Rossellini and Dennis Hopper top the cast of lunatics he
meets along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bull,'' TNT at 10: Rerun of this week's debut episode of the
cable network's first drama series. The action takes place on Wall
Street, where a group of upstarts led by George Newbern makes a
break from their old-line brokerage firm to set up shop on their
own. Stanley Tucci also stars.
</P>
