<HEADER>
A1184 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPM     08-14 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A photo of a mouse in a beaker, an illustration of a
space-based flywheel, and a photo of a deep-fat Spin Fryer are
available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELECTRIC MEMORY ERASER
</P>
<P>
   Those scenes in spy movies in which secret agents have their
memories erased may be more fact than fiction.
</P>
<P>
   In testing whether more powerful electroconvulsive therapy could
speed relief of depression, researchers at Wake Forest University
Baptist Medical Center in Winston-Salem, N.C., found that these
treatments also wipe out memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person had ECT during May, then their memory of what had
happened in the months of April and May would be at risk of being
forgotten, perhaps forever,'' says Dr. W. Vaughn McCall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this shortcoming, researchers say the treatment is
effective.
</P>
<P>
   DRUNKEN MUTANT MICE
</P>
<P>
   Some drink to forget. Mutant mice drink because nature forgot to
give them the gene that produces the brain protein called Protein
Kinase A (PKA). ``This is the first direct evidence that PKA is
associated with the voluntary consumption of alcohol,'' says Todd
Thiele, head of the University of Washington research team that
made the discovery. Allowed all the alcohol they wanted, mutant
mice drank twice as much as normal mice. And mutants had milder
hangovers. The research may help find treatments for human
alcoholics.
</P>
<P>
   SWAN SONG FOR MILITARY GPS?
</P>
<P>
   A White House order that recently gave civilian GPS users access
to high accuracy signals has fueled rumors that the Pentagon is
building a new military navigation system.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence experts say that GPS satellites have become
vulnerable to rogue missiles. GPS has also performed poorly in the
field, in one case being jammed by homemade transmitters.
</P>
<P>
   A ``gravity mapping'' system like the one used on subs is one
possible alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ANCIENT TECHNOLOGY FOR FUTURE SATELLITES
</P>
<P>
   Ancient technology may cure one of the biggest headaches for
designers of 21st century spacecraft. Power demands on satellites
are rapidly outpacing improvements in batteries. One solution
offered at a recent space conference by Honeywell of Tempe, Ariz.,
uses an idea that's thousands of years old: the potter's flywheel.
</P>
<P>
   For that part of its orbit when a satellite's solar cells bask
in sunlight, the flywheel would behave like a motor, storing
kinetic energy in a fast-spinning composite disc. When the
satellite moves into the dark, the disc's momentum would make the
motor function as a generator.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on satellite design say that a flywheel's inherently
high reliability and ability to withstand an unlimited number of
charge cycles and deliver high-power pulses could make it the
preferred satellite power supply.
</P>
<P>
   STEPPING UP TO 42-VOLT POWER
</P>
<P>
   Your next car could have a 42-volt electrical system _ triple
today's 14-volt charging required for a 12-volt battery. Higher
voltage enables carmakers to power electric steering, shifting,
suspension and braking, more sophisticated communications, and
entertainment and safety systems. Car keys will disappear and be
supplanted by keyless entry, even fingerprint ID. Electromagnetic
valve actuators will replace the engine camshaft. Belt drives will
disappear. The water pump, power steering and a/c compressor will
be electrically operated on demand only, saving power and fuel
otherwise lost to belt drives. All carmakers have agreed to 42
volts, and the first systems will appear next year in Europe. The
changeover will be gradual.
</P>
<P>
   POWERFUL PULSING MAGNET
</P>
<P>
   The most precise and powerful pulsing electromagnet ever created
is now operating at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New
Mexico. It can hammer a sample with a 60-tesla field, pulsing as
rapidly as 1,000 times a second. To keep the system from
overheating it is cooled in a liquid nitrogen bath.
</P>
<P>
   Strength and speed are not the magnet's only virtues. Operators
can control the shape of the magnetic pulse with a degree of
precision that is the highest ever achieved.
</P>
<P>
   The magnet consumes an enormous amount of power, enough to drive
more than 80 locomotives.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHY DEEP-FAT COOKING
</P>
<P>
   If your favorite foods come out of a deep-fat cooker, your
arteries will sing the praises of the Spin Fryer. Developed by
Synergy Worldwide of Alpharetta, Ga., it makes fried foods less
fatty by limiting their contact with cooking oil. Upon starting,
the main chamber tilts 25 degrees, rotating the food in and out of
the oil. At the end of the cooking cycle the chamber returns to its
horizontal position, drains the oil and begins to spin at 800 rpm
while vibrating at ultrasonic frequencies. In 4 seconds the food is
virtually oil-free. The oil itself goes through a carbon filter so
it will be fresh for your next meal.
</P>
<P>
   The Spin Fryer will be manufactured by Salton Maxim and goes on
sale early next year.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
