<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TONIGHT-ADV17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV17 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release THU., AUG. 17, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final night of the Democratic Convention in Los Angeles
concludes with Al Gore's first major address since his formal
nomination as the party's presidential candidate. Can he give a
speech that will cut into George W. Bush's lead, or even create a
big convention bounce of his own? Or will he give Leno and
Letterman fodder for more jokes about what a stiff he is? It's what
passes for a high-stakes moment this year.
</P>
<P>
   You can tune in on ABC or CBS from 9:00-11:00 p.m., and on NBC
from 9:30-11:00 p.m. PBS goes on the air at 8, and C-Span will
carry the festivities gavel to gavel. Also on the air for extended
coverage will be CNN, MSNBC and Fox News Channel; which one you
choose will depend on the flavor of pundit you prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Even MTV is getting in on the fun, with a ``Choose or Lose:
Party 2000'' special at 9. And don't forget Comedy Central's
``Indecision 2000'' on ``The Daily Show with Jon Stewart'' at 11.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC at 8: Regis Philbin
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: By today, another housemate will have
been ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends,'' NBC at 8: Ross is concerned about his new, young
girlfriend's plans for spring break. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF Smackdown,'' UPN at 8: Maybe if the Democrats called their
gathering a smackdown, more people would watch. Just a thought.
Anyway, this is two hours of pro-wrestling, mayhem and sexual
innuendo _ definitely not V.P. candidate Joe Lieberman's favorite
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC at 8:30: Charity begins at home _ with
Karen's favorite pair of pumps. Rerun. Another episode follows at
9, featuring Gregory Hines as Will's new boss. Also a rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charmed,'' WB at 9: Prue turns herself into a man to catch a
demon. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``PGA Championship Highlights,'' CBS at 12:35 a.m. Between
Letterman and Kilborn comes the Tiger Woods show.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre,'' Disney Channel at 7: An abandoned seal bonds with a
girl in Maine. Keith Carradine and Tina Majorino star, George
Miller directed. From 1994, rated PG.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane,'' American Movie Classics at 8: If you're one of those
folks who find the Democrats lacking character, you'll enjoy this
1953 Western about a strong, quiet hero, with Alan Ladd as the
ex-gunfighter and Jean Arthur, Van Heflin and Brandon DeWilde as
the homesteaders he aids. George Stevens directed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' pay-per-view, various times: Matt
Damon, Jude Law and Gwyneth Paltrow star in Anthony (``The English
Patient'') Minghella's adaptation of the Patricia Highsmith
thriller about shifting identities. From 1999, rated R.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rear Window,'' American Movie Classics at 10: Alfred
Hitchcock's 1954 voyeur classic, with James Stewart and Grace
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali-Frasier I: One Nation Divisible,'' HBO at 10: Documentary
focuses on the ``Fight of the Century'' and how it reflected
America's cultural divisions at the time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: George
Clooney, Warren Zevon. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: James Carville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05: Penn
Jillette, U.S. Rep. Barney Frank. You won't get a word in edgewise
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 1:05 a.m.
(delayed by golf): Ed McMahon. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Elizabeth
Berkley. &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL; 
 &UR; For information concerning the above material call (800) 972-3550.
After 5 p.m. contact The New York Times News Service (212)
556-1927. &QL;
</P>
