<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1199 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-JANIKOWSKI-HNS &LR;      08-14 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JANIKOWSKI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JANIKOWSKI IS WORKING OUT THE KINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANK BLACKMAN  
 &HT;    c.2000 San Francisco Examiner
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Sebastian Janikowski's kickoff to begin the second half
had just returned to earth at the nine-yard line. On TV, one of the
Dallas announcers wondered: ``They gave him how many million to do
that?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a reasonable question. While the Raiders first-round pick
had his moments in Oakland's 21-20 exhibition victory over Dallas
Sunday night, he also had some others that made people wonder why
the team felt compelled to draft him so high and then give him $6.2
million, including a $2 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski did make two of three field goal attempts, hitting
from 47 yards and 44 yards. And his miss was from 57 yards, hardly
a gimme for anyone. However, that is supposed to be in his range
and what was troubling about that kick was it was booted so low
Dallas defensive tackle Brandon Noble, who is only 6-foot-2, still
was able to reach up a paw and deflect it.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, Janikowski was unable to put any of his kickoffs
into the end zone. One was a purpose pooch, but the other two were
not and were returned for good yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Cowboys, Janikowski kicked off five times. Only one
made it into the end zone. The others were caught and returned from
the goal line and 1-, 9- and 14-yard lines.
</P>
<P>
   Glum after his performance against the Rams, Janikowski was much
more upbeat the second time around as a pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It was) better,'' he said, smiling. ``I relaxed a little bit
more. I just went out there and just tried to turn the next page.''
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski knows he isn't kicking off well, but thinks he can
correct the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm messing up with my steps,'' he said. ``Sometimes I'm
taking two long steps and getting under the ball. If I take it
perfect, the ball is going deep. I got to find out what I'm doing
wrong. Watch the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Raiders coach Jon Gruden was delighted by Janikowski's made
field goals. Asked about the kickoffs, the coach said, ``He had a
few balls _ I don't know if he didn't quite get all of it or half
of it. But he did have one touchback.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the competition for the punting job continued. Leo
Araguz kicked twice. He got off a mediocre kick on his first
attempt, but benefited from a great bounce, and it wound up a
47-yarder. He did an outstanding job his second time, punting the
Cowboys into a hole at the four-yard line. Rookie Shane Lechler
kicked once for 32 yards to the Dallas 13, and got bonus points
from his coach for handling a low snap and setting the ball up for
Janikowski's second field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane did a great job getting the last hold down for
Janikowski,'' Gruden said. ``A great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to evaluate the competition, Gruden said, ``I'm pleased
with both punters. Have been since the beginning of camp. It's very
close, if it's not even.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
