<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following travel
articles for release Sunday, August 20, and thereafter:
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ALASKA (Undated) _ A camping trip becomes a grand tour of
the largest state _ by van, boat, rail, air, even on foot. By Matt
Nesvisky.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ALASKA-CRUISE (Undated) _ Cruising the Inland Passage on
a small ship avoids the crowds and allows intimacy with icebergs,
whales and bears. By John Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ALASKA-ENVIRON (Undated) _ A place once thought too cold
and too wild to attract tourists is debating limits on visitors. By
Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AUSTRIA-ALPS (Undated) _ Twenty miles southeast of
Vienna, vineyards sweep down from a line of low, wooded hills to a
shallow lake, and Eastern Europe begins. Austria's present-day
frontiers with Hungary and Slovakia may be a few miles farther on,
but the shift from central, Alpine Europe is sudden, dramatic and
unmistakable. By Michael Ratcliffe.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ESSAY-ROME (Undated) _ On a study trip to Rome in the
Jubilee year, a couple is immersed in the holy and the worldly. By
Ray Cormier.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AIRFARES (Undated) _ Americans who postponed vacations
this summer hoping that airlines would announce major fare sales
have had good reason to be disappointed: there haven't been any, at
least nothing comparable to those a few years ago. And while most
analysts attribute the paucity of summer discounts to continued
high demand for flights, they note that the carriers' growing
sophistication in knowing when to lower or raise fares on
everything from individual flights to entire routes could spell the
end to the periodic fire sales of years past. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Student fares on planes, trains
and buses. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: Michelin has come up with a
new recipe for a series of guidebooks: to an exotic destination add
one part Red (as in the Red Guide listings of recommended hotels
and restaurants) and one part Green (descriptions of places of
major and minor interest), then fold in a generous helping of
practical information and vignettes about the local culture. The
result is a series called NEOS, with volumes about Tunisia;
Guatemala and Belize; Reunion, Mauritius and the Seychelles; Syria
and Jordan; and Turkey. Due in December are guides to Indonesia,
Rajasthan, and Sri Lanka and the Maldives. The name NEOS is drawn
from the four compass points in French _ Nord, Est, Ouest, Sud.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Questions: Renting homes in Crete,
touring the Baltic countries (Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia) and
traveling Tuscany by train.
</P>
