<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-THESTREETCOM-CRAMER-N     08-14 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THESTREETCOM-CRAMER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERATED GETS GUTTED; AUDIBLE NO LONGER HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Financial Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from TheStreet.com, the
premier business/finance Web site, is available from the New York
Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By JAMES J. CRAMER  
 c.2000 TheStreet.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes assumptions go awry. Usually, the result is not that
costly. Someone orders the wrong kind of sweater for a
department-store chain. A hardware store takes down lots of snow
shovels and sleds, but it doesn't snow.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, however, the mistakes are devastating. An
insurance company misjudges the risk associated with workers'
compensation. A car company doesn't grasp the enormity of a tire
deficiency. A brokerage house misjudges the rate of repayment from
a giant mortgage bond. Or a retailer misjudges the default rate on
its credit business.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is what is happening right now to Federated Stores
(FD on the New York exchange). This giant retailer bought Fingerhut
for about $1.7 billion a year ago. We thought they did it to have
some Internet exposure, because it was during that wacky period
where everyone needed to commit to the Net. Fingerhut was a giant
infrastructure/logistics play. It sounded super.
</P>
<P>
   But Fingerhut was also a low-end catalog company with a steady
clientele and a steady delinquency rate. Before the sale, however,
Fingerhut had been changing some of its credit policies. These
policy changes accelerated under Federated.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts are all pretty deferential to Federated about what
happened next. But Fingerhut basically gutted Federated because the
assumptions Federated had made about Fingerhut's customers were all
wrong. They started defaulting wildly and Federated got completely
smoked by the change in assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Fingerhut wiped out about a buck of Federated's
earnings _ and all of its credibility with Wall Street. Federated
holders dumped the stock like mad. They took out about $1.7 billion
in market value. Irony? That was what Federated paid for Fingerhut.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens now? I am sure the value guys are sniffing. And
I don't blame them. This seems like an overwhacking if there ever
was one. But people hate being bagged. Federated bagged people.
Heck, Federated bagged itself. They probably didn't understand the
habits of the Fingerhut consumers. Why should they? Fingerhut
shoppers don't go to Bloomingdale's. Classic case of not sticking
to your knitting.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up this whole fiasco to one more company trying to please
the Street after sitting out the Web for too long. Ultimately, I am
waiting until year-end tax season to pick this one up. I think it
will still be right here at that time. Too much damage to bounce
back any quicker.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIBLE IS NO LONGER HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Last week I saw that Audible Inc. (ADBL on the Nasdaq) hit that
sickening one-buck level (it closed Friday at 1 27/32). That's the
point of no return for most stocks, as surely as if they've passed
through Halifax on the way to England.
</P>
<P>
   So I took a look at what went wrong. Aside from the tragic death
of its very young CEO last year, astoundingly I can report that
nothing, nothing at all went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was above plan. Everything was what venture capital
firm and key investor Kleiner Perkins might have expected or that
investors Random House and the now nonprescient Amazon (it bought 5
percent of the company at the now stupid price of 15) would have
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Audible grew the market for audio Web downloads in a serious and
methodical fashion. It had books by Stephen King read by Stephen
King. It had issues of key newspapers downloaded audibly on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   It sought and got Microsoft's backing for the downloadable
content. It even gained Robin Williams for a weekly show of
original content.
</P>
<P>
   These guys were smoking, promotion-wise. They were in all of the
papers and constantly on television with puff interviews that made
this company sound like the next RCA!
</P>
<P>
   How about those numbers? All of the bankers who brought this
company public had analysts that consistently applauded the
company's triple-digit revenue growth. So what that it was still in
the hundreds of thousands instead of the millions? The point was
that it was ``better than expected'' and we know that's
nirvana-ville on Wall Street. Or at least it seemed so going into
the April Net correction.
</P>
<P>
   So what went wrong? Absolutely nothing. Audible is a small
company with a small franchise and a small-scale operation that is
valued, well, with a small capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing wrong with Audible is what happened to its stock
in the interim. That's what was wrong. Now everything seems just
right. It's just that nobody made much money except the insiders
who sold right after the Amazon news, just when the nauseating
decline began.
</P>
<P>
   Oh well. Now, Audible's just another tree falling in the dot-com
woods. Nobody's hearing it. Rather ironic, now, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   (James J. Cramer is manager of a hedge fund and co-founder of
TheStreet.com. At time of publication, his fund was short Amazon.
His fund often buys and sells securities that are the subject of
his columns, both before and after the columns are published, and
the positions that his fund takes may change at any time. Under no
circumstances does the information in this column represent a
recommendation to buy or sell stocks. Cramer's writings provide
insights into the dynamics of money management and are not a
solicitation for transactions. While he cannot provide investment
advice or recommendations, he invites you to comment on his column
at jjcletters(at)thestreet.com.)
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
