transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-PEACE (Johannesburg) _ A major effort to broker a peace
agreement designed to end years of war in central Africa appears to
be collapsing, dramatically increasing the danger of a new round of
bloodletting. Burundi looms as the next flashpoint. By Kurt
Shillinger. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-PEDOPHILES (Portsmouth, England) _ A sensational case
involving the apparent sexual murder of a 7-year-old girl leads to
an explosion of vigilante justice after a Murdoch-owned paper
starts publishing the names and pictures of reported child abusers.
By Kevin Cullen. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AIDES (Washington) _ The kids who joined Bill Clinton's
administration back in 1993 are now getting ready to reenter the
real world. By Ann Scales. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IVY-CANDIDATES (Undated) _ Pedigree isn't supposed to matter
anymore -- so why do almost all the candidates for top national
office hail from Yale (Bush, Cheney, Lieberman, Nader) or Harvard
(Gore)? By Scot Lehigh. 16730 words.
</P>
<P>
   SECULAR-JEWS (Undated) _ While Sen. Joseph Lieberman's selection
has been hailed as a milestone for the American Jewish community,
to some more secular Jews his rhetoric and positions are
unsettling. Some non-religious Jews say American Jews should
continue to resist the integration of religion and government. By
Joanna Weiss. 1490 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RESUME-FRAUD (Undated) _ A ``doctor'' in Cleveland had operated
dozens of times before his supervisors discovered his medical
degree was bogus. One-third of the applicants for a prestigious
medical fellowship at Johns Hopkins falsely claimed they had
published research papers. The medical profession has a major
problem with falsified credentials. By Anne Barnard, 1620 words.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGES-MALE (Amherst, Mass.) _ The number of men in higher
education has been declining for years, a trend attributed to
demographics. But increasingly, men feel that they are under attack
by campus judiciaries, deans of students, and college officials. By
Patrick Healy. 1450 words; includes friendly/unfriendly campuses
text table. PHOTO
</P>
