<HEADER>
A1232 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      08-14 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Safer Nuclear Waste
</P>
<P>
   High-level nuclear waste in storage is like an unruly guest in a
tidy house. The material that's used to contain the waste _ be it
glass, ceramic or whatever _ owes its strength and stability to its
orderly structure, with every atom in its proper place.
</P>
<P>
   Decaying waste, like used fuel from nuclear reactors, upsets the
structure: it produces radiation that causes atoms to shift,
creating defects that can eventually lead to cracks or other
problems that can affect safety. Indeed, most storage containers
are designed to last only a century or so.
</P>
<P>
   Now, scientists from Los Alamos National Laboratory and
universities in Britain and Japan say that a class of ceramics
known as complex oxides may hold promise for longer-term waste
storage. The key, they say, is that this material is not so
fastidious: it can tolerate radiation-induced defects.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, who reported on their work in the journal
Science, first created computer simulations of the effects of
radiation on these materials, and then tested them in the
laboratory. They found that one kind of complex oxide ceramic,
similar in structure to the mineral fluorite, was relatively
disordered to begin with. When radiation starts to monkey with it,
its atoms can shift to accommodate the defects with relative ease.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggest that similar materials beyond those that
they studied may also be radiation resistant. In any case, much
more work remains before a satisfactory solution to the problem of
long-term storage of waste is achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Rare View of a Comet
</P>
<P>
   The celestial soap opera that is Comet Linear continues.
</P>
<P>
   In our last episode, the comet, after disappointing backyard
star gazers, seemed to be fizzling to oblivion. As Linear made its
closest approach to the Sun late last month, the heat had caused
the comet's nucleus to bubble and blow apart, leaving what
astronomers thought was just a cloud of dust.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast. While Linear will never be a recurring
character like other comets, it's not dead yet. The Hubble Space
Telescope and the European Southern Observatory's Very Large
Telescope in Chile have observed a group of tiny comets left behind
as Linear came apart.
</P>
<P>
   There are about a dozen of these ``comettes,'' each consisting
of a small piece of the original nucleus, perhaps 100 feet or so in
diameter, with a tiny tail. While these objects may eventually
disintegrate completely, before they do they may provide insight
into the comet's original structure. Such a cometary breakup has
never been seen in such detail before now.
</P>
<P>
   Puzzle of a Jupiter Moon
</P>
<P>
   For the past several decades, scientists have been intrigued by
cracks and other signs of stretching on the surface of Jupiter's
icy moon Europa. But the scientists have been puzzled by what may
be considered a lack of give and take _ that is, stretching in one
area of Europa must result in squeezing elsewhere, but no solid
evidence of such compression had been discovered.
</P>
<P>
   But now, scientists from Johns Hopkins and Brown, examining
images taken by the Galileo spacecraft, have uncovered what they
say are folds in Europa's surface caused by compression, like the
ripples in cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   A high-resolution image of one part of the surface, taken when
the Sun was at a low angle, shows subtle shading of a fold's hills
and valleys. Other images show cracks on the tops of the hills and
small ridges in the valleys, kinds of structures that would be
expected in a rippled surface.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, writing in Science, suggest that tidal forces
within Europa caused the compressional folding, and that the
amplitude of the folds was originally much greater _ the hills were
higher and the valleys lower. But over time, because of relatively
warmer conditions below the surface, the folds relaxed, leaving the
faint structures hardly visible today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 1531EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
