<HEADER>
A1237 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-N     08-14 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUSCLE GROUPS: Stretching: Myths, Legends and Facts
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have gained new insight into what happens when
athletes stretch, but the actual advice handed out by coaches,
trainers and even physicians is a hodgepodge of myths and outdated
assumptions, according to an article in the August issue of The
Physician and Sportsmedicine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many of the common practices are either ineffective or
potentially harmful, said the researchers, who are from Sir
Mortimer B. Davis-Jewish General Hospital and St. Mary's Hospital,
both in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a summary of some of the findings they report from
recent studies:
</P>
<P>
   _ Stretching before exercise does not appear to decrease the
risk of injury, but it does reduce pain or discomfort from
stiffness, extending the comfortable range of motion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Warming up _ engaging in light activity before strenuous
exertion _ does not increase range of motion, but it does reduce
rate of injury, most likely by increasing the temperature of muscle
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bounce'' stretching _ repeated brief stretches of a muscle _
can increase stiffness and actually be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   _ For most people, one 15- to 30-second continuous stretch will
suffice for most muscle groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adding heat or cold to a muscle makes stretching more
effective, most likely by reducing the pain of stiffness.
</P>
<P>
   _ The best stretching strategy is likely to vary from person to
person and varies depending on injuries.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION: A Menu for Fighting Rickets Resurgence
</P>
<P>
   Infants being fed with breast milk only, particularly black
infants, should be given vitamin D supplements, according to a
study that reports a resurgence in cases of rickets, a
bone-weakening condition caused by a deficiency of the vitamin.
</P>
<P>
   In an article last week in The Journal of Pediatrics, North
Carolina researchers reported an increase in rickets among all
babies studied, but particularly among dark-skinned babies. Dark
skin hinders the absorption of sunlight, which is needed to make
vitamin D.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers _ Dr. Henry N. Kirkman Jr. of the University of
North Carolina and Drs. Robert Schwartz and Shelley Kreiter of Wake
Forest University _ linked the increase primarily to the growing
popularity of breast-feeding; infant formula has contained vitamin
D supplements since the 1930's. Other possible factors include a
decrease in the use of vitamin supplements and the reduced amount
of time children spend outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Rickets, which until this decade had almost disappeared in the
United States, can lead to a failure to thrive, bone fractures and
bowlegs. ``This disease is 100 percent treatable,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Beyond the Pain of Gastric Reflux
</P>
<P>
   A new article in The Annals of Internal Medicine reports an
association between drugs that have a side effect of allowing
gastric reflux and the rates of a rare but deadly kind of gastric
cancer whose incidence has been on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Yet an editorial in the same journal said that the findings were
not likely to lead to any immediate decrease in the use of the
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The study focused on esophageal adenocarcinoma, which has been
on the rise in recent years among men in America and Western
Europe. Previous research had determined that gastrointestinal
reflux, the backward flow of stomach fluid into the esophagus, was
a risk factor for the cancer, which has a five-year survival rate
of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from Sweden and the Harvard Center for Cancer
Prevention, speculate that various drugs that loosen the sphincter
at the base of the esophagus, thus making reflux occurrence easier,
could play a role in the rise of the cancer. The medications were
introduced around the time the increase began.
</P>
<P>
   Those drugs included nitroglycerin, asthma medicines like
albuterol and aminophyllines, Valium and a class of intestinal
medicines called anticholinergics.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers collected data on the cases of about 600 people
with the disease from 1995 to 1997 and surveyed the patients and a
control group of healthy men to determine who among them had taken
the medicines in question. The cancer was almost four times as
common among those who had taken the drugs daily for more than five
years.
</P>
<P>
   But the article and the editorial noted that the absolute risk
for the cancer was so low that doctors were not likely to abandon
useful medicines on that basis alone, particularly since the class
of drugs with the highest association, anticholinergics, had fallen
out of favor for other reasons. More study is also needed, the
editorial said, to determine whether the medicines are actually
causing the gastric reflux.
</P>
<P>
   And the researchers wrote that, in one sense, the findings could
be seen as reassuring for users of these medications, because ``our
data suggest that persons who use these drugs for short periods may
be at little or no increased risk.''
</P>
<P>
   OUTCOMES: A Hernia Repair Job That Lasts Longer
</P>
<P>
   Using mesh to repair hernias that result from surgery is more
effective than repairing them with stitches, according to a Dutch
study published last week in The New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Incisional hernias, as such wounds are called, are common
complications of abdominal surgery. The traditional repair has
involved stitching the hole; more recently surgeons have implanted
a mesh that allows new flesh and scar tissue to close the gap. Both
methods have had fairly high rates of recurrence, with conflicting
reports on which one works better.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from University Hospital in Amsterdam,
organized a study that ran from 1992 to 1998 at a number of medical
centers in which 200 patients in need of such surgery were randomly
assigned to sutures or mesh.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years after the surgery, 48 percent of the suture
group had hernia recurrences while only 24 percent of the mesh
group did. The researchers speculated that stitching could subject
the surrounding tissue to excessive tension.
</P>
<P>
   REACTIONS: Exploring the Circuitry of Sleepwalking
</P>
<P>
   To help figure out just what goes on in the head of a
sleepwalker, a team of Swiss researchers hooked a teen-ager to a
device that measures brain activity, turned out the lights and
waited.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old had been a sleepwalker since childhood, as were
his maternal grandmother, mother and younger brother. The episodes
would occur several times a week, and were occasionally accompanied
by feelings of terror.
</P>
<P>
   Electrodes were placed on the boy's head and the firings of his
neurons were recorded using a technique called single photon
emission computed tomography. About 50 minutes into the boy's
sleep, a mild episode of sleepwalking occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers reported in the Aug. 5 issue of The Lancet that
one area of the brain was being turned on and others that normally
functioned in tandem with it remained quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The activated area, called the cingulate cortex, ``is part of a
functional network that modulates behaviors involved in emotional
processes,'' the researchers wrote. ``Seizures and stimulations of
the cingulate cortex in human beings elicit several motor,
autonomic and emotional responses that are similar to those seen in
sleepwalking and sleep terror.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
