<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1267 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-KIDS-PARENTS-LIFEBEAT     08-14 1603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-PARENTS-LIFEBEAT-1500-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PROBLEM WITH KIDS TODAY? TODAY'S PARENTS, SOME SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.
 By KAREN STABINER   
 c.2000 New York Times   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. James Varga, a pediatrician, has been in practice in Santa
Monica, Calif., for 21 years, enough time for a generation of
well-educated, middle- and upper-middle-class parents to have
visited his examination room with their children. His diagnosis of
those parents: ``Absolutely too permissive.''
</P>
<P>
   The syndrome, according to Dr. Varga, starts with sleep
problems, when the child is nine to 12 months old. Then come the
tantrums when the child is two or three. By adolescence, it is
drugs and alcohol. ``People are not setting limits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is almost certainly a prescription for trouble, experts
say. Parents may assume that a laissez-faire approach to child
raising will make youngsters relaxed, happy and independent. In
fact, children read flexibility and a willingness to negotiate as
inconsistency, and it makes them nervous. ``When discipline is
sacrificed for the 'palness' of the relationship, the child does
not feel safe,'' said Dr. Linda Rubinowitz, clinical psychologist
and director of the Family Institute at Northwestern University, in
Evanston, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the parents of today's parents, those strict
disciplinarians of the 1950s and early '60s, may have been right
all along: Father and mother did know best, many psychologists and
pediatricians say. But that style of parenting is as out of fashion
as last season's pants. Permissiveness fits better, particularly in
a world that seems much more threatening than it did a generation
ago. Daily life is so full of constraints that many parents are
reluctant to introduce more.
</P>
<P>
   Like fashion, permissiveness is primarily a function of
affluence, and the work schedule required to maintain it. Poorer
families aspire to discipline but often practice ``permissiveness
by default,'' Dr. Rubinowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're working on a lower socioeconomic scale, the intent
may be to set firm limits, but they end up being permissive because
of the complexity of life _ working so many jobs and handling
responsibilities on a personal level that a more affluent person
would farm out, like shopping or cleaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who can afford to choose are motivated by a number of
factors. Dr. Varga, the father of two daughters, ages 13 and 15,
blames a strong ``reaction formation'' in some adults who, trying
not to recapitulate their parents' authoritarian style, ``end up
lopsided the other way.'' In other words, baby boomers who entered
adulthood on a wave of rebellion continue to fight the
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Varga cites parents who have proudly told him that they
smoked marijuana with their children. ``Most parents of teens today
have smoked pot, and they don't want to be hypocritical, so most of
them are very lenient,'' he said. ``But if parents don't have a
position, it's difficult for a kid to figure out what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Other parents abandon discipline because they want to enjoy the
little time they have to spend with their children. ``With working
mothers, there is definitely an issue of guilt,'' Dr. Varga said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rubinowitz said that single parents feel a similar pressure.
``The complexity of life and lifestyle is a constraining factor,''
she said. ``People feel, 'I just don't have the energy, I don't
want to have another fight, I have limits myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed adults take what Nancy Samalin, a parent educator in
New York City, believes is the path of least resistance. ``Parents
want their children to love them, and it's harder to say 'no' than
'yes,''' she explained, ``especially if you've been working all day
and you're tired.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology that makes the universe one big chat room can
also make it harder to converse at the dinner table. ``The nuclear
family used to have dinner and then perhaps watch a family program
on TV together,'' said Reveta Bowers, the head of school at the
Center for Early Education in Los Angeles, a private elementary
school where families include celebrities, dual-career couples and
those receiving financial aid. ``Now they all go off to their own
rooms, to the computer. Even the poorest families have TVs.''
</P>
<P>
   The autonomy that technology encourages has undermined the
family, Ms. Bowers said, noting, ``Everyone does what feels best
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Ms. Samalin and other experts say that children are
making too many decisions, often subsidized by money, which is
easier to hand out than attention.
</P>
<P>
   Vicky Mann is a middle-school teacher on Mercer Island, a
middle-class suburb of Seattle, Wash., and the mother of two
daughters, 13 and 11. Mrs. Mann said she was appalled when her
seventh-grade students circulated a petition challenging a school
dress code that forbade spaghetti-strap tops and dresses at a
dance. She has never let her daughters wear such revealing clothes.
What did it mean that her preteen students wanted them so badly?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think parents are involved,'' Mrs. Mann said. ``I
assume they just give the kids money to go shopping at the mall,
and they come home with clothes meant for older girls. The parents
think it's fashionable, and they think of themselves as hipper than
their parents were. So they don't institute rules.''
</P>
<P>
   She tells her own children that they cannot wear clothes that
``advertise'' a young body, ``and my girls go along with me because
I give them a reason.'' Which is that it's inappropriate for girls
to dress in such revealing styles.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of parents putting on the behavioral brakes,
schools are increasingly assuming the traditional parental role.
``Schools now make rules,'' Ms. Bowers said, ``which in many
instances are the only rules that are not open to arbitration or
negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``What children really need is guidance and love and
support. We expect them to act more and more like adults, while we
act more and more like children. Then, when we're ready to act like
parents, they bristle at the retaking of authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Among her students' families, permissiveness can become a
competitive sport. Indeed, two years ago, she sent out a note
asking people to tone down birthday parties. ``There's this formula
_ the rentals, the trained acts,'' Ms. Bowers said. ``It's how we
express our love, rather than putting our arms around them and
saying 'no' in a loving way.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rubinowitz said that ``no'' is often the most loving thing a
parent can say. ``It gives the child a sense that you really
understand what's going on,'' she explained. ``And it gives the
child a way to deal with a problem in a social context. You can
tell them, 'Say your mom and dad won't let you do it, and grumble
if you want.' That's face-saving for the child.''
</P>
<P>
   There are signs of a backlash among wealthier parents. Kathleen
Kennedy and Frank Marshall, film producers whose credits include
the Oscar-nominated ``Sixth Sense'' and ``E.T.,'' could underwrite
all manner of permissiveness with their two daughters, Lili, 3, and
Meghan, 15 months. But they have decided not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We originally designed the kids' rooms so we could put TVs in
them,'' Ms. Kennedy said. Instead, the television and computers
will be installed in a communal space in the house because, Ms.
Kennedy said, ``I want to know what they watch and have some
control; I'm a big believer in boundaries and discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, as Ms. Kennedy sees it, is to figure out how to
be strict in a world that has far more rules than when she grew up.
``The seeds of my imagination and creativity came from the fact
that I could say, 'Hey, see you later,' and our parents didn't
worry about it,'' she said. ``They'd just say, 'Be home in time for
dinner,' and I'd be off on my bike. But today, you can't send your
kids riding their bikes in the canyon alone, because it isn't
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The old freedoms have become casualties of fear related to
teenage violence, drugs and alcohol; the sexual revolution that the
current generation of parents lived through now has life-or-death
consequences. Ms. Kennedy's children spend more time under adult
supervision than she ever did, and she wonders how children will
learn to be independent. ``Everything is so regimented now,'' she
said. As Dr. Rubinowitz said, ``This is the challenge for this
generation _ to find ways to enable a child to develop her own
judgment without a created structure around her, to find ways to
'work in' experiences that allow more flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The umbilical cord stretches,'' she concluded, ``but I do
think it's a harder world.''
</P>
<P>
   -----------------------------------------------
</P>
