<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-ENTRANCE-EXAMS-LIFEBEAT-650-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE COUNSELING CAN HELP KIDS BOOST COLLEGE ENTRANCE SCORES
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.
 By BEN GOSE
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's one good thing about the rising cost of college
tuition, it's that it makes a private college counselor or an SAT
tutor seem cheap by comparison. You've probably heard about these
paid consultants who'll help your child search for the right
college and fill out the applications.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, students have been seeking outside help on at
least one aspect of their college applications _ the SAT and ACT,
the most widely used college-entrance exams. Today, they usually
turn to one of the two big test-preparation companies: Kaplan and
the Princeton Review.
</P>
<P>
   The College Board, which oversees the SAT, had long argued that
``coaching'' does not help students improve their scores. But in
1998, it published a study acknowledging that coaching can improve
scores on the test _ which has a maximum of 1600 points _ by about
twenty-five points. (Today, the Board itself sells books on test
prep.)
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan and the Princeton Review say their studies show that, on
average, their courses improve students' scores by more than 100
points. The Princeton Review, in fact, promises to continue working
with students who don't improve their scores _ by at least 100
points _ absolutely free.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaplan and Princeton Review SAT preparation courses cost
about $700 to $900. Classes typically meet once a week for two to
three months. (Students who take an online course alone can cut
those costs nearly in half.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the test-prep business, private college counseling is
dominated by individuals, many of whom are former guidance
counselors or admissions officers. Their fees range from $500 to
$3,000, depending on the student's needs. Since there's virtually
no regulation of the industry, families are well advised to check
references before hiring anyone.
</P>
<P>
   You can also ask the guidance counselor at your child's school
for advice _ but be aware that the school counselor might be
offended. (``Isn't that my job?'' he/she might wonder, even though
the time this counselor can give each student is sometimes
minimal.)
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find an acceptable private counselor locally,
contact the Independent Educational Consultants Association in
Fairfax, Va. Its more than 300 members agree to abide by Principles
of Good Practice _ such as never accepting compensation from a
college for hyping it to students.
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton Review and California-based Achieva College Prep
Centers have begun creating national chains of private
college-counseling centers. Their prices are slightly lower than
those charged by independent consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring outside help is not without its critics. ``Students with
initiative can get for free a lot of what these very expensive
services are offering,'' contends Alice Kleeman, a college adviser
at Menlo-Atherton High School in Atherton, Calif. But perhaps the
strongest argument against the practice is that admissions deans
are wary of consultants who provide too much help. An admissions
officer at Duke University says that she tosses aside applications
with essays that seem ``too polished'' (read: ghostwritten).
</P>
<P>
   For more information: Achieva College Prep Series;
www.achieva.com. The College Board, (212) 713-8000;
www.collegeboard.org. Independent Educational Consultants
Association, (703) 591-4850; www.educationalconsulting.org. Kaplan
Educational Centers, (800) KAPTEST; www.kaplan.com. The Princeton
Review, (800) 2-REVIEW; www.review.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Ben Gose writes for ``Town &AMP; Country'' magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
