<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIBET-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL TIBET: A MAGNET FOR EXPLORERS, SPIRITUALISTS AND THE
STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the centuries, Tibet has been mythologized in the Western
imagination as a magical, utopian realm. For 19th-century explorers
trying to scale the daunting peaks of the Himalayas, it was a kind
of alluring El Dorado _ one of the great unmapped places of the
world, a place whose very isolation endowed it with a frisson of
mystery and allure. For spiritualists like Alexandra David-Neel,
who journeyed to Lhasa in 1924, it was a fairy tale realm where
lamas practiced magic and astral projection. For readers of James
Hilton's 1933 novel ``Lost Horizon,'' Tibet was the inspiration for
the never-never land of Shangri-La, a refuge from a desperate
world, a paradise where nothing was wanting and no one ever grew
old.
</P>
<P>
   In his highly uneven new book, ``Virtual Tibet,'' Orville
Schell, dean of the Graduate School of Journalism at the University
of California, Berkeley, and the author of several books on China,
attempts to assess the role that Tibet has played in the fantasy
life of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Although his chapters dealing with historical material have been
energetically researched and make for engaging reading, the
remainder of the book (detailing Hollywood's relationship with
Tibet) is flawed by strangely fuzzy thinking. There are inane
interviews with such ``Buddhists'' as Oliver Stone, the director of
``Natural Born Killers,'' and the action actor Steven Seagal, who
once played ``a CIA agent turned cop with a Buddhist bent.'' There
are also long, self-indulgent accounts of Schell's visits to the
movie set of ``Seven Years in Tibet,'' accounts that attempt to
draw strained analogies between the fantasies the public projects
on movie stars like Brad Pitt (the star of that movie) and the
fantasies it has projected on Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   It is Schell's thesis that Tibet's isolation and, for many
years, its inaccessibility turned it into a blank screen on which
Westerners could project their wildest imaginings. In the years
before air travel, the very difficulty of getting to the holy city
of Lhasa made it a challenge to explorers, while the reluctance of
Tibetans to welcome outsiders galvanized the urge of these
adventurers ``to transgress forbidden places.''
</P>
<P>
   As the West grew increasingly industrialized and embarked on two
world wars, Tibet also became a magnet for those weary of
civilization and its discontents: The country's spectacular
Himalayan vistas acquired a kind of religious significance, even as
the land came to fill the need of Westerners ``to imagine a
peaceful, spiritual, serene country, at once beautiful and
removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Culling through the eclectic writings on Tibet left by
explorers, missionaries and spiritual pilgrims, Schell gives the
reader an entertaining account of the disparate Westerners who made
their way to Lhasa, or tried. We are introduced to Father Ippolito
Desideri, a Jesuit priest who arrived in Lhasa in 1716 after a
harrowing trip across the Himalayas and who left the first
comprehensive account by a Westerner of life in Tibet; Col. Nikolai
Mikhailovich Przhevalsky, a Russian explorer who embarked upon five
grueling and unsuccessful expeditions to reach Lhasa and eventually
died of typhus on the way; and Mr. and Mrs. St. George Littledale,
who set off from India in 1894 with their fox terrier, Tanny, and
came within 70 miles of their quest.
</P>
<P>
   Schell discusses the heroic efforts of such Indian cartographers
as Nain Singh and Sarat Chandra Das to map the wilderness of Tibet,
and recounts the efforts of eccentric spiritualists like Helena
Petrovna von Hahn _ aka Madame Blavatsky _ to promote Tibet as the
epicenter of a new spiritualism. ``The ensuing Western infatuation
with Tibet and its form of Buddhism was somewhat reminiscent of the
idealization of China by the physiocrats and philosophes during the
French Enlightenment,'' Schell writes. ``Only then, Europeans
admired China's practicality and rationality whereas now they
admired Tibet's propensity for the irrational and supernatural.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as Tibetans under Chinese rule have tried to
focus world attention on their plight, they have forsaken their
once willful isolation. The attention of Hollywood and New Age
seekers is welcomed, even cultivated, as is the attention of the
press. ``Like a river that has reversed its course,'' Schell
observes, ``Tibetans now desperately turn outward rather than
inward.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that such provocative historical analysis is
intercut in ``Virtual Tibet'' with long-winded chapters on the
making of the movie adaptation of ``Seven Years in Tibet'' that
read like outtakes from a hastily written magazine piece.
</P>
<P>
   Schell spends an enormous amount of space talking about his
negotiations with movie publicists to visit the set in Argentina,
where the Andes were used as a stand-in for the Himalayas. Worse,
he jokily compares his difficulties in gaining access to the movie
set to the hardships suffered by early adventurers trying to make
it across the Himalayas to Tibet. Elsewhere, in a discussion of
``Tibet's evolving mythology,'' he callously lumps together the old
Western myth of a ``paradisiacal Tibet'' with the current Western
view of the land as a spiritual society ``crushed under the
jackboot of an aggressive materialist overlord,'' as though both
notions were equally projections of ``the popular imagination of
the West.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, such glibly tossed-off observations distract
attention from the more serious aspects of this book, and cast an
unnecessary shadow over Schell's more thoughtful observations.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `VIRTUAL TIBET: SEARCHING FOR SHANGRI-LA FROM THE HIMALAYAS TO
HOLLYWOOD' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Orville Schell
</P>
<P>
   340 pages. Metropolitan Books/Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
