<HEADER>
A1278 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-14 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MORE LEAP INTO THE CLINTON CESSPOOL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just what we needed _ another confession/apology from Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons known only to the self-indulgent, lame-duck penitent
in chief, President Clinton showed up at a ministers' conference in
Illinois and rehashed his oh-so-horrible feelings of guilt and
remorse regarding the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm now in the second year of a process of trying to totally
rebuild my life from a terrible mistake I made,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't specifically mention which ``terrible mistake'' he was
alluding to, but his oh-so-heartfelt remarks had the name ``Monica
Lewinsky'' written all over them.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he specifically speak the words ``I'm sorry'' this time
around, but he defended a previous apology that some Americans
apparently found unconvincing:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I gave a clear, unambiguous, brutally frank and
frankly personally painful statement ... because I had to do it. I
mean, I finally realized that I was _ you know _ that I'd never be
all right unless I stood up there and said what I did, and said it
was wrong, and apologized for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that anyone who saw that, and who observed what
happened afterward, would not doubt that there had been a full and
adequate apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton previously apologized _ sort of _ six times, according
to a list published by the New York Daily News and distributed by
the Knight Ridder/Tribune news service.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``I'm sorry'' in at least one of the apologies, and in
another he said, ``I'm profoundly sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   You just can't be much sorrier than ``profoundly sorry,''
although I'd still like to hear him proclaim that he is
``oh-so-sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's remarks caused a stir on a day when the only
other news had to do with self-destructing tires _ so much of a
stir, in fact, that Ted Koppel featured them on ``Nightline.'' Ted
asked ABC commentator/ex-Clinton confidant George Stephanopoulos
why Clinton would be talking about such things at this stage of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't help it,'' Stephanopoulos said. ``He can't stop
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that the longtime compulsive philanderer has turned
into a compulsive apologizer?
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos, by the way, offered the opinion that Vice
President Al Gore and his campaign strategists could have lived
without Clinton's latest comments about the Lewinsky business.
Gore, after all, had just added Joe ``Moral Conscience of the
Senate'' Lieberman to the Democratic ticket in hopes of putting
some distance between himself and Clinton's misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was the one Democrat who denounced Clinton's
relationship with Lewinsky as ``immoral'' way back when the
president was still trying to get away with calling it
``inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan seemed to be working until Clinton decided to walk
the path of repentance one more time. By reminding voters of
something that Gore would like them to forget, Clinton made life
more difficult for his would-be successor.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that Clinton didn't make an effort to give
Gore some breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get enough credit for what we did together that is
good,'' Clinton said. ``And surely no fair-minded person would
blame him for any mistake that I made.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't Clinton's mistakes that some Americans are blaming
on Gore. The vice president is being blamed to a certain degree for
his blind allegiance to Clinton _ and to a large degree for his own
actions as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted Cliff May, communications director
for the Republican National Committee:
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's personal foibles and failings have nothing to do
with the fact that Al Gore went to a Buddhist temple to raise money
and that his closest associates and fund-raisers were convicted of
multiple felonies in regard to that event.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Gore has plenty to answer for in his own right
before anyone thinks about dragging him into Clinton's cesspool.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton, well, he really ought to stop splashing.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
