<P>
   CVN-CONVENTION-RDP (Los Angeles) _ President Clinton will boast
about his eight years as president when he addresses the Democratic
National Convention tonight. Hillary Rodham Clinton, who will
introduce her husband, is set to talk about issues of special
interest to women and children. Ten other women will speak on
opening night. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-DEMS (Los Angeles) _ President Clinton and First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton take their bows before the Democratic
National Convention and leave the stage to Al Gore. By JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-HILLARY-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton is
preparing to deliver a 10-minute speech tonight at the Democratic
National Convention under a coveted prime-time spotlight, serving a
dual role as a first lady introducing her husband's and as her
party's candidate for the Senate seat from New York. By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-BRADLEY (Los Angeles) _ Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley,
who finished a distant second to Vice President Al Gore in the
Democratic primary contests, will address the Democratic convention
Tuesday, having formally released his delegates to cast their votes
to nominate Gore. By ALAN BERNSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GORE-PROTESTS (Los Angeles) _ Environmental demonstrators
target Al Gore on the opening day of the Democratic National
Convention, calling on the vice president to sell his family's
shares in Occidental Petroleum Corp. The company is seeking to
drill on land in Colombia claimed by the 5,000-member indigenous
U'wa tribe, which has vowed to walk off a 1,400-foot cliff if
Occidental begins the project. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-DNC-PROGRESSIVES (Washington) _ Liberal Democrats rally to
make their voices heard at a convention aimed at nominating two
decidedly centrist candidates, Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman.
Liberals, who call themselves progressives, are not completely in
sync with Gore, and some are supporting Green Party nominee Ralph
Nader. But others feel Gore is the best hope of holding back a
complete Republican takeover of Washington. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LAZIO-CLINTON (Albany, N.Y.) _ Rep. Rick Lazio spearheaded
the U.S. Congress' effort to overhaul public housing and he is
using the issue to tout his effectiveness as a candidate for Senate
against Hillary Rodham Clinton. The 1998 housing overhaul
highlighted Lazio's mainstay in Congress since 1994, an area of
expertise rarely associated with Republicans, in which he is widely
credited with working on both sides of the political aisle. By LARA
JAKES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BERYL (Undated) _ Authorities have issued hurricane warnings and
are urging residents along the southern Texas coast to move inland
as Tropical Storm Beryl gains strength. The storm is expected to
hit land sometime Tuesday. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Vice President Al Gore's father
once told a reporter that his son was so nervous when he announced
for Congress that he fled to a bathroom afterward to vomit. This
was not the disciplined, cool Al Gore voters think they know. Now
is the time for the real Al Gore to stand up as he prepares to
accept the Democratic nomination for president. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
