<P>
   HARLEY'S LEADERSHIP U-TURN
</P>
<P>
   HARLEY-U-TURN-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW _ When Rich Teerlink
became president of Harley-Davidson's motorcycle division in 1987,
the hard work of saving the company was done. After seven years of
crisis, it was growing steadily. In this first-person essay,
Teerlink tells how a new kind of leadership was needed _ one that
encouraged union and salaried employees to break new ground and
care about the company on a personal level _ and how hard it was to
make the shift. By Rich Teerlink.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN BOTS COLLIDE
</P>
<P>
   PRICEBOT-WAR-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW _ Many buyers on the
Internet routinely use shopbots _ software agents that
automatically canvass the Internet looking for the cheapest price
for a given product. Now e-businesses are deploying agents of their
own. For example, the online retailer Buy.com is reportedly using
price-comparison software that automatically adjusts its prices to
undercut competitors' prices. But if online sellers deploy
pricebots, will the result be digital mayhem? A report. By Jeffrey
O. Kephart and Amy R. Greenwald.
</P>
