A1296 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN-TE     08-14 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JFK'S SPIRIT PERVADES DEMOCRATS' CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BOB RAY SANDERS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This city has changed drastically since John
Fitzgerald Kennedy stood on the podium in the old Memorial Coliseum
here to accept his party's nomination for president and to tell
Americans about his vision of a ``New Frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that LA is bigger, smoggier and even more
culturally diverse, but its sparkling new skyscrapers _ once
forbidden for fear of earthquakes _ are testimony to the city's
confidence, if not arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kennedy's nomination in 1960, Los Angeles has endured and
withstood earthquakes, fires, mudslides and some of the worst
rioting in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its periodic setbacks, it is still regarded by many as
the ``city of the future.'' That's one of the reasons Democrats
wanted to come back here for the first time in 40 years, hoping to
focus the nation's attention more on what will be than what has
been.
</P>
<P>
   And the spirit of John Kennedy will be here throughout the next
four days. There is no way to avoid it, not than any Democrat would
want to.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Kennedy family will take center stage here this
week. The president's lone surviving brother, Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D.-Mass., and his only surviving child, Caroline Kennedy
Schlossberg, will speak Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Their very presence will remind us not only of the late
president's life and death, but the death a year ago of his son,
who had captured the heart of America.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who, as a teen-ager, was literally touched by
President Kennedy, will undoubtedly borrow one of Kennedy's themes
in that 1960 convention address, by saying that the Republican
nominees want to hang on to the past while Vice President Al Gore
and running mate Sen. Joseph Lieberman are the best choices for
leading America into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   In that speech 40 years ago, Kennedy felt compelled to talk
about his faith, admitting that many would see nominating a Roman
Catholic ``as a new and hazardous risk _ new, at least since 1928''
when Catholic candidate Al Smith was soundly defeated. In his case,
Kennedy felt that his party had put its faith, not in polls, but in
the American people.
</P>
<P>
   You will hear similar sentiments expressed from the
futuristic-looking stage here this week, as speakers talk about the
historic nature of Lieberman's selection as the first Jew on a
major party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, Gore and Lieberman were greatly influenced by
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore was only 12 years old when Kennedy was nominated
for president, as the son of a Southern senator, he was keenly
aware of the Kennedy administration's effect in breaking down the
barrier of segregation. Later, he would see his father defeated for
re-election primarily because the elder Gore had voted for the
Voting Rights Act of 1966.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, the year Kennedy was assassinated, Lieberman spent time
in the South helping to register blacks to vote. The next year, he
attended his first Democratic National Convention, holding fast to
the spirit of the slain president.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' goal in 1960 was to recapture the White House
after Republicans had held it for eight years. The goal this year
is to keep it after having occupied it for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, they will need the spirit of Kennedy and will have
to convince voters of something that Kennedy said in that
acceptance speech four decades ago: ``For courage _ not complacency
_ is our need today; leadership _ not salesmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
