   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The widely held notion that Al Gore hired on the
overtly religious Sen. Joseph Lieberman as his running mate in
order to wash himself of scandal raises an awkward question. Dare
we ask, ``What scandal?'' Two matters are charged against the vice
president's account, neither amounting to a hill of beans. (Teepen,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ SANDWICH, Mass. _ Listen carefully and tell me
what you hear. Car horns? Power lawn mowers? An '81 Oldsmobile
excreting trash-rap through its open windows? If you answered yes
to any one of the above, or heaven forbid, all of them, then you're
probably an average Joe, living on Main Street, Anywhere, USA. And
you're pretty used to the cacophony we've come to accept as a part
of our daily lives, not even noticing until it turns up missing.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Everyone but the most
hardened partisans have decried the staged, empty, smiley-faced
conventions of the major parties. Commentators of all stripes have
wished out loud for the old days of platform fights, credential
challenges, delegate walkouts and red-meat oratory that lambastes
the bad guys, exalts the good and whips the faithful into
spear-shaking battle readiness. Well, be careful what you wish for.
(Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
