<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS OF 90210 GOING ALL OUT FOR CLINTONS, GORE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Forget the Playboy Mansion. Forget that
$100,000-a-couple brunch on Monday at Barbra's house. And, Al Gore
would beg of you, please forget that little soiree four years ago
out at a suburban Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the money is flowing this week, on top of $3
million already donated to political campaigns from residents of a
single ZIP code: Beverly Hills 90210.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more money here than I ever imagined,'' said K.C.
Sorber, manager at the new Reata on Rodeo Drive, a Tinseltown
spinoff of the popular Fort Worth restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Democratic National Convention is in Los Angeles
this week: to score money. Beverly Hills' money is going to Gore in
a big way.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you hear around here is Gore,'' said Richard Clark of the
elegant Menage a Trois salon, where store workers once included a
Beverly Hills teen-ager named Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody in Beverly Hills ever gave money to a Republican _
they'd never say so.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of convention week and what amounts to a four-day
political rally, Gore needs more money for his presidential
campaign, and Beverly Hills is the best place to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, music executive David Geffen and moviemakers Steven
Spielberg and Jeffrey Katzenberg tossed a little party for Gore and
President Clinton. Among the guests: Whoopi Goldberg, Sarah
McLachlan, Kevin Spacey and even comedian Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   The cheapest ticket: $25,000. The total: $2.8 million for
Democratic campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   That's a movie matinee special compared with Monday's Clinton
brunch at Barbra Streisand's house, where the money from the
$100,000-a-couple event is earmarked for the Bill Clinton
Presidential Library.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Democratic campaigners were quoted in Friday newspapers
grumbling because both Clintons, Bill and New York Senate candidate
Hillary Rodham Clinton, are here raising $18 million this weekend.
The problem isn't that the Clintons are stealing too much attention
here. They're getting too much money.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the most creative protest group this week is a Boston
comedy troupe called Billionaires for Bush (or Gore). Dressed in
tuxedos, gowns and jewels, the fake ``billionaires'' gathered at
The Gap in Santa Monica Sunday night to begin a week of protests
against big money in both parties, to culminate with Tuesday's
satirical Million Billionaire March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel fortunate that billionaires now have so much clout in
American politics,'' said Billionaire character ``Robin U. Blind,''
27, of Boston. Out of costume, she is protester-spokeswoman Dara
Silverman of United for a Fair Economy, a lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made my money the old-fashioned way _ I was born into it,''
the fake billionaire said sarcastically. ``However, I do appreciate
that so many of the new billionaires in music and entertainment are
free to use their money to influence the government, just as in any
other industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in LA, the loony left of California is in full flower.
Other enlightening events this week, as listed in the Orange County
newspaper OC Weekly, include:
</P>
<P>
   _Community Convergence: ``The Direct Action Network prepares you
to protest the Democratic Convention'' with training in
``nonviolent direct action ... legal and jail solidarity, first
aid.''
</P>
<P>
   _People's Convention Los Angeles 2000: ``Jam-packed'' with
workshops covering ``police/prison reform, homelessness, labor
struggles, universal health care, ecology and more; a keynote
address by union activist Sabina Virgo; plus music, comedy, food
and networking.''
</P>
<P>
   _Los Angeles Sweatshop Tours: A ``guided reality tour'' of
garment shops by a bookstore named Libros Revoluci''n.
</P>
<P>
   _Mothers' Convention on Welfare: ``Welfare mothers, community
leaders and activists meet.''
</P>
<P>
   _National Homeless Convention: ``Speeches, panel talks, strategy
sessions, rallies, marches, candlelight vigils, concerts and
more.''
</P>
<P>
   _Celebration of Democracy and March for Workers Rights: ``Bring
instruments, kites and banners.''
</P>
<P>
   _Pre-Protest Kick-Off Party and Rally: ``A healthy dose of
raucous rock from the appropriately titled World Liberators.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters have it all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If they were smart, they wouldn't be out marching. They'd be
throwing fund-raisers in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
