<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1314 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FLOCKHART-WOMEN-TEX     08-14 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOCKHART-WOMEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOCKHART SPEAKS OUT ON WEIGHTY ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKI TURNER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I suppose if I cared how much ``Ally McBeal'' star Calista
Flockhart weighed, I might be inclined to write about it. However,
I don't, so I won't.
</P>
<P>
   If the rumors about Flockhart's alleged love affair with Garry
Shandling kept me up at nights (yawn), I'd probably (not) consider
writing about that, too. But since I've been getting plenty of
sleep, there's no need to waste precious newsprint on that, either.
</P>
<P>
   And, like many other critics, I think ``Ally McBeal'' is in dire
need of artificial resuscitation, but even that isn't enough for me
to pull out the old laptop and rag on some fictional character.
</P>
<P>
   I have, however, dug up some dirt on the 35-year-old Illinois
native. The girl's got heart.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Flockhart traveled to Nairobi, Kenya, to do what
she could to help end violence against women worldwide. This issue
is particularly important in Kenya and other African countries
because one of the most horrific offenses against African girls and
women is female genital mutilation (female circumcision). According
to Amnesty International, at least 32 percent of Kenyan women
between the ages of 4 and 12 have had part of their clitoris
removed by rudimentary circumcisions performed without anesthesia
or proper surgical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does this cultural, yet horrendous, ritualistic act
affect women physically and psychologically, it's also killing
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what ritual it is. If people are dying, then
it's just wrong and it's time to change it,'' Flockhart said
emphatically during a Fox network party in the Hollywood Hills.
``Most of the people in Nairobi, once they become educated, they
acknowledge that this ritual is a mistake. Education is key.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the reasons Flockhart felt compelled to spend part
of her hiatus in a Third World country. The other is very noble,
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first went, I felt a bit presumptuous _ like who am I
to go there _ but as a woman I feel I am entitled to do that. Women
should be helping women all around the world. We all have to stick
together, and we all have to end violence against women in every
way, shape and form. And the only way we're going to do that is to
bond together.''
</P>
<P>
   I must admit that when I approached Flockhart, who was dressed
in a clingy black and silver shirt and pants outfit, I never
imagined our conversation would go beyond that mindless exchange
that usually transpires between celebrities and reporters at these
``command performance'' events. Example:
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: ``So what have you been up to lately?''
</P>
<P>
   Celeb: ``Oh, we've been looking at some things, but I really
can't talk about them now.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: (thinking, Who is this `we'?) ``OK. So can you talk
about the direction your character is taking on the show?''
</P>
<P>
   Celeb: ``Oh, well, she's blah, blah, blah. And blah, blah, blah
(brief exchange of air kisses with some Vince Vaughn look-alike)
blah, blah.''
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, there was none of that between Flockhart and me.
Sure, we talked about ``Ally McBeal'' _ she thinks the show is
still quite good and had nothing but praise for her boss, David E.
Kelley. Also, there was some minor chitchat about how much she
missed Gil Bellows (his Billy character died last season) and about
the downside of fame _ she wouldn't wish ``the bad parts of it'' on
her worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of our conversation, however, was about our recent
experiences in Kenya. We were there at the same time, but had
different agendas. And although Flockhart and I are about as
different as Ally and Ling are, for that moment in time we were as
close as sisters.
</P>
<P>
   There's something surreal that happens to you when you
experience despair and devastation up close and personal. It is
impossible not to be deeply affected by the famine, the AIDS
epidemic and, yes, the female genital mutilation issues in eastern
Africa. Whatever emotional baggage you arrived with definitely
won't clear customs on your way home, because every problem you had
will seem no larger than a pinhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even begin to articulate what it did to me,''
Flockhart said. ``It's probably something I'm never going to be
able to articulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time in the slums of Nairobi, and it put
things into perspective very quickly,'' Flockhart said. ``But what
I really loved most about Africa was the people. They don't have a
lot and they're happy. I didn't know how they were going to react
to me, but they were warm and embraced us. The women of Africa were
especially inspiring. They hold everything together. They have the
wood on their backs, their babies under their arms, and they take
care of and hold the communities together.''
</P>
<P>
   As emotionally draining as that experience was for Flockhart,
however, there were some ``Ally'' moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time talking to the women of the Masai tribe,
and the funniest thing a woman said to me is that she had walked
about three hours to get to the meeting that we were having. She
suddenly got up and said, `I have to get home; I have to beat the
elephant traffic.'''
</P>
<P>
   We all have our priorities.
</P>
<P>
   What I found most appealing about Flockhart, however, is that
she doesn't presume to be anything more than what she is. She's
just an actor, albeit a very good one. She knows the world will not
be a better place if she goes on a
Big Mac binge. She realizes that even if she did expose the truth
about her private life, there would still be starving people all
over the world. And although her fans might have difficulty
separating Flockhart from Ally, neither of them can bring an end to
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   She's done what she can do to affect change. She lent her name
to a worthy cause, and it did make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   She, too, has her priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come to realize that you can really make a difference in
the world if you use your fame in the right way,'' Flockhart said.
``And what I've learned is that as a celebrity, you have some
power, you have some status and people will listen. So if you find
what you're passionate about and talk about it, you can raise
public awareness. It's important to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is. But watch out for those elephants, girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   (Miki Turner is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
