<HEADLINE>
BACK-TO-SCHOOL TRAVEL DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 20)  
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a standing-room-only Amtrak train from New England to New
York, I recently found myself nose to chest with a passenger
wearing a Hosteling International card on a lanyard around his
neck. The lavaliere reminded me that youth migrations are upon us,
as students flock back to college.
</P>
<P>
   Like senior citizens, students are a group that transportation
companies want to attract, hoping that they will fill seats at
times that business travelers do not: Saturdays, for example, or
Tuesday mornings. AirTran, a discount airline with a hip
conversational Web page for youth standby travel,
www.airtran.com/deals, delineates the week with its Best Days to
Fly Standby chart. Its message:
</P>
<P>
   Sunday: No Way
</P>
<P>
   Monday: Way
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: Most Excellent
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Most Excellent
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: Not Quite Excellent
</P>
<P>
   Friday: No Way
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: Somewhat Excellent
</P>
<P>
   AirTran serves 31 cities using DC-9 and 737 jets. Most of its
service is east of the Mississippi. The standby plan, in operation
two years, is simple. Anyone age 18 to 22, student or not, can fly
standby for $47 a segment _ a flight with one takeoff and one
landing _ whenever there are seats, but never on Friday, Sunday or
holidays, including Labor Day weekend and Thanksgiving. Tax and
airport charges of up to $5.50 are extra. A driver's license or
similar official photo ID must be presented, and payment may be
made by cash or credit card. AirTran's current program expires Dec.
14; if it follows last year's pattern, it will resume in January, a
system that avoids what would be a long blackout, according to
Sarah Duffin, a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   There are two drawbacks: Almost all AirTran flights go through
Atlanta, so getting from New York to Chicago is going to take two
segments and quite a while. In addition, standbys cannot check
luggage, so everything must be carried on. AirTran: (800) 247-8726.
</P>
<P>
   Trans World Airlines also has a basic plan, although not for
standbys. It requires putting money up ahead of time. It sells
Travel Pak coupons to students age 14 to 24 that are similar to
senior books. A book, which costs $548, has four coupons, each good
for a one-way flight in the lower 48 states, or from there to
certain Caribbean and Canadian cities; most trips go through St.
Louis. Segment taxes and airport charges are not included in the
price. Two coupons are needed each way for Hawaii or Alaska. The
coupons are good for a year but not after the holder's 25th
birthday; student identification and proof of age are required at
the time of travel. TWA: (800) 221-2000; www.twa.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta Shuttle sells travelers 12 to 24 years old (as well as
those over 62) packs of four coupons for the heavily collegiate
Boston-New York-Washington corridor. The hours of use are
restricted: Travel is permitted only between 10:30 a.m. and 2:30
p.m. or 7:30 to 9:30 p.m. Monday to Friday, or anytime on Saturday
and Sunday. Coupons for the short trips (Logan-La Guardia or La
Guardia-Reagan) cost $232 for four or $413 for eight. For
Logan-Reagan, the cost is $353 for four, $598 for eight. The prices
do not include segment taxes and airport charges. Coupon books are
valid for a year. They may be ordered on the phone, but must be
picked up in person, with proof of age. Delta: (800) 221-1212.
</P>
<P>
   Membership programs involve discounts, but are full of wrinkles
and caveats. American Express offers two types of cards to
students: credit cards, which have no annual fee but require
interest payments on unpaid balances, or charge cards, which cost
$55 a year, on which the balance must be paid in full each month.
American Express has linked up with Continental Airlines to offer
student cardholders four domestic flights a year at prices starting
at $119 for a weekday round trip to a destination up to 1,000 miles
away and rising to $279 for a weekend trip of 4,000aux:dupe miles
or more. An offer of discounts of $100 to $250 on 10 round-trip
tickets a year to international destinations is also included; the
year begins Sept. 6 and runs until Sept. 5, 2001. These fares
require Saturday-night stays and involve blackout dates, and the
tickets must be charged to the card. American Express: (800)
942-2639; on www.americanexpress.com, go to Visit Our Cards Center,
then American Express Student Cards.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank has linked with American Airlines for its Citibank
Platinum Select Card for College Students, a no-fee credit card. In
the first year of membership, a student gets four certificates to
buy domestic round-trip tickets that range from $139 to $299,
depending on distance, plus one companion certificate. There are
also three certificates for discounts for travel elsewhere, a
discount of $100 to $250 on a ticket to Europe, for example. The
process is slow. It takes three weeks to get a card; information on
getting certificates comes four weeks later, and it take two to
three weeks for certificates to be delivered. Saturday-night stays
may be involved, as well as blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   The answers to frequently asked questions on Citibank's Web site
(www.citibank.com) are quite clear, explaining, for example, what
the prime rate is and how it is linked to interest on unpaid
balances. Citibank: (800) 248-4226.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines has a college-student frequent flier program,
United College Plus, that has been sending its members coupons good
for 15 percent off certain tickets. The program is in revision,
according to marketing officials. A Web site for discounted fares
has been folded into the frequent flier site. The program is linked
to a college Visa credit card that earns one mile for every $2
spent. The minimum age is 18; www.collegeplus.com.
</P>
<P>
   Student Advantage, a Boston company, sells a card for $20 a
year, plus $2.50 shipping and handling, that provides a 15 percent
discount on Amtrak and Greyhound walk-up bus fares. College and
high school students, part-time or full-time graduate students and
faculty members are eligible; Mark A. Egan, a spokesman, said that
age was not a qualifier, only enrollment as a student. The card is
sold on campuses, in college bookstores and through a lot of the
merchants it is linked to, including Amtrak and Greyhound.
</P>
<P>
   The Amtrak Student Advantage discount applies to most national
trains. In the Northeast Corridor, it may be used on Acela Regional
trains, but Stephen Taubenkibel, an Amtrak spokesman, said the line
had not decided if it would apply to the Acela Expresses, when they
finally start operating. Some Metroliner trains are also excluded.
There are blackout periods; advance ticketing or reservations may
be required.
</P>
<P>
   At Greyhound, the 15 percent applies to walk-up fares, which are
full fares. Different reductions may be available for buying in
advance or for long circuits on the road, but the 15 percent does
not apply to these. Student Advantage: 280 Summer Street, Boston,
Mass. 02210; (877) 256-4672 or www.studentadvantage.com. Greyhound:
(800) 231-2222; www.greyhound.com. Amtrak: (800) 962-6872;
www.amtrak.com.
</P>
<P>
   For collegians packing all those belongings, Greyhound has a
Student Advantage wrinkle worth a look: 50 percent off package
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
