<HEADER>
A1323 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-TRAPPED-SAILOR     08-14 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TRAPPED-SAILORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN 100 RUSSIAN SAILORS TRAPPED IN SUNKEN NUCLEAR SUBMARINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs to add additional information on the location in lede
graf. This early version will be updated.)  
 By SABRINA TAVERNISE with JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ More than 100 Russian sailors were trapped at the
bottom of the Barents Sea above the Arctic Circle Monday with
little hope of rescue after their nuclear submarine was seriously
damaged in a collision, the commander of Russia's navy said.
</P>
<P>
   The navy said it had begun an effort to rescue the crew using a
compression chamber dropped from a ship above. The rescue effort
was expected to last through the night, but Adm. Vladimir
Kuroyedov, the commander of the Russian navy, said there was little
chance of rescuing the men trapped aboard the submarine Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the efforts being taken, the probability of a
successful outcome from the situation with the Kursk is not very
high,'' Kuroyedov told the ITAR-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
   He did not offer any details of the collision that crippled the
Kursk, which went into service in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are signs of a large and serious collision with an
unknown object,'' Kuroyedov said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a U.S. Naval Intelligence official, the Russian
navy has the capability of rescuing crew members from damaged subs.
They have both deep-diving mini-subs and ships carrying compression
chambers that can hook up to the sunken vessel, allowing crew
members to escape through an emergency exit hatch.
</P>
<P>
   The accident apparently occurred during military exercises,
which were under observation by a U.S. electronic surveillance
ship. U.S. officials said the Russian government has not asked for
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear submarine weighs more than 17,000 metric tons and
carries a crew of 107 to 130. The sub is believed to be as much as
480 feet below the surface. At that depth the pressure would
complicate any rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 ships, including an aircraft carrier, have been
sent to the scene. But the weather there is poor, further
complicating the rescue efforts, Russian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is serious,'' Kuroyedov said. ``All rescue
forces have been directed there.''
</P>
<P>
   The sub was not carrying any nuclear weapons, the Russian navy
said. But the submarine has two atomic reactors and could cause an
environmental disaster in the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Russian navy officials said the crew shut down the reactors
after the accident. The government of Norway, which has a
scientific ship in the area, reported that there has been no sign
of a radioactive leak.
</P>
<P>
   The accident comes at a critical time for Russia's navy, which
has been under strict budget constraints since the fall of the
Soviet Union. As recently as May, the navy owed officers as much as
six months' back wages.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, Russia has slashed its fleet of nuclear-powered
submarines, which now number about 40 in Russia's northern waters,
down from about 120 during the Soviet era, according to Bellona, an
environmental organization based in Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no money for maintaining the existing number of
submarines, nor is there money to dismantle the old ones,'' said
Alexander Pikayev, program director at the Carnegie Moscow Center.
''The risk of radioactive leakage exists. There are more than 100
potential Chernobyls floating out there.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1989 a fire broke out on a Soviet submarine, killing 42
of the 69 sailors aboard. That sub sank to the bottom of the
Norwegian Sea. The survivors escaped before the sub hit the ocean
floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
