<HEADER>
A1329 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-COMIC-BOOK-MOVIES-STA     08-14 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMIC-BOOK-MOVIES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMIC BOOK HEROES: SKYROCKETING FROM PAGE TO SCREEN
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color photo of Michael Keaton in a scene from the 1992
film ``Batman Returns.'') 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By JEREMY GELTZER 
 c.2000 Jeremy Geltzer 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More and more comic-book heroes are springing to life.
</P>
<P>
   Leaping from their pulpy pages right into blockbuster movies,
they're getting a little assist from superstars and super special
effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Men,'' released by Warner Bros., was the first of a
series of films based on Marvel Comics characters. This one strives
to please all audiences with a combo of respected actors _ Patrick
Stewart, Sir Ian McKellen and Academy Award winner Anna Paquin _
and scantily-clad sex symbols like Halle Berry and Rebecca
Romijn-Stamos, together with state-of-the-art effects.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the world of unpredictable box office returns, this
formula would almost guarantee a hit, and Hollywood's major studios
are banking on it. Twelve more superhero-themed films are in
development, including ``The Fantastic Four'' and ``Spider-Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Men'' film heralds the beginning of a new
comic-book-movie era, with 20th Century Fox featuring mutant heroes
of their own. ``The Fantastic Four'' will begin production in
September and aim for release next summer. Co-written by Sam Hamm,
who helped envision the 1989 ``Batman'' film, ``The Fantastic
Four'' promises dazzling high-tech special effects _ a far cry from
Roger Corman's 1992 B-movie version.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, over the last year, Columbia Studios has been
developing a Spider-Man project. Teen heartthrobs Leonardo Di
Caprio and Freddie Prinz Jr. had been considered for the role but
those rumors were squelched when Tobey Maguire (``The Cider House
Rules'') signed in July to play the web slinger.
</P>
<P>
   The Hulk will star in his own vehicle due out in the summer of
2002 from Universal Pictures, and even more Marvel heroes are
waiting in the wings, including Captain America, Iron Man, Silver
Surfer, Dr. Strange and Daredevil.
</P>
<P>
   To filmmakers, the X-Men always had an attractive potential as a
franchise. There was a built-in cult appeal as well as the dynamics
for sequels and the ability to merchandise comic books, games and
action figures. By featuring stellar actors and mesmerizing special
effects, the franchise grew to become a prestige project for Warner
Bros. Marvel Comics, on the rebound from filing for Chapter 11 in
1996, warmly embraced the studio's interest in their properties.
</P>
<P>
   Marvel began building their venerable illustrated empire with
``The Fantastic Four'' in 1961 and followed with ``The X-Men'' in
1963. These two titles created a new type of superhero who
struggled with everyday problems in between battles with
megalomaniacs.
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Fantastic Four'' immediately found a cult of devoted
fans, ``The X-Men'' auditioned a varying cast of characters before
hitting pay dirt in 1991. In a bold marketing move, Marvel packaged
``X-Men 1'' with five different covers. It sold over 8 million
issues to become the industry's best selling comic. A feature film
might have been the logical next step had special effects
technology been able to simulate the characters' signature powers.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing comic book characters to the big screen isn't a new
idea. Hollywood produced their first superhero films less then a
decade after the Golden Age of comics in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after his introduction in ``Action Comics 1'' (June
1938), Superman made his film debut in a series of low budget
movies made by Republic Pictures. Kirk Alyn starred in six pictures
including ``Atom Man vs. Superman'' (1950) before George Reeves
took over the role in 1951. Lacking the technology and the budget
for special effects, Reeves still made a convincing hero, even
though in ``Superman vs. The Mole Men'' (1951), he never even
demonstrated his ability to fly!
</P>
<P>
   Batman, who originally appeared in ``Detective Comics 27'' in
May 1939, burst upon the screen in a campy 1966 film. In addition
to creating a world of surreal gadgets and trendy fashions, this
Batman series also featured journeyman actors such as Cesar Romero
as The Joker and Burgess Meredith as The Penguin. Like ``Superman''
a decade earlier, ``Batman'' successfully spun off to a television
series.
</P>
<P>
   Through the 1970s, comic book characters could only thrive on
the small screen. First appearing in Allstar Comics in 1941, Wonder
Woman, played by Lynda Carter, starred in her own TV series in
1976. Bill Bixby and Lou Ferrigno personified the before-and-after
versions of The Incredible Hulk in a 1977 series. Made-for-TV
movies brought the occult hero Dr. Strange and the patriotic
Captain America from the page to the screen in 1978 and 1979. These
moderately successful exploits led the way for another screen
version of ``Superman.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Christopher Reeves brought the Man of Steel back to the
movie screen with effects far superior to his television
counterpart. Three ``Superman'' sequels were spun off by 1987. Two
years later in 1989, Batman made his move back to the big screen,
shedding the flippant attitude of the TV series for a Gothic edge.
</P>
<P>
   These films helped elevate comic-book-movies from pulpy serials
to more serious cinema with the budget to attract Hollywood's
hottest talent, like Marlon Brando, Gene Hackman and Jack
Nicholson. As in the case of ``Superman,'' ``Batman'' lasted three
sequels, ending in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While Superman, Batman and the company of costumed heroes
presented definitive good guys in past decades, the new wave of
comic book movies presents more tormented figures. Rather than
clean-cut champions, these characters struggle with personal
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Men'' centers on two troubled youths: Rogue, whose touch
will kill any soul, and Wolverine, a man whose tortured past is a
mystery even to him. The Fantastic Four reckon with internal
conflict as well as ruthless villains. Spider-Man, one of Marvel's
most popular heroes, is essentially a geeky teen. He's a figure
everyone can relate to as he battles girl troubles and a crabby
boss along with desperados.
</P>
<P>
   Each generation sees their heroes in a new light.
</P>
<P>
   Superman and Batman grew out of the depression era and Cold War.
They represented the ultimate Nelson Algren story, ``Young Man
Makes Good by Saving the World,'' on the one hand _ and a vision of
the urban underworld on the other.
</P>
<P>
   The recent crop of Gen X superheroes illustrates more complex
protagonists as they struggle with their own psychological demons.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Lane and The Joker were a piece of cake compared to the
troubled teen angst of today. Will Spider-Man get a date? Tune in
next summer.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeremy Geltzer is an Atlanta-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information check out The New York Times
Syndicate web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;  &QL;
</P>
