<HEADER>
A1330 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-ELIZA-DUSHKU-STARBEAT     08-14 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIZA-DUSHKU-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZA DUSHKU, A SWEET TEENAGER WHO LOVES BEING BAD
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color photo of Eliza Dushku as Missy in a scene from
the movie ``Bring It On.'') 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By IAN SPELLING 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eliza Dushku never imagined that she'd one day play a
cheerleader named Missy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never!'' shouts the actress, who co-stars with Kirsten Dunst
in ``Bring It On,'' a pompom parade that will march into theaters
on Aug. 25. ``Never, ever, ever. Nor did my three older brothers,
who are going to have a field day when this movie comes out.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brothers and my best friends were all there through high
school when I promised I'd never be a cheerleader. So they're all
ready to tear me apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences will likely be shocked, too, particularly those
familiar with Dushku's career. The 19-year-old Boston-born actress
usually plays serious, smart and dark characters, and she's best
known for her portrayal of Faith, the bad girl, on ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think of me in characters as the bad girl, but it
goes much deeper than that,'' Dushku says by telephone from the Los
Angeles home she shares with her brother, Nate. ``That's why I
choose to play them, because I try to give these characters more
depth and facets than people tend to give them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think they're more interesting to play. I can't say
they're challenging, because they come easily to me. I don't mean
to say it's easy for me to be bad, but it's something that's in
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that in real life, you can't act out the way evil
characters act out,'' she explains. ``And, by playing them
realistically so that you get different reactions _ compassion,
sympathy _ that's the real challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Missy, in ``Bring It On,'' is far from evil, but she's got an
attitude, something the cliquey cheerleaders, the Toros, at her new
high school, notice instantly when she turns up for a tryout.
However, Torrance (Kirsten Dunst), the squad's captain, recognizes
Missy's talent and wants her on the team.
</P>
<P>
   The real trouble starts, though, when Torrance realizes the
Toros' routines were pilfered from a team at an inner city school
that's about to compete against them for a national cheerleading
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like a lot of fun,'' Dushku says. ``I went in to
read and I loved the director (Peyton Reed), who's hysterical. At
the beginning, Missy is the anti-cheerleader, and I felt like that
when I first went in to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got there and all these girls were in the waiting room.
There were also girls in the courtyard doing flips and stunting. I
was giving everybody dirty looks and then went in for my meeting.
That attitude was apparently just what they were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I signed the contract and went in for the first day, I
realized what I had missed. I was doing a lot of films when I was
growing up, so I couldn't be part of a cheerleading team or have
the kind of female bonding that girls on teams experience. I never
realized cheerleading was so physical or so dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' she adds, ``to discover something totally
new.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene that will likely push Dushku's brothers and pals over
the edge is the one in which Missy first appears in her
cheerleading uniform. As her friends look on from their car, Missy
stands in a doorway posing and laughing. Dushku's face and body
language convey equal parts embarrassment, flirtatiousness and
``this isn't so bad!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the first scenes we shot,'' the actress says.
``I was in wardrobe and it was the first time I put on the uniform.
They did my makeup and said, `Let's put ribbons in your hair.' I
said, `Ribbons! I've never had ribbons in my hair in my entire
life!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside, they had the car with Kirsten and the other kids. I
came through the back of the house, and when they said `Action,' I
walked out there with the camera rolling. I was completely
mortified, completely humiliated, but kind of excited, too, because
no one had ever seen me like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I goofed off and did my little dance. It was fun, and
pieces of that first take are in the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Dushku hopes moviegoers appreciate the scene and that they like
``Bring It On'' as a whole. It's not, she readily admits, going to
win any Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a comedy and it's supposed to be fun,'' she says. `You
could say it's about taking cheerleaders more seriously, but the
film doesn't try to shove that down anyone's throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew going in that it wasn't `American Beauty,' but it's
what it is. It's light. It's a feel-good movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Dushku's next film, ``Soul Survivors,'' is a return to the dark
side. She plays party girl Annabel, one of several college freshman
who may or may not be dead following a horrific car crash. The
red-hot cast of the thriller, which will be released next year,
includes Wes Bentley, Casey Affleck and Melissa Sagemiller
</P>
<P>
   Dushku herself has been red-hot before. She made her film debut
in ``That Night'' (1992), then acted opposite Robert De Niro in
``This Boy's Life'' (1992) before hitting the big time with ``True
Lies'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ''`True Lies' was a blockbuster, a huge jump from my first two
films, which didn't get any recognition at all,'' Dushku says. ``It
was also a $120 million movie with Arnold Schwarzenegger. It was
the most fun a 12-year-old could have.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me cell phones and pagers, and Arnold took my
friends and me to Planet Hollywood in his Hummer. And then, when
the film came out, everyone I knew saw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised Mormon and practically every Mormon in Boston
went and saw an R-rated movie, which just doesn't happen. So it was
huge and for a while `True Lies Girl' was a fun title to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Dushku worked intermittently after ``True Lies,'' forsaking
Hollywood and acting in Boston and high school. When she decided to
pursue acting full-time, she relocated to Los Angeles, went on the
audition trail and landed her role as Faith, butt-kicker
extraordinaire on ``Buffy.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith was meant to appear in just a handful of episodes in
1998-1999, during the show's third season. The character proved so
popular, however, that the show's producers invited Dushku to stick
around. And, much to the satisfaction of Buffyphiles everywhere,
Dushku guest-starred not only in several well-received fourth
season episodes of ``Buffy,'' but also two episodes of the
``Buffy'' spinoff, ``Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience really reacted to her,'' Dushku says. ``Buffy
(Sarah Michelle Gellar) is the blonde heroine who's always doing
the right thing and Faith was just a beautiful thing to throw in
there, not necessarily to stir things up, but just for the
contrast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans, who take the show really seriously, were so open to
having something new, and that was great. I was surprised and I was
delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   Dushku is open to reprising Faith on ``Buffy'' and ``Angel,''
and she'd also be willing to reclaim her ``True Lies Girl'' title
if James Cameron and Schwarzenegger go forward with a ``True Lies''
sequel. Like any 19-year-old, though, Dushku prefers not to think
too long or hard about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goals and my everything change daily,'' she says, laughing.
``It's insane. It freaks me out. My life feels like it's in speed
mode right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking a class at UCLA, just learned how to rock climb and
I have the two movies coming out. So I've got all these things
going crazy inside me.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of these days, it's going to hit me what I want to do for
the long haul, but it's so unclear to me at this point. Talk to me
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting and it's scary. But I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Eliza Dushku in ``Bring It On,''
consult the official web site at www.bringitonmovie.com. And check
out The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;  &QL;
</P>
