<HEADER>
A1331 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-BETTE-MIDLER-STARBEAT     08-14 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTE-MIDLER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL REALITY SERIES OF 2000 IS `BETTE'
</HEADLINE>
 
 EMBARGOED for use by CANADIAN CLIENTS until SEPT. 10.  (Includes a color photo of Bette Midler with cast members from the
new TV series ``Bette.'') 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By KEVIN DICKSON 
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada 
 Not to be published in Canada before Sept. 10. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Unlike Survivor Island, the world of ``Bette'' is actually
inhabited, albeit in a much less exaggerated form, by Midler
herself.
 &HT;    The TV Bette is a brassy stage and screen star with a husband
and a teen-age daughter and, coincidentally, has starred in the
same movies as Midler herself.
 &HT;    And, after watching mere mortals battle against the maelstrom of
the Divine Miss M's TV-alter ego, it's tempting to ask her if
anyone in her life has ever asked to be voted off?
 &HT;    Of course, given Midler's notoriously caustic tongue, it's much
safer to ask just how much the TV diva resembles the real one.
 &HT;    ``Not really,'' Midler answers thoughtfully. ``I love a good
laugh but I'm also a quiet soul and not very social. I work hard
and I try to give back to my community.''
 &HT;    She also admits: ``My behind-the-scenes life is actually quite a
serious one and I wish it were a little sillier. I've been working
for years to lighten up, but it's very hard, especially after you
reach a certain age.''
 &HT;    In light of Midler's lengthy career as a bawdy comic, it's
almost impossible to listen to her speak so earnestly without
expecting her almond eyes to narrow mischievously, the way they do
before she delivers a hilarious punch line. But it appears this
show is going to make fun of our perceptions of a star, not
necessarily give us insight into the private life of one.
 &HT;    Still, in this current sudden-death TV climate, where shows are
cancelled after only two or three weeks on air, the smartest thing
that Midler can do is capitalize on her larger-than-life image.
This way, viewers can skip the acclimatization to a new character,
a hurdle that Geena Davis faces in her own new series, which
ignores her celebrity baggage entirely and puts her into a
quasi-``Sex and The City'' scenario, with not a single Cutthroat
Island joke in sight. Midler knows this is true.
 &HT;    ``We read a lot of pilots,'' Midler explains, ``but this one was
the truest. The others were very typical sitcom situations.''
Midler goes on to explain that this was the only format that she
felt ``captured her voice.''
 &HT;    And what a voice it is. Indeed, the most magical moment in the
first episode of the new CBS show is the one in which her
character, undergoing an age crisis, decides to spice up her act by
incorporating contemporary songs.
 &HT;    She starts by attempting thug-rock-rapper Kid Rock's
unfathomable ``Bawitdaba,'' and ends up turning it into a trademark
Midler boogie-woogie. If the series' writers are able to come up
with other scripted opportunities to showcase Midler's voice,
``Bette'' could be this year's big hit.
 &HT;    One observation Midler is prepared for is that she had to turn
to TV because the film offers have dried up. ``I've had a good run
in films,'' she points out, adding that many of her female
contemporaries ``don't have the kind of jobs they once had.''
 &HT;    Midler has also grown tired of the film development process, or
as she puts it, ``the sturm und drang, the angst of pulling these
movies out of your ... your kishkas,'' she laughs. ``Then you have
to wait for the 25-year-old to give you the green light. I mean,
forget it,'' she laughs again. ``Life is too short.''
 &HT;    Although the native New Yorker will be flying to Los Angeles to
film the first season, she's been promised that if the ratings are
good, the show will move to her home town, ``the center of the
universe,'' in its second season.
 &HT;    Midler plans to be a hands-on star, guiding the show as much as
she can. ``The one thing I would like to avoid is anything
saccharine or overly sentimental. I'd like it to be drier. And I
like the idea of physical comedy because that's something I do. I
also like the idea of using music because that's something I can
bring that most people can't.''
 &HT;    So, with production about to start in Los Angeles, it looks like
there's only one storm cloud on the ebullient star's horizon: She's
been scheduled against ratings powerhouse ``Who Wants To Be A
Millionaire?'' in the United States. ``I'm really hoping for the
best and I'm really going to do my best,'' she says. ``I'm going to
promote, promote, promote, flog, flog, flog.''
 &HT;    She laughs loudly and then her eyes take on that trademark
naughty sparkle.
 &HT;    ``You know what?'' she teases, ``How long can Regis go on? Maybe
he'll be struck by lightning!''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Kevin Dickson is Los Angeles correspondent for TV Guide
Canada) 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada 
