<HEADER>
A1332 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-JENNIFER-LOPEZ-STARBE     08-14 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENNIFER-LOPEZ-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING LA VIDA LOPEZ IS NEVER EASY
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color photo of Jennifer Lopez in ``The Cell.'') 
 ART NOTE: A color cartoon by Vance Lehmkuhl of Jennifer Lopez in
``The Cell'' is available for purchase. 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN 
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you heard the rumor about how Jennifer Lopez insured her
body for a billion dollars?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best rumor I ever read about myself! It's actually
been on the front page of newspapers!'' Lopez says with whooping
laughter. ``It's not true. I haven't even insured it for $50.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, 30, wants to set the record straight on a number of
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   No, she doesn't demand $2,000-a-night hotel rooms. Nor does she
expect instant, perfectly chilled champagne 24 hours a day. And no,
her boyfriend Sean ``Puffy'' Combs didn't forbid her from smooching
it up with Matthew McConaughey in their Valentine's Day 2001 flick,
``The Wedding Planner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All untrue,'' Lopez says with a sigh. ``Puff did come to the
set. He was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds, ``It is uncomfortable for both Puffy and me to watch
each other do love scenes. It's just weird. When he kisses some
girl in his videos, I'm like, `Ewwwwwww.' But as far as being
upset, no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just read another good one,'' she offers. ``that Puff bought
me a house for $4 million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, it's not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life is like a circus act and all I can do is keep
juggling,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez is not a diva _ and she can provide references.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you the numbers of everyone I've ever worked with
who will tell you I'm not a pain,'' Lopez says. ``People have a
totally happy experience with me. I get along with everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent D'Onofrio, who stars with her in ``The Cell'' (opening
August 18), confirms this: ``Jennifer is hands down an actress. She
never held anyone up on this movie. She never acted out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the flesh, Lopez is quieter and smaller than you would
expect, with big brown saucer eyes, and she asserts she doesn't
usually rely on anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm East Coast. I think there's a different mentality,'' she
says. ``I operate from the base of `You've got to take care of
yourself.'''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Cell,'' she plays a child-therapist who helps invent a
mental transferral system where you can go into the minds of coma
patients. She must enter the brain matter of a psycho serial
killer, played by D'Onofrio, to save his last victim.
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by new talent Tarsem, is clearly one of the
most edgy and disturbing movies of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read it, I thought it had that `Silence of the Lambs'
feel to it and you could go places in the dream sequences,'' Lopez
says. ``I loved the freaky visuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez actually went to a therapist to research the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really interesting. I started telling this therapist
about a problem I had pretty much figured out. And she was like,
`No you haven't figured it out.' It was actually very helpful to go
into one's own head.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez always imagined a different life.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up poor as a Puerto Rican living in the Bronx. Her
escape was going to the movies. Lopez grew up idolizing Barbra
Streisand, Bette Midler and anyone else who could carry a show
tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to grow up to be Anita from `West Side Story,''' she
says. ``She wasn't a wimp like that helpless Maria.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987 after graduating from high school, the non-wimpy Lopez
got a job with a European theater group that sang Broadway hits. By
1990, she came back to the States where she was hired as one of the
Fly Girls on TV's ``In Living Color.''
</P>
<P>
   Movies like ``My Family,'' (1995) ``Money Train,'' (1995)
``Jack,'' (1996) ``Selena,'' (1997) ``Anaconda,'' (1997) ``Blood
and Wine,'' (1997) ``U Turn'' (1997) and ``Out of Sight'' (1998)
followed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest, ``The Wedding Planner,'' a romantic comedy with
McConaughey, is in the can. She has also wrapped the drama ``Angel
Eyes'' set for 2001 release.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a second Jennifer Lopez album is due out this
October. She's not worried if it doesn't go double platinum like
``On the Six,'' her mega-successful debut CD.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to touch people with this new music. It's not
about selling more records. It's about having something to really
say through the music. And this is a personal album,'' she
divulges. ``There are many songs about love. I think of it as the
soundtrack to my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask her about her life outside her career, like marriage, and
she shrugs evasively.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's a private thing. Puffy and I have a
relationship right now and we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez divorced her first husband, model and waiter Ojani Noa, in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   She says the media attention hurt their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to really become famous when I had first gotten
married. I had this responsibility and then I lost my anonymity.
And the press was making up stories about me and my husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't deal with it. He was just a regular guy. I saw
that it was hurting him and bothering him, which broke my heart.
All these totally fabricated stories about how we were not getting
along came out barely a month after we were married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to explain it to him, and even I couldn't understand
it. I wanted to sue or boycott the media,'' she says. ``It was
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe too crazy. Shortly after she split with her husband, Lopez
started dating Puffy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's easier for me to be involved with a public
figure. Puffy understands everything. He helps me cope. He is as
busy as I am. But then we can come together.''
</P>
<P>
   They're not your average couple.
</P>
<P>
   Take their biggest fight. He gets mad that she won't use his
bodyguards to go to the mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `I don't care! I'm going out! If people recognize me,
it's OK,'' she declares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to walk around with a bodyguard,'' she insists.
``I like to be a normal person and do my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Jennifer Lopez in ``The Cell,''
consult the official web site at www.cellmovie.com. And check out
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
