 ART NOTE: Photos and cartoons are available by computer on NewsCom.
For more information phone NYT sales representative Debra Weydert
at 732-390-4480.
<TEXT>
<P>
   (All stories moved in the ``e'' entertainment file.)
</P>
<P>
   LIVING LA VIDA LOPEZ IS NEVER EASY
</P>
<P>
   JENNIFER-LOPEZ-STARBEAT _ Jennifer Lopez, who just turned 30,
says her life is like a circus act. No wonder. She has recently
wrapped three movies, one ``The Cell'' opening Aug. 18, and a new,
very personal album, due out in October. In ``The Cell,'' she plays
a child therapist who helps invent a way to go into the minds of
coma patients. And the album is ``about having something to really
say through new music.'' What's next for this talented young Puerto
Rican from the Bronx? ``All I can do is keep juggling,'' she
exclaims. By Cindy Pearlman. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   THE REAL REALITY SERIES OF 2000 IS `BETTE'
</P>
<P>
   BETTE-MIDLER-STARBEAT _ The new CBS fall show ``Bette,''
starring, of course, Bette Midler, is geared more to making fun of
everyone's perceptions of a star, rather than offering insight into
the private life of one. But it capitalizes on her larger-than-life
image. Contrary to popular assumption, Midler's behind-the-scenes
life is actually quite a serious one. ``I wish it were a little
sillier,'' she admits. ``I've been working for years to lighten
up!'' By Kevin Dickson of TV Guide Canada. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ELIZA DUSHKU, A SWEET TEENAGER WHO LOVES BEING BAD
</P>
<P>
   ELIZA-DUSHKU-STARBEAT _ Eliza Dushku, 19, who portrays bad girl
Faith in TV's ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' never imagined she'd
one day play a cheerleader. Never! ``In high school I promised I'd
never be a cheerleader,'' she asserts. But once she started work in
``Bring It On,'' she realized what she had missed. ``I never had
the kind of female bonding that girls on teams experience, nor did
I realize cheerleading was so physical or so dangerous,'' she
confesses. ``It was awesome to discover something so totally new.''
The movie opens Aug. 25. By Ian Spelling. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMIC BOOK HEROES: SKYROCKETING FROM PAGE TO SCREEN
</P>
<P>
   COMIC-BOOK-MOVIES-STARBEAT _ More and more comic-book heroes are
springing to life on the big screen. But unlike their pioneer
counterparts, Batman and The X Men, with all their powers, can also
count on a little assistance from dazzling special effects and
glittering superstars. By Jeremy Geltzer. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FACE VALUE: Jennifer Lopez
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonist Vance Lehmkuhl offers his offbeat take on Jennifer
Lopez as she appears in the upcoming film ``The Cell.''
</P>
