   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IRS-ABUSE (Undated) _ Two years ago, after hearings on suspected
abuse of taxpayers, Congress passed a law to crack down on
perceived abuses by IRS workers. But of the first 830 complaints
made under the new law, not one complaint of taxpayer harassment
was upheld, IRS data released by the Congressional Joint Committee
on Taxation shows. The IRS did fire four of its 16,000 auditors for
improperly threatening to audit a taxpayer. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TURKEY-ARCHEO (Sardis, Turkey) _ In the ruins of Sardis,
capital of the Lydians of yore, archaeologists are striving to
separate fact from legend, seeking glimpses of what it meant in
antiquity to be ``rich as Croesus.'' But they are also finding much
more: monumental remains of the passage of time and fortune for a
major city under subsequent Persian, Greek, Roman and Byzantine
rule. Here, on the slopes of a broad river valley about 50 miles
inland from the Aegean Sea, in what is now western Turkey but was
then known as Asia Minor, King Croesus reigned in the sixth century
B.C. over the flourishing empire of Lydia. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT5,6.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEGATIVE-ATTITUDE (Undated) _ Dr. Barbara Held has had just
about enough of accentuating the positive and eliminating the
negative. She does not want to cheer up, look on the bright side or
let a smile be her umbrella. And she is not planning to put a
smiley face sticker on her car bumper any time soon. In fact, Held
views such activities as rather worrisome. She is one of a small
band of psychologists who believe their profession _ and indeed
America as a whole _ has succumbed to an ethos of unrelenting
positivity. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-JEWISH-MEMORIALS (Berlin) _ The idea seemed simple,
pleasing in its balance: Bring the German capital back to Berlin 55
years after the fall of Hitler's Reich while marking that return
with several major cultural projects commemorating, in different
ways, the Holocaust and Germany's lost Jews. But almost a year
after the government returned, these projects are plagued by delays
and confusion. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUITIES-COMMISSION (Undated) _ Last week, the White House
unexpectedly touched off a furor in the rarefied world of
archeology when it announced President Clinton's intention to
appoint Shelby White, a wealthy collector of antiquities, to a seat
on the government committee formed to help combat the illicit
international trade in antiquities. By William H. Honan.
</P>
