<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EYMAN-0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Journey to Mars, right from your reading chair
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Mars looks like New Mexico, except with
rocks instead of cactus.
</P>
<P>
   I know that because of the National Geographic's new trade
paperback of ``Mars: Uncovering the Secrets of the Red Planet.''
It's a collection of NASA photographs of images deriving from the
Pathfinder Mission, but what makes the book a keeper are the images
that have been processed for 3-D.
</P>
<P>
   The book includes several pair of 3-D glasses, so now you can
get the same effect as if you had actually traveled to Mars ... or
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Before Uncle Vanya ...
</P>
<P>
   Somehow or another, I missed the hardcover edition of ``The
Undiscovered Chekhov `` when it came out last year, but I have no
intention of slighting the paperback (7 Stories is the publisher).
The volume translates 43 (!) stories, 41 of which had never been
published in English. All of the work derives from the early years
of Chekhov's writing career, before age and illness settled him
into the ruefully gentle pessimism that we know so well from his
plays and later stories.
</P>
<P>
   This Chekhov is brighter, more experimental and certainly more
energetic _ one might even say zippier, although his use of
language, or what seems to be his use of language in Peter
Constantine's translations _ still seems the quietly perfect work
of a young master.
</P>
<P>
   Lovers of Chekhov, or of Russian literature, will certainly want
to have this volume.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com, among the best of the Web's literary/cultural sites,
is publishing yet another anthology of its best work. ``Salon
Wanderlust: Real Life Tales of Adventure and Romance,'' will
showcase writers like Isabel Allende, Po Bronson and Jan Morris.
Villard will publish.
</P>
<P>
   Heading in the other direction, James Ellroy will publish a
collection of pieces that originally appeared in GQ on
Contentville.com. The deal was for online rights only, with Ellroy
reserving rights to a print collection.
</P>
<P>
   Contentville.com agreed to pay Ellroy an advance as well as a
royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Quote Unquote ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nervous work. The state you need to write in is the state
that others are paying large sums to get rid of.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Hazzard
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
