<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1355 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BOOKS-SHAKESPEARE0815     08-14 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SHAKESPEARE0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Shakespeare biography written for the general audience
 &HT;    ``WILLIAM SHAKESPEARE: The Man Behindthe Genius,'' by Anthony
Holden. Little, Brown; 367 pages; $29.95.
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Anthony Holden dispenses with the
primary idiocy right out of the box, as he confidently asserts that
no one but Shakespeare wrote Shakespeare's plays.
</P>
<P>
   To imagine that the tight little world of Elizabethan theater _
300 people? 500 people? _ would lovingly embrace someone they
couldn't have helped knowing was a front without enthusiastically
blowing his cover is to have no concept of what vicious, backbiting
spoilsports writers really are.
</P>
<P>
   If Shakespeare was a fraud, then Ben Jonson's moving
remembrances were lies, and the friends who lovingly gathered their
old friend's manuscripts and published them seven years after his
death were merely engaged in an expensive and pointless charade
calculated to throw all but cranky eccentrics off the track.
</P>
<P>
   It won't make any difference, of course; for a conspiracy
theorist, logic is just the most insidious part of a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, here is a sprightly biography of Shakespeare
written for a general audience. Its author has previously written
biographies of Olivier, Tchaikovsky, Prince Charles and that
ubiquitous subject for all U.K. journalists, Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Holden is sensible and occasionally amusing as he punctures the
premises of the anti-Stratfordians. The conspiracy theorists have
always held that Shakespeare couldn't have written the plays
because he couldn't have done the vast amounts of traveling
necessary to investigate the locales.
</P>
<P>
   Holden points out that he managed to set two plays in Venice
without ever mentioning that the streets were full of water.
</P>
<P>
   Holden takes a couple of things as given that, last time I
checked, were still suppositional _ the extent of Shakespeare's
contributions to plays by other writers, and the possibility of
some manuscript pages from a play called ``Sir Thomas More'' being
in his hand. Aside from the similarity in handwriting to his
signatures, there is the teasingly interesting misspelling of
silence as ``scilens'' _ the same eccentric spelling found in the
speech prefixes for Justice Silence in an early folio of ``Henry
IV, Part 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden also gives surprising credence to the poet laureate
William Davenant's claim that Shakespeare was not merely his
godfather but his father. (George Bernard Shaw believed that
Davenant's mother Jeannette, a reputedly beautiful woman, was the
Dark Lady of the sonnets.)
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Holden emphasizes Shakespeare's sophistication _
shrewdly able to plunge into the mind of every one of his
characters, but also a man who lived in the world.
</P>
<P>
   While writing an average of two plays a year, Shakespeare was
also juggling a wife, mistresses, a large circle of friends and
co-workers, and amassing an estate that included a piece of the
Globe theater, real estate ventures in London and Stratford and a
little money-lending on the side.
</P>
<P>
   By around 1599, Shakespeare would have been earning about 200
pounds a year from the theater alone; by the time he turned 40,
Shakespeare could have afforded to retire completely, but he kept
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Holden points out how assiduously Shakespeare stole plots, but
``as always with Shakespeare, close comparison of the text and its
sources show his pillaging to be the prelude to layer upon layer of
miraculous enlargement, as often mundane details are reworked into
far more subtle, ingenious effects in a far grander scheme ... this
is the hallmark of the genius drily noted by T.S. Eliot: `Immature
poets imitate; mature poets steal.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are some amusing contributions from Peter O'Toole, a
friend of the author, who doesn't believe the oft-repeated line
about Shakespeare being a mediocre actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't get billing as a tragedian with the King's Men
unless you could act,'' says O'Toole, who has a hunch Shakespeare
played Mercutio.
</P>
<P>
   Where Holden's book falls down is in the spaces between the
facts. The gaps in the historical record in Shakespeare's life _
which are by no means extreme, by the way; we know more about him
than any other Elizabethan writer save Ben Jonson _ are not
problems for a biographer as much as opportunities: the equivalent
of a musician getting a chance to improvise a solo on themes set
out in a symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where a creative mind can show off, as with Anthony
Burgess' and Robert Payne's biographies from 25 years ago. But
Holden lacks imagination. He can dutifully narrate, make the
connections between the historical record and the plays, but he
can't entrance us with his own particular take on these people in
their time.
</P>
<P>
   This means that Holden never makes a fool out of himself, as
writers who put more of an emphasis on empathetic leaps than
research are wont to do, but it also means his Shakespeare doesn't
dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Stratford man did nothing else, he dazzled.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: scotteyman(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
