<HEADER>
A1373 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-RIBOSOME-NYT     08-14 0263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RIBOSOME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WAY TO BUILD A BETTER ANTIBIOTIC
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists at Yale, led by Dr. Thomas A. Steitz, a professor of
molecular biophysics and biochemistry, have figured out the
three-dimensional structure of a ribosome, a part in cells that
constructs proteins.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, reported in the current issue of Science, cast
insight into the evolution of the very earliest life on earth and
offer a new avenue of research for developing antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   A ribosome consists of two parts: One reads protein-building
instructions transcribed from the cell's DNA and encoded in strands
of ribonucleic acid, or RNA; the other builds the proteins. The
Yale researchers looked at the protein-building part of the
ribosome of a bacterium found in the Dead Sea. However, ribosomes
work similarly in almost all creatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you understand how one ribosome works, you understand how
all ribosomes in all cells work,'' Steitz said.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed picture, showing the positions of 100,000 atoms,
should aid drug researchers in designing antibiotics that latch
onto and foul up the ribosomes of attacking bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures also show that the active parts of the ribosome
structure are made of RNA, seen in gray, and not proteins, seen in
yellow. That supports the theory that the earliest life was based
solely on RNA, without proteins.
</P>
<P>
   In a modern-day cell, the main role of RNA is to transcribe
protein-making instructions from DNA, located in the nucleus, to
the ribosomes, located in the outer part of the cell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1375 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-RADIO-TELESCOPE-N     08-14 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RADIO-TELESCOPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 NATIONS TO BUILD A GIANT TELESCOPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astronomers have signed an agreement to build a radio telescope
that would, in effect, be 100 times as large as today's largest.
</P>
<P>
   The plans were announced on Aug. 2 by scientists from 10
countries at the International Astronomical Union General Assembly
in Britain. They said they hoped to come up with a design and
location for the telescope by 2005 and to finish construction by
2015.
</P>
<P>
   The installation is likely to consist of 10 individual radio
telescopes spread over thousands of miles but connected by
computers and high-speed data links. The resulting system, called
the Square Kilometer Array, because it will have a collecting area
measuring one square kilometer, or the equivalent of nine football
fields, would act as one enormous telescope.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the installation sprang from astronomers' desire to
study faint emissions from hydrogen gas structures formed soon
after the Big Bang, the theorized explosion that gave birth to the
universe. The scientists said they hoped it would help answer the
most fundamental questions about the universe, like how it took
shape and its fate.
</P>
<P>
   Radio telescopes have a big advantage over optical telescopes
because they can pick up radio waves despite cosmic dust, which
sometimes obscures light from galaxies and regions where stars are
forming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the radio telescopes in use today were designed in the
'60s and '70s before today's technological advances,'' said Dr.
Seth Shostak of the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence, a
privately financed effort to detect evidence of life elsewhere in
the universe, one of the groups that will use the telescope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
