<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1379 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER15-COX     08-14 2284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bye, bye Clintonn
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as he said to expect no surprises from his final address as
his party's leader, President Clinton hinted that tonight's speech
will not be tame. The address, the main event on opening night of
the Democratic National Convention, will include a partisan rebuke
of Republican claims that Clinton deserves little credit for the
economy, aides said. ``I think Republicans may have had a little
amnesia about where things stood in 1992. The president will be
happy to remind people about that,'' said White House chief of
staff John Podesta. Clinton will also spend equal time praising Al
Gore's qualifications as a partner in prosperity. Soon after, he
will leave town. The president knows ``it's his moment to get off
the stage and let someone else get on the stage and do the job,''
Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
   HELLO HILLARY
</P>
<P>
   As her husband prepares for his political farewell to the party
faithful today, Hillary Clinton is making her debut at the
Democratic convention as the first family's new candidate. The
first lady's prime-time, 10-minute address to the convention will
precede President Clinton's appearance _ a to-die-for spot for any
fledgling candidate. She is running for the U.S. Senate from New
York. The first lady declined to talk about the speech saying,
``I've got to go work on it.'' But she did say she would talk about
the progress made over the last eight years and ``make the case
that Al Gore and Joe Lieberman are the leaders for the 21st
Century.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW ABOUT A JUST LITTLE HUMOR?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, preparing the most important speech of his life, said
he is cramming it with detailed proposals for the future and
counting on the voters to welcome that approach because ``the
people of the country want the facts. People who want the facts
will get them in this speech. If you want a show without facts
then, you know, that can be found somewhere else,'' Gore said. The
vice president, who is on the campaign trail headed toward the
convention where he will accept his party's nomination Thursday
night, said he was writing the speech himself, spelling out his
plans on tax cuts and Social Security. ``It is a gamble but it
doesn't worry me because I think in the final analysis ... people
deserve to know what the specifics are so they can judge for
themselves,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   OCCIDENTS HAPPEN
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of activists angered by an oil company's plans to drill
near a Colombian Indian reserve and Al Gore's ties to that company
marched today to the site of the Democratic convention.
Demonstrators carried a series of giant papier mache puppets, some
of them an unflattering rendering of Gore. Others carried a banner
reading, ``Mother Earth Rocks, Corporate Greed Sucks.'' During his
campaign, Gore has been dogged by protesters upset about his
connection to Occidental Petroleum Corp. They have urged him to
divest his family of the stock, worth as much as $500,000, which
was among the assets Gore inherited from his father who died last
December. Later today, activists plan a march by ``Billionaires for
Bush (or Gore).'' So far, the protests at the convention have been
raucous, but largely peaceful. A 12-foot-tall fence separates the
official protest area from the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   OOPS, BUSTED!
</P>
<P>
   As the Democrats open their convention today, George W. Bush
will be at his ranch in Texas where he will spend several days in
strategy and policy meetings preparing for the fall campaign. Bush
suspended active campaigning yesterday to lie low for the
convention and added that he may not watch or listen to it. ``I
already know what they are going to say about me. They've been
saying it for the last six months. It's predictable,'' Bush said.
Bush noted that he would not watch the convention, in part, because
he does not have cable TV. When reporters suggested that he could
get parts of it on regular television and perhaps radio, Bush said:
``You've caught me. I don't know if I'll watch it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   SO MUCH FOR THE BOUNCE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has canceled out George W. Bush's post-convention bounce
and almost erased his lead in the presidential race, according to a
new Reuters/Zogby poll published today. The poll of 1,005 likely
voters found Bush leading the vice president 43 percent to 40
percent. Green Party candidate Ralph Nader polled 7 percent and Pat
Buchanan of the Reform Party 2 percent. With a margin of error of
plus or minus 3.2 percent, the result was a statistical dead heat.
One week ago, in the aftermath of the Republican National
Convention, Bush led Gore by 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   OF COURSE HE'S NOT BOTHERED
</P>
<P>
   As if he did not have enough problems, embattled Reform Party
faction presidential candidate Pat Buchanan today fou chapter of
the group that once polarized American society with its allegations
of communist infiltration into the highest levels of government.
Its founder had even called President Dwight D. Eisenhower a
conscious agent of the communist conspiracy. Said Buchanan: ``I am
not bothered. My choice of Ezola Foster is as good a thing
politically as anything I have ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   A MILLION-DOLLAR PICK
</P>
<P>
   John Hagelin, the other Reform Party nominee, has picked Nat
Goldhaber, a successful Silicon Valley entrepreneur, as his running
mate. Goldhaber, who recently sold his direct-marketing Web firm,
Cybergold Inc., said he was unconcerned about the outcome of the
fight within the Party about which faction can rightfully claim the
$12.5 million in federal matching funds. ``$12.5 million will not
make or break the Reform Party,'' he said. Goldhaber declined to
disclose his net worth other than to say party founder Ross Perot
has just ``a wee bit more than I do.'' He added that his attorneys
were trying to determine how much of his wealth he can spend on the
campaign. He reportedly sold his company for $142 million.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S NOT INFLUENCE PEDDLING; IT'S GOODWILL SOWING ...
</P>
<P>
   Oil, gas and mining interests are throwing a blues bash for Rep.
John Dingell. Heavy-hitters Texaco and Bristol-Myers Squibb are
among 24 companies picking up the tab for an extravagant Mardi
Gras-like celebration for Louisiana Sen. John Breaux. And insurance
giant Transamerica is opening its corporate suite for Rep. Charles
Rangel. These events go far beyond typical convention-week soirees
-- each is aimed at the Democrat who would take over a key
committee if the party manages to regain control of Congress in the
November elections, and each is underwritten by special interests
whose business is affected by those committees. Said Larry
Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive Politics
: ``If the Democrats retake control of Congress, then everyone will
be their friend. But being their friend before they take control
probably wins you a special place in their heart.'' But the chief
of staff for Rangel (D-N.Y.) who stands to take control of the
House Ways and Means Committee, said the lawmaker is being honored
``because of the leadership he provides in the Congress,'' not
because he is in line to take over a top committee.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WAS THAT ABOUT LIBERAL BIAS?
</P>
<P>
   Television networks have given George W. Bush more favorable
coverage than Al Gore, both during the GOP convention and
throughout the presidential race, a new analysis finds. The study,
released today by the Center for Media and Public Affairs, examined
72 stories that aired during the Republican National Convention on
the ABC, CBS and NBC evening news. It found that 60 percent of
people quoted in stories praised Bush's policies, political skills
or personal character, while 80 percent of people quoted criticized
Gore. The study also looked at coverage during the primaries, and
found 53 percent of the comments about Bush positive, compared with
40 percent of comments about Gore. This is the inverse of 1992 and
1996, when President Clinton received much more positive coverage
than his opponents, the center said.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S NOT A CONVENTION WITHOUT THE KENNEDYS
</P>
<P>
   Democrats could convene in Los Angeles without Kennedys, but it
would not seem right. Democrats have celebrated Kennedy triumphs
and grieved over Kennedy tragedies _ and pained over Kennedy
misadventures _ at every convention since then. Now, 10 conventions
after John F. Kennedy's triumph in Los Angeles, the torch passes to
his determinedly private and non-political Caroline Kennedy
Schlossberg, a lawyer and co-author of books on privacy and the
Bill of Rights. She will be given eight prime-time minutes Tuesday
night to speak and introduce her uncle, Sen. Edward Kennedy, who
will also speak. Other Kennedys have been given brief roles in the
convention's daytime sessions. Rep. Patrick Kennedy (D-R.I.), son
of Edward, had a moment in today's opening session. Maryland Lt.
Gov. Kathleen Townsend Kennedy, daughter of Ethel and Robert
Kennedy, also is down for a moment _- less than a minute -- Tueaday
afternoon. And Robert Kennedy Jr. speaks tomorrow afternoon about
his heartfelt interest, the environment.
</P>
<P>
   NOT THE SAME OLD SONG AND DANCE
</P>
<P>
   Gary Smith, who has served as the executive producer for the
Democratic conventions since 1988, has identified the basic problem
wih the event this year: ``You're taking four days to do what could
be done in one.'' He's doing what he can to put some life in the
party: tonight's finale, following President Clinton's speech, will
be `76 Trombones,' performed by the cast of Broadway's revival of
`The Music Man.' Smith is also gleeful over locating a 1928
recording of Al Gore Sr. playing the fiddle, which will be heard
Thursday when the younger Gore accepts the presidential nomination.
But he has made a rather risky decision: to play ``Mambo No. 5'' --
a song about womanizing -- in the convention hall to keep up
delegates' enthusiasm between speeches. Since one of the lines in
the song is `A little bit of Monica' -- obviously something the
Democrats don't want to use -- the lyrics have been rewritten with
names of states instead of names of women.
</P>
<P>
   A DELEGATE SITUATION
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Alaska delegates are planning to withhold their
support for Al Gore until he listens to their concerns about the
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge. The Alaska Democratic Party
endorses responsible development of the vast oil reserves in the
region, but the National Democratic platform opposes any drilling.
Because Alaska's electoral votes seem solidly in the GOP column,
the faction sees a threat to deny Gore a unanimous nomination as
the only way to get his attention. Said Alaska AFL-CIO head Mano
Frey: ``I don't expect to change his mind as far as (the wildlife
refuge), but he needs to know the importance of what that means.''
The Gore campaign said it was unaware of Frey's plan.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY MICE MEET CITY MICE
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee delegates have been told not to wear any ``Road Kill''
T-shirts at this week's convention. The instructions illustrates
the delicate balancing act they face this week: how to testify
about Gore's small-town and rural roots without making the state
look backwoods. ``They told us we're going to be on national TV, so
we need to show Tennessee pride and respect,'' said Nashville
attorney Mario Ramos. The ``road kill'' advice refers to a
Tennessee law that allows residents to ``salvage road kill for home
cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   LOVING THE MONEY BUT HATING THE BUNNY
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats praised Rep. Loretta Sanchez (D-Calif.) for
moving her Hispanic Unity fund-raiser, and Playboy founder Hugh
Hefner called the uproar ``ludicrous and hypocritical,'' the New
York Times reports today that in the last decade, Hefner and
daughter, Christie Hefner, Playboy's CEO, have given about $95,000
to Democratic candidates and committees, with at least $8,000 going
to the Clinton and Gore campaigns. The contributions reflect the
Hefners' socially liberal ideology, with a large amount going to
Democratic women, including Hillary Clinton's Senate campaign.
Incidentally, the event has been moved to B.B. King' Universal
Studios' CityWalk, even though King himself is a GOPer who backs
George W. Bush. And this morning, Sanchez withdrew herself as a
convention speaker because she said the publicity generated was
taking away from ``what we really have to do here at the
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   DAUGHTERS OUT FRONT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's daughters, Karenna Gore Schiff and Kristin Gore, will
serve as their family's chief ambassadors until he and and wife
Tipper arrive at the convention lateke her political debut when she
introduces Tipper on Thursday night. Karenna said she hasn't ruled
out a possible run for office in the future. ``I look forward to
when I have more people in my generation running, but I don't think
we should all come from the same family, so Kristin and I are
campaigning for some fresh blood,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY, TAKE THREE
</P>
<P>
   Citing people who have worked with ex-Sen. Bill Bradley, the
Trenton Times reports that the one-time Democratic presidential
candidate said he knows his speech at the convention Tuesday has to
be a good one, as he is acutely aware that he can ill afford a
third prime time disaster in the spotlight of a national
convention. Bradley is haunted by dismal performances at two
previous national conventions, and the immediate goal of his speech
is to win favorable comparisons to the one Sen. John McCain
delivered two weeks ago in support of George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Saeed Ahmed
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
