<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NEW-ORLEANS-ARMSTRONG     08-14 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ORLEANS-ARMSTRONG-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING FOR SATCHMO'S ROOTS IN THE CITY THAT SPAWNED HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ In this not-quite-centennial year of Louis
Armstrong, there may not be a better way to see this city than
through the eyes of his latest and perhaps most obsessive
biographer, Tad Jones, a 48-year-old music writer and
fifth-generation New Orleanian. It is a ghostly business, conjuring
a legendary life and vanished landmarks from yellowed archives,
shuttered ruins and renamed streets, but a labor of love for Jones,
who is deep into the most exhaustive excavation yet of Armstrong's
hometown roots and the influences that made him, in the reverent
words of Bing Crosby, ``the beginning and the end of music in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   In his dozen years of research and writing so far _ with no
publication date set _ Jones, co-author of an earlier study of New
Orleans music, has dug deep into local property archives to trace
Armstrong's slave ancestry back to 1818. He has haunted Armstrong's
streets, where music once spilled from every saloon, where young
Louis once dipped his face in flour and won an amateur contest in
whiteface, and where he worked for the Karnofsky family, who gave
the future trumpeter his first gig tooting a tin horn on their junk
wagon.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for any commemorative plaques. There are none to
mark these and other landmarks, a lapse that Jones is trying to
remedy with appeals to various officials. Indeed in many cases
there is no place to hang a plaque: The sites have vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's very birth was long shrouded in myth, one fostered
by Satchmo himself: that he was born on July 4, 1900. But in a
baptismal registry Jones found proof that Armstrong was born on the
more prosaic Aug. 4, 1901, which has stretched out the centennial
commemorations being held from here to Corona, Queens, where
Armstrong died at home in 1971 when he was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Just blocks from where young Louis grew up here, in a long since
demolished row of red brick rooming houses near today's Loyola
Avenue and Perdido Street, Jones pointed out a boxy green glass
office building at 234 Loyola. On this site in the 1870s, Jones
said, his own great-grandfather Jacinto Buno ran a saloon and
restaurant. In 1907 his family sold the property to the Colored
Knights of Pythias, which put up a 13-story headquarters with
offices, theater, dance hall, movie house and roof garden. It was
the first such elaborate black enterprise in the South, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly it captivated young Louis: ``He's 7 years old, waiting
to go up,'' Jones said, savoring the imagined scene. In 1913, at
age 11, he was remanded to the Colored Waifs' Home for Boys for
firing a blank pistol and disturbing the peace. But before his
release a year and a half later, Armstrong returned to the Pythias
hall as a member of the orphans' orchestra to play a concert. Years
later, as an accomplished jazzman in 1921, Armstrong was playing
the hall's roof garden.
</P>
<P>
   One block away toward the Mississippi River, South Rampart
Street bears its own Armstrong imprints. It is a street still lined
with the frames of old pawnshops and secondhand stores where blacks
barred from white Canal Street shopped in Jewish markets and drank
in Sicilian bars. Today its parking lots are ghostly markers of the
Armstrong legend _ one was once home to the Astoria Hotel, others
to the Pelican Saloon and other honky-tonks where Armstrong and Kid
Ory on trombone and Joe Oliver on trumpet played.
</P>
<P>
   It was the melange of musical and cultural influences that
fostered Armstrong's humanitarianism, Jones suggested. For all the
deprivation, poverty and discrimination he endured, Armstrong
somehow emerged with singular ebullience, although among friends he
could be caustic about the evils of segregationist America.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the confluence of all this music, he was taking his
genius and synthesizing it, from blues to gospel, ragtime and
opera,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out the easy-to-miss shuttered wood and red brick
shell on South Rampart Street, all that remains of the Iroquois
Theater, built in 1912. In his memoirs Armstrong told of watching
movies there for a nickel and of his triumph in the amateur contest
where he performed in whiteface.
</P>
<P>
   A few doors down, at 427 South Rampart, Jones stopped at a small
building that once housed the secondhand shop of the Karnofsky
family, peddlers whose welcoming home and payroll sustained young
Louis in hard times. ``You name it, the Karnofskys sold it,'' Jones
said. In 1920 the father, Morris Karnofsky, opened a record shop
where the 19-year-old Armstrong and other black musicians were
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Torn down almost 50 years ago for the City Hall complex were the
nearby row houses where Armstrong and his sister grew up after
their mother, Mayanne, moved the family from squalid Jane Alley in
an outlying slum Armstrong called ``Back o' Town.'' A tree marks
the spot where their house probably stood, Jones said, and a nearby
grassy rise is all that remains of the music mecca called Kenna's
Hall, but that Armstrong and his cronies knew by a cruder nickname.
The building of City Hall also wiped out all traces of the Fisk
School, the local public school for blacks, which Louis barely
attended when he was 6 or 7. ``If he went there for more than two
years, I'd be surprised,'' Jones said. Blacks needed to attend
school only for 120 days a year, he said, whites, 180.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1988, while doing research for Gary Giddens, the jazz
writer, and Toby Byron, a television producer preparing an
Armstrong book and documentary, that Jones began to think that
Armstrong had actually been born a year or two later than he said.
An overlooked clue had come from Armstrong himself. In the 1940s he
told his Belgian biographer, Robert Goffin, that he was baptized at
the Sacred Heart of Jesus Church. The church, on Lopez Street, was
for whites, but urged on by Giddens, Jones discovered that black
infants, including Armstrong, had been baptized there as well, and
he came up with the new birth date.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the easiest thing I've ever done,'' said Jones, dressed
in jeans, a maroon golf shirt and sneakers, as he strolled through
Armstrongland. ``Do I look like a rocket scientist?''
</P>
<P>
   He said he gave the news to Richard Allen, a former jazz curator
at Tulane University, who passed it on to The New Orleans
Times-Picayune, which sent it out on the Newhouse news service
``That was it, 50 newspapers picked up on it,'' Jones recalled. ``I
was getting phone calls like I had discovered the Holy Grail or the
cure for cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Several years later Jones landed a book contract with the
University of Illinois Press. All told, he said, his advance and
grants over his decade of work have barely reached $5,000, although
he and his co-authors, Jason Berry and Jonathan Foose, had written
the well-received ``Up From the Cradle of Jazz: New Orleans Music
Since World War II'' (University of Georgia Press, 1986). A dabbler
on the guitar and piano, although he does not play for a living,
Jones has supported himself working as a paralegal and manager of a
music publishing group owned by the long-running New Orleans-based
rock band the Radiators. (He is also scheduled to lecture on
Armstrong's musical influences in a commemorative series at Lincoln
Center in New York in October.)
</P>
<P>
   Retracing some of his archival research in the conveyance office
in City Hall, Jones pulled out heavy quill-penned books that
summarized hundreds of thousands of property transfers _ including
the sale and purchase of slaves _ from 1827 to 1865. New Orleans
was one of the largest slave markets in the South. ``Once you get
one sale you can track forward or backward,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   So he traced the roots of Armstrong's family tree. The baptismal
certificate with the crucial 1901 date had listed a Catherine
Walker as a co-sponsor of the child. ``I initially thought she was
a white neighbor whom the Armstrongs might have worked for,'' Jones
said. But the summaries in the conveyance office and the original
documents in the city's nearby notarial office told a different
story.
</P>
<P>
   He found the record he was seeking on Page 344 in a thick volume
labeled ``Acts, Jan.-July 1818, Marc Lafitte, Notary.'' On May 18,
1818, a slaveowner named Antoine Turcas purchased Daniel Walker,
32, from Richmond for about $600, a substantial price at the time.
Walker, a further search of the records showed, had a son, also
named Daniel, who married Catherine Washington, born in 1837 and
brought with her mother and sister from a plantation in Madison
County, Miss., to New Orleans, where they were auctioned off
together. Catherine and Daniel Walker had a daughter named
Josephine who later married Ephraim Armstrong. They had a son named
Willie, the father of Louis Armstrong. Catherine Walker, Louis'
great-grandmother, attended the baby's baptism in 1901 as a
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he knew he was spending a lot of time on local
details but that it was important for the understanding of
Armstrong and the myriad influences, musical and otherwise, that
shaped him. Some of his predecessors may have been in too much of a
hurry, he said, too eager to distance Armstrong from his roots and
catapult him to universal fame. ``They race through New Orleans to
get to Chicago,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
