<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BULL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BULL': FAST-PACED BUT ROUTINE DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, those wacky rich people and their colorful nicknames. The
hero of the new TNT series ``Bull'' is the grandson of a prospering
investment firm's founder. The grandfather, Robert Roberts, is so
imperious, heartless and soulless he is called the Kaiser behind
his back. The grandson, Robert Roberts III, is nicknamed Ditto.
Even his friends call him that, which seems a misfortune serious
enough to offset all the silver spoons positioned in his mouth at
birth. Ditto is also not a bad word to describe this routine drama.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first of a boomlet of shows and movies set on Wall
Street, tapping into the feeling that everybody's an investor
today. (Fox's fall series ``The Street,'' created by Darren Star of
``Melrose Place'' and ``Sex and the City,'' promises to be
soapier.) But ``Bull'' simply plugs an all-purpose cast of types
into a financial setting. If they were yelling ``Stat! Chem
seven!'' instead of ``Dot-com IPO!'' these people could be in a
hospital show. The bright side: because the financial schemes are
no more than background noise, there's no need to dig into ``Wall
Street for Dummies'' before viewing.
</P>
<P>
   The handsome Ditto (George Newbern) is so sweet, soulful and
independent you have to wonder how he turned up in the cutthroat
Roberts family. In the premiere Tuesday night, he and some friends
leave the old firm to start a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the current interest in Wall Street, it's hard to give a
broker the life-saving adventures of a doctor, so ``Bull'' makes
Grandfather Roberts actively evil. The veteran actor Donald Moffatt
makes him smooth, silver-haired and silver-tongued; it is easy to
see why he is so successful a manipulator. But his actions are
those of a mustache-twirling villain.
</P>
<P>
   The versatile Malik Yoba (from the police show ``New York
Undercover'') plays Corey Granville, an Ivy League-educated broker
who has just sold $60 million worth of Brazilian bonds the company
has been desperate to unload. The Kaiser insists that because
Granville is black, he would never have made the sale if he had
been negotiating in person instead of on the phone. ``There's a
glass ceiling'' for blacks, he tells Ditto. Grandfather also
orchestrates an illegal trade and gives the credit (and potential
jail time) to Marissa Rufo (Alicia Coppola), a bright young broker
with a working-class background and a family secret. ``How's she
doing?'' she coos into a phone.
</P>
<P>
   Next to all this, Ditto's bolt from the firm seems like an act
of social conscience. Yet when he rallies his friends to join him
he sounds as if they are going off to audition for ``A Chorus
Line.'' Stanley Tucci is also around, wasted as a character whose
villainy is telegraphed with every move but who has been invited to
join the new firm anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bull'' does have energy, with a swift style _ noisy,
overlapping conversations and constant motion _ that works well for
a generation that takes MTV and the Internet for granted. But the
half-dozen main characters haven't defined themselves yet, and
there's only a glimmer of hope that ``Bull'' will be given time for
that to happen. Already, the producers of ``Bull'' and ``The
Street'' must be kicking themselves for arriving a season too late.
These shows about the Wall Street boom are turning up after
technology stocks have tumbled and investors have become jittery.
Ditto is young; there's still time for him to go to law school.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BULL'
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Tuesday on TNT
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chernuchin, Ken Horton and Eric Laneuville, executive
producers; Doug Palau, supervising producer; Peter Giuliano and Gay
Walch, producers; John Niss, associate producer; Janis Diamond,
executive story editor. A production of Nooch Co. in association
with Warner Bros. Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: George Newbern (Robert ``Ditto'' Roberts III), Malik Yoba
(Corey Granville), Ian Kahn (Marty Decker), Christopher Wiehl
(Carson Boyd), Alicia Coppola (Marissa Rufo), Elisabeth Rohm
(Alison Jeffers), Stanley Tucci (Hunter Lasky) and Donald Moffat
(Robert ``the Kaiser'' Roberts). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
