NYT-08-14-00 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SUBMARiNE-TOUR0815-CO     08-14 2410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBMARiNE-TOUR0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 days aboard a submarine, a weapon of unimaginable power
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - From the bottom of the ladder, looking
up, way up, the circle of sky beyond the open hatch looks pretty
small. Very small. Far away, and very small.
</P>
<P>
   Then a sailor pulls down on the hatch and dogs it tight with
metallic finality, and a few drops of water jump from the hatch,
fall past the steel ladders and twisting cables and splat onto the
deck, where they glisten in the dim red light of the control room,
stowaways entirely out of their element.
</P>
<P>
   A voice nearby, a sailor: ``It's quiet, no?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's quiet on board the USS Hampton. Very quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's even quieter down at 600 feet,'' says the sailor.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, joy.
</P>
<P>
   Submarines, the silent service.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, it was the downright mute service, shrouded
in secrecy as deep as ocean canyons, unfathomable to laymen, even
to most members of Congress, but not always to the Soviets, and
apparently not to Tom Clancy.
</P>
<P>
   For almost 50 years, since Admiral Hyman Rickover first put
nuclear reactors on board, subs have been off limits to the press
and public. What we didn't know about modern subs made them seem
all the more mysterious. Nobody, not even the president, could
contact a nuclear sub when it was out there somewhere, submerged,
armed with enough weaponry to obliterate a civilization. Or two.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Navy celebrates the 100th anniversary of its
submarine forces, it has popped the hatches of these weapons for
closer inspection, rides even, by members of the media who, until
now, had only blacked-out declassified documents, rumor and Tom
Clancy to go on.
</P>
<P>
   The subs are open for inspection, and it's as if the bedroom
light has been flicked on during dreams full of dark images, of
forces beyond comprehension. And do the myths and mysteries
evaporate when a nuclear sub is explored in the clear light of day?
</P>
<P>
   No. They are verified.
</P>
<P>
   Three days on board the Hampton in the North Atlantic about 220
miles east of Norfolk, Va. Conclusion: These boats are weapons of
unimaginable power. Scary. Terrible. Apocalyptic. A force almost
beyond comprehension. And, just maybe, the most significant
deterrent in our national arsenal, the reason no enemy has ever
dared fire a missile our way.
</P>
<P>
   And one more thing: From captain to cook, the entire crew could
be lifted off and sent to work in some start-up company, product
irrelevant. The result would be a company to reckon with. Almost
half of them are nuclear engineers. Many hold advanced degrees in
engineering, business, foreign policy. They're entrusted with
almost $2 billion worth of hardware. They make big decisions on a
minute-to-minute basis. They work independently, yet as one. They
are diligent. They are young.
</P>
<P>
   Their sub is something else, too: a Los Angeles-class fast
attack sub, 330 feet long, 36 feet in diameter and almost
impossible for the enemy to find. It's as big as a World War II
cruiser, but it lives underwater.
</P>
<P>
   Subs have come a long way since John Holland, an Irish patriot
and inventor who lived in New Jersey, sold the Navy its first, the
Holland, commissioned SS-1 on Oct. 12, 1900. It was the sixth sub
Holland had built. He sold the fifth to Irish revolutionaries who
wanted to toss _ or sink _ the British out of Ireland. The Irish
took their boat _ without paying Holland _ but they didn't get far.
The British and U.S. navies scoured the Atlantic for months looking
for the rogue sub, but it had never left America. It was found in a
barn in Lyme, Conn., decades later. How it got there, nobody knows.
In a sense, that's a typical submarine anecdote: A submarine is a
weapon designed to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what the Hampton does a few minutes after the
hatch closes. It disappears. That's what makes it so dangerous. It
can simply ... disappear. Well, that and 23 radio-controlled, high
explosive torpedoes and a dozen Tomahawk cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Weapons make the Hampton dangerous, but the crew makes it work.
</P>
<P>
   They're all young. The captain, John Lovering, a Cape Cod
native, is in his early 40s, the oldest guy on the boat, except for
one chief petty officer who's 46. More than 130 men in the crew and
not a one of them remembers where they were when JFK died. Most of
them weren't anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   No women on board. Politics aside, it takes maybe nine seconds
to grasp the obvious: Privacy does not exist, except for the
officers, and then minimally. Crew members live side-by-side for
weeks, months. No exit. Two people cannot pass in a corridor
without touching. Bathrooms are shared. Everything is shared.
</P>
<P>
   Bunks are scattered everywhere _ next to torpedoes, over
computers, under torpedoes. They're stacked four high, maybe a foot
of headroom. The bunks _ called racks _ are shared. One sailor
sleeps, another works, then they switch. It's called hot racking,
because the bunks never cool off.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does the reactor. It occupies the rear third of the boat
and is way off limits to outsiders, even to crew members who are
not nuclear-rated by the Navy. When the reactor runs out of fuel in
about 12 years, the Hampton gets junked. The ship will probably be
obsolete before then anyway. It was launched in 1992. It's very
fast, very sneaky. Cost: $1.8 billion, before yearly operating
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The reactor produces steam, which drives the turbines that turn
the propeller _ one propeller, its specific design and material top
secret. The Hampton is, at a certain level, a steamboat, which is
ironic because the first steamboat Robert Fulton built was a
submarine, Nautilus, in 1801. He tried to sell the idea to both
Napoleon and the British, but they thought Fulton's idea was
stupid. So he came home to the U.S. and built a riverboat, the
Clermont.
</P>
<P>
   These are good things for a visitor to ponder, because when the
Hampton's diving alarm sounds _ karoooong, karoooong, just like in
the movies _ and a voice cracks dive, dive, dive over the intercom,
a visitor may ponder that patch of blue sky, which may lead to
unsettling feelings of close confinement and downright panic. So,
you tell yourself, hey, this is a big, safe boat, and you try not
to think of the hatch slamming shut. Which is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The two periscopes in the control room are trained on the stern
of the boat. Slowly, the sea washes over the deck, then covers it,
then sloshes against the periscope lens. Then, the boat slips
gently below periscope depth, 62 feet. Below 100, 150. Air pressure
increases just enough to notice, not because of the immense force
of the sea against the hull, but because the crew pumped air
throughout the boat to see if any valve, anywhere, was not closed
tight. If a valve were leaking, the air pressure would slowly
decrease. It doesn't. 200, 250, 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take it to 450,'' commands Lovering.
</P>
<P>
   His orders pass along to the men at the controls _ simple
controls, two small wheels. The sub is easy to steer, very
responsive. The slightest touch on the controls send the boat up at
a steep angle. Or down.
</P>
<P>
   450 feet.
</P>
<P>
   How deep is the ocean here?
</P>
<P>
   ``Aboutresso. Brewed by a fine Italian coffee machine. Very
important for crew morale, says Lovering. Unfortunately, 27
visiting midshipmen from various college R.O.T.C. programs had very
quickly broken the machine. The cook unplugged it. The crew was not
happy. The midshipmen kept mostly to themselves after that.
</P>
<P>
   Sonar? You bet. Banks of screens in pitch-black rooms are the
eyes and ears of the boat. Computers enhance the images. And, yes,
the experienced sonar operator can spot a whale at 5 miles or tell
the captain what sort of ship is out there, based on the unique
noise of its propeller.
</P>
<P>
   Food? Excellent and plenty of it. Even though there is no day,
no night under the waves, meals served in the morning tend toward
the breakfast end of the spectrum, those at night toward dinner.
Loads of coffee, fresh fruit, sausages, eggs, cakes, popcorn,
steak, spaghetti, meat balls. As much as you want. The dozen or so
officers dine in their mess, a small room with a big-screen TV that
displays the view from the periscope. The intercom is always tuned
to the control room. A direct telephone line to the control room
plugs into the bulkhead next to the captain's chair. Stewards serve
the officers. Enlisted men dine in their mess, watch first-run
movies there as well. Senior enlisted men _ chief petty officers _
stick mostly to their part of the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Toilet seats? Toilets on board have seats, a nice homey gesture.
But. Woe to the sailor who leaves the seat up, not for the usual
reasons of domestic tranquility, but because a falling toilet seat
in a submarine will clang against a steel toilet with a resounding
metallic crash throughout the steel hull that can be heard miles
away by enemy sonar, which could, theoretically, result in the
sub's coming under attack. What a way to go.
</P>
<P>
   In order to assure that all those toilet seats are secured,
along with everything loose on board _ coffee cups, wrenches,
brooms, everything _ Lovering puts Hampton through a series of
steep maneuvers soon after diving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angles and dangles we call them,'' says Lovering. ``We'll go
up from 400 feet at a 30-degree angle. Then we'll go down. We'll
turn, sharp turns. We'll twist and turn, and if I hear so much as a
drinking glass slide off a table, someone's gonna hear from me.''
</P>
<P>
   So the sub shoots up. Movable bow and stern planes, like the
flaps on an airplane, set the angle. Steep. And fast, more than 20
mph. So steep you lean forward at an angle that keeps you level
relative to the ocean floor. And although top speed is classified,
Lovering says he usually does this faster, and at steeper angles.
</P>
<P>
   Then he turns the sub. The rudder is big, can push a lot of
water. Very tight turns. Crew members grab steel bars overhead.
Subway straps would come in handy. The sub is cavorting like a sea
lion. It is, essentially, flying underwater.
</P>
<P>
   Lovering explains that these boats are incredibly responsive _
can turn full around within their length. But they were built with
an engineering glitch not discovered until they were put through
their paces. Like an airplane, if you tell a sub to turn and dive
at a fast enough speed, it will tend to roll out of control and
plummet straight toward the bottom. Unlike an airplane, a sub
cannot be allowed to roll over because hundreds of gallons of acid
in the 126 giant batteries (battery power is still used on nuclear
subs, in emergencies mostly) would flood out, creating poisonous
chlorine gas and otherwise wreaking havoc.
</P>
<P>
   This would not be good, deadpans Lovering.
</P>
<P>
   Taped to the control panel is something like a manufacturer's
advisory, step-by-step instructions for ``pulling out'' of such a
dive. Turn the rudder this way, raise this plane, lower that one,
reduce speed. Very reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   Lovering snaps his commands. The crew and the boat respond. Up,
down, twist, turn. No cups slide, no wrenches tumble. All is quiet.
There is no hum from the reactor room when power is piled on. No
hum anywhere. No engine vibration. Not even enough to ripple the
surface of a cup of coffee secured in a metal holder. Silence
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Silence is also what you get when you ask a crew member about
top speed, lowest diving depth, torpedo speed and range. The press
packet for the Hampton says top speed is ``in excess of 25 knots,''
about 28 mph. But how much in excess? Hampton's crew members shrug.
Even former attack sub crew members are sketchy, but some will say
top speed is closer to 40 mph.
</P>
<P>
   That's fast. Very fast.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the three days the Hampton cruises at between 600
and 700 feet.
</P>
<P>
   And how deep does it dive? ``In excess of 800 feet,'' says the
press packet. But ex-submariners say it's beyond 1,200 feet.
Besides, as one Hampton sailor says, look at the depth gauge.
</P>
<P>
   The depth gauge goes well beyond 1,200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The crew of Hampton passes the three days on fire drills,
simulated torpedo shoots, a hunt-and-kill exercise with a U.S.
ballistic missile sub _ a ``boomer'' that Hampton locates in a few
hours and ``kills'' shortly thereafter. Then, more fire drills,
clean the decks, take readings on every piece of equipment on
board. And then do it all again. When the pressure on the
1-inch-thick skin of the boat can be measured in tons per square
foot, one mistake, one broken valve is one too many.
</P>
<P>
   The midshipmen are suited up for a fire drill. The suits and
helmets are bulky and hot. It's hard to see, hard to move, even in
the comfort of white lights and air conditioning. Worst of all, air
is supplied to the suits by connecting an air hose to an overhead
air line. This is how you move toward the fire: Plug in, breathe,
unplug, grope along down the air line, plug in. If there were
really a reactor fire, thick radioactive smoke, melting metal ... ?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the intent is to keep the men busy helping their
shipmates,'' says a chief petty officer. ``But if the reactor went,
if the hull fractured ... we all go. But that sure as hell ain't
gonna happen as long as I'm around.''
</P>
<P>
   It is known on these boats that the chiefs run the boats; the
officers fight the boats in battle. They depend on each other, and
everybody depends on the chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn on the last day, one last exercise, an ``emergency''
surfacing from 450 feet. Air under thousands of pounds pressure is
blasted into the flooded ballast tanks. A whooomp reverberates
through the boat when the air is released. The air pushes water out
of the tanks. Fast. The depth gauge wavers for a few seconds, then
starts upward, faster and faster like an express elevator. In less
than three minutes, the ship bursts up and out of the deep. At that
last second, everybody on board goes weightless. You float on
tiptoes just for the briefest and most refreshing of moments.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the hatch up top is swung open. A few drops
of water plop to the deck. And a pale blue eye of sky probes the
dark interior of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   The Hampton has been out for three months. Most of the men won't
see that patch of sky for eight more hours, when the boat ties up
in Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take it home,'' says Lovering.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to repeat the order.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: paulreid(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
