<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vanity Fair's content a formula that works
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Tina Brown tinkers with Talk to find the right mix, Vanity
Fair ($3.95) editors continue to follow a formula that nearly
always works. Two or three celebrity profiles, a true crime story,
a usually insightful column from James Wolcott, a compelling book
excerpt and a finely crafted investigative article.
</P>
<P>
   There's always a certain amount of fluff, such as this month's
cover story on Gwyneth Paltrow and other ``It'' girls, but even
that is done with flair. Paltrow, by the way, confesses that her
split with Brad Pitt left her heartbroken forever. Presumably this
is not the sort of thing on-and-off-again boyfriend Ben Affleck
wants to hear.
</P>
<P>
   More serious articles include Nick Tosches' report on his search
for an opium den in Bangkok and Hong Kong; Buzz Bissinger's
portrait of Joe DiMaggio as a flawed, tortured hero; and an excerpt
from a new book by Anthony Summers and Robbyn Swan that claims
Richard Nixon prolonged the Vietnam War by scuttling LBJ's 1968
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the campaign: If you're not interested in politics, you can
skip reading the newsweeklies this week. Both Time ($3.50) and
Newsweek ($3.50) have nearly mirror image covers of Al Gore and
Joseph Lieberman with similar coverage inside. Both magazines
examine the impact of a Jewish vice presidential candidate and both
rehash Gore's background. Time, however, adds a new twist with a
piece on the women who shaped the vice president. U.S. News &AMP; World
Report ($3.50) devotes fewer pages to the campaign but adds a
historical perspective with an article about the first Democrats.
The magazine also notes that Gore's chances for victory depend
heavily on the loyalties of white, married female voters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Games people play: This week's double issue of The New Yorker
($3.95) is all about sports, from Roger Angell's analysis of the
problems of Yankees infielder Chuck Knoblauch and pitcher David
Cone to David Owen's profile of Tiger Woods. One of the most
interesting pieces is Malcolm Gladwell's ``The Art of Failure.''
Gladwell talks to psychologists and other experts about the
difference between ``choking'' and ``panicking.'' Greg Norman
choked at the 1996 Masters, for example, when he dropped 10 strokes
in 10 holes. John F. Kennedy Jr. panicked during his fatal flight.
Choking, Gladwell writes, ``is about thinking too much. Panic is
about thinking too little.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coming soon to a theater near you: Yes, that scruffy, bearded
fellow on the cover of the Aug. 18 Entertainment Weekly ($3.50) is
Tom Hanks as the star of the December film ``Castaway.'' Talk about
great timing. When Hanks and screenwriter William Broyles came up
with the idea six years ago, ``Survivor'' was not even a gleam in
CBS' eye. In its fall guide to the movies, EW speculates on what
will be a box office hit and what will be a miss. Possible hits
include ``Play It Forward'' with Kevin Spacey and Helen Hunt;
``Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2''; ``How the Grinch Stole
Christmas'' with Jim Carrey; and ``The Legend of Bagger Vance''
with Matt Damon and Will Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kid stuff: Fans of the Atlanta-based Cartoon Network'features
the controversial interview with Elizabeth Hurley in which the
actress/model complains about Hugh Grant's shortcomings in the
bedroom. Hurley has denied making the remarks, but Jane editor Jane
Pratt stands by the story. ... And in the ``right career decision''
category, Jennifer Lopez tells Glamour ($3.50) that her parents
wanted her to be a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
