<HEADER>
A1407 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PRODUCE15-COX     08-14 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRODUCE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With its bounty of fresh produce, summer's the perfect time to
get your quota of fruits, veggies
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With New Year's Day verve, countless people resolved to eat a
healthy diet: good fats, not bad; fiber, not fluff; five fruits and
vegetables a day.
</P>
<P>
   Those promises are long forgotten by many, and it's back to life
in the fast-food lane. But summer's the perfect time to re-commit _
seasonal produce offers vitality in juicy, fleshy flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Fruits and vegetables supply nearly all the vitamins and
minerals required for good health. Some contain complex
carbohydrates that furnish energy. Most provide dietary fiber, and
some even offer protein. As a bonus, they contain no cholesterol,
have little or no fat and are low in calories.
</P>
<P>
   A study published this year in the Journal of the American
Medical Association found that women who regularly ate fruits and
vegetables along with whole grains were far less likely to die
prematurely from heart disease, cancer and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Along with health benefits comes the simple joy of enjoying the
summer harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the berries, the yellow squash, the field peas, I could
just go on and on,'' said Sonya Jones, owner and chef of Sweet
Auburn Bread Co. in the Sweet Auburn Curb Market. ``I definitely
eat more vegetable plates during this time of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The drought means the harvest is a little short for some summer
favorites, such as tomatoes and squash, said Ann Brewer, manager of
Georgia Grown: Certified Organic Produce and organizer of the
Morningside Farmers Market. ``But the outlook is good for all the
wonderful greens, all the chards and arugula,'' Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 summer treats worth a stop at the gardener's truck
or a cruise through the organic market or produce section at the
grocery.
</P>
<P>
   Berries
</P>
<P>
   Pretty, small and juicy, berries have a lot going for them,
especially when eaten fresh and unadorned. Many are a good source
of vitamin C, potassium and fiber. Blackberries, strawberries and
blueberries are most popular in this region.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberries have the most vitamin C _ 3 1/2 ounces (about 2/3
cup) contains 95 percent of the recommended daily allowance (RDA)
for adults. ``I love to have just a bowl of mixed fresh berries,''
said Jones. ``You don't need to do anything to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cantaloupe
</P>
<P>
   Summer melons are refreshing, but some favorites, like
watermelon, don't have a whole lot to offer in nutrients. But a
2/3-cup serving of cubed cantaloupe provides 70 percent of the RDA
for vitamin C for men and women, and 64 percent of vitamin A for
men, 81 percent for women. The orange color comes from
cancer-battler beta carotene.
</P>
<P>
   Corn
</P>
<P>
   Corn is not necessarily a nutritional powerhouse, though it's
fairly well rounded. Just a 1/3 cup of kernels provides 10 percent
to 20 percent of the RDA of vitamin C, folic acid and important
minerals like magnesium, phosphorus and thiamin.
</P>
<P>
   Corn is high in protein, but lacks some important amino acids.
To compensate, combine with beans or meat. Similarly, to help
release the niacin in corn, combine it with an alkaline substance,
such as lime juice. Try a lime-splashed corn salsa with a grilled
chicken breast for a well-rounded meal.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   The health claims of garlic are numerous, and many are
unsubstantiated. Garlic does contain a substance that interferes
with the formation of blood clots and may also have some
cancer-fighting agents. But it's unclear if cooked garlic looses
some of its punch.
</P>
<P>
   People would have consume very large amounts of garlic to get
its full effect. For instance, men who could stomach 33 cloves at a
time would get 60 percent of their RDA of B6; women, 75 percent.
(B6 helps maintain brain functions and the formation of red blood
cells.) But three cloves offers a smidgen of nutrients and loads of
flavor, especially when combined with other summer favorites like
squash and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Okra
</P>
<P>
   Our good Southern okra is high in fiber and packed with folacin.
One cup sliced provides 44 percent of the RDA of folic acid for
men; 49 percent for women. It's also a good source of vitamin C, B
vitamins, magnesium, potassium and calcium. All of that for a mere
38 calories. That is if it hasn't been drenched in cornmeal and
fried. Try cooking it quickly, preserving some of its natural
crispness, then combining with chopped tomatoes and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Peppers
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a source of vitamin C? Try peppers, which ounce for
ounce have more vitamin C than citrus fruit. Green peppers have
twice as much; red peppers three times as much. Hot peppers contain
357 percent more vitamin C than an orange. A 1/2 cup of chopped
sweet red pepper delivers 158 percent of the daily need for vitamin
C.
</P>
<P>
   Red peppers are packed with beta carotene, too. A sweet red
pepper provides nearly 11 times as much beta carotene as a sweet
green one; hot red peppers 14 times as much.
</P>
<P>
   Salad greens/arugula
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule, the darker the leaf, the more nutritious the
salad green. Romaine and loose-leaf lettuces have up to six times
as much vitamin C and five to 10 times as much beta carotene as
iceberg lettuce. Greens like arugula and dandelion offer even more.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 3 1/2 ounces of raw arugula has 91 milligrams of
vitamin C compared to 4 in iceberg; and it offers a whopping 309
milligrams of calcium (about 25 percent RDA) compared to 68 in
romaine. It's also a cruciferous vegetable, which means it may help
to protect against cancer. Arugula has a peppery taste and is most
often mixed with other salad greens. Try tossing torn strips of
arugula with pasta, olive oil and garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Shell beans/field peas
</P>
<P>
   ``Butter beans and lady peas are my favorites in the
summertime,'' declares Watershed chef Scott Peacock. ``I love the
way they look, the way they taste, everything about them.'' Shell
beans like butter (also called Fordhooks), lima and cranberry are
loaded with protein, fiber and iron. Southern field peas such as
purple hull and lady are close cousins nutritionally.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the shell beans, limas are the best, but can be hard to
find fresh. A 3 1/2 ounce serving of lima beans delivers 38 percent
of the RDA of vitamin C. Boil or steam beans until tender, season
and enjoy. Crisp-tender beans are also a delightful addition to
green salads or mix them with corn to make succotash.
</P>
<P>
   Summer squash
</P>
<P>
   The best thing summer squashes have going for them is they are a
guilt-free pleasure, with only 19 calories per cup. That is, if you
prepare them in a healthy manner, say steamed or stewed with onions
and herbs. Battered and fried, zucchini sticks can have 210
calories for a 3 1/2-ounce serving, 47 percent from fat. Most
squash offer vitamin C and folacin; patty pan squash (pictured)
provides double the amount of vitamin C as other summer squashes.
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Though not as high in nutrients as some other vegetables,
tomatoes are the leading vegetable source of vitamin C in the
American diet because of the quantities we eat. They also provide
beta carotene and lycopene, both believed to help reduce the
chances of certain cancers. And this is one case where processing
can concentrate rather than dilute nutrients. So tomato juices,
sauces and even ketchup carry vitamin C, A and E. But with fresh
tomatoes in season ``just slice them and eat,'' said Brewer of
Georgia Grown: Certified Organic Produce.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Wellness Encyclopedia of Food and Nutrition, by
Sheldon Margen and the editors of the University of California at
Berkeley Wellness Letter, (Rebus, $29.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BERLIN-JEWISH-MEMORIA     08-14 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-JEWISH-MEMORIALS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JEWISH MUSEUM STRUGGLES TO BE BORN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The idea seemed simple, pleasing in its balance: Bring
the German capital back to Berlin 55 years after the fall of
Hitler's Reich and mark that return with several major cultural
projects commemorating, in different ways, the Holocaust and
Germany's lost Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But almost a year after the government returned, those projects
are plagued by delays and confusion. Sitting in a sweltering office
in Berlin's still-unopened Jewish Museum, Ken Gorbey, a New
Zealander recently appointed its project director, posed just one
of the central questions: ``Why on earth should a Kiwi gentile be
here?''
</P>
<P>
   He is not the only person pondering that conundrum. Eleven years
after its design was approved, three years after Daniel
Liebeskind's building was completed, more than a year after the
public was allowed a peek into its vertiginous space, one of the
emblematic projects of the new Berlin has a new artistic leader
from down under even as it struggles to install an air-conditioning
system that works.
</P>
<P>
   A revised opening date has just been set: Sept. 9, 2001, more
than a year late. And there are rumblings. Of an unhappy
falling-out between Michael Blumenthal, the museum's American chief
executive, and his former deputy, Tom Freudenheim. Of soaring
costs. Of growing unease over Berlin's many Jewish projects. Of a
``Disneyland aesthetic.''
</P>
<P>
   As things stand, the so-called triangle of major new Jewish
projects planned to coincide with the German capital's return to
Berlin form a bizarre picture: a building without an exhibition
(the Jewish Museum), an exhibition without a building (the
Topography of Terror site at the former SS headquarters) and an
embarrassingly vacant central lot (the numbingly debated Holocaust
Memorial).
</P>
<P>
   In theory, they form a whole: The museum commemorates Jewish
life in Germany; the Topography of Terror focuses on the Nazi
perpetrators; and the Holocaust Memorial recalls the 6 million Jews
murdered by the Nazis. But while the theory is tidy, the reality is
not.
</P>
<P>
   Big issues are at stake: how Germany should recall the cataclysm
of the Third Reich, whether the projects are for Germans or for
Jews or both, and whether the uneasy relationship between Germans
and Jews, both marked forever by the death camps, can remain calm
even as Holocaust fatigue grows in this country. Irritation is
evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish Museum building is interesting, but to me it's a
Holocaust sculpture, not a museum,'' said Julius Schoeps, the
director of the Moses Mendelssohn Center, a Jewish research
foundation, and a prominent member of the Berlin Jewish community.
``And now there is an attempt to adorn it in a very American way,
to make a museum of experiences with what I have called a
Disneyland aesthetic.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with the newspaper Die Welt in which he
first invoked Disneyland, Schoeps also took a swipe at Gorbey,
saying that multimedia installations might work in Washington and
``maybe even New Zealand,'' but that Europeans wanted to see
original objects.
</P>
<P>
   Having developed Te Papa, New Zealand's enormously successful
national museum in Wellington, Gorbey, 58, took up his new post in
April. He was drawn to Berlin by what he called ``the incredibly
exciting project'' of chronicling the flowering, destruction and
partial rebirth of German Jewish life in a building of great power.
</P>
<P>
   With its towering empty spaces (what Liebeskind calls voids),
its zigzag form and its angular walls and windows, the building
induces a sense of loss, sometimes even panic. It has been widely
acclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been aesthetic concerns _ will the building
overwhelm any exhibition it houses? _ and practical problems, not
least the discovery last year that the air-conditioning system was
inadequate, toilets too scarce and the layout of the entrance
liable to create what Blumenthal called ``a traffic jam of major
proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems are linked partly to the very popularity of
Liebeskind's building, which suggests that crowds will be greater
than originally predicted, and to the haphazard way the museum has
evolved from a mere adjunct to the Berlin City Museum into a
full-fledged national institution. Still, the result was more
outlays _ $5 million on top of the $60 million already spent _ and
more delays.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Gorbey, speaking no German and with no particular
knowledge of German or Jewish history. Are these handicaps? ``At
times, but perhaps a certain neutrality is a bonus,'' he said. ``I
am in the museum industry. This building is a massive capital
project, and part of my task is to spend large sums prudently.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Gorbey is here to get things done, and there is
a lot to be done after a period of turmoil. Shaike Weinberg, a
former director of the Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington, who
had been working closely with Blumenthal, died early this year;
Freudenheim quit in frustration this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The institution, not a Holocaust Museum despite its appearance,
is to tell the entire 2,000-year history of Jewish life in Germany.
It will deploy what the museum's latest manifesto calls ``objects
in cases, supported by texts and graphics.'' But it will also
engage ``customers'' with ``other experiences provided by object
theaters, computer interactives and opportunities for hands-on
engagement with subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorbey explained his plans. ``Look,'' he said. ``We're not going
to have people saying, `Let's go and have fun at the Jewish
Museum.' No, we will be fronting up to the Holocaust, and so the
emotive side will be a little more harrowing. But we hope we will
give a balanced view, showing the joy in the Jewish community at
times and its sense of achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Schoeps' criticism is a little shallow,'' he continued. ``This
museum will be based on scholarship, not whimsy. But we want to
appeal to a broad range of people and help them come to terms with
history. So we will animate things, bring people and objects to
life. If Schoeps thinks that's Disney, he needs to visit a standard
object theater in any museum.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By ``object theater,'' Gorbey means the animation of objects
through sound, movies, robotics, lighting and other means to add
drama and perhaps a message to what is known in the trade as ``the
museum experience.'' Wuerth &AMP; Winderoll, a German company based in
Bavaria, has been contracted to work on the design of the exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   As a possible example of animation, Gorbey cited the
correspondence between two 20th-century German Jewish scientists,
Albert Einstein and Fritz Haber.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein came to scorn Germany _ ``a country of mass murderers''
was his lapidary assessment _ but Haber retained some attachment to
a nation he once described as ``bourgeois to its very depths.''
Gorbey said he found the discussion deeply revealing and could
imagine ``doing it in a coffee shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, a 74-year-old former secretary of the Treasury who
was born in Berlin and whose family fled Hitler, said: ``This is
not going to be a museum for intellectuals, and so the intellectual
snobs don't like it. We hope children will have fun, or at least
not be bored. But this will be a serious, talked-about place.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, a tough manager, has proved extremely adept at
cutting through layers of bureaucracy to obtain funds from the city
of Berlin and the nation. This drive has culminated with the
federal government's taking over the museum from a hugely indebted
city and promising to provide most of an annual budget of about $15
million.
</P>
<P>
   It was for a similar efficiency that Blumenthal said he chose
Gorbey. ``Our new deadline is going to stretch all of us very
far,'' he explained. ``And what I needed was someone very, very
good at knowing what it takes to open a museum. He's the best
museum manager in the world today.''
</P>
<P>
   Freudenheim, another old museum hand and an American who worked
for many years at the Smithsonian Institution, departed a few weeks
ago after several disagreements with Blumenthal. ``It's the first
time in my life that I've not been respected for doing professional
things, and I'm very sad about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The men clashed over several matters, including whether, as
Freudenheim urged, the museum should have opened much sooner with a
partial exhibit, whether a recent show on Berlin Jews at the Jewish
Museum in New York should have been brought to the museum and
whether the empty building could have been used for theatrical and
musical productions.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, it seems, was that Blumenthal came to see
Freudenhem as a gifted networker rather than a talented manager,
while Freudenheim came to view his boss as a martinet. The friction
between the two American directors was hardly fruitful.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's turbulent history has been matched by difficulties
with the other two memorial projects. The Topography of Terror has
not evolved beyond a temporary exhibit of photographs. Abutting a
solitary remnant of the Berlin Wall, the display chronicles the
suffering of people tortured and killed by the SS and the Gestapo.
Construction at this site of a building by the Swiss architect
Peter Zumthor, whose plans were approved in 1993, has not even
begun.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that the Berlin administration has balked at the
cost, now estimated at $35 million. ``We were supposed to get a
final report from the city building commission in July, but that
has been delayed to September,'' said Reinhard Ruerup, the academic
director of the Topography of Terror project. ``The fact is, the
mayor is not very enthusiastic, but I do not think he will stop it
in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, Eberhard Diepgen, is well known for his reservations
about both The Topography of Terror and the Holocaust Memorial. But
Ruerup argued that the new German capital could not do without a
museum ``located at the spot where the central agencies of terror
worked and focusing on the perpetrators.''
</P>
<P>
   But does Germany want more reminders? Notably, the country has
deferred to foreigners in the conception of all three projects: an
American architect and chief executive for the museum, a Swiss
architect for the Topography of Terror and a New York architect,
Peter Eisenman, for the Holocaust Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish-German question is so delicate and hot that any
person who takes on these projects is going to be burned in some
way, but perhaps more so a German,'' said Wenzel Jacob, the
director of the Federal Museum of Art in Bonn. ``Guilt complicates
everything, which is a pity because a lot of Germans are capable of
doing these jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The most treacherous job of all may be the Holocaust Memorial, a
prominent field of columns adjacent to the Brandenburg Gate that
could easily become a target for resurgent right-wing groups.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of discussion, the final touches to the design
are still under review. A planned archive or research center that
was to have been above ground has been moved underground, where
Joseph Goebbels' former bunker complicates the design. Construction
will begin next year at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give the Germans a lot of credit for doing all
this,'' Blumenthal said. ``But in the minds of many of them, there
is the notion that they are doing it for the Jews, not for
themselves. And so sometimes they feel we are asking for too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps by tying together Jewish and German life over many
centuries, and by evoking what Germany lost of itself in the
Holocaust, the Jewish Museum may finally have its greatest impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This museum will also be about what is missing,'' Gorbey said.
``A pocket handkerchief can tell the story of a whole family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
