<P>
   RUSSIA-TRAPPED-SAILORS (Moscow) _ More than 100 Russian sailors
were trapped at the bottom of the sea above the Arctic Circle with
little hope of rescue after their nuclear submarine was seriously
damaged in a collision, the commander of Russia's navy said. The
navy said it had begun a rescue effort in the Barents Sea on
Monday. In the early hours of Tuesday the navy was using small subs
to both inspect the damaged vessel and try to replenish the crew's
oxygen. Rescuers planned to attempt to evacuate the crew sometime
Tuesday, an effort that is expected to be complicated by the
extreme pressure that exists at the depth where the sub is lodged,
approximately 480 feet below the ocean surface. By Sabrina
Tavernise.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SRILANKA-OUTLOOK (Colombo, Sri Lanka) _ Sri Lanka's public life
seems to take place on two planes. In the political arena, the
country's governing alliance wages war on the rebels, while trying
to find a negotiated solution to the conflict that has taken more
than 60,000 lives. But beneath this discouraging, but still
potentially hopeful, process lies a deep public cynicism with
politics itself and a feeling that the war is no longer a conflict
between the Sinhalese and the Tamils that can be peaceably settled.
By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   IRS-ABUSE (Undated) _ Two years ago, after hearings on suspected
abuse of taxpayers, Congress passed a law to crack down on
perceived abuses by IRS workers. But of the first 830 complaints
made under the new law, not one complaint of taxpayer harassment
was upheld, IRS data released by the Congressional Joint Committee
on Taxation shows. The IRS did fire four of its 16,000 auditors for
improperly threatening to audit a taxpayer. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
