<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AIRFARES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER IS NO LONGER BARGAIN AIR-FARE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Hawaii, Wis., Minn.)  (For release Sunday, August 20)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans who postponed vacations this summer hoping that
airlines would announce major fare sales have had good reason to be
disappointed: There haven't been any, at least nothing comparable
to those a few years ago. And while most analysts attribute the
paucity of summer discounts to continued high demand for flights,
they note that the carriers' growing sophistication in knowing when
to lower or raise fares on everything from individual flights to
entire routes could spell the end to the periodic fire sales of
years past.
</P>
<P>
   That forecasting ability was made possible by the computer
application called yield management. Because of it, ``the airlines'
skill at filling seats with targeted sales makes it unnecessary to
offer across-the-board fare sales,'' said Terry Trippler, the
air-fares expert at onetravel.com, a Web site for travel bargains.
Besides, he added, Wall Street doesn't like such wholesale
giveaways, which can result in lower revenues and depressed stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Summarizing the airline industry's performance in the first
quarter of this year, Raymond Neidl, director of equity research at
Ing Barings, the investment bank, recently observed that ``the
positive thing is that the ticket price increases seem to not have
dampened travel.''
</P>
<P>
   That is also true of the second quarter of this year, as well as
of last month. ``With most airlines reporting a much higher demand
than last year, there is less incentive for the typical summer fare
sales we usually see,'' said Sandra Hughes, vice president for
travel-related services for the AAA.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, leisure air fares _ that is, discount fares that
usually require advance purchases, off-peak flights and a Saturday
night stay-over _ jumped almost 16 percent in June, according to
the AAA monthly leisure travel index. While fares decreased 5
percent last month they were still almost 10 percent higher than in
July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for flights is still so strong, that the three fare
increases this year did little if anything to discourage Americans
from flying. Most airlines carried record numbers of passengers in
recent months, including Delta, which carried a company record 32
million passengers in the three months ended June 30. In June,
Northwest achieved a company record 82.8 percent load factor _ the
percentage of available seats occupied by paying passengers _ and
Continental's 80.4 percent load factor last month was its highest
ever _ 0.4 percent higher than the record set this June and 2.6
points higher than July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, industrywide load factors, which have been in the high
70s most of this year and 80.2 percent in June, may eclipse the
post-World War II record annual load factor of 70.1 percent set
last year. (Between 1942 and 1945, when civilian flights were few,
load factors ranged from 72.7 to 88 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   In Hawaii, where arrivals rose each month from February through
May this year and the state appears headed for a record number of
visitors, round-trip air fares have averaged $600 to $700 for
seven-day-advance-purchase tickets between the West Coast and
Honolulu, almost double the $300 to $400 in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually by this time you could figure on at least one or two
fare sales,'' said Kana Leong, the owner of Pacific Island Travel,
an agency that handles both corporate and individual travel, in
Honolulu. ``But we haven't had any sales this year, because the
planes are coming in and going out loaded.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is true on the mainland, where flights to popular
tourist destinations are full and fare bargains rare. And even when
there have been sales, they have been limited: on Aug. 1, TWA
announced a sale good for travel through Dec. 15 that included $398
round trips from New York to Los Angeles or San Francisco, but
tickets had to be bought by Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there has been no shortage of other advertised fare
sales this summer _ sales to call attention to new routes or
additional flights on the same route, sales to stimulate traffic on
routes, sales to off-season destinations and sales offering
discounts of up to 10 percent for booking online. But most of these
discounts were modest and followed fare hikes as well as the $30
surtax to cover increased fuel costs. Even heavily advertised
``discounted'' fares on one airline are often 25 percent or more
higher than the regular fare on competing airlines flying the same
route.
</P>
<P>
   As skilled as the airlines are at yield management, they seem to
have had trouble figuring out the seasons this year _ at least
summer, which most of the travel industry, including the nonprofit
Travel Industry Association of America and the AAA, considers to be
June, July, August and possibly the few days until Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while ``summer sales'' to such off-season
destinations as the Caribbean advertised discounts of about 25
percent, most such sales were announced in mid-July and required a
14-day-advance purchase, thus greatly shortening summer. Delta's
``early summer sale'' to certain cities in Asia, Europe and Latin
America was valid for travel only through June 15, meaning it ended
before summer started.
</P>
<P>
   At another extreme, AirTran's mid-July ``Beat the Heat'' fare
sale is good for travel through Dec. 15, because, the airline said,
``our customers don't want summer to end.''
</P>
<P>
   With crowded planes and higher fares it would be easy to
conclude that passengers aren't interested in discounts. But as the
Department of Transportation recently noted, after Sun Country
Airlines started twice-daily discount service between Milwaukee and
Minneapolis-St. Paul a year ago, fares on that route, dominated by
Northwest, fell 55.4 percent (from $240 to $107) while passenger
traffic rose 76.7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
