<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1418 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-BAXTER15-COX     08-14 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BAXTER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AL GORE'S PROBLEM IS NOT BILL CLINTON
 &HT;    By TOM BAXTER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Al Gore's big problem, so the story line went
before his predecessor's speech Monday night, is too much Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his wife, according to the broadband of
preconvention analysis, have been leaching limelight and sucking up
campaign money that might have gone to Gore. The only blessing, it
would seem, is that after Monday night, they're gone.
</P>
<P>
   As often as it has been repeated, there's a great deal wrong
with this logic. At bottom, it's a means of injecting drama into
what amounts to a natural progression: Two-term presidents, by
their nature, cast a shadow, and vice presidents running for
president have to struggle to stand on center stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really think of any way for it not to happen that
way,'' observed Education Secretary Richard Riley after speaking to
the Georgia delegation Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very natural when you have a president going out and a
vice president coming in, that you have a period of saying goodbye
to the president, and then of welcoming in the new voice,'' Riley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there were similar stories in 1988, as Vice President
George Bush prepared to take the reins from Ronald Reagan in New
Orleans. The story has longer legs this year, however, because of
the Democrats' perceived desire to distance themselves from the
Monica Lewinsky scandal, and because Gore is farther behind George
W. Bush than Bush's father trailed Michael Dukakis in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   With the selection of Sen. Joe Leiberman as his running mate,
Gore clearly has attempted to separate himself from the scandalous
side of Bill Clinton. But Gore's core problem isn't that Clinton
continues to get too much attention, and to believe too literally
in this analysis is to risk throwing the baby out with the bath
water. If Gore does turn this election around, he will owe as much
to Clinton's legacy as the elder Bush did to Reagan's.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of numbers from the latest CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll
starkly illustrate this point. Sixty-eight percent of those polled
rated Clinton's presidency a success, while 47 percent said there
was no chance they were going to vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that only 7 percent thought Gore's association with
Clinton helped him, while 37 percent thought it hurt. But what that
really means is that when you add up all the people who care either
way about Gore's association with Clinton, it's still a smaller
percentage than those who are sure they aren't voting for him.
</P>
<P>
   What these numbers suggest is that Gore's real problem is his
personal favorability. That may be due in part to the familiarity _
and inevitably, fatigue _ that has grown around him over the past
eight years, while Bush remains relatively unknown.
</P>
<P>
   But his difficulties in getting the public to warm up to his
candidacy are not unlike those he had when he ran for president in
1988, when Clinton was still governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for all his faults, is the first Democrat since
Franklin Roosevelt to be elected president twice. His legacy is
infernally complicated, and his personal weaknesses have been a
matter of national obsession for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, he is not Al Gore's problem.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
