<HEADER>
A1420 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-ESSAY-ROME-$AD     08-14 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ESSAY-ROME-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ACCIDENTAL PILGRIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 20) 
 By RAY CORMIER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until I went to Rome this summer, the word pilgrim usually
conjured up images of the dour early arrivals on American shores. I
certainly couldn't conceive of myself as a pilgrim, the kind who
makes a journey to a holy place for religious purposes. I'm a
lifelong Catholic, but I don't have the kind of faith that I
associate with people who go to great lengths to visit the four
major basilicas of Rome for Holy Year indulgences.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rome overflows with both the sacred and the profane, and
there are plenty of reasons to visit the city. And so when my wife,
Eileen, had an opportunity to take a graduate education course at
the Jesuit Curia, the order's headquarters, a block from St.
Peter's Square, we jumped at the chance to finally visit Rome. We
decided to ignore the warnings about how crowded the city would be
for this Roman Catholic Jubilee year.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, we more than mingled with those crowds of
special visitors: the trip, organized by Fordham University mainly
for teachers and administrators in Catholic schools, included tours
to all the big basilicas and a papal Mass. Not only would I get a
first-hand look at all those pilgrims but I would also become one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The experience began with our accommodations. An 18-room guest
house, the Fraterna Domus, is run by sisters of the Volunteers of
Christian Social Service. It was spotless, quiet and spartan. Our
small, L-shaped, marble-tiled room had three twin beds (the alcove
with the third bed actually gave us more room than most of the
other guests had), a desk, a small, low table and a closet. Our
compact private bathroom somehow included a sink, a toilet, a bidet
and a shower _ but no shower curtain.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The price was right, though _ $45 apiece a night, including a
minimal breakfast. Do pilgrims need television or wake-up calls? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While friendly and helpful, the sisters were serious about the
11 p.m. curfew. When they gave the key to our group's leader, Dr.
Gerald Cattaro, so some of our companions could try to find some
night life, two who returned separately (in fact, earlier than the
others) knew they had received a scolding from the sister who let
them in, even without understanding a word of Italian.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Fraterna, though, is just a five-minute walk to the
spellbinding Piazza Navona (plenty of nightly entertainment, and
free), and about 10 minutes to the Spanish Steps, the Piazza del
Popolo, the Pantheon and Castel Sant'Angelo. So the secular tourist
in me would have been satisfied even without the group bus tours to
other classic sights: the Colosseum, the Forum and the Sistine
Chapel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Cattaro kept saying, we were on a pilgrimage, and the
program quickly made us feel it. On guided tours, we eventually
passed through all four Holy Doors, at the basilicas of St.
Peter's, St. Mary Major, St. John Lateran and St. Paul's Outside
the Walls. Cardinal Giovanni Cheli, a friend of Cattaro's who is a
former representative of the Vatican to the United Nations, said
Mass for us at the Basilica of SS. Cosmos and Damian, next to the
Forum. I'd never heard of this church, but it has a colorful mosaic
ceiling so brilliant that it didn't seem possible that it was
almost 1,500 years old.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We also attended a special, intimate Mass in the former living
quarters of St. Ignatius Loyola, founder of the Jesuits. The 35 in
our group sat and stood in an unadorned whitewashed room with a
timbered ceiling, next to Ignatius' former bedroom, where his desk
and chest of drawers are displayed. It was a casual, warm liturgy,
without pomp. I imagined that it was similar to the gatherings of
the early Christians in the catacombs and the area uncovered in the
fascinating excavations leading to St. Peter's grave under St.
Peter's Basilica (begun in 1939, secretly, out of fear the Nazis
would find out), which we later visited.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At just about every stop, we saw other pilgrims. In fact, a
group had lunch at the Fraterna on our first day _ the sisters
offer one of the best bargains in town: $10 for a home-cooked,
four-course meal, as long as you make reservations before noon and
don't mind a set menu (wine or soft drinks are a little extra). The
diners, Italians but not Romans, wore matching, distinctive
kerchiefs around their necks, like Boy Scouts, and talked and
smiled and laughed nonstop.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we heard groups break into prayer or song, as a cadre
of about 30 did in St. John Lateran. It served to remind me,
surrounded by tourists, that we were in a church, after all, not a
museum.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, however, it was at the evening papal Mass in
St. Peter's Square for the Feast of St. Peter that we were immersed
in pilgrim spirit. The excitement of the crowd, which filled about
three-fourths of the 35,000 seats in the vast space, was almost
frightening. Some had shoved us out of their way to get through the
metal detectors under Bernini's magnificent colonnade in a rush for
the closest seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We were so early that we found space in about the 10th row, and
a young American couple sat down next to us. They quickly left,
though, after we told them that Mass was still a couple of hours
away and would probably last that long again.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But their seats were quickly taken and, at one point, the
90-degree heat and crowding had me thinking that perhaps the couple
had made the right decision. But since we were near the front,
shadows from the facade that almost inexplicably hid Michelangelo's
great dome brought us some relief from the blazing sun. That was
around the time the Swiss Guards took up their positions _ they
would not budge for hours _ and formally attired men ushered in
families of the honored guests. These included the church's newest
archbishops, among them New York's Edward M. Egan, who were to
receive their palliums, stoles that signify their ecclesiastical
rank. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As we waited, the atmosphere was laid back, with people
chattering as they cowered from the sun under umbrellas or stood in
hope of a breeze. Three rows ahead, a man held a radio to his ear
listening to the play by play of the European soccer championships
semifinal between Italy and the Netherlands. Homage was being paid
to both of Italy's national religions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 6:29 it became clear why the crowd was there. The tiny,
hunched-over, red-clad form of John Paul II appeared through the
great door behind the outdoor altar. Applause began, and as the
pope, looking extremely frail, slowly moved toward the altar, the
clapping swept backward in waves across the square.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two dozen archbishops, also in red, huge bunches of red
roses on the steps, and the red-draped altar canopy framed the
pontiff. As we sat for the chanting of the Kyrie (Lord, have
mercy), the people just to our right started waving tiny Polish
flags and red-and-white scarves, trying to get the pope's
attention. Smiling, they half rose in their chairs to see if they
would elicit a glance, a wave, any kind of notice from the altar.
Eileen and I looked at each other, stunned by what seemed behavior
from a football game or concert.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it happened again _ just after the gospel. And again _ after
the archbishops received their palliums. And again _ at the end of
the Mass. The Poles were not alone: a young nun in full habit waved
Peru's flag when the Peruvian archbishop was called up, and the
Croatian archbishop was cheered lustily by a flag-waving group of
about 50 of his compatriots.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And throughout the liturgy, there were muffled sounds of the
soccer match on the radio. Just as Mass ended at sunset, about
8:40, with the pope getting into a jeeplike vehicle to ride among
the crowd that surged to barriers to get close to him, car horns
started blaring in the distance. Italy had won!  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This holy, and worldly, city was ready for another celebration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
