 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   P O L I T I C S &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This city has changed drastically since John
Fitzgerald Kennedy stood on the podium in the old Memorial Coliseum
here to accept his party's nomination for president and to tell
Americans about his vision of a ``New Frontier.'' It's not just
that LA is bigger, smoggier and even more culturally diverse, but
its sparkling new skyscrapers _ once forbidden for fear of
earthquakes _ are testimony to the city's confidence, if not
arrogance. By BOB RAY SANDERS. Story has moved in ``p'' political
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CVN-KENNEDY-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Forget the Playboy Mansion. Forget that
$100,000-a-couple brunch today at Barbra's house. And, Al Gore
would beg of you, please forget that little soiree four years ago
out at a suburban Buddhist temple. This is where the money is
flowing this week, on top of $3 million already donated to
political campaigns from residents of a single ZIP code: Beverly
Hills 90210. By BUD KENNEDY. Story has moved in ``p'' political
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CVN-DAILY SHOW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The funniest (and, one could argue, most incisive)
coverage of the Republican convention came from the team at ``The
Daily Show'' on Comedy Central. We look back at the best bits from
the Republican Convention as the ``Daily Show'' correspondents
prepare for the Democratic Convention. By TODD CAMP. Story will
move in ``p'' political category. (Accompanied by CVN-DAILY
SHOW-CORRESPONDENTS.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
