<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FALLBOOKS-1000(3Takes     08-14 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLBOOKS-1000(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAFING THROUGH THE BOOKS OF AUTUMN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JEFF GUINN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The kings are dead. Long live the new kings _ whoever they turn
out to be.
</P>
<P>
   Fall 2000 finds the book industry at an unexpected crossroads.
For the past few decades, so-called ``entertainment'' fiction
writers have dominated bestseller lists, then disappeared (remember
Arthur Hailey, anyone?), but the mainstays of recognized literary
excellence could always be counted on to sell hundreds of thousands
of books, in addition to garnering ongoing critical kudos.
</P>
<P>
   But while the better-known ``pop'' fiction writers have
continued to flourish _ John Grisham's ``The Brethren'' sold 2
million copies and J.K. Rowling's ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of
Fire'' has sold 3.8 million and counting _ the old heavyweights
have begun to stumble. In recent months, literary lions Philip Roth
(''The Human Stain'') and John Updike (''Gertrude and Claudius'')
have had first-rate novels published _ and neither sold well. Other
longtime reliables like Thomas Sanchez (''Day of the Bees'') and
the late Joseph Heller (''Portrait of an Artist, As a Young Man'')
have also failed to ring many cash registers.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it's time to wonder just who will be proclaimed the
next ``great'' writer. Several candidates, including Jane Hamilton,
Ha Jin, Barry Lopez, Kazuo Ishiguro, William Gay, David Hollander,
Terry Kay and Rick Moody all have books being published between
Sept. 1 and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, veteran ``literary'' writers will be fighting for
attention as well in the coming months _ Tom Wolfe, Margaret
Atwood, Gore Vidal, Alice Walker, Larry McMurtry, Barbara
Kingsolver and Armistead Maupin all have imminent titles. Updike,
not one to give up easily, is back for another try.
</P>
<P>
   Historians Stephen Ambrose, Richard Ben Cramer, David Levering
Lewis and William J. Cooper, among others, deliver much-anticipated
nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the highbrow is crowding out the mass-market offerings.
Bestseller list perennials Anne Rice, Patricia Cornwell, John
Sandford, Dave Barry and Jonathan Kellerman are back this fall.
More professional wrestlers have penned their memoirs. Even the
Beatles have a book they'd like you to buy.
</P>
<P>
   So it's going to be an interesting, if uncertain, literary
winter. Here's our annual guide to the books that are heading for
the shelves, with special attention to the best and the most
promising.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST OF THE OLD GUARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. ``The Way Forward Is With a Broken Heart'' by Alice Walker
(Random House, October). It seems odd to think that a former
Pulitzer Prize winner could be in a make-or-break situation. But
many critics _ as well as many of her loyal readers _ believe
Walker hasn't really offered much since 1982's ``The Color
Purple.'' (Quick: Name even one of her subsequent books.) A look at
the galley proof of ``The Way Forward Is With a Broken Heart''
indicates that Alice Walker did, indeed, have more than one great
book in her. It's a mesmerizing collection of short fiction based
on experiences in the author's life.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Boone's Lick'' by Larry McMurtry (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
November). Whether McMurtry wants to face it or not, what the
reading public wants from him is western fiction. After some time
off from his signature genre for two first-person ruminations
(''Walter Benjamin at the Dairy Queen'' and ``Roads'') and an
excellent, if overlooked, novel (''Duane's Depressed''), McMurtry
has another western yarn to offer. This one follows the lives of
the Cecil family as fate draws them toward the Fetterman Massacre
of 1866.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Hooking Up'' by Tom Wolfe (Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux,
October). No, it's not another meganovel. Instead, ``Hooking Up''
comprises reprints of novellas originally published in magazines,
plus some essays. After ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' and ``A Man
in Full,'' it's easy to forget that Wolfe cut his literary teeth
with groundbreaking magazine work. ``Hooking Up'' will remind you
that Tom Wolfe is an author of ``great'' variety.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``The Blind Assassin'' by Margaret Atwood (Doubleday/Nan A.
Talese, September). Every Atwood book has some specific theme, some
point it intends to make. But while ``The Blind Assassin'' isn't
going to be as easy to decipher as, say, ``The Handmaid's Tale,''
this convoluted novel-within-a-novel _ the protagonist wants to
find out if her sister's death was really accidental, only to have
her story eclipsed by a seemingly unrelated second story _ will
reward readers who stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   Honorable mentions ``The Golden Age'' by Gore Vidal (Doubleday,
September): another installment in the saga of the fictional
Sanford family. ``Pagan Babies'' by Elmore Leonard (Dell,
September): A priest may not be a priest _ so, what is he?. ``The
Night Listener'' by Armistead Maupin (HarperCollins, $26): Radio
writer bonds with an abused child. ``Licks of Love'' by John Updike
(Knopf, November): short stories and ``Rabbit Remembered,'' a coda
on Harry Angstrom.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CONTENDERS FOR THE THRONE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Disobedience'' by Jane Hamilton (Doubleday, October). Too
many critics have dismissed Jane Hamilton as simply the product of
Oprah's Book Club. Reverse snobbism being what it is,
anti-Oprahites have failed to see the immense quality of ``A Map of
the World'' and ``The Book of Ruth.'' But ``Disobedience'' may just
put an end to such carping. In this compelling story, 17-year-old
Henry Shaw reads his mother's e-mail, with disastrous results. Life
will never be the same again _ and, in Hamilton's gifted literary
hands, how Henry changes and why is a story to be savored.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``The Bridegroom: Stories'' by Ha Jin (Pantheon, October).
Last year, Ha Jin was a surprise National Book Award winner for the
novel ``Waiting.'' Now he returns with short fiction about Chinese
men and women adjusting to life in the West. The literary quality
cannot be denied, but will a large audience of non-Chinese readers
really go out and buy the book? Let's hope so, because Ha Jin
deserves to be a major literary figure.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Demonology: Stories'' by Rick Moody (Little, Brown &AMP; Co.,
December/January). You'd be hard-pressed to find any critic or
fellow writer who wouldn't praise Moody's ``Garden State'' or ``The
Ice Storm.'' The man is simply a marvel; his prose yanks audiences
into odd reading rhythms that somehow turn out just right _ sort of
like Miles Davis experimenting with the limits of jazz. Yet Moody's
quirky and complex work hasn't built a large audience.
``Demonology: Stories'' probably won't change that, and we should
be glad he hasn't compromised his unique voice for greater sales.
</P>
<P>
   Honorable mentions ``L.I.E.'' by David Hollander (Villard,
September): interwoven stories about riders on the Long Island
Expressway. ``When We Were Orphans'' by Kazuo Ishiguro (Knopf,
September): After being orphaned there at age 9, man returns to
Shanghai 20 years later. ``Taking Lottie Home'' by Terry Kay
(Morrow, October): Ex-ballplayers meet a woman who changes their
lives. ``Light Action in the Caribbean'' by Barry Lopez (Knopf,
November): short fiction from a master writer. ``Provinces of
Night'' by William Gay (Doubleday, December): After 20 years, a man
returns to backwoods Tennessee and the family he abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CERTAIN BESTSELLERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Prodigal Summer'' by Barbara Kingsolver (HarperCollins,
November). It's time to come out and say it: Circa 2000, Barbara
Kingsolver is the best writer currently dominating the bestseller
list. That doesn't mean she's the best writer, period, but she's
certainly the finest craftsman to sell in the hundreds of
thousands. ``Prodigal Summer'' is more of what her legion of fans
expect _ a solid story about Deanna Wolfe, a wildlife biologist who
finds more than her work to think about in Southern Appalachia. If
that sounds like an outtake of a Nora Roberts novel, think again.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``The Devil's Code'' by John Sandford (Putnam, October).
Sandford has made his bestseller mark with cop Lucas Davenport and
the ``Prey'' mystery franchise, but his other ongoing series _
following artist/computer whiz/professional criminal Kidd _ is even
better. High-tech high jinks abound here as Kidd tries to crack a
case where the bad guys are linked to government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Dave Barry Is Not Taking This Sitting Down'' by Dave Barry
(Crown, October): One of the subjects is low-flow toilets _ hence
the title. Yes, the humor is often sophomoric, but that doesn't
prevent it from being laugh-out-loud funny and often right on
point. Sales of the last few collections of Barry's newspaper
columns have dipped; this one should mark his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Honorable mentions ``Merrick'' by Anne Rice (Knopf, October): A
new tale that ``weaves the witches' world with the vampires'
world.'' ``The Last Precinct'' by Patricia Cornwell (Putnam,
November): Kay Scarpetta tries to solve an ages-old mystery. ``Dr.
Death'' by Jonathan Kellerman (Random House, December): When a
doctor famed for assisting suicides dies himself, Dr. Alex Delaware
gets involved.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BALLYHOOED NONFICTION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Joe DiMaggio: The Hero's Life'' by Richard Ben Cramer
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, November). There is simply no other nonfiction
writer like Cramer. His ability to get inside the heads of his
subjects is uncanny. That's why this book, all about the
ultra-reclusive Yankee Clipper, is one of the most highly
anticipated titles of the fall.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``W.E.B. Du Bois: The Fight for Equality and the American
Century'' by David Levering Lewis (Henry Holt, October). This is
the second installment of a three-part biography, and Part I won
the Pulitzer. As Lewis continues to demonstrate why W.E.B. Du Bois
was surely one of the greatest Americans of any era, he also makes
it clear that a second Pulitzer isn't out of the question. It would
be wise, though, to pick up a copy of volume one before tackling
volume two.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Sex &AMP; Power'' by Susan Estrich (Putnam, September). Guess
what _ women still aren't getting an even break. What makes
Estrich's book different is that she doesn't waste pages and
chapters bemoaning the obvious. Rather, Estrich focuses on women
themselves and asks what mistakes they may be making that lead to
ongoing prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``A Life in the Twentieth Century'' by Arthur M. Schlesinger
Jr. (Houghton Mifflin, November). Schlesinger, the former JFK aide
who has won two Pulitzers for previous books, finally views past
decades through the lens of his own experiences.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Rabbi Jesus'' by Bruce Chilton (Doubleday, October).
Chilton, a professor/priest, presents Jesus here as a man and a
teacher of his time. This is the sort of book that gets discussed
on radio talk shows; no matter what your personal religious
leanings, or lack of same, you'll probably find much here to talk
about with your own family and friends. It's safe to predict that
those who insist every word in the Bible is absolute historical
fact won't be praising ``Rabbi Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Honorable mentions ``The Prince of Tennessee: The Rise of Al
Gore'' by David Maraniss and Ellen Nakashima (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
September): Maraniss, whose biography of Bill Clinton is considered
one of the best and most objective, takes on Gore. ``Nothing Like
It in the World'' by Stephen Ambrose (Simon &AMP; Schuster, September):
the story of the transcontinental railroad. ``Off Camera: Private
Thoughts Made Public'' by Ted Koppel (Knopf, September):
supposedly, all the things he didn't mention on TV. ``Natural
Blonde'' by Liz Smith (Hyperion, September): Fort Worth's own
celebrity chronicler tells her life story. ``Singing Him My Song''
by Malachy McCourt (HarperCollins, October): second
autobiographical installment from Frank McCourt's brother. ``A
Short Guide to a Happy Life'' by Anna Quindlen (Random House,
October): Columnist says she's going to explain ``how to fully
engage our days.'' ``King: The Photobiography of Martin Luther King
Jr.'' by Charles Johnson and Bob Adelman (Viking, November):
Advertised as great prose illuminated by equally great photography.
</P>
<P>
   THE WRASSLERS: The last two autobiographies of World Wrestling
Federation superstars _ Mick Foley and Dwayne ``The Rock'' Johnson
_ both hit No. 1 on the New York Times bestseller list, and Chyna
plans to be the third with Chyna (HarperCollins, September). Also
from the grunt brigrade, ``Do I Stand Alone?'' by
grappler-turned-governor Jesse Ventura (Pocket, September) and
``I'm Next'' by Goldberg (Crown, November).
</P>
<P>
   THE GREAT UNKNOWN: Putnam's fall catalog promises a new novel by
the very talented Amy Tan _ but details aren't available because
Tan is going to be working on it right up until the presses begin
to roll.
</P>
<P>
   MOST INTRIGUING BOOK: Stephen King's ``On Writing: A Memoir of
the Craft'' (Scribner, October) is rumored to be as much a
confessional as a how-to.
</P>
<P>
   BEST BOOK BY AN UNKNOWN AUTHOR: You heard it here _ ``The Blood
Runs Like a River Through My Dreams,'' a memoir by Native-American
writer Nasdijj (Houghton Mifflin, October), is going to be huge.
</P>
<P>
   THE MOST PERSONAL MEMOIR: The author of the justly praised ``The
Liar's Club'' continues with the story of her teen years, including
``the thrills and terrors of her sexual awakening,'' with
``Cherry'' by Mary Karr (Viking, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   ENOUGH, ALREADY: ``The Arrogance of Power: The Secret World of
Richard Nixon'' by Anthony Summers (Viking, September). It seems
legislation will be needed to stop the endless flow of books about
the alleged misdeeds of Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   THE SADDEST BOOK: ``Never Die Easy'' by Walter Payton, with Don
Yaeger (Villard, September). The Chicago Bears all-time great
running back died of liver cancer before this book hit print. Much
of his message here is a lesson in courageous acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   SERPENT'S TOOTH AWARD: Margaret A. Salinger, daughter of J.D.,
offers ``Reflections on Reclusion'' (Pocket, September). First an
ex-lover, now a daughter. Can't a reclusive genius writer trust
``anybody?''
</P>
<P>
   A BOOK EVERYONE SHOULD READ: ``An American Story'' by Debra J.
Dickinson (Pantheon, September) is about growing up under difficult
racial and emotional circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ALL YOU NEED IS LOVE _ AND A FAT WALLET: After so many books
about them, the three surviving Beatles tell their own stories in
``The Beatles Anthology'' (Chronicle Books, October). There's no
telling how much is ghostwritten, though, and it's pricey _ $60.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOOK WE NEEDED LEAST: ``All That Glitters Is Not Gold'' by
Marla Maples (ReganBooks, $24). Another ex-wife of The Donald
spills her guts.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
