<HEADER>
A1442 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BIZMAGS0815-COX     08-14 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Creative economy' may become the new economy
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The ``new economy'' some day will be the old economy.
By that time, the new economy will be the ``creative economy,''
according to Business Week (Aug. 21-28).
</P>
<P>
   The magazine takes a stab in its cover story at predicting what
the corporation of the 21st century will be like, with the aim of
helping existing companies ``thrive in the decades ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many surprises pop up in Business Week's forecast, but the
ones that do are attention-grabbers. For one, the magazine suggests
that investors are likely to lose influence. That's because the
``commodity they supply _ money _ is no longer scarce,'' Business
Week offers. ``What's scarce are the good ideas,'' the magazine
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Business Week: Too much of a good thing is hurting the
reputation of Stanford University's MBA program. So many grads are
starting their own businesses or taking jobs in Silicon Valley that
some major companies have given up trying to recruit at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate entertainment
</P>
<P>
   Wired (September) has something for anyone with a passing
interest in Time Warner or America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine suggests that Time Warner brings more than content
and delivery systems to its planned merger with America Online.
According to Wired, the little extra involves ``a long history of
amazingly expert corporate infighting, ankle-biting, and all-around
backstabbing.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's advice to Chairman Steve Case of America Online
is fairly simple: confiscate the long knives.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune's annual list of fastest growing companies shows up in
the Aug. 14 issue. Companies are ranked on earnings per share
growth, revenue growth and total return _ change in stock price
plus any dividends. The magazine measures the companies over a
three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Three Atlanta-based companies made this year's list: Profit
Recovery Group International is 59th, down from 40th a year
earlier; AHL Services is 71st; and Nova is 98th. Neither of the
latter two was ranked last year.
</P>
<P>
   4Kids Entertainment _ a beneficiary of Pokemon _ took the top
spot on the Fortune list.
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell
</P>
<P>
   Looking for the next sure thing? Kiplinger's (September) offers
some bets _ not for this quarter or this year _ but for the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine claims to have spotted nine companies ``standing on
the brink of enormous gains in revenue and profit.'' Kiplinger's
goes on to acknowledge that there are on guarantees in investing,
but says the nine it picked ``are as close as it gets to slam dunks
in coming years.'' The nine are Applied Biosystems, Genentech,
Medimmune, Flextronics, American Tower, Maxim Integrated Products,
VeriSign, Charles Schwab and Capital One Financial.
</P>
<P>
   More change is afoot
</P>
<P>
   The shakeout of Internet incubators has eliminated some of the
exuberance investors in the industry felt not long ago, notes the
Economist (Aug. 12-18). The magazine looks at some of the weakness
in the industry and at how some incubators are changing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
