<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FLA-SPRINGS0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A refreshing dive into some of Florida's freshest, coolest
waters
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ginnie Springs
</P>
<P>
   7300 N. E. Ginnie Springs Road, High Springs. Phone: (904)
454-2202.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A second-magnitude spring, Ginnie has a
flow of 29 million gallons per day.
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 72 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: While kids floated in bright-colored inner tubes and
boats, divers searched the caves below. We could see the bubbles
from the air tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Ginnie Springs is an extremely pretty place, with its turquoise
waters and its shady campgrounds. It's easy to understand why
divers from all over the world come here.
</P>
<P>
   You actually get seven springs for the price of one (Deer, Twin,
Dogwood, Ginnie and three that are part of the Devil Spring
system). All of them dot the Santa Fe River. The clear, blue spring
water provides a stark contrast to the dark, tannin-stained river.
When the two mix, as they do at the river's edge, the results are
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: More divers learn to cavern and cave dive at
Ginnie Springs than anywhere else, according to the Ginnie Springs
Web site. Be warned: If you want to explore the caves, you must be
certified. Cave diving can be dangerous. At least 27 divers have
lost their lives here.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Swimming, diving, tubing, canoeing, kayaking,
hiking, camping, picnicking.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $7 per person, per day.
</P>
<P>
   Homosassa Springs
</P>
<P>
   4150 S. Suncoast Blvd, Homosassa. Phone: (352) 628-5343.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A first-magnitude spring, Homosassa has a
flow of 113.8 million gallons per day
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 75 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: Unless you swim with them, you're probably not going
to get any closer to a manatee than you will inside the ``fish
bowl,'' a sort of reverse aquarium. The bowl allows visitors to go
below the surface of the water and watch the manatees as they munch
on carrots and lettuce and swim inches away from the glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also see turtles and a variety of saltwater and
freshwater fish that can travel unrestricted between the headwaters
and the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Also fun: the zoo, which features a 40-year-old hippo, a couple
of American bald eagles, a silver fox, a Florida black bear,
alligators galore, lots of flamingos and other birds.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: The park is a rehabilitation center and refuge
for endangered West Indian manatees that have been orphaned or
injured in the wild. Most of the birds and animals living at
Homosassa could not survive in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Educational programs about manatee, alligators, and
wildlife encounters. Picnicking, hiking.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $7.95 for adults (age 13 and over), $ 4.95 for
children ages 3 through 12; free for kids under 3.
</P>
<P>
   Manatee Springs State Park
</P>
<P>
   11650 N.W. 115 St., Chiefland. Phone: (352) 493-6072.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A first-magnitude spring, Manatee has a
flow of 116.9 million gallons per day
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 72 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: Surrounded by cypress, gum, ash, and maple trees,
Manatee Springs is an ideal place for canoe rides.
</P>
<P>
   The morning we visited, the swimming area was beginning to fill
with children and their mothers. A trio of moms were doing some
serious toe-dipping and then retreating up the stairs to warm up on
the park benches. The kids didn't seem to mind a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: Located on the Suwannee River just 23 miles
upstream from the Gulf of Mexico, the park consists of 2,075 acres.
It opened to the public in 1955. At this spring, you need to visit
in fall or winter months to see the manatee.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Picnicking, fishing, swimming, canoeing, hiking and
biking on the 8.5-mile north end trail system, scuba diving, nature
study and camping.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $3.25 per vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Poe Springs
</P>
<P>
   28800 N.W. 182 Ave., High Springs. Phone: (904) 454-1992
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A second-magnitude springs, Poe has a flow
of 60 million gallons per day
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 73 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: A cypress nature walk leads you through the woods to a
splendid, blue-green swimming hole. The day we arrived, it was full
of summer campers. The trek to the spring is long, but a dip in the
cool swimming hole makes up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Poe is along the winding course of the Santa Fe River. It is
owned by Alachua County and managed by the North Central Florida
YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: Moonlight canoe trips are routinely scheduled
(Sept. 16, Oct. 14 and Nov. 11) on the Santa Fe to Poe Springs
park. Tiki torches light the bank of the river. Tickets are $25 and
includes a picnic lunch.)
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Swimming, boating, picnicking, hiking, camping.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $4 per person
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow Springs
</P>
<P>
   9158 S.W. 81st Pl. Road, Dunnellon. Phone: (352) 489-8503.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A first-magnitude springs, Rainbow has a
flow of 493.2 million gallons per day
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 70 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: Rainbow is a good description for these multi-colored
waters. We sat outside of the snack bar sipping lemonade and
watching swimmers and canoers in the magnificent waters below. The
view is awesome.
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow Springs State Park drew 112,000 visitors in 1999. With
the park's elegant gardens and three waterfalls built in the '30s,
tourists and locals love it. We did, too.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: In the 1930s at the spring, a lodge,
bathhouses, gift shop, boat dock and picnic pavilion were built. A
glass-bottom boat launched in 1934. In 1939 came a reptile exhibit,
alligators, monkeys and tropical birds. By 1967, after a few more
owners, Sperry &AMP; Hutchinson (of S&AMP;H Green Stamp fame) and Holiday
Inns bought the attraction and pumped money into it. In 1990,
Marion County paid $1 million and the state of Florida $9.26
million to buy the 55-acre, long-closed family attraction and 910
surrounding acres off U.S. 41 in Dunnellon.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Swimming, snorkeling, tubing,diving, hiking,
canoeing, picnicking.
</P>
<P>
   Admission cost: $1
</P>
<P>
   Silver Springs
</P>
<P>
   5656 E. Silver Springs Blvd., Silver Springs. Phone: (352)
236-2121. www.silversprings.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A first-magnitude spring, Silver spews 532
million gallons per day _ the largest known flow in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 76 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: In 1859, an archaeologist, John LeConte, wrote that
the most remarkable feature of this place was ``the truly
extraordinary transparency of the water ... surpassing anything
which can be imagined.'' His assessment holds true today, not only
for Silver Springs, but all of the springs we visited.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, swimming is allowed only on weekends. And,
since we arrived on a Friday, we spent the day taking a
glass-bottom boat ride, a jungle cruise and strolling through the
gardens and the petting zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Local legend has it that if people have their picture taken
standing surrounded by the trunk of the horseshoe palm tree at the
water's edge, they will have five years of good luck. We stuffed
lottery tickets in our pockets and posed with the lucky tree. (No
winners, to date, but we have have our fingers crossed.)
</P>
<P>
   Interesting facts: The glass-bottom boat, invented in 1878 by
Hullam Jones, made its debut here in 1910 and has been a popular
attraction ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Weismuller came here to film Tarzan movies. But he
wasn't the only star to work in Silver Springs. Others include
Gregory Peck and Jane Wyman for Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings' ``The
Yearling''; Esther Williams for ``Jupiter's Darling,'' Gary Cooper
for ``Distant Drums,'' and Lloyd Bridges for more than 100 episodes
of ``Sea Hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Reptile shows, boat rides, petting zoo, monkey
island, playland for kids, an antique and race car show, swimming,
and concerts. There's a large water park near the springs. The park
also hosts a concert series with country acts.
</P>
<P>
   Admission cost: $30.95 for adults; $21.95 for kids 3-10.
</P>
<P>
   Wakulla Springs
</P>
<P>
   550 Wakulla Park Drive, Wakulla Springs, 32305. Phone: (850)
224-5950.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A first-magnitude spring, Wakulla has a
flow of 252 million gallons per day.
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 73 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: Tarzan movies were filmed here and Old Joe (a
12-foot-long, 650-pound, 200-year-old dead alligator) is enshrined
in the lodge. There's a great swimming hole, diving ramps, and a
1937 lodge with marble floors, an ornate lobby ceiling, antique
furniture and what looks like one of the first elevators ever made.
</P>
<P>
   But what really lifted our spirits was the glass-bottom boat
ride. The guide, clearly a fan of fishing, diving and tale-telling,
had us applauding Henry, the pole-vaulting fish.
</P>
<P>
   After the guide hollered out to the reel star, (Hen-REEEEE!) we
watched as the black bass, less than a foot long, sailed out and
flopped over a cypress pole several feet under water. Henry, or his
descendants, have been doing the stunt since 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: Wakulla has been a tourist favorite since the
1930s. The park has the world's largest and deepest freshwater
springs and is surrounded by 3,000 acres of virgin forest. Ponce de
Leon discovered the springs in 1513 and thought it was the fountain
of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Hiking trails, picnic areas, swimming, diving, boat
rides ($4.50).
</P>
<P>
   Admission cost: $3.25 per vehicle
</P>
<P>
   Warm Mineral Springs
</P>
<P>
   Halfway between Sarasota and Fort Myers. Take U.S. 41 to Ortiz
Road right to the springs. Phone: (941) 426-1692
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A third-magnitude spring, Warm Mineral has
a flow of 9 million gallons per day.
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 87 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: People come here believing that the high mineral
content restores vigor. They say it helps people with muscular
problems, arthritis and rheumatism.
</P>
<P>
   The bathers we saw were elderly. There's a gift shop with terry
cover-ups, bathing caps, knickknacks and a lot of pamphlets on
staying healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Locals say Warm Mineral Springs was Ponce de Leon's destination
when he came to this country in search of the fountain of youth in
1513. We thought the resort, which is privately owned, looked like
it needed a face lift.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: Warm Mineral Springs, which is listed in the
National Register of Historic Places, is Florida's only truly warm
spring open to the public. The water has five times more mineral
content than all other famous spas in the world, including Hot
Springs, Ark., and Baden Baden, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the spring was founded in the 1800s, although
archaeological evidence shows that people lived here more than
10,000 years ago. The resort was built in the early 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Bathing, swimming, picnicking.
</P>
<P>
   Admission cost: No charge just to look, but if you want to swim,
or even stick your toes in the water, you'll pay $10 ($5 for kids).
</P>
<P>
   Weeki Wachee
</P>
<P>
   45 minutes north of Tampa at the intersection of U.S. 9 and
State Road 50. Phone: (877)-GO-WEEKI or www.weekiwachee.com
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A first-magnitude spring, Weeki Wachee has
a flow of 113 million gallons per day.
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 75 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: Although The Little Mermaid show in the Weeki Wachee
amphitheater is geared to kids, adults will be amused. The high
school boy, who seemed to run the show, not only sold popcorn, but
played the tambourine during the performance and made sure kids
weren't clogging up the stairways. On the other side of the glass,
the mermaids swam and lip-synched to recorded songs, taking breaths
of air from hoses.
</P>
<P>
   We recommend the wilderness river cruise, or the ``geezer''
cruise, as I like to call it. Our grandfatherly guide, with his
Rodney Dangerfield delivery, told silly jokes that fell on mostly
deaf ears because most of the passengers were kids or from foreign
countries. You had to be over 45 to get his punch lines. But more
than the funny old man, the cruise was a delight because pelicans
and egrets guided the boat down the river. We saw dozens of birds
in such a very short time. Most of them were healthy, but we saw
some wounded guys, as well, at the pelican orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   Also spotted: a pair of manatee and a raccoon.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: Mermaids began performing at Weeki Wachee in
1947 when Navy frogman Newton Perry built the underwater theater 45
minutes north of Tampa. Some of the famous guests the mermaids have
entertained include Elvis Presley, Esther Williams, Don Knotts and
Howard Cosell.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Live mermaid shows, nature boat tour, swimming,
diving, canoeing, water slides, petting zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Admission cost: $14.95 for adults; $10.95 for children 3-10
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
