<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITHSPRINGS-0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is a spring?
</P>
<P>
   A spring is an opening at or near the surface of the earth where
water from underground sources flows. Florida's springs are formed
because of the porous limestone topography.
</P>
<P>
   After it rains, the water infiltrates the earth and seeps down,
replenishing the aquifer below. Some of the water moves slowly
through spaces the size of grains of sand. Other water moves
quickly down through sinks and swallet holes.
</P>
<P>
   Deep underground, this water then moves horizontally along
bedding planes and fractures. This is where the moving water
dissolves the rock, creating a network of underground conduits.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's springs are especially large and productive because of
the tremendous size of the aquifer that supports them. The springs
here are artesian, rising from an artesian aquifer that holds water
trapped beneath impermeable clay or nonporous bedrock.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Florida's springs are in the north-central part of the
state, where the aquifer is near the surface and where rivers have
gnawed through confining clay beds.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: www.britannica.com, www.floridasprings.com and ``The
Springs of Florida'' by Doug Stamm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
