<P>
   EDITORS: The New York Times is planning several pages of
Democratic convention-related stories for Tuesday, Aug. 15. The New
York Times News Service will file the following stories, photos and
graphics today in the ``p'' news file. For repeats or information,
call 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   HELD: DEM-LOBBYISTS.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-RDP-NYT (Los Angeles) _ A roundup: The Democratic party's
convention opens with President Bill Clinton preparing to tell the
delegates _ and the nation via television _ that the country's
progress and continuing prosperity can be assured only if Vice
President Al Gore and his running mate, Joseph Lieberman, inherit
power when Clinton leaves the White House in January.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: An early version of the roundup by Christopher S. Wren has
moved and will be updated, with quotes from late speeches, by 9
p.m. ET with a final version written by Richard L. Berke.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo CVN1.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-HILLARY-CLINTON-NYT _ Hillary Clinton's speech to the
convention. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT12.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-CLINTON-NYT _ President Clinton's day preparing his
prime-time speech. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Text: &LR;  Complete text of the Clintons' speeches will be
available the New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   DEM-ASSESS-NYT _ A political analysis on the convention by R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New stories: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEM-FUNDRAISING-NYT (Los Angeles) _ Democratic Party leaders
claim that they are not doing any fund-raising in Los Angeles.
Instead, they are calling their activities `donor servicing.'' By
John M. Broder and Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-SANCHEZ-NYT _ U.S. Rep. Loretta Sanchez, who clashed with
Democratic Party leaders over a Playboy Mansion fund-raiser, has
withdrawn as a Democratic convention speaker.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-GORE-NYT _ Al Gore's day; he campaigns in Independence,
Missouri. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Also scheduled: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEM-JACKSON-NYT _ Jesse Jackson, now a senior statesman of the
party, deals with Jesse Jackson Jr., the young firebrand his father
once was. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-BRADLEY-NYT _ Bill Bradley, the man who for a few brief
moments last fall seemed capable of stealing the nomination. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-MILITARY-NYT (Washington) _ A look at the Democrats and
missile defense. The issue is back, in full force. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-PROTESTS-NYT _ Developments on protests in Los Angeles. By
Todd S. Purdum.
 &UR;  &LR;   &UR; Daily convention columns &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   DEM-DIARY-NYT _ The convention diary column by Elisabeth
Bumiller and Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-POLITICAL-SURFING-NYT _ The view from TV and the Web. By
Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-MEDIA-NYT _ How the message is communicated and how
successful the Democrats are in managing the TV images. By Peter
Marks.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's political commentary (columns will be filed in ``k''
category):
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT by Gail Collins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK TIMES PARTNERS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Please note that your New York Times News Service report
includes news and features from The Arizona Republic, The Boston
Globe, Cox News Service, The Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Kansas City Star, The Los
Angeles Daily News, The San Francisco Chronicle, The Seattle
Post-Intelligencer, States News Service and the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group at the convention
will file the following feature story. For more information, call
Carl Hulse, Washington bureau chief, at convention headquarters,
213-336-0072.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-BLUEDOG-NYTR _ It was easy to tell that the party on the
Santa Monica Pier was not for your run-of-the-mill Democrats _ the
National Rifle Association was one of the sponsors. The
conservative Blue Dogs _ led by Reps. Bud Cramer of Alabama and
Chris John of Louisiana _ are howling at this convention, trying to
position themselves for power should Democrats gain the majority.
Their celebration at the Santa Monica pier Sunday wasn't a total
success since protesters managed to block the entrance for part of
the evening. By Carl Hulse.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT11.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following commentary for
Tuesday. See CONVENTION-BUDGET-HNS for complete list. If you have
questions, call Chuck Lewis or Susie McBee at 213-336-1800.
</P>
<P>
   LORETTA-SANCHEZ-HNS _ The Latino Committee 2000 brunch last
weekend at Paramount Studios included almost every top California
Hispanic politician, but was notable for one no-show: Rep. Loretta
Sanchez. The second-term Orange County, Calif., congresswoman,
blasted by the Democratic National Committee over her plans for a
fund-raiser at the Playboy Mansion, has kept a low profile since
the issue went public last week. By Zachary Coile.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe is moving the following convention-related
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients. For further
information, call Frank Perrotta at 617-929-2597.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-INSIDE-BOS _ Sam Allis' singular take on the convention's
first day. By Sam Allis.
</P>
<P>
   CELLUCCI-BOS _ Massachusetts' Republican governor, Paul Cellucci
_ who has been mentioned as a possible Cabinet choice in a Bush
administration _ is in Los Angeles providing plenty of GOP spin. By
Tina Cassidy.
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service will move the following stories tonight; see
also SPOT-BJT15-COX. For questions, call 404-526-2300 or Art
Dalglish at the Cox convention workspace, 404-526-2300.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-TEXAS-COX _ Texas Democrats go to work as the Democratic
National Convention begins, including 263 delegates who are for Al
Gore and five non-delegates here to back Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-DNC-PROGRESSIVES-COX (Washington) _ Liberal Democrats rally
to make their voices heard at a convention aimed at nodding two
decidedly centrist candidates. Liberals, who call themselves
progressives, are not completely in sync with Gore, and some are
supporting Green Party nominee Ralph Nader, but others feel Gore is
the best hope of holding back a complete Republican takeover of
Washington. By Dan Freedman.
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN-COX _ Vice President Al Gore's father once told a
reporter that his son was so nervous when he announced for Congress
that he fled to a bathroom afterward to vomit. This was not the
disciplined, cool Al Gore voters think they know. Now is the time
for the real Al Gore to stand up as he prepares to accept the
Democratic nomination for president. By Marianne Means. (Will move
in `k' category)
</P>
