<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ALASKA-ENVIRON-$ADV20-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA TOURISM IS HOT, AND SO IS THE DEBATE ABOUT ITS EFFECTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (For release Sunday, August 20)  
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was not so long ago that most of Alaska was cloaked in
anonymity, and the idea that more than half a million people a year
would pay money to visit a waterlogged fishing village or come
within smelling distance of a grizzly bear was laughable. Towns
that had seen their last mines sealed, their timber mills shuttered
and their fishing docks empty huddled against the elements, the
people wondering whether one last boom would come their way.
</P>
<P>
   In the minds of many outsiders, Alaska was too cold, too wild,
too remote. But those very words have become the selling points of
a $1 billion tourism industry that has exceeded even the wildest
projections. Visits have tripled since 1980, and tourism has caught
up with fishing to become the state's second largest industry,
behind oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
   But even as cash registers clank and whirr from Deadhorse, in
the far north, to Sitka, in the southeastern rain forest, an effort
to rein in explosive growth has taken hold and appears to be
gaining momentum. Some of the people who live in the coastal towns
that have had their economies transformed by the cruise ship
industry are trying to limit visits.
</P>
<P>
   In the national parks, which used to be some of the loneliest
places on the planet, the number of visitors has doubled in 10
years, and officials say the crowds at some sites are threatening
the very thing that is their draw _ the sense of wildness.
Backpackers, kayakers and sports fishers are complaining about
excessive helicopter flights, Jet Skis and group fishing tours.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism itself is not under fire. There is nary an Alaskan
village, from the Bering Sea to the roadless interior, that does
not welcome visitors. What bothers many Alaskans is the onslaught
of ``industrial tourism,'' a term coined by the environmental
writer Edward Abbey to describe mass tourism and its effects _ in
Moab, Utah, for example, the crush of visitors has damaged the
fragile desert and forced federal officials to limit visitation to
some areas. People also fear that the singular character of the
state is changing as Alaskans conform to the expectations of large
tour companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is that the people coming to see Alaska ultimately
won't see it,'' said Kelley Weaverling, a former mayor of the
fishing village of Cordova, on Prince William Sound, who runs a
bookstore in the town. ``When I first came here, this place was
almost prehistoric. Now, it's in danger of becoming very
Disneyfied.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cordova is the kind of town where dogs fall asleep in the middle
of the road and relentless rain wraps the town in a towel of
moisture nine months a year. It is known for the fleet that brings
in the first wild salmon of the year, from the nearby Copper River.
But its quirky charms have been discovered by some of the biggest
tourism operators in the world _ to mixed reception.
</P>
<P>
   When Princess Cruises and Tours recently announced that it would
be building a $10 million, 100-room lodge on 200 acres of the
Copper River, a wild expanse of glacial runoff that feeds one of
biggest wetlands in the Western Hemisphere, it was hailed by the
company as a new frontier in Alaska tourism. The lodge would border
the Wrangell-St. Elias National Park and Preserve _ at 13 million
acres, the largest unit in the National Park system. Princess
officials described the lodge plan as a way for visitors to
experience ``one of the state's best-kept secrets,'' and said it
would not harm the marine ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   But while new lodges are welcomed for the construction and
service jobs they bring, small tour operators and wilderness
advocates fear that much of the state's tourism is being ceded to
foreign-owned interests. Princess, a subsidiary of the London-based
shipping company P&AMP;O, runs four big lodges in Alaska, 10 private
rail cars between Fairbanks and Anchorage, numerous buses, and a
fleet of ships carrying more than 200,000 people a year to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruise ships are kind of like colonists,'' said Weaverling,
referring to the companies that run the lines. ``They come in their
own large ships. They put people on their own tour buses. They
build their own lodges. Until, finally the cruise ship visitor
never sees an actual Alaskan unless it's somebody who made their
bed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dean Brown, an executive vice president at Princess, scoffs at
such characterizations. Alaska cruise ship passengers, he said,
defy the stereotype of sedentary seniors tied to the cocoon of the
cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people used to come to Juneau or Sitka, they wanted to
ride a tour bus,'' said Brown. ``Now they want to kayak, or
ice-climb or canoe or hike to a glacier _ and we don't own any of
those attractions or the services built around them.''
</P>
<P>
   As for fears of Alaska's being loved to death, the solution,
according to state tourism officials and some cruise line
executives, is to spread out the visitors. ``People forget that
Alaska is a huge land mass, and we have a million visitors a year _
just a fraction of what Hawaii gets,'' said Ginny Fay, director of
tourism for the state. ``We just need to disperse our visitors
more.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brown pointed to the plan to build a lodge on the Copper River
as an example of how the major tour operators were trying to move
visitors out of crowded areas.
</P>
<P>
   The most vocal and organized opposition to the growth of the
cruise ship industry is in Juneau, the state capital, where more
than 630,000 passengers are expected this year, in a town of 30,000
_ a nearly 50 percent increase over the last five years. The
biggest of the 540 ships that will tie up in Juneau this summer is
the 10-story Sea Princess, which is taller than the highest
building in Juneau.
</P>
<P>
   Juneau residents complain about excessive noise, air and water
pollution, and crowds from the cruise ships, which usually dock in
the morning and leave in the evening of the same day. Helicopter
and small-plane sightseeing tours, working with the cruise ships,
have made the skies around Juneau a zone of noise and air clutter
in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like `Apocalypse Now,''' said Kimberly Metcalfe-Helmar, a
Juneau resident who has helped to promote two ballot initiatives to
limit tourism related to cruise ships. ``You just can't get away
from the noise. If you're on your favorite hiking trail, there may
be six helicopters overhead. People are fed up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the outrage, voters in Juneau last year bucked the
cruise ship industry and Alaska's political leaders. Seventy
percent of voters agreed to put a $5 a person tax on every arriving
cruise ship passenger. The money is used for hospitals, parks,
roads and other parts of the city that are burdened by heavy
visitation.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Juneau residents are likely to vote on the so-called
Peace and Quiet Initiative, which would restrict helicopter flights
in the area. It is being promoted by some bed-and-breakfast owners,
who stress that they are not against tourism but are unhappy at the
growth of mass tourism. A Web site run by Crondahls' Bed &AMP;
Breakfast in Juneau (www.juneaucrondahls.com) has links to the
campaign, with pictures of ships belching smoke into the sky above
the clear harbor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   North of Juneau, the town of Haines voted last year to limit the
number of cruise ships that can dock. But in nearby Skagway, a
former ghost town that had its glory years during the Gold Rush,
the ships are welcome, as they bring more than 8,000 passengers a
week to a village of 800 people.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise industry responded to the campaigns in Haines and
Juneau by cutting donations to the arts and canceling some visits.
Princess pulled out of Haines, and Holland America reduced its
charitable donations. And while this cutback has prompted many in
Alaska to label the industry arrogant, it has spurred merchants to
fight future efforts at restricting tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise ship passengers spend more than $160 million a year in
southeast Alaska, according to Alaskan tourism officials and
studies sponsored by the industry. To towns like Ketchikan and
Sitka, which saw their big timber-processing mills close in recent
years, the cruise ships are the key to prosperity. Cruise industry
officials say they oppose head taxes, because they already pay in
excess of $10 million a year in local sales tax and fees.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be wrong for the industry to ignore or dismiss
complaints from the towns most affected by heavy growth, said Fay,
the Alaska tourism director. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think of these residents as the canaries in the coal
mine, the fact that they are complaining is a good indication that
visitors may soon start complaining,'' she said. ``The message from
Juneau was: `I'm trying to tell you something.' And I'm not sure
the response of the industry was as constructive as it could have
been because it has not calmed down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another concern is that the growth of large-scale tourism will
come at the expense of not just individual communities but also of
Alaska's largely pristine environment, and the many small outfits
who cater to the growing eco-tourism market.
</P>
<P>
   These critics point to the dumping of toxic waste water by Royal
Caribbean Cruise Lines during the mid-1990s, and recent citations
of other lines for violating air pollution levels. Royal Caribbean
agreed to pay $6.5 million in criminal fines _ a record for a
cruise ship operator in U.S. waters _ for the discharges at sea.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The industry promotes itself as environmentally clean, and says
it processes solid waste on board and then disposes of it ashore.
The water used in showers, dishwashing and laundry is still dumped
at sea, but cruise ship operators say it is harmless and in
compliance with federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Torok, the Environmental Protection Agency's senior
representative in Juneau, and Capt. Ed Page, chief of marine safety
for the Coast Guard in Alaska, said the only regulations for this
so-called gray water is that it comprise solely waste water from
showers, food preparation and laundry. Yet there have been
violations over the years, they added, because hazardous materials
were mixed with the waste water and dumped. As a result, Page said,
spot-testing of such water began this year.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond pollution concerns, some critics say Alaska's wild lands
and formerly empty fiords and inlets have simply become too
crowded. Twenty years ago, President Carter more than doubled the
size of the national park and wildlife refuge systems in the state.
The move outraged members of Alaska's congressional delegation, who
said the new parks and refuges would not attract sufficient
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have people flocked to these federally protected lands,
but Alaska's powerful representatives in Congress have become the
biggest promoters of the expanded tourism industry that has
resulted. In the mid-90s, the delegation pushed through a change in
the law allowing cruise ship traffic to nearly double _ to 184 _ in
June, July and August in Glacier Bay National Park and Preserve,
the nation's largest protected marine ecosystem. A compromise
eventually set the limit at 139.
</P>
<P>
   The congressmen have also promoted plans to build a 90-mile road
through the wilderness of Denali National Park, and have quashed
efforts to limit visitors around the falls where brown bears gather
to eat salmon in Katmai National Park. Sens. Frank Murkowski and
Ted Stevens, R-Ala., say Denali needs more development and Katmai
can accommodate more visitors without affecting the behavior of the
big bears.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Chip Dennerlein, director of the Alaska office of
the National Parks Conservation Association, which is opposed to
many of the new development plans in or near Alaska's parks,
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come all the way to Alaska to experience the wild,'' he
said, ``and what you see is a free-for-all to watch bears, or you
go to pristine camp site and there are 35 helicopter flights over
your head, that's going to give you second thoughts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
