 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
WILL THE REAL AL GORE PLEASE STAND UP? &HT;    By MARIANNE MEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore's father once told a
reporter that his son was so nervous when he announced his
candidacy for Congress in 1976 that he hastily fled afterward to a
bathroom to throw up.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the cool, distant, disciplined Al Gore who has been
at President Clinton's side the past eight years. The Gore the
public sees is something like the new J. Paul Getty Museum in the
Santa Monica Mountains near here _ all sharp angles, hard rock and
steel, handsome, efficient and impressive, but not warm and cuddly.
</P>
<P>
   The upchuck episode happened a quarter century ago, when Gore
was very much a novice at the political game he would gradually
come to master.
</P>
<P>
   But just who is the real Al Gore these days? Most voters
indicate that despite his long-running national role, they don't
have a sense of his inner self and find his public personality
stiff and unfriendly. He suffers by comparison with Clinton, the
Democrats' best people-pleaser, and with Gov. George W. Bush, whose
shirt-sleeve approach to issues is widely appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Convention gives Gore his greatest
opportunity to let the nation get to know him. It is his last
chance for prolonged massive exposure until the debates with Bush
in October, by which time his image may be frozen and incapable of
change.
</P>
<P>
   He fully recognizes the importance of this moment. ``I don't
think I'm well-known as a person and as a presidential candidate,''
he concedes.
</P>
<P>
   First impressions stick. And for many voters this will be the
first impression they will have of Gore the man, speaking by
himself, of himself, for himself. They may aleady have heard he's a
serious fellow, but will they like him?
</P>
<P>
   Gore's problem is similar to that of another vice president a
dozen years ago, who was also forced to confront doubts about his
personality and leadership ability when he sought to move up to the
presidency. That 1988 candidate was the current Republican
nominee's father, George H. W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He had labored silently for eight years in the shadow of a
popular president, much as Gore has, and he was not seen as a
strong, independent figure capable of carrying on in the grand
tradition of his predecessor, Ronald Reagan. To some extent, every
vice president suffers from this second-banana syndrome. The
Democrats had a jolly good time chanting ``Where was George?'' at
their own convention that year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush the elder solved his problem by taking a substantial share
of the credit for the peace and prosperity of the Reagan years and
promising even better times to come. He delivered a more forceful
acceptance speech than many delegates had expected, attacking
Democrats as dangerously liberal, vowing to run hard and fight hard
and thundering, ``I am that man'' who could lead the GOP to
victory.
</P>
<P>
   His speech was a tremendous hit with the conservative delegates,
and it wrapped him in the aura of leadership that had been missing,
although his reckless pledge of ``no new taxes'' would later come
back to haunt him. Bush then went on to wage a relentlessly
negative campaign, smearing his rival Michael Dukakis as
unpatriotic and weak. It worked and Bush won.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush formula sets an appropriate example for Gore to follow.
Gore should ignore advisers who demand that he condemn Clinton for
the Monica Lewinsky affair. After all, the younger Bush failed to
mention the last big scandal of the Reagan administration, the
Iran-contra affair. This is the time for Gore to be positive, to
look forward rather than back and to stamp his own identity upon
his party.
</P>
<P>
   It is also time to stop the silly pretense that he will never
again say ``a single unkind word'' about his rival. A presidential
candidate who does not counter the charges of his opposition is a
loser. But Gore is concerned that he has gained a reputation as an
attack dog, which voters tell the pollsters they do not like. So he
has been trying to show a kinder face. The other day he vowed that
in his acceptance speech ``there will be no negative points about
Governor Bush or Mr. Cheney, either overt or covert, either direct
or implied.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats can only hope that this pledge does not apply to the
rest of the campaign once his speech is over.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans keep saying they won't go negative, either, but
of course they have. Their convention was loaded with snide remarks
about the need to ``uphold the honor and dignity'' of the White
House supposedly lost by the behavior of the Democrats. George W.
Bush said, ``This administration for seven years has squandered the
political capital of the previous administration'', that of _ guess
who? _ his father, who presided over huge national deficits and a
recession. And Bush tried to bait Gore by noting,``Either you're
part of an administration or you're not part of an administration.
If Al Gore has differences with the president, he ought to say loud
and clear what they are.'' Actually, Gore has already pointed out
many differences, including his dismay at Clinton's affair with
Lewinsky. Bush just hasn't been listening.
</P>
<P>
   It is incumbent upon Gore to answer this garbage. His running
mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, can do some of it, but ultimately only
the presidential candidate carries the clout to make his case to
the public. In politics, politeness is often mistaken for weakness.
This is Gore's time to show us his muscle. If Bush the elder could
do it, so can Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at means(at)hearstdc.com
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
