<SLUG> BC-CVN-TEXAS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRO-BUSH TEXAS DEMOCRATS TEE OFF ON GORE
 &HT;    Attn: Texas pointsBy KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was supposed to be four days of Democratic
peace, love and understanding. Then the Texans showed up.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more discordant notes on the opening day of the
Democratic National Convention, Texans loyal to Al Gore, who will
get the party's presidential nomination here this week, clashed
with Texans who have crossed party lines to back GOP nominee George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It made for some harsh words among folks usually on the same
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really just think it's outrageous how the Gore campaign has
tried to trash Texas,'' said former Texas Supreme Court Chief
Justice John Hill, a Bush supporter. ``That's very offensive to me
and I think to just about everyone, Democrat and Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Bush Democrats, none of whom are convention delegates,
did their show Monday at a Republican Party office across the
street from the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't understand why the Democratic Party is trying to
trash one of the states of our union,'' House Appropriations
Chairman Rob Junell, a San Angelo Democrat backing Bush for
president, said about Gore's attack on the Texas record on
education, the environment and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Junell, here on the Bush campaign's tab, said he made the trip
so he could discuss ``the wonderful job Governor Bush has done in
the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you like Washington, D.C., if you like partisan gridlock,
if you like talking to one another through press conferences as
opposed to sitting down and trying to reach consensus ... then you
shouldn't vote for Governor Bush. You ought to go vote for the guy
across the street,'' he said, referring to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, a former state attorney general who was the Democrats'
unsuccessful 1978 gubernatorial candidate, said Bush has ``done a
marvelous job'' as governor. Bush appointed Hill to the Texas
Lottery Commission, a post he no longer holds.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hill and Junell, state Sen. Ken Armbrister of Victoria and
Sandy Kress of Austin, who represents educational interests, said
they were asked to come out here by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It behooves me to try to understand why my party thinks the
way that you elect somebody to the highest office in the land is to
identify one state out of 50'' and attack it, said Armbrister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel betrayed when it is my party saying these things about
my great state,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Garnet Coleman of Houston, a Gore backer posted outside
the office building where the Bush backers held their event, said
there is nothing non-Texan about pointing out the state's
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the problem-solvers in the Texas Legislature, not the
people who try to sweep those problems under the rug,'' said
Coleman, who was joined outside the Republican Party office by Rep.
Scott Hochberg of Houston and Sen. Mario Gallegos of Galena Park.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman's e-mail address is kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
