<HEADLINE>
GORE SPEAKS IN TRUMAN'S HOMETOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Editors please note: A longer version will move later.)
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ Al Gore came to Harry Truman's adopted
hometown Monday to claim the mantle as defender of senior citizens
and Medicare, the health-care program that Truman championed half a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told a crowd of several hundred mostly senior citizens that
if elected president, he would use the nation's projected budget
surpluses to expand the Medicare program to cover prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to strengthen Social Security, to improve benefits
for long-term care for seniors and to establish full health
insurance for all children within the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need step by step to get to Truman's goal of universal
health care coverage,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's appearance was part of a weeklong campaign swing leading
up to his nomination Wednesday at the Democratic National
Convention. He has talked about tax cuts to spur economic
development in Connecticut, children's health care in Cleveland and
cleaning up the environment in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   He chose senior issues for Monday's forum because President
Johnson came to Independence 35 years ago to sign into law the
legislation that created the Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   Before the law, about half of the nation's elderly had health
insurance, Gore said. After the law, 95 percent were covered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
