<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ALASKA-CAMPING-$ADV20-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPING IN ALASKA: JUST ROUGH ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 By MATT NESVISKY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm uncomfortable around animals that stand taller than I do and
can eat me. I don't water-ski and I don't enjoy riding in tiny
airplanes that do. I'm wary of icy sidewalks, so the thought of
having lunch on a mountain of ice 1,000 feet thick tends to chill
my appetite. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In short, Alaska is the kind of place that intimidates me.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet a camping trip to Alaska last summer _ including excursions
on seaplanes, encounters with wildlife, even a picnic atop a
glacier _ turned out to be an excellent way for a first-time
visitor to experience in two weeks a good helping of this
preposterously huge and nearly roadless state. And a local touring
outfit called CampAlaska was up to the logistical task, providing
an invaluable driver-guide, good food, transportation and all
camping equipment besides personal gear and sleeping bags.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our 14-day Sourdough package took my wife and me to some of
Alaska's loveliest and most memorable sites: Denali National Park,
where we rafted down a glacial river; the little-visited
Wrangell-St. Elias National Park and Preserve, with its fields of
summer wildflowers; and Childs Glacier on the salmon-rich Copper
River. In between our wilderness adventures, we visited Seward,
Valdez, Cordova and other Alaskan towns.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mixed lot that assembled for various itineraries Sunday
morning at our hotel near Anchorage International Airport, in
couples and singles, ranging from their late 20s to their late 50s.
From throughout the United States and from Germany, Japan and
India, all had done some camping and hiking, but most were visiting
Alaska for the first time.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our personable, knowledgeable guide was Bill Dyke, at 32 a
veteran member of the 15-year-old CampAlaska company. After a trip
to Anchorage's largest supermarket for last-minute perishables, our
group of five headed south in a 12-passenger van on the Seward
Highway.
</P>
<P>
   Early on in the 108-mile route we stopped at Beluga Point, where
we failed to see any of the whales that purportedly frolic in the
Turnagain Arm of the Cook Inlet. We also passed through no fewer
than three locations called Moose Pass _ but at each one, the moose
apparently had already passed. Later Bill excitedly braked at the
foot of a high slope of the Chugach National Forest to point out
tiny white specks he claimed were dall sheep. Through my binoculars
the tiny white specks appeared only as larger white specks. I felt
fated to be the first visitor to Alaska to encounter no wildlife. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I certainly had no complaints when we stopped near Seward for
our first hike along a level, three-mile trail. Here in the Kenai
Fjords National Park we came within 20 yards of the startlingly
blue, 150-foot-high Exit Glacier, part of the great Harding
Icefield.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We didn't linger long in Seward, a not-especially-attractive
fishing and ferry port at the head of Resurrection Bay on the Kenai
Peninsula. Seward was largely destroyed by a tsunami caused by the
1964 Alaska earthquake. Nothing in Seward commanded attention as
much as the surrounding mountains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We set up for our first night's camping at Miller's Landing, on
the bay two miles south of town. The site offered few amenities,
but the choice was felicitous for its thick and fragrant spruce
forest and for the bald eagles that favor the area. After patiently
instructing his tenderfoot charges in assembling the company's
two-person tents, Bill prepared our dinner of fresh halibut with
pesto baked in a Dutch oven and salad (wine was provided by
individual campers), we cheerfully made the coffee and did KP; Bill
usually refused help with the cooking itself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite this happy picture, camping in Alaska has its downside.
One is rain; parts of Alaska record annual precipitation in feet,
not inches. Fortunately, only twice during our two weeks did it
rain, and never enough to interfere with our activities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A more certain camping discomfort is mosquitoes; like everything
else in the state, the mosquitoes we encountered were oversize, if
lethargic. We were never entirely free of them, but only once _ on
the Copper River delta _ were we forced to don head nets at our
campsite.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A third irritant is the perpetual summer daylight. While the
constant light allows for nonstop sightseeing, it largely obviates
one of camping's great pleasures, the campfire. We dutifully built
a fire every night, but darkness never arrived to justify it. Most
nights remained light enough for reading inside the tents.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Next morning, I was up hours before what would have been sunrise
had the sun ever set. After a breakfast of cold cereal, pancakes,
fresh fruit and coffee, we campers had a choice of activities out
of Seward, and my wife and I chose the seven-and-a-half-hour cruise
and salmon bake with Kenai Fjords Tours.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy seas prevented the boat from venturing into other inlets
of the Kenai Fjords National Park. But we did sail for four hours,
and the tour operators cheerfully refunded all passengers a third
of their fares. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the salmon bake on Fox Island, we thrilled to the thickly
forested mountainsides of the bay, still spattered with snow in
midsummer. And we saw abundant wildlife, including puffins, Steller
sea lions and _ most spectacularly _ a humpback whale, which we
could photograph at close range for nearly an hour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in camp for supper, Bill treated us to two-inch-thick
steaks, baked potatoes, salad and apple crumble baked in the Dutch
oven. In the long light of evening we were able to observe the
eagles, stroll the beach, or sit in the campsite office where we
could sample pickled halibut from an iron pot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heading north of Seward the next day, we stopped at the Portage
Glacier Recreation Area in the Chugach National Forest. The
glacier, which lurks behind an ice-filled lake, is one of the most
popular tourist sites in Alaska. By noon we were having a tailgate
lunch as our van stood in line for loading onto a train from
Portage to Whittier, which is one fjord over the mountains.
Passengers stayed in their vehicles, which were carried on flatbed
railway cars through funhouse mountain tunnels _ the only darkness
we would experience in two weeks. (Vehicles can now make the trip
through the tunnels without using the train.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Whittier, where all 300 residents live in one huge apartment
building, Bill drove the van into the belly of a Marine Highway
System ferry, and for the rest of the day we relaxed topside,
photographing the 35-mile-wide Columbia Glacier as icebergs drifted
by.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We debarked at the port of Valdez, historically one of the major
gateways to Alaska's gold fields and today the shipping terminus of
the 800-mile Trans-Alaska oil pipeline. After setting up the tents
on the edge of town at the Eagle's Rest campground, we ventured
into one of the numerous waterfront saloons. This was the sort of
place that featured wailing country music, Harley-Davidson devotees
at the pool table, and a poster that read: ``Earth First! We'll Log
the Other Planets Later.'' From what I can recall, a good time was
had by all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day was devoted to hiking the mountains and admiring
the Bridal Veil Falls in nearby Keystone Canyon. The following
morning we drove to Robe Lake, seven miles out of town, and flew in
a float plane over stunning mountains, lakes and fjords to the port
of Cordova, where another CampAlaska van met us. We were delighted
that Bill, our guide, remained with us for this leg.
</P>
<P>
   Inaccessible by road, Cordova is less visited (and much more
charming) than either Seward or Valdez. One largely unpaved road,
the grandly named Copper River Highway, does lead out of town, but
after 48 miles it abruptly terminates in the wilderness. We took
that road because it is widely considered the most beautiful drive
in Alaska, skirting a half-dozen glaciers, the most spectacular of
which is Childs Glacier. Here even Cordovans turn up with their
lawn chairs to watch the calving, in which Wal-Mart-size slabs of
ice crack off the glacier and explode into the silty but
salmon-rich Copper River, causing sizable waves.
</P>
<P>
   It was along this road, too, that we saw our first beavers,
moose, trumpeter swans, willow ptarmigans (the quail-like Alaskan
state bird). And a black bear bounded across the road right in
front of the van. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a second day's hiking, we boarded a plane at the minuscule
Merle K. (Mudhole) Smith Airport in Cordova for a one-hour flight
to Anchorage. Rejuvenated by a night in hotel beds, we rose the
next morning for the second half of the camping trip. Now we headed
north 235 miles to see Mount McKinley, at 20,320 feet North
America's highest peak, and to spend three days at Denali National
Park and Preserve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 6 million acres, Denali has almost as much land as
Massachusetts. The group _ we numbered 10 this time _ camped at the
nearby Grizzly Bear campsite, which proved aptly named: During our
stay we saw at least a half dozen grizzlies. The bears were usually
at a distance of a quarter-mile, encounters quite close enough for
me. Caribou, however, ambled right across our path.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I later spent two hours on a white-water rafting
trip ($55), offered by the Denali Outdoor Center, through a canyon
on the glacial Nenana River, which disorientingly runs south to
north. Shooting through Class III and IV rapids (on a scale of I to
VI, with the latter being unnegotiable), with such endearing names
as Train Wreck, Razorback, Royal Flush and Ice Worm, this novice
paddler was hurled once into the center of the raft, but not into
the 45-degree water. Our reward at dinner was Bill's Alaskan king
crab legs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Impressive as Denali was, the highlight of the trip was our
three days at the much larger (13.2 million acres) Wrangell-St.
Elias National Park and Preserve. Six times the size of
Yellowstone, Wrangell-St. Elias is chiefly wilderness. The Wrangell
Mountain Range is snowcapped and volcanic, and Mount St. Elias
(18,008 feet) is the second highest peak in North America. Many of
the mountains in both ranges remain not only unclimbed, but
unnamed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The park itself is penetrated, but only slightly, by two gravel
roads. Its ``urban center'' is McCarthy, which has a year-round
population of about 30 and is reachable only by air or by a
footbridge across the furious Kennicott River. We left the van at
the footbridge and carried personal gear across for two nights at
the rustic McCarthy Lodge. The remains of the town, which earlier
this century entertained hundreds of miners from the adjacent
copper mine with saloons and brothels, have a discarded and forlorn
air. Melancholy, too, is the 14-story Kennicott mine and mill,
which was abruptly shut just before World War II. But our hikes in
the spruce and birch forests, full of alpine aster, lupine, berry
shrubs and fireweed, were exhilarating, as was a four-hour glacier
walk led by St. Elias Alpine Guides, which is headed by Bob Jacobs,
a veteran of Everest and polar expeditions. While on the glacier we
came across a moulin _ a corkscrew opening in the translucent blue
ice _ carved by a melting water channel.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One last night on our way back to Anchorage was devoted to
tenting at Lake Louise, where we spotted a solitary loon on the
placid water. As I saw how adept we were at setting up our tents, I
realized I had become a happy Alaskan camper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA BY FOOT, RAFT AND PLANE: ARRANGING A TRIP
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CampAlaska, in an Anchorage suburb, offers 15 summer
itineraries, from 6 to 16 days. The seven-day Scout Tour, for
example, is $800 a person; the 14-day Sourdough Tour, which we
took, is $1,550 a person.
</P>
<P>
   Participants contribute about $65 a week for food, which covers
most meals. CampAlaska provides two-person tents; campers provide
sleeping bags, pillows and towels. Some campsites have laundry
facilities, and there were clean, bug-free outhouses at the sites.
All sites but Tangle Lakes had sinks and showers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some activities cost extra; for example, white-water rafting
costs $50; sightseeing flights of 35 to 90 minutes are $50 to $130,
and an all-day kayaking excursion costs $125. Our full-day boat
trip and salmon bake was $119 a person.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CampAlaska can help book flights. Recent discount round-trip
fares between Anchorage and Newark ranged from $440 to $600, with
regular fares about $775. Contact Fantasia Travel at (800)
478-2622.
</P>
<P>
   CampAlaska, Post Office Box 872247, Wasilla, Alaska 99687; (800)
376-9438; www.campalaska.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other Tours
</P>
<P>
   Cruises of various lengths on Resurrection Bay and in Kenai
Fjord National Park are offered by Kenai Fjords Tours, Post Office
Box 1889, Seward 99664; (800) 478-8068 or www.kenaifjords.com.
</P>
<P>
   Guided rafting and kayaking excursions on the Nenana River may
be arranged with the Denali Outdoor Center, Post Office Box 170,
Denali Park 99755; (888) 303-1925or www.denalioutdoorcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sightseeing flights over Wrangell-St. Elias National Park and
Preserve are available from Wrangell Mountain Air, McCarthy No. 25,
Post Office Box MXY, Glenallen, Alaska 99588; (800) 478-1160 or
www.wrangellmountainair.com.
</P>
<P>
   Guided glacier walking and climbing in Wrangell-St. Elias
National Park and Preserve may be arranged with St. Elias Alpine
Guides, Post Office Box 111241, Anchorage 99511; (888) 933-5427;
www.steliasguides.com.
</P>
<P>
   Information on Alaska's national parks is available at Alaska
Public Lands Information Center, 605 W. Fourth Ave., Suite 105,
Anchorage 99501; (907) 271-2737, or at www.nps.gov/aplic/center.
Information on state parks is available at the Public Information
Center, Department of Natural Resources, 550 W. Seventh Ave., Suite
1260, Anchorage, 99501; (907) 269-8400; www.dnr.state.ak.us/pic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dining and Accommodations
</P>
<P>
   At the lively Snow Goose Restaurant and Sleeping Lady Brewing
Co., 717 W. Third Ave., (907) 277-7727, in downtown Anchorage, a
seafood dinner with wine or microbrews on a deck overlooking Cook
Inlet and the Chugach Mountains costs about $35.
</P>
<P>
   We dined amid gold rush memorabilia at Gwennie's Old Alaska,
4333 Spenard Rd.; (907) 243-2090. A salmon or rib dinner with wine
is about $25. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CampAlaska offers discounted rooms before or after its tours at
the Executive Suite Hotel, 4360 Spenard Rd., Anchorage; (907)
243-6366; www.executivesuitehotel.com. Rooms that regularly cost
$187 are $125 for a single, $130 double, with tax and Continental
breakfast.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
