<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: FRENCH AD BUSINESS ENJOYING CAFE LIFE _ AND
PROFITING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC PFANNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Siemens, the German electronics giant, has reserved
8,000 of the choicest tables in France this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Foie gras and fine wines, however, are not on the menu. Siemens
is more interested in consumer eyeballs. It is using the tables _
modified versions of the ubiquitous Parisian bistro table _ to
display advertisements for a new line of cellular telephones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get very original promotions where our
competitors are not,'' said Christine Blanc Montmayeur, a
spokeswoman for Siemens.
</P>
<P>
   Risking the wrath of a society that takes its cafes very
seriously, a French startup company introduced the advertising
medium this spring, altering the traditional small, round French
cafe table to put marketing on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Impact Diffusion, was formed last year by two
entrepreneurs, Akim Rezgui and Jacques Delavault, with 20 million
francs, about $3 million, in backing from a private investor.
Rezgui and Delavault developed a new tabletop, adding a
snare-drum-like enclosure. Underneath a glass cover, there is room
for a three-dimensional display.
</P>
<P>
   Since spring, Impact Diffusion has run campaigns for everything
from beer companies to florists to Internet service providers.
Impact Diffusion charges 750,000 francs, or just over $100,000, to
rent out the network of tables for two weeks. Out of that revenue,
Impact said it pays cafe and nightclub owners a fee based on the
size and locations of their businesses, but declined to be more
specific.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, a unit of the UAL Corp., used the tabletop
advertising to introduce a nonstop route linking Paris and Los
Angeles. The advertisement showed a paper-cutout plane making its
way down a runway paved with the stars of the Hollywood Walk of
Fame. ``Because United Airlines was one of the first, that gave it
extra visibility,'' said Geoffroy Epron, a media consultant at
Young &AMP; Rubicam, which handles United's advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the advertisements _ including one for Max, a young
men's magazine with covers that feature barely covered models, and
one for a brand of cigarette-rolling paper _ appear only in tables
placed in nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens, whose campaign started July 29 and is scheduled to run
through the end of August, is trying to take the medium a step
further, giving it an interactive element. Customers seated at the
tables are supposed to get coasters with their drinks that work in
conjunction with the advertisements. The coasters include a
mini-quiz; clues to the answers are provided on the tabletops.
Customers also can mail in their coasters to participate in a
lottery for prizes varying from vacations in Spain to wristwatches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good to entertain the customer when he is very
relaxed,'' Blanc Montmayeur explained.
</P>
<P>
   Parisian waiters appear to be approaching the game with the same
relaxed nonchalance they sometimes employ when asked for the check.
At a cafe in the Latin Quarter, the waiter simply shrugged when
asked recently why the coaster was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Some Parisians, however, are anything but relaxed.
Globalization, and the host of evils attributed to it, have been a
hot topic here. Jose Bove, a sheep farmer turned anticorporate
crusader who is accused of trashing a McDonald's restaurant in the
south of France, has become something of a celebrity. Is Impact
Diffusion the cutting edge of a further commercial incursion?
</P>
<P>
   ``What a horror,'' said Camille Mouries, a librarian at the
National Audiovisual Institute, pointing to the colorful Siemens
advertisement with a mobile phone protruding prominently under the
glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a store closes in Paris, it is replaced by one
selling portable phones,'' she said, adding that the profusion of
marketing for digital gadgets in Paris made her uneasy. ``It's
everywhere. That and the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Delavault argued that France is changing; market research showed
that 70 percent of people liked the new advertising format. And
advertising is not new to French cafes: Logo-laden umbrellas,
ashtrays and other promotional materials have long been a part of
the scene, though the Impact enterprise is the first to sell
advertising space to third parties.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Delavault said, the tabletop advertisements are far
less intrusive than other forms of outdoor advertising, like
billboards. ``We have the chance to show advertisements in the
heart of the city without destroying the environment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, added Delavault, the advertisements serve a useful
purpose in a country where whiling away spare time in a cafe is
part social ritual, part therapy. ``When I'm all alone, I can look
at that, not at my neighbors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Business is going well, Rezgui said, though he would not provide
figures on sales or profitability. In June, he said, Impact
Diffusion even had to turn away potential advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the six-person company, which built its advertising
network by going door-to-door to approach cafe owners, has placed
its tables in more than 50 cafes and nightclubs in 14 cities across
France.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 62,000 cafes in France,'' Rezgui said. ``That gives
us a great opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
