<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Monday, intense thunderstorms developed over northern Minnesota
as a jet stream disturbance passed over the upper Middle West.
Tuesday, a stronger disturbance escorting a cold front across the
eastern Great Lakes region will pose a greater threat.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of thunderstorms, a few capable of spawning severe
weather, will erupt over Michigan and parts of Ohio and move into
western New York and western Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Beryl, which intensified suddenly Monday
southeast of Brownsville, Texas, may become a hurricane and brush
the south Texas Coast Tuesday. Squally thunderstorms in the outer
bands of Beryl could produce tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms will affect New England as a
sluggish upper-level low pivots northeastward.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: A TOUCH OF AUTUMN
</P>
<P>
   A dry air mass reminiscent of midautumn soothed the
traditionally sultry Deep South and Gulf States on Sunday. The
refreshing, autumnlike humidity did not come from Canada. Instead,
the dry air originated several thousand feet above the surface.
During the day, heating of the ground incited rising currents of
hot air. In compensation, air subsided, transporting drier air
toward the ground. Sunday's autumnlike dryness was short-lived,
however. By Monday morning, the amount of water vapor in the air
over Houston had nearly doubled from Sunday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
