<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: R.I.)  
 NEW MICHELIN SERIES HEADS IN ALL DIRECTIONS; DORIS DUKE'S SUMMER
PLACE OPENS FOR TOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 20)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michelin has come up with a new recipe for a series of
guidebooks: To an exotic destination add one part Red (as in the
Red Guide listings of recommended hotels and restaurants) and one
part Green (descriptions of places of major and minor interest),
then fold in a generous helping of practical information and
vignettes about the local culture.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a series called NEOS, with volumes about Tunisia;
Guatemala and Belize; Reunion, Mauritius and the Seychelles; Syria
and Jordan, and Turkey. Due in December are guides to Indonesia,
Rajasthan, and Sri Lanka and the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
   The name NEOS is drawn from the four compass points in French _
Nord, Est, Ouest, Sud.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Duke's Summer Place Opens for Tours &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rough Point, the Newport, R.I., summer ``cottage'' of the
tobacco heiress Doris Duke, has opened to the public for the first
time. But the owners, the Newport Restoration Foundation,
established by Duke in 1968, are restricting visits to three
24-person tours a day, Tuesday to Saturday, through Nov. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The 1889 granite mansion takes its name from a jagged promontory
on the famous Cliff Walk in Newport. Its original owner was
Frederick W. Vanderbilt, grandson of Commodore Cornelius
Vanderbilt. The architects were Peabody &AMP; Stearns; Frederick Law
Olmsted landscaped the 10-acre grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The English Manorial style house was purchased in 1922 by James
Buchanan Duke and his wife, Nanaline. Horace Trumbauer, a
Philadelphia architect, enlarged it to its present 30,000 square
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Duke was an ardent art collector, a passion shared by his only
child, Doris. The tours allow viewers time to admire the art and
antiques in all the main parts of the roughly 70-room mansion.
Furnishings from France, England, Italy, Spain and China fill the
drawing, music, morning and dining rooms, and the solarium on the
first floor. On the second floor is Duke's room, with its
mother-of-pearl bedroom set. Nearby is the Pine Room, where she
practiced the piano.
</P>
<P>
   Ming Dynasty garden seats and jars are seen throughout the house
as are many paintings, mostly portraits, by Renoir, Van Dyck,
Reynolds, Gainsborough, Bol and others. In the Great Hall, with its
circa 1510 Brussels tapestries and English paneling, flags hang
from staffs above, creating a baronial effect.
</P>
<P>
   The grand staircase is lighted by large windows on the landing
that are decorated with stained-glass coats of arms.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for Rough Point must be bought the day of the tour at
the Gateway Center, 23 America's Cup Ave., (401) 845-9130. The
office opens at 9 a.m. and the tours are at 10 a.m. and 12:30 and 3
p.m. Admission is $25; $22 for ages 65 and up and 3 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   Parking, which costs $1.75 an hour or $10 a day, is available at
the center; no cars are allowed at the house. A free shuttle bus
takes visitors to and from Rough Point. The first floor is
wheelchair accessible.
</P>
<P>
   _ LEONARD J. PANAGGIO &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
