<HEADLINE>
RENTING IN CRETE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLORENCE STICKNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q.  &UR; Next spring my family and I would like to rent a house on
Crete, but I am having difficulty finding information. Do you have
any suggestions? _ Anne Zachos, Manchester, N.H. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. Spring is usually a wonderful time to visit Crete, with fewer
crowds and typically glorious weather. You should have no problem
finding accommodations, with prices often 20 percent to 40 percent
lower than in high season, according to one agent who rents houses
there.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, director of Villas International in San Rafael,
Calif., in business for 21 years, says his company works with three
or four agents on Crete and concentrates on two main areas of the
island: Canea, also known as Chania or Hania, at the foot of the
White Mountains west of Iraklion, the capital, and Agios Nikolaos,
to the east. Accommodations include everything from simple studios
to five- or six-bedroom villas, a few on the water, some with
private pools.
</P>
<P>
   In Canea, a good base for hiking into the Samaria Gorge or
relaxing on the sandy beaches stretching to the west, and in the
seaside town of Rethimno, 20 miles to the east, two-bedroom houses
cost $1,000 to $1,250 a week (prices quoted are rates for next
spring). At the high end, and near the resort of Agios Nikolaos at
the other end of the island, a three-bedroom house on a cliff
overlooking Mirabello Bay with a private cove starts at $3,500 a
week, depending on the number of occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Villas International also has a few properties on the southern
and eastern coasts of the island, where there are secluded beaches
and small fishing villages. Generally, a minimum stay of seven days
is required.
</P>
<P>
   For information, contact Villas International, 950 Northgate
Drive, Suite 206, San Rafael, Calif. 94903; (800) 221-2260, fax
(415) 499-9491; www.villasintl.com; e-mail info(at)villasintl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Another company offering a few rentals (it has more houses for
sale) goes by its Web site name, www.a-house-on-crete.com;
telephone and fax (30-831) 72668. A new two-bedroom house in
Roumeli, near Rethimno, with a pool and garden, a mile from the
beach, costs $500 a week (April through October). A 250-year-old
restored villa in Hamalevri, a tiny village seven miles east of
Rethimno, with three large bedrooms, two baths, a garden and sea
and mountain views, costs $800 a week. There is a 10 percent
discount for stays of more than two weeks. Mark Last, the owner,
says more houses will be available for rent by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek National Tourist Organization in New York suggests you
look at the listings of houses, villas and apartments on the Web
site of Crete Tournet, at www.crete.tournet.gr. The site includes
address, telephone and fax for each property, with descriptions of
accommodations and facilities, color photographs, location
(distance from the beach and from the nearest town) and last
renovation.
TOURING THE BALTICS
</P>
<P>
   Q.  &UR; I am interested in touring the Baltic States (Latvia,
Lithuania, Estonia) and parts of Russia next May or June. Are there
any tour agencies that arrange these trips? _ L.B., Glen Head,
N.Y. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. Next year will be a particularly good time to visit the
Baltics, as Latvia is celebrating its 800th anniversary. There will
be a wide range of competitions, festivals, exhibitions and special
events in Riga and around the country.
</P>
<P>
   One agency handling Baltic tours, in business for 70 years, is
Uniontours, 245 Fifth Ave,, New York, N.Y. 10016, (212) 683-9500 or
(800) 451-9511; www.uniontours.com; e-mail
travel(at)uniontours.com. Exact itineraries and dates have not been
set for next spring but should be similar to this year's. Prices
would be somewhat higher, said Stephanie Horton, the president,
because accommodations will be in Radisson hotels in Vilnius, Riga
and Tallinn.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-night tour of Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia that costs
about $1,695 this year would include air fare between New York and
Vilnius, Lithuania ($599 land only). Two days are spent in Vilnius
touring the modern and medieval city, followed by an afternoon
exploring the resort town of Trakai, with an excursion to a
14th-century island castle, now an art museum. In Riga, Latvia,
visitors are taken to see the magnificent 18th-century Rundale
Palace, the Old Town and its churches and cafes and the Art Nouveau
district. If you go in mid-June you will be in time for Riga's
Opera Festival, June 8 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   In Sigulda, known as the Latvian Switzerland, visitors explore a
13th-century castle and a cave covered by inscriptions dating from
the 17th century. The trip includes a drive along the Baltic coast
to the Estonian resort town of Parnu, and then on to Tallinn, with
its old fortification walls, cobblestone streets and massive
14th-century town hall. The company also offers tours of Moscow and
St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Another company specializing in the Baltics is Baltic Design
Tours, 5650 Yonge St., North York, Ontario Canada M2M 4G3; (888)
226-3628 or (416) 221-9212, fax (416) 221-6789;
www.baltic-design-tours.on.ca.
</P>
<P>
   Its seven-day Baltic Panorama tour begins and ends in Helsinki
and includes Tallinn, Vilnius and Trakai, the former capital Kaunas
and its Old Town, Riga and the university town of Tartu; this year
the cost is $1,100. Prices and itineraries are not yet set for next
year. The eight-day Baltic Highlights tour includes two days in St.
Petersburg with a visit to the Hermitage ($900 this year). Prices
do not include air fare.
Trains in Tuscany
</P>
<P>
   Q.  &UR; I want to use the train as my mode of transportation for a
vacation in Tuscany from Sept. 21 to Oct. 12. Do you know how I can
buy tickets for travel to several cities (Florence to Siena to Pisa
to Lucca to Florence) before I depart the United States? _ L.P.,
Portland, Ore. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. You can buy train tickets through C.I.T. Rail, a division of
C.I.T. Tours, at (800) 248-7245. The company will send the tickets
by standard two-day Federal Express. Schedules and prices can be
found at the company's Web site, cit-tours.com. The cost of the
two-hour trip from Florence to Siena is $20 first class, $14 second
class; the two-hour trip from Siena to Pisa, with a change at
Empoli, is $23 and $16; the half-hour trip between Pisa and Lucca,
$12 and $9; and the hour-and-a-half leg from Lucca to Florence, $18
to $12. Trains between each city run frequently, with between 17
and 25 a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
