<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-PRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN CRACKS DOWN ON TWO MORE REFORMIST WRITERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Ataollah is CQ.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ The crackdown on reformers in Iran continued over
the weekend with the detention of two writers. A popular satirist,
Ibrahim Nabavi, and a newspaper columnist, Mohammad Qoochani, were
interrogated by a hardline court and detained.
</P>
<P>
   Both men wrote for a banned daily, Asr-e Azadegan, and won
awards from their peers on Saturday in an annual press festival.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several months, the government has closed the
reformist newspapers that supported the moderate president,
Mohammad Khatami. Five journalists have been jailed in the last 10
days, and the last major reform newspaper, Bahar, was shut down.
</P>
<P>
   The newly elected Parliament, which has a preponderance of
reformers, suffered a setback last week when Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, the country's supreme leader, ordered it to drop a bill
for press reform. The bill was a centerpiece for Parliament, which
opened in late May.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was meant to counter the hardline crackdown on the
press, under which almost 25 newspapers have been closed and a
dozen journalists jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a moderate deputy judiciary chief, Hadi Marvi,
said Monday that some of the newspapers might be allowed to publish
again because there was disagreement over the closings within the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   He said many of the judges believed that the interpretation of
existing law under which the newspapers had been shut down was
``not right.''
</P>
<P>
   The reformist minister of culture and Islamic guidance, Ataollah
Mohajerani, a close ally of President Khatami and the official who
has issued newspaper licenses for three years, was summoned to
court Monday to answer questions about his ministry's expenses for
cultural projects.
</P>
<P>
   Mohajerani, who is also the government spokesman, escaped a
dismissal vote last year by the previous Parliament, which was
dominated by hardliners.
</P>
<P>
   The current crackdown appears to be an attempt to slow down the
reform movement after its strong showing in the parliamentary
elections this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamid Reza Jalaipur, the publisher of five of the banned
newspapers, said the cost of closing the papers would be greater
for hardliners than for reformers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new era in which one cannot rule without popular
support,'' he said. ``Hardliners have lost their credibility among
the people by these radical measures. The heart of reform is the
votes of the people, which cannot be stopped by closing newspapers
and jailing journalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite enormous pressure, 161 reformist members of the 290-seat
Parliament renewed their pledge to their constituents in a
statement read on the floor on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The honorable people should know that their representatives
are faithful to the oath they took to protect their rights and will
take all necessary measures to fulfill them,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   It warned the opponents of reform to ``quit their attempt aimed
at disappointing people,'' and be aware that such acts would not
affect ``people's decision in pursuing reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad-Sadeq Javadihesar, the publisher of the banned daily
Tous, said the statement indicated that the reformers ``will not
give up because of such obstacles but will only change their
approach and strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said: ``Reformers and the people should not
expect all plans to succeed. What matters is that the reform
movement moves forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
