<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPAIR-CELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARROW CELLS BECOME NERVE CELLS   IN LAB EXPERIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a finding that may offer hope to people with brain and spinal
injuries, researchers say they have found a way to turn bone marrow
cells into nerve cells, possibly creating a plentiful supply of
cells to repair nerve damage once thought irreversible.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be proven that the new nerve cells have all the
capabilities of normal nerve cells, or neurons, said other
researchers. There are many types of neurons that transmit
information in the body.
</P>
<P>
   However, if they do mimic ordinary neurons, bone marrow stem
cells taken from a person might be converted into nerve cells and
implanted to heal a disease in the same person, like Alzheimer's,
Parkinson's or Lou Gehrig's disease, a spinal cord injury, the
scientists are reporting.
</P>
<P>
   And the researchers are confident that they can make the nerve
cells both rapidly and efficiently, potentially bypassing the
controversy about using stem cells from days-old human embryos in
nerve cell regeneration research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were simply astounded by the rapidity of the response,''
said Dr. Ira B. Black, a neuroscientist and senior author of the
paper, ``so that even within an hour we could see it in front of
our eyes. The cells converted from a rather flat, mundane looking
appearance and rounded up into neuron-like form.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 80 percent of the bone marrow cells changed into
nerve cells in the experiment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are described in an article in the Journal of
Neuroscience Research by scientists from The University of Medicine
and Dentistry of New Jersey and from Hahnemann University in
Philadelphia. The lead author is Dale Woodbury from the New Jersey
medical school.
</P>
<P>
   Black said the researchers cultured the bone marrow cells in
dishes along with a mixture of chemicals that nudged the cells into
changing their ``fate,'' or final function. They added chemicals
including antioxidants that they hoped would resemble the chemical
environment of brain cells, and that would coax the bone marrow
cells into becoming nerve cells.
</P>
<P>
   The report is one in a string of stunning findings over the past
year or two suggesting that various kinds of stem cells in the body
_ including the ``embryonic stem cells'' that form all the body's
tissues _ can be directed to become very different types of cells.
For example, blood-forming cells have changed into muscle cells,
and neural stem cells have given rise to liver cells in recent
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Treatments that would use embryonic stem cells are problematic
because of ethical considerations: harvesting the stem cells kills
the human embryo.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the new report is encouraging because it
suggests bone marrow cells could be taken from adults to treat
their own disease, circumventing the ethical issues. And, said the
researchers, the marrow cells would be easier to obtain than
another type of repair cell that's being studied, which has to be
harvested from deep within the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The work was supported in part by the Christopher Reeve
Paralysis Foundation and in part by the National Institutes of
Health. The actor Christopher Reeve is paralyzed from a spinal cord
injury in a riding accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are most excited about the future potential this finding
holds for patients with spinal paralysis, stroke and degenerative
brain disease,'' said Black in a statement issued by the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   However, some other scientists in the young and turbulent field
of stem cell research said the claims in the report were premature.
They questioned whether the experiment really produced fully
functioning neurons, and they said that just because it could be
done in a laboratory dish didn't mean it would work in people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long way to go to even say that these are neurons,''
said Fred Gage, a neurobiologist at the Salk Institute in Southern
California. He agreed that many experiments are suggesting that
immature cells in the organs of adults can be induced to take on
different functions, but he said this can't be done reliably and
predictably yet.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald McKay, a molecular biologist at the National Institute of
Neurologist Diseases and Stroke, also expressed reservations
because the work had only been done in the laboratory. He said
scientists really know very little about how these dramatic
conversions take place. But, he added, ``There's all kinds of stuff
coming out in the next three to six months that will make your hair
stand on end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
