<HEADER>
A1475 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS &LR;      08-14 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERTIME MAJOR STUMBLING BLOCK TO VERIZON STRIKE SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For several days, negotiators for Verizon Communications and its
two striking unions have been locked in debate over an issue many
working Americans can surely identify with: overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The strike by more than 85,000 telephone workers entered its
eighth day Tuesday, with an announcement that the Communications
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers would launch mobile picketing at manholes, cable
installation sites, and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The CWA, which represents 72,000 telephone operators and
customer service employees, said the protests would continue until
the company agrees to ease mandatory retirement procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by a state waiver that will permit Verizon trucks to
travel along Massachusetts roadways for unlimited hours, the CWA
also announced plans to protest outside the Massachusetts State
House on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Verizon spokesman Eric Rabe said the company is
trying to find a balance between the strikers' demands and the
company's need for overtime during peak periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree that work in our call centers is tough,'' Rabe told
reporters. ``The question is `How can we address legitimate issues
of job stress and still provide the service that customers want and
deserve?' ''
</P>
<P>
   That question has resounded throughout corporate America as
employers have instituted policies designed to increase or decrease
hours according to production or consumer demand. Not surprising,
workers in health care, manufacturing, and now telecommunications
have spoken out against such policies.
</P>
<P>
   In April, 535 registered nurses walked off jobs at St. Vincent
Hospital in Worcester, Mass. after negotiations between Tenet
Health Care and their union, the Massachusetts Nurses Association,
broke down. The reason for their anger: a contract proposal
mandating overtime when patient admissions were high.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, more than 500 workers at a Coca-Cola Bottling plant in
Massachusetts walked off their jobs after voting down a contract
their labor union had approved. One of the issues on the table:
mandatory overtime.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the United Auto Workers union settled a contract with
General Motors Corp that forced GM to close six assembly plants in
the United States and Canada. In all, 2,800 workers struck the
Warren, Mich., powertrain plant. Among other things, the union
wanted the company to hire several hundred workers to make up for
retirements and reduce overtime stress among workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mandatory overtime is one of the most important issues in
American workplaces today, especially among professional or skilled
workers,'' Tom Juravich, director of the labor center at the
University of Massachusetts at Amherst, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that work forces are being pared down to a minimum, people
are being asked to work longer and employers are using mandatory
overtime to help achieve their goals. This is what we are seeing at
Verizon.''
</P>
<P>
   While federal statistics do not document the overtime hours of
telecommunications workers, the Bureau of Labor Statistics reports
that the average work week of telephone workers was 42 hours in
January 2000, up from 38 in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the percentage of families in which both spouses
worked more than 40 hours per week increased from 3.6 percent in
1969 to 10.1 percent today, according to the agency's current
population survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back and look at the average number of hours worked
by middle-class couples with children in 1979, you will find that
they worked the equivalent of a part-time job and a full-time
job,'' said Eileen Appelbaum, research director at Economic Policy
Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``But between the two of them there was someone at home
half-time. That is gone, and people are feeling much more
pressured.''
</P>
<P>
   The CWA, the largest of the two striking Verizon unions, is
demanding more flexible work schedules for its members. IBEW
represents about 13,000 telephone technicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to be able to refuse unreasonable amounts of
overtime, particularly when it is mandated week after week and
month after month,'' CWA representative Steve Early. ``In New
Jersey, where there is no cap on overtime, it can mean an extra 20
hours per week. In New England, we have a cap of 10 hours of
overtime per week, except in certain months when a person could be
asked to work 12 hours. Those workers want people with serious
medical or personal issues to be excluded from overtime entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   CWA also wants a guarantee that people who have had an approved
transfer to another department will be allowed to leave. Many have
been forced to stay in their old jobs because the company is short
staffed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle McCormack, a 31-year-old mother of three, joined
Verizon Communications eight years ago. Now, employed as a customer
service representative in the company's Andover facility, she says
she is constantly juggling her schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to keep your fingers crossed because you never
know until noon whether you're going to have to work the extra
hours or not,'' McCormack said. ``I've been late for picking up the
baby at daycare, late for doctor's appointments, late picking up my
husband at the train. I've had to find someone at the last minute
to pick up my son at daycare.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Verizon's Rabe said the company is doing all it can
at the bargaining table to return its striking employees to work.
``Managing overtime is linked to the ability to shift demand (for
workers) among our call centers,'' he said. ``Reducing stress is
directly linked to our ability to manage call center volume.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
