<HEADER>
A1481 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-CVN-DAILYSHOW-TEX     08-14 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-DAILYSHOW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS TAKES A BEATING IN COMEDY CENTRAL'S CONVENTION COVERAGE
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanied by CVN-DAILY SHOW-CORRESPONDENTS)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By TODD CAMP 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comedy Central's coverage of the 2000 Republican Convention was
best summed up by Jon Stewart, the star of the network's mock news
broadcast ``The Daily Show With Jon Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a fake news organization and this (convention) is a fake
news event. So I think we're the only people who should be here,''
Stewart said at a news conference before the convention began.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates showed up anyway, even though the nominations were
set in stone and there was very little room left for surprises of
any sort. The only thing on display were a bunch of politicians
delivering carefully scripted speeches and lots of people in funny
hats.
</P>
<P>
   The Comedy Central response to this, for Democrats as well as
Republicans: Why not make fun of it all?
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central's ``Indecision 2000'' for the Philadelphia
Convention, dubbed by the network as ``the most important
convention coverage ... ever,'' included nightly ``live'' ``Daily
Show'' broadcasts from their digs at the University of
Pennsylvania, with five correspondents reporting from the
convention floor. There was political commentary from former
presidential candidate Bob Dole, former Clinton Cabinet member
Robert Reich and former Nixon speechwriter-turned-game-show-host
Ben Stein. There were interviews with Sen. John McCain,
congresswoman Mary Bono and ABC news anchor Peter Jennings, and a
``Nightline''-style debate on gay conservatives featuring elderly
fringe presidential candidate Charles Doty, ``space-alien
ambassador'' Jody Pendarvis and singing psychic Fran Baskerville.
``Indecision 2000'' continues Tuesday night when the ``Daily Show''
team reports from the Democratic Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to give anyone the wrong idea, because this is my
first convention, but I gotta say, it's awful boring,'' Stewart
told Dole the first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventions are a lot of fun ... for delegates,'' Dole said.
``And some people watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many, but some. And more and more of those watching are
tuning in to Comedy Central's coverage as viewership declines on
the networks. The networks, in fact, are paying less attention to
the conventions than they have in years past. ABC leads the Big
Three in coverage, but it was still tiny in comparison to the cable
news presence. CNN devoted more than 100 hours to the convention
(up 25 from 1996), and led the cable ratings, followed by Fox News
Channel and MSNBC. Of course, that didn't make it any less dull.
Which is why political humor outlets like Comedy Central, HBO's
``Dennis Miller Live'' and ABC's ``Politically Incorrect With Bill
Maher'' have been able to mine comedy gold with viewers' general
disinterest in the convention process.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central seems to be making the biggest splash. The cable
channel first stepped into the political melee in 1992, when Al
Franken hosted ``State of the Union: Undressed,'' live comedic
coverage of President Bush's State of the Union Address _ only
after the network successfully pressured ABC, NBC, CBS and CNN to
provide access to the pool feed of the speech. ``Indecision '92''
followed with nightly reports from the Republican and Democratic
conventions, and an in-depth election night special. Bill Maher and
his then-Comedy Central show, ``Politically Incorrect,'' continued
the legacy in '96 with correspondents Al Franken, Arianna
Huffington and Chris Rock.
</P>
<P>
   And this year's coverage proves that the network is continually
sharpening its claws. To help you decide whether Comedy Central's
snarky, no-holds-barred coverage of this week's Democratic
Convention is for you, here's a look back at some of the highlights
from this year's coverage of the Republican Convention:
</P>
<P>
   Stewart kicked off the week saying, ``... delegates from the
gated communities of New York to the gated communities of
California gathered at the First Unity Center to celebrate
diversity, inclusion and the obligatory nod to American Samoa.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning the opening night speeches, Stewart said, ``George W.
Bush actually introduced Colin Powell live last night from a
classroom in Ohio. Now what that tells us is that Bush is committed
to education. So much so he's willing to keep people in school till
10:30 p.m. ... in August.''
</P>
<P>
   When accused by U.S. Rep. Mary Bono of obviously being a
Democrat, Stewart replied, ``No, I'm not. Honestly, I'm just
disgusted by the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Daily Show'' version of the Bush tribute film, ``George W.
Bush: From Wealth to Riches,'' featured candid photos of the Texas
governor with a voiceover telling the story of a man who ``has
overcome an incredible lack of obstacles, but behind the successful
man of today lies a soft-luck tale of perseverance and dogged
determination to not die young.''
</P>
<P>
   The mock film also included barbs such as, ``He later put
himself through Yale after being awarded the coveted Barbara Bush
scholarship,'' and ``For five turbulent years of Vietnam he served
as a pilot in the Texas Air National Guard, singlehandedly keeping
the Lone Star State free of Charlie.'' It ended with the summation,
``George W. Bush, the kind of man who has traditionally been
elected president.''
</P>
<P>
   George W., however, often took a back seat to coverage of the
inner workings of the convention itself. Bob Dole offered this
insight: ``It's so boring that even some of the protesters are
trying to get a job for the first time in their lives. We haven't
been this excited since David Eisenhower married Julie Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Black said while watching footage of Hispanic singer Jon
Secada's performance opening night, ``I assure you this is the
first time Republicans have heard Jon Secada's music when it wasn't
blaring from their gardener's truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Black on another convention favorite, Lee Greenwood's song
``Proud to Be an American'': ``Of course we all know that
`American' is code for `I'm proud to be a wealthy, white,
middle-aged Caucasian in a stupid ... hat who still thinks he's
master of the universe.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In summing up, Nancy Walls offered this incisive take on what
the convention is all about for the delegates: ``Beer, plus too
much time on your hands, equals elephant balloon hats.''
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7691, or e-mail:
tcamp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
