<SLUG> BC-WPP-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WWP GROUP REPORTS SURGE IN PROFITS AND REVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE KAPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ WPP Group, which will become the world's largest
advertising firm with its acquisition of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc.,
reported a surge in profits and revenue Monday and forecast that
the boom in advertising spending would last through the end of the
year, buoyed by the Olympics and the presidential elections in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts, however, said the climate for big advertising
firms like WPP is currently as good as it will get.
</P>
<P>
   WPP, based in London, said operating profit for the first six
months of the year grew 22 percent, to 146.5 million pounds ($220
million), or 12 pence a diluted share, compared with 120 million
pounds, or 9.8 pence a diluted share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 18 percent, to 1.2 billion pounds, driven by new
accounts, like SAP AG, and increased spending from existing clients
like the Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   Including Young &AMP; Rubicam, which WPP is buying for $4.7 billion
in stock, and excluding one-time merger costs, revenue increased 19
percent while operating profit jumped 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Martin Sorrell, WPP's chief executive, said shareholders
would vote on the merger in September. Calling his company a proxy
for the new economy, Sorrell sought to counter concerns that an
expected slowdown in Internet advertising spending would dent WPP's
growth prospects. He said that online spending tripled to (PS)90
million, or about $135 million, during the first half of the year.
What has changed, he said, is who is buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big traditional companies are spending more on the new
economy, while new economy companies have had difficulties due to
stock market falls and are spending less,'' Sorrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Going forward, analysts said the currently vibrant conditions
for all types of advertising spending were unlikely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year, you won't have the presidential elections or the
Olympics or anything particularly big,'' said Gareth Thomas, an
analyst with Commerzbank. ``Even if the economy stays strong, the
top line will slow. And the margin enhancements we've seen to date
won't be replicated.''
</P>
<P>
   WPP has been preparing for an eventual slowdown by paying more
of its employees on a bonus schedule and hiring more staff on
contracts. Sorrell said such flexible costs, which are equal to 7
percent of revenue, could be easily reduced in a downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of WPP, which owns the J. Walter Thompson and Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather Worldwide advertising agencies along with the public
relations firm Hill &AMP; Knowlton, rose as much as 2.4 percent on the
earnings news, but fell back at the close of London trading to end
down 0.11 percent at 907 pence, or about $13.60.
</P>
</TEXT>
