<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1493 &Cx1f; tab-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-SPEECH-NNS &LR;      08-14 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-SPEECH-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY FACES TOUGH CROWD FOR LAST HURRAH
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, AUGUST 14, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By ROBERT COHEN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Bill Bradley and his legions of supporters have wanted ever
since they realized back in March that he would not be the party's
nominee -- a chance to talk to a national audience about the issues
he considers important.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night he gets that chance. It will be Bradley's last
hurrah of the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   During prime time, the former New Jersey senator will offer his
support of Al Gore, the man who soundly defeated him in the Iowa
caucuses, the New Hampshire primary and 16 other contests held
March 7.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, whose previous national convention speeches in 1988
and 1992 failed to ignite the partisan Democratic crowds, might
have a hard time getting a convention united for Gore to give him
anything but polite consideration.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he is sharing the spotlight with a group of
speakers who may overshadow him.
</P>
<P>
   On an evening some have dubbed ``liberal night,'' Bradley will
appear onstage along with the keynoter, Tennessee Rep. Harold Ford;
Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg; and two of the party's best orators,
the Rev. Jesse Jackson and Sen. Edward Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman, said the former senator is
looking forward to addressing the convention. And whether or not
his oratory matches the others, Hauser said, Bradley believes it is
``more important for the record than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley certainly would have preferred to be delivering
the acceptance speech Thursday night as the party's nominee, his
spokesman said he has ``no regrets'' about his campaign, is over
his disappointment and without any hesitation will reinforce the
endorsement of Gore that he finally made last month.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Bradley finally released his 359 delegates, freeing
them to vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bradley will talk ``about his support for Al Gore
and his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, and the basis for that
support,'' said Hauser. ``He will tell why Gore will make a
significantly better president than George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, Bradley surfaced after four months of political
seclusion and offered a belated and minimalist endorsement of Gore.
During a rally in Green Bay, Wis., where he was unavailable to
answer any questions, Bradley essentially told the crowd that Gore
was far preferable to Bush, the Republican presidential candidate,
and as a Democrat, he wanted to see his party win in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, Bradley used his July endorsement speech to talk
about the agenda of his unsuccessful presidential primary campaign,
including his commitment to erasing child poverty, expanding health
care coverage to everyone and enacting campaign finance reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Hauser said Bradley will talk about these issues again Tuesday,
noting that ``these challenges haven't gone away.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry South, an adviser to the Gore campaign in California, said
Gore is hopeful Bradley will rise to the occasion and put his stamp
of approval on the Democratic ticket ``in a way that appeals to the
voters he was aiming at in the primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore may have bashed him easily, but he's still an important
national figure and he could be an effective campaigner in the
Northeast and in Missouri where he was born,'' said South. ``He
could be helpful if he wants to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the primaries, Bradley did not cloak his disdain for
Gore, accusing the vice president of distorting the impact of his
universal health care plan and aspects of his record as a New
Jersey senator.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had made his deep commitment to racial unity a central
campaign theme and was particularly upset when Gore charged his
health plan would hurt blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we believe you will tell the truth as president if
you don't tell the truth as a candidate?'' Bradley asked Gore on
Jan. 26. That's a question the Republicans used to criticize Gore
during their convention and are likely to use again this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that he and Bradley have put the primaries behind
them, and added he would welcome the former senator's help in the
fall. Bradley has said he is willing to campaign for the Democratic
standard-bearer, but he has already scheduled a tour in September
and October for his latest book, ``The Journey From Here,'' which
explores the issues of his own presidential campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
