<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1496 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BATTLING-CANCER0815-C     08-14 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATTLING-CANCER0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cancer experience begins with frightening choices
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Jim Morris is the outdoor reporter for the Dayton Daily News.
Morris, 55, spent the past three years battling Non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma. In a two-part series, he recounts his struggle and shares
his insights about this fight for his life. Today, Morris writes
about his initial diagnosis, treatment and the news that he didn't
want to hear.
 &HT;    By Jim Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - I was scared to death.
</P>
<P>
   There really isn't any other way of putting it. I could look
back at the experience and say it was a ``piece of cake,'' now that
it's several months in my rear view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   But I won't. No cake here. If you want cake, go find Sara Lee.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrifying experience. It was, and continues to be, a
life-or-death situation. I don't really know when cancer ceases to
be life or death. They say five years. I don't know. I'm not there
yet. I look forward to it, although I suspect it will never leave
my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a doctor at the James Cancer Hospital in Columbus put it
in the simplest of terms: ``The only choice you have is to take
this treatment or die of your disease.''
</P>
<P>
   How's that for take it or leave it?
</P>
<P>
   I have been told I have cancer twice. The first time was on a
winter day in early 1997. Don't let anybody tell you differently,
it has to be the worst day in a person's life.
</P>
<P>
   I wince when I hear of a person finding out he or she has
cancer. You go through your daily life and don't think about it.
Me? Cancer? Naw.
</P>
<P>
   Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma is my particular brand of the nasty
stuff. As cancers go, it's ``better'' than some and ``worse'' than
others. You don't want it. But I will say, it's probably better to
have it now than, say, 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best days of a person's life is the day when someone
tells you it's gone. After seeing friends die from cancer, one type
or another in recent years and months, you count yourself very
lucky at every little milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tumors are reduced 70 percent,'' I heard after my second
or third CAT scan. Then later that same year, after many weeks of
chemotherapy, two doctors seemed overjoyed to be the ones to tell
me their tests found no more lymphoma in my body.
</P>
<P>
   My good days lasted about 18 months. No more cancer, right?
What's this remission stuff? It's gone. I refused to use the term
remission.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day in May 1999 I woke up with my right leg about twice
the size of my left. A quick call to my doctor brought a quick
ultrasound test. Every doctor in the hospital knew what it was
without looking: a nasty little condition called deep vein
thrombosis. A blood clot in the leg.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, I don't think the doctors were as concerned about
treating the condition (they knew what they were doing with blood
thinners, etc.) as what caused it. Another CAT scan confirmed their
diagnosis and hit me like the proverbial ton of bricks: The
lymphoma was back.
</P>
<P>
   A tumor was pressing on a vein, causing the restricted blood
flow in the leg and creating the condition for a clot. And there
were other tumors, too, ones that had grown since my last checkup
scan a few months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Another bad day, maybe worse than that day in 1997. I really
thought it was gone. I thought all those toxic chemicals I had
pumped through my body for about eight months had cured me. How
foolish to think that. I know now.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't go home to think about what to do next. My oncologist
and cardiologist sat with me and said the best course was to go on
the attack again, right away. The next round of chemotherapy would
begin the next day, a 24-hour drip.
</P>
<P>
   I had been told when I ``had cancer'' the first time that there
was a program at several of the nation's top cancer hospitals
called a bone marrow transplant. The doctor said it was being used
more and more for people with lymphoma. I heard even more about it
during a second-opinion visit to the Cleveland Clinic in early
1997. Only there, they went into more detail, saying the procedure
was being done by capturing the patient's own ``baby cells'' and
later returning them to his body.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great fortunes for me was that it was determined
early, by a most painful test, that my marrow was clean. Good
stuff, my marrow. The only problem was I was 52 and had diabetes. I
might not be a good candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on the last day of my chemotherapy in late 1997, I had a
heart attack. That's all I needed, right? I won't go into the
details, but it was an MI (myocardial infarction). The doctors
didn't believe it had anything to do with the chemotherapy, but
I'll always wonder. My arteries were clean. Doctors didn't see any
kind of heart operation or procedure in my future, just diet and
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Now I had two battles to fight _ make it three, with the
diabetes. But the cancer was gone, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   As I gained some strength back, I began a program that has, I
believed, changed my life for the better _ cardiovascular
rehabilitation at Upper Valley Medical Center, the hospital nearest
my home. (It began at Stouder Memorial Hospital in Troy, before
that facility closed.)
</P>
<P>
   Having a heart attack, no matter how well I survived it,
certainly didn't do anything for my chances at a stem cell
transplant. I think my doctor realized that, too.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed, too. After early treatments proved successful
on the lymphoma the second time around, the doctor had brought the
idea of a transplant back into the picture. He set up an
appointment in Columbus, at the James Cancer Hospital at Ohio State
University, and we were all talking about a ``stem cell
transplant.'' The old ``bone marrow transplant'' wasn't in my
future.
</P>
<P>
   When I walked into the Columbus hospital for my first interview
with a transplant doctor, it was, no question, a scary experience.
Remember, no cake here.
</P>
<P>
   That doctor _ and all the others who would review my case _
literally held my life in their hands. They could reject me, and
with all those strikes against me, who could blame them? I was over
50, diabetic, had a partially functional heart and lymphoma that
came back once after I was ``cured'' (my term). My father had died
of a heart attack at 54 and my mother died of cancer at about the
same age. Oh, and one other thing, I was overweight and had been
since high school.
</P>
<P>
   Overweight isn't good. I know it, you know it and every doctor
in the world knows it. But in a strange way, it might have done me
some good, because I didn't look sick. Despite what I had been
through with diabetes, cancer, chemotherapy, heart attack and
cancer again, I didn't really look all that sick. Yes, my stride
was slower, but tmail at jimmorris(at)coxohio.com or by phone at
225-2409.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
