<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PEARSON-MARKETPLACE-1     08-14 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARSON-MARKETPLACE-1020(2TAKES)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: PEARSON CHIEF USES HER TEXAS ATTITUDE TO INSPIRE
GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Two graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Word in bold is italics.) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The folks back in Texarkana, Texas, should be proud of Marjorie
Scardino. True to her Lone Star State roots, Scardino, the chief
executive of Pearson PLC, thinks big.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1997, when she took charge of Pearson _ a British
publisher whose holdings include Penguin Books, The Economist, The
Financial Times and a major educational publishing operation _
Scardino has overhauled the formerly sleepy company, engineering
major acquisitions and asset sales as well as smaller deals.
</P>
<P>
   The result, Scardino contends, is a media company poised for
growth by extending its books, newspapers and magazines into
online, interactive communications. But the dizzying pace of change
has made it difficult for even some sophisticated financial
analysts to gauge the impact of the makeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyzing how the existing businesses are performing is very
difficult, which makes it tough to evaluate management,'' said
Michael Nathanson, a publishing industry analyst for Sanford C.
Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   So far, investors in Britain seem to love Scardino's attempt to
propel a stodgy company into the new economy. Since she took the
reins, the stock, which trades on the London Stock Exchange, has
risen more than 160 percent _ nearly triple the performance of
Britain's main index, the Financial Times Stock Exchange 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a Marjorie factor,'' one analyst said. ``They think
she can do magic.''
</P>
<P>
   And the company is so confident of investor support that Pearson
has secured a listing on the New York Stock Exchange, where its
shares will begin trading in September.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month Scardino announced Pearson's purchase of
National Computer Systems, based in Minneapolis, for $2.5 billion
in cash. The purchase is meant to let Pearson expand its electronic
educational business to include testing services and the connection
of schools to homes.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson is raising the money for the deal through a rights
offering that creates roughly 25 percent more shares _ a move that
worried some investors because the shares were sold at below-market
prices. Nonetheless, investors and analysts generally supported the
deal. And despite some concerns that Pearson was making yet another
high-priced acquisition, analysts generally found it a good
strategic fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really think education will change, and technology has
given people the way to change it,'' an enthusiastic Scardino said
in a telephone interview last week. ``It gives us the way to
integrate the assessment portion of education in our school
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Worthy as the deal may be, though, it goes on a Pearson plate
already heaped with acquisitions still waiting to be digested _
including the educational book division of Simon &AMP; Schuster, which
Pearson bought for $4.6 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Scardino has been unflinching in selling high-profile,
but peripheral, operations, like the group that owns Madame
Tussaud's wax museum, Pearson's stake in various Lazard Freres
investment arms, and its holdings in the BSkyB satellite
broadcasting business. But at some point, analysts say, Pearson's
chief will need to demonstrate her ability to manage the company
she has recast in her image.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Picker, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston, wrote
last week in a report that recommended holding, but not buying, the
stock that ``management is increasingly important, as publishers
attempt to shift from a preservation focus to a growth focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating Pearson's management skills is particularly difficult
at a company that is undergoing change at such lightning speed.
Even a key measurement _ profits or losses from continuing
operations _ tends to be a floating figure on such a fluid ledger.
</P>
<P>
   Profits and losses generated by one-time transactions have
accounted for an unusually large _ and varying _ chunk of operating
profit before taxes. In 1998, for example, the company reported 250
million pounds in operating profits. That represented 37.4 percent
of profits before taxes and interest. Last year, it posted 318
million pounds in operating profits, which accounted for about 50
percent of the 627 million pounds in profits before taxes and
interest. The balance was asset sales that included 348 million
pounds from the sale of Pearson's stake in the BSkyB satellite
broadcasting business.
</P>
<P>
   This year, analysts' estimates vary, but a new Morgan Stanley
report projects Pearson's profits from continuing operations at 357
million pounds, or 62 percent of profits before restructuring
charges and interest.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce it all to the simplest numbers: net per-share earnings
rose from 6 pence in 1997 to 74.1 pence in 1998 and fell back to
48.2 pence last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company whose financials change so dramatically with
acquisitions and sales, as evidenced by the huge percentage of
profits generated by transactions, makes it impossible with any
certainty to see what is happening to the performance of the
underlying operations,'' said Bruce Greenwald, a professor of
finance and economics at Columbia University's business school.
``That issue is crucial to the future because acquisition activity
only makes sense if supported by strong operating abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   In any acquisition, a buyer has some flexibility about writing
down costs in the year of the purchase. With publishing companies,
for example, those costs may include a portion of the expenses of
creating educational reading programs, paying writers' advances and
carrying inventory. Depending on how the numbers are recorded,
future profit projections can look better than they might have
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson's publishing operations represented 52 percent of its
$5.37 billion in 1999 sales. But while the company provided pro
forma comparisons for sales between 1998 and 1999, to reflect the
acquisitions, it did not provide pro forma numbers for 1998
operating profits.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein's Nathanson expressed his frustration over this issue
in a recent report. ``Pro forma historical comparisons are
difficult to make, to say the least,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even some bottom-line estimates are particularly complex. For
example, Pearson releases three different per-share earnings
figures _ earnings per equity share, earnings after removing
one-time charges but before Internet investments, and earnings per
share after one-time charges and after Internet investments.
</P>
<P>
   A Pearson spokesman, John Phallon, contends that such numbers
illuminate, rather than obscure, its financial performance because
they distinguish performance before and after acquisitions. Still,
Nathanson and a second analyst who insisted on anonymity said that
separating out Internet spending implies that Pearson wants
outsiders to view it is a mere extra. ``The reality is that
Internet spending is not an option,'' Nathanson said. ``It is a
necessity, given their businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Phallon added that the company also provided ``underlying sales
growth, trading margins'' and other measures to help investors. And
he said that providing 1998 pro forma figures for the Simon &AMP;
Schuster unit would have been difficult since its former owner,
Viacom, treated costs differently than did Pearson. Still,
Nathanson said those comparisons would have been helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Several other analysts said they too found the numbers
exceedingly complex. But they said they were leery of being
critical for fear that Pearson could make access more difficult.
Phallon contends he has found no difficulty among analysts ``in
understanding how we present our financial results.''
</P>
<P>
   Some deals, experts acknowledged, have been extremely clever.
Nathanson cited Pearson's television programming units, which were
worth about $1.5 billion before Scardino formed an alliance with
Bertlesmann and CLT-UFA, the big European broadcaster, to create
Audiofina. Pearson's 22 percent of Audiofina currently has a market
value of $4.84 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the premium prices paid for some recent acquisitions
have put extra pressure on Pearson's management to make them pay
off. Pearson paid $460 million, or about 1.6 times annual sales,
for the small children's book publisher Dorling Kindersly _ a high
multiple by traditional standards, according to industry
executives. The price for National Computer Systems was 50 times
annual profits, which analysts have also generally characterized as
top dollar.
</P>
<P>
   And while Pearson's expansions may bring many advantages, size
alone is not magical. Even after combining Pearson's existing
educational businesses with the Simon and Schuster unit, the
company has had mixed results in getting schools to use its books.
Though Pearson has done well in California, for example, its
performance in Texas has been mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Jovanovich, president of Pearson Publishing, said he was
pleased that educational sales were up 15 percent, but added, ``I
wish we had done better in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   And not all publishing experts are impressed by Pearson's heavy
investment in the education market. ``Why couldn't Pearson have
done a joint venture with NCS,'' one industry expert said of the
National Computer deal. ``Why did they need to buy it?''
</P>
<P>
   Jovanovich said that National Computing's software programs for
helping parents and teachers assess students' classroom performance
could be complementary to Pearson's textbook business and online
testing operations.
</P>
<P>
   And while Pearson says that it can find $50 million in cost
savings by combining with National Computer, gaining additional
revenues could be a far trickier route to increased profitability.
To one expert in the educational technology field, the issue will
be getting two different cultures to work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creating educational content is different from building and
testing administrative software for the schools,'' this person
said, speaking on condition of anonymity to avoid riling Pearson in
a field in which the company holds increasing power. ``The question
is whether they can integrate the educational experience and
combine it with the assessment business.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson itself had initially considered only an alliance with
National Computer and had even discussed that possibility with the
company. But when National Computer's chairman, Russ Gullotti, said
he was going to retire, he approached Jovanovich about assuming his
position. Scardino _ always on the lookout for a deal _ chose to
buy the company, perhaps, in part, because she was concerned about
losing Jovanovich.
</P>
<P>
   Now, while Jovanovich and other Pearson managers toil to
incorporate this latest acquisition, investors and analysts will
have their work cut out for them, too _ trying to get a fix on
Scardino's ever-changing company. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
