<P>
   WHAT IS STEPHEN KING TRYING TO PROVE?
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN-KING-CENTERPIECE _ In the same year as an accident that
nearly killed Stephen King, the world's most successful living
author has written a memoir, released an audio-only short-story
collection, put out the first mass e-book and even self-published a
novel on the Web, scaring the staid book business out of its wits.
By Stephen J. Dubner.
</P>
<P>
   (Stephen J. Dubner is the author of ``Turbulent Souls,'' a
family memoir. He is working on a book about hero worship.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Stephen King is available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
</P>
<P>
   THE NASDAQ-ING OF CAPITOL HILL
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-LOBBYISTS-CENTERPIECE _ Think big money rules politics in
America? Wait until the new dot-com lobby makes good on its plan to
habd out stock options as campaign donations. By Sara Miles.
</P>
<P>
   (Sara Miles is the author of ``How to Hack a Party Line: The
Democrats and Silicon Valley,'' to be published in January.)
</P>
<P>
   DEAD AIR: WHY CAN'T THE CAMPAIGNS STAGE A GOOD SPECTACLE?
</P>
<P>
   BORING-CAMPAIGNS-CENTERPIECE _ Political junkies, chew on this
demoralizing fact: Al Gore and George W. Bush have already spent
$150 million, and their campaigns get built-in coverage from the
networks, yet not only have they failed to produce a spectacle as
compelling as the World Wrestling Federation's ``SmackDown!'' they
can't even muster the ratings of ``The King of Queens'' reruns. By
David Plotz.
</P>
<P>
   (David Plotz is the Washington editor of Slate.com.)
</P>
