<SLUG> BC-DEM-POLITICAL-SURFING-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)  
 BEHIND THE SCENES: BRENTWOOD, BUNNIES AND BARBRA By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Everybody wanted to go behind the scenes Monday at
the Democratic National Convention, at least during the long hours
before President Clinton's address.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you looked on television or on the World Wide Web,
people were promising to take you backstage, past the security
guards, beyond the tall hedges of those Brentwood estates where the
glitterati were celebrating their wonderfulness and where,
presumably, all the really juicy stuff was going on. But if
Monday's reports are any indication, the convention is a lot like
Hollywood, with nothing behind the scenery but plywood, sawdust and
a snoozing gaffer.
</P>
<P>
   The National Journal, on its Web page, followed Rod O'Connor,
the convention's chief operating officer and ``a moving target for
favor seekers of all sorts.'' O'Connor's day began at 8 a.m., with
a staff meeting at the Staples Center. At 8:45, he and the
communications staff discussed the message of the day. At 9:15,
there was the first official media briefing, and the whining began.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor promised to help smooth the ``check-in-crush'' of
journalists waiting to get into the convention. At 10 a.m., he was
cornered by a staff member from Speakout.com, which was upset about
its placement in the media center. At 11:15 a.m., meeting with the
hall management staff in the Los Angeles Lakers' dressing room,
O'Connor had to figure out how to get more local media people onto
the podium, at least briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at a another staff meeting, O'Connor had to parcel out
skyboxes for opening night. ``Let's give B-3 to the mayor,'' he
decided. His cell phone rang. A major campaign donor wanted more
tickets to Thursday night. O'Connor made soothing noises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the whole business of the convention here,'' he told
the National Journal. ``You try to sift out what people really need
as opposed to what they'd like to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Web pages featured their Hollywood party reports,
promising to take us into those exclusive enclaves. Long gone,
apparently, are the days when starlets jumped nude into the
swimming pool while Errol Flynn got into a fistfight at the bar.
Yes, the reports were filled with bold-faced names and the sound of
champagne corks popping, but there was a noticeable scarcity of
juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats' deft decision to hold this week's extravaganza
in the heart of Los Angeles has given the party scene an almost
mythical quality as the nation's top political bigwigs connect with
some of Hollywood's hottest celebrities,'' wrote Molly M. Peterson
for the Hotline's Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Almost mythical, but not quite.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Friedman, the gossip columnist for Fox News, praised
Barbra Streisand's lavish Malibu compound, where Democrats with
thick wallets were gathered Sunday to donate $5 million to
President Clinton's presidential library. But, there was some
discontent beneath the surface, he reported. Some of the fat cats
were upset that Streisand did not favor them with a song. (``Good
dirt, Roger,'' the anchorwoman enthused.)
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's Jeannette Walls went to a party at the Playboy mansion
and found that some of the well-known names in attendance did not
wish to be photographed in such a place. And the bunnies were
off-limits, too. ``These girls are working,'' beefy security guards
warned reporters. ``They're not here to be interviewed. They're
here to mingle with the guests.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Eszterhas, the screenwriter of ``Showgirls'' and
best-selling author of ``American Rhapsody,'' wrote in Salon.com
that Hollywood was of two minds about the nomination of Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, a well-known critic of violence and sex in movies, as
Vice President Al Gore's running mate. Should they shun him for
fear of their livelihoods, or embrace him as better than a
Republican? ``This was a quandary worse than whether to pay Adam
Sandler 20 mill for his next picture,'' Eszterhas explained.
</P>
<P>
   And then, Monday afternoon on CNN's ``Talk Back Live,''
Eszterhas joined a panel fussing over whether Hollywood was going
to dominate the convention and the campaign. Cynical views abounded
from all points of the political spectrum, though none were able to
match the levels of cynicism exhibited by the people whose e-mail
messages are regular features of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians will take money from whoever will give it to
them,'' one cyber-citizen opined. ``It's the American way.''
</P>
<P>
   Another pleaded, ``Stop glorifying these egomaniacs.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Rothenberg of CNN decided that the Democratic convention
was structured pretty much like the Republican one, to deflect
attention from each party's weak points. ``Democrats gathering in
Los Angeles are being treated to a strong dose of religion,
morality and character,'' Rothenberg wrote. ``Welcome to Bizarro
World, where each party addresses its weaknesses and hopes to
neutralize its opponents' advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   So pay no attention to the man behind the curtain. It's just
another day in Bizarro World.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever you do, don't go near the bunnies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
