<HEADER>
A1511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      08-14 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSILE DEFENSE IS ONCE AGAIN A CAMPAIGN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the waning days of the Cold War, one of the main
disputes on national security between Republicans and Democrats
involved missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   President Ronald Reagan dreamed of protecting the United States
with an impenetrable missile shield _ a Strategic Defense
Initiative _ that, as he said in his second Inaugural Address,
``would render nuclear weapons obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats derided this ``Star Wars'' plan as technologically
infeasible and preposterously expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Soviet Union fell, other national security matters like
Iraq and Bosnia moved to the forefront politically and the question
of missile defense faded into the background. It was hardly
mentioned in the 1992 and 1996 election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Now the issue is back, in full force.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican party platform adopted in Philadelphia this month
and the Democratic platform to be approved in Los Angeles this week
both advocate construction of a missile defense system. But beyond
the superficial political statement that they are in favor of the
idea, the parties are proposing quite different systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans want ``robust missile defenses'' to be deployed
``based on an evaluation of the best available options at the
earliest possible date.'' The Clinton administration, the
Republican platform states, ``has become hopelessly entangled in
its commitment to an obsolete treaty signed in 1972,'' a reference
to the Antiballistic Missile Treaty, signed with the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, by contrast, accuse the Republicans of favoring
``an unproven, expensive and ill-conceived missile defense system
that would plunge us into a new arms race.'' The Democrats call for
a ``limited national missile defense system'' that would be
``compatible with the Antiballistic Missile Treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has made clear that he supports a
defensive system that would be based on land, at sea and possibly
in space to cover all 50 states and be extended to protect allies
in Europe, the Middle East and Asia. It sounds very much like a
revival of the Reagan dream.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, adopting the Clinton policy, supports a
much more modest land-based system that could provide protection
against a small number of missiles fired at the United States by
mistake or by what the Clinton administration previously called
rogue states but now describes as ``states of concern,'' like North
Korea or Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   This system should be built, in the Clinton-Gore view, only if
it can be shown to enhance national security and if the cost and
the technology are feasible. Bush calls this approach timid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who as vice president has been instrumental in setting the
administration's policy toward Russia, has expressed concerned that
any missile system would violate the Antiballistic Missile Treaty
and undermine U.S.-Russian relations. The Democratic platform's
insistence that the defense system be compatible with the treaty
was seen by some as a guarantee that no such system would ever be
constructed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he has no qualms about pulling out of the 1972
pact if the treaty keeps a missile defense from being built.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' positions are firmly grounded and have gone
unchanged despite recent technological developments and
intelligence estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Pentagon conducted a highly publicized test over
the Pacific Ocean to show that an incoming missile could be shot
out of the air. The $100 million test failed, the second one to
fail this year, meaning that the Pentagon has yet to prove that
even a basic missile defense is practical.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, a highly classified report was sent to Congress
warning that deployment of an American national missile defense
could prompt China to expand its nuclear arsenal tenfold and lead
Russia to place multiple warheads on ballistic missiles that now
carry only one.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the candidates' positions in favor of missile defense
may not be shaken by such developments is that they seem to be
based as much on domestic political calculations as strategic
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush clearly understands how Reagan's dream captured the public
imagination. As recently as this spring, years after the Reagan
plan was abandoned, a New York Times/CBS News poll found that 58
percent of American adults favored building a shield against
nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   As his campaign developed this year, Bush made a concerted drive
to speak out on national security issues to allay concerns about
his lack of experience in foreign policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, seeking to dispel any notion that Democrats
were soft on defense, developed his plan for a limited defense
system in his 1996 re-election campaign. In doing so, he employed
the technique of co-opting and modifying a popular Republican idea,
which had proved successful in areas like welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton plan was written into the Democratic platform in
1996, and it is basically the same plan Gore and the party have
adopted this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
