<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Tuesday, Aug. 15, and thereafter. The Daily News continues its
extensive coverage of the Democratic National Convention and
related issues with today's stories. For questions on any stories,
contact Gerry Hoppe at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   DNC-LEAVING (Los Angeles) _ If this is the capital city of the
21st century, how come half its residents want to secede and form
their own cities? Interviews with secessionists, litany of problems
in the city, history of how a once right-wing town run by a
committtee of 25 became a Democratic stronghold and frittered away
its wealth and qualilty of life to the point it may be broken up.
By Harrison Sheppard. (Will move in the ``a'' national, ``n''
California and ``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DNC-RAGE (Los Angeles) _ Rage Against the Machine performs a
live concert in the Staples Center protest zone to coincide with
President Clinton's speech. By Daily News Staff. (Will move in the
``a'' national, ``n'' California and ``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DNC-WELCOMES (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan,
never known as a slick or graceful public speaker, steps up to the
podium and welcomes the Democratic delegates and VIPs to the city.
About 30 children from across Los Angeles accompany the mayor as he
takes the stage. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``a'' national,
``n'' California and ``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   COSTCO-SHOOTING (Los Angeles) _ Owen Alexander Wolf, a
21-year-old Studio City resident who worked as a production
assistant for the television show ``Felicity'' was identified as
the shopper killed when he was shot in the head during a bungled
robbery of an armored car at Costco in Van Nuys. The injured
suspect who was arrested is from Tijuana, and police think the
other suspects are trying to make a run for the U.S.-Mexico border.
By Lisa Van Proyen. (Will move in the ``a'' national, ``n''
California and ``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAFFIC-LA (Los Angeles) _ Traffic was remarkably lighty across
Los Angeles on Monday, the first working day of the Democratic
National Convention. Longtime Angelenos say it reminds them of L A.
during the '84 Olympics, when fear of mass congestion caused most
residents to stay home or leave the region entirely for a summer
vacation. By Jason Kandel. (Will move in the ``a'' national, ``n''
California and ``p'' political news files.)
</P>
