<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEMOCRATS SAY THEY'LL SET THE RECORD STRAIGHT ON BUSH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 By BOB RAY SANDERS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a good thing that Republican nominee George
W. Bush doesn't plan to watch the Democratic National Convention
this week, because some of his fellow Texans have come here to help
``set the record straight'' about their governor's leadership
qualities.
</P>
<P>
   While the delegates here insist that they will not ``mess with
Texas'' by bashing their state during the convention, they will
definitely mess with Bush. They plan to tell anyone who will listen
that Democratic legislators had to fight Bush and his party all the
way in order to help poor children, teachers and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the governor used Texans during the Republican National
Convention to tout his record, Democrats will use Texans to show
that the governor either sat on the sideline, was held hostage by
Republicans in the Legislature or that he was a very reluctant
participant when it came to some very important legislation _
legislation for which he is now taking credit.
</P>
<P>
   They will portray the recent Republican convention as a sham,
one which touted diversity and inclusion. In reality, they say,
those are traits that Bush and the Republicans have never fully
understood or represented.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas County Commissioner John Wiley Price was even more harsh
in referring to the Philadelphia convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a minstrel show,'' Price said, alluding to the large
number of blacks and Hispanics who performed on the stage, and the
very small percentage of minorities who were delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Houston State Rep. Sylvester Turner, a trial lawyer who will
address his fellow state delegates this morning, likened the two
conventions and their messages to a courtroom proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   In a civil trial, he said, the plaintiffs go first, as the
Republican did two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge tells jurors, `There are two sides,''' he said.
```Don't make up your minds after hearing only one side. Wait to
hear both sides.'''
</P>
<P>
   With a big smile on his face, Turner declared, ``The second half
is about to be told.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that the message of the defense _ the Democrats _ is
``so strong, so real and so substantive,'' that it will resonate
with American families to the extent that they will realize Al Gore
is their obvious choice for president.
</P>
<P>
   Two Texans who will help carry that message to the convention
floor are State Rep. Domingo Garcia of Dallas and State. Sen. Mario
Gallegos Jr., of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who will speak tomorrow night, will talk about Bush's
education plan. He said he'll point out that Texas is No. 48 in SAT
scores and dead last in the number of children with health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will pick up on the Republican theme of ``Leave no
child behind,'' suggesting that if Bush and Republican legislators
had gotten their way many children in Texas would have been left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to fight and we had to push it,'' Gallegos said. ``He's
saying he did it. Let's get the record straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos said that when it came to the fight for expansion of
kindergarten in Texas, Bush's ``own aides went and testified in the
Senate that it would cost too much. George Bush fought us on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto on the teacher pay raise issue and the children's health
care initiative, with Republicans wanting far less than what
finally passed the Legislature. Still Bush is taking all the credit
for both, Gallegos said.
</P>
<P>
   After Democrats finish presenting their defense this week, it
will be up to the jury _ the American voters _ to decide which side
was most convincing.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
