<HEADLINE>
WORDS OF PLEDGE TO TEXAS FLAG NOT KNOWN BY SOME TEXAS DELEGATES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The embarrassment started early for Al Gore's
loyal Texas Democrats yesterday, when the delegate chosen to lead
the morning Pledge of Allegiance was a high school senior who
needed two tries to pass Government 1.
</P>
<P>
   She passed the test.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' other delegates flunked.
</P>
<P>
   Gwendolyn Creacy, 19, of Corpus Christi, didn't care much about
politics and said she hadn't planned to go vote last March in her
first presidential primary. But her father, a union member, made
her come along to the polls, and her fellow Democrats somehow
decided that she'd be a great national delegate.
</P>
<P>
   When the party selected her to lead the U.S. and Texas pledges
of allegiance yesterday, she said she didn't even know Texas
``had'' one.
</P>
<P>
   Sad. But she memorized it.
</P>
<P>
   Sadder yet: Almost none of the other Texas delegates knew the
pledge to the Lone Star Flag.
</P>
<P>
   After the pledge to the U.S. flag, she turned to the Lone Star
flag with her hand over her heart and began:''Honor the Texas
flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates looked at each other in confusion. ``What's this?''
one woman whispered.
</P>
<P>
   It's been Texas' pledge of allegiance since 1933:
</P>
<P>
   ``Honor the Texas flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pledge allegiance to thee,
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas, one and indivisible.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few faint voices in the giant ballroom recited along with
Creacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised,'' said delegate Hal Ray, a Fort Worth
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not a member of a group or civic club that starts
with a pledge of allegiance, nobody knows it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Creacy said her Corpus Christi public schools never began the
class day with a pledge of allegiance. Amazing. The way I figure
it, I recited the U.S. and Texas pledges more than 2,000 times
before my departure from the Fort Worth public schools.
</P>
<P>
   By 12th grade, we actually learned how to say ``indivisible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard it before,'' Creacy said. ``I don't think
anybody had.''
</P>
<P>
   And these are the people who are supposed to uphold the honor of
Texas?
</P>
<P>
   Texas' honor became fightin' words later in the day, when four
Texas Democrats barged into downtown Los Angeles _ not to campaign
for Gore, but to campaign for Republican presidential nominee
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A former attorney general, a state senator, a state
representative and a former Dallas County Democratic chairman all
came to defend the state against ridicule by the Gore campaign,
which has generally portrayed Texas as a backward territory and
which published a tongue-in-cheek news release declaring Houston
medically unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine Texas Democrats not being proud of the
education reforms adopted by Democrats and Republicans,'' said
Sandy Kress, an Austin lobbyist and former Dallas party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Former Democratic Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby and the late Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock helped initiate education reform, Kress said, but Bush
deserves credit for strengthening the reforms and adding tougher
school discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting at the curb outside the Republicans' campaign
headquarters was a quorum of Texas Democratic lawmakers, including
Democratic state Sen. Mario Gallegos Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats, not George W. Bush, led the way to improve
health insurance for children and to bring more diversity in higher
education,'' Gallegos said. ``He has had the opportunity to improve
things. He hasn't done it.''
</P>
<P>
   This was only the first of many Bush roasts to come this week,
if Bill Clinton ever leaves town.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody should remind the Texas delegates that until 1997,
Democrats had controlled the Texas Legislature for 126 years.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody should also remind them to learn the Texas pledge.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
