<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR STRAIGHT TALK FROM UNITED AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, Aug. 15, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lame lame lame! Does United train their people to lie?''
</P>
<P>
   _ United Airlines passenger Laura Bradley, one of hundreds of
dissatisfied customers who have vented their frustrations on the
griping web site, www.untied.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike just about everybody else who has flown United Airlines
this summer, I've had lovely experiences with the beleaguered
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   On-time departures and early arrivals. Tasty meals served with a
smile. Plenty of leg room. Courteous ticket clerks. Luggage
delivered with a gentle, caring touch.
</P>
<P>
   One crew even sang ``Leaving On a Jet Plane'' over the intercom
as our flight took off from O'Hare, and their harmonizing abilities
put Peter, Paul &AMP; Mary to shame. And when that Miss America-looking
flight attendant pinned those special golden wings on the lapel of
little Timmy with the IV in his arm, there wasn't a dry eye on the
plane ...
</P>
<P>
   Kidding of course. Sorry to mislead you, faithful reader, but I
couldn't resist the idea of some United Airlines executive at UAL
Corp. headquarters in Elk Grove Township, reading the above
paragraphs and allowing himself to feel a glimmer of optimism
before being jerked back to harsh reality _ which is sort of how
United passengers often feel these days, come to think of it.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, my adventures with United have been as wobbly and
perilous as a Cade McNown bomb: Even when the connection is made it
ain't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Typical was the experience I had while waiting in a line that
moved about as fluidly as Jabba the Hut after a half-dozen Happy
Meals. I actually found myself cheering when the ``DEPARTURE''
board changed to reflect an additional delay in my flight _ because
that meant I had a chance to make it to the front of the line and
check in before the damn thing took off. (I had a 95-minute cushion
when I took my spot in line. It took 110 minutes to reach the
counter.)
</P>
<P>
   At least I eventually got on my flight. A college-age woman a
few spots ahead of me _ her mountain of luggage indicating she was
either at the launch point or the tail end of a very long trip _
was given such bad news by the clerk that she was soon sobbing
full-out, her shoulders heaving as she covered her face. After she
shuffled off in search of a solution, the blase expression on that
clerk's face had several of us in line debating what sort of
penalty would be levied if one of us cracked him on the jaw and
told him to at least pretend to be concerned about the disappointed
passenger.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not all heavy drama on the United front. In fact the
biggest laugh I've heard from a live audience this summer did not
occur in a theater showing ``Scary Movie'' or ``The Klumps,'' it
was the roar of derisive hooting and guffawing I heard on a United
plane as it perched in a comatose state on a runway _ engines
turned off to preserve fuel, cabin air as stale as a ``Wassup!''
joke, flight attendants offering plastic glasses of water and
orange juice to us as if we were contestants on ``Survivor'' who
had won a beverage challenge _ and the pilot got on the intercom to
explain why we'd been on that runway for more than an hour, even
though the weather was fine.
</P>
<P>
   It went something like this: ``Ladies and gentlemen, we've got
about a dozen more aircrafts lined up ahead of us, so it'll be a
while before we even get word about when we're going to be able to
take off. The problem isn't the weather here or in Chicago, but the
storms in between _ and the skies are very congested today already,
so any trouble like that is bound to cause a chain reaction. I know
you've heard a lot about the situation with United pilots, but I
wanted to let you know in this case, it's really about the weather
and a lot of traffic in the skies, and nothing else. We appreciate
your patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Haw! Get this guy his own comedy special on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I'm saying the pilot was lying; the factors he cited
probably really were the reasons we were trapped on that damn
runway.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that we don't want to hear that kind of thing right
now from anyone who works for United. We don't want to hear
explanations, rationalizations or excuses of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   What we want is straight talk from someone who has answers or at
least can admit to not having answers, and we want that at the
airport as well as on the plane. Right now there shouldn't be a
single ``Position Closed'' sign hanging above a single computer in
any United terminal in the country. Management needs to pay
staffers double-time, triple-time, whatever, to speed up those
lines and figure out solutions when flights are screwed up.
</P>
<P>
   There also should be a clearly identifiable supervisor at every
turn _ someone who can provide answers or at least take the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Hell, there ought to be a dunk tank set up, with a revolving
cast of UAL execs taking the plunge. I'd wait in line for that.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
