<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL OPENS CONVENTION WITH PRAYER FOR THE UNBORN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill., N.Y.)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Roman Catholic archbishop of Los Angeles
called for an end to abortions as he delivered the invocation at
Monday night's opening of the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief address, Cardinal Roger Mahoney, one of the leading
religious voices against abortion in the state, said, ``In you, oh,
God, we trust that you will keep us ever committed to protect the
life and well-being of all people, but especially unborn children,
the sick and the elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a striking message that might have sounded more familiar
at a Republican convention, especially with the difficulties
Democrats have had in the past trying to attract Roman Catholic
leaders to speak at their conventions. Four years ago, the late
Cardinal Joseph Bernardin declined an invitation for the convention
in Chicago. In 1984 and 1992, when the Democrats held conventions
in New York, the late Cardinal John O'Connor turned them down. Both
clerics said their reason was the party's support of abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   With Democrats urgently trying to reach swing and undecided
voters in what figures to be a close election, Vice President Al
Gore tried again, this time issuing an invitation last week to
Maloney. Although his anti-abortion message was antithetical to
many Democrats, the cardinal's words could be viewed as an effort
to broaden the Democratic base, and to avoid controversy over
issues like the party leadership's decision in 1992 not to permit
Gov. Robert P. Casey of Pennsylvania, who opposed abortion, to
speak at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But just how far the cardinal's words spread was unclear. The
four-minute invocation followed welcoming remarks by Joe Andrew,
co-chairman of the Democratic Party, who opened the convention by
tapping a gavel in mid-afternoon, a time few would be watching on
television. In the main hall of the Staples Center, only a few of
the 4,339 delegates were in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Among those listening, Gloria Johnson, a delegate from San
Diego, shook her head in disgust. She said she was a strong
believer in the separation of church and state and an advocate of
abortion rights, adding that such an invocation deserved no place
at the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's offensive,'' she said. Then referring to convention
planners, she added, ``It's their decision, but I don't want to
listen to his prayer for the unborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Other delegates said the participation of the cardinal would
serve the Democrats well, even if his message contradicted core
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideological rigor was never a hallmark of the Democratic
Party, except the goodness of government,'' said George Moses, a
delegate from Boise, Idaho. ``But it pleasantly surprised me to
have a discussion of the issue at any time. I consider it a sign of
good politics.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
