<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-SANCHEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANCHEZ WON'T BE GIVING SPEECH AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ U.S. Rep. Loretta Sanchez withdrew Monday as a
featured speaker at the Democratic National Convention, saying that
her clash last week with party leaders over her plan to hold a
fund-raiser at the Playboy Mansion had already focused ``too much
press'' on her and the party.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, who represents the 46th Congressional District of
California, just south of Los Angeles, and is a co-chairwoman of
the Democratic National Committee, reluctantly agreed Friday to
shift the event from the mansion to a Universal Studios site after
angry convention planners revoked her invitation to address the
Tuesday session. She then was restored to the speakers list.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders had warned her that if a party official of her
high rank presided over a fund-raiser in a Playboy hangout, the
party's efforts to portray itself as the party of ``family values''
rather than the party of sex scandals would be set back
immeasurably. She resisted, arguing that the event was already sold
out, but eventually gave in when Vice President Al Gore and his
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, let it be known that they,
too, disapproved of the mansion site.
</P>
<P>
   Convention planners figured that was the end of the matter. But
Monday morning, Sanchez surprised them by requesting that her name
again be struck from the speakers list. On second thought, she
said, it would be best for her to stay out of the convention
limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was totally unexpected and a big disappointment to all of
us,'' said Jennifer Backus, a spokeswoman for the Democratic
National Committee. ``We had been planning to give her a rousing
welcome from the floor, complete with signs and banners. She's one
of our rising stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, who is Hispanic, represents a heavily Hispanic district
and her fund-raiser, scheduled for Tuesday, will raise money to be
used to get out the increasingly important, mostly Democratic
Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing her withdrawal as a convention speaker, Sanchez said
Monday morning during an interview with Fox News that it was not
true that she had shifted the fund-raiser to the Universal Studios
site because she feared losing a speaking spot. Rather, she
insisted, she made the move to avoid more adverse publicity for
both herself and the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved it away, `` she said, ``because it was getting too
much press, versus what we really have to do here at the
convention. In fact, that is one of the reasons why I won't be
speaking at this convention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
