<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-WASH-SENATE-NYT     08-14 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASH-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC SENATE PRIMARY IN WASHINGTON JUST STARTING TO HEAT UP 
</HEADLINE>
  By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It may be a stretch to say that Washington state
Democrats are paying rapt attention to next month's U.S. Senate
primary, in which the state insurance commissioner, Deborah Senn,
and former U.S. Rep. Maria Cantwell, now a wealthy Internet
executive citing her experience in the ``new economy,'' are
battling for the right to take on the three-term Republican
incumbent, Slade Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Senn arrived here the other evening for a campaign
speech to an electricians' union that had already endorsed her,
several of the electricians said they could not name the candidates
in the Sept. 19 primary, and they also labored a bit to identify
the issues they considered most pressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really going to focus on that till it's closer to the
time to go out and vote,'' explained one electrician.
</P>
<P>
   Another, Ed Pecotte, 57, seemed to sum up the mood of many at
the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, when he said:
``People are working, the economy seems to be humming along pretty
well. I'd like to hear how these candidates intend to help things
keep rolling along.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a clear sense on the campaign trail that voters are just
starting to concentrate on the race, the Democratic match-up shows
signs of becoming an intriguing and bitterly fought contest. And
the Washington Senate race is one that some national Democrats view
as a prime opportunity in the party's battle to take back control
of the Senate, where Republicans have a 54 to 46 edge.
</P>
<P>
   For Cantwell and Senn, the primary is the standard double-edged
sword of such contests: The candidates will likely create a lot of
publicity as the primary grows nearer but also risk draining their
resources and energy in the battle, with the victor having barely a
month and a half to shift gears for the main bout against the
well-financed Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   Senn got into the contest early, after several potential
Democratic heavyweights, including Gov. Gary Locke, state Attorney
General Christine Gregoire and King County Executive Ron Sims, all
took a pass on the race. (Locke is running for re-election, and
Gregoire and Sims, who lost to Gorton six years ago, seem to be
interested in running for his job later.)
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old Senn has racked up dozens of endorsements from
labor groups, lawmakers and others, and frequently points out that
she has won statewide races twice with more than 1 million votes,
more than Gorton has received in any of his six statewide races.
</P>
<P>
   Cantwell, on the other hand, enjoys the advantage of the
millions of dollars she has earned as a software executive at Real
Networks here and, in some ways, getting booted out of Congress
after one term in the 1994 Republican tide could turn out to be the
best thing that ever happened to her politically. The former
congresswoman, 41, has vowed to spend ``whatever it takes'' to
unseat Gorton, 72, and also says she has ``real world''
private-sector experience with the Internet economy that, she says,
makes her a stronger candidate than if she had stayed in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Under Washington's unusual ``blanket primary'' system, all
candidates for Senate, including Gorton, will be on the ballot
Sept. 19, with the top vote-getter among Democrats, regardless of
her percentage, surviving to face the incumbent on the November
ballot. Any third-party candidate who receives more than 1 percent
of the primary vote also makes the general election. This will
almost surely be the last year Washington uses such a system,
though: After a U.S. Supreme Court ruling in June threw out a
similar primary system in California that was open to all voters,
state officials here are virtually certain to change the rules to
withstand a similar challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Cantwell has already been on the air with a series of television
advertisements, describing her background and pledging to fight for
ways to control the costs of prescription drugs, an issue that has
emerged here, as in other states, as a major concern for many
voters, especially older ones. With stock options estimated to be
worth at least $10 million and a declared willingness to spend her
own money, the former congresswoman is likely to be firmly fixed in
voters' minds by next month. And, for the moment anyway, she seems
to be all but ignoring Senn, explaining that only she can win by
making a much larger impression on the voters, rather than by
dissecting her primary opponent's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this as a huge task of a cynical public that really
doesn't want to hear too much about politics,'' Cantwell explained
the other day after a campaign event in which she had appeared with
Helen Jackson, the widow of Sen. Henry M. Jackson, to support an
increase in federal conservation funds. ``So my challenge is bigger
than Deborah Senn and Slade Gorton,'' Cantwell says. ``It's
convincing the public that you can make a difference in this
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Senn said she has been battling insurance companies and fighting
for lower drug costs for years in her state post, and scoffed at
Cantwell's interest in the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with all that, with all the work we've done, I'm faced
with Maria Cantwell on the air spending a million bucks, telling
people she's going to solve their prescription drug problems,''
Senn said in an interview this week, after speaking to the
electricians' union. ``There's no record behind that ad. It is a
promise, not performance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cantwell said she has a record in Congress on all kinds of
health-care issues, and she has also made computer privacy a
campaign issue, noting that she was a prime player in 1994 in
fighting Clinton administration proposals, later dropped, that
privacy advocates feared could increase government surveillance of
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Senn has attacked that stance, noting that Real Networks itself
got into hot water a few years ago after it emerged that one of its
software programs could store information on customers'
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``A privacy pledge from Maria Cantwell is like having Jesse
James promote bank security,'' Senn said.
</P>
<P>
   While differing in some respects on free trade _ Cantwell was a
strong supporter of the North American Free Trade Agreement, while
Senn has said she would probably not have voted for the accord in
the form that came before Congress _ the candidates agree on many
other issues. And they both identify health care, education and the
environment as major campaign themes. For that matter, so does
Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say Gorton, who has been in public life almost
continuously for more than 30 years, is more conservative than most
Washington residents and thus vulnerable to an upset this November.
He has failed to get a 50 percent approval rating in some polls,
another sign of hope for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gauging the candidates' support at this juncture is tricky,
since voters are just starting to pay attention and Senn, who has
raised $1.6 million and will likely have less to spend than
Cantwell, has yet to start running television ads. The Democratic
candidates are not scheduled to debate until next month. One
statewide poll last month of 400 registered voters by Stuart Elway,
an independent pollster who is not working for any candidate in the
race, found 21 percent supporting Cantwell and 12 percent for Senn,
with 42 percent for Gorton and most of the rest undecided.
</P>
<P>
   All three candidates do have at least one thing in common: they
were raised in the Midwest. If Gorton loses, Patty Murray, a
Democrat, will become the senior senator and Washington will become
the third state, after California and Maine, to have two women in
the Senate. Just over 40 percent of state lawmakers are women, the
highest percentage in any state Legislature in the nation's
history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
