 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DEMONSTRATORS CLASH WITH POLICE DURING PROTEST AGAINST GORE &HT;    By MARK HELM
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ About 600 environmental protesters marching on the
opening day of the Democratic National Convention here clashed with
police Monday during a demonstration targeting Al Gore's ties to
Occidental Petroleum Corp., which plans to drill for oil on land in
Colombia claimed by an indigenous tribe.
</P>
<P>
   After a rally across the street from the Staples Center, site of
the convention, the protesters _ holding 30-foot papier mache
puppets and chanting, ``Al Gore, Reject Big Oil'' _ began marching
under the watchful eye of several hundred police in riot gear
toward Pershing Square in downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks from the square, about a third of the marchers
stopped at an intersection. Police warned them to move along to
allow traffic to flow. When they refused, the police charged with
their batons and began pushing the protesters up the street toward
the square. After about 15 minutes and 10 arrests, the protesters
backed off and rejoined the march.
</P>
<P>
   Beka Economopoulos, speaking for the D2KLA, an umbella group
that helped organize the protests, accused the police of
overreacting. ``Our people were completely nonviolent, and yet the
police attacked them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But police spokeswoman Donna Danko said the officers used
``appropriate force'' to keep the streets clear. ``Considering the
taunts and attitude of the protesters, our officers used
extraordinary restraint,'' she insisted.
</P>
<P>
   The march was the latest in a series of protests that have
followed Gore throughout his presidential campaign. The
demonstrators want him to denounce the company's Colombia plans and
shed his family's shares of Occidental, which he valued at $500,000
and $1 million on his May 22 public financial disclosure report.
Gore has refused.
</P>
<P>
   The stock originally belonged to Gore's father, onetime Sen.
Albert Gore Sr., D-Tenn., who in 1972, two years after leaving the
Senate, became chairman of an Occidental subsidiary, Island Creek
Coal, earning a $500,000 annual salary. He died in 1998 and left
the shares in a trust for Al Gore's mother Pauline. Gore, as
executor of the trust, has control of the shares.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials could not be reached for comment, but in
the past the vice president has said that the stock belongs to his
mother and not him.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles-based Occidental has fought for nine years to
begin drilling on land in Colombia's Andes Mountains, which experts
say holds as much as 1.3 billion barrels of oil. But an indigenous
tribe, the U'wa, claims the land belongs to it. Leaders of the
5,000-member tribe contend that the drilling would would bring
environmental disaster and the demise of their culture. In 1997,
the leaders vowed to walk off a 1,400-foot cliff if Occidental
drills on the land.
</P>
<P>
   The issue threatens to embarrass Gore, whose campaign has
focused on his history as an environmentalist.``The guy is a total
hypocrite,'' said Tim Roacher, 19, a student from Portland, Ore.,
who held a sign reading, ``Gore, Oxy out of U'wa land.'' ``He says
that he's for the environment, but when no one is looking, he does
what they all do, which is take the money.''
</P>
<P>
   More protests were scheduled for Monday, including one entitled
``Billionaires for Bush (or Gore).'' A concert by the band Rage
Against the Machine was also set to be held across the street from
the Staples Center, which is protected by hundreds of officers and
a 13-foot concrete fence.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's march was considerably smaller than a demonstration
Sunday, in which more than 3,500 protesters jammed downtown streets
in support of Mumia Abu-Jamal, a Pennsylvania death row inmate
convicted on killing a Philadelphia police officer in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
