u p BC-DEM-GORE-ART-NYT     08-14 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ACCUSES GOP TICKET OF HIDING BEHIND GENERALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Will be updated with St. Louis rally.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo  NYT5  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ In a flash preview Monday of his upcoming
convention speech, Vice President Al Gore plunged into some of the
details of how he would shore up Medicare and Social Security and
suggested that Gov. George W. Bush was hiding behind generalities
because his tax-cut proposal would cut benefits and hurt other
programs like community policing.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is hoping that his speech on Thursday, when he accepts the
Democratic nomination for president, will accomplish a couple of
things _ give him a political mandate to follow the course he is
proposing, and portray the Republicans as speaking vaguely because
their positions are unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give generalities and not give the specifics _ that's not
the best way to elevate our democracy,'' the vice president said
during a discussion with senior citizens Monday at a forum here in
Harry Truman's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers say these discussions, while not exciting,
address the concerns of ordinary Americans and play to Gore's
strengths, including his grasp of policy, and at the same time
suggest that Bush is unprepared to grapple with such basic issues.
Gore has opposed Bush's broad tax-cut proposal, saying it would
force the government to cut back on various programs like Social
Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely they're worried that the American people won't agree
with them because otherwise they'd give you the specifics,'' Gore
said as he described Bush's proposal to allow people to invest some
of their Social Security payroll taxes in the stock market and to
grant a $1.3 trillion tax cut over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you going to make up a trillion dollars over the
next 10 years?'' Gore asked of Bush's tax-cut proposal. ``That's a
fundamental question. And it's not a partisan question. It's a
question that the American people have a right to get an answer
to.''
</P>
<P>
   As he looked toward his convention, Gore also sought to place
himself in the populist Democratic tradition of presidents Franklin
D. Roosevelt, who signed Social Security into law on Aug. 14, 1935,
and Truman, who first argued for Medicare, which President Lyndon
Johnson signed into law in Independence on July 30, 1965, in honor
of Truman.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gore seemed to gain inspiration during his discussion
of specifics versus generalities from a 1936 speech by Roosevelt.
In that speech, delivered at a state Democratic party convention in
Syracuse, N.Y., Roosevelt referred to the ``smooth evasion'' of the
Republicans, who hated his social programs but knew the public
liked them.
</P>
<P>
   After reading the quotation from Roosevelt, Gore declared,
``Well, he had their number, didn't he?'' and the audience of about
200 seniors burst into applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people on the other ticket are good men,'' Gore asserted.
``I'll never attack them personally. But I do think the American
people deserve to know the specifics about how the American people
would be affected if the other side won, how the American people
will be affected if we win,'' he said, in a careful shift from the
subjunctive when speaking of a Republican win and a more certain
future tense when projecting a Democratic win.
</P>
<P>
   ``And here's what I want to do,'' Gore said. ``I want to extend
the life of Social Security, I do not want to cut benefits, I do
want the kinds of reforms that make sense, using the trust fund to
help pay down the debt and make big savings in the interest we have
to pay on that debt. I want to extend the life of the Medicare
trust fund through a similar approach, and I want to add a
prescription drug benefit for seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on: ``I will take the Medicare trust fund and the Social
Security trust fund and put them in an ironclad lock box with a
sign that says, `Politicians, hands off! That's to be used only for
Social Security and Medicare and not for anything else! Hands
off!'''
</P>
<P>
   Gore traveled later in the day to St. Louis, where he was
holding a rally with his vice presidential running mate, Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, and their wives before watching President
Clinton's valedictory speech at the convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
