<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-DNC-PROGRESSIVES-     08-14 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-DNC-PROGRESSIVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
PROGRESSIVES WARN GORE OF NADER THREAT
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DAN FREEDMAN
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Hearst Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Leaders of the liberal wing of the Democratic
Party on Monday said Vice President Al Gore must start making
distinctions between his policy proposals and those of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush or risk losing liberal voters to Green Party
insurgent Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a meeting of liberal activists on the Democratic
National Convention's opening day, Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn.,
offered a warning to Gore: Start emphasizing hard differences
between himself and Bush on such issues as higher wages, health
care, Social Security, or liberal voters might look more seriously
at Nader, the veteran consumer rights advocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president ... has got to speak to these economic
issues,'' Wellstone told the group of 100 activists. ``There are a
lot of people I see right now voting for Ralph Nader and I don't
think they should be taken lightly at all.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I think we need to come out of this convention with
a strong speech that speaks directly to these bread-and-butter
economic issues that are so important.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Bush's strength in the polls, Wellstone and other
liberals indicated they are willing to overlook their own policy
differences with Gore in order to prevent a Bush victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to be persuaded that the differences make a
difference,'' said Wellstone, referring to Gore and Bush. ``I think
George W. would repeal the 20th Century if he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Differences between liberals and Gore are significant. Liberals,
who now refer to themselves as ``progressives,'' oppose the death
penalty but Gore supports it. They oppose the overhaul of welfare
requiring work after two years but Gore supports it.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals such as Bob Borosage, co-director of the
Washington-based Campaign for America's Future, believe ``there is
much more agreement with Gore-Lieberman than disagreement,''
particularly on Social Security and other economic issues.
Borosage's group sponsored the Monday meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants private investment accounts in Social Security; Gore
opposes them. And Bush wants government vouchers for parents whose
children attend failing schools that show no sign of improving;
Gore supports lowering class size and building more schools, but
opposes vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals are in sync with Gore on all these issues.
</P>
<P>
   Urging liberals to support the Gore-Lieberman ticket, James K.
Galbraith, an economics professor at the University of Texas in
Austin, said they are ``part of a coalition....when you're part of
a coalition, you help the coalition win.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jan Schakowsky, D-Ill., a leading Capitol Hill liberal,
said a Gore-Lieberman victory would ``give us a leg up, no question
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with a Democratic takeover of the House of
Representatives, a Gore administration would ``help us get out of
our defensive crouch and move our agenda at a faster pace,'' she
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The position of liberals in the Democratic Party is analagous to
that of social conservatives within the Republican Party. Gore and
Bush both value those outlying wings of their respective parties
and throw occasional bones to each in speeches and party platforms.
But ultimately, their strategies involve keeping the wings to the
side, not letting them cloud the image each hopes to project of
inclusive centrism.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, Lieberman and other centrist Democrats who dominate the
party never talk about increased government spending, a favored
progressive theme. It's always ``investment.'' They never talk
about the Democratic Party as wanting to uplift the poor and
minorities. To them, the party is ``fighting for working
families.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reality, according to Borosage, is that union workers,
teachers and environmentalists _ people he describes as ideological
liberals _ represent 40 percent or more of the convention's
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The base of the party is progressive and the activist base is
even more progressive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In sheer numbers, only 23 percent of voters consider themselves
``liberal'' or ``very liberal,'' according to a New York Times poll
released Monday. But among delegates, that rises to 34 percent, the
survey showed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   American liberalism has been in eclipse since its high-water
mark in the 1960s and President Lyndon B. Johnson's ``Great
Society'' spending programs aimed at eliminating poverty and social
inequality.
</P>
<P>
   Liberalism appeared to be interred forever with the election of
Ronald Reagan in 1980. As president, Reagan spent heavily on
defense but pushed tax cuts and diminished domestic spending under
the banner of doing away with big government. The Democratic
nominee in 1984, former Vice President Walter Mondale, said he
would raise taxes as would Reagan, but Reagan would not admit it.
Reagan was re-elected that fall, winning 49 states in the greatest
Republican landslide in history.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, liberals re-invented themelves as progressives. In
the past seven years as the Clinton-Gore administration crab-walked
to the center supporting the death penalty, overhauling welfare,
and cutting a deal with Republicans to balance the budget,
progressives have re-positioned themsevles as the Democratic
party's the left-of-center conscience.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of the campaign, progressives say they are
concerned by Gore's playing defense to the Republican offensive on
the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal that almost cost President Clinton
his job last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's choice of Lieberman was widely viewed as an attempt by
Gore to insulate himself against Republican attacks on the Lewinsky
scandal and Democratic Party moral values in general. Lieberman, a
deeply religious orthodox Jew, was the first Senate Democrat to
publicly excoriate Clinton for having an affair with the former
White House intern and then lying about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice (of Lieberman) is about rebuking Clinton, but the
public showed us (during impeachment hearings and off-year
elections in 1998) that they're not voting on that,'' said
Borosage. ``The Gore-Lieberman ticket needs to move beyond
(defending Clinton and the Clinton-Gore administration.) Time is
getting short.``
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reaced at 213-336-1800 or via e-mail:
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
