<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-FUNDRAISING-NYT     08-14 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS CALL CONVENTION PARTIES A LOT OF THINGS _ EXCEPT
FUND-RAISERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (Exclusive) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The party that closed a city block outside Spago
in Beverly Hills on Sunday night was not a fund-raiser, Democratic
officials contended Monday. Nor was the reception for big-money
donors at the Giorgio Armani boutique, they asserted. Nor was the
late-night dessert reception for the Democratic Party's most
generous givers with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In Democratic fund-raising parlance, these were merely ``donor
servicing'' or ``donor maintenance events.'' The distinction party
leaders draw is that no money actually changes hands at these
affairs; the checks have already long since been cashed. The lavish
fetes are designed to ``energize'' donors and keep the cash flowing
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have not staged a fund-raising gala in Los
Angeles, as the Republicans did in Philadelphia with a $10 million
event headlined by George W. Bush. Yet the Democratic Party has
been as aggressive as the Republicans in using its convention to
give royal treatment to the biggest donors to put them in the mood
to write new checks for the fall campaign. In fact, supporters who
contributed at least $100,000 to the Democratic National Committee
were issued a glossy, 18-page ``Convention 2000 Passport.'' It
lists four days and nights of invitation-only meals, receptions and
intimate events with party leaders, including the president, Vice
President Al Gore and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, party leaders, worried about criticism of overzealous
fund raising four years ago, are trying to play down the fund
raising occurring here.
</P>
<P>
   Terry McAuliffe, the Democrats' fund-raising impresario and
chairman of the Democratic convention, said the party's national
convention is nothing like the Republican gathering in Philadelphia
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in stark contrast to what went on in Philadelphia,
where they turned the entire Republican convention into a
fund-raiser,'' McAuliffe said. ``One night they bragged they raised
$15 million. I mean, thank goodness the Liberty Bell was bolted
down or they would have sold that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another reason party leaders want to keep the money
chase more muted, at least officially. In its convention platform,
the party advocates a federal ban on the large political
contributions known as ``soft money.'' Gore has pledged to make
outlawing soft money his first legislative priority. Democrats are
worried that the continuing investigation of fund-raising abuses in
the 1996 election could hurt Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In defending against charges of abusive fund raising four years
ago, Democratic leaders have done some semantic gyrations in
explaining some of their fund-raising techniques. For example, the
White House said that more than 100 coffees for top donors during
the 1996 campaign were not fund-raising events, but rather ``donor
maintenance'' affairs to reward supporters for past generosity.
Gore likewise initially described the now-infamous luncheon at the
Hsi Lai Buddhist Temple in 1996 as a ``community outreach''
session, not a fund-raiser, even though nuns and others at the
temple contributed more than $100,000 to the Clinton-Gore campaign.
Later, he said his temple visit was ``finance-related.'' When he
was questioned last April by the special counsel investigating
campaign finance abuses, Gore again insisted the temple event was
not a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The party is sensitive about appearing overzealous once again.
But that has not stopped the establishment of an elite donor club
for $500,000 contributors called the Chairman's Circle. Several
unions and three individuals are among its inaugural members:
Baltimore lawyer Peter G. Angelos, Philadelphia philanthropist
Peter L. Buttenwieser and SlimFast Foods founder S. Daniel Abraham.
(The Republicans' own top-donor club, the Regents, has 139
individuals and corporations that have given $250,000 or more.)
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party identifies four dozen sponsors of their
``donor servicing'' affairs in Los Angeles, including America
Online, BellSouth, Ernst &AMP; Young, Fannie Mae, Texaco and United
Parcel Service. The list also includes more obscure sponsors such
as Homestore.com, the American Society of Cataract and Refractive
Surgery, the Pechanga Band of Luiseno Mission Indians and the
Soboda Band of Mission Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the efforts by McAuliffe and other Democratic officials
to distinguish their convention from the Republicans' gathering in
Philadelphia, some party officials acknowledge that thanking donors
and soliciting more funds are an important part of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not pretending we're not trying to raise money here,''
said Joe Andrew, the Democratic national party chairman. ``We're
obviously trying to raise money to get the message of Gore and
Lieberman to the country. It costs money to get that message on
television.'' But Andrew also said many of the receptions this week
fall in the ``donor servicing'' category.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russell D. Feingold, D-Wis., who, with Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., has championed campaign finance overhaul legislation, said
in an interview Monday that he is disgusted and ashamed of his
party's fund-raising activities here. He called them ``a system of
legalized bribery and legalized extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   When told that some party officials said that little or no fund
raising was occurring outside the Staples Center, Feingold scoffed.
``That's absurd,'' he said. ``In room after room, hotel after hotel
and private home after private home, there are literally scores of
fund-raisers that include contribution levels as high as $50,000 or
$100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Feingold is the co-sponsor, with McCain, of legislation that
would ban soft money. Before a cheering throng at the shadow
convention here on Sunday, Feingold declared that the major
political parties' conventions have become nothing more than a
brazen chase for large donations and ``corporate trade shows for
the delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These conventions are serving as a symbol of the corruption
and influence of money in our system that surely will not be lost
on the American people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold cited as examples the numerous ``tributes'' to members
of Congress sponsored by major corporations and attended by donors
of $20,000 to $100,000. Among them are a luncheon for Sen. Dianne
Feinstein of California sponsored by Chevron and a dinner for Sen.
Tom Daschle of South Dakota paid for by Global Crossing, a
telecommunications concern. BellSouth, US West, EchoStar
Communications and UPS are picking up the tab for a late night
concert by singer Cheryl Crow on behalf of Sen. Patrick Leahy of
Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Convention is holding only one formal
fund-raiser, a concert featuring Barbra Streisand, Babyface and
Whoopi Goldberg on Thursday night following the close of the
convention. Party officials estimated the concert will raise
between $3 million and $4 million in ``hard money,'' contributions
that are limited in size (the maximum individual donation is
$1,000) but can be used for any political purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventions are used to rally the political troops but also to
get our donors excited and motivated for the fall,'' said Jenny
Backus, the DNC spokeswoman. ``We all have the same goal _ to elect
a Democratic president and Congress.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
