LOS ANGELES: and Congress.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The convention itself is being underwritten by a roster of
blue-chip corporations, many of whom also sponsored the Republican
convention. General Motors, for example, is contributing $1 million
in cash and services and 400 cars, the same level of largess it
displayed in Philadelphia. The nation's largest automaker is also
sponsoring several receptions for lawmakers and donors.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jordan, the political director of the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee, said the convention was a time to reward past
donors and build a fund-raising base for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the convention package we offer donors is an
incentive for generosity,'' Jordan said. ``But this isn't the week
for picking up checks. This is the week for picking up business
cards.''
</P>
