 PERSONALS: All That Glitters in Los Angeles 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Glimpses of the convention-related party scene over the weekend:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Barbra Streisand &LR;  raised about $5 million for the Clinton
library with a lunch for 50 couples at her Malibu ranch on Sunday,
August 13, but she hardly hobnobbed with her guests. ``Streisand
looked bored and never said a word,'' a guest told the online
gossip Fox411. ``She was not a gracious hostess, although her house
is maybe the most beautiful house I've ever seen . . . just about
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   _ At Saturday night's (Aug. 12) Hollywood Farewell to  &UR; Bill &LR; 
 &UR; Clinton &LR;  ($1,000 for the concert, $25,000 for dinner), the
president's eyes filled with tears when  &UR; John Travolta &LR;  told him,
``We only wish we could have you another eight years.'' The New
York Post reported that  &UR; Chelsea Clinton  &LR; ``showed cleavage.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Porta Pottis at the Hollywood salute had oaken floors with
matching seats, Oriental carpets, faux marble sinks, brass fixtures
and faux crystal sconces. The Chicago Tribune overheard
 &UR; Carol Burnett &LR;  giving them a rating of 10-plus.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Albert Brooks &LR;  attended a Los Angeles Times party for
journalists and actors who play journalists on TV and in movies,
and told the Tribune that most people in Hollywood cozy up to
politicians with ulterior motives. ``It's more than hanging around.
I don't think Hollywood types would hang around any politicians
unless there was some sort of symbiotic relationship . . . to get
their phone calls returned, to have an influence on policy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that after ``Broadcast News,'' he was invited to a
dinner with Ronald Reagan, and then to a state dinner at the Reagan
White House. ``But I didn't go,'' said Brooks. ``It got to be too
much. All of a sudden, I'm the Republican poster boy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; OBSERVANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Council of Torah Sages, an ultra-Orthodox community in
Isral, has banned the Internet from ultra-Orthodox homes, reports
Wired magazine. The council calls the Net ``one thousand times more
hazardous than television,'' which it banned 30 years ago. The
problem council members see is the need to shield children from
pornography and violence.
</P>
<P>
   At least one spiritual leader, Rabbi  &UR; Levi Itzhak Halperin &LR; , is
developing technologies for office use that will be acceptable to
the ultra-Orthodox, but these will be strictly for use in offices,
not homes. The rabbi's Web site is  &LR; www.machon- &LR; 
 &LR; science-halacha.org.il &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ul  &LR; _ &LR; A recent letter from an Encino man to the editor of the
Los Angeles Times complained about the bass player in the rear row
of the Los Angeles Philharmonic, who never joins in when ``The
Star-Spangled Banner'' is played. ``It's very noticeable and
annoying to our guests,'' writes the complainant.
</P>
<P>
   A response _ forwarded to Personals by &UR; Michael Jarvis &LR;  _ was
forthcoming: ``The bass player is a member of the Jehovah's
Witnesses,'' says the Philharmonic's  &UR; Rachelle Roe &LR; . ``He has
complete respect for the government of the United States of
America. However, his religious belief calls for complete
neutrality. He cannot give his allegiance to a flag or country. . .
. The L.A. Philharmonic does not interfere with the religious
beliefs or private lives of its musicians.''
