 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON TELLS DEMOCRATS THAT GORE WILL KEEP PROSPERITY ROLLING &HT;    (EDS: Will be updated with full speech)
 &HT;    lBy STEWART M. POWELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES President Clinton, declaring that the Democratic
ticket of Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman ``will keep our prosperity
going,'' boasted to the Democratic National Convention Monday night
that his eight-year partnership with Gore has fashioned ``a better
country`` from the wreckage of past Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The president, a charismatic Arkansas Democrat who has sparked
controversy almost from the day he took office, bid farewell to the
Democratic faithful, offered warm praise for his loyal vice
president and appealed to voters to choose Gore's specifics-rich
policy proposals over what the president portrayed as the vague,
ill-considered schemes of Republican rival George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment of unprecedented good fortune, our people face
a fundamental choice: Are we going to keep this progress and
prosperity going?`` Clinton rhetorically asked cheering party
faithful crammed into the 20,590-seat Staples Center for the
opening night of the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built our bridge to the 21st century. We crossed it
together. And we're not going back,`` Clinton declared. First lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton, who introduced her husband for his
valedictory to the faithful,
</P>
<P>
   echoed her husband's theme in remarks designed to bolster her
campaign for a Senate seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a stronger, better country than we were in 1992,'' Mrs.
Clinton said, adding that America's progress can continue with Gore
and Lieberman. ``They have what it takes; they'll do what it
takes,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president, a combative partisan, sought to counter claims
voiced by Bush at the Republican convention on Aug. 3 that the
Clinton-Gore administration had squandered`` opportunities
presented by unprecedented prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who say the progress of the last eight years was an
accident, that we just coasted along, let's be clear America's
success was not a matter of chance, it was a matter of choice,``
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president proudly laid claim to responsibility for the
longest economic boom in American history and for generating
federal budget surpluses, slashing the national debt, restoring
national confidence and transforming education, child care, the
welfare system, inner cities and the federal tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has progressed not just economically but as a
community,`` Clinton said. ``We're not just better off we're also a
better country
</P>
<P>
   more decent, more humane, more united moving forward and working
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who seized the limelight with appearances at more than
20 events over four days in Los Angeles, was scheduled to leave Los
Angeles on Tuesday for a campaign rally in Monroe, Mich., where he
will symbolically pass the torch to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the convention that Gore had been worked side by
side in the Oval Office ``in the most difficult days of the last
years, when we faced the toughest issues.'' Clinton added: ``He was
always there.'' Gore ``understands the future and how sweeping
changes can affect Americans' daily lives,'' Clinton said, adding
that a Gore-Lieberman administration ``will keep our prosperity
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, White House press secretary Joe Lockhart derided Bush's
claims that Americans had suffered under the Clinton-Gore
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush family may be worse off than they were eight years
ago, but I think the vast majority of Americans will argue that
their lives have become better,`` Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also planned to use his farewell address to give a boost
to the Senate campaign of his wife of 25 years, who faces a tough
fight with Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., to succeed retiring Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. , Lockhart said. Clinton, who has said he
plans to join his wife at their newly-purchased home in Chappaqua,
N.Y., after leaving the White House, wanted to outline ways that
she could help New York's 18 million people, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman linked up on the campaign trail in St. Louis
to watch the Clintons' nationally televised address.
</P>
<P>
   Gore staged a symbolic pilgrimage earlier in the day to the home
town of President Harry S. Truman, the scrappy, plain-spoken
Missouri Democrat who came from behind in 1948 to extend Democrats'
hold on the White House to 20 straight years until 1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a contrast in this election and the American people
deserve to know the details of what's being proposed by the two
major parties,`` Gore told a forum in Independence, Mo. ``The
American people need to know the specifics of how the American
people would be affected if the other side won.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Stanley Greenberg, who served as the Clinton-Gore
campaign's pollster in 1992, told reporters that Gore needs to
ignite voter turnout by focusing public attention on differences
between the rivals. ``What matters for turnout is having an
election that matters,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest nationwide survey, conducted by John Zogby of Zogby
International in Utica, N.Y., and released Monday, showed Bush's
17-percentage-point edge over Gore following the GOP convention had
been cut to 3 percentage points 43 percent for Bush to 40 percent
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter said in an NBC News' interview
that Clinton's successes are helping to overshadow a dark chapter
in his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the escapades of President Clinton in the White
House are still in people's memories, but I think that time is
passing by,`` Carter said, adding: ``There has never been a hint of
scandal about Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who returns to the campaign trail on Friday with a
symbolic raid on Gore's native Tennessee, remained at his
1,500-acre ranch in Crawford, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
stewarthearstdc.com)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
