<HEADER>
A1557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SRILANKA-OUTLOOK-760&AMP;     08-14 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SRILANKA-OUTLOOK-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF SRI LANKA MOVES TOWARD PEACE, BUT OTHERS DO NOT
FOLLOW
</HEADLINE>
 By CELIA W. DUGGER  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka _ This war-haunted nation's president,
blinded in her right eye by a suicide bomber's attack, still talks
of peace. But many ordinary Sri Lankans are more convinced than
ever that no end is near to the country's 17-year war with the
Tamil rebels.
</P>
<P>
   President Chandrika Kumaratunga hoped that a new constitution
she proposed on Aug. 3 would preserve Sri Lanka as a unified nation
while satisfying the demands of the Tamil minority for greater
authority to rule themselves in the north and east, which the
Tamils regard as their traditional homelands.
</P>
<P>
   That effort has collapsed for now, though Kumaratunga has vowed
to revive it after national elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a feeling of menace hovers over the capital, even
though there has been a lull in the fierce battles between the
rebel group, known as the Tamil Tigers, and the government in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors are rife that the Tigers are gearing up for a surprise
attack in the north or east _ and more terrorist bombings in
Colombo. Armed sentries dot the cityscape, on the lookout for
suicide bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Parliament from Kumaratunga's party were whisked to
Parliament in helicopters to avoid feared attacks while the
proposed constitution was debated. Streets around it were closed to
cars. The only approach was on foot.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Buddhist monks in saffron robes who cast themselves
as guardians of the nation, hiked to the gates of Parliament to
denounce the proposal as a first step toward a division of the
country between the majority Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists,
and the Tamils, who are mostly Hindus.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaratunga, head of the Sri Lanka Freedom Party, spent months
negotiating with the opposition United National Party and had come
closer than ever before to reaching a consensus with its leaders _
which would have meant a united front of all the major Sinhalese
politicians in favor of greater autonomy for the Tamils.
</P>
<P>
   But just before the constitution was introduced, the UNP
announced that it would oppose the proposal, largely because it
included transitional provisions to allow Kumaratunga, who was
re-elected president in December, to continue in power until 2005,
despite the new constitution's abolition of the executive
presidency in favor a parliamentary system headed by a prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry for this lady,'' said V. Anandasangaree, senior
vice president of the Tamil United Liberation Front, a moderate
political party. ``She had moved heaven and earth to find a
solution to the problem, but the UNP took her for a ride and then
dropped her like a hot potato.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just among the Sinhalese opposition that
Kumaratunga has run into political trouble. Her proposal, written
with the hope of winning over the Tamils, has stirred more
ambivalence than enthusiasm among Tamil politicians who have risked
their lives and the wrath of the Tigers by favoring a political
settlement of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Tamil United Liberation Front decided they could
not support the constitution because they felt that Kumaratunga had
diluted the autonomy provisions too much in her negotiations with
the UNP.
</P>
<P>
   Their decision was particularly poignant because a member of
Parliament from their party, the constitutional scholar Neelan
Tiruchelvam, was the chief Tamil architect of earlier drafts _ and
was assassinated by a suicide bomber a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kumaratunga considers her proposal the country's best
chance for peace. She says it would eventually convince Tamils that
the Sinhalese were willing to share power with them, sapping
support for the Tigers, whose group's full name is the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weapons that the LTTE fear the most are not the weapons of
war,'' she said in an interview on Friday at Temple Trees, the
presidential residence. ``The weapon they fear most is peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But many Sri Lankans have ceased to believe that the Tigers will
ever compromise on their demand for the independent homeland they
call Eelam, an intransigence that condemns the country to endless
warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing is to fight until the Tigers surrender,'' said
Pradeep Edirisooya, 31, a Sinhalese travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   While praising the president's new constitution for giving
Tamils a better deal, Thirumahal, a Tamil law student who has only
one name, said she, too, felt it would not end the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tamils aren't fighting the Sinhalese,'' she said. ``The
government is fighting the LTTE. You cannot stop the war. It used
to be about ethnicity. Now it's a power struggle.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Sinhalese hardliners who oppose Kumaratunga's plan
organized raucous protests, there were few if any spontaneous and
emotional demonstrations in favor of it. The constituency for peace
was very quiet.
</P>
<P>
   And her government's frantic efforts to put together a
two-thirds majority in Parliament failed. Less than a week after
she introduced the plan, she withdrew it rather than face certain
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, Kumaratunga has not given up. She has a
new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The six-year term of this Parliament ends on Aug. 24, and
national elections must be held by early November. If she is unable
to resurrect the constitutional package in the coming week, she
said her party's candidates would ask the public for a mandate to
pass it with a simple parliamentary majority, rather than the
required two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may go slightly against a clause of the present
constitution,'' she said, ``but it is democratic and legal.''.
</P>
<P>
   If the constitution is adopted in the way she describes, it will
inevitably face legal challenges _ and would still have to be
adopted in a national referendum. Even if it surmounted those
hurdles, many here question whether it would bring the country
closer to peace.
</P>
<P>
   And the Tigers, as well as the hardliners among the Sinhalese,
are likely to do all they can to make sure she does not succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Though the proposed constitution gives the central government
sweeping powers to crush any secessionist movement and enshrines
Buddhism in ``the foremost place,'' the monks who protested at the
gates of Parliament last week denounced it is a betrayal of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   A raucous cheer of victory rose from a throng of holy men when a
priest announced that the government had withdrawn its peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants to give a certain part of this country to Tiger
terrorists and stay in power all her life,'' said M. Ananda, a monk
who shielded his shaved head from the blazing sun under a
multicolored umbrella. ``That's her ulterior motive. She has not
revealed the secret to the people of this country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
