<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1562 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-GORE-SPEECH-PINK     08-14 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-GORE-SPEECH-PINK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN YOUR OWN WORDS _ PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, Aug. 15, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By DANIEL H. PINK    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The terrifying report hopped from skybox to skybox
like the West Nile virus: Al Gore was writing his own acceptance
speech. Eek! cried the talking heads and the pundits. The speech
will be dull, boring. It will be _ gasp _ specific.
</P>
<P>
   It was probably the first time anyone has been scared by the
absence of a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a method to Al Gore's supposed madness _ a
recognition that politics and the broader culture are in the midst
of a significant transition.
</P>
<P>
   While the Republican Convention two weeks ago captured barely 7
percent of the viewing audience, CBS' ``Survivor'' scored ratings
higher than all the convention coverage on all the broadcast and
cable networks combined. Why? ``Survivor'' has real people, real
suspense and no scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Or take Yahoo. That same week, it attracted 25 million visitors
(not counting the same people coming back more than once), nearly
10 million more people than watched the elephant hats in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   By writing his own speech, speaking in his own authentic voice,
and offering specifics for people to evaluate on their terms, Gore
may be much more in sync with the voters than his opponent or the
press corps dare to be.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Convention reminded me of my worst days as a
political speechwriter. I'd labor over a carefully argued,
beautifully reasoned, elegantly written text. Then some grizzled
senior aide would toss the draft back to me and say: ``Uh, it's
fine, but you need to add a little more rhetoric'' _ as if back in
my office, I had a spice rack with little bottles of phrases, a few
sprinkles of which could disguise the taste of what I'd written.
</P>
<P>
   The punditocracy hailed George W. Bush's acceptance speech, but
when The Washington Post convened a panel of swing voters, the
reaction was overwhelming: Lovely speech, but where were the
specifics?
</P>
<P>
   When Newsweek asked voters how important it is that Gore offer
specifics in his convention speech, a stunning 75 percent said
``very important.'' Contrast that with 24 percent who said it was
very important for him to talk about his own life experiences and
the 18 percent who thought it crucial that he discuss his faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that an Al Gore policy-laden speech might be hard
going,'' said Fox News' Brit Hume when he heard that the vice
pesident was hunched over his laptop. But that's probably because
he's not one of the 41 million Americans who can't afford health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   If I were still advising the vice president, I'd recommend the
new media full monty. Write the speech in your own voice _ make it
conversation, not oratory. Deliver it your own way, and follow it
with a live, nationally televised call-in question and answer
program. Put all your policy proposals on the campaign Web site,
and let voters plug in their own preferences to see if they agree.
The era of Big Speechwriter is over.
</P>
<P>
   (Daniel H. Pink, Al Gore's speechwriter from 1995 to 1997, is
author of the forthcoming ``Free Agent Nation.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
