<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      08-14 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE PROGRESS AS VERIZON STRIKE DRAGS INTO SECOND WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the ninth day of the 12-state strike against
Verizon Communications, negotiators made little progress Monday as
unions and company executives debated the effect on workers of the
Bell Atlantic merger with GTE, which created Verizon and made it
the nation's largest telecommunications employer.
</P>
<P>
   And with no easy solutions in sight, both sides were gauging how
long a strike each was willing and able to endure. Verizon has
begun to consider bringing in managers from other parts of the
country to provide relief for the 30,000 managers within the region
who are trying to fill in for the 86,000 employees on strike.
</P>
<P>
   Some strikers on picket lines, meanwhile, were voicing worry
about more days without a paycheck than many had expected when they
walked off their jobs on Aug. 6. The Communications Workers of
America and International Brotherhood of America have set their
sights on other issues, after having secured a concession late last
week allowing them to organize more easily in Verizon's wireless
division.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle now to settling the strike involves
Verizon's ability to shift work from one region to another in an
effort to increase the efficiency of operations or reduce labor
costs.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Bell Atlantic, the local telephone company merged with
GTE, a telecommunications company that operates telephone companies
in more than a dozen other states around the country. Verizon also
includes a venture with Vodafone Airtouch of Britain that has
become the largest wireless carrier in the United States.
Altogether, Verizon has 260,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that their jobs might be threatened by movement of
some work to other states, striking employees are seeking greater
job stability. The strikers are in 12 states from Maine to
Virginia, and the District of Columbia _ where union membership is
generally more widespread and wages higher than in other parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Given the consolidation in the telecommunications industry in
recent years, it is little surprise that Verizon and its unions
would lock horns over cost-cutting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we consider essential to the functioning of
our company on a competitive level,'' said Eric Rabe, Verizon's
spokesman. ``This is about the workings of capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as they worry about losing some work, the unions are
also protesting they sometimes have too much of it. They are
seeking to limit mandatory overtime, which can tack on 15 hours to
20 hours of extra work each week for some employees. Source of
stress in the workplace, such practices as the monitoring of
operators' calls with customers, is also an important issue for the
unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it comes down to,'' said Jeff Miller, a spokesman
for the Communications Workers union. ``We're waiting to see action
on these major issues which management seems to consider normal, or
even minor.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, strikers and the company have settled down for
a walkout longer than either side seemed to have expected.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having managers fill in for striking employees,
Verizon said it had brought in nearly 300 retired employees to work
as technicians and customer service representatives. If the strike
goes on much longer, the company said it was also considering
bringing in managers from regions that had been served by GTE to
perform some work. Most of the managers filling in for the strikers
have not had a day off since the strike began, and have been
required to work 12-hour shifts. Verizon executives have said the
managers would have to work 13 days consecutively before getting a
break.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon is also considering hiring people from outside the
company, although it is not clear when and how this would occur,
said Rabe, Verizon's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, union officials have said they are prepared to dip
into their $400 million strike fund to provide strikers with $200 a
week if the strike enters a fifteenth day.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stagliano, a striking technician who was part of a group of
rain-soaked pickets at Verizon's building at 140 W. St. in New York
Monday, said he was willing to endure the subsidy of instead of his
regular weekly income of $1,110.
</P>
<P>
   ``I equate this to the Pharaoh and the slaves. These people will
treat you like a slave, if you give in to them,'' Stagliano said.
``If you say no, they will respect you and think twice before
pulling this thing again.''
</P>
<P>
   But some other striking employees were not so sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Marino, who worked in installation and repairs for six
years at Bell Atlantic before it became Verizon, said he never
imagined that he would be out on strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think that it would come to this, definitely; I
thought this would last only two or three days,'' said Marino, who
married last month. ``I have to keep going back to my wife and tell
her I don't know what's going to happen. Then she gets worried and
asks what am I going to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
