<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1573 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-SERGIO-0815-COX     08-14 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SERGIO-0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Only a year ago, Garcia seemed a threat to Tiger Woods
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Only a year ago, he seemed certain to be the
main threat to Tiger Woods. Coming up one stroke short to Woods in
the 1999 PGA Championship at Medinah, Sergio Garcia won a million
hearts, if not the Wanamaker Trophy, with an eyes-wide-shut miracle
shot from a tree root at the 16th hole and a childlike sprint up
the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   With another PGA starting Thursday at Valhalla Golf Club, a few
things have become obvious since 1999:
</P>
<P>
   a. Not only did Garcia fail to emerge as Woods' most serious
challenger, nobody else did, either.
</P>
<P>
   b. While Garcia has two wins on the European Tour, he has none
on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   c. Overall, the El Nino wave peaked at Medinah and is presently
just a few ripples on the water.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Garcia has become known more for his explosions than
generating the same type of excitement that built so marvelously at
the 1999 PGA.
</P>
<P>
   At a European Tour event last year, he threw a shoe down the
fairway after an poor drive, then kicked it.
</P>
<P>
   He has tossed away caddies similarly and already is on his third
as a pro.
</P>
<P>
   At last month's British Open, where he finished 10 shots behind
Woods, Garcia made headlines mostly for the final-round, overhead
hack he took on the ninth fairway at St. Andrews. After his drive
landed in what he called a ``3-inch deep super divot,'' Garcia
unsuccessfully tried to strike down on the ball with an 8-iron and
exit the lie. Upset when the club's face closed and the ball
squirted left (though he still made par), Garcia slammed his club
into the ground, causing heads to shake in the gallery, getting a
scolding from the Royal &AMP; Ancient Golf Club and a fine from the
European Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, to discourage Garcia from showing his emotions, even on
those out-of-control occasions, would be to stifle his game, said
countryman Miguel Angel Jimenez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a big temper, but that's good,'' Jimenez said. ``It
pushes you to play good golf. He's a great player. He hits the ball
wonderful. There is a lot of potential in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Woods in the beginning, Garcia has made some judgment
errors, such as last spring during Atlanta's BellSouth Classic,
practicing for the Masters 20 minutes down the road at the Golf
Club of Georgia and refusing a sponsor's exemption.
</P>
<P>
   A young man who in small interview sessions does not always ooze
the charm he saves for network TV cameras, Garcia demanded that
writers merely call him ``Sergio,'' dropping the surname even on
first mention. Later, Garcia decided he no longer wanted to be
called ``El Nino,'' even though the name remained on his cap, his
golf bag and was used in commercials.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Garcia has fumed about losing a spot in the
upcoming $5 million NEC Invitational because of an internal
decision by the same European Tour that has so warmly embraced him.
He has emphasized the PGA Tour this year, earning $486,813 (72nd)
for 11 events. With a limited European Tour schedule, he's 32nd on
the Order of Merit.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for something to ignite his game, Garcia found some
success from a switch to cross-handed putting toward the end of the
U.S. Open. Yet, that's not a great indicator, either, to be
switching putting styles within a major championship. It's
anybody's guess how a made-for-TV match against Woods will go Aug.
28, in the sequel to last year's so-so prime-time contest that
Woods won against David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics wonder whether Garcia at this stage has the
patience to contend consistently. Some think his mental game, while
possessing the same brashness and confidence that used to drive
mentor Seve Ballesteros, is as loose as his backswing. At least
Sergio is saying he has to be patient. His comments nearly mirror
those made by Woods in late 1996 and early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have to take my time,'' said the Spaniard. ``If I
won now, it will be great, but (people forget) I'm 20 years old.
I'm hopefully going to play a lot of majors and hopefully I'll be
lucky to win some of them.''
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Garcia, while fully aware that Woods is the man
he must conquer to excite Europe, realizes that several other
players worldwide, not just Woods, are knocking him down
leaderboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you focus in on one player and you're trying to do
some of the stuff he does and be as consistent as him, it can be
bad, because you forget about yourself. You've got to try to be
your own person and realize that sometimes you're going to have bad
tournaments. You just try to be yourself and just try to play your
own game,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
