<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIDE THE TOOTHPASTE: THE NRA IS BARING ITS TEETH AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   I never went to summer camp as a
kid, partly because I couldn't find a place that offered a suitable
mix of bugle-free mornings, marathon wiffleball games, and all the
ice cream I could eat. Looking back, I doubt ``the Whittington
Adventure'' would have made my short list.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a camp run by the National Rifle Association on a ranch in
New Mexico. For $725 each, according to a story last week in USA
Today, kids between the ages of 13 and 17 spend two weeks learning
to shoot guns, track deer, slap together a meal of forest food,
pitch a tent, and revel in other outdoorsy activities.
</P>
<P>
   They also engage in their share of pranks, apparently. USA Today
recounts a stern lecture campers got for smearing toothpaste on the
handles of cabin doors. The smell attracted a bear, which a camp
counselor had to shoo with a slingshot.
</P>
<P>
   The camp's Web site, at www.nrawc.org, fondly recalls the days
of Kit Carson, when ``puffs of black powder smoke drifted into the
clear mountain skies as buckskin-clad hunters brought down mule
deer and elk, antelope and bear.'' The camp acknowledges, however,
that we live in a different era, when kids with guns are too often
cause to scream and run for 911.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my teacher asked where I was going for the summer, I'd just
say adventure camp, not NRA shooting camp,'' camp-goer Tucker
Phelps, 17, told USA Today. ``I don't want my teachers to be scared
of me.''
</P>
<P>
   The camp includes sensitivity training, with pointers on how to
deal with people who are offended by hunting or guns. Kids are
advised, for instance, not to walk into a restaurant with a gun or
hunting knife on their belts and blood on their clothes.
</P>
<P>
   As you might expect, campers also learn to view the world
through the NRA's scope. Guns are guns, never ``weapons.''
Restricting guns makes as much sense as restricting wiffleball
bats. And, of course, guns don't kill people, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Whittington Adventure sounds like fun. Long walks in
the woods (in blaze orange) would be relaxing, and I could use help
pitching a tent that won't collapse in a brisk breeze. All in all,
though, the camp isn't my sort of place.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I can see why some kids and parents think it's a
valuable experience. In some ways, I'm a knee-jerk liberal on gun
issues. But I understand the desire to keep a firearm in one's
house for protection. Hunting doesn't repulse me; I come from a
long line of folks who hunted. And, although I wince at the
possibility of an NRA camp drawing troubled teens who are too
gung-ho about guns, I've known kids who went through similar
training and didn't grow up to be trigger-happy or murderous. The
experience may have done them some good.
</P>
<P>
   But I'll probably be thinking of Whittington sensitivity
training when I view the ads that the NRA will run this week during
the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The gun group is planning to spend about $1 million on TV
commercials. Charlton Heston, as usual, is the star. ``From
anti-gun mayors and marchers to gun-hating celebrities and
politicians, they're almost all Democrats,'' he booms. ``Tell me:
Why are so few Democrats willing to defend constitutional
freedoms?''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like somebody smeared toothpaste on the cabin door again.
</P>
<P>
   I know some Democrats unjustly demonize all gun owners as bears
on a rampage. I can't understand, however, the froth and foam that
Heston routinely works up for every gun-control measure.
</P>
<P>
   I've yet to see a gun law enacted in this country that's a real
threat to freedom. The Brady law? A minor inconvenience to
law-abiding gun owners. Trigger locks? Ditto. One-gun-a-month
limits on gun purchases? Hardly a hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, criminals will always find a way to get a gun. But I'm
baffled by why we shouldn't put as many obstacles in front of them
as possible to make their ``work'' harder. Because gun hobbyists
want to get weapons, no questions asked? Please. Because an armed
citizenry is a protection against an authoritarian government?
Doubtful. Taken a look at the Pentagon arsenal lately?
</P>
<P>
   The NRA says it promotes gun safety. At the Whittington
Adventure, it apparently does. Much of the rest of the time,
though, the group's leaders unintelligently bear their teeth and
growl.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make me want to stand guard over my toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
