<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-SANCHEZ15-COX     08-14 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SANCHEZ15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SANCHEZ CANCELS DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION SPEECH
 &HT;    By ANDREW ALEXANDER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rep. Loretta Sanchez, forced by top Democratic
officials last week to move a Hispanic fund-raiser from the
politically incorrect Playboy Mansion, surprised party leaders
Monday by withdrawing as a convention speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Her cancellation was an unwelcome distraction for party
officials trying to project harmony as they opened their convention
to nominate Vice President Al Gore for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have time to write a speech, and I don't have time to
give a speech,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old California congresswoman is co-chair of the
Democratic National Committee and was head of Gore's congressional
political action committee two years ago. She emerged as one of the
national's most prominent Latino officials in 1996 when she
unseated conservative Republican Robert Dornan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone here respects the decision she made,'' said
Rick Hess, deputy press secretary for the Democratic National
Convention. ``She's a strong leader in our party and someone we
respect. This is a small event in a very large convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez was to be one of the convention speakers at Monday's
opening session.
</P>
<P>
   Her decision early Monday rekindled a fiery controversy that
party leaders thought had been doused. It erupted late last week
when Sanchez refused to move the event after party leaders said the
Playboy Mansion venue could embarrass Gore, who is trying to show
he cares about family values.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez caved in and shifted the event to B.B. King's Blues Club
at Universal Studios's CityWalk, a touristy strip of shops and
restaurants, after Democratic National Committee Chairman Joe
Andrew stripped her of her speaking role and threatened to remove
her as party co-chair.
</P>
<P>
   The flap subsided, and her speaking slot was restored. But
Sanchez then found herself the target of critics who accused her of
yielding to moralists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some suggested that I changed the event (location) to get my
speaking slot back. That's not true,'' Sanchez said Monday in an
interview with CNN from the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   By not speaking, she said, she would have more time to
concentrate on fund-raising for Hispanic Unity USA, a political
action committee she heads. The Playboy Mansion fund-raiser was for
that group.
</P>
<P>
   Some Hispanic leaders have said Sanchez is primarily to blame
for not switching the fund-raiser location after Gore campaign and
party leaders first voiced concern.
</P>
<P>
   On the convention floor Monday night, Texas state Sen. Gonzalo
Barrientos of Austin, a co-chair of his state's delegation, said
Sanchez brought the problems on herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know all the details, but I know there were
discussions with her in advance,'' said Barrientos. ``Some people
don't think she was treated fairly, but some of that she should
have known was going to be coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent Wilkes, executive director of the League of United Latin
American Citizens, said the controversy is ``a story everyone is
aware of'' among the group's 115,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The League, the nation's oldest and largest Hispanic
organization, has not taken an official position on the issue
because ``it's more an internal thing ... within the (Democratic)
party.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I think it's a little confusing to us why she
would have pressed the issue if the Gore campaign thought it was a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Hispanic delegates said they were both disappointed and
relieved that Sanchez would not appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unfortunate because I thought she had some
positive things to say on the major issues that we're trying to
focus on, but it would have taken away from what we're trying to
accomplish here,'' said Bob Henriquez, a delegate from Tampa, Fla.
``If she had spoken, you would have had all the talking heads
talking about it before and after her speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Anastasia Garcia, a delegate from Miami, said she felt it was
``unfortunate that where a fund-raiser was being held caused a
problem. I do believe it was a mistake to have planned it for there
because we don't want to give the Republicans a chance to attack
our party as immoral when, of course, we're not immoral.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing is she has done a lot for Hispanic women, for
Hispanic Democratic women, and none of that is being highlighted,''
Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Herman of the Austin American-Statesman and Larry Lipman of
The Palm Beach Post contributed to this report, as did the
Associated Press).
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Alexander can be e-mailed at: andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
