<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG GREEN CONSPIRACY
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if yard work weren't unpleasant enough, it now appears that
our plants may be talking about us behind our backs.
</P>
<P>
   According to researchers at Kyoto University in Japan, plants
have the ability to ``talk'' to one another via chemical signals.
Lima bean plants, for example, deter impending attacks by spider
mites by emitting a chemical that wards off the mites while at the
same time attracting the mites' natural predators.
</P>
<P>
   While this may or may not account for my lifelong dislike of
lima beans, it certainly makes me wonder what plants talk about
during those peaceful interludes between insect attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The weather would seem a logical topic, given the fact that
plants are exposed to it day and night and are pretty much at the
mercy of the elements. This implies that plant conversations are
just as boring as most human conversations, consisting of comments
like ``Hot enough for you?'' and ``Boy, we could sure use some
rain.''
</P>
<P>
   However, my experience with plants suggests that maudlin
conversations of this sort are few and far between. Plants are
prickly by nature and generally underwhelmed by any humans who
venture into their vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that you can improve the health of a plant by talking
to it is not only foolish but potentially dangerous. The plant just
wants you to get close so it can spray you with insect-attracting
chemicals or jab a thorn in your eye. Before you know it, the whole
room smells like burned lima beans and spider mites are crawling
down your pants.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that most plant conversations are carping and
hypercritical, an understandable attitude given the fact that they
spend their entire lives rooted in dirt. Plants also have an
agenda, which is nothing short of world domination. Humans often
interfere with this goal, whether by rain forest destruction or
simply careless mowing, which is why we're seen as the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I learned early is that plants can sense weakness,
which is why I always carry a bottle of Roundup with me whenever I
venture into the yard, even if it is only to pick up the paper.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of each year, I also conduct a State of the
Yard address in which I evaluate the previous year's performance
(thriving weeds, listless effort on the part of winter rye, some
invisible rapacious thing chewing holes in citrus leaves) and spell
out what I expect in the coming year (verdancy on par with Selby
Gardens, redoubled efforts on the cinch bug front, hold summit with
leaders of mole-cricket coalition).
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the remark, the plants will either wave their
tendrils in an approving fashion or visibly wither, a sign that
they do not share my vision of a proud, strong, hard-working garden
that is accepting of all plants regardless of species,
drought-tolerance or abundance of chlorophyll.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreements are bound to occur, but I think as long as I keep
the lines of communication open, my lawn and garden will learn to
flourish, preferably with little or no involvement on my part.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, I'll continue keeping the jug of Roundup
close at hand, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-MCNEELY-0815-COX     08-14 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MCNEELY-0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS LAWMAKER WORKS TO REBUILD STATE DEMOCRATIC DOMINANCE
 &HT;    ATTN TEXAS PAPERS
 &HT;    By DAVE MCNEELY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ That balding guy with glasses you may see near the
Texas microphone at the Democratic National Convention here is
probably unknown to most people outside the Dallas area.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to co-chairing the Texas delegation, and
throwing a party for Texas delegates here Monday night featuring
the Austin western swing band ``Asleep at the Wheel,'' Martin Frost
plays a significant role in trying to keep Texas Democratic
officeholders from going the way of the dodo bird.
</P>
<P>
   That includes himself. Frost, 58, elected in 1978, is the
longest-tenured Democrat in the Texas delegation in the U.S. House
of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Frost has managed to survive several attempts to redistrict him.
With a Democrat in the White House and no Texas Democrats to
exercise authority in the U.S. Senate, Frost also oversees the
process of picking nominees for federal judgeships in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And as chair of the Democratic Caucus, he's the third-ranking
figure in the Democratic power structure, behind minority leader
Dick Gephardt and whip David Bonior.
</P>
<P>
   But Frost's influence has made the most difference for Texas
Democrats in trimming the length of George W. Bush's coattails.
He's done it by using his position as chairman of the Democratic
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Campaign Committee for the past four years to
steer a bundle of money into Texas _ including $3 million in the
2000 election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Battleground Program targeted races where Texas
Democrats in Congress and the state legislature were threatened, as
well as open House seats. Part of the reason was looking forward to
2001, when the state legislature will re-draw legislative and
congressional districts _ a process the Democrats have controlled
for more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to hold on to the state House (currently with a 78-72
Democratic edge),'' Frost said in an interview here. ``We hope to
pick up control of the state senate (now 16-15 Republican).
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do one of those two things _ if we were to lose
both houses of the legislature _ then we would have dire problems
with congressional redistricting. We would have a hard time
recruiting candidates for statewide office for 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost said he jumped in partly because he saw statewide
Democratic officeholders rapidly being voted out of existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Necessity is the mother of invention,'' Frost said. ``We had
to do it. There were no options for us. If we hadn't funded the
Battleground Program in `98, there's a serious question whether
(Democrat Pete) Laney would be speaker (of the Texas House of
Representatives) today, or whether Democrats would still be in a
majority in the U.S. House delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did was pretty extraordinary, because we re-elected
all 17 Democratic congressmen in 1998, and picked up a state senate
seat, and held on to the state house, while Bush was getting more
than 68 percent statewide.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost says Texas could provide some of the six additional seats
needed for the Democrats to take over control of the U.S. House.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are in good shape to hold onto their current 17
seats, and are making strong challenges to pick up the 5th and 14th
district seats.
</P>
<P>
   In the 5th, which stretches from Dallas to Bryan, Democrat
Regina Montoya Coggins of Dallas is mounting a stiff and
well-funded challenge to Republican Pete Sessions of Dallas. In the
14th, which stretches from Austin to the Gulf Coast, Democrat Loy
Sneary of Bay City is trying again to unseat Republican Ron Paul of
Lake Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible Bush could carry the state for president, and we
could gain two congressional seats,'' Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, and the Democrats hold the Texas House and win
a Senate majority, Frost's fellow Democrats will be happy to give
him a lot of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
