A1585 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MP3com0819-COX     08-14 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 com0819-COX &HT;    MP3.com reaches pact to move into retail stores
 &HT;    By Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Online music company MP3.com Inc. is planning to
take the business of selling music back where it came from _
brick-and-mortar retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com on Monday announced it had struck a deal with a budding
company that is planning a string of stores and entertainment
complexes where music fans could use computer kiosks equipped to
digitally download different songs from different artists using
MP3's site. They could then ``burn'' custom-made compact discs for
$1 a title.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 partner Outernet Inc. isn't set to open its first location
until September, in Apple Valley, Minn., but it has grand plans. By
the end of the year, it wants to open stores in Dallas, Chicago and
New York, and by July it wants to be in Atlanta and about 15 other
big cities, according Paul Uhlemann, vice president of Edina,
Minn.-based Outernet.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be able to come in and browse and burn,'' Uhlemann
said, adding that Outernet shoppers also will be able to download
and create custom CDs of games, software and other content.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of creating customized music CDs is nothing new. Major
record labels as well as retailers worldwide are testing similar
ideas that would let customers create a CD with, say, a Frank
Sinatra tune on one track and a Rage Against the Machine song on
another.
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of San Diego-based MP3.com, however, represents
the next step in the ongoing evolution of online music.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com and other online music companies have been positioning
themselves to look less like underground music pirates and more
like traditional businesses _ and find ways to make a profit along
the way. In recent months, MP3.com has forked over tens of millions
to settle copyright suits by several major record labels, and is
still negotiating settlement of others.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the shift is the highly-publicized Napster Inc.
copyright infringement case. The recording industry won an
injunction last month against Napster after a federal judge in San
Francisco found that Napster's service violated record companies'
copyrights. That injunction was stayed.
</P>
<P>
   Although music fans will still be able to download and store
music from MP3.com using their home computers, the Outernet kiosks
could let them do it more quickly and easily _ especially if they
lack high-speed Internet access. It would also give MP3.com a
potential new revenue stream and also some exposure outside the
world of home computing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this relationship with the Outernet perfectly
illustrates our resolution to give consumers access to the great
music they want, while creating revenue possibilities for digital
artists,'' MP3.com Executive Vice President Steve Sheiner said in a
news release.
</P>
<P>
   But since MP3.com and other online music businesses typically
work with relatively unknown artists who play for cheap, the
big-name record labels and the retailers they work with may have
the advantage as downloadable music moves into retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the choice of artists that you get,'' with
MP3.com, said Malcolm Maclachlan, media and e-commerce analyst with
researcher International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cool idea, and it shows that MP3.com is being forward
in their thinking, but it's not a world-changer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: bkeefe(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
