<SLUG> BC-DEM-DIARY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER BACK IN CONVENTION SPOTLIGHT; FUND-RAISER STAYS AWAY FROM
LIMELIGHT; A RIVALRY IN NEW YORK; CLINTONS AT STREISAND
FUND-RAISER
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD WEINRAUB and ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Four years ago, Jimmy Carter conspicuously avoided
the Democratic National Convention in Chicago. His relationship
with the incumbent presidential candidate, Bill Clinton, was testy.
Put bluntly, the two former Southern governors were both
competitive and uneasy with each other. ``I've always had good
relations with Vice President Gore,'' said Carter, picking his
words carefully, as he spoke over a cellular phone Monday afternoon
from a limousine as he rode to a reception.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter is back.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of the Democratic convention, Carter was
plainly delighted at the half-dozen press interviews and
spontaneous bursts of applause from delegates in the sweltering
streets of Los Angeles. Monday night, Carter was scheduled to be
honored with a five-minute film at the convention, before President
Clinton was to deliver his farewell address as chief executive to
the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was not planning to attend the convention in Los Angeles.
Four years ago, he had spent convention week at the Montana ranch
of Jane Fonda and Ted Turner. ``At first Al Gore invited me and I
told him I'd prefer not to come and make a big speech,'' said
Carter. ``But then the idea came for a video presentation. It's
been a very, very pleasant experience.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not been such a pleasant experience with Clinton, who
has, nonetheless tried to make amends with Carter in the past year.
Last August Clinton flew to Atlanta to present the Medal of Freedom
to Carter, an obvious effort by the White House to smooth ties with
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The strains between Carter and Clinton were the result of the
former president's intervention in some high-profile humanitarian
and foreign issues, such as Haiti, which collided with the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were strong supporters of President Clinton,'' Carter
insisted. But what about tensions with Clinton? ``We haven't had a
close relationship with him,'' said Carter. He spoke warmly about
Gore. ``Whenever there was a problem I called Al Gore,'' he said.
``I always called him. I've known him for 25 years. He's been my
key friend and trusted ally.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's enthusiasm for Carter is not altogether altruistic.
Although George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, is
favored at the moment in numerous southern states, Georgia could
prove a battleground, especially now with its new Democratic
senator, Zell Miller. And Carter could be enlisted to campaign in
the state for the Gore-Lieberman ticket. ``I'll do as requested,''
said Carter, obviously pleased at all the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-Raiser Stays Away From Limelight &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one in Hollywood has ever matched Lew R. Wasserman for his
prowess raising tens of millions for the Democratic Party since the
days of John F. Kennedy. Now 87, and a bit frail, Wasserman hosted
one more fund-raiser Monday at his art-filled Beverly Hills home.
Quietly, his associates said, Wasserman is seeking to pass off some
of his political responsibilities onto his grandson, Casey
Wasserman. By the time the next Democratic convention rolls around,
the younger Wasserman may have assumed some, or all, of his
grandfather's fund raising for charities and politicians. In
contrast to younger Hollywood moguls, who crave media attention,
Wasserman, the one-time chairman of MCA, Inc., does not give
interviews and said that he holds no interest in writing a book
about his years in Hollywood because he has always viewed his roles
_ as a talent agent and then executive _ as one of discretion and
privacy. He once told a visitor that his one regret was not having
accepted a top Cabinet job with President Johnson because his wife,
Edie, did not want to leave Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon's guarded event, given by the Wassermans, was
for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee. Wasserman and his
wife attend parties infrequently now _ although President Clinton
is known to speak frequently to him over the phone. Although
Wasserman is still actively engaged in Democratic politics,
associates acknowledged that the fund-raiser Monday _ and the
current Democratic Convention in his hometown _could mark a final
chapter for Hollywood's most powerful political fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A Rivalry In New York Delegation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York delegation is hardly a vision of party unity,
displaying the not-so-simmering rivalry between two likely
gubernatorial candidates in 2002, State Comptroller Carl McCall and
Andrew Cuomo, the U.S. housing secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates close to McCall _ which seems to be the majority of
them _ say that Cuomo, who is helping to run Al Gore's presidential
campaign in New York, is using the Gore-New York party apparatus to
help with his own contacts and political future.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo responded: ``How could I possibly be using the Gore
apparatus if I'm not saying anything about the gubernatorial race _
and he is?'' Cuomo was referring to McCall and his energetic,
public efforts here to line up support for his own race for
governor. McCall responded: `If somebody wants to compete with me,
I wish them luck.'' McCall added that he had very briefly said
hello to Cuomo at events here, but no more. `I don't know what kind
of a discussion we would have at this point,'' he said. `I mean,
what would we talk about?'''
</P>
<P>
   Clintons At Streisand Fund-Raiser
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton arrived early and left late (and his wife and
daughter arrived late and left early) at a Sunday brunch at Barbra
Streisand's Malibu compound that is said to have raised $10 million
for the president's library _ the most impressive haul of the
Clintons' prodigious fund raising in Los Angeles this past weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The brunch was off limits to the press, although a small group
of White House reporters stationed near the event tried to listen
through an immaculately trimmed hedge. A mole at the brunch
provided the following details:
</P>
<P>
   The 60 guests included such longtime Clinton fund-raisers as
Bernard Schwartz, the chairman of the Loral Space and
Communications Corp., the company whose export of satellite
technology to China attracted the scrutiny of Justice Department
investigators; Robert Johnson, the chairman of Black Entertainment
Television Holdings; Alan Patricof, the chairman of Patricof &AMP; Co.
Ventures, a venture capital firm, and Smith Bagley, the grandson of
the tobacco magnate R.J. Reynolds. Bagley's wife, Elizabeth, was
the Clinton administration's ambassador to Portugal until last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Streisand and her husband, James Brolin, there were
no other Hollywood celebrities in evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Guests started arriving at noon for cocktails near Streisand's
garden of roses overlooking the Pacific. The president arrived
around 12:30 p.m., met privately with Streisand and Brolin, then
schmoozed with guests. The first lady and Chelsea Clinton arrived
some time later, got a lengthy tour from Streisand of her rooms
filled with quilts and American folk art, then sat down to an
outdoor buffet. Both the president and first lady made remarks.
Terry McAuliffe, the Clinton's chief fund-raiser, started off the
speeches, calling Streisand ``the greatest artist of all time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
