<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-PLANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS AT ILLINOIS PLANT SAY THEY ARE NOT TO BLAME FOR TIRE
DEFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Also see TIRE-RECALL) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DECATUR, Ill. _ A day after Ford Motor Co. singled out a factory
here that makes Firestone tires as the main source of a problem
that led to the recall of more than 6.5 million tires last week,
workers and union officials said they were not to blame for the
faulty tires.
</P>
<P>
   The workers said Ford might be trying to deflect attention from
possible design flaws in its sport utility vehicles that used the
tires and that the announcement last week by Bridgestone/Firestone
that singled out the Decatur plant could be a pressure tactic in
the company's continuing labor negotiations with the union.
</P>
<P>
   The workers, however, did say they were puzzled by statistical
evidence released by Ford and Firestone that showed that the
Decatur plant, more than any other one, produced a sharply
disproportionate number of defective tires. Indeed, on Sunday, Ford
said it recently discovered evidence that the rate of injury and
damage claims for tires made in Decatur between 1994 and 1996, when
the plant here was largely manned by replacement workers, was often
three to six times that of other factories.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these figures, many factory workers here say they are
skeptical of the evidence because it is inconsistent with the
awards the plant has won and management satisfaction with the jobs
many of them have done for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   They point to the all the ``Quality One'' awards they have
received over the years from Ford. And they say that when Firestone
wanted to create a new line of tires, they often came to a huge red
factory building that is spread across 52 acres here in Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Werve, a 29-year employee of the factory, said many
workers here thought the cause could be design or engineering
flaws. And they are questioning why Ford was recommending the tires
be inflated with air pressure at 26 pounds per square inch when the
plant recommends and tests the tires at 30 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at Ford and they're looking back at us,'' he
said Monday. ``It's a chess match. And we're pawns in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even though the factory was staffed by replacement
workers when the union went on strike in 1994, union leaders said
Monday that they were unaware of any quality control lapses during
that period and that they did not think the quality of the tires
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know any time that the plant put out a bad tire,''
said Roger Gates, president of the union. ``I've never seen the
company jeopardize the product.''
</P>
<P>
   The Decatur workers also bitterly denounced a lawsuit filed in
Florida that contends that there were quality control problems at
the plant for more than a decade, including processes that may have
created faulty tires more prone to splitting apart.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Kaster, a lawyer in Ocala, Fla., who has filed suit
against Bridgestone/Firestone, says he has evidence that Decatur
and other Firestone plants were producing flawed and dangerous
tires and that several former Firestone employees from Decatur are
willing to testify that there were many quality control problems at
the plant here and that the demands put on workers contributed to
the production of dangerous tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always an emphasis on quantity and not quality,''
Kaster said Monday. ``A breakdown in quality control in the plant
results in a catastrophe on the highways.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the workers interviewed Monday said they had known about
such conditions, even though many said they were 20- and 30-year
employees. They questioned the motives of the former employees and
said that the plant workers had always taken pride in the tires
they produced and even bought them for their own cars and their own
families, believing they were entirely safe.
</P>
<P>
   The reason so much attention has focused on Decatur, though, is
clearly the bitter union strike that began in 1994. At the time,
there were also strikes at the city's two other major employers:
Caterpillar and A.D. Staley.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the 1,800 workers here walked out after
Bridgestone, a Japanese company that acquired Firestone in 1988,
began making stringent demands to scale back the work force, pay
and vacation time, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had good working relations, and we just wanted to keep
things the way they were,'' said John Blair, 67, who decided to
retire after the strike. ``But the Japanese wanted more. They
wanted to cut back on vacation time.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the workers were out for more than a year and angered
when the company hired replacement workers and some union members
crossed the picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Coates, 63, said that about that time his wife, a nurse at
the company, was diagnosed with cancer, and he was out of a job
watching people he considered friends cross the picket line.
Harland Smith, who has been with the company more than 30 years,
says it was ugly and painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people couldn't survive,'' he said. ``If you wanted a
job, you had to go out of town. Many went to Indianapolis, which is
150 miles away.''
</P>
<P>
   When the workers returned in 1995, the regular eight-hour days
had become 12-hour days where they worked in two and three-day
cycles. The company was demanding more, and some former workers
admit there was often too much pressure to produce, and perhaps
even problems hiring replacement workers skilled enough to produce
quality tires on the company's rigid schedule. But even they doubt
any of that resulted in years of defective tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speculate; I wasn't there,'' Werve said about the
allegations that faulty tires were made during the strike. ``But I
think quality control would have caught it. You know, all we do is
make the tire. Ford and Firestone design it and they test it.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers here also say they would never have engaged in
retaliation because of hard feelings about the strike. They say
they realize how important tires are and they know they're dealing
with human lives.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them believe a combination of factors are at work. They
speculate about possible design flaws, of pressure on Ford and
Firestone to find answers that will appease a wary public; and
about a handful of former workers who may have some other reason
for saying the quality wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   They say they enjoy their jobs, the pay (at about $18 an hour),
and feel they are being unfairly singled out. Indeed, Decatur, they
say, has been hit again. After the major strikes in the mid 1990s,
the Archer Daniels Midland Co. was rocked by a major price-fixing
scandal; Jesse Jackson came to town recently because of a racial
incident at a local high school. And now, the city they call ``the
Pride of the Prairie'' is being blamed for one of the largest tire
recalls in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' Coates said. ``We went from being the Pride of the
Prairie to Sin City almost overnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
