<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-ADMIRAL-NYT &LR;      08-14 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ADMIRAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn: Ore., Calif.)  
 VIRGINIA ADMIRAL, 85, PAINTER , WRITER AND MOTHER OF ACTOR ROBERT
De   NIRO  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Virginia Admiral, an American painter and writer who
studied with Hans Hofmann, died on July 27. She was 85 and lived in
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Admiral was born in Oregon and studied at the Art Institute of
Chicago. While working on the Federal Arts Project in Oakland,
Calif., in 1938, she became closely involved with the San Francisco
poetry scene. With the poet Robert Duncan she published a single
issue of a small-press magazine, Epitaph, which developed into The
Experimental Review. Later, in New York, she wrote for True Crimes
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, she enrolled at the Hofmann School in New York to study
painting, where she met the artist Robert De Niro, who was working
as a class monitor. They married in 1942; their son, the actor
Robert De Niro, was born in 1943 and lives in New York City.
Admiral's husband died in 1993. She is survived by a sister,
Eleanor Haefele of Sacramento, and five grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Admiral exhibited in the Springs Salon for Young
Artists at Peggy Guggenheim's Art of This Century Gallery in
Manhattan. She had a solo show there in 1946 and was included in
the Peggy Guggenheim Collection at the Venice Biennale in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Admiral was active in the antiwar movement, often
contributing work to shows based on political themes. She was also
instrumental in establishing low-cost housing for artists in SoHo.
From 1973 to 1980 she showed at Buecker and Harpsichords gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Her work is in the permanent collections of the Metropolitan
Museum of Art, the Museum of Modern Art in New York and the Peggy
Guggenheim Collection in Venice. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLEMISSPREVIEW0815-CO     08-14 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLEMISSPREVIEW0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cutcliffe asks fans for patience with Manning waiting in wings
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mississippi coach David Cutcliffe spoke to booster clubs
around the state this summer, he asked one thing of his team's
fans: Don't create a quarterback controversy.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand Cutcliffe's concern. Mississippi senior
Romaro Miller was the SEC's fourth-leading passer last season,
throwing for 1,999 yards and 14 touchdowns. He threw only seven
interceptions in 270 pass attempts and led the Rebels to their
third consecutive bowl game, a feat the program hadn't accomplished
since playing in 15 bowl games in a row from 1957-71.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller's backup is getting a lot of attention in Oxford. The
optimism has nothing to do with what he's done on the field. It has
everything to do with his last name.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Eli Manning, a redshirt freshman, faces even loftier
expectations than his older brother, Peyton Manning, endured at
Tennessee. Not only must he play in the large shadow of his
brother, now a star quarterback for the NFL's Indianapolis Colts,
but he'll also draw comparisons to his father, Archie Manning, a
two-time All-American at Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Cutcliffe knows there is pressure to put a Manning under center.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Manning name out there, I decided before I went out
on my (speaking) circuit that I was going to ask our fans to be
responsible,'' Cutcliffe said. ``On every team I've ever coached,
the backup quarterback has always been the most popular player on
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutcliffe, who begins his second full season at Mississippi, was
Tennessee's offensive coordinator during Peyton Manning's
record-setting career in Knoxville. He avoids comparing the two
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eli has done everything I've asked him to do as a redshirt,''
Cutcliffe said. ``That's a big deal because a lot of guys just sit
on their redshirt year and don't do anything. But he went to work
in the weight room and it paid off in the spring. If you haven't
seen him, he looks like a completely different person. I'm anxious
to see how he looks on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   So are Mississippi fans, who were outraged when Peyton Manning
snubbed his father's alma mater and signed with the Volunteers. Eli
Manning, 6 feet 4 and 200 pounds, was the 1998 USA Today player of
the year in Louisiana after he threw for 2,381 yards and 30
touchdowns as a senior at Isadore Newman School in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about Eli is that he's comfortable with being
Eli, and we're going to let him do that,'' Cutcliffe said. ``He's
not chasing Peyton or trying to be Peyton.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller says he's comfortable with the situation, too. Miller,
who has a 15-8 record in two years as a starter, needs only 454
yards to surpass Archie Manning as the school's fourth-leading
passer of all-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no animosity between us,'' Miller said, referring to
Eli Manning. ``We're great friends. I think when you've got a
player like Eli behind you, it only makes you better.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI
</P>
<P>
   -Location: Oxford, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   -Enrollment: 13,481.
</P>
<P>
   -Coach: David Cutcliffe, 9-4 in two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   -Stadium (capacity): Vaught-Hemingway (50,577).
</P>
<P>
   -All-time record: 552-410-35.
</P>
<P>
   -SEC championships: Six _ 1947, 1954-55, 1960, 1962-63.
</P>
<P>
   -1999 record: 8-4, 4-4 in SEC West.
</P>
<P>
   -Schedule: Sept. 2 vs. Tulane; Sept. 9 vs. Auburn; Sept. 16 at
Vanderbilt; Sept. 30 vs. Kentucky; Oct. 7 vs. Arkansas State; Oct.
14 at Alabama; Oct. 28 vs. Nevada-Las Vegas; Nov. 4 at Arkansas;
Nov. 11 vs. LSU; Nov. 18 at Georgia; Nov. 23 vs. Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
