<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTORT-BLOOMBERG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MEN FROM KAZAKHSTAN CHARGED IN E-MAIL EXTORTION OF BLOOMBERG 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On March 24, a strange e-mail message popped on the computers at
the Bloomberg corporate offices in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the message, addressed to the financial-information company's
founder and chief executive, Michael Bloomberg, a person named Alex
claimed detailed knowledge of the financial information company's
computer system. Alex said he was ``not a criminal,'' but claimed
to have obtained passwords of senior Bloomberg employees and
proposed that Bloomberg pay him for pointing out the security
breach. Alex closed the electronic missive by stating ``(y)our
security and reputation are in your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, a fax machine rang at the Bloomberg offices.
Streaming out of the machine came computer screen printouts with
confidential corporate files, including Bloomberg's employee
photograph, his computer password, and his personal credit card
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began a cat-and-mouse game pitting the mysterious Alex
against FBI agents and Bloomberg employees acting under their
direction. After exchanging a series of computer messages Bloomberg
agreed to deposit $200,000 in a European bank on Alex's promise
that he would reveal how he had cracked Bloomberg's security and
help the company's programmers shore up their defenses. FBI agents
and the Bloomberg employees then persuaded the mysterious
correspondent to travel to London for a meeting. Bloomberg agreed
to attend himself.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting in the Hilton Hotel in London last Thursday, the
agents sprang their trap. London police officers arrested two men
who attended. Monday, federal prosecutors in New York unsealed
criminal complaints against Oleg Zezov, 27, and Igor Yarimaka, 37,
charging them with unauthorized computer intrusion and extortion.
If extradited to the United States for trial and convicted on all
counts, each man faces as much as 20 years in federal prison,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are from Kazakhstan, authorities said, and according to
the complaint, Yarimaka claimed to be a former prosecutor in that
former Soviet state northwest of China.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Zezov gained access to the Bloomberg system
through a securities company he worked for in Almaty, Kazakhstan's
former capital.
</P>
<P>
   For a financial information company such as Bloomberg, which
uses computers to provide financial data to more than 200,000
customers around the world, some of whom trade stocks and bonds
over the network, computer security is critical. Officials at the
company said Monday that they were continually upgrading their
systems to prevent unauthorized intrusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are as confident as anyone can be that the security of our
system was, is, and continues to be adequate to protect our
customers,'' Chris Taylor, a company spokesperson said. ``We are
100 percent confident that they did not gain access to any of our
customers' data.'' Taylor did not want to comment further, although
the company issued a brief statement about the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   In detailed criminal complaints filed in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, federal agents described how they used their computers
to track the person calling himself Alex at the same time they
arranged the meeting in London. In the computer messages listed in
the complaint, Alex referred to the Bloomberg system as ``a toy for
hackers.'' At the same time assuring Bloomberg that he meant no
harm to his company, Alex also insisted on payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am honest and well-intentioned person as far as you could
see,'' one message read, according to the complaint. ``But I can't
give up my principles and in any case will get my money for done
job.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail goes on to suggest that Bloomberg deposit $200,000 in
an off-shore bank account. If the money is received, Alex wrote,
the information on the company would be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In case of nonpayment, I'll send the report to your clients,''
the e-mail said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, Bloomberg opened an account at a
Deutsche Bank office in London and deposited $200,000. The account
was set up so that Alex could confirm the money was present, but
could not transfer or withdraw the funds. A few days later, Alex
requested ``total control'' of the account and asked that Bloomberg
release $7,500 for travel expenses for the proposed meeting in
London.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI learned that the $7,500 was electronically transferred
to a bank in Riga, Latvia. Soon after, on July 25, Alex sent an
e-mail to Bloomberg agreeing to meet in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking forward to meet with you,'' the e-mail said.
``Today is my birthday, 27 years old. And on this day I don't want
you to think about me bad.''
</P>
<P>
   At the London meeting, the complaint says, Bloomberg told the
two men he was concerned they were extorting money from his
company. Yarimaka said they were not criminals, and that ``Alex''
had not broken any criminal laws in his country. He was concerned
that Bloomberg had used the term extortion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
