<HEADLINE>
BENNETT OK WITH NOT BEING UCLA QB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To know where Drew Bennett has gone in the last
year, all you had to do was be at UCLA's media day on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, like the rest of his teammates, had his photo taken in
full uniform and then milled around for the next hour, available
for anyone who wanted to interview or photograph him. He waited.
And waited. And waited.
</P>
<P>
   If only he'd had this much time in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was a good an indication of how Bennett's life has
changed in the last year, from Cade McNown's heir apparent to
fourth-string split end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was the center of attention,'' Bennett said, as he
sat in the bleachers among a group of similarly anonymous
teammates, far from any reporters or TV cameras who were zeroing in
on Cory Paus and Ryan McCann. ``It's a lot different this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5, 207-pound senior began last season as the Bruins'
starting quarterback, but by early October he had lost the job to
Paus and switched to receiver, a position where he hopes to put his
considerable athletic ability to use. He also might be the holder
on the field-goal unit.
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore, he caught a Hail Mary pass from Cade McNown that
looked as if it would beat Oregon. Kicker Chris Sailer missed a
short field goal before the Bruins won in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as glamorous, but there's not as much stress,''
Bennett said of his new role. ``I just want to play wherever I can.
Switching and getting a chance to play at receiver is better than
being the third- or fourth-string quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``From playing quarterback, I know all the routes and the
coverages, but it's different.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said the one thing he misses is having is hands on the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plays where you're not going to be looked at,'' he
said. ``Sometimes you might just run a guy off and you know you're
not going to get the ball. At quarterback, no matter what happens,
you're going to touch the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like thinking back with all the wouldas, shouldas,
couldas. There are a lot of things different about last season. I
just want to have fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
