<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS MAY NEED TO IMPROVISE AT CONVENTION OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
  By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like its network morning-show rivals, CBS's
``Early Show'' with Bryant Gumbel was all set to kick off its week
in Los Angeles on Monday with an extensive sitdown interview with
President Clinton and a separate talk with Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, Lyne Pitts, the program's executive producer, got
the distressing news that the president and first lady were backing
out. They also pulled out of an agreement with NBC's ``Today''
show, and Mr. Clinton decided not to do ABC's ``Good Morning
America,'' either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all set,'' Pitts said. ``Bryant was supposed to
interview him Saturday afternoon _ it had been booked for quite
some time. I got the calls at a little bit after 9 in the morning
saying that, sorry, the president's schedule would not accommodate
the interview.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not unknown for sought-after newsmakers to bump a news
show or two from their itineraries. But such a wholesale
withdrawal, at a time when the news media was fixated so avidly on
the Clintons, inevitably raised eyebrows. ``We knew Thursday night
how upset the Gore folks were with Clinton's confessional on
Thursday and that would be the talk of our interview,'' Pitts said,
adding it was ``more than an assumption'' that the Clintons had
dropped out to try to turn down the media heat on them a notch or
two. Mrs. Clinton, however, did a round of interviews with anchors
on all of the major broadcast and cable networks on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Though the convention is intended as a crowning television
moment for Vice President Al Gore, it was the sitting president who
weighed most heavily on the minds of editors and producers on
Monday. For the broadcast networks, it was not merely the issue of
Clinton's absence in the morning, but also his presence on Monday
night, as the featured speaker on the convention's opening day.
</P>
<P>
   The hoopla surrounding Clinton's appearance seemed to reflect a
sense in the press corps here that Los Angeles may indeed generate
more interesting and entertaining tidbits than did Philadelphia. On
``The Early Show'' for instance, Pitts said that one of the
interview segments on Tuesday would feature Hugh Hefner and his
daughter Christie from the Playboy Mansion. The Hefners, hefty
contributors to Democratic causes, found themselves at the center
of the news in recent days, after Democratic officials pressured
Rep. Loretta Sanchez of Orange County, Calif. to move a benefit out
of the Playboy Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been the one bit of interesting controversy here,''
Pitts said.
</P>
<P>
   News executives at the big three broadcast networks had
decisions to make about how much of the president's speech to cover
if, as expected, he spoke past 11 p.m. on the East Coast, intruding
on local news shows. Last week the chairman of the Republican
National Committee, Jim Nicholson, had admonished the networks that
it would be unfair to give Clinton more air time than had been
allotted to former Gen. Colin Powell, the featured speaker on the
first night of the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Cable networks are covering the party proceedings nonstop, but
the big three networks are each taking different approaches. On
Monday night, ABC planned to begin an hour of coverage at 10 p.m.,
provided that the preseason ``Monday Night Football'' game ended on
time; CBS planned to insert convention coverage in its ``48 Hours''
news program at 10, and NBC News _ which has shifted most of its
coverage to its cable channel MSNBC _ scheduled its broadcast of
Mr. Clinton's speech for 10:30.
</P>
<P>
   All three networks said that Clinton's speech would be more
newsworthy than General Powell's and probably worth staying with.
(None of three networks ran the general's speech in its entirety.)
``In all respect to Colin Powell, I don't think they're equal in
that one is the president and has been president for eight years,''
said Marc Burstein, executive producer of special events for ABC
News.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had another sudden worry: what if Monday night's football
game between the Tennessee Titans and St. Louis Rams ran well past
10? Burstein said that while he did not watch a lot of football,
his understanding was that the evening's matchup was likely to be
largely a passing game, which made it more likely that the game
would move slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a nightmare I don't even want to deal with,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
