<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALHALLA WILL OFFER A TOUGHER TEST FOR PGA CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ When Valhalla Golf Club played host to its
first major championship in 1996, the weather was hot, but the
course received lukewarm reviews.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1996, when Mark Brooks won the PGA Championship by
one stroke over Kenny Perry, two solid players, but hardly legends.
Meanwhile, the course was criticized for being too easy, with 46
players finishing under par.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the PGA Championship is back at Valhalla, for
the year's final major, which begins Thursday. But this year's
tournament has the potential to be far more memorable than the one
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods did not play at Valhalla in 1996 when he was still
an amateur. Coming off his record-setting victories at both the
U.S. Open and the British Open, Woods could become the first player
to win three consecutive majors since Ben Hogan in 1953. Imagine
the galleries Woods will attract this week. Though Woods will not
arrive at Valhalla until Tuesday, Monday's practice rounds were
heavily attended, and the crowds will be huge once the tournament
begins.
</P>
<P>
   The Jack Nicklaus-designed course, which opened in 1986, has
been lengthened and toughened since 1996, and most players who
practiced Monday said the changes were for the better. A more
mature course, a world-class field, enthusiastic galleries and a
major championship at stake seemed like reason enough to give
Valhalla a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one of the traditional courses, and it's not the same
style of course we usually play majors on,'' said Jim Furyk, who
tied for 17th here in 1996. ``So there's a lot of talk about the
course. But I'm excited about the week. It's a major championship.
We'd all like to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning will require accuracy off the tee and precise approach
shots into the severely undulating greens. Twelve of the 18 holes
have been altered in some way since 1996, with most of the changes
on the front nine encouraging players to use their driver more
often. The first hole has been lengthened 21 yards to 446 yards,
and the fairway was narrowed at the par 5, 533-yard No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   But on paper, Valhalla remains a course where length is not a
prerequisite for winning. Brooks, who won in 1996, is not among the
tour's longest hitters, and the prevailing theory is that Valhalla
may not fit Woods as well as Pebble Beach and St. Andrews did. But
any course fits Woods when he is playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winner will be someone who's making putts, who's handling
the greens well,'' said Steve Jones, who won the 1996 U.S. Open.
``Everyone knows Tiger's the best player. He hits the ball great,
but the key to him running away at the U.S. Open was that he made
all those putts for par that kept his momentum going. And at St.
Andrews, his length was a big factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good course. Sure, tradition counts for
something, especially in your own mind. I would've been thrilled to
win any U.S. Open, to win it at Oakland Hills and to have my ugly
mug up there next to someone like Ben Hogan only made it more
special. But this is a major championship, and whoever wins Sunday
will be thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   The first three majors of the year were played at three of
golf's most treasured venues _ the Masters at Augusta National Golf
Club with its unique tradition, the U.S. Open at Pebble Beach Golf
Links with his special beauty, and the British Open at St. Andrews,
a historic site known as the home of golf. Valhalla is following
some tough acts, but the public is certain to become more familiar
with Valhalla in the coming years. The PGA of America, which owns
Valhalla, is bringing the PGA Championship back here in 2006, and
the Ryder Cup will be played here in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   The par 4, 470-yard No. 12 is Valhalla's toughest hole, but the
par 5, 542-yard No. 18 could provide the best theater. The
finishing hole features a three-level green that can be reached in
two shots, providing the potential for an eagle finish that could
produce a two-or-three-shot swing.
</P>
<P>
   So with Woods chasing history and the Louisville area ready to
embrace golf's biggest stars, another major championship will be
played at Valhalla. There was a buzz in the air Monday, and it was
only Monday. And once the tournament begins, the venue will not
matter as much to the players as the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's excited to be here, but I hope some guys
aren't,'' Furyk said. ``Maybe that might make it easier for me to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
