<HEADLINE>
THE MONEY QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before this campaign is over, the most significant of Senator
Joseph Lieberman's moral targets may not be the licentiousness of
Bill Clinton, but the corruption of money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is: While Lieberman's sharp criticism of
Clinton's behavior with Monica Lewinsky helps distance Vice
President Al Gore from that swamp, the senator's work on campaign
finance reform could be an embarrassment to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Their policy positions on the issue are similar, but their
behavior is not. Gore cannot escape his record of fund-raising
phone calls from the White House and the infamous Buddhist temple
fund-raiser right here in Los Angeles _ all in service to the
gluttonous 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, in a scathing 1998 Atlantic magazine article, blasted
both Clinton-Gore and the GOP for ``sleazy behavior,'' which he
said ``betrayed the public trust'' and ``effectively hung a giant
FOR SALE sign on our government and the whole of our political
process.
</P>
<P>
   This April, Gore pledged to make campaign finance a major
priority, but, as Common Cause President Scott Harshbarger noted
Monday, ``he hasn't said one thing about it since.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley and John McCain proved the issue has political
worth, and Governor George W. Bush's indifference, combined with
his own extraordinary fund-raising juggernaut, create an opening
for the Democrats. But Gore has only jacked up the Democrats' soft
money collections this year, and he broke an agreement with the GOP
by being the first to use that money in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lavish, corporate-dominated convention here _ equal to
the GOP's in Philadelphia _ Gore is vulnerable to questioning from
people like Harshbarger, who asks: ``How credible's the
messenger?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore must begin to answer that question Thursday night.
Lieberman can help, but only if Gore moves to renounce the past
errors that Lieberman identified so pointedly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-NYT &LR;      08-14 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG COMEBACK WITH A SMALL, UGLY SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Teammates on the U.S. Olympic squad, Jenny
Thompson and Dara Torres have built an engaging swimming rivalry
that represents both the wonder and suspicion that attends women's
swimming at the elite international level.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry, which continued Monday night in the 100-meter
freestyle, has been a primary story line here in the Olympic trials
that determine the American team for the 2000 Summer Games next
month in Sydney, Australia. Both swimmers had the luxury of knowing
they had qualified in the 100-meter butterfly, in which Thompson
defeated Torres last Thursday. They will meet again Wednesday in
the 50-meter freestyle and, a month from now, they will challenge
the ascendant Inge de Bruijn of the Netherlands, who holds world
records in all three of the sprints.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, Thompson, who is 27, and Torres, who is 33,
represent the multitudinous possibility for women in this age of
Olympic professionalism and gender equity fostered by Title IX.
Once, female swimmers had to retire in high school, with no college
scholarships or money-making opportunities available to them. Now,
they can keep their careers buoyant on prize money and
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, in particular, is a species as rare as a snail darter _
the female athlete still competing among the world's best as she
nears her mid-'30s. She returned to swimming last year after a
seven-year retirement in which she worked as a fashion model and
television personality. She is talented and effervescent and has
overcome a battle with bulimia. Apparently, no swimmer has ever
taken such a long sabbatical, then seriously challenged for an
Olympic medal. She will be the first American swimmer ever to
compete in four Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   But no Olympic sport has been compromised by the use of
performance-enhancing drugs as women's swimming has been, and the
singular aspect of Torres' career that makes it celebratory also
has led to skepticism about her performances that even her coach
acknowledges have clouded any accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Torres has never failed a drug test, and no other swimmer or
coach here has accused her of take banned, performance-enhancing
substances. But after three decades of demonstrated cheating in
this sport involving East German and Chinese athletes, the 1996
Irish Olympic champion Michelle Smith and even American athletes, a
despairing ritual has become the habit in swimming and almost every
other Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   Though testing is conducted at all major meets, no tests have
been approved for substances that athletes are believed to be
widely using such as EPO and human growth hormone. Cheaters have
become sophisticated by using synthetic versions of substances that
exist naturally in the body and are difficult to detect. An EPO
test may be implemented at the Sydney Games, but the International
Olympic Committee's own doctors are saying privately that they fear
the tests will not withstand legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, coaches and athletes concede, passing a drug test
no longer provides convincing evidence of being drug-free. In such
a climate of uncertainty, every remarkable performance becomes
suspicious, and news conferences have become tense give-and-takes
involving skepticism and denial.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Quick, the coach of the American women's Olympic swim
team, said in an interview that he understood the distrust. He was
among the loudest in his skepticism about the Chinese, who have had
some three dozen swimmers test positive in the 1990s, and Smith,
who was banned last year after having contaminated one of her drug
tests with alcohol and having previously tested positive for
androstenedione. He said he blamed the IOC for betraying athletes
who do not take drugs, because, given the current testing
deficiencies, the innocent can no longer prove their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that sport is at the point where every great
performance has a cloud over it,'' said Quick, who coaches both
Thompson and Torres in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm bitter toward the IOC. They've allowed cheating
to go on far too long. They are a lot more into sponsorship money
and television money. They are a lot more concerned about many
things other than the rights of fair competition for athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   His athletes are clean, Quick said. Torres is at the cutting
edge of nutrition, strength and flexibility training, he said, and
she works out ravenously. And, he pointed out, she did not come
from nowhere. Before she retired after the 1992 Summer Games,
Torres won two Olympic gold medals on relays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks it's a huge miracle that I'm swimming
faster,'' Torres said. ``This is what I think was in me when I was
younger. The circumstances weren't right. I had an eating problem.
Training is better for me. Nutrition is better for me. Everything
is in a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   She has a supporter in what may seem to an unexpected place.
Phil Whitten, the editor of Swimming World magazine, has been at
the forefront of revealing widespread drug use in swimming. His
magazine first published reports from the files of the East German
police, known as the Stasi, that uncovered the state-sponsored
system of cheating in the sport. But he said he was not suspicious
about Torres, given her history of swimming fast, and the new
training techniques being used.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, while teaching anthropology at Harvard, Whitten said he
conducted research on masters swimmers, tracing several thousand
athletes over a 20-year period and showing that swimmers reached
their peaks at 32 or 33. Until recently, however, elite athletes
did not have the financial support to remain in the Olympic side of
the sport that long.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '93 and '94, I was banging my head against the wall, trying
to get the major media to realize there was a widespread drug
problem in the sport,'' Whitten said. ``Now that they've realized
it, they've overlearned the lesson. They can't distinguish between
people whose performances are suspicious and people whose
performances are legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry between Thompson and Torres here has focused on
their own relationship, which appears respectful if not cordial.
Thompson is from New Hampshire, a taciturn Yankee, though she has
drawn much attention, and some criticism, for posing without a top
on in the current issue of Sports Illustrated magazine. (She said
she posed so that girls could see that it was okay to have a
muscular appearance.) Torres is from Beverly Hills, sunny and
gregarious. They train at different times, Torres saying that
workouts became too intense together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two great athletes desired a lot of individual attention and
somewhat demanded it,'' Quick said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
