<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CRAB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSIBLE CRAB LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week the federal government took long overdue action to
protect the horseshoe crab from commercial devastation, while still
making the animals available for critical medical uses. Until last
week, the government had it backwards, trying to keep a Cape Cod
company from bleeding some horseshoe crabs for a substance used in
medical equipment sterilization, but allowing mid-Atlantic
fishermen to slaughter hundreds of thousands of them for bait.
</P>
<P>
   The government action establishes an 1,800-square-mile sanctuary
for horseshoe crabs from Delaware Bay out into the Atlantic, and it
directs worst-offender Virginia to drastically reduce its catch
voluntarily or risk being shut down by government order. Fishermen
use horseshoe crabs as bait for eels and a form of conch, the
channeled whelk, that is a mainstay of Cantonese cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The government's actions are needed to protect the horseshoe
crabs, a quickly dwindling species that predates dinosaurs and is
actually closer to spiders than it is to ordinary crabs. Horseshoe
crabs are critical not only to an industry that produces Limulus
Amebocyte Lysate from their blood for the detection of bacterial
contamination, but also to several species of shore birds that use
excess horseshoe crab eggs as a fast-food stop on their migration
flights.
</P>
<P>
   While mid-Atlantic breeding grounds for the crabs have suffered
from lax oversight, regulators have erred in the opposite direction
in New England. The US Interior Department has tried to stop a
lysate company based in Falmouth from bleeding any of the horseshoe
crabs off the Cape Cod National Seashore and the Monomoy National
Wildlife Refuge, even though a study in the 1980s showed that the
process kills few if any of the animals. This spring, a federal
judge had the good sense to issue an injunction to lift Interior's
ban for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   The real battle to ensure the long-term survival of the
horseshoe crab will be fought in the mid-Atlantic states. It is
gratifying to see that the federal government understands the
stakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
