<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-PROTEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMONSTRATORS SEEK TO RECLAIM LOST VOICE IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Face pressed against the chainlink fence
encircling the protest pit, Jonah Zern shouted, pleaded, to be
taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In the background, speaker after speaker took to the microphone.
Several thousand demonstrators roared their approval. But Zern, a
22-year-old recent college graduate, worried that no one who wasn't
nearby would hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're protesting to protest,'' said Zern, whose T-shirt
advertised a group called Students Alliance to Reform Corporations.
``We have to protest. To be heard in the United States, you have to
have wealth. For the average person, you have to find another
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, from Patriotic Hall where the second Shadow Convention is
being held to the Convergence Center where puppets and other props
are built to Pershing Square where protesters rally before marching
the dozen blocks to the convention center, the massed opponents of
the status quo wonder whether their messages resonate, not just
with the Democrats gathered in Los Angeles but also with a
citizenry impatient with activism.
</P>
<P>
   There are, after all, dozens of messages vying for attention.
Protest organizers could sew an enormous quilt using just the
slogans on signs, shirts and caps that can be spotted at any
demonstration. Whether the cause is saving the ancient forests,
shuttering sweatshops or ensuring access to health care, it is sure
to be represented somewhere in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But above the din -- once the paraders dressed as Mother Earth
and Uncle Sam and billionaires buying government influence have
passed -- one concern comes through loud and clear: regardless of
specific issue, these demonstrators no longer believe that America
belongs to Americans. It is what unites them, they say, even when
their agendas overlap or conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is really boils down to, at least here at the DNC, is
that we don't have a say in politics anymore,'' said Meagan
Cartwright, a 20-year-old college physics major from Seattle who is
interning at a nonprofit organization working to stop global
warming and save the ozone layer. ``That's what brings us all
together.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era when poll after poll shows increasing political
apathy, the thousands of demonstrators who paid their own way to
bake in the sun outside the Staples Center understand that they are
an anomaly. With their aggressive slogans and guerrilla stunts,
they have watched themselves dismissed as fringe fanatics or
raucous rioters. Many blame the media for emphasizing another day
of peace over any of the substantive issues under discussion on
stages and street corners around the city.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the demonstrators, in fact, are young, in their teens or
twenties, and not always well-showered. But just as many are in
well-worn T-shirts espousing causes dating back 20 or 30 years.
Union hats bob in the crowds. Ask them, and many demonstrators say
they are just ordinary Americans whose country is at an
extraordinary crossroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around at the diversity of the crowd,'' said Donald
Kegley, 46, a third-generation steelworker from Eureka, Calif., and
co-chairman of a group called the Alliance for Sustainable Jobs and
the Environment. ``I think what we're all trying to say is that
government caters to corporations and not the needs of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Francisco Argerre, 45, a Mexican immigrant and furniture
mover who lives in Los Angeles, ``Corporations even influence
immigration. That's what worries me most.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Kegley were at a rally Monday to save an indigenous
Colombian tribe called the U'wa, whose lands are allegedly being
destroyed by Occidental Petroleum -- an issue on which protesters
say Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore has declined to take
a stand. ``Al Gore: Reject Big Oil $$'' read the banner under which
speakers addressed the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As Julie Freitas, an Angeleno whose 24-year-old son was murdered
in Colombia last while working to defend the U'wa, told them, ``You
are the ones who can make change. We used to make change, but we're
old and tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside The Gap in downtown Santa Monica, where
hundreds of demonstrators on Sunday demanded an end to what they
claimed are sweatshop conditions at factories around the world used
by the retailer and other clothing companies, environmentalists
dressed as frogs mingled with ``billionaires'' whose top hats and
tails were intended to mock money's influence on politics.
</P>
<P>
   Said Medea Benjamin, co-founder of the human rights group Global
Exchange and the Green Party candidate for a US Senate seat from
California, ``It's the kind of thing where people can really make
the connection between these clothes and sweatshop conditions. .
.We need to make people understand that a system based on corporate
greed is not good for the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans needs not corporate greed'' was Monday's official
protest theme. Upcoming themes revolve around the criminal justice
system, environmental protections, and worker rights. At the Shadow
Convention, the day's topic was the gap between rich and poor, and
enough people turned out to fill an auditorium almost to capacity.
Tuesday's theme is the failed war on drugs. Wednesday's is campaign
finance reform -- a theme that activists of every stripe raise at
every rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing it the right way, hitting four or five major
themes and laying the groundwork for the future,'' said Allen
Powell, 47, a high school economics teacher who set aside his
social activism after he had a family but was drawn to the Shadow
Convention Monday. ``It's always difficult when you have so much
prosperity to get people to care. But it's important for people to
make these connections because when times aren't so good, they'll
be together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
