<HEADLINE>
MEET THE PRESS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies DAILY SHOW)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get to know the correspondents of ``The Daily Show With Jon
Stewart,'' who are in the trenches covering this year's political
conventions:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS BLACK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back story: This stand-up comic, known for his ``Back in Black''
``Daily Show'' segments, has headlined at various A-list comedy
clubs throughout the United States and Europe and has performed his
one-man show, ``Black Humor,'' off-Broadway in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Sound bite: ``And how do Republicans include minorities? By
letting them perform.'' (Shot of an African-American gospel choir.)
``This choir taught Republicans the importance of faith ... and how
to clap on two and four.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STEVE CARELL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back story: This Bostonian, a veteran of Chicago's famed Second
City improv troupe, sharpened his comedy skills as a
writer/performer on the short-lived ``Dana Carvey Show,'' as well
as a number of other short-lived and never-to-be-seen TV shows.
He's also the voice of Gary, The Commissioner, and various other
characters on the animated ``Saturday Night Live'' series ``The
Ambiguously Gay Duo.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound bite: When asked if George Bush is a man of character who
can unite our country and get things done: ``Yes, but his son is
running this time.'' (Gales of laughter.) ``I was just ``waiting''
for you to ask me that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN COLBERT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back story: This South Carolina native got his start with Second
City and has since become a regular face on Comedy Central, having
helped develop the half-hour sketch comedy series ``Exit 57,'' as
well as the network's first live-action narrative series,
``Strangers With Candy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound bite: ``Well, John, as a journalist I have to maintain my
objectivity, but I would say that the feeling down here (on the
convention floor) was one of a pervasive and palpable evil. A thick
demonic stench that rolls over you and clings like hot black tar.
... This is hell, John, where the damned languish forever in a
black flame that gives no heat, sheds no light, yet consumes the
flesh forever and will not go out.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   VANCE DEGENERES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back story: This New Orleans native was almost lost to the world
of rock 'n' roll, having performed with The Cold and former Go-Go's
drummer Gina Schock's band, House of Schock. A military stint led
to a gig as a broadcast journalist for the Marine Corps, followed
by a successful career in television writing, starting with
``Eerie, Indiana.'' He wrote for his sister Ellen's show during the
``coming out'' season of ABC's ``Ellen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound bite: On whether George W.'s acceptance speech surpassed
his father's ``thousand points of light'' phrase in '88 or Dole's
``strings of sparkling diamonds'' in '96. ``No, but he did surpass
my expectations. Knowing his oratorial style, I was expecting
something along the lines of, `America: Shiny things good.'''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MO ROCCA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back story: Honed his skills as a news writer while serving as a
writer/producer for PBS' kid's series ``Wishbone'' as well as
Nickelodeon's preschool ``Wubbulous World of Dr. Seuss.'' His
diverse career has included stints as editor of the adult
publication ``Perfect 10,'' the only nudie mag to feature
exclusively models without breast implants.
</P>
<P>
   Sound bite: ``There are now real opportunities for minorities in
the GOP. For instance, of the nine African-American members of the
Republican Party, six will be speaking here this week, two will be
singing, and the ninth, of course, is Alan Keyes. As you can see,
they're on a fast track.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   NANCY WALLS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back story: This Massachusetts native was another Second City
veteran, who eventually landed a spot on ``SNL'' during the
1995-1996 season. She's married to fellow ``Daily Show''
correspondent Steve Carell.
</P>
<P>
   Sound bite: ``The GOP hit on strengthening Social Security. Bush
has suggested that the government be free to invest Social Security
funds in the stock market, thereby assuring the comfort of millions
of Americans by linking their retirement to the success of
Pets.com. This has Republicans very excited about what most
Americans think is the worst idea in the world ever.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Todd Camp
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
