<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BEI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRESTED POET AN INTERNATIONAL CHAMPION OF FREE SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tendency Quarterly, the literary magazine whose
contents apparently landed the Boston-based poet Bei Ling in a
Chinese prison last weekend, has never managed to come out
quarterly, or to push its circulation over 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the tiny publication brought Bei Ling, who was formally
detained by Beijing police Monday, to the attention of the Chinese
government and won him broad support among free speech advocates
both internationally and in the Chinese intellectual underground.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official, stressing that the United States
has not confirmed the jailing of Bei, said Monday that such an
arrest would be ``extremely disturbing'' to the US government. News
of the arrest reached US officials and the media through Bei's
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bei Ling to our knowledge has not engaged in any criminal
activity,'' the official said. ``China has committed itself to
uphold the principle of freedom. . . . To detain an individual for
the peaceful expression of political or other views is a violation
of these commitments,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The formal detention allows police to hold Bei for 30 days while
attempting to build a case against him, according to a relative who
relayed the news to the media. The police have made no specific
charge, the relative said.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the specific charge is the last thing that matters to the
regime,'' said Ross Terrill, an author of books on modern Chinese
political leaders. Terrill himself was expelled from China in 1992
for allegedly exceeding the activities allowed by a tourist visa.
``They will think of something.''
</P>
<P>
   Bei, who visits China annually, ``has had his problems, as we
all have,'' said Terrill, a research associate at Harvard
University's East Asia Center. ``He has been harassed, he has been
pressured, he has suffered mysterious incidents of boxes (of the
journal) disappearing while he was trying to distribute it. But
this is an escalation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bei came to the United States from Beijing in 1988, while a
surge in free expression was sweeping through China. He was
participating in a literary exchange program sponsored by a New
York Chinese newspaper when the free speech and democracy movement
came to an abrupt and bloody end the next year, with China's
massacre of demonstrators around Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   The slaughter, and the long period of repression that followed,
made Bei a determined activist, willing to take the risks involved
in participating in the underground literary world of China.
</P>
<P>
   First he joined protests against the crackdown, and tried to
organize support for the victims. Then he enrolled in ``Freedom to
Write,'' a Brown University program from writers from China, Cuba,
and other countries where repression was common. When that program
ended in 1993, he moved to Boston to be near the humanist and
Chinese cultural centers of Harvard, and because he had friends
here who would help him launch the journal.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 issues of Tendency Quarterly that have appeared since
then have stretched the boundaries of a literary journal to include
dialogues between Chinese and Western intellectuals and interviews
with writers and poets including Nadine Gordimer, Seamus Heaney,
and Susan Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   Gordimer and Sontag became editorial advisers, according to
executive editor Meng Lang, a cofounder of the journal who now
lives in Cambridge, Mass.; so did Nobel laureates Elie Weisel,
Czeslaw Milosz, and Octavio Paz.
</P>
<P>
   Tendency also attracted the attention of the National Endowment
for Democracy, a quasi-independent, US-government funded
organization set up during Ronald Reagan's presidency; the
organization provided financial support in 1995 and 1996, Meng
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meng said that he and Bei have been associates since the 1980s,
and that he followed his friend to the writers program at Brown,
arriving in 1995 after having been harassed and detained himself in
the southern city of Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
   Tendency Quarterly is sold in bookstores in Hong Kong and
Taiwan, and by subscription to libraries and Sinologists
internationally, Meng said, but most copies are given away in
mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   Bei was seized and the current issue confiscated Friday night
following a forum near Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   Terrill, who was contacted in Australia, said Bei caught the
attention of the increasingly control-oriented Chinese authorities
_ who in recent months have cracked down on independent journalists
and dissident websites _ because ``a poet is not always a
conforming spirit, and Bei Ling is a true poet. He is not an
organizer. He is not a diplomat. He is a serious literary figure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
