<SLUG> BC-BERYL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GULF COAST UNFAZED BY BERYL'S APPROACH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HARLINGEN _ Tropical Storm Beryl quickened its pace toward the
Gulf Coast shore Monday, but many residents, mindful of last year's
weak pass by Hurricane Bret, seemed unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they watched Beryl's development, planned to weather
the storm at home and hoped it would mean a needed soaking of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hurricane Bret, a powerful Category 4 storm, barreled
through the open ranch country of South Texas, doing little harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's left yet and nobody is talking about leaving,'' said
Matt Moreau, owner of Pico Ace Hardware on South Padre Island.
``Most people are laughing about it and being cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the National Weather Service predicted that Beryl's
effect on the Houston area would be limited to widely scattered
showers and thunderstorms ending Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get a quarter of an inch (of rain), consider yourself
lucky,'' said weather service meteorologist Kent Prochazka.
</P>
<P>
   Beryl was declared a tropical storm Monday when its sustained
winds reached 40 mph. It could reach hurricane strength _
consistent winds of at least 75 mph _ before blowing ashore Tuesday
somewhere near the U.S.-Mexico border, said James Franklin at the
National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Beryl was centered about 135 miles south-southwest of
Brownsville and was moving northwest at 8 mph. Meteorologists said
if it continued at that pace, it might not have time to grow into a
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the U.S. government issued a hurricane warning for a
100-mile stretch from Baffin Bay, just north of Corpus Christi, to
the Mexican border. The Mexican government issued a hurricane
warning from the border south to La Pesca, a stretch of about 130
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the warnings, few South Padre Island residents purchased
plywood sheets and flashlight batteries. People were confident the
storm would follow weather service predictions and hit land south
of Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   If the storm passes to the south, residents of the Rio Grande
Valley would see strong winds and get a much-needed drenching of 5
inches to 10 inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not boarding up windows or advising evacuation, and
we're not planning to do that,'' said Ray Kendall, South Padre
Island city manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through our countdown: closing off the low access
points to the beach so the water won't flood the streets; moving
trash barrels back to vegetation line; trying to get people to move
their umbrellas off the beach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron County's two beachfront parks on South Padre Island were
closed Monday as crews boarded up facilities facing the Gulf. An
evacuation of mobile homes at Isla Blanca Park also was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a steady stream of shrimp trawlers moved through the
Brazos Santiago Pass on their way to Port Isabel, cutting short
fishing trips into the roiling Gulf waters.
</P>
<P>
   At the island's U.S. Coast Guard station, three rescue boats
were hauled out of the water and a 41-foot patrol boat was moved
inland.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer Mike Watson said the station was preparing for an
intense tropical storm _ with a storm surge and high winds _ but
not a major hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, everything is calm,'' Watson said. The turmoil at sea
was good news for some: Near the island's southern jetties, eager
surfers lined the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stay out there 'til I get washed back in,'' said
Houston surfer Aaron Lloyd, watching the waves hiss to shore. ``We
always come down here for the hurricanes _ it's the only good surf
all summer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
