<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-NILE-VIRUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD CROWS TRACK SPREAD OF NILE VIRUS IN EASTERN MASS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State officals identified six more crows infected with
the West Nile virus Monday, doubling the number of bird cases to
date and suggesting the virus is spreading more quickly in August
as the mosquito population swells.
</P>
<P>
   The virus hot spot is now clearly the Jamaica Plain-Brookline
area, where all six infected birds were found, said state
officials. However, they said Monday's finds were expected and
likely will be repeated again this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting to have positive birds each week, not only in
JP-Brookline, but scattered in other areas,'' said Ralph Timperi,
director of the state public health lab in Jamaica Plain. ``I'm
sure we'll find (infected) birds until the first week of October,
when the frost puts the mosquitoes down.''
</P>
<P>
   The news followed a weekend of events that affirmed the virus
has found a home on the East Coast: Rhode Island's first infected
crow and two more non-fatal human cases in New York. The
potentially lethal virus has now surfaced in every state between
New Jersey and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, East Coast health officals already have begun turning
their attention to next summer, when the cases of the virus could
multiply _ especially in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquitoes born in mid-August will probably be the ones to
carry the virus into next year. Crews are blanketing greater Boston
neighborhoods, laying tablets in breeding areas they hope will kill
these new arrivals before they hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Migrating birds are thought to carry the virus from state to
state, but mosquitoes spread it locally. Paul Jacobsen, the deputy
commissioner of the state Department of Public Health, said that
the leafy area where Jamaica Plain meets Brookline ``appears to be
the center of West Nile activity in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, 10 of the 12 infected Massachusetts birds have been
found there. One of the crows identified Monday was actually found
in Wellesley but officials said the bird probably strayed. A
secondary hot spot is thought to be in the Hopkinton area, where
two birds have been found.
</P>
<P>
   All six birds found Monday died between Aug. 7 and 9 in the
heaviest virus toll to date. That mirrors the experience elsewhere:
New York has seen a jump in bird and mosquito cases in recent
weeks, and the virus was most deadly in August 1999, when it killed
seven and sickened about 60 in Queens, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's crow body count coincides with a dramatic increase in
the Culex pipiens mosquito, which carries the virus. Since
mid-July, its population has increased tenfold every two weeks. It
peaks this week.
</P>
<P>
   The state lab has tested more than 500 dead birds this summer,
and 35 new ones came in this weekend. The testing can take up to
three days.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the mosquitoes that have been hatching since Aug. 10
that are likely to survive the frost and the winter. Next summer,
they may continue to spread the virus here, perhaps at an
accelerated pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems likely that there will be more cases next year,''
said Andrew Spielman, a professor of tropical public health at
Harvard's School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the turning point for this summer's mosquitoes is
already at hand. Aug. 10 is when long summer days begin to contain
less than 14 hours and 15 minutes of sunlight. This is a
physiological trigger for the mosquitoes about to hatch, telling
their bodies to concentrate on food storage instead of
reproduction. They feed for a few weeks in August but their
newly-instructed bodies can draw from the food supply for months,
allowing them to survive winter. The older mosquitoes, fatigued by
reproduction, will probably not make it.
</P>
<P>
   These new mosquitoes, if infected, will start the disease cycle
again next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect (the virus) will appear in areas as far as 200 miles
from here,'' said Spielman.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the virus made its first appearance in Rhode
Island, killing a crow found in Warwick. The state had been
practicing all summer for the possibility and greeted the finding
calmly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's positive indication of West Nile virus in Warwick is
not unexpected, with positive results already turning up to our
south in Connecticut and to our north in Massachusetts,'' said
Rhode Island Governor Lincoln Almond in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no human cases this summer anywhere but Staten
Island, N.Y., which appears to be the virus' epicenter. This past
weekend, officials there revealed that a 63-year-old woman and a
64-year-old man tested postive for it, bringing the total of West
Nile victims to three. All have recovered, they said. The virus
produced a mild form of meningitis in all three, a dramatic
contrast to the rapid brain-swelling encephalitis that killed
Queens residents a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the majority of cases, West Nile virus causes mild flu-like
symptoms. It can occasionally be fatal. The elderly, infants, and
those with weakened immune systems are most at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
