<SLUG> BC-DEM-BRADLEY-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY RELEASES HIS DELEGATES TO GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo CVN5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the last symbolic act of his failed
presidential campaign, former Sen. Bill Bradley released his 390
delegates to Vice President Al Gore on Monday, telling them that
``Al Gore will stand for the things we fought for in this campaign
and he deserves our support.''
</P>
<P>
   Bathed in spotlight for the first time in months and flanked by
his wife and daughter, Bradley delivered a speech that echoed his
stump appearances of the winter, praising the ``goodness of the
American people'' and hailing the importance of universal health
care, campaign finance reform and programs for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Then, recalling an event last month where he formally endorsed
Gore, he encouraged his supporters to set aside their hard feelings
about the bitterly contested primaries and work hard for the
Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is a team sport,'' Bradley said. ``We have to win in
the fall. The stakes are large. The Supreme Court. Social Security
at a cross roads. And what happens when the budget surplus is up
for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Bradley's brief remarks, William Daley, Gore's
campaign chairman, praised the former senator as ``a special
person'' who had a ``special understanding of the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To honor him is to make sure that the sort of things he wanted
come into being,'' Daley said. ``For that, we need your strong
support for Al Gore and Joe Lieberman.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley noted that Bradley often took ``controversial positions''
that ``may have caused him problems in the short term, but in the
long term were right.'' Paradoxically, Gore harshly attacked
Bradley throughout the campaign for taking positions that did not
conform to Democratic Party orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is to make a 15-minute address to the convention Tuesday
night in prime time. His speech, his aides said, would be unlike
the poorly received keynote address he made to the convention in
1992 when he angrily accused President George Bush of ``not getting
it'' and complained that ``For too long, American leadership has
waffled and wiggled and wavered.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, his aides said, Bradley will call for ``a new kind of
politics'' that is more upbeat and optimistic. But they said he
would not shy away from criticizing the Republican agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bradley spoke fondly on Monday of the 15-month campaign
that he called ``a joyous journey,'' it is difficult to say what
mark he left on the party or its standard-bearer.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley himself contends that he pushed Gore into taking
stronger positions on expanding health care, gun control, child
poverty and campaign finance reform. And many of Gore's aides
acknowledge that Bradley's challenge _ which early on seemed
formidable but melted quickly _ made Gore a better campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even though he amassed a warchest of more than $20 million
and assembled a sprawling if poorly organized band of followers in
most major states, Bradley failed to win a single primary or
caucus, and had no apparent input on the writing of the Democratic
platform.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said Bradley has not decided what he will do next.
They said he was likely to follow a path similar to before the
campaign, writing a book, working as a consultant and possibly
teaching on the side.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Bradley entered the room, he was enveloped by supporters,
and as he left, he worked his way slowly to the rear of the room
shaking hands and signing autographs to all comers. But as he often
did on the stump, Bradley looked somewhat uncomfortable in the
spotlight, tightly gripping his microphone in both hands and
looking stone-faced into the crowd when they interrupted him with
applause, which was often.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the delegates in the crowd said they were prepared to
work enthusiastically for Gore, if only out of fears that voting
for Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate, or not voting at all,
would lead to a Bush victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want Gore to lose,'' said David Loebsack, a
professor of political science at Cornell College in Iowa and a
Bradley delegate. ``There is a real difference between Gore and the
Republican ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in the room agreed. Cornel West, a Harvard
professor who is close to Bradley, said there was still deep
wariness among some Bradley supporters toward Gore and his more
centrist agenda. ``Bradley still hasn't had his due,'' West said.
``It's clear we still don't have two clear choices in this race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
