<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUNK-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS SEEK WAY TO RESCUE TRAPPED SUB CREW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's navy struggled to find a way Monday to rescue
more than 100 crew members trapped on a crippled Russian nuclear
submarine stranded on the bottom of icy seas north of the Arctic
Circle.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk, a massive Oscar-II class submarine designed to
destroy aircraft carrier groups such as those deployed by the US
Navy, plunged to the ocean floor of the Barents Sea early Sunday
after the crew was forced to shut down its two nuclear reactors
during a magor naval exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the Kursk, which is capable of carrying 24
nuclear-tipped ship-killing missiles, had no nuclear weapons on
board at the time of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials disclosed the accident only Monday, as rescue
ships rushed to the area where the distressed vessel lay, about 500
feet down in international waters, just north of the Kola
Peninsula. But officials here gave conflicting assessments of the
accident's cause and their chances for recovering the craft and
saving the crew.
</P>
<P>
   As rescuers in miniature submarines circled the stricken vessel,
the commander of Russia's navy, Admiral Vladimir Kuroyedov, said
the Kursk apparently had been involved in a major collision and
sustained serious damage, and expressed grave doubts that the 116
officers and sailors on board could be saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the efforts being taken, the probability of a
successful outcome from the situation with the Kursk is not very
high,'' Russian news agencies quoted Kuroyedov as saying.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia's Itar-Tass news agency quoted a defence company
source later Monday as saying preliminary surveys of the Kursk
ruled out a collision as a cause of the disaster, and instead
suggested that an explosion had occured in one of the forward
sections, where the submarine's torpedos are kept.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials said the rescuers had not abandoned their
efforts to save the crew. A nuclear submarine normally generates
oxygen and electric power with is reactors, and they have been
turned off since early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian state television reported that the navy would make a
decision on how to try to rescue the crew early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is serious, but according to the command of the
Northern Fleet its rescue teams have enough resources to deal with
the issue without turning to others for help,'' Tass quoted the
fleet's command as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials declined to say how long the Kursk could remain
submerged before it ran out of air for the crew. But Russian naval
command said rescue teams were busy fixing a special rescue diving
bell to the body of Kursk that would help restore the power and the
air supply to the submarine. The gear also can be used to help the
crew escape through rescue hatches.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials also declined to report the depth of the
vessel, though a Norwegian report said the Kursk was submerged in
480 feet of water. This would make it difficult to rescue the crew
by letting them out and allowing them to float up to the surface
because of the enormous water pressure at that depth, although
submarine crews have been known to train for undersea escapes at
even lower depths.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the accident were sketchy and at times contradictory.
As they first disclosed the accident early Monday, Navy officials
emphasized that the submarine was not carrying any nuclear weapons,
had no radiation leaks, and that the crew of the Kursk was in no
immediate danger.
</P>
<P>
   But as the day went on and Russian rescue ships rushed to the
area, the focus of concern shifted to the dire situation of men on
board.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters quoted a Russian news agency as saying that some of the
crew already may have died, though this report was not confirmed by
the military. Other speculation focused on the cause of the
accident _ NTV television reported that the Kursk may have collided
with a foreign submarine shadowing the Russian exercises. Western
and US submarines commonly monitor Russian naval manuvers, leading
to some close calls and even scrapes at sea. In 1993 a Russian and
an American sub collided in the Barents, but both vessels were able
to return to base.
</P>
<P>
   A US Navy spokeswoman said in Washington that US Naval Ship
Loyal, which gathers underwater acoustical data, was about 250
miles away from the Russian submarine when it went down. The ship
was there by coincidence and had nothing to do with the Russian
submarine or subsequent rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, spokesman Rear Admiral Craig Quigley said the
US military has not been asked to assist in the rescue. Other
military officials said that although the US Navy has submarine
rescue vessels, their hatches are compatible only with US-made
submarines and could not be used in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday the Russian navy said it had two submarines
investigating the hull of the stricken vessel for possible signs of
damage. Privately owned NTV television reported that rescuers were
also communicating with the crew by sending coded messages by
banging on the hull.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1995, the Kursk is one of Russia's most modern
submarines and served as the prototype for a Russian sub portrayed
in a 1997 Hollywood action flick, ``Delta Force 2.''
</P>
<P>
   The submarine's main weapons, 24 supersonic SS-N-19 missiles,
are designed to be fired in a salvo at enemy aircraft carrier
groups. Each of the missiles, called Shipwreck by NATO, weighs
seven tons and has a firing range of more than 310 miles. Russian
military officials say the salvo fired from an Oscar-2 is
impossible to evade or shoot down.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the Kursk became a sad symbol of the poor
financing and dilapidated state of the once mighty Northern Fleet,
when its captain, Gennady Lyachin, 45, and officers accepted a
shipment of food aid from the governor of Kursk region in southern
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Home to the huge Russian Northern Fleet, which at its height in
the 1980s had about 150 nuclear submarines, the Kola Peninsula for
decades was a certain target for a massive Western strike in the
event of nuclear war. In recent years, the area has become the site
of mishaps involving the aging fleet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 a Soviet nuclear submarine sank off north Norway,
killing 42 of the 69-man crew. The Komsomolets submarine, the
prototype of the Mike-class sub, now lies rusting, along with its
nuclear torpedoes, on the sea bed of the Barents.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998 a Delta-class nuclear submarine, armed with 12
ballistic missiles, suffered what Western defense and environmental
agencies described as a serious accident involving a fire on board,
causing a brief panic in the Kola Peninsula port of Murmansk.
Russian officials denied an incident took place.
</P>
<P>
   The following September a sailor killed eight of his fellow
crewmates and briefly hijacked a nuclear-powered attack sub. The
sailor, Alexander Kuzminikh, an 18-year-old draftee from St.
Petersburg, threatened to blow up the ship's nuclear-tipped
torpedoes. The drama ended when he took his own life.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have tried to crack down on environmental agencies
trying to disclose the dangers posed by the fleet. Alexander
Nikitin, a former submarine captain, was charged with treason after
he co-authored a report by the Norwegian environmental agency
Bellona report on hazards caused by the Northern Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin won a battle in court when a judge found him not guilty,
but only after he spent two years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
