<SLUG> BC-DIAMOND-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE BEERS AGREES TO PAY HIGHER PRICE FOR CANADIAN DIAMOND COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ De Beers Consolidated Mines, the South African giant
of the global diamond industry, won control of a promising diamond
company in Canada Monday, agreeing to its demands for a higher
price after a seven-week takeover struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The De Beers purchase of Winspear Diamonds Inc. of Vancouver is
the first diamond property the company has bought in Canada. It
reflects the company's effort to broaden its sources of supply away
from the war zones of Africa. Winspear owns a potentially lucrative
underwater diamond deposit at Snap Lake in the Northwest
Territories.
</P>
<P>
   Winspear directors endorsed the sweetened De Beers offer of 5
Canadian dollars a share, or 305 million Canadian dollars ($205
million). Winspear's president and chief executive, Randy Turner,
said the bid ``recognizes the value and potential of the Snap Lake
diamond deposit.''
</P>
<P>
   Winspear's shares rose 18 percent to 4.93 Canadian dollars
($3.32) on the Toronto Stock Exchange after the agreement was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers' first offer of 4.25 Canadian dollars a share, on June
26, was dismissed as hostile by Winspear management. The Canadian
company also said its Snap Lake ore reserves were triple what had
been claimed _ and worth at least 500 million Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Richard Molyneaux, president of De Beers Canada
Inc., noted that no reserve had actually been defined on the Snap
Lake property, which is about 140 miles northeast of Yellowknife,
and that reaching under the lake bed to mine the shallow deposit
would be risky. But 10 days later, De Beers extended the expiration
date on its bid and Winspear dropped two legal actions, opening the
way to friendlier talks.
</P>
<P>
   Snap Lake would be the first underground diamond mine in Canada.
Since De Beers has unmatched experience in this area, and some
urgency about expanding in Canada, there was some expectation that
it would eventually buy Winspear.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers was a bystander in the late 1990s, when the first
diamond mines were discovered in Canada, but it has become more
active since Molyneaux, who has mine experience in South Africa,
became head of the Canadian subsidiary early this year. The company
now markets 35 percent of production from the Ekati mine, also in
the Northwest Territories.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers will inherit a legal battle with a minority partner in
the Snap Lake property. Aber Resources, also of Vancouver, had 33
percent of the claim but, after it did not maintain its share of
expenses, Winspear said that Aber's interest had been reduced to 15
percent. Aber disputed the claim, which is now in the courts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
