<SLUG> BC-CERULEAN-AETHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND FIRM TO BUY CERULEAN TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cerulean Technology Inc., a Marlborough, Mass. company that
makes wireless systems for police and other emergency workers, has
agreed to be acquired by Aether Systems Inc. of Maryland for $150
million.
</P>
<P>
   As a unit of Aether, a wireless data products company, Cerulean
will continue to pursue the ``mobile government'' market. It offers
wireless software for laptops and palm computers for police cars
and 911 services, among other users.
</P>
<P>
   The sale gives privately held Cerulean an alternative to a
public stock offering to finance its growth plans. The company has
received $20 million in venture financing since 1995, from firms
including Atlas, Commonwealth Capital, OneLiberty Ventures, and MF
Private Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Cerulean chief executive Bob Badavas called the deal a ``leap
forward'' for the company. He said the mobile government concept
continues to gain ground, noting, ``When I look at growing the
business, first and foremost is access to capital.''
</P>
<P>
   As hot as the wireless sector is, Cerulean fetched a modest
price relative to some of the billion-dollar deals being struck
recently in the communications realm. Analysts said that's because
the government customer base _ despite providing millions in steady
revenues _ isn't as sexy on Wall Street as private-sector revenue
streams.
</P>
<P>
   Aether, by contrast, has a red-hot stock and a $5.4 billion
market value. The Owings Mills, Md., company went public in October
and has seen its shares soar 791 percent. Its shares fell $6.9375
Monday on the buyout news, to $142.50.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan McCallum, general partner with OneLiberty in Cambridge,
Mass., said the venture firm made five times its investment on the
deal. That's not a knockout by Internet standards, but McCallum
says he likes the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This combination can be one of the winners in wireless data
applications,'' McCallum said. ``I like the idea of Aether stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Aether's strength is in wireless hosting and consulting
services, analysts said. Its software is being used at the
Democratic convention in Los Angeles this week, to put convention
information and news on palm computers. The company reported $16.2
million of revenue for the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Cerulean offers products such as in-vehicle mapping, to help law
enforcement officers quickly arrive at emergency calls. Its
products also lets police tap records remotely. The company has 130
employees and plans to add more in the coming months, Badavas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
