<SLUG> BC-AGILENT-LAYOFFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGILENT TO SHED 450 FULL-TIME WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Agilent Technologies Inc., facing slower sales of its patient
monitoring, ultrasound and cardiology equipment, is firing 450
full-time employees, including 150 in Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly the Medical Products and Instrument Group of
Hewlett-Packard, the Palo Alto, Calif. company was spun out as a
separate company with an initial public offering last November.
Since then, sales of Agilent's health care products have been soft
as U.S. hospitals, which account for 60 percent of the company's
revenue, have curtailed spending.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide layoff announcement Monday comes just days before
Agilent is scheduled to release its third fiscal quarter results on
Thursday. The move affects about one percent of its staff of 42,000
but nine percent of full-time employees of its Healthcare Solutions
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the 450 full-time employees, the company said it will
terminate 200 of its 350 contract workers. Agilent said it will
take a $25 million one-time charge in its fiscal fourth-quarter to
cover expenses related to the firings.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where the Healthcare Solution Group is based,
the dismissal of 150 employees will leave the Andover operation
with 2,050 employees. Seventy contract workers will also lose their
jobs here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The layoffs were across the board in research and development,
marketing, sales, service, manufacturing and administration,'' said
Stephen Rusckowski, senior vice president and general manager of
Agilent's Healthcare Solutions Group.
</P>
<P>
   Under the severance plan, each full-time employee will receive
half of one month's pay for each year worked at both
Hewlett-Packard and Agilent. Employees who agree to leave quickly _
within 10 days of receiving formal notification _ will receive an
additional two month's base pay provided they sign a waiver
agreeing not to bring suit against Agilent.
</P>
<P>
   All employees being dismissed will be notified by 5 p.m.
Tuesday, said Agilent spokeswoman Heidi Wilson. She stressed they
are losing their jobs because of overlapping functions and not for
work performance-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   She noted the U.S. layoffs are expected to be completed by Oct.
31, although the dismissals will take longer in Germany because of
stiffer worker protection laws. The company said the cuts in
Andover, Boblingen, Germany and Qindao, China, will streamline
company operations and save about $80 million a year starting in
fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Rusckowsky said there was one hopeful sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S., there are some signals that health care
reimbursement through Medicare might improve, such as an increase
in some reimbursement payments. And when that happens, our
customers, the hospitals, have said that will help them in their
purchasing efforts,'' said Rusckowski.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2133EDT &QL; 
