<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUB-RESCUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUE MAY BE POSSIBLE, RETIRED US SUB CAPTAIN SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the crew of the crippled Russian submarine can maintain
enough oxygen to survive for a few days, rescue vehicles from the
United States or other nations may be capable of saving them from
their deep inprisonment, a retired US Navy submarine captain said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said Washington had offered to help with the
rescue, but had yet to receive a request from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The US Navy's device for rescuing the crew of a disabled
submarine, called the Deep Submergence Rescue Vehicle, or DSRV, has
never been used in a real emergency, but is designed to deal with
just such an emergency as this, said retired US Navy Captain
William Gaines of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian sub may have an escape pod of its own that could
be sent to the surface, said Robert Brown, an engineer at the Woods
Hole (Mass.) Oceanographic Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all submarines in the world are equipped with escape
hatches that are designed to fit the DSRV's fittings, Gaines said.
Though he was not familiar with the details of this specific
submarine, he said, ``It's very hard to believe that there's any
submarine force in the business that wouldn't make their hatch
cowling compatible'' with the rescue craft.
</P>
<P>
   And if so, he said, ``a rescue at 450 feet is doable. That's not
very deep.'' Russian officials declined to report the depth of the
sub, but reports out of Norway say it is at 480 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue craft and support equipment are designed and its crew
are trained to deploy anywhere in the world within a few days, he
said. It can hold about 10 people at a time and can make multiple
trips with brief stops to recharge its batteries.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the sub is resting on the sea floor at an extreme
angle, it might not be possible to attach the craft, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is at least one other possible rescue method: using an
old-fashioned rescue bell, a system that was used to rescue 33 of
59 crewmembers from the US submarine Squalus, which sank off
Portsmouth, N.H., in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Although some reports have speculated that the crew might be
able to swim or float to the surface by escaping through an hatch
or even through the torpedo tubes, Gaines said, this was highly
unlikely to work at such a depth.
</P>
<P>
   In a so-called free ascent, a person would simply take a big
breath then gradually let the air out during the ascent. Because
the pressure is getting lower as the diver ascends, air expands
quickly and could explode the person's lungs. Such escapes are part
of every submariner's training, Gaines said.
</P>
<P>
   That system might work from a lesser depth, Gaines said, but
ascending from nearly 500 feet would take at least four minutes,
and ``there aren't many people who can hold their breath for four
minutes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the extreme cold of the water in the Barents Sea
could pose a problem, because parts of the submarine are
undoubtedly flooded, and crewmembers could be incapacitated, and
ultimately killed, by the cold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CLINTON-OHIO15-COX     08-14 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OHIO15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OHIOANS CHEER CLINTON DESPITE STATE PARTY'S DECLINE
 &HT;    Attn: Ohio points.
 &HT;    By BILL HERSHEY and MIKE WAGNER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Clinton didn't have to show up Monday to
get a rousing, hooting-and-hollering standing ovation when Andrew
Cuomo invoked the president's name and record at a breakfast
meeting of the Ohio Democratic delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have done an historic job as president,'' said Cuomo,
secretary of housing and urban development. ``He will go down as
one of the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who gave his farewell to the convention Monday, still
gives Ohio Democrats something to cheer about, even if he's not in
the room with them.
</P>
<P>
   He is the first Democrat since Franklin D. Roosevelt to carry
the state in two presidential elections _ Roosevelt did it three
times _ and he ended a string of three Republican presidential
victories in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legacy to Ohio Democrats, however, is more complicated
than his winning record at the top of the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   While he was winning the state twice, Democratic fortunes in
Ohio dipped to one of their all-time lows. Republicans control all
statewide administrative offices, both houses of the state
legislature, Ohio's delegation to the U.S. House and hold both Ohio
U.S. Senate seats.
</P>
<P>
   As Cuomo pointed out, Clinton steered the national Democratic
Party to the political center.
</P>
<P>
   ``What President Clinton did, he brought this Democratic Party
to a place where it can win,'' said Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's success, however, didn't help Ohio Democrats, said
University of Akron political scientist John Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton had the good fortune or bad fortune to become
president in a period of transition in American politics. Clinton
brought the Democrats a middle-class constituency they haven't had
before,'' Green said. ``The bad news is he didn't help state and
local officials capitalize on that constituency. (But) in the long
run, this may bode well for the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Mark Owens, 43, Dayton Municipal Court clerk, said that
during the past eight years Democrats may have put too much
emphasis on winning the national election ``to the neglect of the
grass roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said grass-roots Democrats actually like Clinton, but
those who are liberals and labor union members aren't so enchanted
with the party's move to the center. ``They would like a more
liberal agenda, frankly,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   On the convention floor Monday, as delegates waited to hear from
their president one last time, there were more memories of good
days than of political disappointments in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made it impossible for Republicans to attack
Democrats like they used to, said Enid Goubeaux, Darke County
Democratic chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Bill Clinton came along we were the tax-and-spend
Democrats. Now we are the budget- and deficit-cutting Democrats,''
Goubeaux said. ``But more than any other president, Clinton has
operated under the premise that if one rises, we all rise. If one
falls, we all fall.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
