<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HUNGER A REAL ISSUE TO GORE, ACTIVIST SAYS
 &HT;    By WILLIAM HERSHEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rep. Tony Hall leads by example in his crusade to
eliminate hunger but is always is on the lookout for allies _
particularly allies in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, Ohio's senior Democrat in the U.S. House, said Monday that
Al Gore as president would be sincerely committed to joining in the
anti-hunger battle.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gore has called him three times to ask what can be done
to combat hunger in a country awash in prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance for the first time not only to end hunger but
to wipe it out,'' Hall told Ohio delegates to the Democratic
National Convention at their breakfast meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Later Hall said, ``(Gore) is the only person running for
president who has ever called me about this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, he said, is the only presidential candidate who has said
he wants to put this issue on his White House agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to make a major dent in it,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, 58, has known Gore since the two men served together in
the U.S. House. Their tenure overlapped from 1979 through 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Hall fasted for 22 days to protest a House decision not
to reauthorize the Select Committee on Hunger. Locally, he has
sponsored gleaning programs to gather food to feed the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Without specifically criticizing President Clinton, Hall said he
he was disappointed that not more had been done recently to end
hunger in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no hunger in a time of prosperity,'' Hall
said. While most Americans have plenty to eat, the bottom 3 percent
suffer as much as citizens of Third World nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
