<SLUG> BC-TECH-LINUX2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES THROW WEIGHT BEHIND LINUX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Hoping to vault the Linux operating software
into the desktop market, a group of key companies are expected to
make a series of announcements Tuesday aimed at boosting Linux's
chance of becoming a viable alternative to Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems Inc., Compaq, Hewlett-Packard, and IBM are
among the heavyweights to throw their support behind a new Linux
organization called the Gnome Foundation, whose goal is to spread
the adoption of Linux by creating a comprehensive suite of software
applications to lure consumers away from Microsoft's ubiquitous
Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are set to make their pledges at LinuxWorld, a
gathering of Linux software developers in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual nonentity several years ago, the Linux operating
system has taken the computing world by storm. Because the source
code for Linux is freely available to anyone, it has attracted a
fanatical following among software developers. And because many
versions of Linux are free, it has also amassed a notable share of
the market. Last year, Linux commanded 24 percent of new US sales
of operating systems for server computers, compared with
Microsoft's 38 percent, according to IDC, a technology research
firm in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Linux is hardly a household brand, particularly within
the world of desktops, where it had just 4 percent of new sales
last year. Microsoft, by contrast, commanded 87 percent of that
market.
</P>
<P>
   One major reason why Linux hasn't caught on with consumers is
that it is relatively difficult to use. Gnome (pronounced guh-nome)
is setting out to solve that by promoting a single graphical user
interface developed by Helixcode in Cambridge, Mass. The interface
is supposed to make Linux as easy and intuitive to use as Windows
or or Apple Computer's Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is also set up to attack another problem _ the
scarcity of software applications that can run on Linux. In a coup
for the fledgling foundation, Sun Microsystems is expected to
announce that its StarOffice software package will be integrated
with Helixcode's Gnome user interface, said Miguel de Icaza,
Helixcode's chief technology officer. StarOffice rivals Microsoft's
Office products.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significantly, Sun will incorporate Gnome on its
popular Solaris machines.
</P>
<P>
   In the consumer market, Linux is expected to gain further
momentum from IBM, which is set to announce a line of ThinkPad
laptop computers that will run a Gnome version of Linux.
</P>
<P>
   While Linux continues to attract powerful allies, including Dell
Computer Corp., whose chief executive Michael Dell is scheduled to
deliver the keynote address at LinuxWorld, it remains unclear
whether Linux will ever unseat Microsoft's Windows as the premier
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Linux to be successful, a lot of people have to buy into
it,'' said Al Gillen, research manager at IDC. ``It's not a
no-brainer that this will all fall into place. There's still a lot
of work ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillen estimates that sales of the Linux operating system will
grow by more than 20 percent a year for the next five years, the
same growth rate he projects for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a surge in Linux shipments,'' Gillen said, ``but
we do not expect Linux to overtake Microsoft anytime soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
