A1649 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-14 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: EDITOR DETAINED
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing police formally detained Bei Ling, the U.S.-based
editor of an independent literary journal. The move gives the
authorities 30 days to investigate Bei. It is not yet clear why he
was arrested, though the police have also seized several hundred
copies of his journal, which carries a photo of the exiled
dissident Wang Dan and a poem by a dissident literary critic, Liu
Xiaobo.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: MESSAGE TO ARAFAT
</P>
<P>
   After talks with Yasser Arafat, President Jiang Zemin appeared
to sidestep supporting the Palestinian intention to declare an
independent state on Sept. 13 with or without a peace accord.
Although Arafat's spokesman said Jiang had expressed support for
``any Palestinian decision,'' Jiang said in a statement issued
after the meeting, ``We believe that the Palestinian National
Authority led by Arafat will think it over and declare statehood at
an appropriate time to achieve the best possible results.''
</P>
<P>
   NORTH KOREA: ROCKET SALES
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jong Il told a delegation of South Korean media
representatives that North Korea had been selling rockets to Iran
and Syria, The Korea Herald, an English-language paper, reported.
He told the group that the sales had raised much-needed cash and
could be abandoned only if the United States was willing to
compensate for it. The United States has been demanding that North
Korea abandon its missile development program, whose extent is not
fully known.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA: ANNIVERSARY AMNESTY
</P>
<P>
   Kim Dae-jung announced an amnesty for 30,647 people to mark the
55th anniversary of liberation from Japanese rule. With the
amnesty, an annual event, the president pardons a range of crimes
from parking violations to low-level corruption. He also said he
planned to revise the national security law, long criticized by the
United States and rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL DECLINES UNITY INVITATION
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Kohl, who as chancellor seized the opportunity to reunify
his country, said he would not attend the 10th anniversary unity
celebration in Dresden on Oct. 3. The decision reflected his
awkward position in his Christian Democratic party since he was
implicated in a financial scandal late last year. Kurt Biedenkopf,
the state premier of Saxony, whose capital is Dresden, is an old
rival of Kohl within the party.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PARAGUAY: RACE TOO CLOSE TO CALL
</P>
<P>
   The final result of a vice-presidential election will be
withheld almost two weeks because it is close enough to require a
manual recount, the national election board announced. The
assassination of Vice President Luis Argana early last year
necessitated the election. An opposition candidate, Julio Cesar
Franco, holds a narrow lead over Felix Argana, son of the slain
vice president and nominee of the ruling Colorado Party, which has
held power for more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: INDIAN ROADBLOCK
</P>
<P>
   Micmac Indians blocked New Brunswick's main East Coast road to
protest a federal raid that netted 700 unlicensed lobster traps. A
group in Miramichi interpreted a Supreme Court ruling last year as
allowing 5,200 traps out of season. Rejecting Ottawa's
interpretation that no more than 40 traps were to be set, the clan
set up a burning roadblock and parked 30 vehicles across Highway
11, a busy tourist road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
