<SLUG> BC-DEMS-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON EMERGES AS CANDIDATE IN HER OWN RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hillary Rodham Clinton delivered both a soulful
message _ thanking the American people Monday night for ``your
faith and support in good times and in bad'' _ and a spirited call
to extend the Clinton era by electing Al Gore and Democratic
candidates like her.
</P>
<P>
   It was a remarkable night _ the president saying good-bye to an
adoring party after eight, eventful White House years, Mrs. Clinton
emerging from her own tumultuous tenure as first lady and wronged
wife to propel herself into a high-profile and solo political
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let anyone tell you this election doesn't matter,'' said
Mrs. Clinton, who is locked in a tight race to succeed retiring
Democratic Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York. ``The
stakes in November are the biggest for those who are the littlest
among us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who is struggling to woo women voters, reminded
the audience she had been an advocate for families while working at
the Children's Defense Fund and that the Republicans had borrowed
the group's trademark _ ``leave no child behind'' _ as their own
convention theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made great progress in the last eight years, but we
still have a lot of work to do,'' Mrs. Clinton said, according to
her remarks prepared for delivery. ``Because when a child can't go
to school without fearing guns and violence, that's a child left
behind. When a child's illness is treated too late, or not at all
because a hard-working parent can't afford health insurance, that's
a child left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a child struggles to learn in an overcrowded classroom,
that's a child left behind,'' said the first lady, assuring the
delegates that as president, Al Gore would leave no child behind.
</P>
<P>
   But a brief reference to her own domestic situation seemed the
most heartfelt for Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing that I can say tonight is: Thank
you,'' the first lady said. ``Thank you for giving me the most
extraordinary opportunity to work here at home and around the world
on issues that matter most ot children, families, and women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for your faith and support in good times and in bad.
Thank you, from the bottom of my heart, for the honor and privilege
of a lifetime,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's appearance capped a whirlwind Los Angeles
weekend of campaigning and fund-raising that drew some criticism
for overshadowing Al Gore's show. The first lady denied that was
her intention and was set to leave Los Angeles at 6 a.m. Tuesday
with her husband and daughter, Chelsea, to meet up with the vice
president in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's speech, delivered in the coveted slot just before
Clinton addressed the convention, was deemed a huge opportunity for
her to showcase her candidacy and boost her campaign. She previewed
it Monday in network interviews, appearances before the black and
Hispanic Democratic caucuses, at a Hollywood salute to women in
Congress, and in remarks at a New York delegation breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one choice in this election, whether we're
talking about president, vice president, or senator from New York,
and the right choice is to keep going forward together,'' said the
first lady, who was introduced as ``Senator Hillary Clinton'' to
the Empire State gathering at the Century Plaza Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Applause from the New Yorkers was sustained but not enthusiastic
as Mrs. Clinton thanked the state Democrats for their support and
promised to ``hit the ground running'' as a candidate after the
convention ends.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction probably reflected the anxiety of New York
Democrats who thought they had a winning celebrity candidate in
Mrs. Clinton. After 13 months of intense campaigning, the first
lady is in an unexpecedly tight race with Representative Rick
Lazio, a Long Island Republican who has no national reputation and
entered the contest late, after New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
dropped out because of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton continues to have trouble convincing white,
suburban women in New York that she is not exploiting either her
marital woes or her position as first lady to win a Senate seat.
She has not been able to completely erase her image as New York
carpetbagger, either, even though she spends almost all her time
now at their house in Chappaqua, N.Y., not the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a luncheon honoring Representative Nita Lowey, the New
York Democrat who probably would have run for the Senate if the
first lady had not jumped into the race, Mrs. Clinton said it was
``abolutely critical'' to elect women candidates who will protect
abortion rights and not roll back gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lowey said Mrs. Clinton's needs to draw clear
distinctions with her opponent on abortion and what she called the
Republican Party's ``antiwoman agenda. ``Once women understand the
differences between Hillary Clinton and Rick Lazio, they are going
to vote for Hillary Clinton,'' Lowey said.
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign has been quick to point out that Mrs. Clinton has a
prominent speaking role at the Democratic convention, while Lazio
turned down what he considered a bit part on the GOP program two
weeks ago in Philadelphia. Of course, Mrs. Clinton has friends in
high places in her party.
</P>
<P>
   She was certainly visible for the three days she spent in the
convention city. Friday, she went directly from the airport to an
appearance on Jay Leno's show. Saturday she attended a star-studded
tribute to her husband that was also a $1 million fund-raiser for
her campaign. Sunday, she raised $50,000 at a small luncheon and
then spoke at a large rally sponsored by several Jewish
organizations on the lot of Sony Pictures studio in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who needs support from New York's large Jewish
constituency, praised Gore's selection of Senator Joseph I.
Lieberman of Connecticut, and she noted they had been friends since
she was a student at Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Mrs. Clinton leaves town _ she and the president will
take a short vacation later this week at Lake Placid, N.Y. _ she
will maintain a shadow presence in Los Angeles. Dozens of ``Hillary
ambassadors'' from New York have been organized by her campaign to
raise money, distribute literature, and promote Mrs. Clinton's
candidacy at events here through Thursday. Many supporters were
expected to watch her speech at fund-raising house parties across
New York Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hope, the state chairman, called Mrs. Clinton's
campaigning here ``one more step in her bonding with the New York
Democratic Party.'' Hope said it was appropriate for the first lady
to leave after the convention's opening day, and Mrs. Clinton was
``very comfortable'' with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for this trip to be a transition where the
Clintons are closing one door and opening another door and handing
the baton to the vice president,'' Hope said. ``Mrs. Clinton
understands that and is very supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is giving a very important speech, she is spending time
with the New York delegation, and she is raising money,'' Hope
said. ``Those are three really important things for her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
