<SLUG> BC-TRAFFIC-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNTOWN L.A. TRAFFIC LIGHTENS FOR THE DNC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON KANDEL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a surprise to visitors and residents alike,
traffic was relatively light across the Los Angeles region Monday,
the first working day of the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the open freeways recalled the days of the 1984
Olympics, when fear of mass congestion seemed to keep most of Los
Angeles at home or sent residents away on an extended summer
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The morning commute wasn't bad,'' said Capt. Don Howard of the
city's Department of Transportation. ``I think a lot people are
apprehensive to come downtown and took this week off as a vacation.
But we're on a high level of awareness right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The only delays downtown Monday were caused by thousands of
demonstrators who filled the streets throughout the day, choking
street traffic. Authorities occasionally closed freeway off-ramps
during the demonstrations and blocked off streets, but traffic
resumed shortly after each wave of demonstrators cleared out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffic has been relatively light so far, which is similar
to the '84 Olympics,'' said city DOT spokesman Tom Swire. ``The
only difference is that there is a lot more security here. It's a
whole different ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relative calm, officials were ready for a traffic
onslaught this week near Staples Center, where the convention is
being held through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Los Angeles Police Department, more than 85 city
traffic officers helped direct motorists and monitor the streets,
while more than 100 cameras recorded traffic trends at downtown
intersections. Officials established a mobile command post near the
Los Angeles Coliseum as well, to monitor traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Ridership was down on the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority's subway and rail systems Monday, too, but officials
monitored stations by camera and added security officers in case of
violent protesters, MTA spokesman Gary Wosk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If demonstrators became extremely unruly where the passengers'
safety was jeopardized, we would have to close it down,'' Wosk
said. ``We hope that surveillance cameras and extra security will
be a deterrent to any type of inappropriate behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Above ground, officials began a DNC transportation services plan
that included extra shuttles and buses, and new routes around
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also planned on opening special bus and left-turn
lanes and they regulated green and red lights when traffic backed
up at intersections.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
