<SLUG> BC-ROBBERY-PLEA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN ADMITS NEW YEAR'S EVE ATTEMPTED BANK ROBBERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 23-year-old Johnson County, Kan., woman
admitted Monday in U.S. District Court that she attempted a New
Year's Eve bank robbery that, for some people, competed for public
attention with millennium celebrations and the Y2K vigil.
</P>
<P>
   Pheng Siriboury pleaded guilty to one count of armed bank
robbery and one count of brandishing a firearm. In exchange for her
plea, the government will dismiss one count of taking hostages,
said Robert Streepy, an assistant U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking softly to Judge Carlos Murguia, Siriboury summed up the
failed robbery in simple words: ``I tried to rob the bank, and I
got scared.''
</P>
<P>
   She faces up to 25 years for the attempted bank robbery and a
minimum of seven years for brandishing the gun. She also faces a
fine of up to $250,000 for each count.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plea agreement, Streepy recommended that, for the
bank robbery charge, Siriboury's sentence be at the lower end of
the guidelines. Murguia scheduled sentencing for Oct. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Siriboury admitted in her plea that she entered a Bank of
America in Olathe, Kan., at 4:45 p.m. on Dec. 31, brandished a 9 mm
Ruger pistol and ordered tellers to get on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Siriboury also said that she ordered tellers to fill her blue
duffel bag with money and that as one of the tellers carried the
bag she pointed a gun at his head.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, police and FBI tactical teams surrounded the bank at
175 N. Clairborne Road. They talked with Siriboury throughout the
evening. In all, 11 employees were trapped inside, including five
who hid and waited for a chance to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Siriboury released some of the hostages. Later an employee
disarmed Siriboury after she had placed the loaded gun on a desk.
About 1 a.m. FBI agents entered the bank and arrested her. No one
was injured.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 6 court hearing, defense attorney Michael Harris
described the attempted robbery as an ``act of desperation''
prompted by financial troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said at the time that Siriboury was a native of Laos who
came to the Kansas City area with her parents when she was 2 years
old. She dropped out of Olathe North High School as a sophomore and
ran away from home after arguments with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said Siriboury had run up gambling debts that might have
reached as high as $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   None of the details presented at the January hearing came out in
court Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
