<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1660 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-LIVINGDOTCOM0815-COX     08-14 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGDOTCOM0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet furniture retailer living.com's future near crossroads
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Living.com is still alive, but for how long is
anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors swirling around the Austin online furniture retailer over
the weekend had it closing up shop, filing for bankruptcy, being
acquired or acquiring another company. An announcement about the
future of the company, one of the highest-profile Internet startups
in Austin, could come as early as today, said people familiar with
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   While 2000 will go down as the year that Internet startups
flickered or flamed out _ including drkoop.com, carOrder.com and
garden.com _ this one has been one of the most promising local
ventures. Led by a successful entrepreneur and backed by plenty of
cash from seasoned venture capitalists, living.com had the markings
of success from its beginning two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials did not return phone calls Monday. But at a
company-wide meeting Friday, employees were told to ignore the
rumors while the company explored its options. They were also paid
for their accrued vacation time
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has been hearing things,'' living.com spokesman
Andrew Springate said over the weekend. ``At this point, really
we're just not going to be able to comment publicly on anything.
We're exploring a number of options.''
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1998, living.com got off to an auspicious start.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Andrew Busey was a whiz kid who already had years of
experience in the Internet world and one successful startup, Acuity
Corp., behind him. His father, Jay Busey, joined him, bringing 35
years of experience in the furniture business.
</P>
<P>
   They envisioned an online superstore selling furniture from a
variety of manufacturers in a range of styles and eventually
broadened that to include accessories such as linens and small
appliances. The Internet would allow living.com to offer customers
more and to serve them faster than traditional furniture stores.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it launched its site in July 1999, living.com had
landed $41.5 million venture capital from some of the biggest names
in the business, including Silicon Valley's Benchmark Capital,
whose previous successes included eBay, the auction site. There was
competition from sites such as Furniture.com, but living.com
committed itself to spending heavily to draw consumers to its site,
including millions of dollars for network television ads during
prime-time shows.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock market turned against Internet retailers in
April, the company had to put off hopes of holding an initial
public offering, to seek more private funding and to lay off 50 of
its 350 employees. Still, in an interview in June, Busey sounded
confident that living.com would survive the turmoil that was taking
down other dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, we're in a good business,'' Busey said. ``The
stuff we're selling people want to buy. It's a giant market. On a
marginal basis, we're making money.''
</P>
<P>
   Living.com was already stockpiling its most popular products at
a warehouse in North Carolina. It had attracted a high-caliber
chief executive in Shaun Holliday from Britain's Guinness Ltd.,
and, perhaps most notable, had forged a partnership with e-commerce
leader Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon agreed to take a minority stake in living.com and feature
the startup as its home furnishings store. The price tag for
living.com was steep, though: $145 million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Amazon has agreed to renegotiate deals with its
e-commerce partners and reduce the amount of cash owed to it, but a
spokesman for the company would not say whether living.com was one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, consumers have not warmed to the idea of buying
furniture over the Internet and investors have lost interest in
almost any consumer-oriented Internet company. Furniture.com, for
example, reached the brink of bankruptcy this summer and is facing
multiple complaints from the Better Business Bureau. Established
brick-and-mortar retailers such as Eddie Bauer, Pottery Barn, Ikea
and Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond have expanded their online operations and
lured many customers away from the Internet-only stores.
</P>
<P>
   With about 500,000 monthly visitors in July, living.com was the
fourth most trafficked home decor site on the Internet, according
to PC Data Online Inc., a Reston, Va., research firm. The site was
rated first in customer service among home sites by Gomez Advisors
Inc., which surveys online shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's high overhead has put a strain on its cash
reserves, former employees say, forcing living.com to go back to
its investors for more funding. It landed about $26 million from
Austin Ventures and Benchmark during the second quarter, according
to PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Amazon.com to rescue living.com, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think right now Amazon is so focused on its own issues, its
own execution, its path to profitability, that anything that might
delay that is unlikely to happen,'' said Heath Terry, an analyst at
CS First Boston in San Francisco. ``The only way it would make
sense for Amazon to get involved with anyone ... is if it
accelerated their path to profitability, and that's certainly not
(living.com).''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens to living.com, Busey, 29, will still have a
high profile in Austin. Last year, he helped found NETPAC, a
lobbying group of high-tech executives opposed to Internet sales
taxes, accepted a seat on Lt. Gov. Rick Perry's Advisory Commission
on the Digital Economy, and won one of the inaugural Texas EComm
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Startups are stressful,'' Busey said in June. ``You get the
good and the bad. If it was all smooth sailing, there would be a
lot more startups.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: apark(at)statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
