<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOOD: BRADLEY WON'T BOOST GORE'S CANDIDACY AS MUCH AS MCCAIN CAN
HELP BUSH'S 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bill Bradley sometimes seemed reluctant to
campaign for himself in the Democratic presidential primary season.
During a charity walk through downtown Des Moines last fall, he was
surrounded by hundreds of people and managed to speak to none for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   What campaign effort will the former senator and basketball star
mount now for Al Gore, whom he once called a liar but has since
endorsed? Democrats would like to know, one week after watching
Republican U.S. Sen. John McCain campaign across California with
and for GOP nominee George W. Bush, his former rival.
</P>
<P>
   But, at a time when some Democrats say there is little room for
error if Gore is to overtake Bush, the answer about Bradley is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley went zestfully through one loyalty rite Monday, formally
telling the 359 delegates he won in the primaries to vote for
Gore's nomination at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Al Gore will stand for the things we fought for
in our campaign and he deserves our support,'' he said at a rally
that resembled his campaign events seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley, who endorsed Gore at a Wisconsin rally last month,
will address the convention tonight in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Both actions mirror McCain's pro-Bush output during the GOP
convention. And Bradley has made it clear that his political
differences with Gore were tiny compared to the differences he
would have with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood here, as well as political factors, suggest that
Bradley won't be able to boost Gore's candidacy as much as McCain
can help Bush's _ and that Bradley isn't planning to try anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has yet to work out any details with the Gore staff
about campaigning for the vice president, spokesman Eric Hauser
said. Also, Bradley is planning to go on a pre-election business
tour to promote a book he just wrote about campaign reform, health
care, racial unity and other issues he raised in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be active for Democrats across the country, including
obviously the vice president,'' Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the toss-up Midwestern states, Bradley doesn't carry the
same clout as McCain in speaking out for his party's nominee, said
political scientist Emmett Buell of Denison University in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   During the primaries, Buell said, ``the story was that McCain
was a winner and Bradley wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain beat Bush in Michigan and elsewhere before fading.
Bradley's best showing was 48 percent of the vote in New Hampshire.
He failed to win a single state against Gore, but picked up
delegates, including 11 in Texas, through a proportionate award
system.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and McCain appealed to independent voters, partly with
their call for campaign finance reform. But in terms of public
attention, ``McCain sort of cornered the market on campaign finance
reform,'' Buell said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Democratic Party platform tacitly recognizes that.
Without mentioning Bradley's matching stance on changing the way
elections are financed, it says the party backs McCain's proposals
to limit campaign contributions from special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Where Bradley can help Gore most, Buell said, is in the appeal
to black voters, liberals and others who form the Democratic voting
base. Although Gore captured most of the black vote in the
primaries, Bradley was backed by prominent blacks such as author
Cornel West, filmmaker Spike Lee and basketball legend Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of any limits on Bradley's pull, Buell said, the
Democratic Party will expect Bradley to help Gore catch Bush in the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley supporters say he has already contributed by making Gore
a better campaigner. The vice president has acknowledged as much.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush backers are using Bradley's words to bolster their
contention that Gore is untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we believe that you will tell the truth as a
president if you don't tell the truth as a candidate?'' Bradley
asked Gore in a primary debate. His complaint was that Gore had
fudged on his own congressional voting record while distorting
Bradley's.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about those comments Monday, Bradley told AP, ``I'm not
going to rehash the primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of McCain's delegates booed in Philadelphia when he
released them to vote Bush. There was no such showing of dissent at
Bradley's rally Monday. But Gore campaign manager Bill Daley, who
showed up to thank Bradley for the endorsement, acknowledged that
the delegates are getting over hard feelings about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it is impossible to give the sort of enthusiasm ...
that you felt for Bill Bradley,'' Daley told the delegates, but
unity for Gore is essential.
</P>
<P>
   New York City lawyer Arthur Schiff said he and his fellow
delegates would back Gore without any wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't like the way he (Gore) campaigned but ultimately
they were very close in their beliefs,'' said Schiff, no relation
to Gore's daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
