<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH-CHRISCRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS CORP. CONFIRMS BUYING CHRIS-CRAFT FOR ITS 10 TV STATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ News Corp. confirmed Monday that it had agreed to
acquire Chris-Craft Industries, which owns 10 television stations,
paying about $85 per share using stock and cash.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp., which is controlled by Rupert Murdoch and owns the
Fox network, put the total price at $5.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. will buy Chris-Craft; BHC Communications Inc., a
company controlled by Chris-Craft; and United Television Inc.,
which is controlled by BHC.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. will own 33 stations after the purchase, with two
stations in five cities, including New York and Los Angeles, the
two biggest television markets. But the company said Monday that it
would sell about $650 million worth of its stations to comply with
Federal Communications Commission regulations that prohibit a
company's stations from reaching more than 35 percent of the
nation's television market.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. is paying a premium for Chris-Craft, roughly 18 times
the estimated 1999 cash flow, several analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has assured investors that by selling some
stations and improving cash flow at the remaining stations _
particularly in markets where it will have two stations _ it can
drastically improve overall cash flow so that shareholders will be
paying a far lower multiple, perhaps as little as nine times cash
flow. The recent industry average is about 13 times cash flow,
according to Chris Dixon, a media analyst at PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Several industry experts questioned News Corp.'s figure Monday,
saying that it was unlikely Murdoch could get such cost savings out
of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts agreed that the purchase had value not only
because of the power it would give Murdoch in markets like New
York, where he will own WWOR and WNYW, but also because it will
assure additional outlets for the reruns of Fox shows like
``X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Viacom had been a bidder for Chris-Craft, but lost to News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   One Chris-Craft shareholder, who requested his name not be used,
said he was not happy with the deal because Chris-Craft had
rejected an offer of $82 a share from Viacom in May, when Viacom
shares were trading at $56. Since then, Viacom shares have risen 28
percent. The outlook for News Corp., he said, is far less certain.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. will receive $1.7 billion in cash that is on the
balance sheets of the three companies it's buying. News Corp. will
use it to pay part of the cash component of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. said it will place the TV stations with Fox
Entertainment Group, the entertainment company of which it owns
82.76 percent, in exchange for 122.2 million shares in Fox. That
will increase News Corp.'s stake in Fox to 85.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp.'s acquisition is complex.
</P>
<P>
   Chris-Craft owns 80 percent of the common stock of BHC and 57
percent of United Television's common stock. In each case, News
Corp. is offering cash and preferred shares for the outstanding
stock. In total, News Corp. said it would pay $2.1 billion in cash
and issue about 73 million American depository receipts, each of
which represents four News Corp. shares, for a total of 292 million
preferred shares.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Schwarzman, head of the Media Access Project, which
represents the public at the FCC, said he is opposed to the deal
because of the danger it poses to media diversity both locally and
nationally. He said Monday that he viewed it as ``an arrogant bet
on the outcome of the election.``
</P>
<P>
   He said it was unlikely that the current FCC would approve the
deal, but that a Republican-appointed FCC would be more
sympathetic. A number of the five positions at the FCC are expected
to change in the next administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
