<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stocks Stage Late Rally as Concerns Ease on Rates
</P>
<P>
   Stocks staged a late-day rally as Wall Street bet that the
Federal Reserve would keep interest rates steady next week after
more than a year of tapping on the brakes to slow dynamic economic
growth in the United States.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 148.34 points, or 1.4
percent, to 11,176.14, its highest finish since April 11. The
Nasdaq composite index, weighted with technology shares, rose 60.22
points, or 1.6 percent, to 3,849.69, while the broader Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index climbed 19.72 points, or 1.3 percent, to
1,491.56.
</P>
<P>
   No Action on IRS Complaints
</P>
<P>
   A new federal law that requires the IRS to dismiss workers who
harass taxpayers has led to investigations of 830 complaints _ none
of which have been upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly Loss Widens at Sunbeam
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam, the maker of small appliances, posted a wider
second-quarter loss and said it would sell its Oster barber, beauty
and animal-grooming products business. Shares of Sunbeam fell 16
percent. The loss was Sunbeam's 10th consecutive quarterly loss.
Shares of Sunbeam fell 43.75 cents, to $2.1875. Sunbeam has $2.4
billion in debt, with $1.5 billion of that owed to banks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Little Progress in Verizon Strike
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators made little progress on the ninth day of the
12-state strike against Verizon Communications as unions and the
company debated the worker impact of the recent merger that made
Verizon the nation's largest telecommunications employer.
</P>
<P>
   $5.3 Billion Deal for Chris-Craft
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp. confirmed that it had agreed to acquire
Chris-Craft Industries, which owns 10 TV stations, for about $85 a
share in stock and cash, or $5.3 billion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   De Beers to Buy Canadian Company
</P>
<P>
   De Beers Consolidated Mines, the South African giant of the
global diamond industry, won control of a promising company in
Canada, agreeing to its demands for a higher price after a
seven-week takeover struggle. The Canadian company, Winspear, owns
a potentially lucrative underwater diamond deposit at Snap Lake in
the Northwest Territories.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WPP Group Reports Profit Surge
</P>
<P>
   WPP Group, which will become the world's largest advertising
firm with its acquisition of Young &AMP; Rubicam, reported a surge in
profits and revenue and forecast that the boom in advertising
spending would last through the end of the year, buoyed by the
Olympics and the presidential elections in the United States. Sir
Martin Sorrell, WPP's chief executive, sought to counter concerns
that an expected slowdown in Internet advertising spending would
dent growth prospects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Inventories Rose 0.9 Percent in June
</P>
<P>
   The nation's companies, still trying to keep up with robust
sales, increased inventories in June by a strong 0.9 percent,
government figures showed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toy `R' Us Earnings Fall 75 percent
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us, the largest United States toy chain, said its
second-quarter profit fell 75 percent on declining sales in its
United States stores and a loss at its Internet division. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Cafe au Lait and an Advertisement
</P>
<P>
   A French start-up company has begun placing ads on the surface
of cafe tables, risking the wrath of a society that takes its cafes
very seriously. ``What a horror,'' said a customer, Camille
Mouries, a librarian, pointing to a colorful Siemens ad under the
glass at her table.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
