<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-1STLD-WRITET     08-14 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG COMEBACK WITH A SMALL, UGLY SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Updates with result.) 
By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Teammates Jenny Thompson and Dara Torres renewed
their engaging swimming rivalry Monday night at the Olympic trials,
representing the wonder and suspicion that attends women's swimming
at the elite international level.
</P>
<P>
   The night's competition came in the 100-meter freestyle, which
Thompson won in 54.07 seconds, an American record. Torres was
second in 54.62, so both qualified at that distance for the 2000
Summer Games next month in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Both swimmers had the luxury of knowing they had qualified
earlier in the 100-meter butterfly, which Thompson won over Torres
last Thursday. They will meet again Wednesday in the 50-meter
freestyle and, a month from now, they will challenge Inge de Bruijn
of the Netherlands, who holds world records in all three of the
sprints.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, Thompson, who is 27, and Torres, who is 33,
represent the multitudinous possibility for women in this age of
Olympic professionalism and gender equity fostered by Title IX.
Once, female swimmers had to retire in high school, with no college
scholarships or moneymaking opportunities available to them. Now,
they can keep their careers buoyant on prize money and
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, in particular, is a species as rare as a snail darter _
the female athlete still competing among the world's best as she
nears her mid-30s. She returned to swimming last year after a
seven-year retirement in which she worked as a fashion model and
television personality. She is talented and effervescent and has
overcome a battle with bulimia. Apparently, no swimmer has ever
taken such a long sabbatical, then seriously challenged for an
Olympic medal. She will be the first American swimmer ever to
compete in four Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   But no Olympic sport has been compromised by the use of
performance-enhancing drugs as women's swimming has been, and the
singular aspect of Torres' career that makes it celebratory also
has led to skepticism about her performances that even her coach
acknowledges have clouded any accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Torres has never failed a drug test, and no other swimmer or
coach here has accused her of take banned, performance-enhancing
substances. But after three decades of demonstrated cheating in
this sport involving East German and Chinese athletes, the 1996
Irish Olympic champion Michelle Smith and even American athletes, a
despairing ritual has become the habit in swimming and almost every
other Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   Though testing is conducted at all major meets, no tests have
been approved for substances that athletes are believed to be
widely using such as EPO and human growth hormone. Cheaters have
become sophisticated by using synthetic versions of substances that
exist naturally in the body and are difficult to detect. An EPO
test may be implemented at the Sydney Games, but the International
Olympic Committee's own doctors are saying privately that they fear
the tests will not withstand legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, coaches and athletes concede, passing a drug test
no longer provides convincing evidence of being drug-free. In such
a climate of uncertainty, every remarkable performance becomes
suspicious, and news conferences have become tense give-and-takes
involving skepticism and denial.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Quick, the coach of the American women's Olympic swim
team, said in an interview that he understood the distrust. He was
among the loudest in his skepticism about the Chinese, who have had
some three dozen swimmers test positive in the 1990s, and Smith,
who was banned last year after having contaminated one of her drug
tests with alcohol and having previously tested positive for
androstenedione. He said he blamed the IOC for betraying athletes
who do not take drugs, because, given the current testing
deficiencies, the innocent can no longer prove their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that sport is at the point where every great
performance has a cloud over it,'' said Quick, who coaches both
Thompson and Torres in Palo Alto, Calif. He added: ``I'm bitter
toward the IOC They've allowed cheating to go on far too long. They
are a lot more into sponsorship money and television money. They
are a lot more concerned about many things other than the rights of
fair competition for athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   His athletes are clean, Quick said. Torres is at the cutting
edge of nutrition, strength and flexibility training, he said, and
she works out ravenously. And, he pointed out, she did not come
from nowhere. Before she retired after the 1992 Summer Games,
Torres won two Olympic gold medals on relays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks it's a huge miracle that I'm swimming
faster,'' Torres said. ``This is what I think was in me when I was
younger. The circumstances weren't right. I had an eating problem.
Training is better for me. Nutrition is better for me. Everything
is in a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   She has a supporter in what may seem to an unexpected place.
Phil Whitten, the editor of Swimming World magazine, has been at
the forefront of revealing widespread drug use in swimming. His
magazine first published reports from the files of the East German
police that uncovered the state-sponsored system of cheating in the
sport. But he said he was not suspicious about Torres, given her
history of swimming fast, and the new training techniques.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry between Thompson and Torres here has focused on
their own relationship, which appears respectful if not cordial.
Thompson is from New Hampshire, a taciturn Yankee, though she has
drawn much attention, and some criticism, for posing without a top
on in the current issue of Sports Illustrated magazine. (She said
she posed so that girls could see that it was OK to have a muscular
appearance.) Torres is from Beverly Hills, sunny and gregarious.
They train at different times, Torres saying that workouts became
too intense together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two great athletes desired a lot of individual attention and
somewhat demanded it,'' Quick said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
