<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1669 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BUSHPARDON0815-COX     08-14 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHPARDON0815-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush plans to issue two pardons
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Gov. George W. Bush announced Monday that he
will issue pardons ``for innocence'' to two men, including one
serving a life sentence, because of serious doubts about their
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The inmate sentenced to life in prison, Roy Wayne Criner, 35,
had been convicted by a Montgomery County jury of sexually
assaulting a 16-year-old girl, Deanna Ogg. She had been found
murdered in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with the Board of Pardons and Paroles that credible
new evidence raises substantial doubt about the guilty of Roy
Criner, and that he should receive a pardon,'' Bush said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The board recommended in an 18-0 vote Monday that Criner be
pardoned. New DNA evidence casts doubt on his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The other man the board recommended for a pardon was Ronnie Mark
Gariepy, 41, who is on parole for a sexual assault he was accused
of committing in 1991 against his stepdaughter, then 13, in
Hutchison County.
</P>
<P>
   Gariepy had asked for a pardon after the girlrecanted. Hutchison
County officials, including the district attorney and the sheriff,
recommended that Gariepy's request be granted.
</P>
<P>
   Criner's attorney, Michael Charlton of Houston, said he had not
yet talked to his client but hopes to see him walk free today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased, yes, that it's finally happening now, that I'll
get to see him walk out,'' Charlton said of the pardon. ``I'm
still, I suppose, angry and frustrated that it took so long, that
the Court of Criminal Appeals didn't do it two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Criner, who served 10 years in prison, was in the Montgomery
County Jail on Monday, not his state prison cell. He was in
Montgomery County awaiting a court hearing today on whether he
could be released on bond pending action by the Board of Pardons
and Parole-- .
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the governor's office said the pardon might take
a day or two of paperwork, but Charlton said he hope-- to get
Criner out one way or the other today _ either on bond or a with a
completed pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Criner has always claimed innocence. A state appeals court in
Beaumont reversed his 1990 conviction in 1991. A year later, the
Court of Criminal Appeals reversed the lower court and upheld the
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, DNA tests indicated that the semen found in the dead
girl's body was not Criner's, and the trial judge recommended a new
trial. The Court of Criminal Appeals said no in a 6-3 vote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A more recent DNA test on a cigarette butt found at the crime
scene also did not match Criner's DNA. That helped persuade the
trial judge and the district attorney and sheriff of Montgomery
County to recommend a pardon last month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's office said the governor has issued 18 pardons, including
Criner's and Gariepy's, since taking office in January 1995,
including five known as a ``pardon for innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: bhight(at)statesman.com or 445-3977.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
