<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CONFEDERATE FLAG ISSUE NEEDS HELP OF ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January 1994, when the Confederate flag issue was beginning
to percolate, a group of 20 sportswriters covering Super Bowl
XXVIII in Atlanta decided to be part of a solution, not the
problem. We planned an impromptu, low-key demonstration to protest
the presence of the Confederate flag outside the Georgia Dome.
There was something irksome about having to walk back and forth
with those stars and bars waving overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Our presence was tacit acceptance of the symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   When the color guard marched out for the national anthem, the
group _ men, women, blacks, whites, Jews and gentiles _ left the
press area and stood in a corridor. No words were spoken; the group
listened intently to the anthem. When the final note ended,
everyone returned to the seats and began working. And that was
that. So we thought.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly seven years later, the Confederate flag issue has moved
squarely back into the sports arena. Last week, the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference asked the National Collegiate
Athletic Association to remove the 2002 men's basketball Final Four
and the 2003 women's Final Four from Atlanta if the state does not
remove the Confederate emblem from its flag. The SCLC said that if
the flag was not redesigned by March 2001, it would call for a
boycott of the events.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the NCAA executive committee said it would consider
the request and in another matter voted to play the first- and
second-round men's basketball tournament games in 2002 in South
Carolina, the scene of a hard-nosed, bare-knuckle fight over the
Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wethington, the executive committee chairman and
president of the University of Kentucky, said the committee would
monitor each situation.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's vote last week ran counter to a resolution drawn
up last season by the National Association of Basketball Coaches
calling for first- and second-round games not to be played in South
Carolina unless the Confederate flag was removed from the
Statehouse grounds. ``I wanted to take it down and put it in a
damned museum,'' John Chaney, the Temple coach, said Monday. ``The
NCAA seems to care more about the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The money is substantial: $50 million in lost revenue for
Atlanta for the men's Final Four and $25 million for the women's.
In the same meeting the NCAA committee approved a $325.6 million
budget for fiscal 2000-1. Most of that money comes from
television-rights income and revenue from licensing and royalties.
The primary source of the revenue is men's and women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen, Chaney was asked, if Temple reached the Final
Four in 2002?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the issue is not resolved, if people like the NAACP are
still fighting, damn right: I'd hold hands with them,'' he said.
``It would be difficult to tell the team not to go, but I can tell
my team why I'm not going.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney wants a fight. The battle needs new young blood. The
fight needs students and student-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If college and professional athletes were in lock step, that
flag would come down immediately,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney thinks that is pretty unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bellies are full,'' he said. ``People are serving money
now.''
</P>
<P>
   As for players joining the protest? ``Players are selfish,'' he
said. ``They are loyal to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney called for athletes to adopt the salmon instinct.
``Salmon is the only species that swims upstream,'' he said. ``We
need some people with guts, with the courage to swim upstream, swim
against the tide. Racism and bigotry are here, worse than ever. The
only ones who see it are old people, hard for us to get off the
mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Dempsey, president of the NCAA agrees with Chaney that
racism is still prevalent. He is not certain of the role the NCAA
should play, or could play, to fight racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very long discussions about this,'' Dempsey said in an
interview Monday. ``What is our role and are we putting the
student-athlete in hostile environments?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In South Carolina, the state did what we asked,'' he said in a
reference to removal of the flag from atop the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think it was right to ask for one thing where that
demand was met to then say, `No, well now we want this,''' he
added, commenting on the fact that there is now objection to the
flag being on the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The flags are flying, the games will go on, the coffers will be
filled. But that flag is still the evidence of things unseen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
