<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-HILLARY-CLINTON-A     08-14 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-HILLARY-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON REVELS IN THE ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hillary Rodham Clinton celebrated her husband's
years in office, proclaimed her faith in Al Gore and used the
moment to advance her bid for the Senate Monday night as she
luxuriated in a level of attention unimaginable for a candidate
conducting her first campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Clinton arrived at the convention hall Monday night,
she had been interviewed by all three network anchors for segments
on the evening news, as well as by CNN's Larry King, a feast of
prime-time exposure that left her aides ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in her interviews and in excerpts selected by her staff
for early release, went to considerable lengths to talk up the
credentials of Gore, as she described the nation's health in
glowing terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to stand here at this extraordinary moment _ the
most peaceful, prosperous, promising time in our nation's
history,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But her interest in her own race for Senate in New York was
equally evident, as she suggested that voters who wanted to
continue the policies of her husband should vote not only for Gore
for president, but for her for senator against Rep. Rick Lazio, her
Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it will be up to the people of New York to decide
whether I'll have the privilege of serving them in the United
States Senate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing that I can say tonight is thank
you,'' Clinton said, according to the advance excerpts. ``Thank you
for giving me the most extraordinary opportunity to work here at
home and around the world on the issues that matter most to
children, families and women. Thank you for your faith and support
in good times and in bad. Thank you, from the bottom of my heart,
for the honor and privilege of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   With her speech, Clinton ended one of the more unusual political
trips undertaken by a candidate running for office from New York.
She spent four days in California, and while the purpose of the
trip was to accompany the president for his last convention as a
sitting president, she turned almost every moment into a way to
advance her own campaign for Senate: raising money, giving
interviews to New York newspapers and television stations and,
Monday night, giving the speech and sitting down for interviews
with Peter Jennings, Dan Rather and Tom Brokaw.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Lazio went to Planet Hollywood to mock Clinton's
efforts on Monday afternoon, as his aides discouraged the argument
that it would do her any good in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important is being here in New York,'' Lazio said,
standing in front of a cut-out photo of Sylvester Stallone. ``I
think the most important thing is to be in New York and talk about
New York issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In the prepared remarks of her speech, and in her interviews
with the television anchors, Clinton spoke about her husband, Gore
and issues that, while national in scope, offered a glimpse for a
national audience of what she had been saying in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made great progress in the last eight years, but we
still have a lot of work to do,'' she said. ``Because when a child
can't go to school without fearing guns and violence _ that's a
child left behind. When a child's illness is treated too late _ or
not at all _ because a hard-working parent can't afford health
insurance _ that's a child left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no mention of Lazio in the prepared excerpts of her
remarks. She was more discursive in the interviews she taped during
the day with the network anchors, using a question about why some
voters disliked the Clintons as a way of hitting the issues she has
used to distinguish herself from Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are not people that are ever going to vote for me and
what I stand for,'' she said on CBS. ``You know, they aren't
pro-choice, they are happy to let the gun lobby, you know, decide
what our laws are. They have a very different view of where we
should go when it comes to the future of New York and America.''
</P>
<P>
   The very fact that Clinton agreed to such an extensive schedule
of network interviews was notable. She has until now resisted doing
interviews with the national media, as her aides argued it would
not help _ and might actually hurt _ her effort to transform
herself into a candidate running for office from New York.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, though, Clinton's advisers have concluded that the
key to winning the contest with Lazio is to present the issues in
partisan, Republican-Democratic terms, rather than as a referendum
on Clinton herself.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, they said Monday, they have decided to encourage coverage
of Clinton as she attends what is in effect a four-day celebration
of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Lazio paid only a cursory visit to the Republican
convention, and did not participate in any of its official events. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
