</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: `THE REPLACEMENTS' AN UPBEAT COMEDY ABOUT THE NFL
STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember scab football? Remember the fun? Those golden moments?
The talent? The dignity?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. The players who replaced striking National
Football League players in 1987 did not distinguish themselves and
faded quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Union-busting made lousy football and worse television.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, wash away those dingy old memories and leap into
fantasy with the upbeat new film, ``The Replacements.'' Here,
greedy, boorish union players are replaced during a strike by a
lovable, hungry bunch of lugs from Washington who bond as a unit
while singing ``I Will Survive'' in a jail cell, win the hearts of
a grateful metropolis and beat Dallas to make it to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (Great film idea: the fuzzy, warm side of thugs working for the
Ford Motor Co. who beat Walter Reuther and other union organizers
in 1937.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Replacements'' is ``Rudy'' and ``Major League'' rolled
into one anti-union comedy starring Gene Hackman as the coach, who
has now gone from coaching fresh-faced high schoolers in
``Hoosiers'' to leading a team with a convict in some kind of
modern correctional reform: a scab football work-release program.
``They have been part of something great,'' Hackman says at the
end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the NFL refused to sanction ``The
Replacements.'' Its refusal to grant Warner Brothers a license
forced the filmmakers to create team names, like the Washington
Sentinels, and fashion new uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think it made sense to remind people of our 1987
strike,'' said Greg Aiello, a spokesman for the league. No doubt
the league would not have been elated to see a replacement player
use a pistol to shoot out the windows of the striking quarterback's
expensive foreign car.
</P>
<P>
   The league's refusal to sanction the film did not keep the
Maryland Stadium Authority from seeking the Baltimore Ravens'
go-ahead to let the producers use PsiNet Stadium. ``We OK'd it
because they felt it would be good for the economy of the
community,'' said Kevin Byrne, a spokesman for the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   (Short historical tidbit: during the 1987 strike, Art Modell,
who owned the Cleveland Browns then and now owns the Ravens, said:
``There are no circumstances under which free agency will work.'')
</P>
<P>
   The NFL Players Association contemplated protesting the making
and opening of the film, but thought better of calling attention to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strike was a dark period for players and to make a comedy
out of it is unfair to its importance in the lives of our
players,'' said Doug Allen, the union's assistant executive
director. ``Anyone who cooperated with this movie perpetuates a
revisionist and unfair view of history that is denigrating to NFL
players who were fighting for the right to choose where they
work.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Replacements,'' issues are never discussed. But hiring
strippers to be cheerleaders is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Replacements'' has two familiar faces: Pat Summerall and
John Madden. The Fox announcers called NFL replacement games in
1987 when they worked at CBS, and call the film's games.
</P>
<P>
   Summerall and Madden were contractually bound to call those
real-life strike games, but chose to play along with the charade in
the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked at it as an entertainment,'' said Sandy Montag,
who represents both men. ``They didn't view themselves as an
ex-player and an ex-coach, but as announcers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Summerall seems more himself than Madden, whose
hyperactive style of analysis seems half as fast as usual. When
they see the film, they may be a smidgen surprised to see some of
their game commentary diverted for use as narration for a love
scene. Oops!
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the film, Madden, as Madden, says, ``I never
thought I'd say this, but I'm going to miss those replacement
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I never thought I'd hear him say that either.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Dierdorf, a NFL analyst on CBS and a former St. Louis
Cardinals union rep, said he received an early inquiry about being
in the film. He said, ``But the NFL wasn't behind it and I was of
the opinion that it would not be a smart thing to do.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
TERRIFIC `NEWS' BY OLBERMANN  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports Net's search for a distinctive show is over: the new
Sunday night ``Keith Olbermann Evening News'' is a sophisticated
and occasionally silly vacation from ``SportsCenter'' or the
``National Sports Report.''
</P>
<P>
   The program is Olbermann's innovative circus, where he juggles
essays, field reports and interviews from his retro perch in what
could have been Grantland Rice's office.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he featured a terrific report on the actors' strike
against television commercial production and the decision by Tiger
Woods and Kurt Warner to cross picket lines to star in their own
ads. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
