<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-HILLARY     08-14 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-HILLARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IN LOS ANGELES, MRS. CLINTON IS READY FOR HER CLOSE-UP
</HEADLINE>
  By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The setting for the Clinton rally in Hollywood
Sunday afternoon was more reminiscent of the first couple's
Arkansas past than their New York future. It was the small-town
Main Street created for the Sony Pictures Studio, a place where
Hillary Rodham Clinton slipped somewhat too easily into her old
supporting role as first lady. After more than a year of
establishing her own political identity in New York, with only five
months to go in the Clinton presidency, she was once again doing
her dutiful first lady act, performing a downbeat opening routine
for her highly oratorical husband.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, she gave an earnest, efficient, plain speech to
this Hollywood group before turning over the microphone. True to
form, he made her look like a novice. Still, when the candidate for
the Senate spoke, people listened; as the president spoke, his
audience began to slip away at the edges.
</P>
<P>
   This moment on an ersatz street in the capital of make-believe
underscored one real-life, if largely unspoken, truth about the
couple that have dominated Democratic consciousness for almost a
decade. He has always been the Clinton with the talent to win
people over, to dazzle them with empathy, to make the Hollywood
crowd envy his glamour and open their checkbooks. But this week in
Los Angeles, the party faithful are going through a collective act
of realization. At long last, Hillary has one thing he doesn't _ a
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now comes the time when she has to talk about who she is, what
kind of person she is, what she thinks about issues and what she
would do as senator,'' says Randi Weingarten, president of the
United Federation of Teachers. Like most of Mrs. Clinton's ardent
New York supporters, Weingarten insists that she has full
confidence in the First Lady's abilities to wow her audiences, to
convince them of her solid credentials, her stands on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality is that Mrs. Clinton is but a few days away from
shedding the first lady role more fully than ever and moving into
the territory of the full-time candidate who will have to rely on
her own talents and resources more than on borrowed charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Like Vice President Al Gore, Mrs. Clinton has to move out more
solidly on her own, holding onto the economic progress in the last
eight years while shedding the sleazier stuff that is clearly a
more complicated part of her life than the vice president's.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend in Hollywood rubbing shoulders with movie stars and
moguls raises money at the same time that it revives the questions
about the Clintons' attraction to glitter and old memories of
Monica Lewinsky's hometown. Back home in New York, Mrs. Clinton's
opponent Rick Lazio was making the connection by holding a press
conference at Planet Hollywood in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Also like Vice President Gore, Mrs. Clinton is enjoying the rush
of support coming from his choice of Sen. Joseph Lieberman as his
running mate. A Democratic candidate in New York State usually
needs about 70 percent of the Jewish vote. Before the Lieberman
choice, only about half of the state's Jewish Democrats were
supporting the first lady. ``It's hard to imagine a more helpful
choice for her,'' said Victor Kovner, a New York City Democratic
Party loyalist who sees the choice as a tie-breaker in this race.
``The Jewish community will come home to their party.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lieberman may also activate the Orthodox vote that is
heavily conservative, Mrs. Clinton seems confident that she will
make a net gain from his presence on the New York ballot. All
weekend, she has used the Lieberman name like a protective mantra,
even letting it be known that she agrees with many of the
Connecticut senator's concerns about too much violence in the
entertainment fare churned out by her big donors here.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her assignment to introduce her husband's speech last
night, Mrs. Clinton seemed determined to create a new aura of
independence in Los Angeles _ not only at the fund-raisers but also
in the many media interviews with anchors big-time and small. It
was she, for example, who announced the pullback in the first
couple's interview schedule when it became clear that their efforts
to upstage Gore were turning into a public-relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Her other appearances here were intended to do more than raise
money. She also wanted to make the point that the New York Senate
campaign was a contest on issues _ abortion, the economy, gun
control _ where she fits more easily with the state's majority than
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, then, this convention marks Mrs. Clinton's graduation
from the campaign-worker phase of her life to the politician phase.
That gave a special resonance to the words that she spoke to a
worshipful crowd of Democratic women in a jammed ballroom of the
Wilshire Grand Hotel. ``We are not going back,'' she said. ``we are
not keeping quiet. We are not giving up. We intend to take our
rightful place at the table.'' Mr. Clinton was not in the audience,
but you have to wonder if he checked the transcript. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
