<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-FORD15-COX     08-14 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-FORD15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KEYNOTE SPEAKER HAS A MESSAGE FOR YOUTH
 &HT;    By MELANIE EVERSLEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tuesday night's buzz at the Democratic National
Convention will likely circulate around Rep. Harold Ford, D-Tenn.,
who may graduate to national newsmaker after delivering the keynote
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who at age 30 is the youngest member of Congress, is the
first African American to offer the keynote to a Democratic
convention since Barbara Jordan in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The Memphis legislator said his 15- to 20-minute address will
tout a collection of Gore-Lieberman proposals. He said he will urge
young people to become more involved in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in my generation are involved in non-profits. We're
literally involved with the grass roots. My message is, that's
great, but if you want to get involved on a macro level, you've got
to get involved in electoral politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Issues aside, there are those in Washington who believe Ford
also fulfills the needed glamour factor at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   He is being compared to George P. Bush, the nephew of Republican
presidential nominee George W. Bush who wowed audiences during the
GOP national convention two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the worst they can say about me, I'm flattered,''
Ford said. ``And I wouldn't want to insult George P. He's a good
looking guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford shares some traits with the man who asked him to deliver
the keynote, Al Gore: Both come from Tennessee but attended a
prestigious Washington private school. Both entered Congress in
their 20s, following in the footsteps of their famous fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's father, the late Albert Gore Sr., served seven terms in
the House and three in the Senate, while Ford directly succeeded
his father, Harold Ford Sr., in the House. The elder Ford served 11
terms and was Tennessee's first black congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, in fact, remembers first meeting Gore when he was 10 years
old. Gore was sitting at his family's kitchen table, talking
politics, and Ford remembers being affected by him.
</P>
<P>
   And Ford also shares a trait with Gore's running mate, Sen. Joe
Lieberman. Like the Connecticut senator, he spoke out about
President Clinton's affair with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
In fact, he was ruled out of order on the House floor in 1998 for
saying President Clinton ``lied'' about his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for the Democratic Party said Ford, who first
came to Congress at age 26, has already drawn attention by forming
the Congressional Children's Caucus and pushing for public school
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harold E. Ford Jr. is a rising star of the Democratic Party,''
Gore said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also is a political role model for young African Americans,
said Mildred Lee Taylor, a Memphis school teacher from attending
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor referred to recent studies that show that a growing
number of young African Americans identify with the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not switching over like a lot of young people. He's not
a selfish person. He cares about people,'' said Taylor, 49, who
lives in Ford's congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
