<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLINTON'S VALEDICTORY  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Aug. 14:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional farewell to the party that he reshaped and led
for eight turbulent years, President Clinton Monday night offered a
passionate defense of his record and a dutiful argument that Vice
President Al Gore is ready to take over. For fans of presidential
oratory, the speech was a reminder of Clinton's skills as an
advocate who can both speak from the heart and argue a case through
a series of logical points. The enthusiastic reception from the
Democrats at the convention was testimony to their mixed feelings _
an eagerness to move beyond Clinton and his outsized personal
problems as well as genuine gratitude for his success in
modernizing Democratic Party ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's valedictory appearance, on the first day of the
convention, was understandably aimed at letting the Democrats dwell
just a little on the past, before sending Gore and his running
mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, into an extremely tough campaign.
Clinton paid tribute to Gore's steadiness under pressure and his
knowledge of government in arguing that the vice president deserved
considerable credit for the successes of the last eight years. He
also portrayed his vice president as the most future-oriented
politician in the country in regard to science, technology and
education issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dealt with his personal scandals by not mentioning them.
He apparently decided that this was not going to be a moment of
contrition or one when the headline writers and Republicans would
have yet another mea culpa with which to work. Instead he dwelt on
his gratitude to the party and to the voters for letting him serve
in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in recent interviews, Clinton also made it clear that
Republican convention oratory about an era of accidental and
purposeless prosperity had nettled him mightily. In response to
recent sallies from the GOP nominee, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
Clinton pointed out that when the administration enacted its
economic strategy of trying to close the budget deficit, even by
raising taxes on the richest Americans, the Republican leadership
in Congress voted uniformly against it and predicted it would bring
about economic ruin. Indeed, as the Democrats have tirelessly
pointed out, it was Gore who supplied the tie-breaking vote for the
program in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The president's tribute to Lieberman was a reflection of the
connection the new Democratic ticket has with his own political
career. Clinton is the one who chose Gore, who had run an
embarrassing presidential campaign in 1988, to be his vice
president. He noted that he had known the Connecticut senator since
working for his first state legislative campaign while a law
student 30 years ago. And when Clinton reminded the audience of his
own personal journey to the White House from a tough childhood in a
broken home, he seemed to be trying to contrast himself with the
pampered upbringing of Governor Bush, who is seen by many Americans
as a man they can empathize with more than Gore. The problem with
Clinton's personal reflections, of course, was that Gore comes from
a privileged background.
</P>
<P>
   One of the strongest flashes of irritation from Clinton came
when he defended his administration's record on military and
preparedness issues. At the Philadelphia convention the Republicans
charged relentlessly that American defenses had declined in the
last eight years, ignoring the fact that military budgets had
started to go down under President Bush and have gone back up in
the last several years. Clinton even suggested that the Republicans
were inviting trouble from overseas with their accusations. Any
foreign country inspired by Republican assertions to think that the
United States is not ready to defend itself, he said, would be
making a grave mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the last convention of any two-term president can be
called the end of an era. But there is no doubt that this farewell
will be remembered by every living Democrat as an unforgettable
time. In party terms, Clinton's great accomplishment was to remodel
the liberal policies that let the Democrats dominate midcentury
politics but that became a straitjacket when Ronald Reagan arrived
on the scene. There will always be the sadness that the Clinton
record will forever be blotted because his leadership gifts were
offset by a self-destructive streak at the center of his
personality. For all that, Clinton will go into party history as
the only politician of his decade with a personal magnetism and
communicative skills to match those of Reagan and Clinton's own
boyhood idol, John F. Kennedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
