<HEADLINE>
FOR THE BLUE DOGS, CONVENTION PROVIDES A NIGHT TO HOWL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ala., Texas., Fla., N.C., Calif., Mich)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 Washington Bureau   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The congressional Blue Dogs and hundreds of their
allies were penned up inside an oceanfront amusement park on famous
Santa Monica pier Sunday night, hounded by protesters trying to
disrupt events at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But the top dogs in the coalition of Democratic moderates and
conservatives wouldn't turn tail. ``It's the First Amendment,''
said Rep. Norman Sisisky, D-Va., as he surveyed the mob trying to
block the entrance to Pacific Park. ``They've got the right.''
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the Blue Dogs could consider it a success that
their celebration was significant enough to attract demonstrators
on the eve of the convention. Started as a small band of mainly
Southern Democrats who felt abandoned by the leadership of their
party, the coalition has grown in stature and is trying to flex its
muscle both at the convention and in the upcoming congressional
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be a high-profile part of the activities here in
Los Angeles,'' said Rep. Bud Cramer, D-Ala., co-chairman of the
Blue Dogs, a group that drew its name from a combination of the old
yellow-dog Democrat label and the famous blue-dog artwork of New
Orleans painter George Rodrique.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 members of the Blue Dog coalition consider themselves the
conservative conscience of the House Democratic caucus, pushing for
sound spending practices and working with Republicans when they
feel the GOP has a worthy idea. The group helped broker the deal
that led to the overhaul of the welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We help bring moderation to both extremes of the party and we
have been successful,'' said Rep. Chris John, D-La., who serves as
co-chairman with Cramer.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them differ from their more liberal Democratic
colleagues in another important respect _ they are supporters of
gun rights, a position brought home by the fact that the National
Rifle Association was among the corporate sponsors of Sunday's
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``On balance, the Second Amendment is pretty sacred in Texas,''
said Rep. Charles Stenholm, a Lone Star lawmaker and early Blue
Dog, making no apologies for the NRA support.
</P>
<P>
   The group's major emphasis at the moment is helping elect
Democrats to Congress this November to recapture the House. After a
close review of Democratic challengers, the group has endorsed and
is financially supporting 13 candidates in Florida, North Carolina,
Texas, Alabama, Michigan and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But their intentions are not totally pure. Leaders of the Blue
Dogs know that if the Democrats regain control, it will be by a
very slim margin and the coalition would then control a decisive
30-vote bloc, making them power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wake up on November 8 and we have a majority, we are
going to be in play,'' said Rep. John.
</P>
<P>
   Though they sometimes give Democratic leaders a headache, the
Blue Dogs have friends in high places. ``We have to have their help
to win the majority,'' said Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, head of the
House Democratic Caucus and a guest at the party.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's party was an illustration of how far the coalition has
come. The members distributed more than 5,000 tickets to the
extravaganza and it appeared a large percentage of them were used
as party goers packed a stretch of the pier, playing carnival
games, enjoying the rides and dancing to big-name entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the night was obvious from the blue dogs given as
game prizes to the blue decorations to the pitchers of the Blue Dog
Special, a blue-tinged rum drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to howl tonight,'' said Cramer as he took in the
party.
</P>
<P>
   But protesters outside were howling as well about corporate
America, heckling guests as they arrived, tossing coins at them and
jostling with police officers clad in riot gear and mounted police
who used their horses to try to keep the entrance open. Overhead
floated a balloon carrying the message, ``People before profits.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the lawmakers and their guests took the
protests in stride until late in the evening when police
effectively were forced to close the entrance for a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from South Louisiana and we don't have protests like that
down there,'' said John. ``It was a little scary when we walked up
but they were exercising their freedom of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
