<SLUG> BC-NY-TERROR-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALGERIAN ARRAIGNED IN EXPLOSIVES SMUGGLING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SULLIVAN  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mokhtar Haouari, an Algerian charged with helping a
group trying to smuggle explosives into the United States, was
arraigned in Federal District Court in Manhattan Monday afternoon
after arriving from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari, who pleaded not guilty at the arraignment, was arrested
by Canadian police officers in Montreal on Jan. 10 after he was
indicted by a grand jury in New York. After being held in Canada
for several months, Haouari waived extradition proceedings and
agreed to come to the United States to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have charged that Haouari helped another Algerian
citizen, Ahmed Ressam, who has been charged with trying to smuggle
explosives over the Canadian border in the trunk of his car. On
Dec. 14, 1999, Ressam was stopped by customs agents as he crossed
the border by ferry at Port Angeles, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, customs agents found bags of
explosives hidden in the spare tire well of Ressam's car.
Prosecutors said Ressam tried to run from the customs agents, but
they caught him after a brief chase.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari has been charged with being a link between Ressam and
another man charged in the case, Abdel Ghani Meskini. According to
papers filed by prosecutors, electronic surveillance of Meskini's
telephone in New York ``implicates Haouari and Meskini in a plot to
have Meskini meet and assist Ressam in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the papers, in another conversation Meskini said
that both ``Meskini and Mokhtar knew Ressam, that Ressam was part
of a well-organized group and that Mokhtar was part of the same
`network.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the indictment, prosecutors charged that Haouari asked
Meskini to travel to Seattle to help Ressam. Prosecutors also
charged that Haouari provided false identification documents for
members and associates of a terrorist group. Among the documents
listed by prosecutors were United States immigration identification
cards and French and Canadian passports.
</P>
<P>
   At hearings in Canada last July, Haouari's lawyer said his
client wanted to face the charges as soon as possible. The lawyer
said they were confident there was not enough proof to find his
client guilty. At Monday's appearance in Manhattan, Haouari's
lawyer reserved the right to apply for bail later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
