<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS PITCHING HAS AN OFF NIGHT AND GIANTS WIN IN A ROUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets pitchers had worked 304 innings
since the last time an opponent exploded like the San Francisco
Giants did Monday night. Then the Giants did it two innings in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring five runs in the sixth inning and six runs in the
seventh, the Giants stomped on the Mets, 11-1, bringing an emphatic
end to a series that began with three Mets victories. As helpless
as the Mets were on the mound, they were just as anemic at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Giants right-hander Russ Ortiz was not sharp, throwing 57 balls
to 58 strikes, but he flustered the Mets over seven shutout
innings, allowing only one hit despite six walks. Ortiz was one of
five Giants with multiple runs batted in, and left fielder Barry
Bonds _ 1 for 11 in the series before Monday night _ went 4 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz's first major league start came at Shea Stadium in Aug.
1998, and he has had great success against the Mets ever since. In
five career starts against the Mets, Ortiz is 4-0 with a 2.83
earned run average over 35 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who had won 16 of their last 19 games before Monday
night, dropped to two and a half games behind the Atlanta Braves in
the National League East. Rick Reed (7-3), who had started only in
victories since coming off the disabled list in mid-July, allowed
eight hits and five runs in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The fateful sixth inning was the highest-scoring inning by a
Mets opponent since July 4, when the long-lost Bobby M. Jones
unraveled against the Florida Marlins. Reed matched Ortiz for
shutout innings through the fifth, but a pitcher's duel quickly
became a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   After Bill Mueller and Bonds singled to lead off the inning, a
Reed fastball tailed too far inside on Jeff Kent, and it hit him,
loading the bases. J.T. Snow drove a sinking liner to center, where
Jay Payton raced in and caught it on a sprint. Payton's momentum
carried him toward the right field foul line, and he threw across
his body to try to catch Mueller tagging up. But the throw was high
and got away from Mike Piazza, the run scored and a runner
advanced, and then a torrent of hits came.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis Burks singled through the left side of the infield for a
run, and Rich Aurilia singled to the same place, also for a run.
Bobby Estalella doubled to the left field corner, and two more runs
came in. It was 5-0, Giants, and for the Mets, the worst was yet to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Cook relieved Reed to start the seventh and gave up the
most runs a Met reliever has allowed in a single game all year.
Cook faced eight batters and retired only one. He walked two and
allowed five hits and six runs. The final two came on a single by
Ortiz, who had fanned three times against Reed.
</P>
<P>
   After the first big inning, Ortiz was still working on a
no-hitter. But Mike Bordick led off the sixth with a single through
the left side of the infield, and stole second as pinch-hitter
Darryl Hamilton struck out. Benny Agbayani struck out looking, but
Derek Bell walked and Edgardo Alfonzo got ahead in the count, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   But Alfonzo swung under a fastball and sent it high in the air
above center field. He bent down and stared at the ground for a
moment, frustrated at the missed opportunity, and trotted toward
first as center fielder Marvin Benard caught it for the
inning-ending out.
</P>
<P>
   That continued a disturbing pattern for the Mets against Ortiz.
They had at least one baserunner in each of the first four innings
but had nothing to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz walked two of the first three hitters he faced, but Piazza
bounced to shortstop to start an inning-ending double play. In the
second, after Robin Ventura drew a leadoff walk, the second baseman
Kent speared Payton's one-out liner, throwing to first to double
off Ventura and end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani walked with two outs in the third and was caught
stealing. Alfonzo walked with one out in the fourth, but Piazza
grounded to Ortiz, who threw to second to start another
inning-ending double play.
</P>
</TEXT>
