<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-FLOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISING WATERS, AND SINKING HEARTS, IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BYRAM TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ Elena Lazzaro and her husband were the
first to build a home on their block of River Road, on the banks of
the Musconetcong River, 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Lazzaro was one of the last in her now well-developed
neighborhood to pack up a few precious belongings and abandon her
home, after police and fire officials went through the neighborhood
with bullhorns, warning residents that the river waters were
continuing to rise two days after a relentless storm flooded Byram
Township and many other towns in northwestern New Jersey, dropping
14 inches of rain in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to put a chair out here and sit and watch the river,''
said Lazzaro, who has been a widow for two years. The river, once
ankle-deep, was a raging torrent Monday, about six feet deep, and
was beginning to engulf her property.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lakes and the rivers are what make this area so
beautiful,'' said Lazzaro, standing in the steady drizzle. ``But I
guess it's also what's making it so dangerous now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as some families were allowed to return to their homes
Monday after Saturday's storm, rescue officials evacuated about 300
more families from Byram Township, Sparta and other nearby towns,
including a day camp here with 800 children, because about six dams
in the complex regional system of waterways had given way, swelling
rivers and streams that crisscross the lush terrain.
</P>
<P>
   A storm that dropped four more inches of rain Monday, and the
forecast of more showers for Tuesday, cast a broad swath of
northwestern New Jersey into soggy despair, almost a year after
Tropical Storm Floyd struck central New Jersey and left
record-setting flooding in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Gov. Christie Whitman put Morris and Sussex Counties
under a state of emergency, allowing the state to order evacuations
and activate New Jersey National Guard units. Parts of Warren
County were also inundated.
</P>
<P>
   The state has asked for the affected areas to be designated
federal disaster areas, which would make homeowners eligible for
aid. The governor said that designation was important because the
state's disaster fund has been depleted since last fall's tropical
storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point there's not a lot of state money available,''
she said, ``because we're still providing money for victims of
Hurricane Floyd.''
</P>
<P>
   No serious injuries have been reported since Saturday's
downpour, although the torrents damaged hundreds of homes,
destroyed water mains in Newton and collapsed dozens of bridges,
roads and dams.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Trenton Monday morning, Whitman, who
toured the flooded areas by helicopter and on the ground, said the
worst damage was confined to a relatively small area. ``The
fascinating thing about it,'' she said, ``is how really
concentrated it was. You're up there and you have one town that got
14.2 inches of rain, and Andover, the next town over, got an inch
and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said the hard-hit areas were reeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that there are lots of businesses that
have been impacted,'' she said. ``Some homes were shifted off of
their foundations by the pressure of rocks, logs and mud up against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimated that the storm caused $160 million
worth of damage, but said it was too early for a final tally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the waters recede in all those lakes and rivers, we
won't know the full extent of what we're dealing with,'' said Eskil
(Skip) Danielson, emergency management coordinator for Sussex
County.
</P>
<P>
   Many people had tales of near-misses with the fast-moving
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Vogel-Short, who lives with her husband near Lake
Hopatcong in a house that was a summer home for his family for 44
years, said they called 911 on Saturday to ask for help when the
lake waters were lapping at their home and threatening to topple
their propane tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us that they had too many calls and they couldn't
come and help unless someone was dying,'' Vogel-Short said.
</P>
<P>
   She said a neighbor's rock wall was directing the flood waters
into her yard. When that neighbor would not allow the wall to be
breached, other neighbors helped dig a trench to divert the water,
and then built a stone barrier around the house and tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like we were colonists or settlers,'' Vogel-Short said.
``We dug with our bare hands.'' She wound up with four feet of
water in the basement and, like many of her neighbors, had no flood
insurance to pay for the cleanup. ``We were afraid we were going to
lose our homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those evacuated Monday were 800 children at the Jefferson
Lake day camp on Waterloo Road here. Officials said they feared
that eroding dams would cause the Musconetcong River to overflow.
The river, which flows out of Sussex County and borders Morris,
Hunterdon and Warren Counties, was rising a foot an hour Monday,
and crested in midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When emergency workers ordered everyone in the area to leave,
camp officials quickly arranged to have the children bused to a
middle school near the Byram Township municipal building. Late in
the afternoon, with military precision, camp counselors and
directors were getting the children, who did not seem the worse for
wear, back on buses to return them home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't flooded,'' said Ira Fish, the owner of the camp.
``The problem was the road nearby. If that had flooded, we'd have
had to sleep everybody at the camp. We've been here 43 years, and
this has never happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of the region, residents returned to their homes
Monday. Ron Earl, 66, stood on his son Randy's property on Glen
View Avenue in Sparta, still staring in disbelief at the way the
storm had scraped the property like a giant bulldozer, erasing its
well-tended lawns, two fish-stocked ponds and a gazebo. What
remained was a muddy field, with huge trees upturned, and remnants
of a stone wall that Randy and his grandfather had built over
several decades.
</P>
<P>
   Earl, who was the football coach at Sparta High School until he
retired a few years ago, said that in the late afternoon on
Saturday, it appeared that the flood waters would overtake his
son's house. But before that happened, falling trees created a sort
of dam, diverting the waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll never be able to rebuild it to the way it was,'' said
Earl, who lives across the street from his son and spent the
weekend hauling debris, worrying about how far the river would rise
and marveling at flooding he had never seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize the power of water,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
