<SLUG> BC-CVN-MAIN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, IN CONVENTION FAREWELL, DECLARES GORE HIS HEIR
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Clinton, occupying political center
stage for perhaps the last time, Monday night declared Al Gore the
rightful heir to a ``more confident, hopeful and just'' America.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton basked in a curtain call unseen at a Democratic National
Convention in more than half a century. He is the first Democrat
since Franklin Roosevelt to serve two terms as president.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the personal shortcomings that tainted his presidency,
Clinton electrified the nearly 5,000 delegates who jammed the
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton led the charge in that effort with a television speech _
delivered most after prime time in the East _ that sought to rebut
the claims made by Republican nominee George W. Bush that his
administration had ``coasted'' through the unprecedented economic
prosperity of the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who say the progress of the last eight years was an
accident, that we just coasted along, let's be clear: America's
success was not a matter of chance, it was a matter of choice,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is more confident, hopeful and just, more secure and
free, because we offered a vision and worked together to achieve
it,'' he said. ``My fellow Americans, tonight we can say with
confidence: We built our bridge to the 21st century. We crossed it
together. And we're not going back.''
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Clinton, a candidate for the U.S. Senate in
New York, introduced her husband and, like him, promoted Gore and
his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   She did not mention Clinton's impeachment following his
extramarital affair with a former White House intern, but did thank
the delegates for their support ``in good times and in bad'' during
her husband's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   And introduced to the strains of ``New York, New York,'' she
reminded the delegates of her Senate race as she vowed to continue
the work she began years ago with the Children's Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe it takes a village,'' she said, referring to
her book that was ridiculed at the 1992 GOP convention for its
promotion of children's rights. ``And it certainly takes Al Gore
and Joseph Lieberman. They have what it takes. And they'll do what
it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   In defending his own political legacy, Clinton also promoted his
vice president's candidacy. He called Gore ``a profoundly good
man'' and said he was ``always there'' as he faced issues of war
and peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anybody else I've ever known in public life, Al Gore
understands the future and how sweeping changes can affect
Americans' daily lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Gore and Lieberman will ``keep our prosperity
going'' in contrast to a Republican administration that would
``spend every dime of our projected surplus'' on tax cuts rather
than on education, Medicare and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore has consistently trailed Bush in public opinion
polls, the Democratic convention opened with unusually high
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's evening session began with a brief video clip of
President John F. Kennedy, nominated here in 1960. As his
distinctive voice echoed eerily through the Staples Center, a
sustained cheer erupted from the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Gov. Gray Davis of California recalled how the
Democrats had ``passed the torch'' to a new generation in 1960 and
that it was now time to ``pass that flame'' to Gore, the party's
first presidential nominee of the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's program was largely designed as a passing of the torch
from Clinton to Gore, who _ not by accident _ was campaigning in
Independence, Mo., the home of Harry Truman, who also had to labor
to escape the shadow of a larger-than-life president, Franklin
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said ``one of the best decisions of my life'' was
``asking Al Gore to be my partner'' in 1992. He reminded the
delegates that his administration's economic program passed
Congress with Gore's tie-breaking vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton grew nostalgic toward the end of his address, noting how
America had given him a chance ``to live my dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tried to give you a better chance to live yours,'' he
added. ``Now, with hair grayer and wrinkles deeper, but with the
same optimism and hope I brought to the work I love eight years
ago, my heart is filled with gratitude. My fellow Americans, the
future of our country is in your hands. You must think hard, feel
deeply, and choose wisely. Remember, keep putting people first.
Keep building those bridges. And don't stop thinking about
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   While the Republican convention two weeks ago in Philadelphia
was noted for its political harmony, the Democratic convention
began with some jarring notes in the ``Prosperity and Progress''
theme:
</P>
<P>
   _ Monday night's finale following Clinton's speech featured the
Broadway cast of ``The Music Man'' performing ``76 Trombones.'' The
play is about a slick traveling salesman who pretends to be a band
leader in order to con working families to buy musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   _ One of the party luminaries, Rep. Loretta Sanchez of
California, declined an opportunity to address the convention on
opening night after bowing to pressure and moving a fund-raiser
from the Playboy Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hundreds of environmental activists tied up the intersections
around the Staples Center with a protest of the Gore family's long
ties to Occidental Petroleum Corp. A trust fund established for
Gore's mother by his late father includes between $500,000 and $1
million worth of Occidental stock.
</P>
<P>
   _ Catholic Cardinal Roger Mahoney, in his invocation, took issue
with the Democratic Party's platform support for abortion rights.
``In you, oh God, we trust ... that you will keep us ever committed
to protect the life and well-being of all people, but especially
unborn children.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The evening ``talk show'' format featuring average Americans
who had benefited from the economic prosperity of the last eight
years developed some technical difficulties, and the attention of
many delegates in the convention hall drifted away. Most of the
television networks skipped it altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But the enthusiasm in the convention hall returned when former
President Jimmy Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, were introduced
before the airing a video tribute to the only living Democratic
ex-president, and one who is widely admired for his personal
character.
</P>
<P>
   The tribute to Carter was Gore's idea after viewing tributes to
former GOP presidents at the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   And a series of women speakers sent scores of demonstrators to
the floor, waving placards that read: ``When Women Vote, Women
Win.'' The speakers included six women from the U.S. Senate: Dianne
Feinstein and Barbara Boxer of California, Barbara Mikulski of
Maryland, Patty Murray of Washington, Mary Landrieu of Louisiana
and Blanche Lincoln of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The prominent role of women Monday night underscored the
importance of women voters in this election. Gore and Bush
strategists view them as crucial and thus far, Bush is running
close to Gore among women, wiping out the gender gap that helped
elect Clinton in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
