<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-PROTESTS-1STLD-WR     08-14 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-PROTESTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE LARGELY PREVAILS IN A LONG DAY OF CONFRONTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Updates and subs lede and 10th graf, That was ..., to correct
number of arrested to nine, sted 10.) 
By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The long-awaited dance between protesters and the
police began here in earnest Monday, with speeches, rallies,
singing, marches and a couple of tense standoffs as demonstrators
tried to block traffic downtown near the Staples Center and
officers, present in overwhlming numbers, arrested nine people for
refusing to move.
</P>
<P>
   Under hot, smoggy skies, knots of hundreds of marchers plied
their way back and forth between the site of the Democratic
National Convention and Pershing Square, a broad public plaza about
a dozen blocks away, protesting everything from Vice President Al
Gore's investments in an oil company that plans to drill near a
Colombian Indian reserve to the influence of the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The official theme of the day was ``Human Need, Not Corporate
Greed,'' but the placards, banners, puppets and armbands that
swirled through the usually sterile streets of downtown Los Angeles
embraced a dizzying range of causes and concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is Not a Commodity,'' read one banner. Another said, ``Al
Gore (EQ) Corporate Eichmann.'' Some demonstrators wore navy blue
T-shirts with the familiar logotype of the Gap clothing stores,
spelling out a rhyming vulgarism for excrement. Perhaps the
bleakest placard: ``All Government is Bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The day was one of mostly placid if wary encounters between
marchers and the police, who seemed to materialize from everywhere
when needed.
</P>
<P>
   This evening, a protest concert by the hip-hop metal band ``Rage
Against the Machine'' began peacefully just outside the Staples
Center in a fenced-off spot from which the authorities had
initially tried to bar demonstrators until a federal judge
intervened. City officials and the police had wor- ried that the
concert posed the most complex challenge of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The morning began with a rally in Pershing Square featuring the
singer Bonnie Raitt to protest Gore's family holdings in the
Occidental Petroleum Corp., which has rights to conduct exploratory
drilling a few miles outside the legal boundaries of the U'wa
Indian reserve in Colombia. Environmental groups have urged Gore to
divest his family of the stock, worth some $500,000, which had been
owned by his father Albert Gore Sr., who died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, the only drug coming out of Colombia
is oil,'' said Raitt, who with John Densmore, the former drummer
for the rock band The Doors, sang the old Buffalo Springfield song,
``For What It's Worth.'' The crowd then headed to the Staples
Center, where it greeted some early arriving delegates, including
Keiffer J. Mitchell Jr., a city councilman from Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in early just to walk around and see what it's all
about,'' Mitchell said. ``The Democratic Party and the Republican
Party may not address everything, but this shows that here in the
United States of America we can speak out on any issue without fear
of retaliation or harm.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not how some protesters viewed reality just a few
moments later, after they turned back toward Pershing Square and
sought to block traffic at the intersection of Sixth and Flower
streets. After ignoring bullhorn warnings to disperse, nine
demonstrators were arrested and taken jail, said a police
spokesman, Officer Mario Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   The police drove the remaining demonstrators back to Pershing
Square, where perhaps 2,000 people were gathered and still more
rallies were scheduled. Just as the group reached the southwestern
corner of the square, there was another tense few minutes as
demonstrators again stood in the middle of an intersection
adjoining the grand old Biltmore Hotel, where top Democrats and
aides to Gore were staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been declared an unlawful assembly,'' the police
commander on the scene warned through a loudspeaker, his voice
barely audible over the din of police helicopters circling
overhead, as officers brandished tear-gas guns. ``We need to clear
the intersection.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, demonstrators, with dueling bullhorns of their own,
answered back with shouted passages from the Constitution and the
First Amendment, including ``the right of the people to peacefully
assemble shall not be abridged.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the protesters retreated and traffic began flowing
again.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Villa, a 25-year-old pre-school teacher from Berkeley,
who came for the protests, looked at the police in disgust. ``These
guys are a brutal force to the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the police seemed bent on restraint, even though they
brooked no interference, pushing back journalists along with
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Even as much of life went on as normal here, the storefronts of
the adjoining jewelry district were deserted and shuttered with
metal grates backed by plywood, and office workers were forced to
take long routes around the block to get back to their desks.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of traffic jams proved a boon for at least one band of
entrepreneurs, the riders of ABC Bike Cabs of Santa Barbara, who
brought a fleet of bicycle surreys to town and drove up and down
downtown streets looking for fares.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here for the duration,'' said one driver, Alt Olmos, as
he swigged from a water-bottle in the midday sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
