u i BC-RUSSIA-TRAPPED-SAILOR     08-14 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TRAPPED-SAILORS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANTIC RUSSIAN EFFORT TO RESCUE CREW OF SUB
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for rewriting, updating thruout; NEW headline; CHANGES
byline) 
 (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By SABRINA TAVERNISE with CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A Russian submarine plunged to the seabed in the
Barents Sea on Sunday during a naval exercise, possibly after an
explosion on board, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   They said the submarine was badly damaged, and was trapped at
least 450 feet below the surface. They said they did not know how
many of the more than 100 crew members on board were alive or how
long they could survive.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the navy began preparing a desperate attempt to
rescue the crew. But navy officials said the odds of saving the men
were slim.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine, called the Kursk, was not carrying nuclear
weapons, the navy said, but was powered by two nuclear reactors,
raising concerns about possible radioactive contamination. But
Russian officials said the reactors had been turned off, and
officials in Norway said a scientific vessel in the area had
detected no signs of a radioactive leak.
</P>
<P>
   A flotilla of ships and rescue vessels was on the scene off
Russia's northern coast in rough weather Monday night, frantically
searching for ways to reach the men. Navy officials said they
intended to mount a rescue attempt on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   News reports said rescue workers had been trying to hook lines
to the submarine to bring it air and fuel. If the sub lost power,
the men could suffocate and the submarine's compartments could turn
unbearably cold in the frigid waters.
</P>
<P>
   The navy's commander, Adm. Vladimir Kuroyedov, said, ``Despite
all the efforts being taken, the probability of a successful
outcome from the situation with the Kursk is not very high.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said that President
Clinton had been briefed about the accident, and that his national
security adviser, Sandy Berger, had told Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov that the United States was willing to help. Lockhart said
the Russians had not followed up on the offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians initially said the sub appeared to have sunk after
a collision, possibly with a foreign submarine. During the Cold
War, one or two U.S. subs were always on reconnaissance missions in
the Barents Sea. But those missions have become much rarer since
the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991, and Pentagon officials denied
Monday that any U.S. sub had been involved.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said a Navy electronic surveillance ship was
operating in or near the Barents Sea at the time of the accident.
They said the ship was monitoring Russian submarine movements but
was far from the scene of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Russian submarines, U.S. naval experts said, the
Kursk apparently was not equipped with pressurized escape chambers
that could have carried the crew to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   One military expert, A.D. Baker III, said Russia's Northern
Fleet once had deep-diving minisubs that could have undertaken such
a rescue, just as the U.S. Navy does. But, he said, that ability
was ``allowed to dwindle away'' during budget cuts that have turned
the once-powerful Russian navy into a shadow of what it was during
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was doubtful that U.S. rescue vessels could be
brought to the site of the stricken submarine in time, adding that
the Russian crew members would probably be lost ``unless a miracle
occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Frequent television news updates galvanized viewers in Moscow
and stood in sharp contrast to the secrecy that surrounded
submarine operations during most of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. experts say Russia lost at least four nuclear submarines in
accidents from the 1960s through 1989, while others were crippled
by reactor malfunctions, fires or other problems. U.S. and Russian
submarines used to track one another at close quarters, seeking
information and advantage in a dangerous effort to control the
ocean depths.
</P>
<P>
   But since the Cold War ended, the Russian submarine force has
stayed close to home, cut in size by a third. It has had little
money for training and maintenance, and many of its submarines and
ships are rusting at their piers.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian navy provided few details of the Kursk accident, and
the information available in Moscow Monday was sketchy and even
contradictory. One news report said crew members could be heard
pounding on the hull.
</P>
<P>
   If the submarine still had battery power to run air-cleansing
equipment, crew members who survived the sinking might be able to
live for several more days, said Thomas Nilsen, a researcher in
Oslo and co-author of a report on the Russian fleet. But even if
the air was still breathable, the carbon dioxide exhaled by any
survivors could gradually make the air toxic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk, an Oscar II-class submarine that was completed in
1994, sank on Sunday in international waters, about 35 miles from
the coast. Besides torpedoes, it normally carries 24 missiles
intended to destroy ships. It usually has a crew of 107 men, though
some reports said 116 were on this cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said the Kursk had been taking part in a naval
exercise when it lost radio contact with its base.
</P>
<P>
   The Itar-Tass news agency reported that a preliminary underwater
investigation showed that an explosion had probably damaged the bow
of the submarine, causing the torpedo room to flood.
</P>
<P>
   The grim efforts to reach the men illustrate the difficult
calculus behind any submarine rescue mission.
</P>
<P>
   The United States lost two nuclear submarines, the Thresher and
the Scorpion, in accidents during the 1960s. After the Thresher
sank in 1963, the Navy built two minisubs that can dive to 2,000
feet, connect their hatches to those of stricken subs and ferry 24
men at a time to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The minisubs can be flown to a port near a submarine disaster
and then ferried to the scene by one of eight specially configured
mother submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the Navy's minisubs are in San Diego. One of them, the
Avalon, is ready for immediate deployment; the other, the Mystic,
is being certified for a return to activity.
</P>
<P>
   But experts said it was not clear whether either vessel would be
compatible with the hatch design of the Russian sub. And it could
take a week or more for one of the mother submarines to reach
Russian waters.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, the editor of Combat Fleets of the World, published by
the U.S. Naval Institute Press, said Russia's Northern Fleet had a
similar mother sub with smaller rescue vessels. But he said those
vessels had not operated since 1990 and were no longer usable.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said Russia's best hope for rescuing any sailors on the
Kursk would probably be through the use of pressurized diving
bells, either from its own fleet or borrowed from oil-drilling
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1930s, 32 men were rescued from a primitive U.S.
sub, the Squalus, in four trips with a diving bell in 240 feet of
water. But Baker said the water in the Barents Sea was much more
treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   And some reports said the Kursk had listed nearly 60 degrees to
one side, which could make it hard to secure a diving bell to one
of its hatches.
</P>
<P>
   The latest accident comes at a critical time for Russia's navy,
which has been under strict budget constraints since the fall of
the Soviet Union. As recently as May, the navy owed officers as
much as six months of back wages, while even the temperatures in
schools at the naval bases plunged last winter because of lack of
money for heating.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's record in nuclear safety has also been troubling, with
some areas of the Barents Sea contaminated with radiation from
discarded nuclear reactors. Russia's last major submarine accident
occurred in 1989, when the Komsomolets sank off the coast of
Norway, killing most of its crew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
