<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1841 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEMS-RDP-1STLD-WRITET     08-14 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, OPENING DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION, DECLARES GORE WILL PROTECT
LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Updates with more from prepared text, adding quotes on budget
and color from convention floor; will be subbed after speech.) 
(ART ADV: Photos CVN1, 2, 6 and 7 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: The text of Clinton's speech is available from The New York
Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Clinton savored what he called ``this
moment of unprecedented good fortune'' and, in a nostalgic and
sentimental valedictory Monday night, implored Americans to protect
his achievements by electing Vice President Al Gore to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best decisions of my life,'' he said, was ``asking
Al Gore to be my partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's prepared text on the opening night of the 43rd
Democratic National Convention made no mention of Gov. George W.
Bush directly. But Clinton scoffed at the suggestion raised by the
Republican nominee at his convention two weeks ago that the nation
had stumbled into prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who say the progress of the last eight years was an
accident,'' Clinton said, ``that we just coasted along, let's be
clear: America's success was not a matter of chance. It was a
matter of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no allusions to the personal scandals he has
weathered; at an event last week the president said his
transgressions should not tar Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton focused Monday on the high points of his entire
two terms, the longest presidential tenure of a Democrat since
Franklin D. Roosevelt, who died in 1945 after 12 years in office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also tried to transfer his popularity among the
Democratic faithful to Gore, who has had a difficult time rousing
his party. Clinton, who has said the election of Gore as his
successor is crucial to protecting his own legacy, offered this
testament: ``In the most difficult days of the last years, when we
faced the toughest issues _ of war and peace, of taking on powerful
special interests _ he was always there.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to directly link Gore to the economic good times,
Clinton said of his budget plan: ``It passed by a single vote in
both Houses. In a deadlocked Senate, Al Gore cast the deciding
vote. Not a single Republican supported it. Their leaders said it
would increase the deficit, kill jobs, and give us a one-way ticket
to recession.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Time has not been kind to those predictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton, who is 53, was trying to hand off his party to
Gore, the political production Monday night at the Staples Center
here did not have the end-of-an-era emotions of Ronald Reagan's
farewell to his convention in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's wife, Hillary, also had a central role Monday night.
And in the text of her speech, she not only commended her husband
and blessed the nomination of Gore but sought to bolster her own
bid for the Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   After calling on the public to ``continue America's progress''
by electing Gore and his running-mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, Mrs.
Clinton turned to her own race.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it will be up to the people of New York to decide
whether I'll have the privilege of serving them in the United
States Senate,'' she said. ``I will always be profoundly grateful
to all of you and to the American people for the last eight years.
Really, the most important thing that I can say tonight is: Thank
you.''
</P>
<P>
   During a year in which Clinton has surrendered the political
stage to his vice president and to his wife _ only grudgingly, his
friends and advisers say _ the event Monday night was a prime-time
reminder of how the president dominates his party as a colossal
political and oratorical force.
</P>
<P>
   And to some delegates, it was a reminder that Gore faces a
daunting challenge in trying to inspire voters as skillfully as
Clinton _ who is widely regarded as the party's most adroit
campaigner since John F. Kennedy, who was nominated at the party's
convention in Los Angeles in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Gore was this: the more powerful that Clinton
was in his speech, the less likely that the vice president could
pull off a climactic acceptance speech on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain sadness to this evening,'' said Cheri
Hamilton, a delegate from Kentucky who covered herself in
Clinton-Gore buttons. ``They have been a good team, Clinton and
Gore. Gore will work well with Leiberman. But I'm really going to
miss Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Grizzard, a delegate from Florida who wore a Clinton '92
T-shirt over his dress shirt and tie, said, ``I would vote for
Clinton again if I could but, unfortunately, the Constitution says
I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere on the convention floor were signs reflecting the
crowd's deep affection for the Clintons. A woman, bopping to the
music, a smile plastered to her face, waved a sign that proclaimed,
``Iowa Loves Clinton.'' The same sign could be seen in the Kansas
section, and in Utah, Florida, Indiana, New Mexico _ and elsewhere.
The New York contingent hoisted dozens of ``Hillary'' posters,
waving them madly and passing a few to delegates in the Colorado
section.
</P>
<P>
   Angie Graves, 24, a delegate from Fayettville, Ark., was
particularly moved by Monday night's program because the president
is from her home state. ``This is all very sad,'' she said. ``He
has been ours, and he is leaving office. We are hopeful for Al
Gore, but he just isn't ours.''
</P>
<P>
   When short excerpts of past convention speeches by Democratic
presidents was shown on overhead screens, delegates responded with
warm applause for John F. Kennedy, and polite applause for Jimmy
Carter. But the moment Clinton's face filled the screen, the hall
exploded in a paroxysm of applause and cheers. It was impossible
not to notice that the sound fell slightly but unmistakably when a
clip of Gore followed.
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation for the bittersweet comments of some of the
4,339 delegates is that, given polls showing Gore trailing Bush,
they lack the confidence that Republicans enjoyed at their
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Clinton faced one of the most precarious political
challenges of his career: to offer a stout endorsement of Gore that
will spur Democrats _ and the American public _ to rally around the
vice president. But he also had to take care to leave Gore some
room to declare his independence.
</P>
<P>
   For much of his address, Clinton recounted what he considered
the triumphs of his administration. Invoking the slogan of his
acceptance speech four years ago, he declared, ``My fellow
Americans, tonight we can say with confidence: We built our bridge
to the 21st century. We crossed it together. And we're not going
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that the new ticket would build on his foundation,
Clinton said, ``Al Gore and Joe Lieberman will keep our prosperity
going by paying down the debt, investing in education and health
care and in family tax cuts that we can afford. In stark contrast,
the GOP wants to spend every dime of our projected surplus and then
some.''
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton's presence Monday night could not help remind
viewers of the scandals of the Clinton administration that the Bush
campaign is intent on keeping alive. For some Democrats, Clinton's
departure from Los Angeles on Tuesday could not be too soon.
</P>
<P>
   As Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr. of Illinois put it at a news
conference Monday, ``We've got to get Bill Clinton _ and I'm going
to say this quite frankly and quite bluntly _ out of town as
quickly as possible and get to these issues and not make our
convention some referendum on what occurred in the impeachment
process.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The evening was clearly an emotional crest for Clinton and his
stalwart supporters. Advisers to Clinton said he was choking up as
he rehearsed his lines earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the objective of pumping up Gore for four nights, the
Democrats sought to portray the Republicans as staging a masquerade
of moderation at their convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker after speaker stirred up the Democratic faithful by
upbraiding the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans put on quite a spectacle in Philadelphia,''
said Terry McAuliffe, the chairman of the convention and the
party's most prolific fund-raiser. ``They pretended they were
tolerant. They pretended they were moderates. They pretended they
cared about education, health care and the environment. Let's face
it, they pretended they were Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   He drew cheers when he added, ``Governor Bush sure delivered a
pretty speech. But it reminded me of a Texas longhorn: Two points
with a lot of bull in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis of California welcomed the delegates to his
state, saying, ``Here in the home of the film industry, we've seen
the previews of the Republicans' movie: `George and Dick's
Excellent Adventure.' I don't think it's gonna make it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Andrew Tobias, the Democratic Party's treasurer, said: ``The
Democratic leadership celebrates diversity, not for show _ for
real. They have made my life and the lives of millions of other gay
and lesbian Americans immeasurably better.''
</P>
<P>
   As the opening gavel fell, Gore was campaigning in Missouri,
emphasizing his commitment to Social Security and Medicare. During
a stop at President Harry Truman's hometown of Independence, he
said, ``Harry Truman said, when he started the fight for Medicare,
`We can afford many things, but the one thing we can ill afford is
not to have good health care for our people.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That is as true today as it was true back then. I believe we
have to move step by step toward Harry S. Truman's goal of
universal health care for all of our people.''
</P>
<P>
   On this first day, there was not quite the harmony that so
marked the Republican convention. Rep. Loretta Sanchez of
California rebuffed an offer to address the delegates, saying she
did not want it to appear as if she had been motivated by
``personal gain'' when, under pressure from the Gore campaign, she
agreed to move a fund-raiser from the Playboy mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Clintons appeared here, two governors, Jean Shaheen
of New Hampshire and Gary Locke of Washington, struggled to perform
like talk show hosts as they asked individuals to tell how Clinton
administration accomplishments like the Family and Medical Leave
Act and a program to put more police officers on the street had
helped them.
</P>
<P>
   And the proceedings opened with an invocation that must have
been unnerving for the majority of delegates who favor abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``In you, oh God, we trust that you will keep us ever committed
to protect the life and well-being of all people, but especially
unborn children,'' Cardinal Roger Mahony, the Roman Catholic
archbishop of Los Angeles, prayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
