<HEADER>
A1845 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-BULL-REVIEW-SFCHRO     08-14 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BULL-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREED RUNS RAMPANT IN TNT'S `BULL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because TV dramas tended to be simplistic, the old idea was to
sort out good and evil and choose your rooting interest.
</P>
<P>
   How totally yesterday. Wall Street shark Robert Roberts (Donald
Moffat) sets us straight in the first scene of the TNT series
``Bull.''
</P>
<P>
   He's the old gray lion at the brokerage house of Merriweather
Marx, and he's rallying the troops after a 324-point drop in the
Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sole purpose in life,'' he says, pacing the brokerage's
war room, ``the one reason God put us on this planet, is to make
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Like that's what it said on one of Moses' tablets.
</P>
<P>
   The show, TNT's first original series, proceeds without a trace
of compassion, or what we might arcanely refer to as humanity.
</P>
<P>
   It's just big sharks versus little sharks. Go forth and gobble
money. Watch your call options and damn the margins.
</P>
<P>
   I'd have expected something more old-fashioned from TNT.
</P>
<P>
   TV is spewing out two new shows about Wall Street. The other
one, due in the fall, is a Darren Star series called ``The
$treet.'' It looks at Wall Street and seems to decide that sex
makes the world go around.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe TNT has it right; ``Bull'' feels more authentic and,
despite its titanium hardness, it's a coolly entertaining piece of
work.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere is on three times Wednesday night, at 8, 9 and 10.
The usual time will be 10 p.m. Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Moffat, who'll appear occasionally in the weekly series, huffs
and puffs tonight, and fires a naif of a young broker, and makes an
illicit killing with insider information.
</P>
<P>
   But the real action swings toward his grandson, Robert Roberts
III (nicknamed ``Ditto'' and played by George Newbern), who defies
the old man and bolts the brokerage with a handful of colleagues to
form his own firm.
</P>
<P>
   They end the episode hoping to attract a proven sharpie, Hunter
Lasky (Stanley Tucci, who's committed to be in six of the first 13
episodes), to their renegade firm. Moffat's senior Roberts, a man
who'd sup on sons and grandsons, will surely be looking to crush
the upstarts, if he doesn't mind soiling the sole of his shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Malik Yoba plays Corey Granville, a broker marked by Moffat for
a limited future because he is black. Alicia Coppola is Marissa
Rufo, a rainmaker who casts in with the upstarts. Ian Kahn is Marty
Decker, a mergers-and-acquisitions expert. Elisabeth Rohm is Alison
Jeffers, another of the Young Turks.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Wiehl shoulders a burden as Carson Boyd, a young
broker with a glimmer of warmth. Boyd is from North Dakota, which
is shorthand for naive and thoroughly wowed by it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the money,'' Boyd says. ``It's about being at
the heart of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Maximum North Dakota. Possibly even Minot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bull'' looks and sounds much like a David E. Kelley show,
though its pedigree lies closer to ``Law &AMP; Order,'' where its
co-executive producer and top writer, Michael Chernuchin, labored
for six years.
</P>
<P>
   The camera is itchy and the show whizzes by with Olympics sprint
dialogue, the sort of tough eloquence and speed you hear only
onscreen.
</P>
<P>
   But then, there's not a millisecond to waste. Time is money, and
money is all the purpose in the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
