 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
  FIRST LADY DELIVERS EMOTIONAL SPEECH AT DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION
 &HT;    (EDs: UPDATES throughout)
 &HT;    By JUDY HOLLAND 
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, speaking as first lady and
as a candidate for the U.S. Senate from New York, told delegates to
the Democratic National Convention in an emotional speech Monday
night that after eight years of her husband's tenure, ``I am proud
to stand here at this extraordinary moment _ the most peaceful,
prosperous, promising time in our nation's history.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she urged them to work for the election of the ticket they
will officially nominate later this week. ``Now how can we continue
America's progress? By electing Al Gore and Joe Lieberman the next
president and vice president of the United States,'' she declared
in her historic prime-time speech.
</P>
<P>
   And while not directly touting her own campaign, she said,
``Bill and I are closing one chapter of our lives _ and soon we'll
be starting a new one. For me, it will be up to the people of New
York to decide whether I'll have the privilege of serving them in
the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   In her 18-minute address, punctuated by cheers from an
enthusiastic crowd, she provided a summary of the themes Democrats
have sounded throughout the campaign, but she listed them with
children as the main focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've held the hands of mothers and fathers who've lost their
children to gun violence,'' she said. ``It's time to honor their
pain by passing common-sense gun-safety laws that keep guns out of
the hands of children and criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   In saying that she hasn't given up on health care, she said that
``it's time to pass a real patients bill of rights and provide
access to affordable health care for every single child and family
in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   And in urging a vote for the Democratic ticket, she pleaded,
``At this moment of great potential, let's not squander our
children's futures. Let's elect leaders who will leave no child
behind. Leaders who don't just talk the talk, but walk the walk:
leaders like Al Gore and Joe Lieberman.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters hoped her and her husband's starring roles on the
opening night of the convention before 4,368 delegates and 600
alternates will bolster her candidacy for the New York Senate in
the tight race against Republican Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island.
Two weeks ago Lazio declined an invitation to address the
Republican National Convention, saying he preferred to concentrate
on his campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, In his valedictory address to the party,
praised his wife for being ``a full-time advocate for her lifetime
cause'' _ helping children _ during his years in the White House..
</P>
<P>
   ``What a job she's done,'' he said. ``She championed the family
leave law, children's health insurance, and increased support for
foster children and adoptions.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hillary Clinton highlighted her concern for families,, she
also thanked the country for granting her family eight years in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for giving me the most extraordinary opportunity to
work here at home and around the world on the issues that matter
the most to children, families and women,'' she said, signaling to
New York voters that she has been more than a traditional first
lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for your faith and support in good times _ and in
bad. Thank you, from the bottom of my heart, for the honor and
privilege of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Her speech appeared squarely aimed at women, a key voting bloc
in her adopted state of New York where she is trailing Lazio among
white women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute poll put her
ahead, 46 percent to 43 percent. But a few days earlier, the Utica,
N.Y.-based Zogby International Pollfound Lazio ahead 50 percent to
42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady stressed that the Clinton administration created
``a stronger, better country than we were in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bill, Al, Tipper and I got on that bus after our
convention eight years ago, we saw faces of hope _ but also faces
of despair _ fathers out of work, mothers trapped on welfare,
children with unmet medical needs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she added that while the Clinton adminstration had made
``great progress in the last eight years ... we still still have a
lot of work to do. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``When a child can't go to school without fearing guns and
violence _ that's a child left behind. When a child's illness is
treated too late _ or not at all _ because a hard-working parent
can't afford health insurance _ that's a child left behind. When a
child struggles to learn in an over crowded classroom _ that's a
child left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the first lady appeared at Raleigh Studios
in Hollywood at a reception honoring Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., who
bowed out of the Senate race when Mrs. Clinton made it clear she
wanted to run.
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon, sponsored in part by the Hollywood studio
DreamWorks SKG was intended for 500, including many female members
of Congress, but several tables were empty.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton praised Lowey for championing abortion rights,
fighting to include contraception in federal health plans and
opposing the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be absolutely critical as we work to elect Al
Gore and Joe Lieberman that women know what's at stake in this
election,`` the first lady said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Lazio criticized her for holding weekend
fund-raisers in Los Angeles that netted more than $1 million in
soft money, the unregulated contributions to political parties that
are supposed to be used for getting out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Mrs. Clinton ``should return to New York, reveal the
special interest sources of all that money, and join me in
banishing it from this race altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Holland can be reached at 213-336-1807.
</P>
