<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-HILLARY15-COX     08-14 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-HILLARY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HILLARY CLINTON PLAYS DUAL ROLES
 &HT;    By JILL VEJNOSKA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Introduced first and foremost as the first lady to
delegates who clearly had other things in mind for her, Hillary
Rodham Clinton spoke her way into history at the Democratic
National Convention Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Making her first ever run for public office, the Democratic
Senate nominee from New York nonetheless got a nationally
televised, prime-time speaking role, right before President Bill
Clinton's eagerly awaited speech.
</P>
<P>
   And despite having to wait to start her remarks while delegates
lustily sang ``New York, New York'' and flashed signs bearing
pointed messages like ``It Takes a Senator,'' Mrs. Clinton devoted
most of her speech to promoting Al Gore's presidential campaign and
praising her husband's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Most, but not quite all.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it will be up to the people of New York to decide
whether I'll have the privilege of serving them in the United
States Senate,'' Mrs. Clinton drew to a close with a line that
sparked huge cheers even as it added to the sense of uncertainty
swirling around her role here.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, during a backbreaking schedule of events that began last
Friday night, she was just as likely to be meeting people as the
aspiring New York Senate hopeful as White House wife.
</P>
<P>
   It got confusing at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's invited as the first lady,'' explained Dianna Aviv of
United Jewish Charities, one of four Jewish organizations that
sponsored a reception Sunday afternoon at which both President
Clinton and Mrs. Clinton spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that wasn't whom everyone in the crowd expected to show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume she's coming here as a Senate candidate,'' said Rep.
Martin Frost (D-Texas), standing amidst cobblestones and fake
storefronts on Sony Pictures Studio's ``Main Street'' set. ``She
certainly should be. She's running, right?''
</P>
<P>
   No question about it. If that wasn't always obvious from what
she said _ her 12 minute speech at Sunday's reception was almost
entirely devoted to boosting the Al Gore-Joe Lieberman White House
ticket, for instance _ it was from what she did. Which was pretty
much everything a candidate does these days, beginning with an
appearance Friday night on the ``Tonight Show'' with Jay Leno, and
continuing on through an hourlong visit Sunday night to the
welcoming party for New York state's convention delegation.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, while her husband played golf, she was again
visiting with the New York delegation over breakfast. She then left
those she wants to represent to attend an event honoring those
whose ranks she wants to join.
</P>
<P>
   This time the location was Raleigh Studios in Hollywood, where
the ``Salute to Democratic Women in Congress'' featured TV stars
Laura Innes (``ER'') and Kelly Williams (``The Practice''), and
special tribute was paid to New York congresswoman Nita M. Lowey,
that state's likely Democratic Senate candidate had Mrs. Clinton
not decided to run.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the not-so-small matter of very big money. A
veteran of raising election dollars for others as first lady, Mrs.
Clinton has been unabashedly filling her own campaign coffers here.
Estimates are that she will have raised as much as $4 million by
the time she leaves Tuesday morning. And turnabout clearly is fair
play in the ``first household'': A concert and dinner Saturday
night that was billed as a ``Hollywood Tribute to William Jefferson
Clinton'' was expected to raise more than $2 million for her Senate
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, trying to force Mrs. Clinton to pick one role and stick
with it here is impossible and a bit shortsighted, one veteran New
York Democratic politician suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they can be separated,'' Rep. Jerrold Nadler
said at Sunday's event at Sony Pictures. ``What she says here can
have a positive effect on her campaign and on the Gore-Lieberman
ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it may have been the weight of those dual roles that
caused Mrs. Clinton to sound almost shy when she finally got around
to mentioning her Senate campaign in her speech.
</P>
<P>
   Or she may just have assumed a third role, that of a skilled
politician. Badly needing Jewish support to win in New York and
speaking before a crowd of nearly 4,000 people clearly energized by
the selection of Lieberman _ an Orthodox Jew _ to the No. 2 spot on
the ticket, Mrs. Clinton may simply have understood the importance
of focusing on another campaign to subtly enhance her own.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, she spent nearly eight minutes discussing
the importance of a Gore-Lieberman victory before finally slipping
in a passing bit of self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it will really matter who's in the Senate,'' she said
about preserving abortion rights, gun control and other bedrock
Democratic issues. ``Of course, as an aside, I'd like to be there
working with Joe and Al to make this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska's e-mail address is jvejnoska(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
