<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1850 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-CLINTON-NORTHWEST-SPI     08-14 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NORTHWEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEAVES LARGE LEGACY IN NORTHWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As his motorcade snaked onto the tarmac at
Seattle's Boeing Field during the 1992 campaign, with Mount Rainier
seeming to rise out of the end of the runway, Bill Clinton mused:
``I think I may move out here some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will divide his time between New York and Arkansas come
January. But the Pacific Northwest has seen more of the 42nd
president than any of his predecessors. He has made 12 trips to
Washington and Oregon, along with two stops in British Columbia,
since assuming office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Has any other president had as much impact on the Northwest than
Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   ``Never. Not even close. No president has even done this much
for this region,'' said Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash. ``He may not be a
perfect individual but he has been a helluva president.''
</P>
<P>
   Dicks may be exaggerating a bit. Franklin D. Roosevelt left a
massive presidential imprint on the region, building great dams on
the Columbia River and creating Olympic National Park. But Clinton
has, undeniably, made his own impact.
</P>
<P>
   He recently designated a 200,000-acre Hanford Reach National
Monument on the one undammed stretch of the Columbia River. Clinton
has curtailed logging and moved to permanently halt roadbuilding
over millions of acres of national forest land.
</P>
<P>
   He personally helped Boeing sell jets to Saudi Arabia and get
Washington apples into the Japanese market. Against resistance in
his own party, Clinton has pushed for expanded trade with China _
and basked in successes of the Northwest's technology economy until
his Justice Department launched a landmark federal antitrust
lawsuit that may break up Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also helped put the Northwest on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   He picked Vancouver, B.C., for a one-on-one summit with Russia's
President Boris Yeltsin, using his people skills to cover for
Yeltsin's apparent inebriation.
</P>
<P>
   On a stormy November day in 1993, he took a boatload of
Asia-Pacific leaders to Blake Island off Seattle for a daylong
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   He drove riot-scarred streets of Seattle last November for an
appeal to World Trade Organization ministers to open trade
negotiations to more public scrutiny and deal with labor standards
and environmental protection. They gave him a cold shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Citing how Washington and the Seattle area have prospered over
the past eight years, King County Executive Ron Sims on Monday
exclaimed on the convention floor: ``Mr. President, thank you!''
</P>
<P>
   The view is far from unanimous. ``Dictator by fiat!'' Idaho's
GOP Sen. Larry Craig, a timber industry ally, described Clinton in
denouncing the president's plan to keep roadless 43 million acres
of national forest land.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton created the Hanford Reach National Monument, GOP
Sen. Slade Gorton of Washington termed it ``one more example of
Washington, D.C., deciding for Washington communities something I
believe they are fully capable of deciding for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the time, the Northwest has smiled on Clinton. On a
Seattle-to-Portland bus tour in 1996, more than 60,000 people
turned out to cheer Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. Clinton
handily carried Washington and Oregon in both his runs for the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The president began the bus tour in a foul mood, furious at CIA
Director John Deutch for conceding at a congressional hearing that
a recent air raid hadn't weakened Iraq's President Saddan Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Stimulated by crowds, however, Clinton was soon plunging into
rope lines. Using the microphone in his bus, the president
endlessly said ``Hi there'' and ``Thank you for coming!'' to waving
bystanders and, in one case, a large black labrador retriever.
</P>
<P>
   The weather cleared, as often happened when Clinton was around.
At Woodland, while looking at cleanup of flood damage, he joined
Gore to push a stuck police vehicle out of the mud.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, the road has been rocky. Clinton stumped Seattle
twice in closing weeks of the 1994 mid-term elections. When the
votes were counted, however, six Democratic House seats had flipped
to the Republicans. Spokane's Tom Foley became the first incumbent
House speaker to lose a re-election race since 1860.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stepped into a Northwest quagmire when he convened a
1993 summit to work out a solution to the region's forest crisis.
U.S. District Judge William Dwyer had halted almost all logging on
federal land because the Bush administration failed to follow the
Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people weren't satisfied with the outcome, but we
stopped shouting at each other,'' said Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's forest plan has reduced national forest
logging to less than 20 percent of its level in the early 1990s _
too deep a cut for mill towns, but not enough for unyielding
environmentalists who want a halt to all logging of federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush has sharply
criticized Clinton's record in the Northwest, particularly on
forests, fish and national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Bush maintains that cutbacks in national forests have had a
``devastating'' impact on small timber towns. He has accused the
administration of delaying and ducking a decision on whether to
recommend breaching of four Snake River dams to restore salmon
runs. The dams would stay in place on his watch, Bush promises.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also depicted Clinton's creation of new national
monuments in Washington, Oregon, California and Arizona as a
dictatorial, Washington, D.C.-driven policy that has ignored
feelings of local people.
</P>
<P>
   During his second term, Clinton has devoted Northwest visits to
diplomacy and closed-door fund-raisers with Democratic donors. Gore
took over the job of rousing Democrats at rallies, particularly in
1998 when Clinton was forced to the sidelines by the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, Clinton's motorcade may still tie up rush
hour traffic in Seattle, but the president is unlikely to be seen
yelling ``Hellooo Seattle!'' at another Pike Place Market rally, or
plunging into a rope line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Al Gore's job, that's Joe Lieberman's job. I don't
think you'll see the president doing that,'' said presidential
press secretary Joe Lockhart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0499 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1851 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG)     08-14 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACKS UNDER THE GUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ As if it wasn't bad enough that Cory Paus and
Ryan McCann, with a total of 28 sacks, one broken collarbone and a
loss to USC, lived under constant pressure as freshmen last season.
Now their own coach is bringing the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Bob Toledo how important the quarterback position is to the
Bruins this year and you get no poor-mouthing about how he's only
one of 11 players on offense, or protests that the quarterback gets
too much credit and too much blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the quarterback goes,'' Toledo said bluntly. ``So goes the
Bruins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins seem to have many of the ingredients to at least
reverse last year's 4-7 record _ their worst since 1989 _ but if
they don't get improved play at quarterback, it won't matter that
DeShaun Foster, Freddie Mitchell and Brian Poli-Dixon are healthy
and a total of 17 starters are returning.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo is using the first seven to 10 days of fall camp, which
began Saturday, to evaluate Paus, the right-hander with the
accurate arm and strong leadership, and McCann, the tall
left-hander with the powerful arm and classic build. Scott McEwan,
a junior with a weakbut accurate arm and a strong understanding of
the offense, is getting about 20 percent of the reps in camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins aren't looking for the most spectacular quarterback,
just the most steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to start with the idea that you're not going to
get us beat,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges said. ``We want to
make the routine plays consistently. That's something that both of
these kids can do. The emphasis will be on executing with as few
mistakes as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an area in which McCann and Paus struggled as freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   While Paus started seven games, he threw nine interceptions to
seven touchdowns and floundered in a three-game drought when the
Bruins were outscored 105-14 by Cal, Oregon State and Arizona.
McCann, who came off the bench to lead the Bruins to their most
significant win _ a 23-20 overtime upset of Washington that knocked
the Huskies out of the Rose Bowl _ threw three interceptions and no
touchdowns in his first start the next week against USC.
</P>
<P>
   They also had problems handling snaps and looked befuddled when
opponents blitzed or disguised coverages. It also didn't help that
so much of the talent around them was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got acclimated to college football last year,'' said Paus,
who is recovered from the broken collar bone and offseason shoulder
surgery. ``The learning curve is pretty good, but I've got a better
feel for the offense and I'm throwing the ball better. I'm more
confident than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Said McCann: ``The SC experience was so important for me, going
through all the preparation. I feel like I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   But how much progress can they make? History says it won't be
enough to lead the Bruins, picked third in the conference by most
preseason publications, to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It might be possible for young quarterbacks to win in other
conferences _ redshirt freshmen Michael Vick of Virginia Tech and
Brooks Bollinger of Wisconsin did last year _ but not the Pac-10.
Not since sophomore Billy Joe Hobert led Washington to the Rose
Bowl and a share of the national title in 1991 has a Pac-10 team
played in the Rose Bowl without a fourth-year quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10's last four Rose Bowl quarterbacks _ Stanford's Todd
Husak, UCLA's Cade McNown, Washington State's Ryan Leaf and Arizona
State's Jake Plummer _ have two things in common: All played as
freshman and all are in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question, the more experience you have at that
position the better you are,'' Toledo said. ``Our conference has
always been more pass-oriented and has been known as a
quarterback's league where a lot is asked of the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the defenses have become so much more sophisticated.
They've become a lot more pro-oriented with things like zone
blitzes. There's a lot more to prepare for now. Not only do you
have to learn the offense, but you have to learn all those
complicated defenses.``
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A around Westwood is McNown. He was wildly inconsistent
his first two years before blossoming as a junior and leading the
Bruins on a 20-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   As Toledo evaluates the quarterbacks, at least he knows he's
further along than last season. When the Bruins came to camp last
summer, Toledo gave five quarterbacks an equal opportunity. Then he
narrowed it to two _ Paus and Drew Bennett, who split time the
first two games.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Bruins will start the season _ against No.
3-ranked Alabama _ with one quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the next McNown might not have ended, but they
hope the search for their next quarterback will.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Cade McNown only comes around so often,'' said defensive end
Kenyon Coleman. ``We don't need Cade. We just need somebody to get
the ball to the receivers. We need a general to lead the
soldiers.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
