<HEADLINE>
IN EMERALD CITY, WIZARD OF OZ ENDORSES THE TIN MAN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...TIMELY for Democratic Convention)   (This timely 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``p'' political
news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There could be no more irresistible political
farewell. Like the flawed hero of his own Hollywood movie,
President Bill Clinton prepared to address the Democratic Party
faithful Monday night (Monday) on a wave of high emotion,
rhetorical magnetism, mixed feelings about his glaring personal
shortcomings, and extravagant praise for the man who would succeed
him, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in the balmy, dream-fuelled Southern California that he
has made his spiritual home every bit as much as Arkansas or the
White House, Clinton could play to his favorite audience of movie
stars, political wheeler-dealers, philanthropic billionaires and
party fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Already, over the weekend, he had been reduced to tears by the
generous tributes of the Hollywood glitterati. Now it was his turn
to return the favor, and use his considerable charisma and
rhetorical skill to propel the Democrats forward and stir their
excitement about the new race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give Al Gore and Joe Lieberman eight years and you will
see that the best is yet to be,'' Clinton told a group of party
donors at a brunch meeting _ the line he was widely expected to
take on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   But if Los Angeles is Clinton's town, it is hardly Gore's. The
flighty, fiercely competitive, morally ambiguous atmosphere may be
a West Coast mirror of the Clinton White House, but it doesn't suit
the earnest, buttoned-down, somewhat prudish temperament of the
Gore-Lieberman ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In the Emerald City, it will inescapably seem that the Wizard of
Oz is handing over to the Tin Man.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between Gore and the Clintons, both Bill and
Hillary, has been palpable and much remarked upon ever since they
entered the White House eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just in the past few days, as the Clintons have coasted
gleefully from the Hollywood Hills to the Malibu beachfront to be
feted and showered with attention at every turn, the Gore camp has
had to worry about being upstaged.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, both Mr. and Mrs. Clinton's speeches were expected
to be ``amazingly gracious'' about the vice president. But that did
not alleviate the risk that, just by opening his mouth and smiling
his infectiously boyish smile, Clinton would put his putative
successor into the shade.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. media has talked of little else _ dredging up the
misgivings Gore had right from the start about Clinton's slipshod
sexual morality and Mrs. Clinton's overweening ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gore's aides have characterized Hillary as something of
a Wicked Witch of the East for daring to run for the Senate in New
York _ an ``act of indescribable selfishness,'' according to one
Gore official, that risks sapping attention and campaign funds from
the race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Clintons have spent their time in California
raising money for her Senate battle and his presidential library,
not the Gore-Lieberman campaign, has hardly improved matters.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Democrats are not seeking to pretend, as the
Republicans did in Philadelphia two weeks ago, that they speak with
a single, spin-doctored, electorally friendly voice.
</P>
<P>
   With the party genuinely torn over its loyalties, between big
business and the unions, between economic growth and environmental
protection, and between the suburban middle classes and the working
poor, it is seeking to make a virtue of necessity and present the
divisions and disagreements as a sign of dynamism and sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's New York Times was filled with convention-related
advertisements challenging Gore to declare his true loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   One urged him to drop the Democrats' pursuit of a Star
Wars-style missile defense system; another questioned the Clinton
administration's record on protecting forests; and a third, from
the bus riders' union, asked Gore: ``Which side are you on? Racism
or civil rights?''
</P>
<P>
   As Gore seeks to define himself as his own man, he will need to
answer and fend off such criticisms. Already, much has been made of
his running mate Lieberman's differing _ and invariably more
conservative _ views on such matters as school vouchers, Social
Security fund investments and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Although the appointment of Lieberman has gone down well _ a
Reuters poll Monday showed the gap between Gore and his Republican
opponent, George W. Bush, closing to just three percentage points _
it will be this convention week that determines whether Gore can
push himself firmly into the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the Clinton farewell will be his first big test. &QL; 
