<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CZAR-SAINTHOOD-1STLD-     08-14 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZAR-SAINTHOOD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S LAST CZAR AND HIS FAMILY ARE CANONIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS to add byline and updating throughout) 
By SOPHIA KISHKOVSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian Orthodox Church today announced the
canonization of Russia's last czar, Nicholas II, and his immediate
family for their ``humbleness, patience and meekness'' when they
were imprisoned and executed by the Bolsheviks 82 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The elevation of the last czar to sainthood has long been
demanded by powerful right-wing factions in the church and had been
the subject of considerable debate and controversy. Revered as a
martyr and victim of Bolshevism by monarchists and conservatives,
Nicholas is also blamed by many Russians for inept, inflexible and
harsh rule that only hastened revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to canonize him, which had been anticipated for
several weeks, was made behind closed doors by Patriarch Alexy II
and the church's 150 hierarchs, sitting as the Council of Bishops.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops did not proclaim the Romanovs as ``martyrs,'' or
those who died specifically for their Christian convictions, but
instead declared them ``passion bearers,'' a category used to
identify believers who, in imitation of Christ, endured suffering
and death at the hands of political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops also canonized 860 others who were killed by the
Bolsheviks, many of them priests and monks, as martyrs and
``confessors of the faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's press service said: ``The council has sanctified as
passion bearers among the throng of new martyrs and confessors of
the faith, the Russian Emperor Nicholas II, Empress Alexandra,
Czarevitch Alexei, Princesses Olga, Tatiana, Maria and Anastasia.''
</P>
<P>
   The formal services will take place Sunday at the Church of
Christ the Savior, an imposing cathedral near the Kremlin that was
rebuilt in recent years on the site of a church destroyed on
Stalin's orders in 1931. Two years ago, remains identified as those
of Nicholas, his wife and three of their children, along with four
servants killed with them, were buried in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   The remains were exhumed from a forest grave outside
Yekaterinburg in the Ural Mountains in 1991 and identified after
DNA testing. The remains of two other children were never found.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian church has not recognized these remains as belonging
to the czar, and neither Patriarch Alexy nor any other bishop
attended the simple interment, though after a last-minute decision,
the then-president, Boris Yeltsin, did.
</P>
<P>
   The Romanovs were executed 16 months after Nicholas abdicated
the throne on March 15, 1917, as revolutionary fervor swept Russia.
He and his family were detained by the Bolsheviks and eventually
sent to Yekaterinburg, where on July 17, 1918, they were shot dead
in the basement of a merchant's house by a squad of Bolsheviks.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate indication of whether President Vladimir
Putin would attend the formal canonization rites. Putin has not
made his position on the canonization known, though there has been
speculation in the Russian press that he supports the act for its
powerful political symbolism. Putin's first months in office have
been marked by efforts to restore central authority to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin is a strong guy, and Nicholas II is a representative of
a strong empire and this canonization would be a canonization of a
strong empire, not of Nicholas II only,'' said Edvard S. Radzinsky,
author of ``The Life and Death of Nicholas II'' (Doubleday, 1992).
</P>
<P>
   As president Putin has demonstrated some loyalty to the Russian
church. One of his first public appearances as acting president was
at Christmas services in January at the Cathedral of Christ the
Savior, where the council is being held and where the canonization
service will take place.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 860 canonized were clergymen and church workers killed
in 1937 and 1938, the worst years of persecution of the church. In
1937, 136,900 churchmen were arrested and 85,300 were executed by
the NKVD, the predecessor of the KGB Of the 28,300 arrested in
1938, 21,500 were shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas II and his family have, in fact, been canonized before,
by the Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia, in New York City,
which canonized the Romanovs as martyrs. But the New York church
does not acknowledge the Russian church and itself is not
recognized by other Orthodox churches. But many believers in Russia
admired its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially divisive debate over the imperial family was
predicted before the bishops' council opened on Sunday. Two icons
of the new saints were reportedly prepared, one with the czar and
his family, and one without their images.
</P>
</TEXT>
