732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``p'' political
news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Thursday night, Vice President Al Gore must
walk on to the platform at the Staples Center in Los Angeles and
give the speech of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Success, as he accepts the Democratic nomination, will keep him
in the presidential race with a sporting chance of winning. Failure
could spell the beginning of the end of his political career, at
52.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, Gore must parry the attacks _ overt and implied _
from the platform of the Republican Convention two weeks ago, but
he must also present himself as a party leader and
president-in-waiting, a superior alternative to George W. Bush and
his well-drilled, seemingly moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The last is perhaps the simplest. The policy ideas set out by
Bush left gaping holes just waiting for the Democratic nominee to
fill.
</P>
<P>
   Health care, pensions, low pay and the environment, as well as
reform of the business-dominated system of political funding, are
areas of public concern that Gore can usefully exploit.
</P>
<P>
   He can claim a share of the credit for the U.S.'s longest period
of economic expansion and cite his eight years' White House
experience to support his claim to be a better steward of the
country's prosperity into the future.
</P>
<P>
   He can also upstage Bush's boast of leading a diverse and
inclusive party by having named Joseph Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew,
as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. But Gore's weaknesses lie less in content than
in manner and character. From his earliest years as a congressman
from Tennessee, even his supporters had nagging doubts about the
mismatch between the scale of his ambition and his political and
intellectual abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Having attained his party's presidential nomination after two
failed attempts, he must now show that there is genuine substance
beneath the exaggerated ardor or anger he often displays in his
public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows he has experience; what they question is whether
he has the spine to take the hard decisions and the insight to read
the nation's mood.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's intellectual caliber, compared with that of
Bush anyway, is not at issue; his political sensitivity and his
ability to connect with the voters are.
</P>
<P>
   While described universally as delightful and even funny in
private, Gore lacks Bush's charm in public. It may be that the
presence of his running mate, the far more relaxed and even
garrulous Lieberman, will loosen him up.
</P>
<P>
   But unless he can make up in gravitas and honesty what he lacks
in charisma, Gore will fare badly by comparison with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Texas, though, is not the only, or even the most
threatening, point of comparison. In Los Angeles, Gore has somehow
to emerge from the giant shadow of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Making the move from vice president to presidential nominee is
always problematical, but Clinton has given Gore an even harder job
than Ronald Reagan gave George Bush senior in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Both two-term presidents had an exceptional talent for
communicating and an uncanny sense of the national mood. Like Bush
with Reagan, Gore will never match Clinton: he lacks his personal
magnetism, political instinct and quickness of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Where Gore is worse off than Bush, however, is in the issue of
ethics. Clinton bequeaths to Gore the fallout from White House
sleaze and his own scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Against that, Gore can set the solidity of his family. The
choice of Lieberman, one of Clinton's earliest critics in the
Lewinsky affair, has given him one degree of separation. Clinton's
own new apology last week gave him another.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore is not without ethical burdens of his own: his
hesitation about condemning Clinton's conduct with Lewinsky is one;
the legality of his fund-raising and his equivocation about it is
another. Somehow he must allay voters' doubts on these scores.
</P>
<P>
   While planned to look less slick than the Republicans'
song-and-dance show of unity and moderation, the Democratic
Convention has been no less choreographed, and to one end alone:
portraying Al Gore as president-in-waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons, Bill and Hillary, will address the convention
Monday and then leave the West Coast altogether.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no joint Clinton-Gore fund-raising or platform
appearance. The remaining three nights will see the progressive
reintroduction of Al Gore: family man, caring politician, national
leader. &QL; 
