<DOCNO> NYT20000814.0507 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-TORRICELLI-NYT     08-14 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TORRICELLI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRICELLI, CHASTENED, ACTS AS UNIFIER 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sen. Robert Torricelli, in perhaps the most
improbable speech of his two-decade career, conceded Monday to New
Jersey delegates who are here for the Democratic National
Convention that he had misjudged their support in trying to usurp
Jim McGreevey's place as the party's likely candidate for governor
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli is here almost as dual personas. He is both the
powerful New Jersey senator who heads the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee and flits from one big-ticket gala to another,
and the chastened New Jersey politician whose bid for the party's
Democratic nomination for governor turned out to be a humiliating
dud.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli did not apologize for the divisions he had created
before withdrawing from the race on July 31, nor for the difficult
decisions he had forced many officials to make. Nor did he endorse
McGreevey. But he nonetheless asked Democrats to unify behind the
party's candidates this November before taking up the 2001
governor's race again. And in an uncharacteristically self-effacing
way, Torricelli suggested that he had accepted his defeat, and was
ready to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed that,'' Torricelli said when greeted with a standing
ovation, adding later that it had nearly moved him to tears.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was off to four receptions (out of 29 this week
that he said should raise $4 million for Democratic Senate
candidates), a short speech on the convention floor, and another
night of party-hopping. And on Tuesday night, Torricelli is to be
the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee's guest of honor at
Spago, the ultimate Los Angeles party place.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago it looked as if this week would also be the
moment of Torricelli's ascension to the throne of New Jersey
politics: his coronation as nominee for the governorship he has
coveted for years. Instead, it is McGreevey who is meeting with
governors and constituency groups here, burnishing his image on the
issues and laying the groundwork to raise as much as $20 million
for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, speaking to hundreds of New Jerseyans at their hotel
in Glendale, was applauded when he declared that Republicans from
Gov. Christie Whitman to the leaders of the state Legislature
``have simply lost the right to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was greeted warmly when he said that Democrats needed to
pull together to heal wounds that he seemed to acknowledge he had
helped to deepen. ``There is no reason for this political party in
the state of New Jersey to have any divisions of region, or
ideology, or personality,'' he said. ``We can all have our
differences about who would lead us best, win by the widest margins
or achieve victory. ``I had my own view,'' he added, eliciting
laughter at his own expense.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite Torricelli's talk of unity, and the standing ovation
his mention of McGreevey received, it was clear Monday that many
who supported Torricelli's candidacy for governor remained
lukewarm, at best, about McGreevey. Some said Torricelli's original
argument _ that McGreevey did not have the electoral heft to sweep
other Democrats into office _ remained persuasive. ``My concern is
the need to elect a Democratic Assembly and Senate,'' said Joseph
Doria, the Assembly minority leader and would-be speaker. ``We need
the coattails.''
</P>
<P>
   And many of McGreevey's supporters continued to speak
disparagingly _ albeit on the condition of anonymity _ of
Torricelli's political future.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Torricelli said Monday that he would run for a
second term in 2002. But he said he had given up his gubernatorial
ambitions for good. ``That moment has passed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For all the damage his image has sustained in New Jersey since
last month, his high profile in Los Angeles gives little indication
that he has been diminished on the national stage.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, who had named Torricelli
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, said
Torricelli had not lost any esteem among his colleagues. ``I was
glad he made a decision to stay in the Senate, because he's an
outstanding leader and he has a bright future there,'' Daschle
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Torricelli's failure in New Jersey was noticed nationally,
nonetheless. One prominent Democratic lawyer attending a
fund-raiser in Santa Monica on Sunday observed that most
politicians interested in running for higher office would float a
trial balloon first, to avoid embarrassment. ``Torricelli floated a
very large and incendiary device,'' the lawyer said. ``He floated
the Hindenburg, and he was a passenger on it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., who has long feuded with
Torricelli, suggested in an interview that his rival's brief
candidacy for governor had not been well received in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``When in New Jersey, we're facing a significant opportunity to
keep a Democrat in the Senate, to help Al Gore get elected with a
significant plurality, everyone knows that we have to do it in
concert,'' Lautenberg said. ``So it's noted outside when a
disruption comes along that is fundamentally divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, inadvertently, it had a good outcome, because it pulled
Democrats together as nothing we've seen in the last four or five
years,'' Lautenberg added. ``And Jim McGreevey is stronger for
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
