These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business section
plans to move for Tuesday, August 15, on the New York Times wire.
For questions, please call Dominick Calicchio at 415-777-6055 or
the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running in
main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MURDOCH _ &LR;  Feisty media mogul Rupert Murdoch added another wrinkle
to the tumultuous Bay Area media landscape Monday by agreeing to
buy KBHK (Channel 44).
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco TV station, a UPN affiliate that airs popular
shows such as ``WWF Smackdown'' and ``Moesha,'' is one of 10 that
Murdoch's News Corp. will acquire as part of a $5.35 billion deal
to buy New York's Chris-Craft Industries Inc.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; KELLY ZITO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WELLS _  &LR; Wells Fargo, a pioneer lender to California's low-income
and minority neighborhoods, has come under fire from a leading
advocacy group that questioned Wells' commitment to those
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The California Reinvestment Committee, a coalition of more than
200 groups across the state, issued a statement Monday warning that
a recent shakeup of Wells' California community development
operations signals a ``downgrading'' of the bank's lending and
investment activities in low-income neighborhoods.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; SAM ZUCKERMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ELECTION _  &LR; Is it just a coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   The great bull market of the 1990s began almost the moment the
Republicans won control of Congress in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, with Democrat Bill Clinton in the White House and
the Republicans hanging onto the leadership of the Senate and House
of Representatives, stock prices _ as measured by the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index _ have more than tripled.  &UR; BY ARTHUR &LR; 
 &UR; M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MONEYBAG (COLUMN) _ &LR;  Q: I know that if I give no more than $10,000
each year to my daughter, I can avoid the gift tax. But what if I
give another $10,000 to someone else, with the understanding that
they will give the money to my daughter? Is this legal or can it be
considered tax evasion?  &UR; BY ARTHUR M. &LR; 
 &UR; LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SIGABA _  &LR; San Mateo, Calif., startup Sigaba Corp. couldn't buy
better marketing than the kind the Federal Bureau of Investigation
is giving to it for free.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation that the FBI has been using a powerful system
called Carnivore to monitor peoples' e-mail has driven home a point
that encryption advocates have been repeating for years: E-mail is
not private. Messages can easily be read by Internet service
providers, the FBI or hackers.  &UR; BY CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CHIRON _  &LR; Chiron Corp. agreed to pay $700 million in cash Monday to
buy a Seattle biotech firm with one drug on the market and a
research pipeline geared toward creating antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, however, seemed underwhelmed by Chiron's
acquisition of PathoGenesis Corp., the manufacturer of TOBI, an
inhalable antibiotic to treat chronic lung infections arising from
cystic fibrosis.  &UR; BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; REDHAT _  &LR;  LinuxWorld Conference and Expo, opening to the public
Tuesday in San Jose, Calif., is the largest trade show devoted to
the cooperatively developed, freely distributed Linux computer
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the show, The Chronicle asked Bob Young, chairman
of Red Hat Inc., the largest Linux distributor, to assess the
progress of the OS and the movement behind it.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BLUELIGHT _  &LR; Bluelight.com, the high-profile Internet subsidiary of
Kmart Corp., said Monday that it has secured $80 million in
second-round financing in one of the year's largest e-tailing
financing packages.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart, a co-founder of Bluelight.com, will provide $55 million
in additional financing while Japanese Internet investor Softbank
Inc. is chipping in $25 million. The funds will go toward Web site
development, marketing, hiring and inventory for the San Francisco
dot-com.  &UR; BY KELLY YAMANOUCHI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
