<SLUG> BC-BLUELIGHT-KMART-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BLUELIGHT.COM TO GET $80 MILLION IN FINANCING  &HT;     By KELLY YAMANOUCHI 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bluelight.com, the high-profile Internet
subsidiary of Kmart Corp., said Monday that it has secured $80
million in second-round financing in one of the year's largest
e-tailing financing packages.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart, a co-founder of Bluelight.com, will provide $55 million
in additional financing while Japanese Internet investor Softbank
Inc. is chipping in $25 million. The funds will go toward Web site
development, marketing, hiring and inventory for the San Francisco
dot-com.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which offers about 100,000 products including DVD
players and Lego toy sets, expects to carry 500,000 products by
mid-October. That will be more than what is available at a typical
Kmart store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect break-even operating conditions toward the end of
next year,'' said Bluelight.com Chief Financial Officer Christopher
Lein.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100 employees and 3.3 million Internet service
subscribers, Bluelight.com has grown rapidly since its Web site was
launched in December. The question, however, is how many of these
customers will stick with Bluelight.com, according to Andrew
Bartels, an analyst with Giga Information Group in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Bluelight.com faces stiff competition from Wal-Mart, which has
joined forces with America Online Inc. to offer low-cost Internet
service. In addition, the Kmart unit must contend with other free
Internet service providers and e-tailers.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at  &LR; kyamanouchi(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
