<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDHAT-LINUX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LINUX ENJOYING ENTHUSIASTIC GROWTH  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ LinuxWorld Conference and Expo, opening to the
public Tuesday in San Jose, Calif., is the largest trade show
devoted to the cooperatively developed, freely distributed Linux
computer operating system.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the show, The Chronicle asked Bob Young, chairman
of Red Hat Inc., the largest Linux distributor, to assess the
progress of the OS and the movement behind it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle: The popularity of Linux seems to be soaring. How do you
explain that?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Young: What open-source software does that proprietary technology
does not is to give users control, for the first time, over the
technology they're being asked to invest in. And that's what's
creating all of this enthusiasm. When you go to user group
meetings, when you talk to MIS directors at General Motors, the
enthusiasm across the spectrum for open-source technologies, for
things like Linux, is that they're no longer beholden to their
vendor.
</P>
<P>
   The proprietary, binary-only model that the software industry
has used to date (the standard system of shipping software users
can't modify) leaves the vendor in control of the vendor-customer
relationship, and we think that's a fundamental flaw.
</P>
<P>
   We ask people, ``Would you buy a car with the hood welded
shut?'' If the hood was welded shut in such a way that the only way
you could get things fixed was to take it back to the original
dealer, then the original dealer is in control of the car.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if he refuses to fix the bug that's causing your
car to stall every few hundred miles, you're stuck _ you'd learn to
live with restarting your car every few hundred miles, the same
principle as rebooting your computer once a day.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit of being able to open the hood of your car is, if
the original dealer can't figure out what's causing your car to
stall, you've got 10,000 other dealers across the country who are
happy to help.
</P>
<P>
   In the software business, with binary-only products, the only
people who can fix them are Oracle or MS or Symantec or whoever
sold it to you. And if they deny that the thing causing your system
to crash is a bug, where do you go?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle: In what markets are people buying into that argument?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Young: Broadly, you've got three markets: first, the server
marketplace _ database servers, Internet servers and so on; second,
the classic desktop machine market, which Windows dominates; and
then the embedded system market, things like easy-to-use Internet
appliances, TV set-top boxes, Internet-enabled phones and so on.
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting is that all of the growth in the future of
the IT industry, according to Gartner Group, is occurring in the
first and third of those markets. The middle piece, the stand-alone
Windows environment, is 1980s technology and it's a big market,
it's not going anywhere soon, but it's no longer a growing market.
</P>
<P>
   Our success is not dependent on getting people to unplug their
working Windows desktop. Our opportunity is the rapid growth that's
occurring on Internet servers talking to Internet appliances. We
are perfectly positioned to serve both of those markets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle: How are you doing in those markets at this point?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Young: International Data Corp.'s numbers show that 24 percent of
the server operating systems shipped last year were Linux. It was
the only OS that had a growing share _ the year before, Linux
represented about 16 percent, and the year before that just 6
percent. So the growth rate is quite dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet appliance side, well, it's going to be massive.
And with the agreements we've had with companies like Ericsson and
Nortel, Red Hat Linux technology is going to be in a huge
percentage of those appliances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle: You don't see any chance that Linux could become a real
alternative to Windows for mainstream PC users?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Young: My point isn't that that isn't an important market and
someone shouldn't go after it _ I'm glad some Linux companies are.
All I'm getting at is, that's not the future of the IT industry.
Back in the early days, when we were working out of an old
apartment in Durham (North Carolina), the conversation would get
around to ``Jeez, there's four or five of us living off our credit
cards trying to compete with Microsoft _ who are we trying to
kid?''
</P>
<P>
   But John ``Mad Dog'' Hall (now head of Linux International, a
nonprofit organization dedicated to promoting the OS) always used
to say, ``Guys, remember, there are 6 billion people in the world.
Your job isn't to look after the 400 million personal computers,
your job is to build the technology that the other 5.6 billion
people will use.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
