<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIRON-ACQUIRE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INVESTORS YAWN AT CHIRON'S $700 MILLION DEAL  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Chiron Corp. agreed to pay $700 million in cash
Monday to buy a Seattle biotech firm with one drug on the market
and a research pipeline geared toward creating antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, however, seemed underwhelmed by Chiron's
acquisition of PathoGenesis Corp., the manufacturer of TOBI, an
inhalable antibiotic to treat chronic lung infections arising from
cystic fibrosis.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron shares slipped 4 percent to close at $46.69 after
Monday's premarket announcement of the deal. Analysts had long
chided Chiron for being slow to use its $1 billion cash hoard to
make a big purchase, and initial reaction was that the PathoGenesis
deal just wasn't big enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors had hoped Chiron would do something larger than
this,'' said Dennis Harp, who follows Chiron for Deutsche Banc
Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron Chief Financial Officer Jim Sulat predicted that Wall
Street would warm up to the deal once Chiron explains why it will
pay $38.50 per share for PathoGenesis, an 18 percent premium over
that firm's closing price of $32.75 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sulat said Chiron is confident that TOBI, which is worth $80
million a year in U.S. sales, has the prospect for generating new
markets in Europe, where the drug is in the approval process.
</P>
<P>
   He said Chiron also is convinced PathoGenesis is poised to
develop antibiotics by using genetic data on microbes to fashion
drugs tailor-made toward diseases such as tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Sulat said, PathoGenesis has expertise in designing
drugs that can be inhaled, an advantage in targeting pulmonary
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron was so impressed with PathoGenesis' research expertise
that the two companies signed a deal last year to share technology
for using genomic data to target microbes. PathoGenesis chief
executive Bill Glantz said that from the start, Chiron chief
executive Sean Lance hinted that Chiron had more than a partnership
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very persistent,'' Glantz said of Lance. ``He was very
clear about where he wanted this relationship to go.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not until June, however, when PathoGenesis hired an
investment banking firm to shop the company around, that the
acquisition talks moved to the front burner. Glantz said he
entertained one other firm bid for PathoGenesis before accepting
Chiron's all-cash offer.
</P>
<P>
   Glantz founded PathoGenesis in 1992 with Bruce Montgomery, a
former scientist with Genentech Inc. who had worked on that firm's
cystic fibrosis effort. After Glantz and Montgomery established
PathoGenesis' research offices in Seattle, the firm moved
relatively quickly to launch TOBI in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But PathoGenesis overestimated the market for the new
cystic-fibrosis compound at around $100 million, and after trading
above $45 a share in 1999, the stock crashed when investors saw
initial U.S. sales more in the neighborhood of $60 million
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Glantz said PathoGenesis shares were trading around $18 in June
when the board decided the company had reached a turning point. On
the one hand, it was poised to broaden the market for TOBI in
Europe, but to capture European sales, it would have to spend
millions to build a sales force.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative was to hang out the ``for sale'' sign, which the
company did when it announced that it had hired bankers to
``explore strategic options.'' The company's stock began to rise,
culminating with Monday's $700 million buyout announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron's Sulat said his company planned to retain most of
PathoGenesis' 320 employees, who are split between research offices
in Seattle and a manufacturing facility in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any head-count reductions will be incidental,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which has been approved by the boards of both
companies, is expected to close in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of PathoGenesis rose 16 percent to close at $37.97 on the
news.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle news services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
