 WELLS FARGO'S LENDING POLICIES ASSAILED  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Wells Fargo, a pioneer lender to California's
low-income and minority neighborhoods, has come under fire from a
leading advocacy group that questioned Wells' commitment to those
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The California Reinvestment Committee, a coalition of more than
200 groups across the state, issued a statement Monday warning that
a recent shakeup of Wells' California community development
operations signals a ``downgrading'' of the bank's lending and
investment activities in low-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The committee called on the Federal Reserve to hold public
hearings on Wells' pending takeover of First Security Corp., the
largest bank in Utah, so that community groups can air their
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Wells' reorganization of its community development department
``suggests that the bank is placing less importance on the needs of
low-income communities in California,'' said Alan Fisher, the
committee's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The bank countered that the reorganization is aimed at
strengthening community lending operations. ``We've actually
upgraded our (community reinvestment) function,'' spokesman Larry
Haeg said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy reflects the different lending philosophies of
the old Wells and Minnesota's Norwest, which bought the San
Francisco bank a year and a half ago, took its name and moved its
headquarters west.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators gave both banks strong marks for their programs to
finance low-income communities. While the old Wells set up a
powerful, centralized department to oversee its community lending
activities, Norwest assigned the responsibility to its regional
managers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Karen Wegmann, the longtime community
development manager of the old Wells, retired. Under her, the bank
had forged strong ties with advocacy groups, signing formal
agreements to lend billions to low-income communities.
</P>
<P>
   Wells used Wegmann's departure as an opportunity to put in place
in California the decentralized community lending model of the old
Norwest.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a statewide community development organization, Wells
created separate staff operations reporting to each of five
regional presidents. The bank named longtime Wells veteran Timothy
Hanlon to replace Wegmann but took away his line authority over the
community development staff.
</P>
<P>
   Community development isn't a full-time job for Hanlon, as it
was for Wegmann. In addition to the development area, he is still
responsible for the bank's charitable, minority vendor and
volunteer programs in California.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization puts the development staff closer to
communities and makes it easier for the bank to respond to the
specific problems of each region, Wells spokesman Haeg said.
</P>
<P>
   But community groups say it will be difficult for the bank to
put together a consistent program and be accountable for what's
happening in each region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is up in the air,'' said Arthi Varma, a California
Reinvestment Committee staff member. ``We don't know who to go to,
who to talk with.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, activists in the Northwest, Midwest and Northeast are
criticizing Wells' home lending record in public comments on the
bank's proposed First Security purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Wells' mortgage company denies loans to African American and
Latino applicants at a much higher frequency than white applicants,
the groups have charged.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Wells' units that charge above-market rates to
borrowers with weak credit records lend disproportionately to
minorities. The disparity is more than the industry average, the
groups charged.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said its lending record is solid. ``We have been named
as the No. 1 lender to people of color and second-leading lender to
low- and moderate-income home buyers,'' Haeg said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
