<SLUG> BC-SIGABA-EMAIL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SIGABA SOFTWARE SEEKS TO EASE PARANOIA ABOUT E-MAIL  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Mateo, Calif., startup Sigaba Corp. couldn't
buy better marketing than the kind the Federal Bureau of
Investigation is giving to it for free.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation that the FBI has been using a powerful system
called Carnivore to monitor peoples' e-mail has driven home a point
that encryption advocates have been repeating for years: E-mail is
not private. Messages can easily be read by Internet service
providers, the FBI or hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sigaba launches a free product on its Web site ( &LR; www. &LR; 
 &LR; sigaba.com &LR; ) designed to make it easy for ordinary people to send
encrypted e-mail that can't be intercepted by Carnivore or anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnivore has been very beneficial for us,'' said Richard
Bliss, Sigaba marketing vice president. ``People have been shocked
into the realization that their mail is not secret when they send
it across the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The product, SigabaSecure, also makes it possible to take back
an e-mail after it has been sent _ a function that will probably
save users embarrassment if they ever accidentally send a message
to someone it's not intended for. The function, called
``shredding,'' works by destroying the key that the e-mail
recipient would use to decode the message. Shredding is possible up
until the receiver decodes and opens the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Sigaba is one of several companies benefiting from the public's
heightened awareness of e-mail's vulnerability. ZixIt of Dallas
recently introduced a product that allows users to send encrypted
e-mail through ZixIt's Web site,  &LR; www.securedelivery.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Both Sigaba and ZixIt are marketing to individual consumers,
banking on the fact that while several encryption products on the
market are capable of keeping prying eyes off e-mail, consumers
have mostly ignored them. The problem is that the products are too
complicated for most people to use.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, a Carnegie Mellon study, ``Why Johnny Can't
Encrypt,'' illustrated this problem by giving 12 people copies of
one of the easier-to-use encryption programs, PGP 5.0. The
participants were instructed to send several encrypted e-mails, but
half the group failed.
</P>
<P>
   Encryption programs typically have had difficult-to-use
interfaces, and some require users to set up a special e-mail
account just for encrypted messages. But the biggest problem with
past security products is their use of a system called public key
infrastructure, said Eric Arnum, editor of Messaging Online
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   PKI makes digital signatures possible, but it can also be used
to send encrypted e-mail. However, some experts such as Arnum say
PKI and e-mail are not a good match.
</P>
<P>
   With PKI, an e-mail's code has two keys: one for encoding and
one for decoding. The encoding key is posted on a company server or
an individual's Web page; it is called the public key. The decoding
key is kept hidden on the e-mail user's computer.
</P>
<P>
   In order to encode an e-mail to send to someone using PKI, you
have to have access to the person's public key. This works fine for
an internal company e-mail system _ everyone's public key could be
stored in a central place that all employees can access. But it
hasn't been very successful for e-mail outside company systems,
Arnum said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using PKI, SigabaSecure creates a new key for each
e-mail message, then enables the intended reader to get the key
from Sigaba's Web site. The software comes as a plug-in that works
with the user's regular e-mail program, such as Microsoft Outlook
or Yahoo e-mail. Once installed, SigabaSecure encrypts and decodes
e-mail at the press of a button.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a solution that is usable by the mass market, I
have a feeling that we could be talking about significant growth
for encryption,'' Arnum said.
</P>
<P>
   Sigaba, which formed in January, takes its name from the only
World War II encryption machine whose code was not broken by the
enemy. The company has $5 million in venture funding and plans to
introduce a corporate version of SigabaSecure later this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
