<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-1STLD-WRITETH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON TELLS DEMOCRATS THAT GORE WILL KEEP PROSPERITY ROLLING &HT;    (EDS: Updated with full speech)
 &HT;    By STEWART M. POWELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Clinton, urging America to stick with
political heir Al Gore to ``keep our prosperity going,'' boasted to
the Democratic National Convention Monday night that the
Clinton-Gore team had forged ``a better country`` since ousting
Republicans from the White House _ and warned that a GOP comeback
could trigger the economic reversals and social upheavals of the
Nixon years.
</P>
<P>
   The president bid an emotional farewell to the Democratic
faithful, offered hearty praise for his loyal vice president and
appealed to voters to choose Gore's specific policy proposals over
what the president portrayed as the vague, ill-considered schemes
of Republican rival George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now at this moment of unprecedented good fortune, our people
face a fundamental choice: Are we going to keep this progress and
prosperity going?`` Clinton rhetorically asked cheering party
faithful crammed into the 20,590-seat Staples Center for the
opening night of the Democratic convention. The hall rocked with a
roar of ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We built our bridge to the 21st century. We crossed it
together. And we're not going back,`` Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who introduced her husband
for his valedictory, echoed her husband's theme in remarks designed
to bolster her campaign for a Senate seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a stronger, better country than we were in 1992,'' Mrs.
Clinton said. But America's progress can only continue under the
leadership of Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., the first lady insisted, adding: ``They have what it
takes. They'll do what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made a hearty endorsement of his wife's candidacy for
the Senate. ``She's always been there for our family and she'll
always be there for the families of New York and America.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, a combative partisan who has relished the
political fray since first entering politics in Arkansas in 1974,
dismissed claims by Bush at the Republican convention on Aug. 3
that the Clinton-Gore administration had ``squandered``
opportunities presented by the nation's longest economic recovery
in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who say the progress of the last eight years was an
accident, that we just coasted along, let's be clear America's
success was not a matter of chance, it was a matter of choice,``
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president, apparently angered by Bush's claim, struck back
by likening a Bush victory to the 1968 victory of Richard M. Nixon.
Democratic-led economic recovery and progress on civil rights gave
way to social and political tumult that deeply divided the nation,
Clinton said. ``The next election took America on a far different,
more divisive course. And within months of that election, the last
longest economic expansion in history was itself, history.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, working to bolster the White House bid of his
vice president, proudly laid claim to responsibility for the strong
economy and for generating federal budget surpluses, slashing the
national debt, restoring national confidence and transforming
education, child care, the welfare system, inner cities and the
federal tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the record,'' Clinton declared, adding in a line from
television's Los Angeles detective Joe Friday: ``Just the facts,
ma'am.``
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that, thanks to his administration, ``Americans are
better off today than we were eight years ago,'' adding: ``America
has progressed not just economically but as a community. We're not
just better off we're also a better country more decent, more
humane, more united moving forward and working together.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just economic prosperity, Clinton said. ``Jobs are up,
but so are adoptions. The debt is down, but so is teen pregnancy.
We are becoming more diverse and more united.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who seized the limelight with appearances at more than
20 events over four days in Los Angeles, was scheduled to leave Los
Angeles on Tuesday for a campaign rally in Monroe, Mich., where he
will symbolically pass the torch to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the convention that Gore had worked side-by-side in
the Oval Office ``in the most difficult days of the last years,
when we faced the toughest issues.'' Clinton added that Gore had
been ``more willing to make the tough choices'' to balance the
federal budget and ``take tough stands against those who would do
it the wrong way on the backs of the poor and working people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``understands the future and how sweeping changes can
affect Americans' daily lives,'' Clinton said, adding that a
Gore-Lieberman administration ``will keep our prosperity going.''
Clinton added: ``They believe the people you're buying your soft
drinks and popcorn from here at the Staples Center deserve the same
chance they have to send their children to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, White House press secretary Joe Lockhart derided Bush's
claims that Americans had suffered under the Clinton-Gore
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush family may be worse off than they were eight years
ago, but I think the vast majority of Americans will argue that
their lives have become better,`` Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman linked up on the campaign trail in St. Louis
to watch the Clintons' nationally televised address.
</P>
<P>
   Gore staged a symbolic pilgrimage earlier in the day to the home
town of President Harry S. Truman, the scrappy, plain-spoken
Missouri Democrat who came from behind in 1948 to extend Democrats'
hold on the White House to 20 straight years until 1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a contrast in this election and the American people
deserve to know the details of what's being proposed by the two
major parties,`` Gore told a forum in Independence, Mo. ``The
American people need to know the specifics of how the American
people would be affected if the other side won.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Stanley Greenberg, who served as the Clinton-Gore
campaign's pollster in 1992, told reporters that Gore needs to
ignite voter turnout by focusing public attention on differences
between the rivals. ``What matters for turnout is having an
election that matters,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest nationwide survey, conducted by John Zogby of Zogby
International in Utica, N.Y., and released Monday, showed Bush's
17-percentage-point edge over Gore following the GOP convention had
been cut to 3 percentage points 43 percent for Bush to 40 percent
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter said in an NBC News' interview
that Clinton's successes are helping to overshadow a dark chapter
in his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the escapades of President Clinton in the White
House are still in people's memories, but I think that time is
passing by,`` Carter said, adding: ``There has never been a hint of
scandal about Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who returns to the campaign trail on Friday with a
symbolic raid on Gore's native Tennessee, remained at his
1,500-acre ranch in Crawford, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
stewarthearstdc.com)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
