<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-LOUIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MONEYBAG: IRS WOULD REIN IN GIFT HORSE  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I know that if I give no more than $10,000 each year to my
daughter, I can avoid the gift tax. But what if I give another
$10,000 to someone else, with the understanding that they will give
the money to my daughter? Is this legal or can it be considered tax
evasion?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: I ran your question past Joe Calderaro, technical coordinator
with the Internal Revenue Service. His response: ``If those were
the facts, and the IRS knew the facts, they would say that you gave
your daughter a gift of $20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   If you tried your scheme, it's unlikely that the IRS would ever
learn the facts. But it could happen if your go-between squeals on
you.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give you the benefit of the doubt and assume that you don't
want to compound the felony by having your go-between bumped off to
preserve the omerta code of silence.
</P>
<P>
   You might consider just obeying the law, like the majority of
your fellow citizens (I hope).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Three Days to Ownership
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I purchased stock in a company on June 19. The company had
stated that there would be a dividend payable on July 10 to
stockholders of record as of June 20. But I didn't receive the
dividend. My broker explained that I was not considered a
shareholder of record until June 22, the third business day after I
placed the trade. Is this correct, or am I being cheated?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You are not being cheated. This is standard procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Under rules imposed five years ago by the Securities and
Exchange Commission, stock trades are settled three business days
after they are placed. (Before that, it was five business days.)
Not until then are you credited with ownership on the books of the
company whose stock you purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that bookkeeping technicality, you don't have to wait
three days to sell your stock. You can place a sell order within
seconds after your buy order. (Day traders do that sort of thing
all the time.) Like the buy order, the sell order won't settle
until three business days later.
</P>
<P>
   I can imagine you asking a follow-up question: ``If I am not
entitled to the dividend, shouldn't I get a discount on the price
of the stock?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes _ and in fact you did get a discount.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the stock went ex-dividend _ meaning that buyers no
longer were entitled to the next payout _ the price of the stock
was adjusted downward on the market. Prospective buyers
automatically offered less for the stock than they would have
offered if they could have received the dividend.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, that adjustment would have happened on the market
day immediately preceding the one on which you placed your order.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Shop Around for CDs
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I am a 74-year-old widow and will soon be selling my home,
giving me several hundred thousand dollars to reinvest. I intend to
live on the income (along with my Social Security and other monthly
income) for the rest of my life. I do not want to risk losing any
of it, so stocks, etc., are out. Do you have any suggestions other
than certificates of deposit? That is what I have most of my cash
in now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You may as well stick with CDs. They are federally insured,
which means they are virtually risk-free. And there don't appear to
be any risk-free investments that can top the 7 percent-plus annual
yields offered by some banks.
</P>
<P>
   CD rates can vary quite a bit from bank to bank. So don't just
walk into your neighborhood bank and accept whatever rate they
offer. Shop around _ not just in the Bay Area but in other areas
and even other states.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to get into a car or airplane to accomplish this.
If you have access to the Internet, go to the iMoneyNet Inc. Web
site at  &LR; www.imoneynet.com &LR;  or the Bankrate.com site at
 &LR; www.bankrate.com &LR; . You will find listings of the highest CD and
savings rates nationwide, along with toll-free telephone numbers
for the institutions that offer them.
</P>
<P>
   You can find similar information in various newspapers,
including The Chronicle, which prints such listings every Monday in
the Business section.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
 &LR; moneybag(AT)sfgate.com &LR; , or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column,
901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
