<HEADER>
A1888 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ELECTION-GRIDLOCK-SFC     08-14 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-GRIDLOCK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DIVIDED, WE PROSPER: GRIDLOCK CAN PAY  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Is it just a coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   The great bull market of the 1990s began almost the moment the
Republicans won control of Congress in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, with Democrat Bill Clinton in the White House and
the Republicans hanging onto the leadership of the Senate and House
of Representatives, stock prices _ as measured by the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index _ have more than tripled.
</P>
<P>
   That's a phenomenal 22 percent annual growth in stock values _
more than twice the historic average.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say that it is more than a coincidence. They
contend that stocks usually can be expected to do better when
Congress and the executive branch are led by different political
parties or when the leadership of Congress is divided.
</P>
<P>
   That's because little or no economically disruptive legislation
gets passed when the federal government is divided. The economy is
allowed to function on its own, and that _ say the experts _ is
good for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gridlock is the best thing you can hope for from Washington,''
says David Wyss, an economist with Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in
Massachusetts. ``If you have a Republican administration and
Congress, they will make too many tax cuts and not pay off enough
debt. If the Democrats are in charge, they will spend too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show Republican George W. Bush ahead in his battle
for the presidency over Democrat Al Gore and that both the Senate
and House will could remain Republican.
</P>
<P>
   None of those results is certain, of course. The safest bet is
that the Republicans will retain control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   There's more chance that the House _ where the Republicans have
a 12-seat majority _ will be captured by the Democrats. Twenty-four
GOP representatives are retiring and rookies are running in their
place. By contrast, only eight Democratic House members are
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   If the leadership of Congress is split between the parties, that
will ensure continued legislative gridlock no matter who becomes
president, predicts Greg Valliere, managing director of Charles
Schwab Corp.'s Washington Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't see either Gore or Bush getting any kind of radical
agenda through with Congress divided,'' Valliere observes. ``There
are many who point to the Bush record as governor of Texas, who say
he is a conciliator, and that he could work with a Democratic
House. But Dick Gephardt (of Missouri), who would be speaker of the
House if the Democrats take over, is not known for his
bipartisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Valliere points out, however, that legislative gridlock doesn't
have to render a president entirely powerless.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that whoever becomes president will be able to appoint
leaders of the Federal Reserve, Federal Communications Commission,
Food and Drug Administration and other regulatory bodies that
influence the destinies of many businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Since World War II, the stock market has performed best with a
Democrat in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats held the presidency for 26 of the 54 years from the
end of 1945 through the end of 1999, and the average performance of
the S&AMP;P 500 during that period was a 10.9 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   During the 28 years that Republicans occupied the White House,
the S&AMP;P 500 on average gained only 8.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, stocks do best when the Republicans control
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have controlled both houses of Congress in nine
postwar years, during which the S&AMP;P 500 made a sensational average
annual gain of 18.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the 39 years that the Democrats controlled both houses, the
S&AMP;P 500 averaged only a 7.6 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have fared very well indeed with the current lineup: a
Democratic president and Republican Congress.
</P>
<P>
   During five years under Bill Clinton and two under Harry Truman,
the combination produced an average annual gain of 18.7 percent in
the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of a Republican White House and a Republican
Congress actually has been slightly better for investors: an
average 19.2 percent gain. But that combination occurred in only
two post-war years, during the Eisenhower administration _ too
small a sample to be meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how the overall market performs, certain companies
are likely to fare better under Bush, others under Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schlossberg, an economist with Wells Capital Management in
San Francisco, notes that Gore, who has denounced rising medical
costs, might circumvent gridlock by issuing an executive order
imposing price controls on health care and drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart J. Pillette of Pillette Investment Management in San
Francisco says Bush's interest in beefing up U.S. defenses should
be good for such stocks as Boeing, General Dynamics, Lockheed
Martin, Raytheon and Rockwell. Those stocks have perked up lately
in anticipation of a Bush victory, he notes.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it might seem that the Bush-Cheney ticket would
be practically ideal for oil and other energy stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as governor of Texas, is friendly to the oil interests,
and his father made a fortune in oil. Dick Cheney, in accepting the
vice presidential nomination, stepped down as chief executive of
Halliburton Co., an oilfield-services company. But Marshall Acuff,
a market strategist with Salomon Smith Barney in New York, figures
that the Republican candidates will simply encourage greater oil
and gas production. Greater production would keep a lid on prices
and prevent profits from spiking.
</P>
<P>
   Valliere predicts that a Gore victory would benefit Fannie Mae
and Freddie Mac, the publicly held, government-affiliated companies
that provide affordable home mortgages to lower-income Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have strong support from the Congressional Black
Caucus, and Gore is more likely than Bush to protect them.
Congressional Republicans want to curtail the subsidies the
companies get from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; alouis(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
