<HEADER>
A1889 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MURDOCH-TVDEAL-SFCHRO     08-14 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH-TVDEAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MURDOCH'S NEWS CORP. TO BUY SAN FRANCISCO'S KBHK  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Feisty media mogul Rupert Murdoch added another
wrinkle to the tumultuous Bay Area media landscape Monday by
agreeing to buy KBHK (Channel 44).
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco TV station, a UPN affiliate that airs popular
shows such as ``WWF Smackdown'' and ``Moesha,'' is one of 10 that
Murdoch's News Corp. will acquire as part of a $5.35 billion deal
to buy New York's Chris-Craft Industries Inc.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. will boost its portfolio of TV stations to 33 and
will own two each in five cities, including megamarkets New York
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch, who built News Corp. from two newspapers in Adelaide,
Australia, into a worldwide media conglomerate, beat out rival
Viacom, which had been negotiating with Chris-Craft, in the 11th
hour.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is subject to both shareholder and federal approval _
which could hinge on whether News Corp.'s TV stations reach more
than the maximum 35 percent of U.S. households allowed. Current
Federal Communication Commission rules would require News Corp. _
which would serve 40.5 percent of U.S. homes with the additional
stations _ to sell six of the 10 Chris-Craft stations, said Merrill
Lynch analyst Jessica Reif Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   However, News Corp. is fighting the 35 percent cap in court,
arguing that cable, the Internet and other advances have made the
rule archaic.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear: With the recent sale of KRON and News
Corp.'s deal for KBHK, the turmoil in the Bay Area's news and
entertainment outlets is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deal raises many questions about KBHK's programming,
whether News Corp. will sell the station and whether another
seismic shift in the TV media marketplace could open the door for a
San Francisco NBC affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   If the KBHK's sale to News Corp. goes through, it could alter
the station's programming. Right now, KBHK offers a mix of
children's cartoons, African American sitcoms and professional
wrestling, following on UPN President Dean Valentine's recent boast
that the network stands for ``youth, diversity and testosterone.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox could retain the UPN programming, or, in a more likely
scenario, replace it with its own or a partner's. In fact, some
media watchers believe News Corp.'s purchase of Chris-Craft is an
attempt to quash rival UPN, which last year saw a 111 percent jump
in the number of 18- to 34-year-old male viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Chris-Craft's agreement to carry UPN programming ends in
January; and Viacom, which owns the UPN network, has said that it
might shut down UPN if the network's losses continue. UPN
contributed to a pretax loss of $60.7 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   However, News Corp. doesn't appear able to simply shift its Fox
programming, which includes animated comedy ``The Simpsons'' and
sitcom ``Ally McBeal,'' to KBHK.
</P>
<P>
   Those Fox programs already reside on Oakland's KTVU, a Fox
affiliate owned by Atlanta's Cox Communications. Under a deal
signed six months ago, Channel 2 will retain the Fox affiliation
for the next 10 years. According to KTVU General Manager Kevin
O'Brien, there is no ``out'' clause in the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no possibility'' of News Corp. stripping KTVU of its
Fox affiliation, O'Brien said. ``It's a very extensive, firm
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. spokesman Andrew Butcher said the company has not
discussed programming for KBHK or any of the other new stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those decisions haven't been made yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that Fox may sell KBHK, because the
company will probably reap the most financial reward from the five
so-called ``duopolies'' in which two stations in the same market
save money by sharing some business operations.
</P>
<P>
   Having two stations each in Los Angeles and New York will give
Fox clout with advertisers and give the company the power to put on
``any syndicated show'' produced by Fox studio, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have the No. 1 market share in both markets,'' said
Mitchell Stern, head of the Fox television station group. ``No
advertiser that is doing business in those markets is going to be
able to go around us.''
</P>
<P>
   Butcher said he doesn't know which stations News Corp. may sell,
``but San Francisco is the No. 5 market and a very attractive TV
market.''
</P>
<P>
   If News Corp. were to sell KBHK, it might find a willing buyer
in NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, KRON parted ways with NBC after KRON, under
new owner Young Broadcasting, refused to pay for network programs.
KNTV (Channel 11) picked up the NBC affiliation, which begins in
2002. But some question whether the San Jose station will be
received clearly in all parts of the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the complexity, according to former KRON President Amy
McCombs, is that ``if NBC were to purchase a station in the Bay
Area, it's affiliation with Granite Broadcasting (owner of KNTV) is
no longer in effect.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC and KNTV officials did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
