<HEADLINE>
HISTORY ISN'T WITH ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia would have you
believe the nine-game road trip to Toronto, New York and Boston is
no more important than any other trip. But history says otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five seasons, the Angels are 35-52 when visiting the
Blue Jays, Yankees and Red Sox. Those are numbers that stand out
considering the Angels were contenders in three of those seasons _
1995, '97 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have held their own in New York, going 14-14 at
Yankee Stadium since 1995. But Toronto and Boston have been
trouble. Last season, the Angels went a combined 0-12 in both
cities.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the Angels' only trips to New York and Boston this
season. They visited Toronto this season in April and lost three of
four.
</P>
<P>
   __ Return of Salmon: Right fielder Tim Salmon is expected to
return to the starting lineup tonight after watching most of
Sunday's game from the bench because of a tight groin. Salmon did
come in and deliver a pinch-single off Roger Clemens in the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, though, will be careful not to come back if he's not
ready. In 1998, a foot injury forced him into a DH role and last
season he played in only 98 games because of a sprained wrist.
</P>
<P>
   That sprained wrist, he says, forced him into bad habits that he
carried into this season. But he's been hot lately, hitting .392
since the All-Star break and establishing a career-best 17-game
hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's use your brain here a little bit,'' Salmon said.
``Everyone has had a tight hamstring or something of that nature
and tried to go hard on it. But if I had been smart the day before
that foot injury, maybe I could have avoided it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is telling me to be smart about this. We've only
got six weeks left in the season. If I do anything that puts me out
for a week or two weeks, that's not good for the team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
