<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UDEZE MIGHT NOT REDSHIRT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ Last winter, Kenechi Udeze was so distraught
over which college to attend, that his mother caught him muttering
``USC'' and ``UCLA'' in his sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would turn over and say USC, and then turn over and say
UCLA,'' Udeze said.
</P>
<P>
   Udeze , who is only 17, eventually chose USC, and his impact
with the Trojans has come much quicker than expected. He made a
splash during the first scrimmage when he swatted down a Carson
Palmer pass, then swung his arms in the air as if he was hitting a
home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either that or start break dancing,'' Udeze said. ``At
halftime, coach (Ed) Orgeron said we had to get pumped up.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's coaches are the ones pumped up today. Udeze, a redshirt
candidate coming out of Verbum Dei High, is not expected to sit out
this season and could see action in the season opener against Penn
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been something about this guy that's been
exciting,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``This is faster than what
I anticipated. The feeling all along is that he has a great future.
The concern is he's a year younger for his class and would need to
redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's come in here and he's just going. With our situation,
it's really been exciting. He gets chances and keeps working.''
</P>
<P>
   Udeze, who is 6-foot-4, 305-pounds, has lost nearly 50 pounds
since the beginning of his senior year at Verbum Dei. He would like
to lose a little more weight to play this season.
</P>
<P>
   His size has already prompted Orgeron to nickname him BKU for
Big Kenechi Udeze.
</P>
<P>
   But before his college career begins in earnest, Udeze will no
doubt cause a minor stir with his comments on the recruiting
process, specifically his home visit with UCLA coach Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really confused about where to go, and he came into my
house and lied and said USC got another commitment from a defensive
tackle, and I was no longer their No. 1 prospect,'' Udeze said.
``He said they got some JC guy. I knew it wasn't true. So I knew I
couldn't go there after he said that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hale departs: Walk-on wide receiver Donald Hale, whom Hackett
felt was a strong candidate for a scholarship, has left camp and
decided to concentrate on academics.
</P>
<P>
   __ Abdul-Shaheed debuts: Defensive end Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed
participated in his first practice after being out the past week
with a sore shoulder. His return means the Trojans have nearly
every player practicing at least once a day except offensive guard
Trevor Roberts (sprained foot), who is supposed to be out for the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Troy Polamalu, who has what might be a minor
concussion, is expected back Wednesday. Linebacker Markus Steele
has seen limited practice time with a left-hamstring injury but
said he should be fine by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Kori Dickerson did not practice Monday afternoon
after being nicked in the shin but is expected to return today.
</P>
<P>
   __ Guenther to play: After a nice scrimmage, tight end Gregg
Guenther of Taft High probably will not redshirt, Hackett said,
meaning the Trojans will play two true freshman (Guenther, Alex
Holmes of Harvard-Westlake) at the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty impressive with the skills he has right now,''
Hackett said of Guenther.
</P>
<P>
   __ Closed scrimmage: The Trojans will scrimmage Wednesday, but
it is not open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   __ Boskovich makes move: Freshman Joe Boskovich of Westlake High
has taken the lead to be the snapper on field goals and extra
points.``It looks like he's about to win the job,'' Hackett said.
``We'll know Wednesday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
