<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT FAR FROM HOME, PETTITTE SHUTS DOWN RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Andy Pettitte ambled into the clubhouse
Monday afternoon and saw about a dozen of his teammates watching
the movie ``American Pie.'' He glanced at the screen once and then
retreated to his locker.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte did not have the interest or the time to watch the
movie because he was engrossed with his own preparation. He had to
remind himself that he could win at the Ballpark in Arlington.
Forget about being so close to home and about being in a place that
has been tougher for him than any other in the American League.
Just focus. Just pitch.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Pettitte did. Pettitte pitched precisely while
Jorge Posada and Derek Jeter stroked two-run homers as the Yankees
cruised to a 7-3 victory over the Texas Rangers. Pettitte did not
allow a run until the eighth inning, and the Yankees stifled the
listless Rangers for the ninth straight time, including the 1999
Division Series. What else is new? The Yankees have now won 34 of
the last 45 regular and post-season games against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After Pettitte started with an 0-3 record and a 16.05 earned run
average in his first three starts here, he has won two straight
starts in the last 51 weeks and chopped his ERA to 9.33. Some of
Pettitte's family members from Deer Park, Tex., which is about
three hours away, did not attend one of his starts a few years ago
because they were worried about jinxing him.
</P>
<P>
   But that should not be a concern anymore. Not after Pettitte won
his fifth straight start in dominating fashion to boost his record
to 14-6. With 48 games left, Pettitte should make about nine more
starts, so he has a chance to win 20 games for the second time in
his career. Monday night, Pettitte, who permitted three earned runs
in seven plus innings, was happy to simply win another game at the
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 93-degree heat, Pettitte worked quicker than normal.
He did not stray too far from the pitcher's rubber and raced
through the first on two groundouts and a strikeout. Gabe Kapler
lined a one-out single to center in the second to extend his
hitting streak to 27 games, the longest in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, Ricky Ledee, the former Yankee, faced Pettitte.
Manager Johnny Oates had originally said that he might not play
Ledee against the left-handed Pettitte, but, if the Rangers want to
know what kind of hitter Ledee can be, it makes sense to play him
every day.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee had only 40 at-bats against left-handers this year and he
had never had a regular season at-bat against Pettitte. But Ledee
showed more flashes of his potential when he crushed one of
Pettitte's pitches to right-center field. Bernie Williams sprinted
toward his left, his arms pumping and his eyes locked in on the
ball. Williams dived and caught the ball about waist high and slid
along the grass, winding up a few inches from the warning track. He
looked up and exhaled after saving Pettitte from allowing a certain
run.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had other chances against Pettitte. Pettitte walked
one in the third, but stranded him. Left fielder David Justice
dropped an easy fly ball in the fourth when he closed his glove too
soon, but Pettitte quickly got Rafael Palmeiro to bounce into a
double play. Kapler followed with a single, but was picked off.
Luis Alicea reached base on Luis Sojo's error in the sixth, but
Pettitte retired three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   It was a refreshing evening for Pettitte, who has had too many
forgettable nights here. Pettitte lost, 15-2, here on July 30, 1996
when he was torched for a career-worst 10 earned runs, and he was
battered, 10-0, on July 7, 1995, before 200 friends and relatives.
But Pettitte was superb Monday night and provided enough excellent
footage to make his own home movie.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
