<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGNSTOP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE VISITS HOME OF TRUMAN TO DISCUSS MEDICARE, SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ Al Gore came to Harry Truman's hometown on
Monday to claim the mantle as defender of senior citizens and
Medicare, the old-age health care program that Truman championed
half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told a crowd of several hundred _ mostly senior citizens _
that if elected president, he would use the nation's projected
budget surpluses to expand the Medicare program to cover
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to strengthen Social Security, improve benefits for
long-term care for seniors and establish full health insurance for
all children within the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need step by step to get to Truman's goal of universal
health care coverage,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's appearance in Independence was part of a weeklong
campaign swing leading up to his nomination Wednesday at the
Democratic National Convention. He talked about children's health
care in Cleveland and tax cuts to spur economic development in a
Philadelphia suburb.
</P>
<P>
   He led a forum on cleaning up the environment in Springdale,
Pa., at the former home of author Rachel Carson, whose 1962 book
Silent Spring sparked the modern environmental movement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore chose Independence as the scene for Monday's forum on
senior issues to evoke Truman's legacy of supporting health
protections for the elderly. President Johnson came to Independence
to sign the legislation that created the Medicare program 35 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking at the Sermon Community Center, said that before
the law about half of the nation's elderly had health insurance.
After the law 95 percent were covered. Today senior citizens'
dependence on prescription drugs makes Medicare drug coverage
essential, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would cover half the cost of prescriptions up to
$5,000 a year. Additional coverage would kick in once a patient
paid more than $4,000 out of pocket. For elderly people with
incomes less than $11,000 a year, the plan would cover all premiums
and copayments.
</P>
<P>
   In the 72-minute forum, Gore criticized big drug companies and
HMOs, answered questions from the audience and listened to accounts
of people struggling to pay for drugs or qualify for government
aid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore never mentioned Republican presidential nominee George W.
Bush by name, but he warned his audience that his opponent's plans
for Medicare and Social Security would jeopardize benefits from
both programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't squander the surplus on a big tax cut for the wealthy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Texas, Bush spokesman Bob Hopkins scoffed at Gore's
criticism. He said the Clinton-Gore administration rejected
bipartisan ideas promoted by the Social Security reform commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is having a convention conversion,'' Hopkins said.
``He is reinventing himself as someone who is actually concerned
with reforming Social Security and Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was especially critical of Bush's plan to let workers place
part of their Social Security taxes into stock and bond
investments. Because taxes on workers pay for retirees' benefits,
the diverted money would have to be made up from general government
revenue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Popular government programs would have to be cut and little
money would be left over to pay for Medicare benefits, which are
expected to swell as the baby-boom generation retires, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with the proposal, he said, is that even a
booming stock market has winners and losers. Programs that have
losers often ask for a government bailout. He compared the
situation with the Freedom to Farm program, which worked well when
farm commodity prices were high but required government subsidies
when prices plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it cost that much to bail out the Freedom to Farm Bill, how
much will it cost to bail out the Social Security Freedom to Fail
bill?'' Gore asked.
</P>
<P>
   In the question-and-answer session, several persons expressed
fear about switching to a system in which part of their Social
Security benefits were invested in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It was a misunderstanding of the Bush proposal, which calls for
letting workers have the choice of investing part of their tax
payments. Bush's plan would make no changes in retirees' benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said nothing to correct their misconception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Couldn't you get on the Internet and find some good
investments?'' Gore asked as the crowd broke into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather keep my Social Security,'' the woman replied as the
crowd cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins, of the Bush campaign, said the Republican plan would
have no effect on current retirees or those approaching retirement.
It would allow younger workers to invest part of their taxes so
they could pay for part of their own retirement, instead of relying
on the taxes of future workers.
</P>
<P>
   Current Social Security taxes pay for retirees' benefits and
fund a surplus that is invested in government bonds. Part of that
surplus could be diverted to private investment accounts without
endangering current benefits, Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush expected that at retirement, most workers would use
their investments to buy annuities, which would provide guaranteed
annual incomes for the rest of their lives. Bush has never
suggested that retirees would have to put part of their benefits in
the stock market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the typical demagoguery that we have seen over the
last 7 1/2 years from Al Gore,'' Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   On Medicare drug benefits, Gore said his plan was in the best
interest of the public. The Bush plan, he said, is designed to
protect the financial interests of major pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Drugmakers say they need big profits to fund the research that
discovers new drug therapies. Gore said it had the ring of truth.
But companies sometimes spend more advertising their drugs than
finding new ones.
</P>
<P>
   And when patents are about to expire to let generic drugmakers
into the market and lower the price, he said, companies hire
lobbyists to get special laws passed to thwart competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our plan leads to lower prices, well, that's good,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wilson, 78, of Independence, said he found Gore's speech
enlightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can propose anything to reduce medical expenses, that
would be a real benefit to senior citizens,'' he said. ``Everyone's
getting gassed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Kansas City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver said he thought Gore
connected with the crowd, particularly while discussing his plan to
protect Social Security benefits. He said critics who described
Gore as wooden were unfairly comparing Gore with President Clinton,
who has an amazing ability to make people feel as if he were
talking directly to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good example of how (Gore) really does relate to
people,'' Cleaver said. ``I've seen him do it with small groups
before. ... He may not have the charisma (of Clinton), but Bush
certainly doesn't have it either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
